<h2><a name = "Westlaw">An Introduction to Searching WESTLAW</a></h2></center>
<h3><Centre>By Gian Medves, Computer Services Librarian</center></h3>
<p>
<I>This month's issue of LawLink features a quick guide to seaching WESTLAW.  It includes: guidelines for developing a search strategy prior to searching, information on navigating the database once you have begun your search, instructions for modifying your search once it is completed  and procedures for printing and saving once you have found the information that you require.</i>
<p>
WESTLAW is a large American legal database service. It contains over 700 databases of American and International legal materials including:
<p>
<uL>
<li> The United States Code.
<li> The U.S. Code of  Federal Regulations.
 <li> U.S. State laws and bills.
<li> American case law.
<li> The full-text of many law review and legal periodical articles.  A list of the periodicals    available on WESTLAW can be found on the Bora Laskin Law Library home page  at (URL=<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/resources/journals.htm">http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/resources/journals.htm)</a>.
<li>News and current information.
<li> Topical databases, etc. 
</ul> 
<p>
Note: WESTLAW uses a modified version of the QuickLaw search software. Many of the commands are the same or similar but there are some differences which will be pointed out in this guide.
<p>
To get on WESTLAW you must first sign-on to QuickLaw. Once connected to QuickLaw type <b>DB WL</b> to connect to WESTLAW. Once connected you will be presented with the WESTLAW copyright screen hit the <b><Enter> </b>key.  You will then be asked to identify your research session.  You must type in something (anything) at this point or the system will not let you continue. Once you do this, you will see  WESTLAW's opening menu and you can begin your legal research.
<p>
Searching WESTLAW can be divided into 3 basic operations:
 <p>          
  
	1) Query preparation<br>
	2) Examining search results<br>
	3) Downloading and printing<br>
<p>
<h3>1) Query Preparation:</H3>
<p>
<b>a) Identify the precise legal issue you wish to research.</b> 
<p>
Think about your research problem and write down the concepts or keywords that describe it best. For example, if you are searching for cases in which a doctor was sued for performing an operation that resulted in the amputation of a limb your keywords would include doctor, malpractice, amputation and limb.<p>
<b> b)Look for synonyms and alternate expressions. </b>
<p>
In this example you would also look for the words physician or surgeon and negligence and leg or arm. You do not want to miss any cases where an alternate term is used.
<p>
<b>c) Decide if any of the words in your query should be truncated to retrieve the various endings for a word root. </b>
<p>
In WESTLAW the truncation command is represented by an exclamation point <b>(!).</b>  In our example the word amputation can be truncated to amputat! to retrieve the words amputate, amputated, amputating, etc.
<p>
<b>d) Choose appropriate connectors (AND, OR, proximity indicator) for the word groups. </b>
<p>
The <b>AND</b> connector specifies that both terms being searched must appear somewhere within the same document (e.g. drunk <b>AND</B> driving).
<br>
The <b>OR</b> connector requires that at least one (or more) of your search words occurs in a document  (e.g. doctor or physician or surgeon). In WESTLAW, as in QuickLaw, a space between words is read as an implicit <b>OR.</b>
<br>
The proximity indicator offers a method for you to indicate in your query that you would like one or more words in your search to appear in a specific proximity to one another. For example, <b>fifth /2 amendment</b>  will look for fifth within 2 words of amendment; <b>verbal written /10 contract</b> will look for either the word verbal or written within 10 words of contract. The proximity indicator<b> /p </b>searches for terms in the same paragraph (e.g. hearsay <b>/p</b> utterance). The <b>/s </b>proximity indicator searches for terms in the same sentence.
<p>
<b>e) Determine if field searching is required. </b>
<p>
Databases on WESTLAW contain numerous fields. Field searching allows you to limit your search. To see what  fields are available in a particular database type <b>F </b>when you are in the database and a list of the fields will be provided.  If, for example, in our sample search involving doctors and malpractice we wanted to restrict our search to 1994 decisions we would add <b>and da(1994</b> (where <b>da</b> is the date field) to our search string.
<p>
<b>f) The final step before going on-line and conducting your research is to determine which databases to search.</b>  
<p>
Since WESTLAW has over 700 databases, a good way to start your research is by selecting a database from the WESTLAW  directory of  databases (WESTLAW Databasics) which is available in the Computer Lab or at the Circulation Desk. You can go directly to the database you have selected by typing in the database identifier. Alternatively, you can follow the menu of options which appears on the first screen. You can choose to search Federal materials, State materials, topical materials by area of practice, law reviews and periodicals, etc. If, for example, you chose to search Federal materials you will then be provided with a further menu of options including cases, statutes, legislative history, etc.  If you do not have a specific jurisdiction in mind, you can do a broad search in one of the global databases such as ALLFEDS, ALLSTATES, or JLR for a global database of journals and law reviews. The  <b>SC </b>(Scope) command displays a database description, coverage information and search tips when entered from a database or when followed by a database identifier (e.g. <b>SC SCT</b> will display the scope and coverage of the U.S. Supreme Court decisions database).
<p>
Our final search query would look like this:
<p>
<b>doctor physician surgeon and malpractice negligence and amputat! /10 limb arm leg and da(1994). </b>

<h3>2) Examining Search Results:</h3>
<p>
Once you have prepared a search query, you can go online and execute your search by typing the search terms that you have chosen and pressing enter. The next step is to examine your search results and determine if the cases retrieved are appropriate. WESTLAW provides several useful commands to allow you to page through your documents to determine if they are relevant. Once you are in a document you can use the<b> T</b> (term) command to display the next page containing your keywords. Your keywords will be highlighted so they are easy to see. <b>T- </b>displays the previous page containing your keywords. <b>P</b> (page mode) displays the next page of a document.<b> R</b> (rank) displays the next ranked document.<b> R#</b> displays a specific ranked document (e.g.  <b>R3 </b>displays document #3). The<b> L </b>command displays a citation list. If the documents retrieved are not relevant then you should consider modifying your search query.
<p>
<h3>2a) Modifying a Search Query </h3>
<p>
To modify your search type <b>Q</b>; your search query will then be displayed to the screen. At this point you can edit your search. You will need to decide whether to add more terms or to truncate existing terms. Another option is to take your search query into another database and see if you retrieve more relevant documents there. To transfer your query to another database type <b>SDB xxx</b> (where xxx is the name of the new database). To begin a completely new search type <b>S</b> and you will be given a blank query screen to start over. To return to the main menu in WESTLAW  type <b>DB.</b>
<p>
<h3>2b) Case History and Judicial Consideration</h3>
<p>
Once you have found an appropriate case or cases you can also use several WESTLAW services (Insta-Cite, Shepard's Citations, and Quick Cite) to show the history of the case, its judicial treatment by other cases, and all its parallel citations.  To retrieve a case history or verify a citation through Insta-Cite, type<b> IC</b> followed by the case citation.  Shepard's Citations display a comprehensive list of citing references. Once in a document type <b>SH</b>  for a display of the Shepard's record for the decision being displayed. Use Quick Cite<b>(QC) </b>to update a Shepard's citation with the most recent citing cases available on WESTLAW.
<p>
<h3>3) Downloading and Printing:</h3>
<p>
Documents may be downloaded to disk, retrieved into a word processing package and then printed.
<p>
To download, use your mouse to select the <b>Functions</b> pull down menu and highlight <b>AutoSave</b>  to save the entire document. Once you select <b>AutoSave</b>  you are prompted to name the file. The document(s) will then be downloaded to disk as a text file. To stop the downloading process, type <b>Alt-V </b> (the Alt key and &quot:V&quot: key on a PC) or press the <b>Command</b>  key plus the <b>Period</b>  key (on a Mac).  We recommend that you download retrieved documents to a file and print the file after you disconnect from WESTLAW. This will allow you to retrieve a downloaded file into word processing software where you may reformat the text and then print. If you try printing from WESTLAW and there is a problem (e.g. your connection is terminated or the printer jams), you may have to re-establish your connection and start your search process all over again.

To logoff WESTLAW type<b> OFF</b>  then press<b> <Enter> </b>   to return to QuickLaw. Type <b>OFF</b>   again to logoff QuickLaw.  Exit the QuickLink software by choosing <b>Exit</b>   or <b>Quit</b>   from the <b>File Menu. </b>



<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "exams"> University of Toronto Faculty of Law Exams
 Are Now Available on the Bora Laskin Law Library Home Page </a></h2></center>
<p>Law students can now find recent versions of Faculty of Law exams on the Web at the Bora Laskin Law Library home page  (URL=<a href="http://www.law-lib2.utoronto.ca/exams/">http://www.law-lib2.utoronto.ca/exams)</a>.
<p>
Exams for December 1994 and April 1995 are already available with December 1995 exams coming soon.  They are arranged alphabetically by course name and can be printed or downloaded.
<p>
Exams previous to December 1994 are available in print at KF 292 T64 U54. 

<p>
