<img align = left src = "../icons/libgry5.gif"><center><h1><cite>LawLink</cite></h1>
<h3>The Newsletter of the Bora Laskin Law Library<p>

University of Toronto</h3><p>
<a href = "http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca">[Bora Laskin Law Library]</a> <a href = "http://www.utoronto.ca/">[University of Toronto]</a></center>
<br clear = "all">
<p><center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<h3>February 1996, Volume 2 Number 5</h3>

<h2>Contents</h2>
<dl>
<dd><a href = "v2n5.htm #QL">Searching Quicklaw: A Quick and Easy Guide</a>
<dd><a href = "v2n5.htm #Newadd">Announcing a New Addition to the Bora Laskin Law Library World Wide Web Home Page</a>
</dl>
<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "QL"> Searching Quicklaw: A Quick and Easy Guide </a></h2></center>
<p>
<h3><centre>By Gian Medves, Computer Services Librarian</centre></h3>
<p>
<I>The following is a brief guide to searching QuickLaw.  It features succinct instructions for
basic search strategies and commands that will be useful to students and faculty alike.  Whether you are using QuickLaw down in the computer lab, dialing in from home or from your newly networked office, keep this issue of LawLink on hand as a quick reference guide to online legal research.
</I><p>
QuickLaw is Canada's largest legal database service.  It includes reported and unreported cases from a variety of Canadian legal publishers.  QuickLaw's LAW/NET bulletin board service includes: &quot; Supreme Court of Canada decisions, which are added within minutes of their release by the court, as well as major court and tribunal decisions and related public documents which are added within two to ten days of being received from the court or tribunal&quot;.
<p>
Learning effective QuickLaw search strategies will save you time (and money, if you are at a law firm) as well as ensure that you receive the best results possible for your search. 
<p>
Searching QuickLaw can be divided into three basic operations:
<p>	
	1) Query Preparation <br>
	2) Examining search results<br>
	3) Downloading and printing<br>
<p>
<h3>1) Query Preparation:</h3>
<p>
<b>a) Identify the exact legal issue you wish to research.</b>
 <p>  
 Write down the concepts or keywords that describe your research problem best. For example, if you are searching for  cases in which a doctor was sued for performing an operation that resulted in the amputation of a limb, your keywords would include <b>doctor, malpractice, amputation and limb.</b>
<p>
<b>b) Look for synonyms and alternate expressions.</b>
<p>	
In this example you would also look for the words <B>physician or surgeon and negligence and leg or arm</B>. You do not want to miss any cases where an alternate term is used.
<p>
<b>c) Decide if any of the words in your query should be truncated to retrieve the various endings for a word root. </b>
<p>	
In QuickLaw the truncation command is represented by an exclamation point <B>(!)</B>.  In our example the word amputation can be truncated to <b>amputat!</B> to retrieve the words amputate, amputated, amputating, etc.
<p>
<b>d) Choose appropriate connectors <B>(AND, OR, proximity indicator)</B> for the word groups.</b>
<p>	
The <B>AND</B> connector specifies that both terms on either side of the <B>AND</B> must appear somewhere within the same document (e.g. drunk AND driving). 
<p>
QuickLaw reads a space between two words as an implicit <B>OR</B>. The implicit <B>OR</B> requires that at least one (or more) of your search words occurs in a document  (e.g. doctor physician surgeon).  
<p>
The proximity indicator offers a method to indicate in your query the proximity of one or more words to another word or group of words. For example, <B>charter /2 rights</B> will look for charter within 2 words of rights; <B>biological natural /10 father</B> will look for either the word biological or natural within 10 words of father.
<p>
<b>e) Determine if field searching is required.</b> 
<p>	
Databases on QuickLaw may contain up to 8 fields. Field searching allows you to limit your search. To restrict your search to a particular field use the <B>@</B> symbol followed by the field number. Usually field 2 is the style of cause, field 3 is the citation field, field 4 is the field containing the judge, court and date information. To see what the fields are available in a particular database type <B>F</B> when you are in the database and a listing of the fields will be provided. If, for example, in our sample search involving doctors and malpractice we wanted to restrict our search to 1994 decisions we would add <B>@4 1994</B> to our search string.
<p>
<b>f) The final step before going on-line and conducting your research is to determine which databases to search.</b>  	
<p>	
A good place to start, if you do not have a specific jurisdiction in mind, is to do a broad search in the DLR (Dominion Law Reports) database for reported decisions and the CJ (Canadian Judgments) database for unreported decisions. Once signed on to QuickLaw type <b>DB</b> and the database name to get into the database. There is an online database list <B>(DBL)</B> that describes what databases are available on QuickLaw.
<p>
Our final search query would look like this: <b>doctor physician surgeon and malpractice negligence and amputat! /10 limb arm leg and @4 1994 </b>
<p>
<h3>2) Examining Search Results:</h3>
<p>
Once you have prepared a search query you can go online and execute your search in an appropriate database.  To execute your search, type in the search terms that you have chosen and press enter.  You will then see a screen which indicates the number of &quot;hits& quot; found by the system.
<p>
The next step is to examine your search results and determine if the cases retrieved are appropriate. If the documents retrieved are not relevant then you should modify your search. QuickLaw provides several useful commands to allow you to page through your documents to determine if they are relevant. Once you are in a document you can use the<b> (locate)</b> command to find your search words anywhere in the document and see the context in which they appear. Your keywords will be highlighted so they are easy to see. Another useful command is <b>H</b> (highlight). When you are in a document you can type <b>H</b>  and QuickLaw will let you highlight any term or terms. You can then search for those terms using the locate command to see if they appear anywhere in the document.
<p>
<h3>2a) Modifying a Search Query</h3>
<p>
If your search query returned no documents or the documents that were returned do not appear relevant then you can modify your search. To modify your search type <b>M</b> and your search query will be displayed on the screen. At this point you can edit your search. You will need to decide whether to add more terms or to truncate existing terms. Another option is to take your search query into a different database and see if you retrieve more documents there. To transfer your query to another database type <b> S DB xxx </B>(where xxx is the name of the new database). To begin a completely new search type <b>S </b>and you will be given a blank query screen to start over. To return to the main menu in QuickLaw type <b> DB.</b>
<p>
<h3>2b) Case History and Judicial Consideration - QuickCite</h3>
<p>
Once you have found a relevant case or cases you can also use a QuickLaw service called QuickCite to show the history of the case, its judicial treatment in other cases, and all its parallel citations and sub noms. Once in a document <b> C</b> for a display of the QuickCite record for the decision being displayed. Cases appearing in a QuickCite record will have a &quot;T&quot; number next to them. To view these cases type<b> Txxx</b> (where xxx is the number of the case). Once you are in the case you can  note it up as well by typing the C command. Type <b> GB</b> to go back one step in the chain until you return to your original document.
<p>
<h3>3) Downloading and Printing:</h3>
<p>
Retrieved documents may be downloaded to disk, transferred into a word processing package and then printed.
<p>
To download, enter one of the following commands:
<p>	
To download the current document 	displayed on your screen:  <b>PL</b><br>
To download a specific rank number from your list of retrieved documents: <b>PLn</b><br>
To download rank(n) through rank(n): <b>PLn-n</b><br>
To download all retrieved documents: <b>PLALL. </b><br>
<p>
When you execute a <b>PL</b> command you are prompted to Save Document(s) to disk or Send Document(s) to printer.  If you select Save Document(s) to disk, you will be prompted to issue a file name and the QuickLaw document(s) will be saved as a text file. You should download retrieved documents to a file and print the file after you disconnect from QuickLaw. This will allow you to retrieve a downloaded file into word processing software where you may reformat the text and then print. If you try printing from QuickLaw and there is a problem (e.g. your connection is terminated or the printer jams) then you may have to re-establish your connection and start your search process all over again.
<p>
To restrict downloading to the first and last page and only those pages where a search term(s) appears type <b>TL</b> (term locate)  and then hit the return key; then type one of the commands listed above <b> (i.e. PL, Pln, Pln-n, PLALL). </b>
<p>
To download certain fields only, enter one of the following commands first then enter one of the PL commands.
<p>
<b>NH </b>= no header (this removes the Rank line) <br>
<b>LC</b>  = list cases (restricts display to fields 2, 3 and 4: title, citation and judge-court-date) <br>
<b>HNC</b>=  = headnote command (restricts display to fields 2, 3, 4 and 6: Keywords/Headnote). <br>
<p>
Once you have downloaded the desired files type FULL  to return to full display.
<p>
To log-off QuickLaw type OFF. Then exit the QuickLink software by choosing Exit or Quit from the File Menu.    
<p>


<p>
