<img align = left src = "../icons/libgry5.gif"><center><h1><cite>LawLink</cite></h1>
<h3>The Newsletter of the Bora Laskin Law Library<br>

University of Toronto</h3><p>
<a href = "http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca">[Bora Laskin Law Library]</a> <a href = "http://www.utoronto.ca/">[University of Toronto]</a></center>
<br clear = "all">
<p><center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<h3>November 1995, Volume 2 Number 3</h3>

<h2>Contents</h2>
<dl>
<dd><a href = "v2n3.htm #virus">Net-iquette: Guidelines for using E-Mail and for Controlling the Spread of Computer Viruses</a>
<dd><a href = "v2n3.htm #Thomas">United States Legislative Documents on the Internet</a>
</dl>
<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "virus"> Net-iquette: Guidelines for using E-Mail and for Controlling the Spread of Computer Viruses </a></h2></center>

<h3><center>
By Gian Medves<br>
Computer Services Librarian</h3></center>

Both e-mail and the Internet can be valuable tools for law students and legal researchers.  E-mail allows students to communicate with colleagues around the world and to subscribe to various law-related discussion groups. The Internet makes it possible to locate law-related sources of information worldwide. 
<p>
Use of  e-mail and the Internet carries certain responsibilites. E-mail should not be used as a forum to harass, abuse or offend others either intentionally or by accident. In addition, students should exercise caution when using the Internet as they may inadvertently download viruses onto their own computers or those in the lab.
<p>
Here are some guidelines for students when using electronic mail and some tips on how to avoid computer viruses.
<P>
<h3>E-Mail Confidentiality</h3>
 <p>
It is important to keep in mind that e-mail is not  confidential. Postmasters of mail systems are able to monitor and read any mail being handled by their post office. If you do not delete unwanted messages or if you save messages onto the hard drive in the Computer Lab, your e-mail can be read by other students.
<p>
<h3>E-Mail Etiquette</h3>
<p>
On the Internet, there are observed rules of e-mail etiquette called &quot; netiquette.&quot;  If you don't observe these rules, you will usually be admonished strongly by other Internet users.
<p>
The following guidelines are provided by the University of Toronto's Computing and Communications Centre and are intended to make people aware of some of the consequences of their actions when transmitting information through electronic mail.
<ul>
<li>Keep your messages short and to the point. Be clear in what you say and ask for. Ambiguous or vague questions often lead to no response at all.
<p>
<li>Be aware of the effects of upper-case letters in words. Depending on the context, the use of ALL CAPITALS will lead the reader to believe that you may be either shouting, highlighting an important point, or distinguishing a title or a heading. Some commonly used e-mail short forms appear in capitals, such as &quot;IMHO&quot; (in my honest opinion) and &quot;BTW&quot; (by the way).
<p>
<li>Limit the length of your lines of text because the lines could get truncated if they are too long for the recipient's e-mail software to handle.
<p>
<li>Do not use academic networks for commercial or proprietary work.
<p>
<li>Add your &quot; electronic&quot;  signature to the end of your messages. A signature should include your name, e-mail address, position and affiliation, and should not exceed four lines. This signature provides information on how others can get in touch with you.
<p>
<li>Be aware that sarcasm and humour do not work because computers cannot convey the inflection or tone in a person's voice, nor can they transmit facial expressions, gestures, or body language. Without the benefit of face-to-face communication, your joke may be viewed as a criticism. One way in which humour or mood is sometimes denoted in electronic mail is with the use of faces constructed from standard keyboard characters, such as the ones following this sentence: :-)  :-(  :-O  ;-)  :-} (Look sideways to view them.)
<p>
<li>Be careful of what you say about others.
<p>
<li>Use discretion when forwarding mail to group addresses or distribution lists. Do not forward mail without the author's permission. 
<p>
<li>Observe the behaviour of your e-mail correspondents for clues to what is appropriate. Inappropriate mail is often responded to with "flames," i.e. antagonistic criticism preceded by the warning text &quot; [FLAME ON] &quot;.</ul>
<p>
<h3>Virus Control</h3>
<p>
Computer viruses are malicious programs (or sets of instructions) which can be passed from machine to machine. These programs are generally designed to; replicate themselves, display messages, destroy data or software, or inhibit access by the user of the system. 
<p>
Computers in the Lab have virus protection software. However, it will only catch known viruses. New viruses are harder to stop. Usually, the only way to become aware of a new virus is to witness the damage it causes. At this point the remedy is to reformat the hard drive thereby losing any text files on that machine. It is important for students to make and keep regular backups of important files.
<p>
<h3>How can you tell if your machine is infected? </h3>
<p>
Recognizing that a system is infected by a virus depends on the type of virus itself. Some examples of known viruses and their effect include: 
<p>
The Stoned Virus: One version of this virus randomly displays the message "Your PC is stoned" on the screen. Ping Pong Virus: This virus plays a Ping Pong game on your screen. Cascade Virus: This virus manifests itself by randomly dropping characters from your screen to the bottom of the screen creating a pile of letters at the bottom. Some viruses, known as &quot;stealth&quot;   viruses, hide themselves on a system and are triggered on a specific date, for example the Friday the 13th Virus. Some viruses may result in slower response time as they tie up your system's resources. Others can prevent you from accessing files by altering directories and file tables.
<p>
<h3>Here are a number of ways in which a machine can become infected:</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>Using an infected diskette on a machine (infected diskettes are the most common way viruses are spread from machine to machine.)<p>
<li>Downloading infected software from a Bulletin <p>
<li>Board or using infected shareware<p>
<li>Pirating computer games.</ul> 
<p>
<h3>What should you do if you suspect that a virus has infected your machine? </h3>
<p>
Acquire the most recent virus detection and desinfectant program and install it on your computer.
If you are in the lab and suspect the computer has  a virus, stop using your machine and inform library staff.
<p>
<h3>What can you do to prevent your machine from becoming infected? </h3>
<p><ul>
<li>Back up your files regularly (at least weekly). Make separate backups of your data files and your software and store your backup diskettes in a safe and secure place away from your machine. Backups may be the only way to recover infected systems
<p>
<li>Do not use illegal or &quot; pirated &quot;software on your machine. This is against University policy.
<p>
<li>Do not use shareware programs unless you are absolutely sure that the programs are free of viruses.
<p>
<li>If you download programs from Bulletin Boards or other sites on the Internet, scan them for viruses before you use them. Download  the files to a temporary directory or to floppy disk then scan these files for a virus.
<p>
<li>If you bring any diskettes from home, scan them for viruses before using them in the lab.
<p>
<li>When you get new software for your machine, make sure it is shrink-wrapped and check the diskettes before using them on your computer.
<p>
<li>Make sure that your diskettes with software programs on them are write-protected. This prevents viruses from being copied onto the diskettes.
<p>
<li>If your &quot;new&quot; machine is in reality a recycled one, ask the individual installing your machine to do a &quot;low-level format&quot; of the hard drive. This will destroy any viruses that may be on the hard drive as well as get rid of illegal copies of software. If your &quot;new&quot; machine comes pre-loaded with software or if the hard drive is pre-formatted, scan the hard drive for viruses before you start using the machine.
<p>
<li>If you are sharing diskettes with someone else or if you use your diskettes on someone else's machine or a machine which is part of a &quot;pool&quot;, scan your diskettes before using them on your machine.
<p>
<li>If you know that your machine or any of your diskettes are infected or if you suspect a viral infection, do not use your diskettes on another PC. Your diskettes are most probably infected too and all you will accomplish is to spread the virus and infect someone else's machine!
<p>
<li>Do not boot your machine with a diskette that has not been scanned for viruses even if you think the diskette only contains data. Never boot your machine from a diskette created on another machine.
<p>
<li>If you normally boot your machine from the hard drive, make sure that there isn't a diskette in your diskette drive.
<p>
<li>Public-domain software should not be used until it is tested and labeled &quot;clean&quot;.
<p>
<li>All software should be acquired from reputable dealers. Non-shrink-wrapped software may be infected although there are known incidents involving spreading of viruses through shrink-wrapped software
</ul>
<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "thomas"> United States Legislative Documents on the Internet </a></h2></center>
<p>
The United States Library of Congress has recently introduced a legislative information service on the Internet URL=<a href="http://thomas.loc.gov/">(http:thomas.loc.gov/)</a>. This service named in honour of Thomas Jefferson includes links to the following information:
<p>
<h3>Text of Legislation</h3>
<p>
Full text of all versions of House and Senate bills searchable by keyword(s) or by bill number.
<ul><li>103rd Congress Bills
<li>104th Congress Bills</ul>
<p>
<h3>Full Text of the Congressional Record</h3><p>

Full text of the daily account of proceedings on the House and Senate floors searchable by keyword(s).
<ul><li>Congressional Record for the 103rd Congress
<li>Congressional Record for the 104th Congress
<li>Congressional Record Index for the 103rd Congress (1994)
<li>Congressional Record Index for the 104th Congress</ul>
<p>
<h3>Bill Summary and Status  [New]</h3>
<p>
Digests and legislative history of bills and amendments, searchable by keyword, index term, bill/amendment number, sponsor/co-sponsor, or committee/subcommittee.
<ul><li>Bill Summary and Status for the 104th Congress</ul>
<p>
<h3>Hot Legislation</h3>
<p>
Major bills receiving floor action in the 104th Congress as selected by legislative analysts in the Congressional Research Service.
<ul><li>Hot bills by topic
<li>Hot bills by popular and/or short title
<li>Hot bills by number/type
<li>Hot bills enacted into law
<li>Hot bills under Congressional consideration this week.</ul>
<p>
<h3>The Constitution of the United States</h3>
<p>
The full text of the Constitution and its amendments, searchable by keyword.
<p>
<h3>How Our Laws Are Made  By Edward F. Willett, Jr., House Law Revision Counsel</h3>
	
An explanation of the lawmaking process from the origin of a legislative proposal through its publication as a law. 
<p>
<h3>U.S. House of Representatives</h3>
<p>
<ul>
<li>House World Wide Web Service,  House Gopher, House Constituent E-Mail Directory, and House of Representatives Audit (Office of the Inspector General Financial Statements and Performance Reports).</ul>
<p>
<h3>U.S. Senate</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>Senate World Wide Web Service, Senate Gopher, and Senate Constituent E-Mail Addresses.</ul>
<p>
<h3>CSPAN (Cable-Satellite Public Affairs Network)</h3>
<p>
<ul><li>C-SPAN Gopher provides program schedules, Congressional information, Federal Election Commission Reports, Supreme Court information and historical government documents. C-SPAN Web Server offers program and events schedules, Campaign '96 info, and other political resources.</ul>
<p>
<h3>Updates</h3><p>
 THOMAS receives text of legislation files several times daily and the text of the Congressional Record once daily when Congress is in session; files are processed and made available immediately upon receipt from the Government Printing Office.





