office: located in the CD-Rom Alcove</center>

<h3>Call for Volunteers</h3>

Are there any law students who are interested in volunteering some of their time, preferably evenings and weekends, to help with keeping the computer lab networks up and running?  Students will be trained in basic troubleshooting on the Macs and PC's and the printers. Interested students can call Gian at 978-5537 or drop by his office. 
<p>
Why you should volunteer
<p>
1) You will be able to "fix" things when you desperately need to print your paper or factum and the deadline is fast approaching. <br>
2) It will look good on your resume.<br> 
3) You will be helping fellow students<br>

<h3>Lexis/Nexis Passwords</h3>

Lexis/Nexis passwords have arrived.  Those students who applied for Lexis/Nexis passwords can pick them up from Gian between 9:00 am and 5:00 pm - Monday to Friday. Students wishing to acquire a Lexis/Nexis password can pick up an application form at the Circulation Desk.
<p>
<h3>UTORmail</h3>
<p>
Students can access UTORmail from either the Macs or the PC's in the lab. The software for accessing UTORmail on the Macs is Eudora 1.4.1. The instructions for configuring Eudora are available in the lab. The software for accessing UTORMail on the PC's is ECSMail 2.4. 
<p>
The PC's in the lab are "shared" machines; therefore students must configure and personalize ECSMail each time they use it. If you do not personalize ECSMail, you will encounter problems connecting to the mail server (i.e. you will get a message saying your user id or password is invalid). Or if you do happen to connect, then any messages sent will have someone else's name in the message header. See the PC lab manual for instructions on how to personalize ECSMail.
<p>
<h3>Computer Lab Etiquette</h3>
<p>
We have had several reports of law students abusing their computer lab privileges. The Library Rules of Conduct indicate that inappropriate behaviour may be sanctioned.  Excessive noise and abusive behaviour will not be tolerated. 
<p>
Please be aware that you must sign up for a computer whether you are using a Mac or a PC.  If you have not signed up for the computer that you are using you have no right to be there.  Who-ever has signed up for the computer in the appropriate manner is entititled to use that computer and to ask you to move. 
<p>
Further, we have heard that students are staying beyond their allotted time period. Just a reminder: students can only sign  for 2-hour blocks of computer time.  If you have signed for a specific block and find that your computer is already occupied, please ask the user to vacate the site immediately.  If you encounter opposition, call the Circulation Desk for help.
<p>
We have found evidence of food and drink in the lab. While it is tempting to eat as you work, DON'T DO IT!   The problem is twofold:  the food attracts rodents and vermin which can do extensive damage throughout the Library, and the drinks can so easily spill and damage the computers. So PLEASE DO NOT EAT OR DRINK IN THE COMPUTER LAB  OR ELSEWHERE IN THE LIBRARY.  The money we save on damage control  will benefit all of us.
<p>
The  lab security rules were established to protect the equipment and avoid the problems of vandalism and viruses, so please follow them. Do not prop the door open for your friends since this defeats the whole purpose of a secured room.  If you see anyone in the lab who is not a law student or faculty/staff member, please report this to the Circulation Desk. 
<p>
The computer lab rules exist for your benefit.  The computer lab is your facility.  Its smooth operation depends on your abiltity to cooperate with your fellow students and to follow the appropriate procedures. 
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "Justice"> Canada's Department of Justice
 Introduces its New Home Page </a></h2></center>

The Justice Department has recently unveiled its new home page on the World Wide Web URL= <a href="http://canada.justice.gc.ca/">http://canada.justice.gc.ca/</a>  Its purpose is to "furnish citizens of Canada and of the world with information originating with the federal Department of Justice".
<p>
This home page contains a number of useful resource items for the legal researcher.  These include:
<ul>
<p>
<h3>Overview of the Department of Justice</h3>	
<p>
<li>News from the Department of Justice
<li>Recent Speeches
<li>Press Releases
<li>Judicial Appointments
<li>Subscription to JUSTICE-L
<p>	 
<h3>Government Initiatives</h3>
<P>
<li>Crime Prevention
<li>Dispute Resolution Project
<li>Law Reform and Multiculturalism
<p>
<h3>Laws</h3>
<p>	     
<h3>Bills and New Statutes</h3>
<li>DNA Bill
<p>
<h3>Consultations</h3>
<p>	 
<h3>Recent Department of Justice Conferences</h3>
<p>	
<li>Justice on the Electronic Highway
<li>Symposium on Digital Technolgies and Copyright (coming soon)
<p>
<h3>Publications</h3>
<p>
<li>Crown Counsel Policy Manual
<li>Information and Education Documents
<li>Reports and Analyses
<li>Other Publications
<p>
<h3>Other Resources in Canadian Law</h3>
<p>
<li>The Access to Justice Network (ACJNet) 
<li>Supreme Court of Canada 
<li>The Research Center in Public Law 
<p>
The Laws section of this home page will be extremely valuable to legal  researchers. It
contains:
<p>
<li>  Constitutional Laws of Canada (1867 - 1982): annotated and consolidated version of the Constitution of Canada, including the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, as prepared by the Department of  Justice (updated September 1, 1993).
<li>Criminal Code
<li>Consolidated Statutes
<li>Explanations on Statutes Structure
</ul><p>
The Consolidated Statutes section is particularly useful; it contains the "consolidated Acts updated to April 1995 as well as Acts of public general application that have been enacted since the 1985 revision". However, before using this service, you should be aware of the following warning: 
<p>
<b>"This consolidation has been prepared for convenience of reference only and has no official sanction.  For all purposes of interpreting and applying the law, users should consult the Acts as passed by Parliament, which are published in the "Assented to" Act Service, Part III of the Canada Gazette and the Annual Statutes of Canada and available in most public libraries."</b>
<p>
It also does not include the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> and other acts still in force but not included in the 1985 or earlier revisions.
<p>
The consolidated statutes section is searchable using Folio VIEWS just like the CD-ROM version of the statutes that the library has available.  Through Folio VIEWS you can go directly to a particular statute through the contents icon.  If you are looking for a topic you can do a search through the query icon.  Once your search is completed you can view the results by clicking on the document icon.  If you get stuck, there is a useful help section, which will walk you through the search process.
<p>
This home page is up-to-date as of June 1995 and according to the Department of Justice will be updated regularly.
<p>
