<h2><a name = "Welcome"> Welcome To All  Students  And Faculty,  Both New And Returning.</a></h2></center>

Those of you who have been reading <cite>LawLink</cite>  during the past year know that it contains a wealth of useful and timely information on developments in legal research and new legal information sources as well as library announcements. Because new technologies are offering more and more to the legal scholar and researcher, the emphasis in <cite>LawLink</cite>  has been decidedly electronic and will continue to be.
<p>
For the coming year, while students and faculty continue to &quot;get connected&quot;, we will bring <cite>LawLink</cite>  to you in paper format. The issues will also be available on the Library's World Wide Web page (see Anne Johnston's article in this issue) where we will attempt to provide hyperlinks to sources on the Internet that we mention in <cite>LawLink</cite> articles. By this time next year we expect you will be consulting <cite>LawLink</cite> online.
<p>
<cite>LawLink</cite>  appears 9 times a year. If any of you have research-related information to share with your colleagues, we hope you will think of contributing it to <cite>LawLink</cite>  by contacting our editor, Susan Barker. We are always anxious to receive your feedback and suggestions for making the newsletter as useful to you as possible.
<p>
Ann Rae,
Law Librarian
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "cyberspace"> The Bora Laskin Law Library
and  U of T's  Faculty of Law Enter Cyberspace </a></h2> by Anne Johnston </center>
<p>
<I>One of the library's summer projects was the creation of a World Wide Web (otherwise known as WWW or the Web) Home Page for the Faculty  and the Library.  Anne Johnston, who is the library's World Wide Web technician  and who has now joined the Information Services  Department as a circulation assistant, has written the following article which explains a little about the Web and describes our new home pages.</I>
 <p>
The Web is part of the Internet that utilizes  hypertext links to navigate cyberspace. It also uses multimedia (text, images, animation and sound) as a method of presenting information through Web pages. Web pages can be viewed via a variety of different browsers ranging from inline text browsers like Lynx, to sophisticated graphical user interface browsers such as Netscape, Mosaic and Cello.  Inline text browsers provide simple hypertext  links to the Web.  Graphical user interfaces like Netscape or Mosaic can best handle the multimedia aspects of the World Wide Web.  
<p>
Web pages are designed using HTML (HyperText Markup Language). HTML codes tell the browser how to display information presented in a page. HTML is an evolving language. Its specifications are being updated at an incredible rate. The Library and Faculty of Law pages, were designed using HTML 3.0 . This means that these pages are designed to take advantage of  Netscape's enhanced features and are best viewed using Netscape 1.1N  (available in the computer lab).
<p>
Individuals, corporate bodies and academic institutions present themselves to the Internet surfing community by means of WWW home pages. They usually provide introductory information and may contain multimedia elements including graphics, pictures, sound, as well as links to other documents. Links are words or images which are highlighted or underlined.  When clicked on with a mouse, these links will then connect to other documents. Home pages can also be located directly using a URL (Universal Resource Locator).
<p>
The Bora Laskin Law Library's Home Page URL=<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/</a>  includes:
<ul>	
<li>History of the library.
<li>Library hours.
<li>Library collection and UTCat.
<li>Loan periods and borrowing privileges.
<li><cite>LawLink.</cite>
<li>Useful law-related Internet sites, including law schools, legal materials, government documents and data, law journals and law associations, societies and organizations.
<li>Past Exams (April 1995 so far, more to come).
</ul>
 
The Faculty of Law Home Page URL =<a href= "http://www.law.utoronto.ca"> http://www.law.utoronto.ca</a> contains links to:
<ul>	
<li>The Faculty of Law Calendar.
<li>The Syllabus.
<li>Biographies of faculty, visitors and special lecturers.
<li>Faculty publications.
</ul>
Future additions will include:
<ul>
<li>What's New? 
<li>The Faculty's calendar of events.
<li>December 1994 exams.
<li>Reading lists (if available).
<li>University of Toronto, Faculty of Law Review.
</ul>
Please check out these pages and let us know what you think. Comments and suggestions can be sent to <a href="mailto: law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca.</a> If you find Internet sites that you think are interesting and relevant, please let Anne know either at the address above or at the circulation desk.  
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
