<h2><a name = "cdrom">CD-Rom Services at the Bora Laskin Law Library</a></h2></center>
The Bora Laskin Law Library has added many new services in our onging efforts to provide patrons with access to information through the latest  technology.  This issue of <cite>LawLink</cite>  will focus on the CD-Rom facilities available for use at the Law Library.  CD-Roms are fast and efficient research tools.  Research that could take up valuable time is finished in seconds.  When you are working on a paper or an assignment it pays to make use of the library's latest technology.  
<p>
Library patrons can use these CD-Rom services at the six workstations in the &quot;Online Services and CD-ROMS&quot; section of the library. Professors, graduate and undergraduate students at the University of Toronto, Faculty of Law also have full access to these CD's via the network in the computer lab.  Library users can print items retrieved from the CD-Roms,  but licensing restrictions prevent the library from allowing patrons to download material to disk. Although this new technology may seem daunting at first, the Reference Staff are available to provide training or answer any questions that you might have about our CD-Rom collection. 
<p>
The following is a list of all of the CD-Rom products that are available in the library as of June 14, 1995.  
<p>
<center><h3>General Subject CD's</h3></center>
<h4>Canadian Law List - 1994</h4>
<dl>
