<h2><a name = "govt">Introducing Government Information in Canada: A New Electronic Journal on the Web</a></h2>
<h3>By Esther Wan<br>
Coordinator, Information Services</h3></center>
<cite>Government Information in Canada/Information Gouvernementale au Canada</cite> is a new electronic journal. It is  available on the Web at the following URL: <i>http://www.usask.ca/library/gic/index.html</i>.
<p>
The inaugural issue of this journal was released in the summer of 1994 and is a quarterly publication in electronic format. Each issue contains  information, discussion and debate on issues surrounding public access to information from all levels of government in Canada.  Contributors to the journal come from, academia, government, and the private sector.  
<p>
The editors have chosen to keep this journal entirely in electronic format for a number of reasons: &quot;Electronic publishing makes a significant part of the work (and cost) of a journal, in particular printing and distribution, essentially trivial... It is unlikely that the market in Canada can support a full-scale, conventional, paper journal in this area ... [and]... it is unclear who might publish such a journal..&quot;  The editors believe that the journal will &quot;...derive its legitimacy, not from its affiliations [but by] the quality of its contents and the integrity of the editorial process.&quot;
<p>
According to this journal's copyright policy, it's contents may be freely copied and distributed on condition that the journal and its contents remain unaltered, that the journal and its authors are credited, and that there is no charge for the journal or its contents. However, the rights for reprints for profit are reserved to the authors. Essentially then, this non-subscription journal is free for world-wide distribution!  You can obtain a copy of an article by having it sent to you by e-mail, sent to a local file, or printed from the screen.
<p>
In the Internet world where files magically appear and disappear constantly, it will be very interesting to see how successful this journal will be. Can an electronic journal survive?
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "parl">Changes to the Parliamentary  Publications Programme Recently Announced by Ottawa.</a></h2>
<h3>by Ann Morrision<br>
Associate Librarian</h3></center>
Severe cut-backs to the Parliamentary Publications Programme were announced on March 22nd by The Honourable Gilbert Parent, Speaker of the House of Commons and Chairman of the Board of  Internal Economy. Effective April 1st 1995, the evidence portion of the Minutes of Proceedings and Evidence of Standing Committees will no longer be published.  Transcripts and their simultaneous translations will be available only to Members of Parliament, research staff and members of the Parliamentary Press Gallery.
<p>
In future, only the minutes of standing committee meetings will be published.  Typically, minutes are one page notices of where and when a particular committee met, who was there and who spoke.  The evidence portion, which was a verbatim record of committee proceedings, will no longer be published.  Therefore, lawyers, students, researchers and any member of the public who wish to find out what issues were discussed,  and what decisions or policy recommendations were made by these committees, will have no ready access to this information.  
<p>
Mr. Boudria M.P., spokesperson for the Board of Internal Economy indicated that these changes were made &quot;to further the board's commitment to streamline and modernise the operations of the House of Commons while reducing costs to the taxpayer&quot;. This all sounds very sensible and fiscally responsible.  However, cancelling the publication of the evidence portion  of the Minutes of Proceedings and Evidence of Committees means that the Canadian public has no access to a vast amount of important  information. 
<p>
This decision to cut these publications is of great interest to librarians across Canada. They are concerned that in the name of fiscal restraint, all access to federal parliamentary proceedings will be denied.  This concern has been translated into action as librarians and library associations are contacting members of parliament, the Prime Minister, the Hon. Lucien Bouchard, Mr. Robert Marleau, Clerk of the House of Commons,  Mr. Peter Milliken, Chair of the House of Commons Committee on Procedure and House Affairs and Mr. Bruno Gnassi, Assistant Director of the Depository Services Programme, to express their concerns.  
<P>
No response has been received yet, but  Mr. Bob Desiamaux, Director of Communications of the  Speaker's Office, has indicated that these transcripts of evidence might be available eventually on the Internet, and discussions are being held with the Canadian Library Association regarding the possibility of eventually putting the transcripts on CD-ROM.
<p>
However, since publication of  the transcripts of evidence stopped as of April lst , the hope of reviving publication in another form seems very slim indeed.  The question now is - can Hansard be far behind?
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "taxpart">Carswell TaxPartner CD-ROM</a></h2>
<h3>Reviewed by<br>
Esther Wan, Coordinator, Information Services</h3></center>
TaxPartner is a comprehensive tool for Canadian tax researchers which incorporates Carswells major tax publications in a single resource on compact disc.  TaxPartner includes:
<ul>
<li>Income Tax Act
<li>Income Tax Regulations
<li>Income Tax Application Rules
<li>Selected Income Tax Remission Orders
<li>Income Tax Cases
<li>Income Tax Treaties
<li>Income Tax Conventions Interpretation Act
<li>Revenue Canada Views
<li>Department of Finance Technical Notes
<li>Interpretation Bulletins
<li>Information Circulars
<li>Advance Tax Rulings
<li>Canada Tax Service - Stikeman Analysis
</ul>
TaxPartner is updated monthly to ensure that the most up-to-date information is available .
<p>
TaxPartner uses the FolioViews 3.1 (Windows version) software as a means to navigate through the database and to search for particular material.  Library users may already be familiar with this type of searching. The Canada Statute Citator, the B.C. Statutes, and the Ontario Statute Citator infobases,  which are all currently available on the CD-workstations in the library use FolioViews software. 
<p>
The windows version of FolioViews gives the researcher the choice of using pull down menus, keystroke commands or the &quot;toolbelt&quot;, which is a panel of command option icons  on the left hand side of the screen.  FolioViews allows the user,  in addition to using the traditional method of reading a file screen by screen, to choose to &quot;jump&quot; between related documents on the infobase via hypertext links. For example, a section of the Income Tax Act may be linked editorially to other sections of the Act, to regulations, application rules, or leading court decisions on the topic in question. The user can move backwards and forwards between related documents by double clicking the mouse pointer on the appropriately marked icon.  In TaxPartner, a feather or text marked in green indicate a hypertext link.  FolioViews hypertext links and the windows environment make TaxPartner easy to use without extensive training, however, the first time user might still want to spend a bit of time looking through Carswell's accompanying documentation before beginning a search. 
<p>
To locate materials on this infobase, researchers have the choice of searching by table of contents or by keyword. The table of contents is the most straight-forward method for locating text on TaxPartner.  Clicking on the contents icon in the toolbelt brings up a general table of contents for the infobase.  Each item on the list is marked with a plus (+) sign which indicates that there is more infomation to be found under that heading.  A double click on the heading will reveal the sub-headings available.  Repeating this process will  lead to a single document which can be read screen by screen. 
<p>
Keyword searching is more time-efficient. First make sure that you are not in the table of contents mode.  Click on the &quot;query&quot; icon on the toolbelt and a search menu will appear. Enter the terms that you wish to search. TaxPartner will display all records containing the keywords in your search.  To move from one record to the next,  click on the scrollbar or on the &quot;next&quot;  or &quot;previous&quot; icons on the toolbelt.   TaxPartner  allows field searches (by case name, case citation, section number, or information circular number). Undoubtedly, Carswell's new TaxPartner will shave more than a few precious minutes off research time. Please drop by the Library and let us know what you think!
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "computer">Computer Lab Update</a></h2>
<h3>By Gian Medves<br>
Computer Services Librarian</h3></center>
Students may have noticed something new in the Computer Lab - Colour.  Due in part to a grant from the Provost's office, the Library has purchased 9  PCs and 9 Macintosh LC 630s. Each computer has a colour monitor, 12 - 16 megabytes of RAM, a network card, and upgraded software. The new computers will be in compliance with the  University's minimum requirements in order to provide students with access to new client server based software like UTORmail, UTLink and the Internet.
<p>
Law students will find that the new computers provide them with more computing power, more versatile word processing packages and greater access to legal information, whether it be available on commercial databases, on CD-ROM or on the Internet.
<p>
The new PCs come equipped with Windows for Workgroups as the main operating environment. The word processing packages available include Microsoft Word 6.0, WordPerfect for Windows 6.1 and WordPerfect 5.1 (DOS). These PCs have ethernet cards and are connected to the Library's Local Area Network (LAN) as well as the University's central network (UTORNet). These PCs can access Lexis/Nexis, Quicklaw and the Library's CD-ROM collection which includes such items as LegalTrac, the Statutes of Canada, British Columbia and Ontario, Carswell's Tax Partner, The Canadian Law List, and the UN Human Rights Bibliography (more titles will be added in future). In addition, students can travel the Internet via Netscape (an Internet browser) and access their e-mail via ECS-mail. Students can access the Library's online public access catalogue (UTCAT) via Telnet software.
<p>
On the Mac side of things the new LC 630s are System 7.5 machines and have the AT EASE software as a front end menu. These Macs are also connected to the Library's LAN and UTORNet. Lexis/Nexis and Quicklaw access is available as is Netscape for surfing the Net. Eudora 1.4.1 is the student e-mail software package available. The problem with sending e-mail messages longer than a screen has been fixed. In order to run Eudora students will have to exit the At EASE menu and run Eudora from their disks as before. The word processing package on these Macs is Microsoft Word 6.0. The LC 630s come equipped with super drives that will read an IBM disk so students working on Microsoft Word 6.0 on an IBM can bring their disks to a Mac and work on them there as well. The LC630s also have a conversion package called MacLink 8.0  that will translate a wide variety of word processing files. Students can access the Librarys online public access catalogue (UTCAT) via NCSA Telnet  2.5. The Library's CD-ROM titles will not be accessible from the Macs as most of the CD-ROMs are DOS or Windows based.
<p>
With these upgrades the Library has moved closer to its goal of providing law students with a <i>scholar's workstation</i> where they can do legal research online, retrieve relevant information and then incorporate that research into their papers with powerful and versatile word processing software.
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
