<h3>World Wide Web Site at the University of Alberta</h3>
The following is a description of the world wide web site at the University of Alberta Faculty of Law.  Brent Pookhay, the computer instruction specialist at the Faculty, is developing the site, and has prepared this description. 
<p>
The World Wide Web (WWW) project makes multimedia, hypertext documents available
over the Internet. At the Faculty of Law, we have developed two WWW sites for our students, 
staff, and interested individuals throughout the world.
<p>
The first site is the Law Faculty Information System. It contains everything you would ever want to know about our faculty. It includes course listings and descriptions for every section of every course we offer. It also includes profiles of all faculty, including pictures and sometimes some sound clips as well! Students can keep up to date with what's happening around the school by clicking on the Law Centre Events link on our Web. There is also detailed information on all our special programs and research centres including the John Weir Library, the Health Law Institute, Centre for Constitutional Studies, Law Reform Institute, and the Indigenous Law Program.
<p>
We have also developed The Electronic Easement, A Property Law WWW Site. This site deals with issues of property law and trusts. People from all over the globe post updates on recent case law and statutes, full text articles, upcoming conferences, sharing of teaching plans and course outlines, and much more. After browsing the site, users can discuss issues on the EASMNT-L listserv.
<p>
Addresses for the sites are as follows:
<dl>
<dt><h3>Law Info System</h3>
<dd>http://gpu.srv.ualberta.ca
<p>
<dt><h3>Electronic Easement</h3>
<dd>http://gpu.srv.ualberta.ca
</dl>
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "supreme">Supreme Court Decisions on the Internet</a></h2>
<h3>by Susan Barker<br>
Circulation Services Supervisor</h3></center>
It is now possible to get access to Supreme Court decisions through the gopher at the Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al, Facult&eacute; de droit, Centre de Recherche en Droit Public.  The database consists of decisions from January 1993 to the present.  The gopher at the Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al can be reached through Netscape in the computer lab or via UTlink, either from the public access catalogue terminals in the library or by dialing into UTLink from home.
<p>
Netscape is the simplest and most efficient way  to connect to the Universit&eacute; de Montr&ecaute;al Gopher.   Instructions on how to use Netscape are in the computer lab manual. You can dial directly into the Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al gopher on Netscape at the following URL: <i>http://www.droit.umontreal.ca/english.html</i>
<p>
Once you are connected, you will see a welcome screen and a list of services offered.  Select <cite>The Supreme Court of Canada (Experimental)</cite>  from the list and you will be taken to an introductory screen which gives you the option of &quot;selecting published rulings&quot; or  &quot;searching by key words&quot;.  If you choose the published rulings option, you will be connected to a menu which lists a number of volumes for you to choose from.  These volumes give you an alphabetical list which you can scroll through in order to find a particular decision. If you choose the search by keyword option, you will be taken to a screen which asks you to enter a search term.  You can search by keyword or keywords, partial word and also use the boolean connectors (and, or, not). With either method, once you have found the document you are looking for you can print or download it to disc by selecting either of these options from the Netscape file menu.
<p>
Outside the computer lab, you can access the Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al  gopher through UTLink.  When you are using  UTLink you must provide the first letter of your last name and the last eight digits of the barcode on the back of your library card to access the Internet.  The system is menu driven,  so you must go through quite a few layers to get to the Supreme Court decisions.  Although this system is is not as simple to use as Netscape, it  does have the advantage of being accessible from home.
<p>
To connect to the internet,  select Item #7  <i>UTLink Campus information system</i> from the main menu.  Once this is selected you will see a list of options, select  the last option on the list (Dir) <i>Internet................Local & Worldwide Connections; guide</i> by moving the curser down until this line is highlighted and press enter. Once you have accessed the <i>Internet and Worldwide connections; guide</i> you will see another menu.  Select: (Dir) <i>Connections to Worldwide Gophers  and Veronica (from U. Minnesota)</i>  and press enter.  Under that heading you will see another menu giving a choice of locations to search.   Select <i>North America</i> from the <i>Connections to Worldwide Gophers  and Veronica (from U. Minnesota)</i>  menu and <i>Canada</i> from the menu after that.  You will see an alphabetical list of gophers available. Using your arrow key, select  <i>&quot;Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al, Faculte de Droit, CRDP&quot;</i>  and you will be in the Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al gopher.  From this gopher main menu select (Dir) <i>Supreme Court of Canada (Experimental)</i>.  Once you are in the Supreme Court database, you have the option of searching the complete decisions index or browsing through a list of rulings. You can only search for a single word; for example,  a search with the words blood transfusion locates all the records with the word &quot;blood&quot; in them.  You cannot print or download from UTLink, but if you have an e-mail address you can mail a decision  to yourself and retrieve it from your mailbox.
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
