<h2><a name = "canadian">Canadian Legal Resources Available on the Internet</a></h2>
<h3>By Gian Medves<br>
Computer Services Librarian</h3></center>
There is a growing number of Canadian legal resources available on the Internet. Law students can access these resources from the Computer Lab via two software packages: <b>Netscape</b>  and <b>NCSA Telnet</b>.  <b>Netscape</b> is an Internet browser that enables you to search the Internet and retrieve files. It has a graphics interface and is quite easy to use. For further information on how to use Netscape refer to the section in the Computer Lab manual entitled Access to the Internet: Learning Netscape.  
<p>
A good place to start to access Canadian legal resources via Netscape is the WWW Virtual Law Library (at http://r106.law.unimelb.edu.au/HTML/virtual.html). (Instructions on how to connect to a WWW site can be found in the Computer Lab manual). Once connected you will see the following menu:
<p>
<h3>The WWW Virtual Library - Law</h3>
<p>
<h4>Topical Organizations</h4>
 <ul>
<li>Material Organized by Legal Topic (Constitutional Law, Copyright ...From the LII)
<li>Material Organized by Type or Source (Treaty, Legislation ... From the LII)
<li>Alphabetical Listing of Law Schools and Law Firms on the WWW
<li>United States Government Servers
<li>State Government Servers
<li>Law and Regulations from EINet Galaxy
<li><b>Yahoo - Law</b>
<li>Topical Index for Law from EINet Galaxy
<li><b>Law-on-the-WEB Master Index</b>
<li>Legal Resource Network
<li>The Seamless Web - Law
</ul>
A useful index of Canadian Legal materials is Yahoo - Law.  Click on Yahoo - Law  on the main WWW Virtual Law Library screen.  Then from the screen headed Law  select  Countries and then from the screen headed Countries select Canada. You will then see the following menu: 
<p>
<h4>Law: Countries: Canada</h4>
<ul>
<li>Canadian Legal and Government Resources
<li>Canadian Legal Resources
<li>Code Civil du Qu&eacute;bec
<li>Directory of Canadian Law Societies Directory of Canadian Law Societies including addresses and phone numbers.
<li>Documents@ (4)
<li>Law Notes - Canadian Legal News Letter
<li>Law-on-the-Web Project Master Index to Legal Resources
<li>Nova Scotia - Law Reform Commission responsible for carrying out the work of law reform in the province.
</ul>
Click on Canadian Legal Resources, you will see the following menu:
<p>
<h3>Canadian Legal Resources on WWW</h3>
<p>
<h4>Canadian Legal Information</h4>
<ul>
<li>News - can.legal
<li>AMG's Legal Resources on the Internet
<li>AMG's Directory of Law Societies in Canada
<li>Supreme Court of Canada
<li>Centre de recherche en droit public (U de Montreal)
<li>Canadian Constitutional Documents
<li>University of Manitoba - E.K. Williams Law Library
<li>University of Manitoba - Faculty of Law Information
<li>Revenue Canada Tax Forms (selection)
<li>University of Alberta Faculty of Law
<li>Newsletter of the Canadian Institute of Resources Law
<li>Citizenship and Immigration Information
<li>International Centre for Criminal Justice (University of British Columbia)
<li>Queen's University Faculty of Law
<li>Law Reform Commission of Nova Scotia
<li>Murphy Collette Murphy - Law Notes
</ul>
<h4>Canadian Government Documents</h4>
<ul>
<li>Open Government Project
<li>Department of Finance Home Page
<li>Government of Manitoba Home Page
<li>C.R.T.C. Materials
<li>Canadian Government Departments and Agencies
<li>Government of Canada Publications
<li>Report of the Auditor General
<li>Canadian Passport Offices
<li>Canada Communcations Group Publishing
<li>Immigration and Refugee Board
</ul>
<h4>Other Legal Sources with Canadian Content</h4>
<ul>
<li>Legal Information Institute at Cornell University
<li>WWW Virtual Law Library
<li>University of Sydney Faculty of Law
<li>Yahoo - Law
</ul>
<h4>Free Speech and Privacy on the Information Highway</h4>
<ul>
<li>Electronic Frontier Canada
<li>Electronic Frontier Foundation
<li>Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility
<li>Political Economy of the Information Highway
</ul>
Move the cursor to any one of the items on the list and click the mouse button,  you will then be taken directly to that particular site.
<p>
If you return to the <b>Law-on-the-WEB Master Index</b>  and select <b>Canadian Legal and Government Resources</b>,  you will connect to another interesting list of resources. The first screen you see will look like this:  
<p>
<h3>Canadian Legal Resources</h3>
<h4>Canadian Government Resources</h4>
<ul>
