<h2><a name = "lexis">LEXIS/NEXIS available in the Computer Lab</a></h2></center>

Lexis/Nexis provides access to case law, summaries, articles and legislation from around the world, including Canada, the United Kingdom, Australia, the United States, and the European Community, plus full-text documents from more than 2,400 sources worldwide including newspapers, magazines, and journals.
<p>
Lexis/Nexis is now available free of charge on 4 computers in the Computer Lab. Macintosh computers #11, 12, 13 and 14 provide free direct access to the Lexis/Nexis databases. Instructions on how to use Lexis/Nexis, including how to download and print cases and articles, have been placed next to the four computers. As well, two copies of the Lexis/Nexis database directory have been placed in the Lab. Students who would like more detailed information can check the Computer Lab Manual. The Library is preparing training sessions on how to use Lexis/Nexis. These sessions will be provided at some point this term if numbers warrant. A sign up sheet for those students who are interested in Lexis/Nexis training has been put up in the lab. If enough students sign up then we will schedule training sessions at a convenient time this term. Keep an eye on LawLink  and Headnotes  for announcements regarding Lexis/Nexis training.
<p>
<h3>Lexis/Nexis Legal Education Program - Passwords at a discounted rate:</h3>
Mead Data International, Inc. has introduced a new Educational Program for Canadian law schools. Students who wish to have their own Lexis/Nexis password can now do so. With their own password students can access Lexis/Nexis from home, if they have a computer and modem, or use one of the other Macs in the Lab and not be restricted to the four designated Lexis machines. <b>Passwords cost only $30.00 for Lexis or $40.00 for Lexis/Nexis access per academic year.</b> Subscription forms are available at the Circulation desk in the Law Library. Under this educational program certain restrictions apply. Students are restricted from using the service from 2 - 4 PM on weekdays; printing is available to an attached printer or to disk but not to the Lexis/Nexis printer; the passwords are only operational during the school term. Copies of the Lexis/Nexis search software are available from Gian Medves (978-5537). Please call for an appointment and bring a 3.5" diskette with you. 
<p>
<h3>Lexis/Nexis Passwords for Faculty:</h3>
The Library has acquired four ports to access Lexis/Nexis for the exclusive use of Faculty members. Faculty interested in accessing Lexis/Nexis should contact Gian Medves (5537) for instructions as well as Lexis/Nexis reference guides.
<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"><p>
<h2><a name = "criminal">Criminal Justice on the Internet</h2>
<h3>by Cathy Matthews and Tom Finlay<br>
Centre of Criminology Library</h3></center>
This article will introduce you to some of the basic sources of criminal law and criminal justice on the Internet. It is divided into two parts: mailing lists (or discussion groups), and gopher sites.
<p>
<h3>Mailing Lists</h3>
There are several lively discussion groups addressing criminal justice interests on the net.  A subscription to a discussion group is a means of sharing ideas or consulting with colleagues teaching or conducting research in your area.  To subscribe send an e-mail message to the appropriate listserv address, as in the &quot;subscribe&quot; line in each example shown below.  Then send the simple subscribe name-of-list your name message.  Remember to save any &quot;opening correspondence&quot; you receive which documents how to unsubscribe, how to retrieve archived postings, and other general rules of the list.  Once you have signed on to a discussion list use the mail address not the listserv address to send messages to the list.
<p>
The three lists monitored most actively at the Centre of Criminology are:
<p>
<h3>LAWSOC-L (The Canadian Law and Society Discussion List):</h3>
This list, coordinated by Prof. Russell Smandych at the University of Manitoba, focuses on interdisciplinary issues relevant to the study of Law and Society in the Canadian context, including law, sociology, economics, psychology, criminology, feminist studies, etc., and to others working in areas of government policy, law reform or the delivery of legal services. 
<p>	
Subscribe to: lawsoc-l-request@cc.umanitoba.ca<br>
Your message : subscribe lawsoc-l Firstname Lastname<br>
Mail to: lawsoc-l@cc.unmanitoba.ca
 <p>
<h3>UNCJIN-L (The United Nations Criminal Justice Information Network List):</h3>
This list, started by Prof. Graeme Newman of SUNY-Albany, and with funding from the U.S. Justice Department, is a large, international list which defines criminology and criminal justice very broadly.  Recent topics included requests for advice on re-writing the juvenile justice laws in South Africa, discussion of minimum age for capital punishment, and the costs of sentencing and incarceration.  In addition, the list often posts job notices, journal tables-of-contents, and occasional book reviews.
<p>
Subscribe to:    listserv@albnyvm1.bitnet  or listserv@uacsc2.albany.edu<br>
Your message: subscribe UNCJIN-L Firstname Lastname<br>
Mail to: UNCJIN-L@uacss2.albany.edu
<p>
<h3>CJUST-L (Criminal Justice List): </h3>
This is a smaller forum than UNCJIN-L, but it is growing rapidly and now has over 400 members.  Recent discussions concerned topics as diverse as whether justice was served by Jeffery Dahmer's murder and fetal alcohol syndrome and the law.
<p>
Subscribe to: listserv@iubvm.ucs.indiana.edu<br>
Your message: subscribe CJUST-L Firstname Lastname<br>
Mail to: CJUST-L@iubvm.usc. indiana.edu
<p>
There are numerous other lists, one of which is:
<p>
<h3>CRIM-L(The Australian Criminal Justice and Criminal Law List): </h3>
Subscribe to:    LISTSERV@sulaw.law.su.oz.au<br>
Your message: subscribe crim-l First Name Last Name<br>
Mail to: CRIM-L@sulaw.law.su.oz.au
<p>
A more complete list can be found in Guide to Internet Resources in Criminal Law and Criminal Justice  prepared by the International Centre for Criminal Law Reform and Criminal Justice Policy. This list is expected to be available on the University of British Columbia Gopher shortly (gopher.ubc.ca) or via World Wide Web (http//view.ubc.ca).
<p>
<h3>Gopher Sites</h3>
Previous articles in this newsletter (see LawLink, Volume 1, Number 1) have explained the importance of the Cornell Legal Information Institute (gopher: fatty.law.cornell.edu) for a host of legal information and resources.  We would like to direct you to a few sites which have particular strengths in the area of criminal law and criminal justice.
<p>
The most frequently used at the Centre of Criminology is the UNCJIN gopher (United Nations Criminal Justice Information Network, as in the discussion list noted above).  This well-organized site contains full text documents (such as U.N. Rules and other instruments, newsletters of U.N. agencies), connections to other gophers, listings and text of Bureau of Justice Statistics documents, the World Directory of Criminological Institutes, access via telnet to the World Criminal Justice Library Network, U.S. Supreme Court Decisions, the CIA World Factbook, primary documents in foreign and international law, the full text of the U.S. Crime Bill, and many other valuable resources. To access this source:
gopher to: uacsc2.albany.edu
<p>
An interesting Canadian legal information site is the International Centre for Criminal Law Reform and Criminal Justice Policy at the University of British Columbia.  It is a recently-initiated gopher site, and a joint initiative of UBC, Simon Fraser and the Society for the Reform of the Criminal Law.  They describe their focus as: 
<ul>	
<li>International criminal law and procedure reform.
<li>International human rights and administration of criminal justice.
<li>Criminal justice research and policy development.
<li>Education, communication and the provision of information in criminal law and justice.<br> 
Source (Guide to Internet Resources in Criminal Law and Criminal Justice)
</ul>
To access the International Centre for Criminal Law Reform and Criminal Justice Policy gopher, gopher to: view.ubc.ca or by World Wide Web (http://view.ubc.ca). Then select "Academic units and information".
<p>
There are other sources which have been helpful to us at the Centre of Criminology.  Their gopher addresses follow:
<p>
Canada Supreme Court Decisions: gopher to gopher.droit.umontreal.ca
<p>
Federal Government (including Statistics Canada): gopher to: debra.dgbt.doc.ca
<p>
NCJRS (National Criminal Justice Reference Service) : gopher to: NCJRS.aspensys.com
<p>
The NCJRS gopher is a new site that is quickly developing into an important source of information.  This site puts one in touch with many information professionals in the U.S. justice system.  It also facilitates the ordering of publications from many departments such as the Bureau of Justice Statistics and the National Institute of Justice.  It has just made the latest edition (#228) of the NIJ Journal  available.
<p>
Please call us at 978-7068 if we may provide you with further assistance, or e-mail us at Matthewsc@vax.library.utoronto.ca or Finlay@vax.library.utoronto.ca.  This information is up-to-date at the time of writing, but information can be changed at gopher sites regularly, and items cited may be dropped and/or new sources added over time. 
<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "netscape">Netscape: Navigating the Internet from the Computer Lab</a></h2></center>
A new Internet browser called Netscape has been loaded on all of the Macintosh computers in the Lab except no's 6, 12 and 13. Netscape makes navigating the Internet relatively easy. Netscape has graphics capabilities that allow you to &quot;see&quot; the Internet.
<p>
Using Netscape you're going to bring pages of the Internet to your computer screen. The Internet is a collection of information stored in computers physically located throughout the world. Much of the information on the Internet is organized onto pages. You'll bring one page to your computer screen, discover its contents, and have the option of bringing more pages of information.
<p>
Some of these pages are richly formatted and colorfully illustrated, capable of bringing you sounds and movies and interactivity. To get to the information you seek, you'll need connections to these pages. Well-crafted pages provide built-in connections to other pages. That is, clicking your mouse button on a highlighted word or picture brings another page of information - a linked page - to your screen. The entire network of pages can be interlinked, one pointing to another. As a result, you can bring information in the meaningful context of &quot;Here is some information on a page in front of me, and highlighted on this page is a connection to related information I might wish to explore next.&quot;
<p>
First and foremost, Netscape software presents pages of the Internet with elegance and efficiency. Netscape software is a browseran interfaceto pages throughout the world. Netscape software allows you to immerse yourself in information unencumbered by the complexity of distributed networks.
<p>
Students and faculty are invited to try Netscape to explore the myriad of legal resources available on the Internet. If you need more information on how to use Netscape beyond running the program and pointing and clicking, check the Computer Lab Manual for detailed instructions.
<p>
<center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
