<P>
<center><h2><a name = "notices">Library Notices</a></h2></center>
<h3>Library Hours During the December Break</h3>
<P>
Students, please note these library hours as they may have an
impact on your research plans: 
<P>
<center><table cellpadding = 3>
<tr><td>December 22nd</td><td>8:45 am - 5:00 pm</td></tr>
<tr><td>December 23rd - 27th</td><td>Closed</td></tr>
<tr><td>December 28th - 30th</td><td>9:00 am - 5:00 pm</td></tr>
<tr><td>December 31st - January 1st</td><td>Closed</td></tr>
</table></center>
<P>
Regular library hours will resume on Monday January 2nd, 8:45
am - Midnight.
<P>
<b>Please note: Because of a planned system upgrade, all services
offered through UTLink, including the online catalog, will not
be available during the break.  Please plan your research schedule
accordingly.</b>
<P>
<h3>Computer Lab and Group Study Room Use</h3>
<P>
Because of problems brought to our attention by law students concerning
the use of group study rooms and the computer lab, all students
will be asked to show their student card when they book  a computer
or a group study room. Although this may seem a little inconvenient,
it is for your benefit as we are making a sincere attempt to keep
the group study rooms and the computer lab restricted to law students
only. We ask your co-operation in making sure that the group study
rooms are locked when you leave them and that you do not let students
without the door code into the computer lab.  Please report any
problems to the Circulation Desk.
<P>
In order to ensure that library users are aware of this policy,
the following notice will be placed on the doors of the group
study and moot court rooms:
<blockquote>
This Room may only be used by University of Toronto Faculty of
Law students for the purpose of group study (i.e. two or more
law students working together).
</blockquote><p>
<h3>Common Room Key</h3>
<P>
The key to the common room is now being kept at the Circulation
Desk for after-hours use. You must sign for the key and must leave
a piece of identification at the Circulation Desk while the key
is in your possession. You are responsible for the key and the
use of the common room while you have the key signed out. Please
note, the Library is providing this service as a courtesy to the
SLS and neither the Library nor its staff are responsible for
the common room or its machines in any way.
<P>
<h3>Security Devices</h3>
<P>
The Faculty's Security Committee has purchased six personal
safety alarms for student use in Faculty buildings. These alarms
may be borrowed from the Circulation Desk. You must leave a piece
of identification when you borrow the alarm. The alarms must be
returned to the desk before you leave the buildings. You should
be aware that use of these alarms does not guarantee a response;
their principal purpose is to scare off an attacker. Please read
the instructions which come with the alarms.
<P>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "three">Introducing Three New Automated Services to Library Users</a></h2></center>
<P>
The University of Toronto Library system has recently introduced
three new timesaving services.
<P>
<h3>Self Charge at the Robarts and Sigmund Samuel Libraries</h3>
<P>
To avoid the line-ups when you are in the Robarts or Sigmund Samuel
Libraries, you may self-charge barcoded books. There are four
self-charge units in the Robarts Library and one in the Sigmund
Samuel/Science &amp; Medicine Library complex. You must have a
barcoded library card with you in order to take advantage of this
system. 
<P>
<h3>Touch Tone Renewal by Telephone</h3>
<P>
You may now renew your loans and get information about your overdue
books, fines and holds by dialing 971-2400 from a touch-tone telephone.
You must have your library card barcode and the book barcode ready
when you dial in. After you are connected, you will be given four
options:
<ul>
<li>Press 1 for renewals.
<li>Press 2 for overdues.
<li>Press 3 for fines.
<li>Press 4 for holds.
</ul>
<h3>See What You Have Signed Out on the UTLink System</h3>
<P>
You can see a list of the items you have signed out by selecting
#12 (See what you have signed out) from the UTLink front-end menu
or by selecting 'Check your loans' under 'UTLink
Options...' in the UTCat (online catalogue) system.
<P>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "dial">Dial in Access to UTLink</a></h2></center>
<P>
Library users with computers and modems can dial in to UTlink
from home. Law  students can also Telnet to UTLink from the computer
lab. The following are brief instructions on how to dial in either
through a modem or via Telnet.
<P>
<h3>PC and Modem:</h3>
<P>
<table>
<tr><td>Communication settings:</td><td>8 bits, no parity, 1 stop bit</td></tr>
<tr><td>Terminal emulation:</td><td>VT100 or higher</td></tr>
<tr><td>Modem speed:</td><td>Phone:</td></tr>
<tr><td>300 Baud</td><td>978-3959</td></tr>
<tr><td>1200 baud</td><td>978-3959</td></tr>
<tr><td>2400 baud</td><td>978-7239</td></tr>
<tr><td>9600 baud</td><td>978-7220</td></tr>
</table>
<P>
<h3>To Logon once you have dialed in:</h3>
<P>
The computer screen will read: CONNECTED<br>
Type:  <b> ;</b>  (do NOT press return)
<P>
<h3>You will then see:</h3>
<P>
UNIVERSITY OF TORONTO COMPUTING SERVICES PACXNET
<br>
***NODE 2.SUBSCRIBE S0100067-TYPE HELP FOR ASSISTANCE***
<br>
SERVICE?      
<br>
Type:   UTLink (press return)
<P>
<h3>Direct Connection to UTCS PACXNET:</h3>
<P>
To establish your connection to the UTCS PACXNET 
<P>
Telnet to:   vax.library.utoronto.ca<br>
username:     UTLINK
<P>
Then follow the onscreen instructions.
<P>
Once you have successfully dialed in or Telnetted to UTLINK you
will be greeted with a number of information screens and a request
for the first initial of your last name and the last 8 digits
of your library barcode number. If you do not have that information
available, you can still get into UTCat by just pressing return
but, in that case, some of the UTLink Internet options will not
be available to you.
<P>
<b>If you do not have your library card, you will see a welcome screen
which looks like this:</b>
<P>
Welcome to UTLink at the University of Toronto Library
<br>
-&gt; 1 UTCat(alogue)<br>
    2 How to use UTCat: an overview<br>
    3 Teach yourself: UTLink, UTCat, Medline &amp;   Internet
tutorials<br>
    4 UTLink campus-wide information system<br>
    5 U of T and selected Toronto libraries: hours,   locations,
etc.<br>
    6 Examination schedules and old exams<br>
    7 Your questions &amp; comments<br>
    8 Display system messages<br>
    9 Logoff/Exit
<P>
<b>If you do have your library card you will see a screen that looks
like this:</b>
<P>
--&gt; 1  UTCat(alogue), Wilson &amp; other journal indexes
and databases<br>
    2  -- Full Boolean searching for #1<br>
    3  -- Screen reader searching for #1<br>
    4  About UTLink resources: UTCat, journal  indexes,
internet, etc.<br>
    5  Medline and health sciences journal indexes<br>
    6  Sociological Abstracts (sociology journal index)<br>
    7  UTLink campus-wide information system<br>
    8  U of T and selected Toronto libraries: hours,         
locations, etc.<br>
    9  Examination schedules and old exams<br>
   10 Other library catalogues via the Internet<br>
   11 Internet resources: gophers, WWW, etc.<br>
   12 Your questions &amp; comments<br>
   13 See what you have signed out<br>
   14 Display system messages<br>
   15 Logoff/Exit
<p>
<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "freenet">The Toronto Free-Net</a></h2>
<h3>By Gian Medves<br>
 Computer Services Librarian</h3></center>
<P>
The Toronto Free-Net is up and running and accepting memberships.
 Free-Nets started as grassroots efforts to provide networking
services to  local communities, with access either at public libraries
or by dialing in. They are a means by which individuals, who would
not normally have direct (and inexpensive) access to the Internet
can now have some limited access to the Information Highway.
<P>
Free-Nets are usually organized around a model town that you &quot;walk&quot;
through. You can stop at the post office and collect your mail,
wander through the arts and entertainment district and plan your
night out or head to the Government building to argue with a bureaucrat.
Aside from discussions and mail, there are bulletin boards, special
interest group forums and news services.
<P>
The Toronto Free-Net offers access to a number of Internet tools
like gopher, World Wide Web and Telnet that are not available
right now through U of T's UTORmail. Law students can access
the Toronto Free-Net from the Computer Lab or from home if they
have a computer, modem and communications software.
<P>
<h3>To access the Free-Net from the Computer Lab</h3>
<blockquote>
 1)Select NCSA Telnet from the Macintosh main menu.
<p>
 2)Select Open Connection under the File pull-down menu.
<p>
 3)When prompted for Session Name, type freenet  and you
will be connected to the Toronto Free-Net. 
</blockquote>
<h3>To access the Free-Net from home</h3>
<blockquote>
 1)Make sure your modem settings are set to 8 data
bits, 1 stop bit, and no parity. The dial-in lines
currently support speeds up to 14,400 bps.
<P>
 2)Dial 780-2010.
</blockquote>
If you have any questions concerning the Free-Net, the voice number
is (905) 568-9944.
<P>
The first time you login to the Free-Net you will sign-on as guest.
This provides you with limited privileges on the system. Once
you register you will be allowed full access to the system which
includes e-mail, UseNet news, WWW, gopher and Telnet capabilities.
Although registration is free, a donation is requested. To register,
select the following menus from the main menu: 
<P>
 <i>Administration Building...
<br>
  Online Registration Program...</i>
<P>
Once you have registered, an account will be created for you.
Next, you must complete and mail the &quot;Toronto Free-Net
Member Agreement&quot;. This form may be downloaded to your
computer and printed out or you can pick up a form at the Circulation
Desk. Allow 4-6 weeks for your application to be processed. 
<p>
