<center><h2>LOOK FOR LAWLINK AT THE<br>
 REFERENCE DESK</h2></center>
<p>
Beginning with the <b>next</b> issue of <cite>LawLink</cite>, you may pick up a copy from the Reference Desk in the Library or the front foyer of Falconer. We're making this change in order to keep printing and distribution costs at a reasonable level. If you miss getting an issue, however, we'll be happy to reproduce one for you. You'll know when the next issue is due through an announcement in <cite>Headnotes</cite>.

If there is information you'd like to see addressed in the newsletter, please talk to our editor, Susan Barker.

Ann Rae, Law Librarian
<p><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "utormail">UTORmail</a></h2>
<h3>Gian Medves, Computer Services Librarian</h3></center>
<p>
<b>Applying for a UTORmail account and password</b>
<p>
As of September 6, 1994 law students, faculty and staff became eligible for free UTORmail, the University of Toronto's institutional e-mail service. During the summer we were told that only graduate law students would have access to UTORmail. In mid-September we were informed that undergraduate law students were now considered graduate students and were also entitled to have free access to UTORmail.
<p>
As the situation now stands all  law students can apply for a UTORmail account and password. To apply for an account and password go to the Circulation Desk in the Law Library and ask for a UTORmail application form. You must then call 978-0444 to make an appointment. When you make your appointment, ask where you have to go because the address has changed three times since the registration process was begun in early September. Take your completed application form along with you to the appointment. If you would like to access UTORmail from home you will need a minimum 9600 baud modem. If you so desire, appropriate software will be provided to you at your appointment. If you intend to use UTORmail from the Computer Lab you will not require software. An e-mail software package (called Eudora) will be available on the Mac workstations in the Lab.
<p>
<b>Please Note:</b>  When we received the Eudora software to access UTORmail from the Computer Lab, we experienced problems connecting to the mail server. That problem has just been resolved. We will get Eudora running on 2 Macs as quickly as possible and add it to the others as time permits.
<p>
<b>Getting started with e-mail</b>
<p>
With UTORmail users can compose electronic messages at their workstations then download them to the University's central mail server (a computer that stores and distributes mail) or they can retrieve messages from the mail server and read them at their workstations. Most of the work is done at a local workstation. The mail server then simply distributes that mail. The mail server determines the best route to reach a recipient and passes the e-mail to the next closest mail server. The e-mail can be passed through any number of mail servers before it reaches its final destination. This whole process usually takes from a few seconds to a few minutes. UTORmail users can:
<ul>
<li> Send text-based messages to any other user on the Internet.
<li> Attach computer files to text-based messages.
<li> Send messages and files to multiple recipients.
<li> Reply to and forward messages that they receive.
<li> Subscribe to electronic mailing lists/listservs (see last issue for more details).
<li> Search archives of various listservs to follow world-wide (conversations) or threads on a particular topic.
</ul>
<b>Using Eudora</b>
<p>
At present the only e-mail program that is supported in the Law Library's Computer Lab is a package called Eudora. Another package, ECS Mail, may also be available in the future. Eudora must be properly configured before you can begin using it to send and receive e-mail. Detailed instructions are provided in the Computer Lab Manual.
<ol>
<li> Launch Eudora by clicking on the Eudora option from the Macintosh main menu.
<li> Select the configuration command from the Special menu.
<li> Enter your user name in the POP account field in the format:<br>
    firstname.lastname@mailboxX.utcc.utoronto.ca <br>(where X equals the configuration  number that you were assigned when you received your UTORmail account).
<li> Enter your real name in the Real Name box.
<li> Enter the name of your mail server in the SMTP Server box using the format:<br>
	     postofficeX.utcc.utoronto.ca <br>(where X equals your configuration number).
<li> Enter your e-mail address in the Return Address box.
<li> Enter phX.utcc.utoronto.ca in the Ph Server box (again  X = your config. number).
<li> Click the OK button. You have completed the basic configuration process; (it looks more complicated than it is).
</ol>
You can now begin to compose and send messages using Eudora. To create an e-mail message go to the Message menu and select the New Message command. Enter  the e-mail address of the recipient in the To: field then press the Tab key. Enter a short subject in the Subject: field then press the Tab key again. You have the option of sending courtesy copies in the Cc: field by entering the e-mail address of other message recipients in this field or you can tab directly to the message field and either type or paste text directly into this field. Once you have completed your message click the Queue button. Your message will be stored on the hard drive of your Macintosh and will be sent to the mail server when you select the Send Queued Messages command from the File menu.
<p>
To receive and read e-mail with Eudora select the Check Mail command from the File menu. The password dialog box will appear. Enter your e-mail password and click the OK button. If you have e-mail waiting it will be downloaded and a list of your messages will be displayed on the screen with the following information: name of the sender, time message was sent and the subject of the message. Double click on the subject line of the message you want to read and the full message will be displayed. To close the message window click on the close box.
<p>
<b>Security considerations</b>
<p>
Make sure that you delete your messages once you have read or replied to them. If you would like to keep your messages, save them to a floppy disk and take them away with you. If you leave them on the hard drive of the Macintosh others will be able to read your messages.
<p>	
<b>UTORmail vs GPU</b>
<p>
At this time UTORmail is simply an e-mail service. You can send electronic mail  to other users on the Internet but you do not have access to such Internet utilities as Archie, gopher, telnet and ftp. If students want to have full Internet access, they should consider getting a GPU account or subscribe to the Toronto FreeNet once that system becomes operational. Unlike UTORmail, GPU is not free. You will be asked for a deposit and will be charged for connect time and storage. Those students interested in a GPU account or information on the Toronto FreeNet can call me (Gian Medves) at 978-5537.
<p>
<center><h2><a name = "annelegge">Introducing  Anne Legge</a></h2></center>

As of May 1, 1994 Anne Legge joined Computer Services Librarian, Gian Medves, as his assistant.  Formerly a member of the Cataloguing Department, Anne is now responsible for: performing regular and preventive maintenance on computers in the lab; assisting students with technical problems; and changing computer passwords and door codes to ensure security.  Anne is available in the Library on Mondays and Tuesdays from 8:30 - 4:30.
<p><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "statute">CANADA STATUTE SERVICE ON CD-ROM</a></h2>
<h3>Esther Wan, Reference Librarian</h3></center>

Finally, the day has arrived when Canadian federal statutes have all been encapsulated on a single disk. Although this does not mean that you will never have to look at the print version again, looking up statutes has suddenly become much easier; (I hear a big hurrah I am sure from most law students).
<p>
<cite>Canada Statute Service</cite> on CD-ROM consists of the Revised Statutes of Canada, 1985 in full text and all Public General Acts subsequently enacted until March 31, 1994 (with the exception of the Income Tax Act, which was excluded). This new cd product also contains the <cite>Canada Statute Citator</cite>, which provides both history and case information for all statutes except for the Criminal Code and the Constitution Act, which includes the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms. These short case annotations provide citation information and a brief headnote for each case. As well, they are linked to longer case summaries available from the <cite>All-Canada Weekly Summaries</cite> (A.C.W.S.) and the <cite>Weekly Criminal Bulletin</cite> (W.C.B.) from December 31, 1988 to March 25, 1994. the CD-ROM will be updated four times a year, thus you will need only to consult the current session bills in order to complete your research (amazing, isn't it?).
<p>
Though the welcome screen looks a little daunting, searching this product is relatively simple. Once you have &quot;double-clicked&quot; on the gray bar entitled, &quot;The Canada Statute Service&quot;, you have two choices: to search the statutes themselves or the Canada Statute Citator. Regardless of your choice, you then have two means of searching this product. If you know the name of the state that you are looking for, consult the Table of Contents. this alphabetical list of the federal statutes cleverly embeds a wealth of information for each state. You are also able jump to any references mentioned within the text of any statue. Do not despair if the name of the Act eludes you, this cd also allows you to search by keyword using boolean operators (&quot;and&quot;, &quot;or&quot;). As you type in the keywords, the system will display the number of records that may be retrieved. Expert searchers may opt to use field searches to refine their queries. 
<p>
Since this is only a demo disk, the Library has 30 days to decide whether or not to purchase it (we have it until early November). Please take a moment to try it out and let us know what you think.
<p><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
