</dl>
<p><center><img src ="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2>Off to a good Start!</h2></center>
<P>
 The first issue of LawLink was well received by its readers.
Now, with the school year beginning, it's time to introduce the
newsletter to law students. Copies of issue #1 will be available
at the Reference Desk. Please pick one up; among other things,
it contains an informative article by Gian Medves entitled <i>Legal
Reference Sources on the Internet</i>.
<P>
 In this second issue, we continue with more information about
the Internet by focusing on discussion lists that are relevant
for the legal researcher. You will also find notices about new
CD-ROM titles,  signing on to QL's online databases and introduction
to U of T's new e-mail system.
<P>
<cite>LawLink</cite> itself may soon go electronic. We are investigating the
possibility of making the newsletter available on the Robarts
Library's gopher. This would, of course, make it accessible to
a much wider audience, namely, anyone who can dial into UTLINK.
For the coming year, however, even if the newsletter is on the
gopher, the Library will continue to make print copies available
to the Law School community.
<P>
 Let me reiterate that we hope to make <cite>LawLink</cite>  as useful as possible
by providing you with relevant, timely information in a concise
format. Please help us do this by making your suggestions to the
Editor, Susan Barker.
<P>
Ann Rae, Law Librarian
<p><center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "discussion">Discussion Lists on the Internet</a></h2>
by Gian Medves<br>
Computer Services Librarian</center>
<P>
<i>As promised in the first issue of <cite>LawLink</cite>, this article provides
information about the various law related discussion lists that
are available on the Internet through e-mail.</i>
<P>
 Keeping up with the Internet is difficult at the best of times,
if not outright impossible.  This is because the Internet is vast,
diverse and continually changing. Therefore, it is necessary that
you utilize whatever expertise is available; e-mail and electronic
discussion lists provide just such a forum.
<P>
 Electronic mail is perhaps the most popular application on the
Internet because it extends and enhances our ability to communicate
with others.  One of the best ways to keep abreast of new developments
in networked legal information resources and to learn how to navigate
through the Internet is to cultivate network contacts through e-mail.
 Others on the network who know of your interests can inform you
of what resources are available and how to get to them.  An electronic
discussion list (or mailing list) utilizes the power of e-mail
to put you in touch with a large number of people with similar
interests who have come together to discuss a particular topic.
 These people usually have similar backgrounds and interests and
a desire to share ideas, opinions, problems and solutions.
<P>
Electronic discussion lists can be &quot;moderated&quot; or &quot;unmoderated&quot;.
 On a moderated discussion list, messages are screened and perhaps
combined with similar messages by a list administrator before
being sent to subscribers.  On an unmoderated list all messages
are automatically forwarded to everyone on the list.  Most electronic
discussions are supported by a software program called a listserv
that automates functions related to setting up, moderating and
interacting with those lists.  The listserv allows users to subscribe
or unsubscribe to electronic discussions, as well as find out
who else subscribes to a particular list and search past messages
of archived discussions.
<P>
To subscribe to a discussion list simply send an e-mail message
to the subscription address of the listserv hosting the discussion
list. Your message should read, <b>subscribe list name your name</b>
where <b>list name</b> is the name of the discussion list and <b>your name</b>
is your full name. For example, to sign on to the Artificial Intelligence
and Law list:
<ol>
<li>Send an e-mail message to:<br>
     listserv@austin.onu.edu
<P>
<li>As your message say:<br>
   subscribe ail-l john doe
</ol>
 Once you are a member of a list, to send messages for distribution,
use the mail,  not the subscription, address.
<P>
Here is a selected list of law related discussion lists:
<dl>
<dt><b>AIL-L:</b> Artificial Intelligence and the Law discussion list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@austin.onu.edu
<dd>Mail to: ail-l@austin.onu.edu
<P>
<dt><b>CJUST-L:</b> Criminal Justice discussion list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@iubvm.ucs.indiana.edu
<dd>Mail to: cjust-l@iubvm.ucs.indiana.edu
<P>
<dt><b>COMLAW-L:</b> This list focuses on computers and legal education
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@ualtavm.bitnet
<dd>Mail to: comlaw-l@ualtavm.bitnet
<P>
<dt><b>EC:</b> European Community discussion list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@vm.cc.metu.edu.tr
<dd>Mail to: ec@vm.cc.metu.edu.tr
<P>
<dt><b>EURO-LEX:</b> All European Legal Information Exchange discussion list
<dd>Subscription to: vlistserv@dearn.bitnet
<dd>Mail to: euro-lex@dearn.bitnet
<P>
<dt><b>FEMJUR:</b> Discussions and information about feminist legal issues
<dd>Subscription to: vlistserv@suvm.bitnet
<dd>Mail to: vfemjur@suvm.bitnet
<P>
<dt><b>GOVDOC-L:</b> Government Documents and Depository Libraries list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@psuvm.bitnet
<dd>Mail to: govdoc-l@psuvm.bitnet
<P>
<dt><b>HISLAW-L:</b> This list focuses on the history of law: canon, feudal and common law
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@ulkyvm.louisville.edu
<dd>Mail to: hislaw-l@ulkyvm.louisville.edu
<P>
<dt><b>H-LAW:</b> Legal history discussion list. Includes discussions on U.S. constitutional history
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@uicvm.uic.edu
<dd>Mail to:h-law@uicvm.uic.edu
<P>
<dt><b>INT-LAW:</b> International Law Librarians discussion list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@vm1.spcs.umn.edu
<dd>Mail to: int-law@vm1.spcs.umn.edu
<P>
<dt><b>LAWPROF:</b> Law Professors and lecturer's list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@chicagokent.kentlaw.edu
<dd>Mail to: lawprof@chicagokent.kentlaw.edu
<dd>When subscribing, include the following information in your
message: Subscribe <b>LAWPROF (Your name and position and institution
here)</b>
<P>
<dt><b>NATIV-L:</b> This list focuses on issues pertaining to aboriginal
peoples
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@tamvm1.tamu.edu
<dd>Mail to: nativ-l@tamvm1.tamu.edu
<P>
<dt><b>NCS-L:</b> National Crime Survey discussion list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@umdd.bitnet
<dd>Mail to: ncs-l@umdd.bitnet
<P>
<dt><b>PSYLAW-L:</b> Psychology and the law list
<dd>Subscription to: listserv@utepa.bitnet
<dd>Mail to: psylaw-l@utepa.bitnet
</dl>
