<center><h2><a name = "library">Library Announcements</a></h2>
<P>
<h3>First Year Students: Legal Research Lectures</h3></center>
<P>
 Ann Morrison, Associate Librarian, will deliver a lecture on
Canadian legal research on Monday, September 19 (and repeated
on Wednesday, September 21) in the Bennett Hall  at 12:00 p.m.
sharp. This lectures will be instrumental in assisting you with
your  library assignments.  Upper year students who would like
to refresh their research skills are also invited to attend.
<P>
<center><h3>QuickLaw (QL) Passwords for Law Students</h3></center>
<P>
QuickLaw has re-activated all educational passwords for 1994-95.
All upper year and graduate students who already have a QL password
should have had access to QL as of September 6, 1994. If you experience
any problems, please call QL at (416) 862-7656.
<P>
QL's computer-based sign-up program will be available to all
first year and new graduate students by the end of September.
First year students will receive their passwords during their
QL training sessions prior to library assignment  #3.   The dates
and times of these sessions will be posted in the Library shortly.

<p><center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "mail">Institutional Electronic Mail Service</a></h2></center>
<P>
 On September 13, University of Toronto's Computing and Communications
will be launching the U of T institutional e-mail service called
UTORmail. The service is free to faculty, staff, and graduate
students. There are plans to make UTORmail available to undergraduate
students at some point in the future.
<P>
 Each person who wants a UTORmail &quot;mailbox&quot; must complete
a &quot;Request for UTORmail Service&quot; form. These forms can be
obtained from Kathy Tam (faculty and law school staff) and Gian
Medves (graduate students and law library staff). On this form
you will be asked for personal information (name, address, department,
personnel number/(graduate) student number and the password you
want to use. You will also be asked whether you will be accessing
the e-mail service from a PC/Windows, Macintosh or DOS workstation.
UTCC will provide electronic mail software for your system: Pegasus
for PC/Windows, Eudora for Macintosh, and PINE for DOS. A mailbox
and a password will be issued upon evidence of eligibility, e.g.
a U of T personnel number for faculty and staff, or a U of T student
number for graduate students. 
<P>
 The minimum hardware and software requirements for accessing
UTORnet are:
<dl>
<dt>PC<dd>386 PC or compatible
<dd>4 megabytes of RAM
<dd>10 megabytes of available hard disk space
<dd>Extended keyboard, mouse, VGA colour monitor
<dd>DOS 5.0 or greater; or Windows 3.1
<P>
<dt>Macintosh <dd>68000 based processor
<dd>4 megabytes of RAM
<dd>5 megabytes of available hard disk space
<dd>Keyboard, mouse and monitor
<dd>Macintosh O/S (version 6.0.7 or greater)
</dl>
 Dial-in service will be available so that users can get their
mail both at the university and from home. Dial-in service is
available only at 9600 or 14,400 bps. UTCC recommends the external
Supra Faxmodem 144LC but any modem that supports the V.32bis standard
should work.
<P>
Graduate students can use the Macintosh computers in the Computer
Lab to access UTORmail. E-mail training sessions will be provided
at some point in the near future. The dates and times of these
sessions will be posted in the Library as well as in the next
issue of <cite>LawLink</cite>. Graduate students requiring more information
can contact Gian Medves at x5537.

<p><center><img src = "../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "cdrom">New CD-ROM Titles at the Law Library</a></h2></center>
<P>
To add to the Law Library's CD-ROM collection (which includes:
the LegalTrac Periodical Index, the British Columbia Statutes
and the CRTC Broadcast Decisions) the Law Library has recently
acquired two new CD-ROM titles: the Code of Federal Regulations
and a demo version of the Canada Statute Service. Instructions
for the use of the CD-ROM products have been placed by each CD-ROM
workstation. If you encounter any difficulty with the CD-ROMs,
please ask for help at the Reference Desk.

