<center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<h2>Introducing...</h2>
<cite>Lawlink</cite> is a new venture for the Library staff, and one we hope
you will welcome. It's not that we think you need more to read.
We simply think you nee to read this newsletter.
<P>
Information sources are changing so rapidly that we wanted a way
of keeping you better informed. <cite>Headnotes</cite> just didn't seem to be
the right vehicle, so <cite>LawLink</cite> was born. We hope to bring it to
you 10 times a year under the able editorship of Susan Barker
and with contributions from all units of the Library. Content
is intended to be short and to the point with the occasional longer
article such as the one we begin with from Gian Medves on Legal
Reference Resources on the Internet. In future issues we will
bring you information on notable new books, electronic sources
of information, how to get an e-mail account, how to get passwords
for various databases and how to start exploring the Internet.
We'll also use the newsletter to ask your opinion on various matters
and to make announcements.
<P>
If you have information of this type that is worth sharing with
colleagues, we hope you will consider contributing it to Susan
so we can include it in <cite>LawLink</cite>. We will always be open to your
suggestions for making the newsletter as useful as possible to
you. If you want us address specific issues, please tell us.
<P>
Ann Rae, Law Librarian
<p><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><P>
<center><h2><a name = "sources">Legal Reference Sources on the Internet</a></h2>
<h3>by Gian Medves<br>
Computer Services Librarian</h3></center>
<P>
<i>This article is intended to introduce some basic Internet concepts
and provide specific examples of useful sources of information.
there is a list of texts to help novice users navigate the information
highway at the end of the article. In addition, a hands-on session
of Internet training with Gian or Esther can help you get started.</i>
<P>
The Internet is a worldwide collection of networks in which regional
networks are connected into one great &quot;living thing&quot;
communicating at amazing speeds. The Internet gives you the ability
to access:
<ul>
<li>specialized databases
<li>electronic discussion lists
<li>electronic books and journals
<li>computer programs, and
<li>a variety of experts and specialists via electronic mail (e-mail).
</ul>
You can gain access to all kinds of information from your computer
at work or at home: all that is required is a modem, a phone line
and some training.
<P>
<h3>Internet Access Methods</h3>
<P>
There are four main methods of gaining access to the Internet,
these are: Gopher, Telnet, FTP and Electronic-mail.
<P>
Gopher is the easiest way to find information. The Gopher utility
enables you to have rapid access to a remote computer located
anywhere on the Internet. Gopher is menu-driven and provides full-text
searching capabilities to identify desired documents. where available,
legal resources are listed in tidy menus; however, it is not uncommon
for some gopher menus to be several layers deep. thus, finding
some information may necessitate a great deal of browsing. Once
you have signed onto the University of Toronto's computer network,
you can use the gopher command to connect to the remote location
of your choice. For example:
<dl>
<dd><i>gopher droit.umontreal.ca port 70</i>
</dl>
will connect you to the Gopher server at the Universite de Montreal
which contains the full text of recent supreme Court decisions.
<P>
Telnet is software that allows users to log in to remote computers
on the Internet. Once connected, you can browse databases, run
software, read files or retrieve documents. From the Internet
you can use the Telnet command to log in to a remote host. For
example:
<dl>
<dd><i>telnet wugate.wustl.edu</i>
</dl>
will connect you to a telnet site at Washington University which
contains information about U.S., European and government library
systems as well as weather reports for the U.S. and Canada.
<P>
FTP (file transfer protocol) is the primary method for transferring
files over the Internet. With this program it is possible to copy
a file (at extremely high speeds) from a computer anywhere in
the world. This normally requires that you have a user id on both
the sending and receiving machines. However, one way around this
restriction is via &quot;anonymous ftp&quot;. Some computer administrators
have set aside areas on their machines that can be accessed without
an account (i.e. anonymously) for the purpose of distributing
documents, software and other files. Use the command ftp to begin
you file transfer session.
<P>
Electronic mail or e-mail can be a very powerful tool for the
legal researcher. Not only can you communicate with colleagues
directly, but by subscribing to an electronic discussion list
you communicate with a variety of experts from around the world
and thereby tap into invaluable information resources.
<P>
<h3>Discussion Lists (Listservs)</h3>
<P>
One of the best ways to keep abreast of new developments in networked
legal information resources and to learn how to navigate through
the Internet is to cultivate network contacts through e-mail.
an electronic discussion list utilizes the power of e-mail to
put you in touch with a large number of people with similar interests
who have come together to discuss a particular topic. Electronic
discussions can be &quot;moderated&quot; or &quot;unmoderated&quot;.
On a moderated discussion list, messages are screened and perhaps
combined with similar messages by a list administrator before
being sent to subscribers. On an unmoderated list, all messages
are automatically forwarded to everyone on the list. Most electronic
discussions are supported by a software program called a &quot;listserv&quot;
that automates functions related to setting up, moderating and
interacting with those lists. the listserv allows you to subscribe
or unsubscribe to electronic discussion lists and to search for
past messages in archived discussions.
<P>
To subscribe to a discussion list simply send an e-mail message
to the subscription address of the listserv hosting the discussion
list. Include in the body of your message the link subscribe [list
name] your name, for example:
<dl>
<dd><i>Subscribe H-LAW Joe Smith</i>
</dl>
adds Joe Smith to the Health Law discussion list.
<P>
For a comprehensive list of law-related discussion lists, please
see the next issue of LawLink available September 15, 1994.
<P>
<h3>The Internet on UTLINK</h3>
<P>
One extremely valuable research tool is the Information Gateway
in the Library's on-line catalogue (UTLink). Through UTLink, you
can access university library catalogues in: The Americas, i.e.
Canada, the United States and Mexico: Europe/Scandinavia and Asia/Pacific/South
Africa. You can search these catalogues by selecting &quot;Other
Libraries&quot; from the UTLink Menu in the Information Gateway.
Once you have selected the library catalogue that you wish to
search, you can sign on by following the on-screen instructions.
the &quot;Internet Resources&quot; option in the UTLink menu will
provide you with access to a wide variety of resources including:
publications on-line, gopher sites, bulletin boards and many other
resources.
<P>
<h3>Canadian Online Legal Resources</h3>
<P>
One source of Canadian legal information is a relatively new gopher
that has been set up at the Facult&eacute; de Droit - Universit&eacute; de Montr&eacute;al.
Though this Gopher you can access: both the French and English
versions of the new Quebec Civil Code, recent Supreme Court judgments
and CUB (unemployment insurance) decisions. You can access this
Gopher either through e-mail at:
<dl>
<dd><i>verona.droit.umontreal.ca</i>
<dd>or by
<dd><i>gopher droit.umontreal.ca port 70</i>
</dl>
The Washington and Lee gopher site has a very large collection
of legal resources including some Canadian materials: the Canadian
Legal Research Files (from Queen's University) and texts of the
Charlettetown Accord, Meech Lake Accord, the Canadian Constitution
Act and the North American Free Trade Agreement. To get there:
<dl>
<dd><i>telnet liberty.uc.wlu.edu</i>
<dd>Login: <i>lawlib</i>
</dl>
<h3>U.S. Online Legal Resources</h3>
<P>
The major American law-related gopher sites include those at Cornell
Law School, Washington and Lee University (Liberty), Washburn
(Washlaw), and the Library of Congress (LC-MARVEL).
<P>
Through its Legal Information Institute, the Cornell Law School
provides access to a wide range of legal materials including the
U.S. Constitution, recent Supreme court decisions, various federal
Acts, and certain articles of the Uniform commercial Code. To
access the Legal Information Institute:
<dl>
<dd><i>telnet fatty.law.cornell.edu 8200</i>
<dd>Login: <i>www or gopher</i>
</dl>
At Washington and Lee some of the information available in the
&quot;legal sources&quot; path (#8) includes the Directory of
Legal Academia, Electronic Jurisprudence BBS, Court Bulletin Boards,
and the United States Federal Register. To access:
<dl>
<dd>telnet liberty.uc.wlu.edu
<dd>Login: law.lib
</dl>
From its initial menu, the Washlaw gopher at Washburn provides
access to such items as the &quot;virtual&quot; law reference
disk, primary U.S. law and federal government information. To
access:
<dl>
<dd>telnet acc.wuacc.edu
<dd>Login: washlaw
</dl>
The Library of Congress Machine-Assisted Realization of the Virtual
electronic Library (LC-MARVEL) provides access to federal information
resources. This includes: access to information relating to the
executive branch, including the White House; access to information
relating to the legislative branch such as Congressional directories;
and access to information relating to the judiciary, including
supreme Court decisions, orders, and biographies of the sitting
justices. The Library of Congress also provides a wealth of full-text
versions of historical documents such as the Emancipation Proclamation,
the Monroe Doctrine and Vietnam era documents. To access:
<dl>
<dd><i>telnet marvel.loc.gov</i>
<dd>Login: <i>marvel</i>
</dl>
<h3>International Online Legal Resources</h3>
<P>
A valuable tool for researching international legal issues is
the INT-LAW discussion list. The list promotes an exchange of
information related to foreign, comparative and international
legal materials and issues. It has several regular features. These
include the posting of advance tables of contents for <cite>International
Legal Materials</cite> and <cite>The American Journal of International Law</cite>
and news of key foreign and international legal publications both
in print and electronic format.
<dl>
<dd>Subscribe to: listserv@vm1.spcs.umn.edu
<dd>Mail to: Int-law@vm1.spcs.umn.edu
</dl>
Another source of foreign and international legal sources is the
gopher at <b>wiretap.spies.com</b>. The wiretap gopher provides access
to a range of foreign legal documents such as the full-text of
some Australian legislations; the United Nations charter and selected
resolutions; the NATO handbook and press releases; and access
to a range of treaties and international covenants in full-text
format including the Maastricht Treaty on European Union, the
Geneva Conventions, and the Hague Conventions. The wiretap gopher
also provides access to various world constitutions and a range
of world documents in full-text format. To access this gopher,
take the following steps:
<dl>
<dd><i>gopher wiretap.spies.com</i>
<dd>then choose
<dd>5. Government Docs (U.S. &amp; World)
<dd>34. World Constitutions
<dd>or
<dd>16. Miscellaneous World Documents
<p>
<dt>then choose from the following:
<P>
<dd>1. Communist Manifesto, 1847
<dd>2. Copyright of Programs in EC
<dd>3. Declaration of Israel's Independence
<dd>4. Declaration of the Rights of Man, 1789
<dd>5. Europarliament Resolution on Tibet
<dd>6. Laws of William the Conqueror
</dl>
An excellent source for treaties is the Multilateral Treaties
Project at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy which is available
through the Cornell gopher.
<dl>
<dd><i>telnet fatty.law.cornell.edu 8200</i>
<dd>Login: <i>www</i> or <i>gopher</i>
</dl>
Select Foreign and International Law from the main menu then multilateral
treaties (item #8).
<P>
A listing of multinational treaties by category includes:
<ol>
<li>Atmosphere and Space
<li>Aviation
<li>Cultural Protection
<li>Diplomatic Relations
<li>Flora and Fauna - Biodiversity
<li>General
<li>Human Rights
<li>Marine &amp; Coastal
<li>Other Environmental
<li>Rules of Warfare; Arms Control
<li>Trade and Commercial Relations (includes Copyright)
</ol><dl>
<dt>Other international documents available on the Internet include:
<dt>German law from Berlin University
<dd>gopher gatel.aedat.fu-berlin.de 70
<dt>The Basic Law of Hong Kong 1990 and the Latin American Legislative
and Legal Database
<dd>gopher marvel.loc.gov
<p>
<dt>Two information services that provide access to European legal
information are:
<dt>1. ECHO (European Commission Host Organization)
<dd><i>telnet echo.lu</i>
<dd>Login: <i>guest</i> and 2
<dt>2. CONCISE (Cosine Network's Central Information Service for Europe)
<dd><i>telnet concise.ixi.ch</i>
<dd>Login: <i>concise</i>
<dd>Password: <i>concise</i>
</dl>
<h3>Additional Resources</h3>
<P>
The largest problem you may face when you first sigh on to the
Internet is finding all that is available. the situation is further
complicated by the fact the new sources are added every day. Although
there is no map to the Internet there are navigational tools and
devices, including printed finding aids and computer programs.
<P>
<h3>Print Resources</h3>
<P>
The Law Library has some excellent guides available to those contemplating
entering the Internet maze. These guides are kept on the computer
shelf in the reserve section. These include:
<P>
Blackman, Josh. ,<cite>Legal Researcher's Internet Directory 1993/1994.</cite>
New York: Legal Research of New York, Inc. 1993.
<br>
Call Number TD 5105.875 I57 B42 1993/94
<P>
Carroll, Jim. <cite>Canadian Internet Handbook, 1994 edition</cite>. Scarborough:
Prentice Hall, 1994.
<br>
Call Number TD 5105.875 I57 C37 1994
<P>
Kehoe, Brendan P. <cite>Zen and the Art of the Internet: a Beginner's
Guide</cite>. Englewood Cliffs, NJ: P T R Prentice Hall, Inc., 1993
<br>
Call Number TK 5105.875 I57 K44 1993
<P>
Tennant, Roy. <cite>Crossing the Internet Threshold: an Instructional
Handbook</cite>. Berkeley, Calif.: Library Solutions Press, 1993.
<br>
Call Number TK 5105.875 I57 T46 1993
<dl>
<dt>Veljkov, Mark. <cite>Pocket Guides to the Internet</cite>. Westport: Mecklermedia,
1994.
<dd>v.1 <cite>Telnetting</cite>
<dd>v.2 <cite>Transferring Files with File Transfer Protocol (FTP)</cite>
<dd>v.3 <cite>Using and Navigating the Net</cite>
<dd>v.4 <cite>The Internet E-Mail System</cite>
<dd>v.5 <cite>Terminal Connections</cite>
<dd>v. 6 <cite>Basic Internet Utilities</cite>
<dt>Call Number TK 5105.875 I57 V45 1994
</dl>
In addition, the library has a useful directory in the reference
section:
<P>
Strangelove, Michael and Diane Kovacs. <cite>Directory of Electronic
Journals, Newsletters, and Academic Discussion Lists</cite>. Washington
D.C.: Association of Research Libraries, 1993.
<br>
Call Number Z 286 E42 D57
<P>
<h3>Online Resource Tools</h3>
<P>
Here are some resource tool that will keep you abreast of what
legal discussion lists are available and how to subscribe to them:
<P>
<cite>The List of Lists</cite> - a comprehensive list of discussion lists.
<P>
You can retrieve this list via ftp:
<P>
COMMAND: ftp ftp.sura.net<br>
LOGIN: anonymous<br>
PASSWORD: (enter your e-mail address)<br>
DIRECTORY: /pub/nic/<br>
FILE: interest.groups.txt
<P>
<cite>The Legal List</cite> - a consolidated list of all law-related resources
available on the Internet.
<P>
You can retrieve this list via ftp:
<P>
COMMAND: ftp ftp.midnight.com<br>
LOGIN: anonymous<br>
PASSWORD: (enter your e-mail address)<br>
DIRECTORY: /pub/LegalList/<br>
FILE: legallist.txt
<P>
Or you can subscribe to this list and receive regular updates:<br>
Subscribe to: legallistrequest@justic.eliot.me.us
<dl>
<dt><cite>Mary Jenson's List</cite> - This list collects Internet legal resources.
<dt>You can retrieve this list via telnet:
<dd>telnet liberty.uc.wlu.edu
<dd>Login: lawlib
<dt>then choose
<dd>10. Legal Sources
<dd>227. Jensen, International Resources-Law.
</dl>

<p><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "cdrom">New CD-ROM Network</a></h2></center>
<P>
The Library has recently expanded its number of CD-ROM workstations
from 1 to 6, and the general response can be described as wild
enthusiasm by researchers. With a simple click of the mouse or
of the arrow keys, you may select any of the compact disk products
currently on subscription.
<P>
Legaltrac, the cd version of the <cite>Current Law Index</cite>, contains citations
to and selective abstracts of journal articles from 1980 to the
present (usually up to the last month). Legaltrac can be searched
by author, subject, or keyword and is very user-friendly; you
don't need an instruction book to figure out how to use it! Also
available are the CRTC Broadcasting Decisions and Public Policy
Notices from 1984 to the present (usually 3-4 months behind) in
both English and French. Finally, the 1990 British Columbia Consolidated
Statutes, including the annual statues since 1992, and current
rules of court can also be searched on the network. From time
to time, test products will also be available on the network for
a trial period, and we may come calling for you opinions on these
items. All of the materials on the cd's can be printed using a
copycard. We will be informing you of new developments and CD-ROM
subscriptions in future issues of <cite>LawLink</cite>.
<P>
Ester Wan<br>
Reference Librarian

<P><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "card">Days Are Numbered for the Card Catalogue</a></h2></center>
<P>
No, we are not thinking of destroying the cards. We <b>are</b> considering
moving the catalogues down to the unfinished space before the
new term starts so that we can use the space along the wall for
other purposes. The cards will still be accessible, although in
a restricted way.
<P>
If you have concerns objections, Ann Rae would like to hear them.
Speak now or ...

<P><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "ql">QL Passwords</a></h2></center>
<P>
How often are you given something free? Quicklaw (&quot;QL&quot;),
the Canadian legal online system which carries case law, press
releases, and secondary literature, is available to you without
charge for most of the files. All faculty members should acquire
passwords. QL has frozen all of the students' passwords for the
summer months. As a result, all research assistants must use their
professor's passwords in order to do their online research. an
additional advantage in acquiring a password is that you have
the option of searching the system yourself at your office or
at home. All you need is a computer, modem and communications
software to hook yourself up.
<P>
Signing up for a password is easy. You can contact either Esther
Wan (ext. 4290) or Gian Medves (ext. 5537), and we will arrange
for a password package to be sent to you by QL. This package includes
the password, contract, and information booklets which you will
need in order to search QL. To activate the password, you must
sign the contract and return it to QL immediately. The Reference
Staff are also available if you should desire training on the
system. While QL may seem intimidating at first, you may soon
find yourself thoroughly addicted - not such a bad situation considering
that the system is free and can save you some time!
<P>
Esther Wan<br>
Reference Librarian

<P><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "new">What's new in the Cataloguing Department?</a></h2></center>
<P>
Cataloguing has recently implemented online cataloguing on the
UTCat System. The cataloguers can now input the record directly
into the local system; the records will then appear instantly
in the online public catalogue.
<P>
For rush cataloguing requests, please call Mr. Rashid at ext.
4209.
<P>
Over the past year, Cataloguing has also been involved in the
Reports Organization Project which was designed to provide better
physical access to the collection. Reports and digest for Canada,
United States, and Britain have already been re-organized and
labelled, and work on Australian and New Zealand reports is currently
in progress.
<P>
H. Rashid<br>
Head of Cataloguing

<P><center><img src="../icons/grkban09.gif"></center><p>
<center><h2><a name = "training">Internet Training Sessions Available</a></h2></center>
<P>
Did you know the University offers training sessions on the Internet?
These sessions are available through either the School of Continuing
Studies or the University of Toronto Library System. For more
information, contact Susan or Esther at the Library.

