<head>
<title>UTLR Vol. 53 No. 2: Abstract 3</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Approaches to Sorting Out Jurisdiction in a Self-Government Context
<p>
JOHN M. OLYNYK</h1>

<center><h3>ABSTRACT / <a  href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/utlr53-2/olynyk.htm">Fulltext</a></h3></center>

Self government negotiations with First Nations are leading to the recognition of a third order of government in Canada. The existing division of powers between Parliament and the provincial legislatures will be altered to accommodate the self government jurisdiction of First Nations.  In some cases, First Nations may have powers defined in ways not currently seen in the Canadian constitution.  An important challenge to be addressed in negotiating and implementing self government arrangements is how First Nations' jurisdiction will interact with and be distinguished from that of the federal and provincial governments.  This paper examines approaches used in two self government agreements to design this jurisdictional interface, as examples of the creativity that will be needed to facilitate quick and effective implementation of self government agreements.
<p>
Les n&eacute;gociations entre le gouvernement f&eacute;d&eacute;ral et les gouvernements provinciaux et les permi&egrave;res nations au sujet de leur autonomie gouvernementale am&egrave;nent &agrave; la reconnaissance d'un tiers ordre de gouvernement au Canada.  Il faudra modifier la pr&eacute;sente distribution des pouvoirs entre le parlement f&eacute;deral et les l&eaucte;gislatures provinciales pour accomoder la juridiction des peuples autochtones.  Dans certaines cas ils auront des pouvoirs d&eacute;fin&eacute;s d'une mani&egrave;re non-pr&eacute;vue par les lois constitutionelles du Canada.  Une question critique dans la n&eacute;gociation et l'ex&eacute;cution de ces ententes sera comment distinguer les trois juridictions l'une de l'autre, ainsi que le r&egrave;glement des conflits potentiels. L'exemple de deux ententes actuelles illustre quelques alternatives
dans le dessein juridictionel ainsi que l'esprit innovatrice n&eacute;cessaire pour faciliter la r&eacute;alisation effective et rapide des ententes d'autonomie gouvernementale.
<p>
