<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 53 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Approaches to Sorting Out Jurisdiction in a Self-Government Context
<p>
JOHN M. OLYNYK<sup><a href="#note">*</a></sup></h1>

<i>Self government negotiations with First Nations are leading to the recognition of a third order of government in Canada. The existing division of powers between Parliament and the provincial legislatures will be altered to accommodate the self government jurisdiction of First Nations. In some cases, First Nations may have powers defined in ways not currently seen in the Canadian constitution. An important challenge to be addressed in negotiating and implementing self government arrangements is how First Nations' jurisdiction will interact with and be distinguished from that of the federal and provincial governments. This paper examines approaches used in two self government agreements to design this jurisdictional interface, as examples of the creativity that will be needed to facilitate quick and effective implementation of self government agreements.
<p>
Les n&eacute;gociations entre le gouvernement f&eacute;d&eacute;ral et les gouvernements provinciaux et les permi&egrave;res nations au sujet de leur autonomie gouvernementale am&egrave;nent &agrave; la reconnaissance d'un tiers ordre de gouvernement au Canada. Il faudra modifier la pr&eacute;sente distribution des pouvoirs entre le parlement f&eacute;deral et les l&eaucte;gislatures provinciales pour accomoder la juridiction des peuples autochtones. Dans certaines cas ils auront des pouvoirs d&eacute;fin&eacute;s d'une mani&egrave;re non-pr&eacute;vue par les lois constitutionelles du Canada. Une question critique dans la n&eacute;gociation et l'ex&eacute;cution de ces ententes sera comment distinguer les trois juridictions l'une de l'autre, ainsi que le r&egrave;glement des conflits potentiels. L'exemple de deux ententes actuelles illustre quelques alternatives
dans le dessein juridictionel ainsi que l'esprit innovatrice n&eacute;cessaire pour faciliter la r&eacute;alisation effective et rapide des ententes d'autonomie gouvernementale.</i>
<p>
<h3>I. Introduction</h3>

Negotiations are taking place with First Nations across Canada with a view to concluding self-government agreements. These negotiations may eventually lead to the creation of a third order of law-making institutions in Canada, along with Parliament and the provincial legislatures. Two main types of issues arise in these negotiations: what range of legislative powers should First Nations exercise; and how will First Nations' legislative powers be made to fit into the existing framework of federal and provincial  legislative jurisdiction. 
<p>
In this article, I skip over the first issue, and focus instead on the second. In particular, I am interested in how current approaches to distinguishing between the legislative jurisdiction of Parliament and the legislative jurisdiction of provincial legislatures will apply in the context of First Nation self-government jurisdiction. This latter question is of particular interest because it is likely that some powers of First Nations will not be defined in the same way as federal and provincial jurisdiction are defined under the Canadian Constitution.
<p>
I have chosen to focus on this aspect of self-government for two reasons. First, it is difficult to discuss the scope and content of self-government powers on a generic basis. The powers that are of great interest to some First Nations may be of only limited interest to others, due to their differing situations, conditions, and goals. This means that self-government powers are best determined on a First Nation-by-First Nation basis, which in turn suggests that it may not be very helpful to comment in the abstract on the specific substantive powers that should be included in self-government agreements.
<p>
Second, while the substance of self-government powers may be difficult to address on a generic basis, the situation is different with respect to some of the legal and other technical challenges associated with the implementation of self-government. Many of these challenges can be expected to recur in virtually all cases where First Nations are negotiating new legal relationships with Parliament and the provincial legislatures; if unresolved, they could become stumbling blocks in the path of implementing workable self-government arrangements. 
<p>
By spotting and removing these stumbling blocks as early in the process as possible, the costs of negotiating
self-government---in financial and in human terms---can be kept as low as possible, so that the benefits of self-government can begin flowing sooner. This will benefit government, which will be able to minimize the negotiation costs. This will be of even greater benefit to First Nations, which will achieve their self-government objectives sooner, and which will also have to spend less money on lawyers and consultants and negotiators, allowing more of the benefits to flow instead to their members. While I may be guilty of exaggerating the
significance of these technical challenges to some extent, the fact remains that they exist and that they must be overcome in order for negotiated self-government arrangements to be implemented.
<p>
Resolving these technical challenges would facilitate the implementation of self-government arrangements. Resolution would also allow both supporters and critics of self-government to focus their attention on the more important issue of the scope and nature of self-government powers. Whyte points out that legal obstacles have been raised by critics of self-government out of genuine concern, but also as an indirect way to express opposition to
self-government;<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> hence addressing the technical concerns surrounding self-government will help to focus debate on the merits of self-government for First Nations. Finally, while it is problematic to discuss the scope of self-government powers without directly involving the First Nations concerned, the situation is different for these more technical issues. As Hall states,
<blockquote>
Perhaps the most useful role that non-natives can play in the effort to achieve native self-government is not to design regimes of self-government but rather to demonstrate methods by which non-native legal and governmental structures can co-exist with native [self-government].<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It is my hope that this article's examination of the implications of the traditional approaches to sorting out legislative
jurisdiction will assist in facilitating the implementation of self-government arrangements for First Nations in Canada.
<p>
SOME UNDERLYING ASSUMPTIONS
<p>
In focusing on this specific topic, I am passing over many other very important issues related to the recognition and
implementation of aboriginal self-government in Canada. Those issues are probably of much greater importance from a public policy perspective than the narrow issue I am examining. Those issues are beyond the scope of this paper, but they are nonetheless present in the background. I propose to deal with them by setting out the
following three assumptions:
<p>
1.  <i>Self-Government Is Coming, and Preparations Should Be Made</i><br>
A great deal of time, effort and money has been invested in self-government in the last two decades in Canada, and results are beginning to show. More and more First Nations are taking on greater responsibility for their affairs and for the well-being of their members. I am assuming that this trend will continue, with more First Nations seeking to have their self-government powers recognized and implemented. 
<p>
Most of the controversy around self-government focusses on whether self-government powers for First Nations are desirable, and on whether First Nations should have law-making powers over certain subject matters. While I feel that First Nations will be better off running their own affairs, my purpose with this paper is not to argue for or against the coming of self-government or its substantive scope and content; those are policy issues beyond the scope of this work.
<p>
Virtually all provincial governments now accept the need to negotiate self-government agreements with First Nations; some of those governments even view those negotiations as desirable. The federal government is also---at least at the political level---pushing for speedy conclusion of self-government agreements with First Nations. Therefore it seems clear that self-government is on its way, and an important contribution that can be made now is to try to resolve known technical problems so that self-government can be implemented as quickly and as efficiently as possible.
<p>
2.  <i>Self-Government Powers Will Likely Be Defined Through Negotiated Self-Government Agreements</i><br>
I am not concerned in this paper with whether self-government powers arise from an inherent right, or from some
other source.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> In either case, it seems most likely that the specific powers and jurisdiction of First Nations will be defined through negotiated agreements with other affected levels of government---the federal and provincial governments, in particular. These negotiated agreements will set out the range and scope of First Nations' law-making powers, and will also address the relationship between those powers and the powers of Parliament and the provincial legislatures. 
<p>
This is not the only possible option. McNeil,<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> for example, argues that First Nations' inherent self-government powers may be exercised by the First Nations, without any need for First Nations to get permission from government or to negotiate agreements with government. In the event of a conflict between a First Nations law and a federal law, McNeil argues that the government would have to meet a stringent justificatory test in order to be able to override the First Nation law:
<blockquote>
For these new definitions to be meaningful, s. 35(1) [of the <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>] has to be interpreted as creating a constitutional space for Aboriginal governments and laws. The jurisdiction these governments can exercise within that space would extend to all components of the Aboriginal and treaty rights that the section recognizes and affirms, which, as we have seen, probably includes all aspects of Aboriginal life. What the Aboriginal peoples have to do if they want to exercise their jurisdiction is to fill this constitutional space with Aboriginal laws. To the extent that these laws, whether customary or legislative in nature, are already in place, the task is simply to act on them and demonstrate their existence. Where they are not in place, Aboriginal peoples have the option of making them by exercising their inherent right of self-government. Failing that, however, federal laws infringing their Aboriginal and treaty rights which meet the justificatory test will continue to apply to them due to the decision in <cite>Sparrow</cite>.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup>
<p>
To the extent that Aboriginal and treaty rights are adequately regulated by Aboriginal laws, federal laws infringing
those rights cannot apply to them. The conclusion flows from the <cite>Sparrow</cite> decision. As we have seen, before federal laws are allowed to infringe Aboriginal and treaty rights, the Supreme Court said a valid legislative objective must exist. Moreover, that objective has to be pursued in a manner which infringes those rights as little as possible. But if an Aboriginal people is already regulating its own rights in a way which is consistent with the
legislative objective, there can be no need, and therefore no justification, for the federal laws to apply.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This approach, therefore, would not require negotiations over self-government powers ---rather, the scope and content of self-government powers and the relationship of First Nations' laws to federal and provincial legislation would be determined in court on a case-by-case basis as disputes arise.
<p>
This is not unlike the current situation in the United States, where a series of court decisions over the last century has recognized and defined a wide range of self-government powers for First Nations in the United States.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> I believe, however, that relying on the courts to define the substance of First Nations' self-government powers, through litigation of specific questions on a case-by-case basis, would be extremely
expensive for First Nations, government and third parties, and would also create an unacceptable degree of uncertainty. In addition, the courts appear reluctant to assume the responsibility for recognizing First Nations' self-government jurisdiction.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup>
<p>
Therefore, for the purposes of this article, I am assuming that the details of self-government powers will be set out in agreements negotiated between First Nations and government. This would include details related to specific powers of First Nations, such as those in the field of criminal law, details related to the application of the <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> to First Nations governments and laws, and details related to the relationship between First Nations jurisdiction and that of Parliament and the provincial legislatures.
<p>
3.  <i>Self-Government Agreements Will Result in the Creation of a Coordinate Third Order of Government within the Canadian Constitutional Framework</i><br>
Although it is by no means certain, and although there is no unanimity of opinion on the question, it appears likely that self-government powers of First Nations will eventually be recognized and constitutionally protected as a third order of government.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> This means that First Nations' law-making jurisdiction
will not be delegated federal or provincial jurisdiction, but rather will be an independent third order of government, in the same way that the provincial legislatures are an independent order of government from the federal Parliament. The simplest way in which this could occur is through recognition of individual self-government agreements as treaties or land claims agreements within the meaning of s. 35 of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>. An alternate approach would be to amend the Canadian constitution itself, in order to accommodate this new order of government. This paper, however does not address the precise means by which self-government powers may be
implemented and protected. For my purposes, I simply assume that this new order of government will be created.
<p>
The implications of this assumption are that First Nations' legislative powers will have to be respected by the federal and provincial levels of government in the same way that they must respect each other's jurisdiction, and that the same types of problems that arise in determining which order of government may properly assume jurisdiction for a given matter will arise between federal and First Nations' jurisdiction and between provincial and First Nations' jurisdiction.
<p>
THE JURISDICTIONAL PROBLEM
<p>
The premise of this paper is that the approach that the courts take to resolving jurisdictional disputes between First
Nations and other orders of government will be rooted in the practices developed to deal with the existing constitutional division of powers. The Canadian court system has been dealing with division of powers disputes since shortly after Confederation, and has developed a number of concepts which it applies consistently.
<p>
It was decided early on that all possible subject matters of legislation are distributed under the Constitution between Parliament and the provincial legislatures. This has been taken to mean that there is no subject matter that is outside the legislative competence of either Parliament or the legislatures.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> In the context of self-government, McNeil notes that this means that no residual powers of self-government are left for
First Nations under the Constitution.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup>
<p>
The concept of the full allocation of powers between Parliament and the legislatures, then, has three implications with respect to government. First, when disputes arise about whether a given subject matter falls within the legislative jurisdiction of Parliament or of the provinces, the courts are normally faced with an either/or decision: the subject matter falls either within Parliament's jurisdiction or within the relevant legislature's jurisdiction---there is no third possibility. However, assuming that First Nations eventually become recognized as a third order of
government in Canada, and assuming that these First Nations exercise their powers independently of one another, in the future the courts' task will be much more complicated. No longer will there be only two parties disputing legislative jurisdiction---there will be the jurisdictional claims of First Nations to consider as well. 
<p>
Second, the current constitutional paradigm views all powers, including those affecting members of First Nations, as being allocated either to Parliament or to legislatures. This means that the subject matters over which First Nations will have jurisdiction will have to be taken from the current powers of either Parliament or the provinces. Most but not all of this jurisdiction will be carved from Parliament's jurisdiction, as section 91(24) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite>, has been given a very wide interpretation by the courts, to the extent that virtually all aspects of life for Indian people and First Nations are governed by the federal <cite>Indian Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#twelve">12<./a></sup> Provincial jurisdiction may be involved as well, as provincial laws of general application apply to Indian people and First Nations, as they would to other residents of a province, as long as they do not single out Indians or affect &quot;Indianness&quot; in some other way.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> As will be shown below, however, it appears likely that self-government arrangements will not adopt this exclusive approach to distribution of powers, but will instead provide for concurrency of powers to a significant extent. The powers of First Nations may overlap to a substantial degree those of Parliament or provincial legislatures.
<p>
Third, the powers of a provincial legislature have been construed as applying only within the fairly strictly defined limits of the territory of the province.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> This means that there has been no significant problem created by provincial powers overlapping in the same geographic area. Under self-government agreements, however, as will be seen below, it is possible that some powers will not be limited to the lands over
which a First Nation has direct control. In part due to the relatively small amounts of land that will be held by First Nations (in comparison to the area of a province), as well as to the fact that the land may be held in the form of many smaller parcels of land instead of one large block, First Nations may not be content---and it may not be appropriate---to have their powers over certain subject matters limited to their land base. Therefore, negotiators of
self-government agreements, and the courts interpreting those agreements, will have to deal with ways of defining the geographic scope of powers that are currently not part of the way powers are divided between Parliament and the provincial legislatures.
<p>
In sum, then, this article focuses on the jurisdictional relationship between First Nations and other orders of government. It starts with the premise that the fact that the negotiated legislative powers of First Nations will likely be seen as being derived from the existing division of powers may lead the courts to apply the traditional approaches to resolving jurisdictional disputes in cases involving self-government jurisdiction of First Nations.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> The purpose, however, of this paper is to demonstrate that there may be situations where the traditional approaches to defining constitutional jurisdiction will not be well suited to determinations of jurisdiction as between First Nations' legislative powers and those of either the federal or provincial levels. By identifying and analyzing the potential problems, I would hope that this paper could form a useful first step in the process of coming up with solutions to what I believe will be an important new issue in Canadian constitutional law---namely, dealing with the new interface between First Nations' legislative jurisdiction and the jurisdiction of Parliament and the provincial legislatures.
<p>
LIMITATIONS OF THIS ARTICLE
<p>
It should be acknowledged that this article is by necessity largely conjectural. This is due in part to the fact that there is virtually no experience in Canada with self-government arrangements, and hence there is no body of directly relevant case law on which I can base my analysis. While there is a burgeoning academic literature addressing many aspects of self-government, it must be recognized that there is still a great deal of uncertainty about how these issues would be handled by the courts. To deal with this, I have chosen to limit my frame of reference to existing approaches used by Canadian courts for dealing with jurisdictional issues between Parliament and the provincial legislatures.
<p>
Now, it should be recognized that not everyone would agree that the best way to go about solving problems related to aboriginal rights and interests would be through an examination of the traditional legal approaches. As Hall notes, aboriginal people in Canada have suffered a great deal as a result of the current legal system in Canada, and hence some people may feel that it is not appropriate to look to that system for new ways to address issues related to self-government.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
<p>
It seems clear, however, that self-government arrangements will be negotiated within the existing Canadian legal framework. The advent of self-government will require changes to the existing legal framework, but is not likely to result in fundamental rethinking of that framework. As a result, the challenge will be to work with the legal system in a way that enables First Nations to achieve their self-government objectives.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup>
<p>
ORGANIZATION OF THE ARTICLE
<p>
The next section of this article looks at the relevant portions of two self-government agreements to illustrate how
self-government powers may be defined, and how the agreements deal with the relationship between First Nations' law-making powers and those of Parliament and provincial legislatures. The first is the self-government agreement for the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, one of four Yukon First Nations to have concluded a self-government agreement along with a final agreement resolving its comprehensive land claim. The second is the Sechelt self-government agreement. The Sechelt Indian Band was the first First Nation in Canada to negotiate a self-government agreement with the federal government, and it now exercises self-government powers set out in federal legislation.
<p>
The following section analyzes how the current approaches of the courts to determining constitutional jurisdiction could work in the context of First Nations self-government jurisdiction. The manner in which self-government powers are defined in the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement and in the Sechelt Indian Band self-government agreement is examined with a view to identifying potential problems in applying the traditional tests as a way to sort out jurisdictional questions. Special attention is paid to concurrent powers to deliver services to members of the First Nations.
<p>
The final section summarizes the conclusions of the paper.
<p>
<h3>II.  The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and Sechelt Indian Band Self-Government Agreements</h3>

Although negotiations on First Nations self-government have been pursued in various parts of Canada for many years now, very few self-government agreements have actually been concluded. This section examines two such self-government agreements, one for the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations in the Yukon, and the second for
the Sechelt Indian Band on the Sunshine Coast in British Columbia.
<p>
THE CHAMPAGNE AND AISHIHIK FIRST NATIONS SELF-GOVERNMENT AGREEMENT
<p>
The Champagne and Aishihik First Nation is one of fourteen Yukon First Nations. The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations are centred in Haines Junction, a small town 150 kilometres west of the Yukon's capital of Whitehorse. The First Nations' 19,000 square mile traditional territory<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> comprises the extreme southwest corner of the Yukon, including the south half of Kluane National Park. While the First Nations have a total membership of about 900, almost half of them live outside of the First Nations' traditional territory, with the majority of those members living in Whitehorse.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a>
<p>
The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations have played a leading role in the negotiation of land claims agreements and self-government agreements in the Yukon. They are one of four Yukon First Nations to have concluded both land claims agreements and self-government agreements with the federal and territorial governments.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> Although the land claims agreement<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> is separate from the self-government agreement,<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> the two agreements were negotiated concurrently and were intended to be complementary.
<p>
<i>The Land Base</i><br>
One of the key aspects of being a government, of course, is having a land base over which the governmental powers will apply. Under the terms of their land claims agreement, the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations will receive 2,427 square kilometres (or about 937 square miles) of settlement land. This will be comprised of:
<ul>
<li>51 larger rural blocks of land ranging in size from less than one square kilometre to 285 square kilometres, with an average size of about 48 square kilometres (or about 18 square miles);
<p>
<li>30 parcels of land in the community of Haines Junction, ranging in size from individual house lots to 384 hectares; and
<p>
<li>191 specific sites in rural areas (cabin sites and other specific sites) ranging from less than one hectare up to 150 hectares, with the majority in the range of about one to five hectares.
</ul>
These 272 parcels of land will constitute the land base upon which many of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations' self-government powers will be focussed.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup>
<p>
<i>The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations Government Structure</i><br>
The self-government powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations will be exercised through their government structure. This government structure is defined in the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations Constitution. According to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations Constitution, there are to be five components to its government.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> Of these, the most significant for the purposes of this
article is the First Nations Council, which is described as the law-making branch of the government.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement itself does not set out elements of the government structure for the First Nations, although it does establish some parameters within which the First Nations' constitution is limited.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup>
<p>
THE CHAMPAGNE AND AISHIHIK FIRST NATIONS SELF-GOVERNMENT POWERS
<p>
Section 13 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement sets out the main legislative powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. They are grouped into three main categories: exclusive powers, powers applying on settlement land, and powers applying to citizens.
<p>
<i>Exclusive Powers</i><br>
Section 13.1 sets out three exclusive powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. These powers were intended to address essentially internal matters of administration of government and of benefits accruing to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations or their members under the land claims agreement. They are described
as exclusive powers, in part in reflection of their nature, and in part to distinguish them from the powers listed in ss. 13.2 and 13.3, which are, by implication, not exclusive. These powers also overlap to some extent with powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations under the terms of their land claims agreement. Various provisions of that agreement enable the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations to manage and allocate the benefits accruing to the First Nations and their members under the agreement. Therefore, ss. 13.1.2 of the self-government agreement in particular is to some extent repetitive of powers already held by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.
<p>
<i>Powers Applying on Settlement Land</i><br>
Section 13.3 sets out a second grouping of legislative powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. These are the powers that are intended to be limited to Champagne and Aishihik First Nations settlement land.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> It will be noted that these powers are framed in a manner that is not unlike the description of the powers of provincial legislatures under s. 91 of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite>. The powers are, by the introductory words of s. 13.3, said to extend to &quot;laws of a local or private nature on Settlement Land... .&quot;
<p>
This means that the powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations as enumerated in this section are limited to the land base of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, in much the same way that the powers of a provincial legislature are constrained within its provincial boundaries. In addition, the subject matter of Champagne and Aishihik First Nations laws is also limited to &quot;a local or private nature.&quot;  This implies that in addition to being limited to settlement land, these powers may only deal with the local and private aspects of those matters on settlement land. Any aspects that go beyond those local and private aspects---the regional, territorial, or national aspects of those matters---would presumably be beyond the legislative competence of the Champagne and Aishihik
First Nations, even though the matters may still affect their settlement land.
<p>
These powers are not characterized as &quot;exclusive,&quot; in contrast to the powers set out in s. 13.1 (above). This is for two main reasons. First, there are already federal or territorial laws covering many of these subject matters and which apply to lands which are to become Champagne and Aishihik First Nations settlement lands.
In order to avoid the creation of a legal vacuum with respect to the subject matters listed in s. 13.2, the self-government agreement provides for the continuation of existing federal and territorial laws, until such time as laws are enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. This is set out in s. 13.5.1:
<blockquote>
13.5.1 Unless otherwise provided in this [self-government] Agreement, all Laws of General Application shall continue to apply to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, its Citizens, and Settlement Land.
</blockquote>
The effect of this section appears to be akin to that of s. 129 of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite>, which provides for the continuation of laws in force at the time of Confederation, but subject to being repealed or amended by the appropriate legislative body. Another consequence of this section is that it is clear that the self-government agreement may set out powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, but it does not do so by removing those powers from the competence of the federal or territorial levels of government. This indicates that concurrent powers are envisioned. This is why these powers are not characterized as exclusive to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.
<p>
The situation in the Yukon differs from that in southern Canada with respect to the possibility of overlap with provincial powers. This is because the Yukon Legislative Assembly is a creature of federal legislation, created under Parliament's powers over lands in Canada not contained in a province.<sup><a href =  "#twenty8">28</a></sup> This means that there is no constitutional obstacle to the Yukon Legislative Assembly
having concurrent powers with the First Nations---the powers of both the Yukon Legislative Assembly and the First Nations are both based in federal jurisdiction.
<p>
Because of this situation of concurrent powers, it was necessary for the self-government agreement to address the issue of paramountcy in the event of conflict between laws. The self-government agreement explicitly addresses the question of the relationship of Champagne and Aishihik First Nations laws to Yukon laws, but does not explicitly address the relationship of Champagne and Aishihik First Nations laws to federal laws. The relevant provisions are s. 13.5.2 and 13.5.3:
<blockquote>
13.5.2 Canada and the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations shall enter into negotiations with a view to concluding, as soon as practicable, a separate agreement or an amendment of this Agreement which will identify the areas in which laws of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations shall prevail over federal Laws of General Application to the extent of any inconsistency or conflict.
<blockquote>
13.5.2.1 Canada shall Consult with the Yukon prior to concluding the negotiations described in 13.5.2.
<p>
13.5.2.2 Clause 13.5.2 shall not affect the status of the Yukon as a party to the negotiations or agreements referred to in 13.6.0 or 17.0.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup>
</blockquote>
13.5.3 Except as provided in 14.0,<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> a Yukon Law of General
Application shall be inoperative to the extent that it provides for any matter for which provision is made in a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.
</blockquote>
The effect of s. 13.5.3 is to make validly enacted Champagne and Aishihik First Nations laws paramount over laws on the same subjects passed by the Yukon Legislative Assembly.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> The situation with respect to federal laws is not so clear. Section 13.5.2 contains a commitment from the federal government to address the issue of paramountcy over federal legislation in subsequent negotiations with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. The effect of this clause, in the absence of a clause along the lines of s. 13.5.3, is to leave federal laws paramount over laws enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup>
<p>
These sections also deal implicitly with the issue of the subsequent repeal or amendment of laws continued in force under s. 13.5.1 of the self-government agreement. Those laws would continue to be in force until changed by the enacting body, or, in the case of a Yukon law, until the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations enacted a law which rendered inoperative the Yukon law under s. 13.5.1. 
<p>
<i>Powers Applying to Citizens</i><br>
The third category of powers is set out in s. 13.2. This category deals with the power of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations to make laws that apply to their citizens. The opening words to this section are key. Section 13.2 says that the power applies to the following matters &quot;in the Yukon.&quot;  This means that the law-making powers apply throughout the Yukon, and not only on Champagne and Aishihik First Nations settlement land. While many of these powers are similar to those exercised by provinces within their land bases, these powers are not limited to the land base of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. The implications of this are
discussed in detail below. It is worth noting that there do not appear to be any examples of powers that are defined in a comparable manner in the <cite>Constitution Acts</cite>---all provincial powers are limited to their provincial boundaries, and federal powers, with some exceptions related to extra-territorial effects of laws, are also obviously constrained to the territorial limits of Canada.
<p>
It may be seen that the powers under this section include both regulatory powers and service-provision powers. For example, s. 13.2.6 allows the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations to make laws regulating adoption of and by its citizens in the Yukon. Similarly, s. 13.2.9 allows the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations to make laws regulating successions of its citizens in the Yukon. Others---like s. 13.2.7, which deals with child custody powers and child care services---are a hybrid of regulatory and service-provision powers, while still others---such as
s. 13.2.1---are purely related to provision of services. This distinction is discussed in greater detail below, as it may
significantly affect the types of problems that may be encountered in trying to keep jurisdiction straight as between the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and government.
<p>
The issue of the paramountcy of Champagne and Aishihik First Nations laws over Yukon laws and federal laws is the same here as it was described above for settlement land-based powers. Similarly, the discussion of the continuation of existing laws is also the same here. It should, however, be emphasized again that these are
concurrent powers, but in this case it is not merely a case of concurrent powers between the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and one government or the other. As stated above, there are thirteen other First Nations in the Yukon, and each of those is likely to end up with similar powers.<sup><a href="#thiry3">33</a></sup> Therefore, it is conceivable that there could be up to fifteen laws (fourteen Yukon First Nation laws plus the law of either the territorial or federal government) applying concurrently to any one given subject matter throughout the
entire Yukon. The only way to distinguish between applicable laws would be on the basis of the identity of the person in question---whether that person was a citizen of a First Nation, and if so, of which First Nation. The implications of this problem are also discussed below.
<p>
THE SECHELT INDIAN BAND SELF-GOVERNMENT AGREEMENT
<p>
The Sechelt Indian Band is located on the Sunshine Coast of British Columbia, approximately 60 kilometres from Vancouver. In 1988, the Band had about 700 members; most of them (about 560) lived on Sechelt lands. At that time, there were also about 500 non-native people living on Sechelt lands, mainly in the town of Sechelt.
<p>
The Sunshine Coast region is experiencing economic growth, and the Sechelt Indian Band is actively participating in that growth. Its land base is located in areas which give it great value due to demand for housing and development. In addition, the Band and its members are involved in many areas of the local economy, from
resource-based activities to tourism and other services.
<p>
The Sechelt Indian Band was the first First Nation in Canada to negotiate and implement a self-government arrangement with the government of Canada. This resulted in the passage in Parliament of the <cite>Sechelt Indian Band Self-Government Act</cite><sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> in 1986. The Sechelt Indian Band has also filed a comprehensive land claim with the federal government which has been accepted for negotiation, but which has not yet been negotiated.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup>
<p>
<i>The Land Base</i><br>
While the Band is centred in the town of Sechelt, its land base includes approximately 1,000 hectares in 32 parcels scattered throughout the Band's 2,200 square mile traditional territory. These parcels were originally held as Indian reserves under the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, but since the coming into force of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, the lands have been transferred to the Sechelt Indian Band. These lands are referred to as &quot;Sechelt lands&quot; under the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup>
<p>
THE SECHELT INDIAN BAND'S GOVERNMENT STRUCTURE
<p>
The government structure of the Sechelt Indian Band is set out in its Constitution. The government structure consists of an elected Band Council comprised of one chief and four councillors.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> The Band Council has the power to pass laws, including laws setting out the procedure, within certain limits, for enacting and challenging laws.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> As was the
case with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations' self-government agreement, the self-government agreement for the Sechelt Indian Band, as set out in the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, does not directly establish elements of the Band's Constitution but rather establishes certain parameters within which the Band's Constitution is limited.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup>
<p>
THE SECHELT INDIAN BAND SELF-GOVERNMENT POWERS
<p>
The law-making powers of the Sechelt Indian Band are defined in two documents, the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> and the Band's Constitution. The <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> sets out the powers for the Band in ss. 14 and 15. It may be seen that the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> does not distinguish between exclusive powers, Sechelt land based powers or
citizen-based powers, apparently because virtually all of the non-administrative powers are limited to settlement land, and none of the powers are described as being exclusive to the Band Council.
<p>
In the case of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, two powers related to the management and administration of First Nations affairs and to the rights and benefits under the First Nations' land claims agreement and self-government agreement were described as being exclusive. Comparable powers exist under the <cite>Sechelt
Act</cite>, for example, in subsections (f), (r), (s), and (t) of s. 14. However, these powers are not stated to be within the exclusive jurisdiction of the Sechelt Indian Band Council. As these powers deal with the administration of the Band and its assets, they are not necessarily limited to Sechelt lands.
<p>
Most of the remaining powers are described as applying only on Sechelt lands. These are primarily powers relating to land management, resource management, and regulation of activities on Sechelt lands. The provision of health services<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> and the education of Band members<sup><a href="#forty1">41<./a></sup> are also limited to Sechelt lands.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<p>
Only one other power is not limited to Sechelt lands. This is the provision of social and welfare services &quot;with respect to Band members,&quot; which includes the custody and placement of children of Band members.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> This power appears to apply to all Band members, whether resident on or off Sechelt lands. As with services-provision powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, the fact that this power extends off Sechelt land creates the possibility of overlap not only with the federal or
provincial government, but also with the laws of any other British Columbia First Nation which has a comparably defined power.
<p>
However, while the Band had this power in theory, it was not able to exercise this power, at least up to 1989. This is because it is not enough that the Band have power under the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> to make laws on certain subject matters: s. 14 also requires that the Band constitution allow the Band Council to enact laws on those subject matters; &quot;The Council has, [power] <i>to the the extent that it is authorized by the Constitution of the
Band</i>, ... .&quot;<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> This means that, while the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> establishes law-making powers, the Band Constitution may limit those powers. This is in fact what happened.
<p>
As of 1989, the Band's Constitution authorized the Council to make laws in relation to 18 of the 21 subsections in section 14,<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> in most cases with either restrictions on the permissible content of laws enacted on those matters, or restrictions on the process to be followed in enacting laws on specific matters.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> However, the constitution did not authorize laws to be made in respect of powers under subsections (g), (h) or (i). Therefore, while the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> says that the Band Council may make laws in these services-related areas, the Council did not, up to 1989, have the power to do so under the Band's Constitution.
<p>
As with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement, another important aspect is the
relationship between laws enacted by the Sechelt Indian Band and laws enacted by Parliament or British Columbia. This includes the two aspects discussed above: continuation of existing laws, and paramountcy.
<p>
With respect to the continuation of existing laws, s. 35 of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> provides for the continuation of the provisions of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>:
<blockquote>
35. (1) Subject to section 36, the <cite>Indian Act</cite> applies, with such modifications as the circumstances require, in respect of the Band, its members, the Council and Sechelt lands except to the extent that the <cite>Indian Act</cite> is inconsistent with this Act, the constitution of the Band or a law of the Band.
<p>
(2) For greater certainty, the <cite>Indian Act</cite> applies for the purpose of determining which members of the Band are &quot;Indians&quot; within the meaning of that Act... .
</blockquote>
This means that, until such time as the Sechelt Band Council exercises its powers in accordance with the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> and the Band's Constitution, the provisions of the <cite>Indian Act</cite> will continue to apply to the subject matters in question. If the Council does make laws inconsistent with the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, then the Band laws will prevail. If there are any matters provided for in the <cite>Indian Act</cite> which are not subject matters over which the Band will have law-making powers under the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, the <cite>Indian Act</cite> provisions will continue to apply.
<p>
Section 37 of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> deals with the application of other federal laws:
<blockquote>
37. All federal laws of general application in force in Canada are applicable to and in respect of the Band, its members and Sechelt lands, except to the extent that those laws are inconsistent with this Act.
</blockquote>
This clause has two effects. First, it ensures that other existing federal laws will continue to apply to the Sechelt Indian Band, its members and Sechelt lands. The second effect, which differs from the effect of s. 35 with respect to the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, is to make other federal laws paramount over laws enacted by the Band Council. Therefore, while s. 35 gives the Band Council the power to pass laws that are inconsistent with the <cite>Indian Act</cite> and allows those laws to prevail over the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, s. 37 means that any law of the Band Council that is inconsistent with other federal laws is inoperative to the extent of the inconsistency.
<p>
Therefore, the situation with respect to federal laws is that the Sechelt Indian Band has powers that are concurrent with federal powers over the same matters. In the event of conflict between a federal law and a Sechelt law, the federal law prevails. The only exception would be where the federal law involved is the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, in which case the Band's law prevails.
<p>
Section 38 addresses the continuation of provincial laws, and the issue of paramountcy with respect to provincial laws:
<blockquote>
38. Laws of general application of British Columbia apply to or in respect of the members of the Bands except to the extent that those laws are inconsistent with the terms of any treaty, this or any other Act of Parliament, the constitution of the Band or a law of the Band.
</blockquote>
The extent of the impact of this clause is not clear. Section 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite> also provides for the application of provincial laws of general application &quot;to and in respect of Indians in the province.&quot;  Section 38 of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> would appear to be aimed at the same laws as s. 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>: laws which may affect &quot;Indianness,&quot; such as hunting laws. As with s. 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, any valid provincial law of general application would apply to the Sechelt Indian Band and
its members regardless of s. 38 of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>. 
<p>
Therefore, it appears that s. 38 has a fairly limited potential application, affecting only those provincial laws that
might have been held inapplicable to the Sechelt Indian Band and its members on the grounds that the laws affected their &quot;Indianness.&quot; In contrast to s. 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, this section does not purport to render those provincial laws inoperative to the extent that they cover the same subject matters as in the <cite>Indian Act</cite> or the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>. Rather, it uses the more restricted test of inconsistency. Hence, provincial laws affecting &quot;Indianness&quot; would by virtue of s. 38 of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> continue to apply, but they would be subject only to the normal rule of inconsistency, and not the expanded rule set out in s. 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>.
<p>
This means that if there is any overlap with provincial laws, it will probably not be very large in practice. In large part this is due to the way in which the Band's powers are set out in the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>; few of those powers overlap with existing provincial responsibilities, with the possible exception of powers related to health, social and welfare services. Therefore, the potential for overlap in the context of the Sechelt Indian Band's
self-government powers under the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> is more in the area of federal jurisdiction than provincial jurisdiction. As well, the effect of this overlap in the area of service provision is less dramatic than with respect to provincial services. This is because in these areas, the federal government is involved in providing these
services only to Indian people and First Nations, and not to all residents of a province.
<p>
 <h3>III.  Determining Jurisdiction in a Self-Government Context</h3>

This section looks at how the approaches used by the courts for determining federal/provincial jurisdictional disputes may work if applied in the context of jurisdictional disputes between First Nations' legislative powers and those of either Parliament or the provincial legislatures.
<p>
In considering how the courts may treat powers such as those outlined in the previous section, it should be remembered that I am assuming that self-government powers eventually will be entrenched in the Constitution as a third order of government. The implication is that the courts will not be dealing with bodies exercising delegated
legislative powers, but bodies which derive their law-making powers directly from the Constitution. Therefore, the analysis that follows does not treat self-government powers as delegated powers, but rather as self-standing powers. As a result, no consideration is given to judicial review of the exercise of delegated legislative powers. The analysis proceeds as though the courts will view First Nations' jurisdiction as coordinate with federal and provincial jurisdiction.
<p>
It should also be noted that this discussion is not intended to be a detailed analysis of the implications of specific wording of specific decisions as they may apply to self-government. Rather, I am more interested in the general approaches that may be taken, and the broader implications of those approaches.
<p>
As was seen above, self-government powers under the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement and the Sechelt Indian Band self-government agreement can be divided into three main types of powers: exclusive powers, powers applying on settlement lands, and powers applying to citizens. Each of these categories is discussed in turn in the sections which follow, in light of the predominant approach currently used by the courts to
resolving questions of jurisdictional overlap between federal and provincial jurisdictions. Courts initially apply the pith and substance approach to determine the content of the laws, and then apply the inconsistency test to determine if the two laws may co-exist or whether they are in conflict.
<p>
APPLICATION IN THE CONTEXT OF EXCLUSIVE POWERS
<p>
As discussed above, some powers of First Nations may end up being described as exclusive powers, in much the same way as powers of provincial legislatures are exclusive under s. 92 of the <i>Constitution Act, 1867</i>. Examples were seen in ss. 13.1.1 and 13.1.2 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government
agreement. Those powers dealt primarily with the internal administration of the First Nations and of the benefits and rights accruing to the First Nations under their self-government agreement and their land claims agreement. In this section, I will use those powers as examples to illustrate how the courts could approach powers which are defined in an exclusive manner.
<p>
The powers are not specifically limited to any one geographic area, such as the settlement land of the First Nations.
However, they are defined very narrowly: the powers cover very specific attributes of the internal affairs of the First Nation, and as such do not directly affect either of the other levels of government. In addition, as these are defined as exclusive powers, it is implicit that there is intended to be no concurrency of powers with either level of government. This would clearly be the case anyway in respect of provincial powers, as provinces would not be
able to legislate on matters which are so clearly related to the &quot;Indianness&quot; of the First Nations. 
<p>
The federal government, of course, would continue to have the power under s. 91(24) to make laws affecting the First Nations, at least while self-government powers are conferred by delegated federal powers (as is now the situation) instead of being entrenched in the Constitution. Therefore, until the powers are entrenched, the federal government would have concurrent powers with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations over the matters set out in s. 13.1 of their self-government agreement. However, as I am basing my analysis on the assumption that these self-government agreements will be entrenched sooner or later, it may be argued that even if Parliament maintains a general residual power over &quot;Indians and lands reserved for the Indians&quot; under s. 91(24), the exclusive powers of the First Nations under s. 13.1 of the self-government agreement should be seen as a specific exception to the federal power. Any other reading of the section would render the term &quot;exclusive&quot; meaningless.
<p>
Assuming, then, that these powers would be characterized as exclusive to the First Nations, the question then arises as to how the courts would address disputes about legislative jurisdiction in this area. I suggest that these powers will not present significant new issues for the courts. The issues that the court will face will be familiar, albeit in a different context. Given that the issues will be familiar, it is likely that the courts will also approach the issues in the same way as they have in other contexts.
<p>
First, the courts would likely follow a similar approach to deciding whether a given law was in fact within the power of the First Nations to enact. This would be in accordance with the &quot;pith and substance&quot; approach that has been used in federal-provincial jurisdictional disputes for over a century now. The courts would have to characterize the impugned First Nations' law on the basis of its purpose and effect to see if it fell within one of the heads of power of the First Nations. If so, the law would be valid; if not, the law would be <i>ultra vires</i>.
<p>
Second, if the law were valid, then the courts would have to determine whether there was a conflict with a federal or provincial law which could affect the First Nations' law. As suggested above, it is not likely that there would be a conflict with a provincial law, because the First Nations powers in s. 13.1 deal with narrowly defined matters which are directly related to the status of the First Nations as &quot;Indians.&quot;  Hence, overlap with provincial powers under the current distribution of powers would not be likely to arise.
<p>
Similarly, if the self-government power is interpreted as implying that there is no concurrent federal power on the same matter, as I believe it should (especially in the case of powers such as those in section 13.1 which apply only to the internal affairs of the First Nation), then there would be no problem with conflicts either, as this would mean that Parliament would not have the power to pass laws on these specifically defined matters. If, however, Parliament maintained a continuing responsibility for Indians and First Nations generally under section 91(24), then the possibility of concurrent legislative jurisdiction would arise in this field.
<p>
In that event, the courts would probably apply the test of inconsistency in the manner that they apply it in cases of overlap between federal and provincial laws. This would mean that the courts would ask if it there was an express contradiction between the two laws, such that compliance with one would mean breach of the other.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> It may be seen that this approach could cause some problems. For example, it is conceivable that the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations could enact a law dealing with administrative procedures to be followed in the management of the First Nations' affairs, and that those laws could conflict with
provisions of the <cite>Indian Act</cite> or some other federal legislation. In such a case, it is quite likely that compliance with the First Nations' law would mean non-compliance with the federal law. This would trigger the application of the doctrine of paramountcy, which at present under the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement is a rule of federal paramountcy. The First Nations' law could therefore be rendered inoperative to the extent of the inconsistency if such an approach were followed by the courts.
<p>
For this reason, if there were held to be concurrency of First Nations and federal powers in this area (despite the express wording of s. 13.1), a better approach to resolving overlap may be required, in order to avoid frustrating the purpose and intent of the self-government agreement. One option is the occupied field test, which has been applied recently by the Supreme Court of Canada, in a case where the Court felt that the inconsistency test would frustrate
the purpose of the federal legislation.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup>
<p>
However, this approach is fraught with other difficulties. For one, the approach is more subjective, as it requires the courts to assess the intent of the legislature rather than the effect of the legislation. In addition, the occupied field test is more likely to find conflict between laws than is the inconsistency test. In this context, where federal laws would be paramount over the First Nations' law, the occupied field test would make it more likely that First Nations' laws would be rendered inoperative due to overlap. From the courts' perspective, the occupied field test is much more interventionist; the inconsistency test, by comparison, represents an attitude of judicial restraint, where overlapping laws are allowed to co-exist as long as there is no direct conflict between them. The difficulty with both approaches is that they countenance federal jurisdiction where the wording of the self-government agreement
suggests none was intended.
<P>Hence, I suggest that a better approach would simply be to construe federal powers as inapplicable to the subject matters in question, meaning that the federal government would not have the power to enact valid legislation which overlaps directly with the powers of the First Nations under s. 13.1.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> This sort of approach---a modified form of interjurisdictional immunity---would also appear to be more in keeping with the courts' mindset of trying to uphold laws unless there are clear conflicts that necessitate imposing the doctrine of paramountcy to render one law inoperative---a mindset of trying to maintain validly enacted laws. 
<p>
APPLICATION IN THE CONTEXT OF NON-EXCLUSIVE POWERS CONFINED TO SETTLEMENT LAND
<p>
An important area of jurisdiction under the self-government agreements for both the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and the Sechelt Indian Band is the powers that are restricted to settlement land or Sechelt lands. The subject matters enumerated in s. 13.3 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement
and in the majority of the heads in s. 14 of the Sechelt self-government agreement confer important powers over resource management, land management, and regulation of activities, public order and other matters.
<p>
As was noted in the previous section, these powers are not stated to be exclusive to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations or the Sechelt Indian Band. In addition, under both self-government agreements, federal and provincial or territorial laws are stated to continue to apply to the First Nations, their members and (under the
Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement) their lands, generally until replaced by First Nations laws. Further, in the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement, the First Nations' powers are limited by the introductory words of s. 13.3 to only the &quot;local or private&quot; aspects of the subject matters enumerated in subsections 13.3.1 through 13.3.23.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> This
may mean that there will be substantial overlapping application of First Nations and federal or provincial laws on settlement lands.
<p>
This is because it is very likely, given the double aspect<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> and incidental effects<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> doctrines associated with the pith and substance approach to determining jurisdiction, that the federal or provincial/territorial governments will be able to find a valid basis
for enacting laws affecting settlement land or Sechelt lands. This is especially true in the case of Champagne and Aishihik First Nations' settlement land, as the &quot;local or private&quot; limitation on the First Nations' powers under s. 13.3 implies that any matters on settlement land that go beyond a local or private nature are not within the powers of the First Nations, and hence are within the powers of either Parliament or the Yukon Legislative Assembly.
<p>
The situation, therefore, will show some similarities to that which arises between federal and provincial jurisdiction, in that a province's jurisdiction is defined in a territory-based manner and is subject in practice to substantial overlap with federal powers. This is due primarily to the effects of the concepts of double aspect and incidental effects. It is also due, however, to the fact that provincial powers are generally construed as limited to matters of a provincial or more local scale, which in some cases has been taken to mean that the broader national dimensions of the same
subject matters should be construed as falling within federal jurisdiction.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup>
<p>
Therefore, in the event that a dispute about overlapping jurisdiction arises with respect to a subject matter in s. 13.3 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement or the powers of the Sechelt Indian Band applying to Sechelt lands, the similarities with federal-provincial jurisdictional issues would likely lead the courts to again apply the same approach described above---the test of inconsistency. Courts would first examine the validity of the two laws (First Nation and federal or provincial) in question. If both were valid (<i>i.e.</i>, within their respective legislative jurisdictions), then the courts would proceed to see if it were possible to comply with the requirements of both the First Nations law and the other law. If that were so, then there would be no conflict, and the doctrine of paramountcy would not come into play. Both laws would be allowed to stand, and persons affected by the laws would be required to comply with the stricter of the two laws. On the other hand, if it were determined that compliance with the First Nations law meant breach of the other law, or <i>vice versa</i>, then there would be a conflict, and the courts would have to determine which law was paramount over the other. In both cases,
the self-government agreements address the issue of paramountcy. 
<p>
In the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement, the paramountcy rules are set out in ss. 13.5.2 and 13.5.3. As demonstrated in the previous section, laws enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations will prevail over laws enacted by the Yukon Legislative Assembly, to the extent of the inconsistency.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> Under the agreement as it now stands, conflict between a
federal law and a First Nations law would be resolved in favour of the federal law.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup>
<p>
In the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, the paramountcy rules are set out in ss. 37 and 38. Laws enacted by the Sechelt Indian Band would prevail over provincial laws,<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> but not over federal laws, with the exception of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> As was pointed out above, because of the way the Band's powers are defined in the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> and because of the current situation with respect to the applicability of provincially-enacted laws to Indians and their lands, the paramountcy rule in s. 38 may not in practice affect many provincial laws.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup>
<p>
This would appear to indicate that powers of First Nations that are defined on the territorial basis of the lands within the control of the First Nations would not present significant difficulties with respect to the application of traditional
approaches to resolving disputes about overlapping jurisdiction. The courts would be able to apply the same type of approach to the issue as it arises between First Nations and government as they currently do in disputes between federal and provincial governments. This is because the issue raised is much the same, even though the context is
different.
<p>
APPLICATION IN THE CONTEXT OF NON-EXCLUSIVE POWERS TIED TO CITIZENS
<p>
As was seen in the discussion of the powers of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations in the previous section,
self-government agreements have included powers that are defined in a manner unlike those set out in the Constitution. This new category consists of laws which are not defined on the basis of territoriality (<i>i.e</i>., that apply only within a given territory or geographic area), but rather on the basis of citizenship. In other words, these
are powers which apply in respect of a citizen of a First Nation, whether that person is on lands belonging to the First Nation or not. This differs from the current situation with respect to the application of provincial laws (which generally speaking only apply to residents in the province) and with respect to the application of the <cite>Indian Act</cite> or by-laws enacted by First Nations under the <cite>Indian Act</cite> (which generally only apply as long as the person is resident on a reserve).
<p>
In the case of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, their citizen-based powers are set out in section 13.2 of their self-government agreement. Some of those powers are regulatory in nature, some are services-oriented in nature,<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> and some include both aspects.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> The powers are stated to apply anywhere in the Yukon.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> In the case of the Sechelt Indian Band, the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite> sets out one services-oriented power which applies to members of the Sechelt Indian Band off Sechelt lands,<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> although it appears that the Sechelt Indian Band's constitution may not currently permit this power to be exercised by the Band Council.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> This power appears to extend throughout Canada, as it is not expressly limited to any geographic area by the terms of the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>.
<p>
The significance of this is that laws made under these powers may apply to citizens or members who are not living on the First Nation's land base---for example, to those who are living in an urban area or perhaps even on the lands of another First Nation. However, in many cases when Indian people leave the reserves, they may no longer be subject to the <cite>Indian Act</cite> regime, and hence provincial laws would apply to them instead. Therefore, a greater degree of concurrency or overlap of powers between the provincial governments and First Nations can be expected to arise in the case of powers applying to First Nations' members off First Nations' lands. 
<p>
While this fact in itself will create new challenges for the courts (or for negotiators of self-government agreements), another significant point to keep in mind is the tremendous potential for overlap between the laws of First Nations and the federal or provincial governments, or between the various First Nations. In the case of the Yukon, if powers similar to those of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations under s. 13.2 of their self-government agreement are included in the self-government agreements for the other 13 Yukon First Nations, the implication is that there may be as many as 15 validly enacted laws that may apply to one of these subject matters in any given area of the Yukon. The situation would be even more complicated in British Columbia, as there are more First Nations than in the Yukon. Although the potential for overlap is therefore very substantial, the difficulties that this overlap may
raise with respect to determination of jurisdiction are likely to differ according to the nature of the power in question. Therefore, the discussion that follows will look separately at the regulatory powers and the services-oriented powers.
<p>
<i>Citizen-Based Regulatory Powers</i><br>
The situation with respect to regulatory powers that are defined on the basis of citizenship may become complex, due to the potential for overlapping laws. However, from the perspective of approaches used by the courts to sorting out jurisdiction, it does not appear that these types of powers would create significant difficulties. 
<p>
The courts would be able to apply the same approach to dealing with jurisdiction under these powers as that used for dealing with self-government powers applying only to lands of the First Nations. They would first determine if the laws in question are both enacted within the legislative jurisdiction of the First Nation and the other government or First Nation, and then, if both laws are valid, determine if there is any conflict between the two laws. If it is possible to obey both regulatory laws by obeying the stricter of the two, then the courts would be able to uphold both laws. In the event that there was a conflict between the two laws, then the courts would resort to the paramountcy rules set out in the self-government agreement.
<p>
The result of this would be that the two overlapping laws would likely be upheld if there were no express conflict between them. For laws of a regulatory nature applying on non-First Nation lands (that is, on Crown land or privately held lands), this would mean that citizens of a First Nation would have to obey the laws of general application at a minimum, and if the First Nation law imposed a stricter standard, then the citizen would have to obey that standard as well. Therefore, the consequence of overlap would simply mean that the regulatory standards applicable to citizens would be no lower than the standards set out in laws of general application applying to other persons located off First Nations lands.
<p>
This result may, however, be seen as a problem in cases where a First Nation wishes for public policy reasons to implement a regime which has lower standards than those in the laws of general application. For example, a First Nation may wish to set up an adoption regime which does not contain the same level of formality as the regime established under the applicable provincial or territorial laws. The application of the normal test for inconsistency may in such cases lead to a result that is not intended or desired by either the First Nation or the government.
<p>
It is possible that another type of conflict could arise under this category of power, due to the manner in which eligibility for membership or citizenship may be defined by First Nations. In some cases, it is possible that a person would be eligible to be a member or citizen of more than one First Nation. Or, it is possible that a person may be eligible for membership or citizenship but has not become a member or citizen. The issue that would then arise
would be to which set of laws that person would be subject. If this question could not be answered under the tests of jurisdiction, courts would be able to resort to applicable conflicts-of-laws rules to resolve the matter. This aspect is, however, beyond the scope of this article.
<p>
<i>Citizen-Based Services-Oriented Powers</i><br>
The situation with respect to services-oriented powers is more complex. The problem in these cases is not so much with the creation of conflicting standards but rather with the concern over duplication of services. The issue arises because First Nations' citizens or members are likely to retain their eligibility for many services and benefits that are available to them as Canadian citizens and residents of a province or territory, in addition to being eligible for services provided by their First Nations.
<p>
This is the case under the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement. Sections 3.4, 3.5 and 3.6 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement address the continuing rights of the First Nations' citizens:
<blockquote>
3.4 Unless otherwise provided pursuant to this Agreement or in a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, this Agreement shall not affect the ability of Citizens to participate in and benefit from Government programs for status Indians, non-status Indians or native people, as the case may be. Benefits under such programs shall be determined by the general criteria for such programs established from time to time.
<p>
3.5 Except for the purposes of determining which Citizens are &quot;Indians&quot; within the meaning of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, R.S.C. 1985, c. I--5, the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, R.S.C. 1985, c. I--5, does not apply
to Citizens, the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations or Settlement Land.
<p>
3.6 This Agreement shall not:
<blockquote>
3.6.1 affect the rights of Citizens as Canadian citizens; and
<p>
3.6.2 unless otherwise provided pursuant to this Agreement or in a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, affect the entitlement of Citizens to all of the benefits, services, and protections of other Canadian citizens applicable from time to time.
</blockquote></blockquote>
These sections were intended to ensure that the First Nations citizens would have continuing rights of Canadian citizenship (including the same eligibility as other Yukon residents to benefit from programs and services offered to residents of the Yukon either by the federal or the territorial government) and that they would still be eligible for programs and services offered by the federal government under the <cite>Indian Act</cite>.
<p>
The consequence of such provisions is that the citizens of the First Nations would continue to be eligible for services provided by the Yukon government or the federal government under laws of general application, if those laws continued to apply to the First Nations' citizens, even though the First Nations had also decided to
exercise their powers under s. 13.2 and begin offering a similar service. For example, citizens could be eligible in their status as Yukon residents for social assistance payments from the Yukon government, and also be eligible for payments from the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations in their status as citizens of the First Nations. Similar situations could also arise with respect to other fields of services, such as health care, education, language
services, and so on.
<p>
It appears very likely that the result of the courts applying the traditional tests of jurisdiction would be to uphold
both sets of laws---after all, there is no conflict <i>per se</i> in being eligible to receive benefits from two sources. There is really no concept of a stricter standard that would have to be obeyed by the persons affected by the overlapping jurisdictions---the only issue would be whether they met the eligibility requirements for the
services in question. The consequence would be that both sets of laws would be upheld as validly applying to the citizens of the First Nations, and hence those citizens would have a right to services provided under both sets of laws. It may be argued that this is not necessarily undesirable from the perspective of the individuals involved, as it means that they will be able to choose whether they wish to participate in services offered by the First Nations or by
the government or perhaps both. However, from the perspective of both the First Nations and of government, serious concerns arise.
<p>
First, a First Nation may be concerned because this dual eligibility would allow its citizens effectively to ignore the
programs and services that the First Nation is offering, perhaps as part of an integrated social service regime, by simply opting to take the programs and services offered by government instead. This could undermine the ability of a First Nation to implement comprehensive regimes of programs and services which it wants to provide directly
to citizens.
<p>
The second concern may be more significant and concerns the financial impact on government and First Nations spending that the duplication of services would cause. If a First Nation begins providing a service that is already provided by government, then there will be a certain degree of duplication, at a minimum administrative cost duplication. There may also be concerns with &quot;double-dipping,&quot; whereby people eligible for both services actually take the services from both sources, even though the intent was that they be mutually exclusive. Government anxiety over this would increase as the number of First Nations with such service-oriented powers increased---and, as mentioned above, this will probably be 14 in the Yukon.
<p>
This potential concern is exacerbated under conditions of scarce financial resources. In such circumstances, government and First Nations will simply not be able to afford duplicate services. The financial impact could be very severe, and could reduce the level of services that government could provide to all residents of the
province or territory. For example, under the Yukon self-government agreements, funding for the Yukon First Nations is provided directly to the Yukon First Nations by the federal government. However, the federal government also provides much of the funding for the Yukon government through a formula financing agreement. This means that the federal government will be in a position to transfer funding from the Yukon government to Yukon First Nations as the Yukon First Nations take on responsibilities. As it is extremely unlikely that the federal government will agree to pay twice for the same service, it means that any funding paid to a Yukon First Nation for the provision of a given program or service will no longer be available to the Yukon government, even though the Yukon government may remain under an obligation to continue providing that same service or program to those citizens of the Yukon First Nation. The consequence of duplication of services would be that the government would have less money with which to provide the services but would still have the same number of people that are eligible for the service. The overall impact would be a reduction of the amount of funds <i>per capita</i> available for provision of services to residents of the territory.
<p>
Hence, in these situations, it seems quite possible that the usual approaches to determination of jurisdiction may not be appropriate. The current approach used by the courts has the effect of allowing two overlapping laws to continue to co-exist, unless there is a real impossibility of compliance with both laws. However, in the context of overlapping responsibilities for provision of services, that may not be the desirable result from a public policy perspective. While under most circumstances governments would want to have their legislative jurisdiction recognized and maintained to the greatest degree possible, which is the effect of the inconsistency test's tolerance of overlap, in the case of the provision of services, governments may be more interested in <i>not</i> maintaining jurisdiction over services which First Nations begin to provide pursuant to their own legislation. It is because of this
problem with the application of the traditional test of inconsistency that other approaches will have to be used to address overlaps in this area.
<p>
SOLUTIONS IN THE CHAMPAGNE AND AISHIHIK FIRST NATIONS SELF-GOVERNMENT AGREEMENT AND IN THE <cite>SECHELT ACT</cite>
<p>
This problem was identified in the course of the negotiation of the self-government agreement for the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and other Yukon First Nations. The more difficult issue was how to deal with the problem in a way that recognized the legal and administrative challenges that were raised.
<p>
The solution that was developed for the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement is set out in ss. 13.5.3 through 13.5.7 of that agreement. These provisions were intended to address the problem of overlaps between laws of the Yukon government and the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations. Although
these provisions apply to all possible cases of overlap under the self-government agreement, they were in the main developed in response to concerns about overlapping laws related to the provision of services to citizens of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations by the First Nations and by the Yukon government. The sections in
question read as follows:
<blockquote>
13.5.3 Except as provided in 14.0, a Yukon Law of General Application shall be inoperative to the extent that it provides for any matter for which provision is made in a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.
<p>
13.5.4 Where the Yukon reasonably foresees that a Yukon Law of General Application which it intends to enact may have an impact on a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, the Yukon shall Consult with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations before introducing the Legislation in the Legislative Assembly.
<p>
13.5.5 Where the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations reasonably foresees that a law which it intends to enact may have an impact on a Yukon Law of General Application, the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations shall Consult with the Yukon before enacting the law.
<p>
13.5.6 Where the Commissioner in Executive Council is of the opinion that a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations has rendered a Yukon Law of General Application partially inoperative and that it would unreasonably alter the character of a Yukon Law of General Application or that it would make it unduly difficult to administer that Yukon Law of General Application in relation to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, Citizens or Settlement Land, the Commissioner in Executive Council may declare that the Yukon Law of General Application ceases to apply in whole or in part to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, Citizens or Settlement Land.
<p>
13.5.7 Prior to making a declaration pursuant to 13.5.6, the Yukon shall:
<blockquote>
13.5.7.1 Consult with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and identify solutions, including and amendments to Yukon Legislation, that the Yukon considers would meet the objectives of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations; and
<p>
13.5.7.2 after Consultation pursuant to 13.5.7.1, where the Yukon and the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations agree that the Yukon Law of General Application should be amended, the Yukon shall propose such amendment to the Legislative Assembly within a reasonable period of time.
</blockquote></blockquote>
It may be seen that these provisions combine a legal approach---a variation on the test of inconsistency---with an
administrative approach---consultation by the Yukon government with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations on legislative initiatives, combined with a power to declare that laws of general application enacted by the Yukon Legislative Assembly do not apply to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations and their citizens and settlement lands. 
<p>
Section 13.5.3 can be seen as an attempt to modify the normal test of inconsistency in an attempt to make it more likely that Yukon laws of general application will be rendered inoperative with respect to the First Nations. Instead of stating that the Yukon laws would be &quot;inoperative to the extent of inconsistency&quot; with First Nations laws (which is the normal test of inconsistency), this section says that a Yukon law is &quot;inoperative to the extent that it provides for any matter for which provision is made in a law enacted by the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.&quot;  Therefore, the test is not whether there is conflict between the two laws. Rather, the test is whether First Nations laws provide for the same matter. In essence, this section attempts to change the methods used by the courts in sorting out overlapping jurisdiction, through the imposition of an occupied field test in the place of the inconsistency test. The effect, of course, would be to make it more likely that Yukon government laws would be found to be inapplicable in circumstances where the First Nations had exercised their law-making powers to provide a service or program. This was intended to make it less likely that there would be a problem with  duplication of services offered by the government and the First Nations.
<p>
However, it was recognized in the negotiation of the agreement that this broader test of conflict between the laws may still not address all of the potential problems that could arise. A serious concern was the possibility that the First Nations could exercise their legislative jurisdiction piece-meal, enacting statutes that addressed very limited aspects of certain fields. The consequence of this would be that the Yukon laws of general application would continue to apply to most of the aspects of the given matter, but would be rendered inoperative here and there by the
First Nations' laws. This was seen as a potential problem with respect to enforcement of regulatory-type laws, and with respect to the implementation and administration of services and programs under Yukon laws. 
<p>
Therefore, other provisions were added in order to make it less likely that problems would be created in legislation, and to provide the Yukon government with greater flexibility in addressing problems that did arise. Sections 13.5.4 and 13.5.5 were intended to ensure that the two jurisdictions consulted one another on their legislative agendas, so that each would be aware of the other's plans and would be able to consider the possible impact on their own legislative schemes. It was also intended that each jurisdiction would consider the possible impact on the other in designing the law that was to be enacted, and would thus identify means of dealing with potential concerns related to implementation and administration of programs and services. In this case, this avenue for control of problems of overlap is in the hands of the legislative branches of the Yukon government and the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations.
<p>
However, it was felt that even the combination of the broader test of conflict between laws and the consultation provisions may not be adequate to deal with problems caused by overlapping jurisdiction and laws. Therefore, ss. 13.5.6 and 13.5.7 were added to provide a further level of control, in this case in the hands of the executive. These sections allow the Yukon government to unilaterally decide that its laws will cease to apply to the Champagne and
Aishihik First Nations, their lands and their citizens. This would operate through a declaration by the Yukon's Commissioner in Executive Council.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> Section 13.5.6 imposes certain restrictions on the discretion of the Commissioner in Executive Council to make such a declaration: the Commissioner in Executive Council must be of the opinion (a) that the Yukon law has been rendered inoperative in part and (b) that this would change the effect of the Yukon law unreasonably or that this would make it too difficult to administer the law effectively. Only if both those conditions were met, in the opinion of the Commissioner
in Executive Council, would it be possible to suspend the application of the Yukon law to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, their lands and their citizens.
<p>
A further procedural restriction is imposed on the Yukon government's ability to make a declaration under s. 13.5.6: the government is obliged under s. 13.5.7.1 to consult with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations before making such a declaration in order to try to identify other solutions to the overlap problem that are less drastic than that in s. 13.5.6, including potential amendments. In the event that the Yukon government and the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations decide that the problem can be dealt with through a change to the Yukon law in question, s. 13.5.7.2 then requires the Yukon government to introduce into the Yukon Legislative Assembly a proposal to make such an amendment to the Yukon law.
<p>
Of the three mechanisms set out in ss. 13.5.3, 13.5.4 and 13.5.6 for dealing with problems of overlap, the power of the Yukon government under s. 13.5.6 to declare laws inapplicable to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations is perhaps the most notable for its potential breadth of application and for the considerable discretion that it vests, notwithstanding the consultative requirements, in the Yukon government. In the Yukon context, the demographic situation will provide a fairly strong check on any plans to exercise this power in an unreasonable manner---Yukon Indian people constitute between twenty-five and thirty percent of the territorial electorate. However, this sort of practical check on the possible misuse of such a power may not exist in southern jurisdictions where Indian people are a very small percentage of the population and hence have less effective political influence.
<p>
It may be noted that a similar provision exists in the <cite>Sechelt Act</cite>. Section 36 confers on the federal Governor in Council a power similar to that contained in s. 13.5.6 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement. Section 36 reads as follows:
<blockquote>
36. The Governor in Council may, on the advice of the Minister, by order declare that the <cite>Indian Act</cite> or any provision thereof does not apply to
<blockquote>
(a) the Band or its members, or<p>
(b) any portion of Sechelt lands,
</blockquote>
and may, on the advice of the Minister, by order revoke any such order.
</blockquote>
Since this section deals only with the relationship between the <cite>Indian Act</cite> and the Sechelt Indian Band, however, its significance as a means of resolving overlaps in jurisdiction is much less than that of section 13.5.6 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement.
<p>
The combination of legislative, judicial and administrative control mechanisms has advantages and disadvantages. The legislative approach set out in s. 13.5.3 has the advantage of placing the responsibility for control of legislative jurisdiction in the hands of independent arbiters. The judiciary would not have a vested interest in the outcome of decisions on overlaps in jurisdiction, in contrast to the legislators and the administrators. However, the disadvantage of relying on the courts to resolve this type of jurisdictional problem is that the approaches used by the courts may not be in accord with the needs of the parties or the fiscal, social and economic realities of the situation. Moreover, the test set out in s. 13.5.3 simply may not be capable of achieving the result needed in the case of overlaps with respect to powers and responsibilities to provide services. In addition, the actual wording of the test of overlap contained in s. 13.5.3 is broader and less concrete than the test of inconsistency, and means that there will be a greater element of judicial subjectivity involved in making determinations as to jurisdiction.
<p>
The legislative and administrative approaches both have the advantages of encouraging communication between the Yukon government and the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations as to their respective legislative agendas and their mutual interests in coordinating legislative initiatives. The disadvantage, especially with respect to the power to suspend the application of Yukon laws pursuant to section 13.5.6, is the potential for disagreement as to their proper use. The conditions set out in the section (&quot;altering the character&quot; of a Yukon law or making it &quot;unduly difficult to administer&quot; a Yukon law) are susceptible to varying interpretations, and furthermore the question of whether those conditions are satisfied is left to the discretion of the Yukon cabinet. While the demographic realities of the Yukon may provide an effective check on the abuse of this discretion, it may prove virtually impossible to rely on judicial supervision of the exercise of this discretionary power. 
<p>
What is interesting about these latter approaches, however, is that they recognize that the advent of self-government means that the traditional approaches to sorting out overlapping jurisdiction---judicial tests of legislative competence and inconsistency---may have to be modified or even supplemented by other approaches. These approaches demonstrate that a willingness to consider creative alternative approaches will be necessary in arriving at workable relationships between First Nations and the federal and provincial governments.
<p>
<h3>IV.  Summary and Conclusions</h3>

This article has provided a look at one of the key technical challenges associated with the negotiation and implementation of self-government arrangements in Canada. That challenge is related to the design of the interface between the existing orders of federal and provincial government and what I assume will be the new third order of government, the First Nations. In particular, the challenge is how to deal with new problems that will arise as a
result of the way in which self-government powers are defined.
<p>
The traditional approaches used by the courts today to address overlapping legislative jurisdictions were, obviously,
developed in the context of only two levels of government, with only limited overlap in their powers. Because of concerns about the roles of the courts with respect to the legislative branch of government, the approaches used by the courts in Canada have tended toward upholding legislation enacted by one level of government despite overlapping jurisdiction of the other level. The test of inconsistency in particular is extremely tolerant of overlap, to the extent that provincial legislation has been upheld despite the fact that in substance it duplicates federal legislation covering the same matter.
<p>
However, self-government powers are being defined in a new way. They are being defined under a paradigm which sees all legislative powers in Canada as having been allocated already to either the federal or the provincial level. Consequently, self-government powers will be overlaid on top of the existing division of powers, which means that a large degree of overlap---much greater than that between the federal and provincial levels---is almost inevitable. In addition, because First Nations may not have extensive land bases, it may not be possible or appropriate to limit
certain of their powers to the lands they control, as this would greatly reduce their ability to govern their own affairs and interests effectively. Therefore, powers have been defined which apply to First Nations' citizens wherever they may be, whether on or off First Nations' lands. This is of particular importance with respect to services, as First Nations' citizens will still have entitlements to services provided by the other levels of government as well.
<p>
These differences mean that the traditional test of inconsistency may not work appropriately when it is applied in such a different context. While the inconsistency test may still work well with respect to First Nations' regulatory powers, it is less capable of dealing with the issue of overlap with respect to services-related powers. This is because the inconsistency test tolerates a wide degree of overlap, and when it comes to services-related powers
overlap will be something that government and First Nations will probably want to avoid. Therefore, different approaches may have to be developed to deal with this type of overlap.
<p>
The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement provides an example of some different approaches that may be considered. The agreement sets out an expanded judicial test for overlap, broader than the usual test of inconsistency, and closer to an occupied field test. The agreement also sets out methods relying
on the legislative and executive branches of government in dealing with overlap. 
<p>
The Yukon government is required to consult with the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations before introducing into the Yukon Legislative Assembly legislation that may affect First Nations laws. This provides a mechanism for the law-makers to consider the potential impact of their actions on the other's jurisdiction, and will provide a means for preventing overlap problems from arising.
<p>
The Yukon government is also given the power to declare that provisions of its laws do not apply to the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations, their citizens and their lands. This gives the executive branch the administrative discretion to deal with overlap problems by, in essence, ceding jurisdiction on the matter. While this power is discretionary and may be hard to supervise through judicial review, there are practical checks on the use of this power in the context of the Yukon where Indian people are a significant proportion of the electorate. Hence, this may prove to be an effective fall-back mechanism for dealing with overlap.
<p>
Whether any of these approaches may work in a southern Canadian context is difficult to assess. In the provinces, the constitutional position is more complicated with respect to jurisdiction over matters of interest to First Nations. In addition, the greater number of First Nations in the provinces in comparison to the Yukon means that addressing overlap may be more complex than in the Yukon. In addition, administrative solutions, such as the Yukon
government's discretionary power to withdraw its laws from application to First Nations, may not be easily or appropriately transportable to the south, where First Nations and their citizens have much less political influence and may therefore be more vulnerable to misuse of such a power. However, these administrative solutions illustrate the sort of creative approach that will have to be employed in the negotiation of self-government arrangements and in the accommodation of a new order of government within the Canadian constitutional framework.
<p>
There is an important role for the legal profession to play in coming up with innovative solutions to technical issues such as these which arise in the context of self-government negotiations. By addressing any technical obstacles that arise in these negotiations, the parties will be able to focus on the more important public policy issues of the scope and content of self-government powers. This may have the added benefit of reducing the costs, in both financial and human terms, of negotiating and implementing self-government arrangements for First Nations in Canada.
<p>
