<li><a name="forty"><cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, s. 14(i).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty1"><cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, s. 14(g).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty2">These two powers provide</a> an interesting example of how certain subject matters may be dealt with differently in different self-government agreements. In this agreement, the Sechelt Indian Band has the power to make laws respecting the education of all Band members, but the power applies only on Sechelt lands. Under the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement, the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations have the power under s. 13.2.8 to provide education services to those citizens &quot;choosing to participate,&quot; but the power extends off settlement land and throughout the Yukon.
<p>
The Sechelt Indian Band's power to provide health services is limited to Sechelt lands, but applies to anyone on
Sechelt land (<cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, s. 14(i)). The comparable power for the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations applies only to Champagne and Aishihik First Nations' citizens, but extends off settlement land and throughout the Yukon (except for regulation of facilities off settlement land) (s. 13.2.3).
<p>
These show how First Nations' powers over similar subject matters may be defined in varying ways from one self-government agreement to another, depending on the circumstances of the negotiations and on the objectives of
each First Nation and the governments involved.
<P>
<li><a name="forty3"><cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, s. 14(h).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty4">Emphasis added.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty5">These are subsections</a> (a), (b), (c), (d), (e), (f), (j), (k), (l), (m), (n), (o), (p), (q), (r), (s), (t) and (u).
<p>
<li><a name="forty6">For example, the</a> Council is given the power to make laws respecting management of
natural resources on Sechelt lands, subject to the proviso that those laws provide standards and rights at least equivalent to those prevailing in British Columbia from time to time (Band Constitution, Part III---Laws, Division (1), s. 7). (s. 14(j)).
<p>
The Council also has the power to make laws prohibiting the sale, barter, supply, manufacture or possession of intoxicants on Sechelt lands. However, before the Council may make a law under this power, the law must first be assented to by a majority of members voting in a special meeting called to consider the proposed law (Band
Constitution, Part III---Laws, Division (1), s. 12).
<p>
<li><a name="forty7">P.W. Hogg,</a> <cite>Constitutional Law of Canada</cite>, 3d ed. (Toronto: Carswell, 1992).
<p>
<li><a name="forty8"><cite>Bank of Montreal v. Hall</cite>, [1990] 1 S.C.R. 121.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty8">It should be noted</a> that this analysis is based only on the types of narrowly defined
exclusive powers set out in section 13.1 of the Champagne and Aishihik First Nations self-government agreement. If a wider range of more broadly defined exclusive powers were to be negotiated, it is possible that this analysis would have to be reconsidered, depending on the subject matters involved.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty">The section reads:</a>
<blockquote>
13.3 The Champagne and Aishihik First Nations shall have the power to enact laws <i>of a local or private nature</i> on Settlement Land in relation to the following matters... [emphasis added].
</blockquote>
<li><a name="fifty1">In</a> <cite>Hodge v. R.</cite> (1883--1884), 9 App. Cas. 117, the Privy Council recognized that matters that looked like a federal responsibility in one case could also look like a provincial responsibility in another. Noting that federal and provincial laws may affect the same subject matter, but for different purposes, the Privy Council stated that &quot;[t]he principle [illustrated] is, that subjects which in one aspect and for one purpose fall within sect. 92, may in another aspect and for another purpose fall within sect. 91&quot; (<i>ibid.</i> at 130). This &quot;double aspect&quot; doctrine has led to significant overlap in federal and provincial legislative powers.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty2">The</a> &quot;incidental effects&quot; doctrine recognizes that a law enacted by one
level of government can have effects on subject matters within the jurisdiction of the other level. This acknowledges the reality that it would be virtually impossible, given the way the powers in s. 91 and 92 are set out, to require that each law enacted by one level of government have no effects on subject matters within the other level's jurisdiction. There is an extensive case law on this point; see, e.g., <cite>A.G. (Quebec) v. Kellogg's</cite>, [1978] 2 S.C.R. 211.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty3">See, e.g.</a> <cite>Interprovincial Cooperatives v. The Queen</cite>, [1976] 1 S.C.R. 477, <i>per</i> Pigeon J.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty4">Champagne and Aishihik First Nations agreement, s. 13.5.3.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty5">Champagne and Aishihik First Nations agreement, s. 13.5.2.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty6"><cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, s. 38.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty7"><cite>Sechelt Act</cite>, s. 37.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty8">See the discussion above.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty9">Examples</a> of services-oriented powers would include powers to provide aboriginal
language services (s. 13.2.2), health care services (s. 13.2.3), social and welfare services (s. 13.2.4), training programs (s. 13.2.5), education services (s. 13.2.8) and services for dispute resolution outside of the court system (s. 13.2.11).
<p>
<li><a name="sixty">An example would</a> include the power over child custody, care and placement (s. 13.2.7), which has both regulatory aspects (with respect to guardianship and custody, for example) and services aspects (with respect to provision of off-settlement land day care, for example).
<p>
<li><a name="sixty1">Champagne and Aishihik First Nations agreement, s. 13.2.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty2">This is the power to</a> provide social and welfare services to Band members (s. 14(h)).
<p>
<li><a name="sixty3">See the discussion of this issue above.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty4">The Commissioner is,</a> under the <cite>Yukon Act</cite>, R.S.C. 1985, c. Y--2, the territorial equivalent to a province's Lieutenant Governor, and the Commissioner in Executive Council is the equivalent to the Lieutenant Governor in Council.
</ol><p><br>
