<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 53 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Protecting Workers' Reproductive Health: Lessons from Quebec and Other Statutory Regimes
<p>
JANIS SARRA<sup><a href="#note">*</a></sup></h1>

<i>Employees are exposed to numerous reproductive health risks in their employment. Possible statutory remedies for these risks in human rights, health and safety, and workers' compensation legislation are analyszed. Outside of Qu&eacute;bec, the legislative regimes do not appear to be effective in either reducing the level of risk, or allowing employees to protect their incomes if they decide to have a child while working for an employer whose workplace
contains risks. In fact, these regimes are hardly ever utilized to address reproductive health issues. Qu&eacute;bec, however, has a unique regime for the protection of pregnant and nursing employees. An employee who produces a medical certificate is entitled to reassignment or paid leave while pregnant or nursing. The Qu&eacute;bec legislation is widely utilized by employees. The contrasting levels of utilization indicate that the problem in the rest of Canada is not there there no reproductive hazards, but rather, an effective statutory scheme is lacking. One of the foundation blocks of such a scheme should be income protection for workers during times when they are most vulnerable to reproductive hazards.
<p>
Les travailleurs se trouvent expos&eacute;s &agrave; nombreux dangers dans le lieu d' emploi qui mena&ccedil;ent la sant&eacute; reproductive. Les recours statutoires dans la Code sur des droits de la personne, la Loi sur la sant&eacute; et securit&eacute; au travail, et la Loi sur les accidents du travail sont analys&eacute;s. Hors du Qu&eacute;bec, le r&eacute;gime statutoire ne semble &ecirc;tre efficace ni &agrave; r&eacute;duire le niveau du
danger, ni &agrave; proteger le salaire d'un/e employ&eacute;/e qui d&eacute;cide d'avoir un enfant pendant qu'il/elle travaille dans un lieu comportant des dangers &agrave; la sant&eacute; reproductive. En fait, ces r&eacute;gimes ne sont que rarement utilis&eacute;s pour vindiquer le droit &agrave; la sant&eacute; reproductive. Cependant le r&eacute;gime qu&eacute;becois  reste unique dans son protection des employ&eacute;es enceintes et
allaitantes. Une employ&eacute;e avec un certificat m&eacute;dical tient le droit d'&ecirc;tre affect&eacute;e &agrave; des t&acirc;ches ne comportant pas de dangers ou &agrave; un cong&eacute; pay&eacute; pendant la grossesse ou l'allaitement. Les employ&eacute;s qu&eacute;becois pont recours &agrave; la l&eacute;gislation. La diff&eacute;rence entre les niveaux d'utilisation des recours statutoires au Qu&eacute;bec et dans le reste du Canada indique que le probl&egrave;me dans le reste du Canada est qu'il n'y existe pas de r&eacute;gime statutoire efficace pour r&eacute;pondre au probl&egrave;me des dangers r&eacute;productifs, et non pas qu'il n'y existe pas des dangers r&eacute;productifs. Une caract&eacute;ristique fondamentale d'une r&eacute;gime statutoire efficace
devrait &ecirc;tre la protection du salaire pendant les p&eacute;riodes lorsque les employ&eacute;s sont le plus susceptibles aux menaces &agrave; la sant&eacute; r&eacute;productive.</i>
<p>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

There is a rapidly growing body of American jurisprudence on the question of reproductive hazards in the workplace.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> At the centre of debate is the relationship between women's rights to equal treatment in employment, the rights of both male and female workers to safe workplaces, and the legal obligations of employers whose workplaces employ substances or practices which are known or suspected reproductive hazards.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> In Canada, outside Quebec, there has been neither the same volume of litigation, nor the intensity of debate around these social and legal questions. Only in Quebec,
where specific measures have been enacted which grant rights to reassignment or paid leave, has there developed a jurisprudence on reproductive health risks.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> This article explores the reasons for this, by examining the Canadian jurisprudence with respect to these issues in the various statutory regimes governing human rights, workers' compensation, and health and safety.
<p>
I suggest that the current patchwork quilt of statutory laws governing workplace reproductive hazards looks more like a &quot;crazy quilt&quot; than a co-ordinated and integrated pattern of laws. Crazy quilts made in rural Ontario at the start of the century were taken from the scraps of old clothing and sewn together in a haphazard
fashion, hence the name. Similarly, this article will demonstrate how the current regime governing reproductive health is a series of legislative measures, each enacted to meet the political exigencies of the time. The overall result is a statutory regime that fails to protect individuals from the adverse effects of reproductive hazards. A non-comprehensive statutory framework can arguably create multiple points of access for individuals seeking to enforce substantive rights, and can undoubtedly help generate different institutional outlooks, but this article will illustrate how these possible advantages are seriously outweighed by the failure of the regimes to provide comprehensive protection.
<p>
It is important to recognize that gains are slowly being made in both Canada and the United States in dismantling discriminatory policies which exclude women of child-bearing age from particular jobs which pose reproductive health risks.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> There is, however, no corresponding recognition in either legislation or social policy of the need to eliminate reproductive health risks for all workers. The lack of co-ordination and coverage between the various statutory regimes has meant that employees are needlessly and continually exposed to these hazards and their adverse health effects. In particular, the failure to enact legislation requiring pre-market testing of new substances creates a situation where workers pay for new economic and industrial advances with their health. Current health and safety laws, which grant the right to refuse unsafe work in jurisdictions other than Quebec, are not being utilized by affected employees to prevent exposure to reproductive health hazards. In contrast, under Quebec law, the right to reassignment or paid leave for pregnant or nursing
women is extensively utilized. Quebec law is unique in recognizing the need to provide alternatives to risky exposure, at the same time as protecting job security and income. The Quebec regime promotes public policy goals of equal access to the workplace and protection of workers who are most vulnerable to adverse reproductive health
effects. The higher level of utilization of the Quebec regime in comparison to regimes in the rest of Canada is not due to the fact that hazards do not exist elsewhere. Rather, the available income protection and job security provisions, as well as the way in which the burden of proof has been interpreted, fundamentally affect how
frequently statutory remedies are used.
 <p>
Part I of this article provides a brief overview of the types of reproductive health issues existing in the workplace. It seems clear that these risks exist for both women and men. This conclusion is reinforced by the findings of the recent report of the Royal Commission on New Reproductive Technologies, which discussed the extent of exposure of Canadian workers to reproductive health hazards.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> Yet the focus of both
research and litigation has been on the reproductive health risks for women, to the virtual exclusion of consideration of risks to males. This is because most of the litigation has dealt with these risks as human rights issues as opposed to issues of workplace health and safety.
<p>
Part II examines occupational health and safety laws that currently exist to protect employees from reproductive health hazards. The Quebec law which provides for preventive reassignment of work or leaves of absence for pregnant women or nursing mothers is examined in detail, as is Ontario legislation which provides workers with the
right to refuse unsafe work. I will discuss why the Quebec legislation is comparatively more successful in protecting reproductive health rights.
<p>
Part III then examines the human rights issues, most specifically, the right to equal treatment in employment and its tension with employer responsibility for reproductive health hazards in the workplace. The leading Canadian decision on this issue, <cite>Weins v. Inco Metals Co.</cite>,<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> is analyzed for its legal and social policy implications. <cite>Weins</cite> is particularly significant given the paucity of Canadian case law dealing with these issues. <cite>Weins</cite> will then be compared with the U.S. Supreme Court decision in <cite>Johnson Controls Inc.</cite>,<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> in order to assess the similarities and
differences.
<p>
Finally, the conclusion looks at recent developments and suggests some immediate and long term prospects for addressing the fragmented and ineffective regimes protecting reproductive health. This article discusses how the Royal Commission on New Reproductive Technologies, in its final report, failed to focus on many of the issues raised in this article and in its own background study. Finally, I propose strategies for future protection from workplace reproductive hazards, modelled on the Quebec experience.
<p>
<h3>PART I:   Overview of Reproductive Hazards in the Workplace</h3>

Over the past forty years, between 67,000 and 100,000 new chemicals and substances have been introduced into the
workplace.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> The health effects of many of these substances are completely unknown. Traditional toxicological studies rarely evaluated reproductive health effects.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> Only in some cases have the negative consequences of various levels of exposure been documented. In even fewer cases have laws or regulations been enacted to limit workplace exposure levels.
<p>
Within the broader framework of the health effects of new substances and procedures is the narrower question of reproductive health hazards in the workplace. Given the large number of women of child-bearing age in the Canadian workforce, it is surprising that more information is not available concerning either the number of women who work during pregnancy or the reproductive hazards they face during this period. Although precise numbers are not known, the fact that 58 per cent of mothers with children under age three were working in 1988, and 75 per cent of families with children this age had both parents working full-time, indicates that a high percentage of women are likely working during pregnancy and probably while continuing to breast-feed.<sup><a href =  #ten">10</a></sup> Few studies have been done on the impact of working upon conception and pregnancy. An early British study found that a woman's chance of bearing a healthy child was greater if she was not employed outside the home.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> The study failed, however, to draw any conclusions about the causes of the higher risks for women working. The study also did not examine miscarriages, which may have revealed important information concerning issues of fertility and early embryo development. A study by the United States Public Health Service found as early as 1968 that 59 per cent of all women bearing a first child were employed during their pregnancy.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> Today, more women work for more years in the labour force for reasons of economic necessity. In Canada, full-time women workers earn on average 40 per cent of the family income, and it is estimated, for example, that the number of two-parent families below the poverty line would increase by 78 per cent if women did not work.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> Thus, it is likely that greater numbers of women are exposed to reproductive health risks during their reproductive years than when these early studies were conducted.
<p>
Workers have been increasingly exposed to chemicals, some of which  are now known to cause adverse health effects and to impair their reproductive capacity. For example, agricultural workers are exposed to pesticides, electrical technicians to polychlorinated biphenyl, and manufacturing and industrial sector workers are exposed to
benzene, lead, mercury, and vinyl chloride. Employees in the pharmaceutical industry are exposed to alkylating chemicals, and operating room nurses, anesthetists, and dental assistants to anesthetic gases. There are also adverse reproductive health effects associated with insufficient oxygen supply, such as the carbon monoxide hazards faced by road workers, traffic control personnel, and toll booth operators. Since women require 20 to 30 per cent more
oxygen and produce 30 per cent more blood during pregnancy, the susceptibility of both mother and fetus to chemicals through inhalation and the bloodstream is increased substantially. These substances are associated with a broad range of adverse health effects, including menstrual disorders, failure to conceive, spontaneous abortion, damage to the developing embryo or fetus, and post-birth defects, such as Down's syndrome.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup>
<p>
In addition to chemical risks, there are other work procedures and practices that create reproductive risks. Both ionizing and non-ionizing radiation and radio-active exposure pose a risk to dental and X-ray technicians.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> Infectious diseases make hospital, chronic care, daycare, and social work occupations risky for those who are pregnant because of the possibility of exposure to measles, chicken pox, rubella, cytomegalovirus, and hepatitis B.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> Those who handle raw meat or animals are at risk if they come into contact with toxic plasmosis, brucellosi, or some strains of herpes.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> More recently, studies have suggested that the design of work, the ergonomics, may be a reproductive risk for workers.<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> This would include work requiring heavy lifting, or work necessitating sitting or standing in a confined position for prolonged periods of time.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup>
<p>
One issue is the danger to the health of both mother and fetus during pregnancy. Once a woman becomes pregnant, the most critical biological period is the first eight weeks of gestation. During this period, all the organ systems are established and thus are highly susceptible to outside influences.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> Often, however, women are unaware that they are pregnant during this early period, and fetal damage may have occurred prior to taking preventive measures. In addition, many women who have given birth return to the workplace while they are still breast-feeding. Substances such as lead, mercury, cadmium, or pesticides can pass from the mother's bloodstream into the milk supply and cause detrimental health effects to the nursing child.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup>
<p>
Recently, the federal Royal Commission on New Reproductive Technologies published research papers suggesting that the magnitude and range of occupational reproductive health hazards is likely much broader than historically defined. It suggests the following: 
<blockquote>
[T]he range of adverse reproductive outcomes runs along a continuum that moves from disorders causing delay or lack of conception (i.e. menstrual disorders, hormonal problems, impotence, sperm abnormalities, uterine fibroid, tubal occlusions) to adverse effects on pregnancy (e.g. toxaemia, spontaneous abortions), to adverse birth outcome (e.g. stillbirth, low birthweight, congenital abnormalities).<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Royal Commission's mandate was to spend four years researching and reporting on current medical and scientific developments in reproductive technology, including the causes and prevention of infertility. Its goal was to provide direction for public policy, and to make practical recommendations to enhance public awareness and facilitate public participation in the future of reproductive technologies.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> In the fifteen volumes of research studies prepared for the Commission, only two studies out of all of the copious volumes actually deal with occupational hazards. Yet the Commission estimated, based on American figures, that roughly 1.5 million Canadian workers may be exposed to potentially harmful chemicals and substances in the
workplace, with an unknown number facing reproductive health risks. It divided the reproductive risks into five categories of possible causes of adverse effects: chemical, physical, biological, psychological (stressors), and ergonomic. It found that there is an &quot;urgent need&quot; to undertake a comprehensive research program, and
recommended studying environmental and occupational health hazards, collecting data, and monitoring exposure levels.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup>
<p>
Many substances have not yet been studied and their possible ill-effects are not known. One ethical problem that the background study for the Royal Commission identified is that the scientific community requires an extremely high standard of proof before it will declare a substance to be a reproductive hazard, and, in the interim, employees bear the risk of uncertainty until hazards are definitively proven.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> The difficulties of lack of research and information about workplace reproductive hazards are compounded for men.
<p>
THE FOCUS ON PROTECTION OF FEMALE RATHER THAN MALE WORKERS
<p>
Exposure to chemicals and other substances in the workplace has an effect upon the reproductive capacity of both men and women, yet very little research has been undertaken with respect to the detrimental health effects on groups other than pregnant women.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> In part this may be due to
historical notions that child-bearing and resulting health issues exclusively affected women.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> A major problem is that there is no requirement to test the reproductive hazards of chemicals or other substances <i>before</i> they are introduced into the workplace. Although both impotence and sterility have been documented, the more complex or subtle effects of exposure to particular chemicals or practices are virtually unknown. Stellman notes that although half the genetic material contributing to the fertilized egg comes from the male sperm, the effect of workplace hazards on male genes is usually overlooked.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> She argues that substances which cause mutations in female sex cells can also cause mutations in male sex cells, citing the documented effects of radiation, X-rays, excessive heat, lead, benzene, kepone, and cadmium as examples of substances which lead to increased impotence and possible genetic defects in offspring.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> Williams is also critical of the lack of research studies on male reproductive risks.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup>
<p>
The paucity of studies on reproductive health effects for male workers has had direct implications for their legal rights. In many health and safety and human rights adjudicative decisions, the explicit premise is that since reproductive health risks cannot be eliminated entirely, the risk must be balanced against the possibility of occurrence and extent of harm in order to determine &quot;tolerable&quot; levels.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> The legal question often posed is one of relative risk. Yet the known occupational risks to a pregnant woman's fetus will almost always be higher than the risk to the male reproductive system, given the accelerated adverse health effects on rapidly developing cell structures and organ systems.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> Thus, when rights to protection are adjudicated as relative risk, the protection of male workers will always fall short of the protection afforded to pregnant workers. Given that the health risks for men are so poorly documented, adjudicators do not concern themselves with the protection of male employees where the evidence is inconclusive.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
<p>
As a result, there is little jurisprudence in Canada with respect to male reproductive hazards and the legal rights and remedies which may be available. In Ontario, for example, there are no published health and safety decisions on male workers seeking to enforce their right to a workplace free from these risks. If male workers were to seek this enforcement, the lack of medical evidence would work to minimize any rights they may possess. In Quebec, a male worker who can medically document that his health has deteriorated because of exposure to a workplace contaminant can request reassignment to duties he is reasonably capable of performing, until his health improves or the working conditions conform to regulatory standards.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> The problem with this provision is that he must demonstrate that his health has already deteriorated, which means, in the case of
reproductive hazards, that the damage has already been done. There is no preventive protection. Furthermore, in Quebec, as in other provinces, the regulatory standards for exposure levels to particular substances rarely address the issue of reproductive hazards, particularly for male workers.
<p>
The American situation is similar in that there are few medical studies or judicial decisions on male reproductive rights. In the landmark decision <cite>Johnson Controls</cite>, the U.S. Supreme Court granted women equal access to jobs with exposure to lead.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> Yet one of the class action complainants was Donald Penney, a male who had been denied a leave of absence for the purpose of lowering his blood lead levels so that he would be able to have children.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> Although the Court noted the debilitating effects of lead on the male reproductive system and thus found that Johnson's policy of excluding only women of child-bearing age from hazardous positions did not really work to protect the unconceived children of all its employees, it failed to grant a remedy for Penney's complaint.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> It thus failed to craft a remedy which protected all employees who may wish to conceive children.
<p>
The failure to address issues of male health risks is in part a result of the fact that reproductive health issues have been largely litigated as human rights issues. Thus, decisions are made in the context of access to employment for women, not the health and safety of workers. Employer policies which exclude women of child-bearing age from hazardous positions are speculated to exclude women from more than 100,000 jobs in the United States  alone.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> As will be illustrated in Part III, anti-discrimination laws provide an easier avenue for workers seeking to enforce their rights than health and safety laws, which do not expressly provide protection against reproductive hazards. Part II undertakes a comparative examination of Quebec's preventive health and safety regime, and its effectiveness in comparison with the limitations of the Ontario statutory framework. 
<p>
<h3>PART II:   Health and Safety Laws</h3>

One of the difficulties with the current statutory regime is that it is like a &quot;patch-work&quot; quilt of legislative protection, each law addressing a very specific issue such as human rights, health and safety or workers' compensation, patched together with little co-ordination to ensure comprehensive protection of employees. Similarly, employer compliance with the patch-work of laws is designed to meet each separate exigency of each law, without an overall vision or strategy to truly make workplaces accessible and safe. Health and safety legislation is a good example of the problems created by this fragmentation.
<p>
Health and safety laws are designed to prevent industrial disease and accidents, and have rarely focused specifically upon reproductive health hazards. In some jurisdictions, regulations exist to limit exposure to the most toxic substances. However, these exposure levels are designed to weigh relative risk against the work process being done. There are no regulations providing for zero exposure to reproductive health hazards, and there is no Canadian legislation which grants any worker the right to be reassigned during the period that she or he seeks to conceive children.
<p>
In most jurisdictions, health and safety laws impose an obligation upon employers to take reasonable precautions to protect workers.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> Little jurisprudence exists on the success of these legislative provisions, and even less on the issue of reproductive health hazards. In addition to the employer's
responsibility to provide a safe and healthy workplace, there are employee rights to refuse unsafe work. In this article, only the Ontario statutory regime of right to refuse unsafe work is examined, but a review of jurisprudence in other jurisdictions reveals little difference from the Ontario experience. In stark contrast, Quebec has a unique regime for the protection of pregnant and nursing employees which is widely used by employees. This part examines why Quebec has a much more effective statutory regime for preventing reproductive adverse health effects in the workplace.
<p>
QUEBEC: PREVENTIVE REASSIGNMENT OR HEALTH LEAVE FOR PREGNANT AND BREAST-FEEDING WORKERS
<p>
In Quebec, workers who are pregnant have the right under provincial health and safety legislation to reassignment to safe job tasks or to paid preventive leave from their work, if the job that they are performing is hazardous to their health. Section 40 of the <cite>L.S.S.T.</cite> provides that a pregnant worker can furnish her employer with a medical certificate which documents that her working conditions create physical danger for her unborn child, or that
working conditions create a danger to the woman's own health due to her pregnancy.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> The employer must then attempt to accommodate the worker by reassigning her to work tasks which do not pose a danger to her or the fetus, and which she can reasonably accomplish.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> If such accommodation is not possible, she is entitled to a paid preventive leave from the time the medical certificate is presented until the end of the pregnancy. She is to be paid her regular salary for the first five days, and then 90 per cent of her regular net pay for the rest of her pregnancy.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<p>
This right to paid preventive leave for pregnant workers is unique to Quebec. There is no such protection in any other provincial health and safety legislation. As of June 1993, the federal government introduced amendments to Part III of the <cite>Canada Labour Code</cite> providing for maternal reassignment for pregnant workers or nursing mothers. If an employer cannot &quot;reasonably practicably&quot; reassign the worker to alternative work, however, the employee must take a leave without pay.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> Although the employee's job is guaranteed, the reality is that without full economic protection, this is at best a half measure, and women will be unlikely to take advantage of the law if reassignment does not seem possible. This is borne out by the fact that more than a year after the statutory amendment, the federal government has no documented cases of its use, and has stated that it does not expect that the right will be exercised very often.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup>
<p>
Significantly, where laws grant strong protective rights with economic security, pregnant workers have exercised these rights frequently. In the first seven years after the Quebec provisions were enacted, claims for protective reassignment or leave rose from zero to 14,337 claims annually.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> In
1993 the number of women who exercised the right to preventive reassignment or paid leave rose to 20,009, and 18,642 of these claims were upheld by the Quebec Workplace Health and Safety Commission.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> It is also one of the few jurisdictions in Canada where case law has developed in any significant way with respect to reproductive health issues.
<p>
The Quebec law has its limitations. Since it expressly applies to pregnant workers, the Quebec law does not cover or provide protection for those women who are exposed to hazards at the time of conception. Since most workers cannot verify that they are pregnant for at least four weeks (a critical period in fetal development), the law affords
no protection at a very crucial stage of pregnancy. There can also be problems associated with any delay in getting a medical certificate, since each day of exposure to a hazardous substance early in pregnancy may put a woman's health at risk. The protection also does not apply to the period prior to conception, when exposure to hazards can critically affect the possibility of subsequent conception or the healthy progress of the pregnancy. Similarly, the
law does not cover male workers who plan to have a family and who wish to be removed from working conditions which may be hazardous to their capacity to reproduce, or which may harm their sperm.
<p>
Despite these limitations, the Quebec regime has been very effective in providing economic and health protection to pregnant and nursing employees. It is helpful to examine some of the leading cases in order to assess the treatment of pregnant workers under this protective legislation. When there are disputes between the pregnant worker and the employer, there are three levels of administrative decision-making. The first level is the Commission de la sant&eacute; et s&eacute;curit&eacute; du travail du Qu&eacute;bec (C.S.S.T., the Health and Safety Commission), the second is an appeal to the Bureau de r&eacute;vision (B.R.P., the Office of Review). Finally, parties are entitled to a full hearing before the Commission d'appel en mati&egrave;re de l&eacute;sions professionnelles (the Appeals Tribunal) whose decisions are final and binding.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> The decisions of the Appeals Tribunal are useful to examine for purposes of this article.
<p>
The cases to date have clarified limits upon the <cite>L.S.S.T.</cite>'s protection. First, the preventive reassignment and leave protection is available only to workers who come within provincial health and safety laws. Those workers employed in a federal undertaking are not eligible, even if the work they perform appears to be within provincial jurisdiction.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> Second, the provisions do not cover employers, supervisors, forepersons or employees who represent employers in labour relations matters.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> Third, the rights do not exist for workers who are laid off during their pregnancies. The
Appeals Tribunal has held that the right to paid leave is secondary to the right to reassignment of work tasks, and that where the right to work no longer exists, there is no right to paid leave.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>
<p>
Where a worker does utilize the protection of the provisions, however, the case law has developed to maximize the protection and remedies available. The medical certificate from the doctor is taken as <i>prima facie</i> proof that a danger to the pregnant woman and her unborn child exists, at least until such time as a full hearing on the merits of a case is heard.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> This removes a potential barrier for employees seeking to enforce their rights---namely, the inevitable delay surrounding litigation and appeals.
<p>
The weight given to the doctor's certificate helps redress the existing imbalance in power and resources between worker and employer, and helps expedite efforts to resolve the issue of possible reassignment or paid leave. It is the doctor who decides the capacity of the pregnant worker to undertake the work safely, not the employer. As a result, delay is prevented by immediately moving from a determination of whether the hazard exists, to a determination of
how will it be accommodated.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
<p>
The Appeals Tribunal has accorded protection under s. 40 for biological hazards, chemical hazards, and ergonomic hazards. For example, in <cite>H&ocirc;pital Sainte-Justine v. Marie-Dominique Cossette</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> the issue was whether a pregnant nurse who had a medical certificate for preventive reassignment had been sufficiently accommodated by the employer. At issue was whether workplace exposure to cytomegalovirus (CMV) was more hazardous than the hazard posed by exposure to the general population, and thus whether she was entitled to paid preventive leave instead of reassignment. CMV is a known teratogen which is transmitted through saliva, urine, maternal milk, sperm, and genital secretions. The hospital had reassigned the
nurse to the day nursery, but she complained that the reassignment still presented a reproductive danger. Among her duties, the nurse was required to care for infants, including changing diapers. The employer argued that with proper hygiene standards, there was no greater risk to the worker or her unborn child than was presented by
exposure to the general population.
<p>
The Appeals Tribunal decided that the worker was justified in contesting the reassignment to the post of nursery nurse.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> It held that intimate contact was required in order to contract CMV and the risk was slight, but that upon contracting the virus, the health risks to the fetus were very grave, resulting
in either deformity or death.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> The Tribunal found that, although the risk of contracting CMV for hospital workers was the same as for the general population, for the worker whose child dies or is born deformed, the effects are devastating.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> It held that the provisions of the statute are exceptional measures designed to extend more protection to pregnant workers than to the average worker, and to that end, the provisions are to be interpreted in a large and liberal manner. As long as the pregnant worker demonstrates that there is a possible danger to herself or her unborn child, she should be accorded the protection of the law.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup>
<p>
The decision is significant for several reasons. It is a clear statement by the administrative tribunal that has ultimate
responsibility for these complaints that the statute will be given a purposive interpretation in order to protect the health of women. In the <cite>Cossette</cite> case, the result was that, although there was no greater risk in the workplace than in the general population, the existence of any risk was sufficient to invoke the protection of the
statute. The worker was truly granted preventive protection. The threshold set by the Tribunal ensured greater protection than there would have been if this case involved compensation for the effects of such exposure after the fact. For a compensation claim, it is likely that the existence of an equivalent risk of exposure in the general population would have led to failure to establish any causal link between the workplace conditions and the resulting harm.
<p>
Second, the Appeals Tribunal looked at two possible interpretations of &quot;danger&quot; to the worker and the unborn child. The Tribunal found that the law requires that the employee's reassignment must eliminate the danger, not merely reduce it.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> In the case before it, the Tribunal did not find proof that there was no danger of contracting CMV through the nurse's work duties, and given the grave consequence of contracting the virus during pregnancy, she was entitled to full protection.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> The legal standard set by this decision places an onus upon the employer to demonstrate that the work reassignment poses no danger to the worker or fetus. In shifting the onus away from the pregnant worker and creating a &quot;no danger&quot; standard for the employer to meet, the Tribunal granted the broadest possible protection.
<p>
The Tribunal has also recognized chemical hazards, such as the solvents involved in the silkscreen printing process, and found that paid leave is necessary in these cases in order to protect the unborn child.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> In <cite>Dyan Royer v. Sheraton Laval</cite><sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> the Tribunal held that a discotheque worker was entitled to preventive leave because the carbon monoxide fumes from the discotheque posed a health hazard to her unborn child. The Tribunal found that the testing undertaken to
determine carbon monoxide levels was &quot;single site&quot; testing and not an adequate sampling, but it held that this would not be a bar to protection. The documented health effects of carbon monoxide fumes causing lower birthweights and increased risk of abortion or perinatal death, combined with test readings well above the acceptable level for exposure for a worker, warranted granting the benefits.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> This decision appears to give the benefit of the doubt to the worker where the testing is not adequate, but the health risks are high.
<p>
With respect to ergonomic hazards, the Tribunal has found that a pregnant woman performing visual inspection and packaging of electrical sockets was entitled to preventive leave. It found that the requirement for the woman to work in a stationary position and press her stomach against a work table in order to accomplish the work tasks constituted a health hazard.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> The employer's modifications of the work station were found to be inadequate to reduce the risk to the fetus, and any further adaptation was not possible because it would slow down the production line. Further, the Appeals Tribunal considered that the fact that the worker was paid on a piece-work basis posed difficulties with further modifications. Thus, it found that she had
the right to the paid preventive leave.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup>
<p>
The Tribunal's identification of piece-work pay as one factor to be considered in determining whether the workplace can be adequately adapted to reduce the risk of harm is interesting. In a contrasting decision, the Tribunal found that the accommodation made to a sewing-machine operator, in allowing for additional breaks, was sufficient accommodation by the employer in the context of stationary working conditions. It appeared significant to the Tribunal that the operator was to be paid henceforth by the hour instead of by piece, thus ensuring that the rate of production was not a health risk to the pregnancy. She was therefore denied paid preventive leave.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup> It is not clear whether her income level was actually guaranteed by the work accommodation and adjustment to an hourly rate of pay.
<p>
Where the reassignment of work is found to pose no danger to the pregnant woman, and where the Appeals Tribunal finds that she can reasonably accomplish the job tasks, the Tribunal will deny the request for paid leave. For example, in the case of a hospital worker who successfully established that her job of lifting patients and other heavy work was hazardous, the employer assigned her to receptionist-switchboard. Although she argued that this work was too difficult for her and created enormous stress which was detrimental to the pregnancy, the Tribunal found she was not entitled to leave because the work was a reasonable reassignment, and stress was not one of the hazards for which she had originally received the medical certificate.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup>
<p>
The Quebec law also provides protection for nursing mothers. Articles 46 and 47 of the <cite>L.S.S.T</cite> are aimed at preventing the mother's exposure to a substance from creating hazards for the nursing infant. These provisions specify that if a worker furnishes the employer with a medical certificate which attests to the fact that her working conditions are a danger to her nursing child, she is entitled to a reassignment which is not hazardous to the health of her nursing baby, and which she can reasonably perform. If such a reassignment is not immediately possible, she is entitled to a leave until such time as non-hazardous work is available or until she has finished nursing.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> This right is seen as a separate and distinct right under the
statute, and a woman who is breast feeding must apply again for coverage under these sections.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> It appears, however, that if she has already established the health hazards during the
pregnancy, particularly chemical hazards, that the medical proof for the continuation of preventive leave is a formality.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>&Eacute;velyne Desmarais v. Centre d'accueil Anne le Seigneur</cite><sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> the Appeals Tribunal concluded that an educational worker who was working with
severely mentally disabled children was not exposed to a sufficient risk of biological hazards that she was entitled to the protection afforded by ss. 46 and 47 of the <cite>L.S.S.T</cite>. The Tribunal found that she was at fairly high risk of contracting hepatitis B and herpes, and some risk of other infections such as AIDS. It concluded, however, that there was virtually no risk to the nursing infant, particularly if the mother's milk was pumped and administered
to the infant without any physical contact with the mother.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> The Tribunal acknowledged that the working conditions jeopardized the continued ability of the mother to maintain nursing, because there was no safe place for the extraction of breast milk in the workplace. The Tribunal noted that,
although this seems deplorable, it did not fall within ss. 46 and 47 which were designed to prevent the dangers of transmission of illness through nursing, not to prevent working conditions which endangered the ability to breast feed.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup>
<p>
This decision appears to make an artificial distinction which contradicts the purpose of these statutory provisions. It found that the law does not protect workers from working conditions that jeopardize their ability to nurse, leaving the door open for employer arguments that any hazardous working condition merely endangers the ability to nurse, not the health of the child. There is not yet adequate case law on this point to determine whether or not this decision was an anomaly.
<p>
The fact that more than 20,000 Quebec women are now annually exercising their rights to preventive reassignment or leave to avoid reproductive health hazards, stands in stark contrast to the rest of Canada where the statutory right to refuse unsafe work is not being utilized to protect employees against the adverse health effects of workplace reproductive hazards.
<p>
ONTARIO: THE RIGHT TO REFUSE WORK FOR REPRODUCTIVE HAZARDS
<p>
In Ontario, the <cite>Occupational Health and Safety Act</cite> (<cite>O.H.S.A.</cite>) gives workers the right to refuse work they believe is likely to endanger themselves or other workers.<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> This includes any equipment, machine, device or thing they are likely to operate, as well as the physical condition of the workplace. Once a worker exercises her or his right to refuse the unsafe work, a series of procedures are activated which attempt to resolve the complaint, including an investigation by health and safety representatives, and if necessary an inspection and an order from a Ministry of Labour inspector.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> Where an employer or an employee is not satisfied with the result of an inspector's finding, he or she has the right to a hearing before an adjudicator with the Office of  Adjudication.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup>
<p>
Given this statutory framework, it is interesting that there are virtually no recorded cases of work refusals due to reproductive hazards.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> There are a few documented cases of work
refusals, including inspector's orders. At the adjudicative level, however, there is only one decision in the province of Ontario regarding a work refusal and reproductive hazards.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> That case
involved VDT operators at Old City Hall in Toronto, and the adjudicator found that the complaint was justified in so far as the miscarriage rate was three times the normal level. The adjudicator chose not to make any order, however, until further study was carried out by the University of Toronto, and there is no further decision as to the outcome of this additional research.
<p>
In <cite>General Motors and United Autoworkers Local 222</cite>, an arbitrator who held that a policy which did not equally exclude male workers from exposure to lead was not discriminatory, wrote in <i>obiter</i> that in his view, male workers in their reproductive years would have the right to refuse.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> Thus, the arbitrator did not address the concerns raised by male workers. Instead he placed the onus upon those individuals to exercise their individual right to refuse unsafe work. Yet the <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite> right to refuse unsafe work has been legislation for fifteen years, and to date, there are no published cases on the right to refuse because of reproductive hazards (except the VDT case noted above).<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> From what little has been documented, where work refusals take place, they have not been upheld by Ministry of Labour inspectors.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> It is often only where unions have intervened, generating attention in the media and the legislature, that the government has moved to clear up some reproductive health hazards, not through legal enforcement of the right to refuse.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> Similarly, although there is a right to refuse unsafe work under the <cite>Canada Labour Relations Code</cite>, including the right to reassignment pending resolution of a complaint, this right has not
been exercised in the context where an employee believes the work is unsafe for his or her reproductive system.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup>
<p>
This failure to exercise these rights may be explained by looking at the informational and economic problems facing workers in such situations. As noted above, lack of information about reproductive hazards means that workers are not always in a position to decide a work practice or substance is likely to endanger their health. Second, although in Ontario the <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite> provides for the worker to be paid and reassigned pending the initial investigation of the work refusal, where the employer does not have alternative work available, the employee can be sent home without pay after the initial investigation, as long as the action is not a penalty or reprisal for exercising the right to refuse.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> Further, if the work refusal shuts down an entire production line or service, the other employees who have not technically &quot;refused&quot; are not entitled to
compensation for their lost work time under the <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite> Thus, a worker, in deciding to exercise her or his right to refuse for reproductive hazards, risks not only her or his own economic security, but that of co-workers. This risk is a strong incentive not to exercise the right.
<p>
There is, however, a recent decision of the Office of Adjudication which may have an impact upon the ability of pregnant women or other workers to refuse unsafe work. In <cite>Canadian Autoworkers v. American  Healthcare</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> the Office of Adjudication, which now adjudicates on issues arising out of the <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite>, explicitly altered long-standing health and safety policy by deciding that the right to refuse could no longer be judged by the &quot;average worker.&quot;  Previously, complaints were judged on this standard, with adjudicators finding that the <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite> was fashioned &quot;to protect the `average worker' from a dangerous work environment and not the worker with special needs arising out of the physical condition of the worker.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup>
<p>
In contrast, in <cite>American Healthcare</cite>, the adjudicator found that the legislation dealing with the right to refuse requires an objective standard in assessing the worker's belief that a situation is hazardous, and the physical condition of the particular worker in the situation is relevant to an objective assessment.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> The adjudicator used the example of a worker with allergies who refuses to enter a work area  because even minimal exposure would have serious health consequences. Under the new test, the worker would be entitled to refuse, and an adjudicator would be hard pressed not to conclude that the work was hazardous to that particular worker.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
<p>
The implications of the <cite>American Healthcare</cite> decision for reproductive health issues are obvious. Previously, a pregnant worker would not have been considered an &quot;average worker&quot; and her physical condition could not have been taken into account in assessing the work refusal. <cite>American Healthcare</cite> opens up the possibility for assertion of these kinds of rights. The pregnant worker would still have to establish that she refused based upon an objective test of her reasonable belief, but her reasonable belief would be assessed from the perspective of her physical condition. To date, however, there has been no further jurisprudence on this question.
<p>
A more interesting question is whether male or female workers who are trying to conceive children would also be able to take advantage of this shift in the jurisprudence. For example, consider the situation where a male is exposed to lead during work, yet is actively seeking to have children. Would the right to refuse accommodate his refusal as a &quot;hopeful father&quot; based upon his reasonable belief that further exposure would be hazardous to his reproductive ability?  Similarly, would a woman seeking to conceive have the right to refuse, if as a concerned &quot;future mother,&quot; she reasonably believes some substance or work practice to which she is exposed is hazardous to her reproductive capacity?  Both would face difficulties in asserting their claim.
<p>
Part of the difficulty for any worker seeking to enforce her or his rights is that health and safety laws have not to date been interpreted in the large and liberal fashion, the way most remedial statutes are supposed to be interpreted.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> Rather, health and safety legislation has been interpreted
as balancing worker health and safety against employer economic interest, and the approach gives equal weight to both.<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> The effect of this interpretive approach has generally been not to uphold a worker's health and safety concern unless there is an explicit standard or regulation enacted which applies to her or his situation.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> Given that it will be many more years before standards are established for most toxic substances, few workers will be able to effectively utilize existing health and safety laws to protect their reproductive health. 
<p>
The same might be said with respect to current laws which provide workers with the &quot;right to know&quot; about toxic substances in the workplace. Great strides have been made in the past decade in legislating rights to information and training in the identification and handling of hazardous workplace substances.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> This ostensibly includes reproductive hazards. Given, however, that there has been so little research on the reproductive health effects of workplace substances, and given that there is no requirement for pre-market testing of possible reproductive health effects of such substances, this right to know is necessarily limited to disclosure of the information the manufacturer possesses. Thus the right to know, while potentially very effective, is of limited value until manufacturers are required to undertake more testing and research.
<p>
 A background study for the Royal Commission on New Reproductive Technologies also confirms the failure of government to use existing enforcement mechanisms effectively. For example, it points out that under the Ontario health and safety legislation, manufacturers and suppliers of new biological or chemical agents must give notice to
the Ministry of Labour prior to their introduction into the workplace. The Director of Health and Safety has the power to order an assessment of the health effects if she or he suspects they are hazardous. Since this provision was enacted, however, there have been 819 notifications of new agents, but no manufacturer or supplier has been ordered to conduct an assessment of potential reproductive hazards.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> Similarly, Fudge and Tucker point out that existing powers to prohibit use of a toxic substance in a specific work location have never been exercised for protection of reproductive health.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup>
<p>
WHY THE QUEBEC PROTECTIONS RESULT IN A MORE COMPREHENSIVE USE OF HEALTH AND SAFETY LAWS
<p>
The Quebec law is, without a doubt, being utilized in a much more comprehensive fashion than the right to refuse unsafe work in other jurisdictions, or the right to reassignment under federal laws. It would appear that there are three reasons for this. First, adjudicators have made it very clear that the rights granted under the statute will be interpreted in such a way as to promote the public policy goals of fully protecting women's reproductive health
rights.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup>
<p>
Second, the Quebec Appeals Tribunal has held that where there are two competing notions of danger to the pregnant worker, and where no proof is submitted that there is no danger, the Tribunal will uphold a woman's right under the law even if the risk in the workplace is no greater than in the population at large.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> By placing the legal onus upon the employer to show that there is no danger, the law has facilitated the use of the right to reassignment and preventive leave. Since employees rarely have the resources or
information to fully document or challenge reproductive health hazards, this interpretive approach has shifted the burden away from those with the least information, thus enhancing their protection under the legislation. In contrast, in other provinces, once a work refusal is investigated by an inspector, the onus shifts to the worker to prove the reasonableness of the refusal, and often she or he does not have adequate information or resources to discharge this onus.
<p>
The third reason is likely an economic one. The Quebec law, by guaranteeing either reassignment or paid leave, ensures that lost income does not become a determining factor in whether a woman will exercise reproductive health rights. This grants much more protection than the federal law which protects wages and benefits only where the employer finds that reassignment is possible.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> In other jurisdictions, although workers could be compensated for time pending disposition of a work refusal on a reproductive health complaint, this benefit is not entrenched in the law. Thus, seeking compensation pending the decision often becomes as onerous as eliminating the hazard. Given the huge disparity in the use of health and safety laws for
reproductive protection (no cases in Ontario versus more than 20,000 each year in Quebec), it would appear that express statutory protection, guaranteed income protection, and employer onus are all critical factors in determining whether laws can be used to provide reproductive health protection.
<P>
<h3>PART III: Human Rights Perspective</h3>

EQUAL ACCESS AND THE TENSION WITH EMPLOYER  RESPONSIBILITY FOR REPRODUCTIVE HAZARDS
<p>
The continued existence of reproductive risks raises the question of whether employer policies which restrict pregnant women or women of child-bearing age from particular jobs are discriminatory within the meaning of Canadian human rights law.
<p>
There currently exists an elaborate human rights regime, articulated in both federal and provincial human rights laws, which prohibits discrimination on the basis of sex. Section 15(1) of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> also guarantees that every individual is equal before and under the law and includes the right
to equal protection and benefit of the law without discrimination.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> These laws protect women's equal access to the workforce. Yet this human rights regime exists concurrently with the scheme of health and safety laws designed to foster safe and healthy workplaces by placing obligations upon employers to take all reasonable precautions to protect their employees. Employer policies seeking to conform to the latter create a tension with laws protecting equal access to employment. Thus, from the perspective of human rights legislation, the question is whether policies seeking to exclude particular classes of workers because of reproductive health hazards represent sex discrimination.
<p>
<cite>WEINS v. INCO METALS CO.</cite>
<p>
The first major case in Canada was the decision by the Ontario Human Rights Boards of Inquiry in <cite>Weins</cite>.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> Inco operated a nickel refinery in which it recovered
pure nickel using a pressure carbonyl process. Although the plant was considered to have extremely safe equipment and work practices, there was some danger of exposure from occasional leakages. Nickel carbonyl gases, if ingested through inhalation, pass through the bloodstream and most membrane tissues, and can cause chemical poisoning from both the nickel and the carbon monoxide released into the bloodstream. It can negatively affect cells in both their functioning and their duplication.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup> Given the rapid cell development of the fetus, this exposure could have serious health consequences for a pregnant worker.
<p>
Inco instituted a policy that women of child-bearing age would not be permitted to work in virtually any of the jobs in the plant.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> Its rationale was based on the potential health hazard to unborn children from both the nickel carbonyl and the antidote medication given upon exposure. The complainant, Ms. Weins, argued that the policy was discriminatory.
<p>
The Board of Inquiry considered the complaint, which spanned over the period of both the old <cite>Ontario Human Rights Code</cite><sup><a href="one01">101</a></sup> and the amended <cite>Code</cite> which came into force in June, 1982.<sup><a href="one02">102</a></sup> Section 4(1) of the pre-1982 <cite>Code</cite> provided that no person could refuse to train, promote, transfer, or exclude from employment any person because of their sex. The 1982 amendments included the provision that every person has the right to equal treatment with respect to employment without discrimination because of sex.<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> It also prohibited a person from either directly or indirectly infringing upon these
rights.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> Section 10 of the <cite>Code</cite> provided:
<blockquote>
10. A right of a person under Part I is infringed where a requirement, qualification or consideration is imposed that is not discrimination on a prohibited ground but that would result in the exclusion, qualification or preference of a group of persons who are identified by a prohibited ground of discrimination and of whom the person is a member, except where,
<blockquote>
(a) the requirement, qualification or consideration is a reasonable and bona fide one in the circumstances; or
<p>
(b) it is declared in this Act that to discriminate because of such a ground is not an infringement of a right.
</blockquote></blockquote>
The Board of Inquiry in <cite>Weins</cite> decided that the exclusion of women of child-bearing potential constituted discrimination on the basis of sex. The decision was a landmark not only in that it was the first such Canadian case involving equal treatment in regard to access to potentially hazardous jobs, but it also departed from the existing Supreme Court of Canada jurisprudence in <cite>Bliss v. Attorney General of Canada</cite>.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> In <cite>Bliss</cite>, the Court had held that different treatment of pregnant women was not sex discrimination under federal human rights law, since pregnant women are treated differently because they are pregnant, not because they are women.<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> In contrast, the Board in <cite>Weins</cite> found that discrimination can still exist even if not all members of the class are affected, in other words, even if not all women get pregnant.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup>
<p>
Subsequent to the <cite>Weins</cite> decision, the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Brooks v. Canada Safeway Ltd.</cite> found that <cite>Bliss</cite> was wrongly decided, holding that discrimination on the basis of pregnancy is a form of sex discrimination.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup>
<p>
There are a number of difficulties with the approach taken in the <cite>Weins</cite> decision, however. First, the Board in <cite>Weins</cite> found that discrimination would be permitted in cases where the employer can demonstrate a &quot;reasonable and bona fide qualification&quot; (&quot;RBFQ&quot;). It suggested that this should be dealt with on a case by case basis under the <cite>Human Rights Code</cite>.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> On the specific facts, it was held that the exclusion of women of &quot;child-bearing potential&quot; as well as the exclusion of pregnant women at the nickel carbonyl plant constituted <i>prima facie</i> sex discrimination under both the old and the new <cite>Code</cite>.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> The Board's approach shifts the focus of the employer's attention, however, to
establishing a &quot;reasonable and bona fide qualification&quot; defence to exclusionary policies instead of eliminating reproductive health risks for all its employees. The underlying premise is that reproductive hazards will continue to exist without serious challenge, and the only question is which employees must face these hazards at a given time.
<p>
Thus employers have a statutory defence to discriminatory practices available to them under human rights statutes. Once discrimination is established, under s. 10(a) of the <cite>Code</cite>, the onus shifts to the employer to establish that the discriminatory employment practice excluding all women of child-bearing potential is a RBFQ. The Supreme Court has held that there is both a subjective and an objective test in assessing reasonable and bona fide qualification.<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> The subjective test is that the policy:
<blockquote>
must be imposed honestly, in good faith, and in the sincerely held belief that such limitation is imposed in the interests of the adequate performance of the work involved with all reasonable dispatch, safety and economy, and not for ulterior or extraneous reasons aimed at objectives which could defeat the purpose of the Code.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Supreme Court also found that there is an objective test for evaluating the performance, in that:
<blockquote>
it is reasonably necessary to assure the efficient and economical performance of the job without endangering the employee, his fellow employees and the general public.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Board in <cite>Weins</cite> followed the reasoning in <cite>Rand</cite> and the Supreme Court in <cite>Etobicoke</cite> in finding that the employer had the onus to demonstrate the policy met both
tests.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> In addition, the Board found that an employer has a duty to accommodate employees, with the onus upon the employer to establish undue hardship before a successful defence against accommodation can be made out.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> The Board found that Inco's policy was enacted in good faith, but that its policy of differential treatment did not relate in an objective sense to the performance of the work.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> It was not reasonably necessary to protect the fetus, nor was it necessary to the efficient performance of the job.<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup>
<p>
The second problem with the decision is that the Board failed to dismiss the idea that a RBFQ could include exclusions from certain jobs based upon the fact of pregnancy alone.<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> The Board held that the risk of endangering a fetus due to an employer's activity is a matter of concern for the employer as well as the worker. By framing the issue as one dealing with the competing interests of worker's freedom of choice, society's interest in the well-being of children, and the employer's interest in avoiding possible civil liability to a deformed child,<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> the Board opened the door for ongoing arguments
and employer defences to exclusionary policies. A more effective approach would have been to place a positive onus on employers to demonstrate that men and their children are not adversely affected by the substances women are excluded from being exposed to. This approach has previously been endorsed in the United States.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> Instead, the Board in <cite>Weins</cite> found only that there must exist a real and
significant risk for a restrictive policy to be &quot;reasonable.&quot;<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> On
the facts, the Board found that the policy was not reasonable because of the safety measures in place, the infrequency of gas leaks, and the availability of good birth control.
<p>
The result of <cite>Weins</cite> is that the employer has the duty to accommodate women of child-bearing age unless to do so would constitute undue hardship. The Board dismissed the employer's argument that it could suffer financially from accepting the risk of employing women of child-bearing age.<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> Interestingly, the Board stressed the fact that the employer's liability under other statutes was extremely limited. Although the Board appears to be trying to reassure the employer, it speaks legends about the failure of the existing statutory regime to truly protect workers. For example, the Board suggested that since the
employer had conformed to existing health and safety regulations, there was little risk of prosecution under the <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite>.<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup> Similarly, it held that the employer would
not risk higher workers' compensation claims because adverse health effects are spread over the industrial class and there are no direct cost consequences.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> Finally, the Board acknowledged that the employer did face some risk of being sued in tort, since the <cite>Ontario Family Law Act</cite><sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> gives a child a right to sue for pre-natal injury. It found, however, that the possibility of success was highly unlikely, and therefore, it did not justify a policy of exclusion for fear of a
lawsuit.<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> Thus <cite>Weins</cite>, while finding that an exclusionary policy was discriminatory, also legitimized considerations such as protection of the fetus and legal liability of employers as defences to exclusionary policies, where such considerations do not affect the ability of the employee
to perform the work. As well, there was no discussion of the elimination or reduction of exposure as part of any accommodation required by the employer.
<p>
OTHER RELEVANT CANADIAN DECISIONS
<p>
<cite>Weins</cite> continues to be a significant decision because there are almost no other cases in Canada which deal with these human rights issues. In <cite>General Motors</cite>, an arbitrator rejected the union's assertion that failure to protect male workers from the negative effects of lead exposure violated the anti-discrimination clause in the collective agreement.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> General Motors' policy of excluding all women, but not men, of child-bearing age was upheld as reasonable given the medical evidence related to fetal exposure to lead.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup> The arbitrator went beyond permitting the exclusion of only pregnant women to uphold the exclusion of all women of child-bearing age. The decision, which predates <cite>Weins</cite>, is inconsistent because the medical evidence relating to lead exposure makes no distinction
between men and women of child-bearing age.
<p>
The Canadian Human Rights Tribunal has departed from the <cite>General Motors</cite> case, and concluded from medical evidence that male and female workers are affected to the same extent in their reproductive capacity from exposure to lead. It held, however, that the fetus was at greater risk of being harmed at much lower levels of
exposure through the bloodstream, and that a baby is at greater risk from lead in the breast milk after birth.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> The practical result of these decisions is that an employee may or may not have access to human rights remedies, depending on the jurisdiction under which the complaint arises, and the particular adjudicator who hears the complaint. Such a hit-and-miss approach creates further uncertainty about the
availability of protection.
<p>
In <cite>Cassan et al. v. Hudson Bay Mining and Smelting Co. Ltd.</cite>,<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> the Tribunal found that a policy of excluding women capable of bearing children from smelter positions and thus from lead contaminants was <i>prima facie</i> sex discrimination.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> Although the policy was directed towards the risks associated with fetal exposure, it was
nevertheless a policy directed towards the employment of women. As a consequence, the Tribunal held that the employer's policy of granting women equal treatment in the workforce only on the condition of, and at the price of, denying their role as mothers constituted sex discrimination.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup> It adopted an approach  similar to <cite>Weins</cite> that such cases must first involve an inquiry into whether the practice is discriminatory, and then an assessment of whether the practice can be justified as &quot;reasonable and bona
fide.&quot;<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup>
<p>
One of the few other cases on point is <cite>Heincke v. Emrick Plastics</cite>. It is a recent Ontario human rights decision which involved a pregnant worker exposed to solvents from spray paints. She was denied a work reassignment to a less hazardous job during her pregnancy.<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> The Board
of Inquiry held that although there was some controversy as to the precise toxicity of the solvents, the employer had violated the <cite>Human Rights Code</cite> by discriminating against her because she was pregnant. Forcing Ms. Heincke to take a leave for the duration of her pregnancy instead of reassigning her to a less hazardous job was a
failure to fulfil the employer's duty to accommodate her pregnancy. As a remedy, the Board ordered payment of all the lost wages of the worker. Significantly, it also ordered general damages of $3,000 because she was forced to return to work only six weeks after birth as a result of requiring her to take the early leave. The award recognized she had suffered from the inability to spend her maternity leave with her daughter, and that she had to forego nursing. Finally, the Board held that a collective agreement provision which requires all pregnant workers to commence their maternity leave at six months, regardless of their ability to continue to do their work, was sex discrimination and contrary to the <cite>Code</cite>.
<p>
The significance of this decision is the explicit recognition that employers have a duty to reasonably accommodate pregnant workers under the <cite>Code</cite>. Employers will be liable for a breach of this duty, and may be required to pay general damages. The difficulty is that the right to protection for this employee was upheld long after the pregnancy and birth of the child, and thus is not an expeditious or preventive remedy. It remains to be seen whether this decision will be used by human rights officers in an effort to expedite resolution or enforcement of future cases.
<p>
COMPARISON WITH <cite>JOHNSON CONTROLS</cite>
<p>
It is instructive to compare the results of litigation on exclusionary employer policies in Canada with those in the United States. The leading case in the United States is <cite>Johnson Controls</cite>,<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup> a class action which challenged an employer policy excluding all women of child-bearing age, except those who could medically prove infertility, from jobs which involved exposure to lead. The U.S. Supreme Court held that the policy was overt sex discrimination because it required only women to provide medical proof of sterility, despite the medical evidence that lead exposure negatively affects male as well as female
reproductive systems. The policy of excluding women of child-bearing capacity was found to be sex discrimination under <cite>Title VII</cite> of the <cite>Civil Rights Act</cite>, as amended by the <cite>Pregnancy Discrimination Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> unless that capacity prevents a woman from performing those duties of her job which fall within the &quot;essence&quot; of the particular business.<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup>
<p>
The Court held that if a policy is found to be facially discriminatory, the business necessity test is not applicable.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> Further, it does not matter why the employer implemented the policy, because the absence of malevolent motive does not correct a discriminatory policy.<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> The statutory defence of &quot;bona fide occupational qualification&quot; must show that the reason for the discrimination is that it affects the employee's ability to do the job, and is reasonably necessary to the normal operation of the business.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> The safety exception to this defence to a sex discrimination claim was found to be limited to cases where the pregnancy or sex of the worker actually interferes with the employee's ability to perform the job. Here, fertile women were able to do the job as well as anyone else.<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> Finally, the Court held that it is not for the courts or the employer to decide whether a woman's economic role is more important than her child-bearing role; decisions about the health of future generations is a matter for the parents who conceive, bear, support, and raise children.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup>
<p>
The U.S. Supreme Court has been very explicit that the &quot;bona fide occupational qualification&quot; is a very narrow defence. The requirement is that the policy must be reasonably necessary to the normal operation of the particular business, imposing an objective standard which must relate to job specific skills and aptitudes.<sup>,a href="#one43">143</a></sup> Third party considerations only apply where it goes to the core of performance of
the job and the essential purpose of the enterprise.<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup>
<p>
<cite>Johnson Controls</cite> serves as a useful comparison in the development of jurisprudence related to reproductive health rights. Although the content of the laws differs, both Canadian and American adjudicators have developed similar jurisprudence and remedies. Both have recognized that policies excluding women of child-bearing age are prima facie discriminatory, and both acknowledge that the only real defence to such policies is the bona fide occupational qualification argument. The American case law is stronger in two respects, however. First, American courts have placed greater emphasis on the narrowness of this defence. Second, the U.S. Supreme Court has made a clear statement of policy that decisions about child-bearing are matters for parents, not employers. This is a stark contrast to <cite>Weins</cite>, which legitimizes the employer's role in such decision-making.
<p>
Both Canadian and American jurisdictions have adopted a purposive approach to the meaning of sex discrimination, including pregnancy within its ambit, but interestingly, have ordered almost no remedies to reduce or remove reproductive hazards for all workers. The recognition of a woman's choice to have access to the economic
benefits of industrial jobs or to have children is an important confirmation of equality rights. It is disturbing, however, that women are seen to be able to choose one or the other, but not both. In fact, for most women and men, the options are not one or the other; they need and desire to secure a decent income and job security while being able to raise a family. This involves ensuring the safety of children from conception through child-rearing. Given
that reproductive health cases are largely litigated as human rights cases, these issues have not yet been adequately dealt with by courts in either Canada or the United States. Decision-makers have limited themselves to a narrow notion of equality, which is reflected in remedies that do not require making the workplace safe.
<p>
Neither regime has used what Beatty would characterize as the &quot;least drastic means&quot; approach to deciding whether policies excluding women from particular jobs are discriminatory.<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> In other words, where an employer has implemented an exclusionary policy, ostensibly for <i>bone fide</i> occupational reasons, the question should be whether there is a means to accomplish
the employer's objectives, of ensuring a healthy and productive workforce which is less detrimental to the equality rights of those persons excluded. Thus in cases like <cite>Weins</cite> or <cite>Johnson Controls</cite>, the test would be whether the employer had made all reasonable efforts to implement alternate engineering and control
strategies before implementing exclusionary strategies. 
<p>
There is some support for this approach in existing Supreme Court of Canada jurisprudence in human rights. In <cite>Brossard (Ville) v. Qu&eacute;bec (Commission des droits de la personne)</cite>,<sup><a href="one46">146</a></sup> the Supreme Court found that an anti-nepotism policy of a municipality was made in good faith and was rationally connected to the objective of avoiding conflicts of interest in employment of public servants, but that it was disproportionately stringent.<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup> The appellant, Laurin, was the daughter of a woman who worked as a secretary in the police station. She applied for a summer job as a life guard and was ineligible to be considered because of her familial relationship (called her civil status) to a full-time employee of the town.<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> The Supreme Court held that the exclusionary policy was too drastic in that it excluded situations such as this where there could be no abuse of power or conflict of interest. It thus found that the policy was discriminatory and could not be supported by the defences under the Quebec <cite>Charter</cite>.<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup> This approach, which interprets BFOQ requirements strictly, and requires employers to implement less drastic employment policies, has obvious application to reproductive health issues. Exclusionary policies for reproductive hazards would become a strategy of last resort, only after employers had explored less drastic means of controlling exposure. Engineering safety controls, or substitution of less harmful substances for harmful ones, would support both the goals of
reducing exposure to hazards and equal access to employment, as well as meeting the employer's objective of a safe and efficient workforce.
<p>
Dayton has argued that by framing the fetal protection issue as one of conflicting rights between mother and fetus, we are inviting resolution of the conflict by denying employment opportunities in favour of fetal  protection.<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup> Sally Kenney points out that the mere term &quot;fetal
protection policies&quot; is highly paternalistic on the part of employers and renders women invisible, &quot;mere vessels that may contain a fetus.&quot;<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup> As Grover has pointed out, however, in striking down Johnson Controls' fetal protection policy, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the worker's interest in employment takes precedence over the company's defence of the well-being of future generations.<sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup> It is not yet known whether the woman's interest is absolute, or whether in particular circumstances, other interests will override it.<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup> These and other feminists argue persuasively that the issue should not be framed as one of equality versus the
right to have healthy children, and that by posing the issues as a dichotomy, we fail to develop more comprehensive strategies to address workplace reproductive hazards.<sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup>
<p>
Swinton discusses the &quot;perils of protection,&quot; in that stereotyping of women has led to policies which are protective of their child-bearing capacity to the exclusion of their role as workers. She argues that women have the right to be regarded as more than child-bearers, and at the same time, there must be policies which protect women from financial hardship because they are barred or have refused to work in risky jobs.<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup> The Board in <cite>Weins</cite> acknowledged that competing with the freedom of choice of the worker is society's interest in the well-being of the child.<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup> Again, by juxtaposing the interests of mother and fetus as separate, the door is open to decisions which will override the woman's rights as both worker and decision-maker with respect to her unborn child. As Becker points out, the fact that employers have often been concerned with fetal protection policies in traditionally male-dominated workplaces, and not in women's work, suggests a discriminatory bias.<sup><a href="#one57">157</a></sup> In fact, traditional women's work poses many of the same kinds of reproductive hazards as I noted in Part I, but employers have not implemented discriminatory policies in those occupations.
<p>
TORT LIABILITY AND THE IMPLICATIONS FOR EQUALITY
<p>
These issues of equal access and protection from reproductive health hazards are complicated by the spectre of tort
liability in both Canada and the United States. There is not sufficient space to deal adequately with these issues in this article. It is important to note, however, that a claim of wrongdoing under the tort law regime is a private action, and there are significant barriers to bringing an action in tort. It is thus questionable whether or not such actions would act as an effective remedy to reproductive health effects or as an effective deterrent to future unhealthy workplace practices. Barriers include the difficulty in establishing causation, the enormous delays in the
legal system in actually hearing and deciding or resolving such claims, the high cost of bringing such actions in terms of both preparation for and conduct of the litigation, as well as the high costs that could be awarded against a plaintiff.<sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup>
<p>
In the future, the issue of tort liability may, however, have some bearing on how cases of alleged discrimination are adjudicated in both Canada and the United States. In <cite>Weins</cite>, the Board found that employers may have an interest in avoiding liability costs from a tort action brought by a child suffering deformity or ill health
effects as a result of her mother having been exposed to workplace toxic substances and that this interest was a competing interest with women's interests in equality and freedom of choice.<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup> Although the Board did not decide the case based on this argument, by raising this as a competing interest, it left open the possibility of potential tort liability as a defence to discriminatory policies. 
<p>
In contrast, in <cite>Johnson Controls</cite>, the majority judgement of Blackmun J., joined in by four other Judges, saw no conflict between <cite>Title VII</cite> protection against discrimination and possible tort
liability because <cite>Title VII</cite> bans sex-specific exclusionary policies. The majority held that if an employer fully complies with the law, fully informs women employees of the risk, and has not acted negligently, under general tort principles any possible liability would be &quot;remote at best.&quot;  It did not find the tort liability argument persuasive, holding that the extra cost of hiring one sex was not a defence to discrimination. Employers cannot use sex discrimination to avoid the obligation to minimize reproductive hazards.<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Johnson Controls</cite>, however, the Court noted that the employer had not argued that it faced any actual costs from tort liability. The majority decision declined therefore, to decide the question of whether <cite>Title VII</cite> would pre-empt state tort laws, as it was not a question before the Court. The majority did note that since the extra cost of hiring women was not a defence to discriminatory hiring based on gender under <cite>Title VII</cite>, the fear of additional costs because of awards for tort damages was also not a defence.<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup> The concurring judgement by Justice White, with whom both the Chief Justice and Justice Kennedy joined, held, however, that a fetal protection policy would be justified if the employer could demonstrate that the exclusion of women from particular jobs was &quot;reasonably necessary to avoid substantial tort liability.&quot;  The concurring judgement strongly disagreed with the majority's decision to set a high threshold, requiring the costs to be so prohibitive as to threaten the survival of the business, and left open the possibility that an employer could establish a BFOQ cost-based defence.<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup> These judgements thus leave open the very real possibility that the Court would consider a cost-based BFOQ as a legitimate reason for utilizing discriminatory hiring policies. 
<p>
For both Canadian and American tribunals and courts, the question is: on what basis would such a defence be judged?  How would costs be calculated, and at what threshold would economic interests of the employer override fundamental issues of human rights? Although workers in most Canadian and American jurisdictions do not have the right to sue in tort because of the statutory bar to civil actions in workers' compensation regimes,<sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup> a child born alive can sue in tort for pre-natal injury. Thus one issue for further debate is whether there are ever circumstances where the cost to employers from tort liability would outweigh the interests of the female workers.<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup> To date, the reality is that there has been virtually no success in bringing a successful tort action for pre-natal occupational injury, in part because of the difficulties in establishing causation.<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup> In Canada, there has never been a successful civil
action for reproductive harm caused by exposure to workplace hazards.<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup> Thus, it is important that tort liability issues not be used to justify broad exclusionary policies. Grover suggests that employers may seek to enter into contracts of indemnity with workers.<sup><a href="#one67">167</a></sup> In Canada, at least, mothers cannot forfeit the tort rights of their child for pre-natal injury. More importantly, such an approach fails to address the primary concern, namely, how to eliminate or minimize the exposure to reproductive
hazards for all employees. There is much debate about how a tort regime fits into the overall context of reproductive hazards. Issues identified in the background study for the Royal Commission on Reproductive Technologies include an analysis of the following: the precise nature of the duty of care owed by employers to employees; whether a more effective approach would be an action for trespass to the person and battery or an action for negligence; questions of how a litigant would establish proximate cause or remoteness of damage; and the defences of contributory negligence and voluntary assumption of risk.<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup>
Similarly, in Quebec, which has a civil law regime codifying wrongdoing for intentional and negligent harms, there are complex issues of how issues of foreseeability, reasonable care and prudence, as well as the causal connection between fault and damage are to be determined and measured.<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup>
Discussion of possible tort remedies, however, is a very complex topic, and far beyond the scope of this article. 
<p>
<h3>PART IV:   Workers' Compensation</h3>

EXISTING CASE LAW ON REPRODUCTIVE HEALTH EFFECTS
<p>
In Ontario, the only workers' compensation decisions which exist on the issue of reproductive health effects are those where another compensable injury, such as a back injury, has given a pregnant woman compensation, and the employer is seeking to reduce or negate the compensable injury because, as a pregnant woman, she is unavailable for work.<sup><a href  = "#one70">170</a></sup> There are no adjudicative decisions in Ontario workers'
compensation law with respect to compensation to women for the effects of reproductive hazards, such as miscarriages, or other health effects due to exposure to toxic substances.<sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup> Similarly, although there are a number of decisions on male impotence, these are almost exclusively decisions arising out of on-the-job back injuries and resultant nerve damage, as opposed to any other reproductive health effect. Interestingly, these are all treated as sexual dysfunction cases, as opposed to injury to reproductive capacity.
<p>
With respect to pregnant workers, there have only been five adjudicative decisions in Ontario since the inception of the current workers' compensation regime which touch in any way upon workers' compensation and pregnancy. Almost all are decisions about whether the pregnancy reduces benefits for other compensable injuries.<sup><a href="#one72">172</a></sup> In one case, for example, a punch-press operator who had suffered a compensable back injury became pregnant and the original pain was aggravated by the recovery from childbirth. The Workers' Compensation Appeals Tribunal found that the worker was disabled due to the delivery and thus her back injury was not compensable for the post-birth recovery period.<sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup> More recently, the Tribunal held that pregnancy does not automatically disqualify a worker from receiving a disability supplement, if the worker is available for work and co-operating in a medical or vocational rehabilitation program. On the particular facts of the case, however, compensation was denied.<sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup> The difficulty is that it is unclear how the worker could meet the Tribunal's &quot;available and co-operating&quot; tests, given her ill health.
<p>
The Workers' Compensation Board has published guidelines for the temporary compensation of pregnant women where there is traumatic injury to the abdominal region, or where women miscarry due to hazardous work.<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup> As there are no tribunal decisions or published statistics, however, it is impossible to assess how frequently or easily women make use of this policy. Temporary compensation for this kind of injury is compensation for wage loss until recovery and does not address emotional suffering or other loss.
<p>
According to the Workers' Compensation Appeals Tribunal, the reason that there are virtually no cases relating to reproductive health effects is because of the difficulty in establishing causation.<sup><a href="#one76">176</a></sup> With so little documented information about workplace reproductive health effects, causation is difficult to establish in a legal or quasi-judicial forum. The increasing exposure to environmental
pollutants both on and off the job, as well as increased exposure to smoke, alcohol and drugs, all complicate the issue of causation.<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup> Furthermore, little is known about the reproductive health effects carried home by one partner in a relationship and transferred to the other through contact with contaminated clothing or skin, or by seminal fluids.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> Yet the Ontario
workers' compensation regime is premised entirely upon a causation model.
<p>
In Ontario, the Industrial Diseases Standards Panel is now studying reproductive health effects for the first time. It will likely be some time before the Panel reports, but it may start to document in a comprehensive way some of the devastating negative health effects of particular substances. The problem is that its statutory mandate is to make recommendations on compensatory illness to the Workers' Compensation Board; it does not have the mandate to propose preventive legislative measures based upon its findings.<sup><a href="#one79">179</a></sup> 
<p>
&quot;LOST EARNING CAPACITY&quot; LAWS AS A BAR FOR COMPENSATION FOR REPRODUCTIVE HEALTH EFFECTS
<p>
With respect to the reproductive health cases relating to men, there have been nine cases relating to male impotence, and no other cases relating to reproductive health effects. Permanent partial disability pensions under the Ontario <cite>Workers' Compensation Act (W.C.A.)</cite>, however, are based upon impairment of earning capacity. In one case, the Workers' Compensation Appeals Tribunal found the impotence resulting from surgery to correct a
compensable back injury had not impaired the worker's earning capacity, and that the injury was not compensable.<sup><a href="#one80">180</a></sup> The Tribunal rejected an approach earlier adopted by the British Columbia Tribunal,<sup><a href="#one81">181</a></sup> and held that the &quot;link between impotence and an indirect impact on earning capacity is too tenuous and speculative&quot; to establish a basis for
compensation.<sup><a href="#one82">182</a></sup> The decision was overturned two years later, however, on a reconsideration application. On reconsideration, the Tribunal determined that there was evidence of a link between male impotence and impairment of work performance, and that the pension must represent the impaired earning capacity of the average worker instead of the individual, given that psychological problems resulting from
impotence likely affect ten per cent of earning capacity.<sup><a href="#one83">183</a></sup> Subsequent to this decision, lost earning capacity is to be examined only in cases where the individual alleges severe psychological impairment affecting greater than ten per cent of earning capacity. Female sterility cannot be compensated unless the employee can establish a causal connection between the sterility and lost earning capacity.<sup><a href="#one84">184</a></sup>
<p>
The Tribunal has thus acknowledged that impotence or sterility could result in a disabling psychological condition which can impair earning capacity.<sup><a href="#one85">185</a></sup> Compensable benefits defined under s. 45(12) of the <cite>W.C.A.</cite> define permanent disability as &quot;any physical or functional abnormality or loss, or any psychological damage arising therein after maximum rehabilitation has been achieved.&quot; The section as worded could be more liberally interpreted to include the psychological effects of impotence: on confidence, work performance, exercise of judgement, etc., which have a long-term impact upon earning capacity. It does seem unfair that the reproductive health effects of harmful working conditions are not compensable, except at a very high threshold of psychological damage.
<p>
In contrast, the jurisprudence in British Columbia held that a worker does not need to demonstrate an actual loss of earnings as a requirement for eligibility for compensation. The Tribunal has recognized the non-economic consequences of impotence and awarded compensation based upon a sliding scale of compensable benefits, from
15 per cent pensions to workers under age 45 to five per cent for those over age 65.<sup><a href="#one86">186</a></sup> Although this in part is accounted for by different statutory language, the B.C. Tribunal has also held that there may well be an indirect effect on earning capacity from feelings of inadequacy, depression, and lack of self-confidence, which should be considered.<sup><a href="#one87">187</a></sup> Similarly, in granting female workers 15 per cent of total disability awards for female sexual dysfunction following a workplace injury, the W.C.B. did not require a demonstrated loss of earnings.<sup><a href="#one88">188</a></sup>
<p>
Given that few reproductive adverse health effects can be shown to cause lost earning capacity, the formulation of workers' compensation legislation in Ontario largely acts as a bar to compensation for those effects. Unless a worker can demonstrate first that there exists a negative health effect, and second, that the effect actually impaired her or his earning capacity, then under existing laws, a permanent disability pension beyond very minimal compensation is rarely, if ever, available. Further, the workers' compensation regime is a comprehensive regime, which means that workers do not have the right to bring a civil action. Thus, it is a catch-22: reproductive
ill-health effects which can have an extraordinary impact on workers' personal lives, cannot be compensated without establishing lost earning capacity. Yet where there is no lost earning capacity, the regime is crafted such that there appears to be no legal recourse for compensation in civil law.
<p> 
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

LOOKING FORWARD: THE ROYAL COMMISSION REPORT
<p>
The federal Royal Commission on New Reproductive Technologies has issued its final report, <cite>Proceed With Care</cite>. It is most unfortunate that the Commission chose to ignore many of the pressing issues identified in this article. Only 8 of the 293 Commission recommendations address occupational reproductive health hazards in any way, and many of the recommendations suggested by its background study were not adopted.<sup><a href="#one89">189</a></sup> In part, this is due to lack of information on the precise scope and extent of workplace reproductive hazards, but it may also be due to the fact that the effects of health hazards are more visible than the causes. Thus, governments may perceive that it is easier to deal with these tangible effects rather than to identify the causes and eliminate the hazards at the source. Far more resources have gone into new technologies which try
to correct the results of workplace and environmental exposure, (i.e. infertility, impotence), than into creating safe workplaces which would prevent many reproductive problems in the future. The Royal Commission focused almost exclusively on the high-tech medical and technological industries which are curative as opposed to preventive.
<p>
The Royal Commission did make a few important recommendations, however, which could assist the federal and provincial governments in looking forward to what needs to be done to minimize reproductive risks. The Commission started from the explicit premise that no work environment can be absolutely safe, but that the balance of risks and costs (to health, to the environment and the financial costs to employees and the employer's competitive advantage) must be factored into the setting of standards or the design of workplace controls. It made four key recommendations. First, hazards must be reduced through workplace design and controls at the source, rather than
through discriminatory policies. This reinforces some of the human rights decisions discussed earlier, but goes a step further to recommend a positive obligation to put engineering controls in place to reduce exposure to reproductive hazards. Although the Commission did not make a formal recommendation, it notes that governments have failed to use existing enforcement powers and urges them to do so to ensure compliance where regulatory standards do exist.<sup><a href="#one90">190</a></sup>
<p>
Second, the Commission endorsed existing experience-rated workers' compensation systems, where employer contribution rates are set based upon experience of injury or illness, and recommended expanding these provisions to use penalties as incentives to reduce reproductive hazards. Third, the Report recommended building upon the existing W.H.M.I.S. system to promote information sharing and move towards establishment of uniform standards for exposure to reproductive hazards. Finally, it recommended that provinces and territories amend their health and safety legislation to conform to the Quebec regime, which vests real decision-making power in joint employee-employer health and safety committees. This would include requiring employers to obtain committee approval of any major workplace changes and providing external resource supports for non-unionized joint  committees.<sup><a href="#one91">191</a></sup> This is a fairly important recommendation for a Royal Commission to make, because legislative change granting real power to joint committees would begin to allow employees some control in eliminating reproductive health risks. Workers who are required to bear the economic, emotional, and physical costs of reproductive health hazards have a direct interest in the decision-making which affects their safety.
<p>
 The Royal Commission ignored many of the substantive findings, however, and failed to adopt the proposals of one of the background studies which comprehensively examined the need for legislative change in this area.<sup><a href="#one92">192</a></sup> The study by Fudge and Tucker examined the current tort regime and its relationship to reproductive issues, assessing current limitations and liabilities, as well as its limited utility in
eliminating reproductive health risks.<sup><a href="#one93">193</a></sup> It also argued that while economic incentives should be utilized through Workers' Compensation administration, employees should not be compensated for pain, suffering, loss of consortium or other non-economic loss. It suggested that the harm caused by reproductive hazards is inestimable, and trying to place a price on loss of reproductive health &quot;cheapens them and encourages a pernicious tendency in our society to reduce even the most basic human emotions to exchangeable commodities.&quot;<sup><a href="#one94">194</a></sup> The issues raised by the study of whether we should
compensate for non-economic loss or encourage a no-fault compensatory system are critically important and somewhat controversial, and deserve more serious consideration than either the Royal Commission accorded them or this article allows.
<p>
 Fudge and Tucker suggest that there is little information about the human and economic costs that can form the basis of policy choices.<sup><a href="#one95">195</a></sup> While such information is being compiled, they call for a generic reproductive hazard standard as an immediate policy response to the current regime. This standard would contain a provision that evidence establishing a <i>prima facie</i> case that workers of either sex are at risk, or that a fetus exposed via the mother or father is at risk, should trigger the assumption that all workers are at risk until proven otherwise.<sup><a href="#one96">196</a></sup> Such a standard would address many of the problems cited throughout this article, particularly if it were accompanied by strong economic protection and enforcement measures. The Royal Commission did not adopt this recommendation. It will be interesting to see whether these and other recommendations for preventive strategies are seriously considered by political decision-makers, given the comparatively small amount of attention that was given to workplace prevention issues by the Royal Commission.
<p>
BUILDING A COMPREHENSIVE REGIME
<p>
In concluding, I argue that lessons should be learned from the Quebec model in constructing a comprehensive statutory regime to address current problems with respect to protection of reproductive health rights. There are three main points. First, hazards must be reduced wherever possible. Although the ultimate goal must be zero
tolerance of reproductive hazards, this is not realistically achievable in our lifetimes. This is not to suggest that we abandon any push for the substitution of less harmful substances, merely that what is required is a continuum of strategies to reduce exposure of both men and women to workplace reproductive hazards. Thus engineering controls and workplace design which control exposure to hazards at their source are a much needed and reasonably effective alternative. As the Royal Commission points out, engineering controls are also easier to enforce than regulated exposure levels, because design controls or lack of them are immediately discernable upon inspection of the workplace.<sup><a href="#one97">197</a></sup> This may be true, but any controls must still be monitored and enforced in order to be truly effective.
<p>
In my view, prevention is likely to be more cost-effective for government, employers, and individual workers than the expensive medical technology required to cure the adverse health effects of poor preventive policies. Prevention, as is discussed below, should entail a range of strategies including mandatory pre-market testing and, where necessary and appropriate, the exclusion of harmful substances from the workplace; the implementation of design controls which focus on those employees at highest risk, namely, women and men of child-bearing age, to protect them from exposure to reproductive hazards; the implementation of preventive rights of reassignment and income protection, not only for pregnant and nursing workers, but also for those who are trying to conceive; and, as a last resort, the setting of maximum exposure levels as a means of lowering if not preventing the risk of harm. Without this continuum of preventive measures, adverse reproductive health effects will persist, as will their serious consequences for society. 
<p>
The direct compensation costs alone for disease and injury in Canada for 1987 were $3.5 billion, with indirect costs estimated at $17.5 billion for that year alone.<sup><a href="#one98">198</a></sup> For workers, the cost is
both economic and social. Reproductive hazards have an impact on their earning capacity, both in terms of access to particular jobs if women or men of child-bearing age wish to have children, and in terms of time lost due to the adverse health effects of workplace hazards. The social costs are enormous in terms of the impact on workers'
ability to have healthy families at a time they consider most appropriate. For employers, any short-term savings in the use of cheaper chemicals or unsafe work practices merely add to long-term costs, not only in terms of experience-rated workers' compensation costs, but in the loss of healthy productive workers who make a valuable contribution to the workplace. For government, the costs are borne in resources expended on the health care system, including increasing resources directed towards medical strategies to deal with the outcomes of reproductive hazards and the soaring costs of workers' compensation. Preventive strategies to eliminate many of the sources of hazards will ultimately be much more cost-effective and socially just than letting individual workers pay for the
consequences of unsafe workplaces.
<p>
Furthermore, there should be mandatory testing of all new chemicals and substances for adverse reproductive health effects <i>prior</i> to their introduction into the workplace. Existing substances in the workplace should be required to undergo rigorous toxicological studies to evaluate their effects on reproductive health. This requires a more serious effort to determine which substances negatively affect reproductive health. One background study by the Royal Commission recommended that co-ordination of previous medical and workplace records could be used to evaluate suspected workplace risks and the reproductive health effects.<sup><a href="#one99">199</a></sup> Instead of having to wait for the time-lag of new studies, researchers and government could learn from existing fragmented data bases, using these as an analytical tool to make the linkages between the cause and effect of substances.<sup><a href="#twohundred">200</a></sup> Although the epidemiological validity of such a strategy may be questionable, use of these data bases could provide an accessible starting point to determine where to focus first in actually studying and establishing cause and effect. 
<p>
Second, I would endorse the strategy suggested by Fudge and Tucker, that in the absence of an ability to eliminate all hazards, a generic reproductive standard be enacted. Once a <i>prima facie</i> case is made that a substance affects one kind of worker, for example, a pregnant woman, the standard would trigger protection for all workers
in their reproductive years. This would begin to address some of the existing problems of standards in scientific research, as well as many issues of equality of treatment raised earlier in this article. Some of the resources being expended on reproductive technologies would be better directed at prevention at the source of the problems, the workplace. Non-toxic alternatives exist for many chemicals, but are more expensive and thus are not used. Without government regulation to set universal standards, even environmentally and health-conscious employers will not change their work practices if they are to maintain their competitiveness in the market. Despite the potential employer complaints regarding too much government intervention and cost, the reality is that the social and economic costs are already being incurred. The question is who will continue to pay for them?
<p>
Third, any control strategies must be accompanied by laws which provide preventive paid leave or reassignment to less hazardous working conditions. Only in Quebec do the laws protect pregnant and nursing mothers from potential harm to themselves or their unborn or nursing children by protecting both the right to reassignment and the
economic security which allows women to exercise this right effectively. Similar laws need to be enacted in other jurisdictions, not only for this category of workers, but for all employees of child-bearing age who seek reassignment so that they can have the best chance possible of having healthy children. The federal law needs to be amended to provide for full compensation for preventive leave. As the Quebec experience has amply illustrated, express legislative provisions and full economic protection are required before workers will exercise any rights they may have to protection of the law. Any such legislation, as it does in Quebec, should remove the onus from the employee to demonstrate the work is hazardous. Further, such legislation must be given the kind of purposive interpretation which has ensured the success of the Quebec experience, and which promotes public policy goals of a safe, healthy, and productive workforce.
<p>
In the interim, existing health and safety laws should be used to test the limits of protection for workers. Unions should be encouraging their members to exercise the right to refuse unsafe work for reproductive hazards, and government inspectors should be issuing orders recognizing such rights. This should include pressing for paid reassignment away from the hazardous work until the danger is eliminated. The recent amendment to Ontario's <cite>O.H.S.A.</cite>, which in exceptional circumstances allows certified worker health and safety representatives to shut down unsafe work operations, should be assessed for its potential to deal with the most egregious reproductive health hazards.<sup><a href="#two01">201</a></sup> Training of both employee and employer health and safety representatives must begin to focus on the unique problems of workplace reproductive hazards, and where possible, joint health and safety committees should begin to seriously address control and elimination of such hazards.
<p>
Human rights laws should also be utilized where possible, particularly the provisions regarding the duty to accommodate. Further, in unionized workplaces, there is enormous potential for use of recent amendments to the Ontario <cite>Labour Relations Act</cite> which grant arbitrators the authority to interpret and apply the requirements of human rights and other employment-related statutes necessary to the interpretation of a dispute under a collective agreement.<sup><a href="#two02">202</a></sup> Finally, workers' compensation regimes which are premised upon lost earning capacity need to be supplanted by more comprehensive compensation schemes which cover all accident and illness, and do not require either the establishing of causation or proof of lost earning capacity. 
<p>
In summary, instead of the current patch-work quilt of laws which are too haphazard to provide comprehensive protection for both women and men, there needs to be a co-ordinated legislative response to implement both short- and long-term protective strategies if the current problems are to be ameliorated. Elimination of reproductive health hazards and their accompanying effects is a crucial public policy goal which requires immediate attention.
<p>
