<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 53 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1>Economic Loss in Maritime Law: On Course for Reevaluating
the Exclusionary Rule
<p>
G. TODD STANLEY</h1>

<i>Recently common law courts have rendered a number of important decisions on the issue of recovery for relational economic loss. The tendency appears to be moving in favour of expanding the grounds for recovery, which runs counter to the traditional common law rule excluding recovery for such loss. The reasoning and results
are far from being consistent, but the cases share one similarity: they arose in the area of maritime law. The author argues that support for these controversial decisions can be found in features and characteristics unique to maritime law. These distinguish maritime law from other areas of law, and speak to the concerns that prompted the development of an exclusionary rule. Consequently, the continued strict application of the rule is not justifiable. In some maritime law cases relational economic loss should be recoverable.
<p>
Au cours des derni&egrave;res ann&eacute;es, les cours de &quot;common law&quot; ont prononc&eacute; une s&eacute;rie de jugements importante sur la question de l'indemnisation d'une perte &eacute;conomique relationelle
d&eacute;coulant d'un contrat. La tendance des jugements est d'augmenter les possibilit&eacute;s d'indemnisation, un r&eacute;sultat contraire &agrave; la r&egrave;gle traditionelle excluant l'indemnisation d'une telle perte. Bien qu'il n'est pas possible de remarquer une tendance uniforme dans la raisonnement et les r&eacute;sultats des d&eacute;cisions prises, les causes se ressemblent dans un aspect: elles provenaient toutes dans le domaine du droit maritime. L'auteur sugg&egrave;re que l'appui pour ces d&eacute;cisions controvers&eacute;es se trouve dans les traits et caract&eacute;ristiques uniques au droit maritime. Ceux-ci servent &agrave; distinguer le droit maritime des autres domaines l&eacute;gaux, tant qu'apaiser les int&eacute;r&ecirc;ts au fond du d&eacute;v&eacute;loppement de la regrave;gle exclusionaire. Par cons&eacute;quence, une application stricte de
la r&egrave;gle exclusionaire dans le domaine du droit maritime ne peut plus &ecirc;tre justifi&eacute;e; selon les circonstances les pertes &eacute;conomiques relationelles devraient &ecirc;tre indemnifi&eacute;es.</i>
<p>
<h3>I. Introduction</h3>

Maritime law and the common law make, at times, strained bedfellows. Their relationship is complex because maritime law does not actually constitute an integral part of the common law. Instead, it is a system of laws developed independently over thousands of years which has come to be grafted onto the common law for
convenience.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> In some areas this union has been virtually seamless. The common law of negligence, for example, is as important to the relationship between maritime parties as in any other context. In fact, the jurisprudence in maritime contexts has generated some of the leading decisions in the  development of the theory of tort law.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> This contribution has not diminished in the present day: maritime law continues to provide a venue for the resolution of issues on the leading edge of the development of the law of negligence. It is not often recognized, however, that at the same time, maritime law also
continues to develop and maintain doctrines and rules which are exclusive to its domain, and have no equivalent outside the maritime context.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> This dichotomy results in situations where jurisprudence developed within the common law conflicts with the theories and policies of maritime law. The inevitable consequence of this is contradiction and confusion in the development of maritime law, particularly in the context of one of the most important current issues in maritime law: relational economic loss. 
<p>
Relational economic loss occurs when a person suffers financial loss as a result of damage to the property of another
person.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> As such, it forms a subset of the law of general economic loss which, in actions for negligence, deals with financial losses not causally related to physical injury of the plaintiff's person or property.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> Historically, common law courts routinely and as a matter of course
refused to award recovery for such damages in claims of negligence. The result was a <i>de facto</i> rule excluding such damages from recovery. The strict application of this common law `exclusionary rule' was justified by the court on a number of grounds, including the promotion of certainty in actions, and the prevention of
never-ending litigation if such recovery was permitted. In the past forty years, however, this rule has been extensively reexamined by these courts. Instead of strictly refusing to grant recovery for these losses, exceptions to the application of this exclusionary rule are gradually being recognized and developed. One of the most active areas of debate over such recovery in recent years has been that of relational economic loss.
<p>
The importance of relational economic loss to maritime law comes naturally. Maritime law, at its essence, represents a body of law devoted to the regulation of the commercial nature of maritime activity. Today, this activity involves a commercial network of highly mobile and sophisticated parties spanning the globe. At the heart of this network are the commercial fleets of the world. It is this fact that makes relational economic loss so important in maritime law. Interference with a vessel can have significant impacts on a number of parties other than the vessel's actual owner. The value of the assets and contracts involved in maritime transactions mean the losses incurred when things go wrong can easily reach tens if not hundreds of millions of dollars. Under the exclusionary rule, claims for relational economic losses in these circumstances would be unrecoverable as against the tortfeasor who caused them. 
<p>
Increasingly in recent years, some maritime courts have found this result to be unsatisfactory. They have responded by relaxing the exclusionary rule in certain contexts. The difficulty is that these decisions have not been made in any coherent manner by the courts. Instead, decisions to award recovery for relational economic loss damages have been made haphazardly, on a case-by-case basis, without providing reasoning or doctrines which can be relied upon to predict what the next court would do on similar facts. The different approaches to economic loss in general, and relational economic loss in particular, which have developed among the various common law jurisdictions in recent years have added to the confusion. The resulting state of uncertainty and confusion has led to a situation in which commentators and even some courts have openly advocated reversion back to the certainty of the traditional absolute bar to recovery.
<p>
The purpose of this article is to advocate against a return to an absolute bar to recovery for relational economic losses in maritime law. It will do so first by tracking the historical development and current status of this branch of the law in England, the United States, Canada, and Australia (the dominant common law maritime jurisdictions of the world). From this foundation it will be argued that these cases demonstrate how the reasons underlying the existence of the exclusionary rule do not always apply in the realm of maritime law. Two aspects of maritime law will then be discussed to explore this point. The first will be three sets of maritime actors, each of which raises unique considerations in arguing against the application of the exclusionary rule: 1) time and voyage charterers; 2) other third parties contractually related to a vessel; and 3) parties affected by so-called `blocking situations'.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> The second aspect will be the availability of limited liability for tortfeasors in maritime law in general. All of these factors, it will be argued, demonstrate that strict application of the exclusionary rule against recovery for relational economic losses does not have a place in maritime law.
<p>
<h3>II.  Relational Economic Loss</h3>

II.1  GENERAL HISTORY OF ECONOMIC LOSS
<p>
In order to understand the law of relational economic loss as it now stands, it is necessary first briefly to examine the law of economic loss in general in order to understand where the momentum for recent changes and developments has originated.
<p>
The exclusionary rule for economic losses of any kind can be traced back to the decision of the House of Lords in <cite>Cattle v. Stockton Waterworks Co.</cite><sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> In that case a contractor was retained by a land owner to construct a tunnel through the latter's land. A third party then interfered with the land in a way which made the contractor's contract less profitable. The House of Lords, while appearing to want
to grant the contractor's claim for damages against this third party, stated:
<blockquote>
. . . if we did so, we should establish an authority for saying that, in such cases as that of <cite>Fletcher v. Rylands</cite> the defendant would be liable, not only to an action by the owner of the drowned mine, and by such of his workmen as had their tools or clothes destroyed, but also to an action by every workman and person employed in the mine, who in consequence of the stoppage made less wages than he would have otherwise done. . . . It may be said that it is just that all such persons should have compensation for such a loss, and that, if the law does not give them redress, it is imperfect. Perhaps it may be so. But, as pointed out by Coleridge, J. in <cite>Lumley v. Gye</cite> courts of justice should not &quot;allow themselves, in the pursuit of perfectly complete remedies for all wrongful acts to transgress the bounds, which our law, in a wise consciousness as I conceive of its limited powers, has imposed on itself of redressing only the proximate and direct consequences of
wrongful acts.&quot; In this we quite agree.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This statement by Blackburn L.J. reveals the driving force behind the exclusionary rule in economic loss: the fear of
indeterminate liability. Any number of people can potentially be affected by one's negligent interference with another's person or property. As a result, it is argued that if economic loss were generally permitted, a tortfeasor in such a situation would potentially face liability for claims which could not be reasonably foreseen in any way at the time of the accident, and for amounts which cumulatively could easily far exceed that relating to the property damaged by the negligence. This `floodgates' argument against the award of economic losses in any situation was best expressed by Cardozo C.J. in <cite>Ultramares Corporation v. Touche</cite>,<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> who characterized liability for economic loss as &quot;liability in an indeterminate amount for an indeterminate time to an indeterminate class.&quot;<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> This spectre of `indeterminate liability' can be seen flowing through the doctrine of economic loss to the present day; the way in which the courts continue to deal with it essentially creates most of the current difficulties.
<p>
The <cite>Cattle</cite> exclusionary rule survived intact in all its parts for almost a century,<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> until 1963 when the House of Lords relented in <cite>Hedley Byrne and Co. Ltd. v. Heller &amp; Partners Ltd.</cite><sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> Even the landmark <cite>Donoghue v. Stevenson</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> while developing the modern tort of negligence by formulating the reasonable foreseeability and duty of care standards, restricted damages to compensation for injuries to person or property. <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> was the first indication of a crack in the exclusionary wall. The
original `negligent misrepresentation' case, it involved a request by the plaintiff to its bankers that they ask the defendant bankers for financial information on a company the plaintiffs were dealing with. The defendants gave the information but disavowed any responsibility for its accuracy. When the plaintiff suffered losses after relying on
the information, it sued to recover. While the disclaimer eventually protected the defendant from liability, the House of Lords clearly stated that economic losses would be permitted where a person, whose advice was relied upon because of his or her specialization or skill, has made a negligent statement or misrepresentation. The law would
impose on that person a duty to protect those who could reasonably be foreseen to be relying on the information.
<p>
It was the acceptance of <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> in common law jurisdictions which marked the explosion in economic loss thinking. Courts, while never quick to embrace wholesale change, began to reconsider the application of the exclusionary rule in certain situations, including that of relational economic loss. The trend has been for decisions and doctrines developed in one area to migrate into others as the courts attempt to formulate tests encompassing a general theory of recovery for economic losses instead of relying upon individual exceptions. The following analysis traces this progression of the law of relational economic loss, from <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> and in cases decided prior to it, to where it stands today in England, the U.S., Australia, and Canada.
<p>
II.2   SUPPORTING THE EXCLUSIONARY RULE
<p>
As the law currently stands, both the U.S. and English courts generally appear to support the strict application of the
exclusionary rule to claims for relational economic loss---in other words, their view is that relational economic losses should not be recoverable under any circumstances.
<p>
<i>England</i><br>
The House of Lords' reconsideration of the <cite>Cattle</cite> exclusionary rule predates <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> to 1947, when it decided <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite>.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> In that case, the plaintiff was a cargo owner who was forced to pay general average damages to the owner of the ship on which it was shipping cargo, because of damage which the defendant had caused by negligently colliding with the ship. The ship's cargo had not been damaged in any way. The cargo owner brought a claim against the defendant for the money it had been so required to pay. The House of Lords agreed that the defendant was liable. In doing so, it stated it was following the reasoning put forth by the U.S. Supreme Court in <cite>The Sucarseco</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> discussed below. Specifically, the House of Lords accepted that in this situation, the ship and cargo owners were so closely intertwined in their relationship as against third parties that they constituted a `common adventure.' As a result, the cargo owner could recover as if the ship had actually been its property.
<p>
This harbinger to the end of the exclusionary rule was quoted and approved of in <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite>, but it did not gain common acceptance as a broad precedent for recovery for relational economic loss. In a succession of three cases decided in the late 1960's, lower English courts refused to award such damages. In <cite>The World Harmony</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> the plaintiff was a time charterer of a ship which was sunk by another's negligence. Claiming lost profits, the plaintiff raised the general principles of <cite>Donoghue v. Stevenson</cite>, as well as the economic loss precedent set in <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite>. The court rejected this
approach, affirming that <cite>Donoghue v. Stevenson</cite> contemplated personal or property damage only, and that <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> was based on an entirely different situation which was not applicable in this case. In <cite>Weller &amp; Co. v. Foot and Mouth Disease Research Institute</cite>,<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> the court refused damages on the grounds of the exclusionary rule, invoking the need to avoid indeterminate liability in commercial situations. The plaintiff cattle breeder had sued for losses suffered
because cattle auctions had to be closed due to the defendant's negligence. Then, in <cite>The Wear Breeze</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> a purchasor of cargo in whom ownership was to vest upon delivery sued the carrier shipowners for negligently damaging the cargo. The court reaffirmed its position from the above cases, specifically stating that under English law ship owners owed no duty to anyone except the legal owner of the cargo.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup>
<p>
Elsewhere in the field of economic loss, the English courts were not being quite so strict. <cite>Junior Books v. Veitchi Co. Ltd.</cite> extended the exception created in <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> into another area: product liability.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> Likewise, <cite>Anns v. Merton London Borough Council</cite> extended recovery for economic loss to public authorities.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> The plaintiffs in <cite>Anns</cite> had unknowingly bought negligently constructed buildings. When the defects were discovered, the purchasers sued the city for failing to carry out its duties of
inspection and certification of the buildings as they were constructed; they sought damages amounting to the cost of
constructing new buildings. Allowing this claim, Lord Wilberforce formulated a two-part test for determining when to award damages for pure economic loss. Success in a claim on this test depended upon 1) the reasonable foreseeability of the losses suffered as a result of the negligent act, and 2) the examination of considerations which
require limitation or negation of that duty or the scope to which it extends.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup>
<p>
Any hope that this doctrine, which was picked up in subsequent decisions such as <cite>Junior Books</cite>, would become the test for relational economic loss in England was quashed with the decision of the Privy Council in 1986 in <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> The plaintiff in this case was in
the unique position of being both the owner and the time charterer of a vessel which was negligently damaged by the vessel &quot;Mineral Transporter.&quot; The plaintiff had chartered the damaged boat back from the bare-boat charterer to whom it had originally chartered the boat. The terms of this time charter included a partial `off-hire' clause. `Off-hire' clauses provide that the charterer does not have to pay hire while a vessel is incapable of providing the services for which it was chartered. In this case the clause reduced the hire payable by the plaintiff to 25% while the vessel was incapacitated awaiting repairs. The plaintiff sued the defendant for recovery of this hire as an expense caused by the accident. The vessel's demise charterer had already recovered for not only the physical damages to the boat, but the economic loss occasioned by losing 75% of the boat's hire under the `off-hire' clause. The Privy Council held that the plaintiff had no cause of action, despite the plaintiff's clear proprietary interest in the vessel as its residual owner outside of the time charter. The Privy Council said that the claim was exclusively based on the plaintiff's time charterer position. The court voiced concerns about indeterminate liability and quoted <cite>Cattle</cite> and its exclusionary rule with approval.
<p>
In the same year, the House of Lords decided <cite>The Aliakmon</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> The facts were almost identical to those of  <cite>The Wear Breeze</cite>, in that the claim was for losses caused as a result of damage done to cargo which was not legally the property of the plaintiff at the time of the damage. The plaintiff argued that recovery should be permitted in this case because there was no danger of indeterminate liability on these facts; only this plaintiff could possibly bring a claim. The House of Lords rejected this idea on the basis of the `slippery slope' theory; if an exception were granted here, there would be no
way to prevent it from becoming a general exception, and the spectre of indeterminate liability would become a reality. The court held that it was preferable to maintain certainty in the law by uniformly enforcing the exclusionary rule. In both The <cite>Mineral Transporter</cite> and <cite>The Aliakmon</cite>, the court explicitly stated that <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite> was an anomalous decision which should be restricted to its facts.
<p>
Any possible doubt as to the English position on relational economic loss ended with <cite>Murphy v. Brentwood District Council</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> On its facts it was a very similar case to <cite>Anns</cite>, in that it involved public authorities and product liability. Yet the House of Lords reviewed the problems that <cite>Anns</cite> and similar cases had caused in determining the outer margins of recoverable economic loss. Their conclusion was that outside the situation of negligent misrepresentation, no sufficient theory had developed under <cite>Anns</cite> or any other approach to prevent the possibility of indeterminate liability. While admitting that cases such as <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite> were still the law, they treated that particular case as being based in maritime law, not common law. The decision of the House of Lords was to overturn <cite>Anns</cite> and hold that outside the negligent misrepresentation context, the <cite>Cattle</cite> exclusionary rule would once again apply in full as good law against any claims for economic loss.
<p>
The result in <cite>Murphy</cite> was not a surprise given the approach towards relational economic loss that the lower courts had adopted. Ending development in all of the areas of economic loss except for negligent misrepresentation was a major step, however, and it involved overruling over twenty years of decided cases. Whether the previous momentum for change can be restricted in this way remains to be seen, but for now, relational economic loss appears to be beyond recovery in England.
<p>
<i>United States</i><br>
Long before <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite>, the U.S. confirmed its adoption of the <cite>Cattle</cite> exclusionary rule in the case of <cite>Robins Dry Dock &amp; Repair Co. v. Flint</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> It involved a claim by a time charterer of a vessel against the defendant repair yard for damage to the vessel during other repairs. The delay caused by the further repairs had caused the plaintiff losses in wasted hire (hire it had been required to pay the shipowner while the vessel was incapacitated). The Supreme Court of the United States held that there could be no recovery for economic losses by someone who did not hold a property interest in the property concerned: this is the traditional formulation of the exclusionary rule. This decision, closely followed by <cite>Ultramares Corporation v. Touche</cite>, and Cardozo C.J.'s comment about `indeterminate liability,<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> appeared to leave little doubt regarding the Supreme Court's position on economic losses. 
<p>
Soon after <cite>Robins</cite>, however, the U.S. Supreme Court permitted a claim for relational economic loss by a cargo owner who sued for recovery of general average damages payable as a result of the defendant's negligent collision with the carrier vessel.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> These facts, almost identical to the later case of <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite> and quoted in it, led the Supreme Court to award damages on the grounds that the relationship between ship and cargo owners was so close and interdependent that it constituted a `joint adventure' which permitted recovery.
<p>
<cite>Robins</cite> remained untouched by the Supreme Court for years after this decision. Into this void stepped the lower courts, particularly the Circuit Courts of Appeal. In the vast majority of cases, these courts simply applied <cite>Robins</cite> and denied any and all claims for relational economic loss.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> In more recent years, however, and especially since <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite>, these courts occasionally moved towards developing further exceptions to the exclusionary rule along similar lines to
their fellow English judges. In 1974, the Ninth Circuit Court established the leading exception in this area,<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> an exception for the economic losses of fishermen as a result of oil company negligence.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> In 1985 the Fifth Circuit Court decided <cite>The Testbank</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> where a collision involving hazardous substances
resulted in the blocking of the Mississippi River, the evacuation of a 10 mile radius, and the filing of 41 claims for economic loss. The court applied <cite>Robins</cite> in all but one claim. It upheld the exception for commercial fishermen put forward in <cite>Union Oil</cite>. In 1986 the same court affirmed the exception to <cite>Robins</cite> for cargo owners as developed in <cite>The Sucarseco</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
<p>
Despite the occasional development of these exceptions, some of which are unique to American law, the U.S. courts have generally been extremely consistent in their application of the exclusionary rule as formulated in <cite>Robins</cite> to the area of relational economic loss. In this, they were for a period on a different jurisprudential track from Canada, Australia, and to some extent, England. With <cite>Murphy</cite>, however, England and the U.S. now appear approximately parallel in their rejection of recovery for relational economic
losses.
<p>
II.3   CHALLENGING THE EXCLUSIONARY RULE
<p>
In recent cases both the Australian and Canadian high courts have produced decisions that imply a much greater willingness to award damages for relational economic loss. As will be demonstrated below, however, these cases have not provided any clear framework for determining the circumstances that will trigger success in such claims, nor for deciding when (or even if) the exclusionary rule should be retained. While these jurisdictions may be more
liberal in their approach to economic loss, this uncertainty makes their decisions entirely unpredictable from one case to the next.
<p>
<i>Australia</i><br>
The leading Australian case on recovery for economic loss is <cite>Caltex Oil (Australia) Pty. Ltd. v. the Dredge
&quot;Willemstad</cite>.&quot;<sup><a href="thirty4">34</a></sup> In a case where a dredge had negligently damaged a pipeline between an oil terminal and a refinery, the terminal owner sued for the economic losses incurred in transporting oil to the refinery using alternate methods. The pipeline was owned by the refinery. The High Court of Australia allowed the claim. Yet while the decision was unanimous, it was arrived at on four separate grounds by the five judges. Their decisions summarize many of the different approaches to relational economic loss which permit recovery instead of excluding it.
<p>
Two judges held that there should be an exception to the exclusionary rule where the spectre of indeterminate liability does not arise on the facts of the case. These would be cases where the plaintiff was someone the defendant should have specially foreseen as likely to suffer economic loss as a result of the defendant's actions. This `known plaintiff' would be the only person entitled to recover. Stephens J., unwilling to apply a general tort standard to the
situation, decided the case on the basis of proximity. This test requires a strong proximate relationship between the injured and the plaintiff. This judge held that in this case there was sufficient proximity between the plaintiff and the property to grant compensation. This test differs from that of the `known plaintiff' in that the defendant's knowledge of this relationship may not be a factor.
<p>
Jacobs J. based his finding on the `physical propinquity test.' He stated that recovery should be granted where the damaged property in some way has physical effects (short of actual injury) upon the assets of the plaintiff. Examples would include an inability to move, operate or utilize one's property because of what the tortfeasor has done to another's property. Here it was accepted that the plaintiff had the movement and use of its oil disrupted by the damage to the pipeline. Finally, Murphy J. applied the broadest exception. He turned to the negligence principles of <cite>Donoghue v. Stevenson</cite> and held that it should include both physical and economic losses on the same grounds: duty of care and reasonable foreseeability.
<p>
It is clear from this case that the High Court of Australia knows where it wants to go with recovery for economic losses; unfortunately, it cannot agree on how to get there. Equally unfortunate is that each of the theories proposed above has been extensively criticized as failing to provide the necessary framework and protections to permit us to abandon <cite>Cattle</cite>, even on a limited basis.
<p>
<i>Canada</i><br>
The doctrine of <cite>Cattle</cite> received the Supreme Court of Canada's approval in <cite>Warner Quinlan Asphalt Co. v. The King</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> The case involved a claim by a time charterer for compensation under the <cite>War Measures Act 1914</cite> for the loss of use of the chartered vessel because it had been expropriated for military service. The Supreme Court affirmed that <cite>Cattle</cite> was the law in Canada and that economic losses could not be recovered for damages to property which one did not possess or own. This stance was later confirmed in <cite>Deep Sea Tankers Ltd. v. The Tricape</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> 
<p>
Relational economic loss was not an area which benefited from the attempted expansions of the <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite> principle in Canada. The most that can be said is that it was suggested in some cases that, in this area, the exclusionary rule should be reconsidered.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> Nonetheless, the impact of decisions in other areas of economic loss gradually migrated to decisions on relational economic loss as well.
<p>
In 1977 the Federal Court decided two cases on relational economic loss: <cite>Gypsum Carrier Inc. v. R.</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> and <cite>Bethlehem Steel Corp. v. St. Lawrence Seaway
Authority</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> Both involved losses suffered as a consequence of damages to another's property. The <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite> case involved claims by four railway companies for the expenses they incurred in rerouting their trains around a bridge negligently damaged by the defendant's vessel. Collier J. pointed to the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Rivtow Marine Ltd. v. Washington Iron Works</cite>,<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> in which the court had permitted
recovery for economic losses in a situation where the maker of a product was held to have a duty to warn its customers about potential problems with the product. Collier J. held that <cite>Rivtow</cite> was authority in Canada that &quot;. . . there need not be physical injury to person or property in order successfully to recover from pure economic loss.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> On this basis, the court analyzed the claims on negligence grounds to see whether the damages were a reasonably foreseeable result of the negligence. In the end the court held that the railways' damages were not proximate enough to the bridge's damage to be a reasonably
foreseeable consequence of the collision. 
<p>
This approach did not survive long, however. The same court in <cite>Bethlehem Steel</cite> quickly retreated from this departure from the exclusionary rule. Addy J. held that the <cite>Rivtow</cite> exception did not extend to situations of relational economic loss. This case involved plaintiffs who had suffered economic losses as a result of the negligent blocking of the St. Lawrence Seaway. The court denied all of the claims against the limited liability fund. The court adopted an extremely pragmatic approach, stating that, although applying the exclusionary rule might offend one's sense of justice, it is important in areas such as relational economic loss for the law to set up a clear system of rules to permit the parties involved to know where they stand and to govern themselves
accordingly.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<p>
Of course this case did not end the debate, not even within the Federal Court Trial Division. Another hint that the exclusionary rule was in doubt in this area of law occurred in <cite>The Atlantic Splendour</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> An ore carrier was damaged due to negligence of the crew while loading at dock. The vessel remained at dock for the 17 days it took to repair the damage, even though the damage did not prevent it from being removed to another location. As a result, plaintiff's vessels were forced to stand off and wait for 17 days before getting access to the dock; the plaintiff sought the recovery for the economic losses caused by this delay. The Federal Court Trial Division granted recovery. Dube J. reviewed <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite> and <cite>Bethlehem Steel</cite> and interpreted both cases as being decided on the basis of foreseeability. In this case, he said, the operators of the &quot;Atlantic Splendour&quot; could clearly foresee the losses their actions were causing to the parties standing off the dock and waiting for 17 days. These parties therefore recovered. On the subject of relational economic loss in general, Dube J. held that liability should flow from the same tort doctrines governing damages to property: duty and foreseeability.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup>
<p>
The Supreme Court of Canada had an opportunity to settle the debate in <cite>Ontario (A.G.) v. Fatehi</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> Estey J., writing for the court, described relational economic
loss as &quot;unrecoverable economic loss.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> He went on to note, however, that in <cite>Agnew-Surpass Shoes v. Cummer-Yonge Investments Ltd.</cite>,<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> Pigeon J. had approved the interpretation of <cite>Rivtow</cite> that permitted recovery without physical loss or damage.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> Estey J. recognized that <cite>Rivtow</cite> had been subject to varied interpretations and applications in courts across the country, but then held he did not have to resolve the debate to in order to decide the case before him.
<p>
This was the situation before the leading relational economic loss case in Canada, <cite>Canadian National Railway Co. v. Norsk Pacific Steamship Co. (&quot;Jervis Crown&quot;)</cite>,<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> was decided. The facts of the case are almost identical to those of <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite>. It involved the economic losses experienced by railway companies who had to reroute their trains around a government bridge over the Fraser River which the defendants had negligently damaged. The bridge was a major link to Vancouver. The only difference between <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite> and <cite>Norsk</cite> was that one of the four railway companies using the bridge, C.N.R., was responsible for 86% of the usage, and the bridge was generally known as the `C.N.R. bridge.' Only C.N.R. brought its claim for economic losses to court; the other three companies agreed to be bound by the decision.
<p>
The Supreme Court decided four to three in favour of the plaintiff, awarding economic loss damages. The case, however, does little to clarify the Canadian position on relational economic loss, despite the result, because the structure of the judgments was such that each proposed approach to the problem was rejected by a majority of the
court.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> The majority consisted of McLachlin J., writing for L'Heureux-Dube and Cory JJ., and Stevenson J.; the dissenting judgment was written by La Forest J. with Sopinka and Iacobucci JJ. concurring. The only issue that these judgments do agree upon is that <cite>Murphy</cite> is not the law in Canada.
<p>
McLachlin's judgment touched on a number of alternatives to the exclusionary rule. She compared the law of various jurisdictions and held that there are two constants in economic loss: that indeterminate liability is the overriding motivation for denying recoverability, but also that the common law will always find ways around strict rules such as the rule proposed in <cite>Murphy</cite>. In light of this, she rejected the <cite>Murphy</cite> approach and approved the incremental development of the law permitted by <cite>Nielson v. Kamloops</cite>.,<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> an earlier decision of the court which had approved of and adopted Lord Wilberforce's two-stage test from <cite>Anns</cite>. She held that this test permitted case-by-case development in the law of economic loss, and yet provided for protections against indeterminate liability.
<p>
McLachlin J. then set out what would be required to grant economic loss recovery in a particular case. She focussed on proximity, stating that &quot;pure economic loss is prima facie recoverable where, in addition to negligence and foreseeable loss, there is sufficient proximity between the negligent act and the loss.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> In applying this formulation to the case, she held that the relationship between C.N.R. and the government in connection with the bridge was of such closeness that they constituted a `common adventure,' as was originally suggested in <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite>. She stated that this placed C.N.R. in essentially the same position as the owner of the bridge and it made no sense to deny them recovery for losses resulting from its damage.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> 
<p>
Stevenson J. rejected this approach. Restricting his comments to relational economic loss (which McLachlin J. had not done), he believed McLachlin J.'s formulation provided insufficient protection against indeterminate liability. Instead, he favoured the `known plaintiff' test for liability; that the plaintiff had to be a specific individual the defendant could foresee sustaining harm by his or her negligence. On this approach he held that C.N.R.'s association with the bridge was sufficiently well known to the defendant that it could foresee the damages which would be  caused as a result of the collision.
<p>
La Forest J., writing for himself and Sopinka and Iacobucci JJ., dissented strongly. He recognized that in other economic loss situations, there may be recovery for economic losses and he rejected <cite>Murphy</cite> as law in Canada; he then restricted his comments to relational economic loss. Referring to the majority judgments, he
dismissed McLachlin J.'s discussion of proximity as insufficiently precise to guard against indeterminate liability. Instead La Forest J. took a more policy-oriented approach to the issue. He stated that there was no policy reason for awarding relational economic loss damages on the basis that it would provide a disincentive to tortfeasors, simply because liability for physical damage does this now. Instead, he said that policy considerations gave rise to a need
to examine the positions of both the plaintiff and defendant to determine their ability to foresee and provide for such damage. His approach advocates that relational economic loss in each case should be allocated to the party best able to protect himself or herself from such harm.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> Only when the situation
warrants would the exclusionary rule be relaxed and the person who actually suffered the loss be allowed to recover. On the facts of <cite>Norsk</cite>, he concluded that this was not such a case. In his opinion the railway companies were sophisticated actors who knew of the bridge's importance to their operation and could have made any number of contractual or insurance provisions against the possibility of its damage. The losses experienced should therefore lie with the railway companies.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> 
<p>
Canadian law of economic loss, therefore, stands in almost as great a state of flux as that of Australia. On a strict reading, McLachlin J.'s decision has to be taken as the <i>ratio</i> of <cite>Norsk</cite> and therefore the leading statement in Canadian law, but it is not possible to ignore the strength of the dissenting opinions in the case. The only certainty is that Canadian law has advanced a much more accommodating approach to economic loss in general, and to relational economic loss in particular, than have England and the United States.
<p>
<i>Analyzing the Alternatives</i><br>
Between <cite>Caltex</cite> and <cite>Norsk</cite>, a number of alternate theories have been proposed as to when and how the exclusionary rule should be relaxed or even abandoned in relational economic loss cases. It is not possible to conduct an extended critical analysis of each here, but it is important to note that none has been free from criticism, either in the decisions of other judges or in academic writings. Murphy J.'s approach in <cite>Caltex</cite>, that economic loss damages simply receive the same treatment as physical damages, may be appealing in its simplicity, but it has been severely criticized by writers who maintain that there are inherent differences between such losses.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> The other approaches have received similar treatments. The `known plaintiff' test, for example, has been rejected as basing liability simply on the level of notoriety of the plaintiff; if, and only if, the defendant has heard of the plaintiff, the plaintiff succeeds.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> Reliance on the principle of proximity, although this principle is recognized as necessary to some extent in any successful theory, has been criticized as too imprecise to protect against indeterminate liability.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> The suggestions of La Forest in <cite>Norsk</cite> that the losses should lie with those best able to provide against them has been denounced as being inconsistent with the entire theory of malfeasance which is the foundation of tort law.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> It also works effectively only in hindsight, as a party will only know whether it will be liable for damages when it knows the identity and financial circumstances of the other party in an action, and can determine which of them is more capable of sustaining such losses.
<p>
II.4   CONCLUSION
<p>
Any review of these exceptions to the exclusionary rule and their problems makes it rather easy to sympathize with the position of the House of Lords in <cite>Murphy</cite>, in other words, that the debate continues to create greater uncertainty instead of resolving anything and as such it is best for it simply to be terminated. This does not appear to be an option, however. The history of economic loss at common law suggests that this debate continue in Canada and Australia in the near future, and to a lesser degree in the U.S. History also suggests that courts in England will soon be developing ways to get around both the <cite>Cattle</cite> and <cite>Murphy</cite> decisions.
<p>
This does not satisfy the needs of maritime actors who need to understand where they stand today with regards to possible liabilities. The next section will be an examination of how the general doctrine on relational economic loss has translated into three very specific areas of maritime law: charters, third party relationships with vessels, and traffic blockages. As will be seen, each area presents new arguments both for and against the exclusionary rule which are unique to its sphere, and suggests that a single approach to relational economic loss may be impractical to
apply.
<p>
<h3>III.  Economic Loss at Maritime Law</h3>

III.1   THE AREAS FOR RELATIONAL ECONOMIC LOSS
<p>
In his article written in anticipation of the House of Lords' decision in <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite>, N.J.J. Gaskell identified three areas of maritime law specifically affected by decisions in the law of relational economic loss. These areas are: 1) charters other than demise charters; 2) third party contractors with damaged vessels; and 3) situations known as `blocking cases,' where traffic or movement of some sort has been impeded by the negligent
action involved.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> 
<p>
The common law of each for these areas is as confusing as the whole law of relational economic loss. While the majority of cases have applied the traditional exclusionary rules, more recent cases have held out the possibility, whether simply in hints or open developments of doctrine, of abandoning this strict restriction in favour of one which will permit recovery in certain situations. The result is a potential quagmire for anyone interested in predicting a party's potential liability, or a given court's decision in any situation. The following is an attempt to summarize in brief where each subset of the law of relational economic loss stands now in each jurisdiction, what the practical consequences of each are, and how they could be avoided by changes in the doctrine.
<p>
III.2   CHARTERS
<p>
As defined in <cite>Chorely and Giles'</cite>, a charterparty is a contract between a charterer and a shipowner for the hire of the use of a ship.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> Demise charterers hire a vessel for an indefinite amount of time, with the charterer providing any and all crew required. Such charterers are by definition deemed to take a property interest in the vessels so chartered.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> As a result, their claims for economic losses arising from damage to a vessel are on the same footing as the actual residual owner, and never constitute claims for relational economic loss. Instead, relational economic loss arises with charterers who do not have this presumed property interest. These are charters for either specific periods of time (time charterers) or for specific voyages (voyage charterers).
<p>
This area is in itself a microcosm of the entire debate over relational economic loss. In a large number of situations the court's denial of recovery on the basis of the exclusionary rule appears both unjust and illogical, as convincing arguments can be put forward to support recovery in these cases. As will be seen with sub-charters, however, the issue quickly gets much cloudier when the parameters are relaxed. In the end, if the exclusionary rule is to be relaxed, the ultimate choice as to where the line is to be drawn against indeterminate liability may have to rely much more on policy than on any substantive legal reasoning. 
<p>
<i>Time Charters</i><br>
A large number of relational economic loss cases have focussed on the position of the time charterer in trying to recover losses, whether for wasted hire during the boat's repair or lost profits from its lack of use, occasioned by the negligent damage of the chartered vessel.
<p>
The application of the <cite>Cattle</cite> exclusionary rule to time charters was specifically confirmed by the House of Lords in two cases: <cite>Chargeurs R&eacute;unis Compagnie Fran&ccedil;aise de Navigation &agrave;
Vapeur v. English and American Shipping Co.</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> and <cite>Elliott Steam Tug Co. Ltd. v. Shipping Controller</cite>.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> In both cases, claims for wasted hire and lost profits were dismissed on the grounds that the common law recognized no right to damages based upon a solely contractual relationship to damaged property.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
<p>
The U.S. adopted this thinking in toto in <cite>Robins</cite>, the case which established the exclusionary rule in American law and which itself is a time charterer case. Holmes J. explicitly adopted the reasoning of <cite>Elliott</cite>, above, in denying liability.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup>
<p>
England confirmed its approach as recently as 1985 in <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> upholding the reasoning of <cite>Cattle</cite> and <cite>Elliott</cite> in what has to be seen as the most extreme of cases.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> The facts, once again, were that the plaintiff was the residual owner of a vessel which it was time chartering back from the bare-boat charterer of the vessel. The vessel was damaged by the negligent actions of &quot;The Mineral Transporter.&quot; The `off-hire'
clause in the time charter provided that while the ship was being repaired, the plaintiff's hire payable was reduced to 25% of the normal rate. The plaintiff claimed against &quot;The Mineral Transporter&quot; for this cost as economic loss. At the time, the demise charterer had already successfully claimed for both damages to the vessel and for the economic losses suffered by having to forego 75% of hire on the vessel.
<p>
The Privy Council said that the plaintiff had no cause of action, based on <cite>Cattle</cite> and <cite>Elliott</cite>. This was despite the fact that the plaintiff had a definite property interest in the vessel as
its residual owner after the demise charter. The Privy Council stated that the plaintiff's claim arose solely from the time charter, and these were the rights to which the plaintiff was therefore restricted. The plaintiff also argued that had there been a full `off-hire' clause, the demise charterer would have suffered these losses as lost hire as well, instead of only the 75% loss which was suffered, but would have been able to recover all of this amount from the defendant. Therefore all the time charterparty and the off-hire clause did was distribute the same loss. The Privy Council dismissed this fact as irrelevant and affirmed <cite>Cattle</cite>.
<p>
In Canada time charterers appear not to have had an easier time than in England and the U.S., but later cases may be leading to a difference in doctrine. In <cite>Warner Quinlan Asphalt</cite>,<sup><a href  = "#sixty9">69</a></sup> the Supreme Court of Canada also specifically adopted the <cite>Elliott</cite> reasoning. In 1955, however, even before <cite>Hedley Byrne</cite>, the Supreme Court hinted in <cite>The Tricape</cite>
that it might be willing to depart from this rule.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> This case involved the claims of the owner and charterer of a negligently damaged vessel; the charterer's claims centred on the full hire paid during repairs to the chartered vessel. At trial, both parties were denied recovery, the charterer specifically on the basis of <cite>Elliott</cite>. Only the owner's case was appealed to the Supreme Court of Canada. The court reversed on this ground, but specifically stated it did not want to comment on the reasoning and authorities
applied at trial to exclude the charterer from recovery.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup>
<p>
This slim ray of jurisprudential hope for time charterers was picked up by the lower courts. In <cite>Courtenay v. Knutson</cite>,<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> the Supreme Court of British Columbia granted recovery to a charterer for loss of use of a barge. The finding in that case, however, rested upon determining that a relationship greater than a standard charter party agreement existed. Yet the position of the time charterer appeared to slip from the minds of most courts. In a number of cases subsequently decided involving claims by time charterers, their status was ignored in the reasoning of the court: they were considered to be in the same position as owners.<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> The most drastic example of this occurred in <cite>The Atlantic Splendour</cite>,<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> in which the plaintiff time charterers were awarded damages due to being delayed for 17 days because the defendants blocked their access to a loading dock. The plaintiffs recovered despite the fact they were time charterers, a fact which was not even mentioned in the case.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> The ignorance of the status of time charterers in these claims went against the clear authorities of <cite>Warner Quinlan Asphalt</cite>, <cite>The Tricape</cite>, and <cite>Elliott</cite>, which all held this fact alone would have prevented recovery.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup>
<p>
The effect of <cite>Norsk</cite> on all of this is unclear, in that it is not a time charterer case. <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite> was discussed and considered by La Forest J., but not expressly applied. McLachlin J.'s `common adventure' approach might provide a ground for recovery for Canadian time charterers, on the argument that the relationship between shipowners and time charterers is close enough to create such a `common adventure' position with regards to the vessel: cargo owners were deemed to be so related in <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite> (see the discussion in the next section regarding voyage charterers). The only clear conclusion is that while <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite> has not been approved of by the Supreme Court, the weight of existing Canadian precedent, while apparently lying dormant, still mitigates against time charterers being able to recover for economic loss.
<p>
Despite all of this judicial consideration and precedent, there is a strong case to be made for allowing economic loss recovery to time charter claimants. The main argument is that the <cite>Cattle</cite> exclusionary rule adopted in <cite>Elliott</cite> is designed to protect against indeterminate liability. Time charterer cases raise no such spectre; the time charterer stands in essentially the same position as the owner of the boat would in relation to the negligent
defendant. No one involved in maritime operations could claim that the existence of a time charterer might not be reasonably foreseeable in relation to any particular vessel. Furthermore, granting time charterers economic loss recovery would not result in liability to an `indeterminate class' because the time charterer is easily identifiable as a discrete set, either of a single or in the case of sub charters (discussed below), a small number of potential claimants. There is no way for this group to grow beyond these small numbers, as the qualifying factor is a specific, and by its nature exclusive, contractual relationship with the vessel.
<p>
The current law creates a situation of extreme unfairness to charterers, in that the defendant's liability for economic loss is determined by the presence or absence of an `off-hire' clause in the charterparty. <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite> demonstrates this quirk of excluding charterers from recovery. If a full off-hire clause existed in that case, then the plaintiff time charterer would not have to pay hire and would therefore suffer no economic loss. The demise charterer would instead suffer a greater economic loss, as now, instead of losing 75% of the hire receivable, 100% of it would be an economic loss. But the demise charterer can recover this amount from the defendant, because its claim for economic loss can be related to its property interest in the vessel. The defendant becomes liable for all the losses, physical and economic, suffered by its action. In contrast, no off-hire clause exists in the charterparty, the demise charterer has no economic losses to claim as it is receiving full hire from the time charterer. The economic losses resulting from the defendant's negligence have therefore been allocated to the time charterer through the off-hire clause, in that the time charterer has to pay full hire without getting any benefit out of the vessel. Yet this loss cannot be recovered due to the exclusionary rule. The result is that the defendant is liable only for the physical damages and avoids paying for economic losses resulting from its actions altogether. In <cite>The Mineral Transporter</cite>, the defendant only had to pay 75% of the economic losses caused by its action, because the off-hire clause had allocated 25% of the loss to the time charterer and therefore was outside the reach of recovery.
<p>
The effect of applying the exclusionary rule to time charters is therefore twofold. It protects the defendant against the possibility of indeterminate claimants from a class which by definition cannot become an infinite class and is instead hardly less foreseeable than the owner of a vessel as a particular claimant. It also results in the extent of the defendant's liability being determined on the basis of the presence or absence of an 'off-hire' clause in the charterparty contract, of which the defendant can have no knowledge before the accident. This clause has the potential to unfairly allocate losses to the time charterer which would otherwise be recoverable from the vessel's owner and to block their recovery. Both of these effects argue for at least a reconsideration of the application of the exclusionary rule to time charterers: as will be demonstrated below, however, this solution may not be as simple as
making a special exception in this case.
<p>
<i>Voyage Charterers</i><br>
Traditionally, voyage charterers have suffered the same treatment as time charterers at common law: no proprietary interest, therefore no recovery for economic losses.<sup><a href  = "#seventy7">77</a></sup> As Gaskell notes, the opportunity for loss by a voyage charterer may be less, in that much of the potential loss will be taken up by demurrage (liquidated damages payable for delays in cargo loading, as set out in voyage charterparties). Losses may still be experienced, however, in the form of lost profits or extra expenses incurred in rerouting cargo.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> 
<p>
The reasons put forth against applying the <cite>Cattle</cite> rule to time charterers apply equally as well to voyage charterers; they also cannot constitute an indeterminate class of plaintiffs, and are prejudiced by off-hire clauses in the same way. There is also an additional argument which bolsters their right to recover for economic losses. It flows from the idea that voyage charterers can be characterized as cargo owners who simply fill all or part of the holds of a carrier vessel. Essentially the only difference between voyage charterers and cargo owners is the size of their respective shipments. In the case of the person shipping cargo, his or her cargo follows the ship's schedule; a voyage charterer's cargo is of so large a size that he or she can get the ship to follow his or her
cargo's schedule. 
<p>
It has already been discussed above that cargo owners enjoy one of the few universally recognized exceptions to the exclusionary rule, permitting recovery for general average economic loss damages. General average damages are damages payable where the loss to either a cargo owner or vessel owner was incurred as a result of a deliberate act to benefit (usually to save) the majority of the cargo or the vessel. As they benefit from the other's loss, the parties
suffering no damage are jointly liable to compensate the party suffering the loss.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> Under the doctrine of <cite>The Sucarseco</cite> and <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite>, cargo owners have the right to recover general average economic damages from those who damage the vessel in which their cargo is carried, even where the cargo itself has not been damaged in any way. <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite> was one of the few exceptions to the exclusionary rule confirmed in <cite>Murphy</cite>; Lord
Keith approved of it on the grounds that it turned &quot;on specialities of maritime law or concerned the relationship of joint adventurers at sea.&quot;<sup><a href="eighty">80</a></sup>
<p>
Yet <cite>Greystoke</cite> was not restricted in its reasoning to general average claims. Lord Roche's examples extended beyond the maritime field to any example of a carrier of goods and the shipper, and beyond general average to any expenses of lost time and rerouting by the shipper.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> 
<p>
Even if we restrict <cite>Greystoke</cite> to the maritime context, on its reasoning a cargo owner should be able to recover expenses for rerouting cargo as well as for general average. The author was unable to find any reported cases discussing this issue. If this reasoning is accepted, however, it appears only logical that the same right
should be available to the voyage charterer. A voyage charterer would stand in a much closer `joint adventure' relationship (<cite>Greystoke Castle</cite>'s test) with a vessel's owner than a simple cargo owner.
<p>
Therefore permitting a voyage charterer to avoid the application of the exclusionary rule would be entirely consistent with existing jurisprudence in the U.S. and England. In Canada, the argument should be even easier to make, because <cite>Greystoke</cite>'s reasoning is similar to that of McLachlin J. in <cite>Norsk</cite>; she specifically approves of the case. It remains to be seen whether the courts will accept this approach.
<p>
<i>Sub-charterers</i><br>
If the situation of individual time and voyage charterers argues strongly for recovery for relational economic loss, the practical results of permitting such recovery, when the group of affected charterers grows, strains this approach somewhat, and possibly renews support for the application of the exclusionary rule.
<p>
Despite the fact that the consideration of sub-charterers extends the list of potential claimants, it does not present the possibility for indeterminate claims by indeterminate numbers of plaintiffs. This is because there are practical restrictions on how long the chain of charters on any given vessel can possibly be. It is unusual to find more than five charters between any vessel's current user and its owner; moreover, arrangements of this type are foreseeable
characteristic of any vessel operating.
<p>
Instead, the difficulty comes from potential indeterminate liability on the part of the defendant in such actions. This liability is not infinite, but it may be entirely unpredictable by the defendant. If recovery is extended to time and voyage charterers suffering economic losses, as argued above, the amount of money the defendant would be liable for in a given situation will depend entirely upon a factor the defendant cannot in any way anticipate before the event: the culprit is once again the `off-hire' clause.
<p>
A complete treatment of the effects of a number of charter arrangements with varying off-hire clauses on the liability of a defendant if charterers were granted recovery is set out in Gaskell.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> Only a simple example will be used here to demonstrate the problem; to simplify the discussion, it will contemplate only claims for expenses and not lost profits.
<p>
A given vessel is negligently damaged by the defendant. This vessel was subject to the following charterparty arrangement: the owner, O, had demise chartered the vessel to A for $10,000 per month. A had in turn time chartered the vessel to B for $11,000 per month; B had then voyage chartered the vessel to C for one month for $12,000. The damage to the vessel requires it to be docked for repairs for the month of C's charter (the line of charters would be O-A-B-C).
<p>
If, as argued, full recovery for economic losses is allowed, and no off-hire clauses exist between any of the parties, then the defendant's liability for economic loss is restricted to $12,000, being the amount of hire wasted by C on the vessel. All the other parties are getting full hire paid under the charters, and they are suffering no losses as a result of the negligence. If instead C had a full off-hire clause in its charter contract with B, then B, not C, would claim for economic loss as C would no longer be suffering while B would be losing $11,000 per month in rent it had to pay to A. The defendant's liability would be to B, not C, and would increase to $11,000 by operation of the off-hire clause. The situation changes greatly if the only off-hire clause exists between A and B. C would still have a claim for $12,000 against the defendant as if no off-hire clauses existed at all. However, A has to pay hire to O but is receiving no income from B because of the off-hire clause. A would therefore have a claim against the defendant for $10,000. The defendant's liability is now $22,000, up $12,000 from the earlier situation, entirely as a result of the existence and position of off-hire clauses in the arrangement.
<p>
One argument for recovery by time and voyage charterers is that the exclusionary rule unfairly benefits defendants when off-hire clauses exist. It can now be seen that if recovery is permitted, defendants would also potentially be prejudiced by the existence of such clauses. The question is whether this problem can be addressed without requiring strict application of the exclusionary rule to all charterer situations. One possible solution might be a policy decision permitting only one charterer to claim per vessel.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> Another solution might be to restrict the number of positions down the chain from the current operating charter that the defendant has to compensate. Or it could be argued that the defendant should get no protection; that these losses are the result of the actions of the defendant and as such the defendant should be liable for all of them without having
the benefit of any such protections. 
<p>
Whatever the solution in the sub-charter situation, it should not be allowed to be a ground for taking the easy road and applying the exclusionary rule to avoid this problem. The exclusionary rule no longer makes any sense in application to time and voyage charterers, if it ever did, and in this area of relational economic loss at least, maritime actors should be able to rely on their reasonable expectations for recovery.
<p>
III.3   OTHER THIRD PARTIES
<p>
In the broadest sense, charterers are simply third parties with a contractual interest in the damaged vessel. As such, while they are distinguishable on the nature of the contract from other claimants, they do not represent the only parties susceptible to economic losses through contractual association with a vessel or other property. Vessels especially are usually surrounded by a web of contractual relations with various parties. A partial list of such
parties includes stevedores and longshoremen, tug owners, cargo owners, fuel suppliers, and maintenance and repair yards. All of these parties and others can at any given time have contracts which are adversely affected by someone's negligent interference with the operation of a particular vessel, resulting in economic losses. For
example, stevedores and longshoremen may have to forego loading contracts for a delayed vessel, and they may never recover the amounts potentially earned under the contracts. Fuel suppliers may purchase diesel for inventory in anticipation of the arrival of a vessel according to a standing contract, only to have that vessel's destination changed as a result of an accident; the fuel purchased may not be sold as quickly as it would have been, or on terms as good, resulting in a loss. A cargo owner's deliveries would be delayed by a delay in the carrier's voyage; tug boats under contract to a particular vessel will be prejudiced if the vessel is delayed or never shows up at the port at all. These are only a sample of the potential sources of economic losses suffered by contractual third parties to a vessel.
<p>
Traditionally the claims of all these parties have been the victims of the exclusionary rule of <cite>Cattle</cite> and have been denied as a result. This is not unexpected. Both <cite>Cattle</cite> and <cite>Robins</cite> have as their central premise that parties related to property only through contract do not have sufficient interest in the property to
recover for economic losses.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> Yet once again, these are cases where the potential for unlimited liability by the defendant has to be questioned. All of these parties, and maybe even the losses they suffer, would be reasonably foreseeable by any defendant, especially given the fact that the defendant in many cases will have similar contracts surrounding the activities of its own vessel. Furthermore, the limits of liability in these cases would be subject to the principle of proximity in the same way as liability for physical damages; the economic loss equivalent of Mrs. Palsgraf would not collect as a result of simply extending the duty to protect the foreseeable contractual parties from economic losses.
<p>
Unfortunately, none of the courts in the jurisdictions examined above appear to be making any move towards extending the bounds of recovery to any party contractually related to a vessel, either to charterers or other third parties. The only ray of hope for these parties desiring recovery is again <cite>Greystoke Castle</cite>, which permits cargo owners to recover their losses from rerouting and delays if their carrier vessel is delayed. That case, as well as <cite>Norsk</cite>, however, awarded damages on the basis of a `common adventure' existing between the property owner and the plaintiff. The limits of this relationship have not been clearly defined, but undoubtedly an
onshore supplier of a vessel will have a harder time satisfying such a test than a cargo owner would. Not only that, but in Canada at least, La Forest J.'s dissent in <cite>Norsk</cite> would argue strongly against recovery in these situations. As discussed above, La Forest J. advocated that the loss be allocated to those parties most capable of bearing the loss in a given situation. For a diversified group of suppliers, the vessel in question would represent only a portion of their activities, and they would also be experienced actors in their particular businesses and therefore able to foresee the possibility of such economic losses occurring. They would most likely, therefore, be deemed to be the appropriate parties to bear the economic losses than the defendant, who would have to bear the sum of these losses alone.
<p>
For most third party contractors with a vessel, the law of economic loss is therefore relatively clear and consistent among all common law jurisdictions. This is despite recent decisions in Australia and Canada relaxing the exclusionary rule in other contexts of relational economic loss in the maritime area. Despite the arguments which
exist to support recovery, the general exclusionary rule, as set out in either <cite>Cattle</cite> or <cite>Robins</cite>, is of full force and effect.
<p>
III.4   BLOCKING CASES
<p>
This area of the law of relational economic loss in the maritime context is perhaps the most complex of all. On one side, the spectre of indeterminate liability that has been a factor in every economic loss decision is front and centre as a consideration. Yet this area has been the focus of recent decisions which have presented a large number of arguments supporting relief from the exclusionary rule in this situation. Particularly, <cite>Norsk</cite> and <cite>Caltex</cite>, two of the most prominent recent decisions in this entire area of economic loss, have awarded recovery in blocking case situations. Furthermore, the importance of understanding what is happening in this debate and where it is going has an urgency beyond simply resolving a conflict at common law. Blocking situations represent potentially the greatest liability situation possible at maritime law, and all parties involved on a practical level need to know their potential liability in terms of the economic losses they can generate.
<p>
In simple terms, blocking claims arise when the defendant's alleged negligence impedes the freedom of movement and/or travel of the plaintiff's property, causing the plaintiff economic losses. There are a number of manifestations of this situation. The most commonly litigated cases, which also cause the biggest problem in terms of theory, are cases where the negligence of the defendant actually blocks a waterway, restricting the traffic of other vessels past the point of the accident. The traffic impeded need not be maritime travel. The so-called `bridge cases' such as <cite>Norsk</cite>, where a vessel damages a bridge used by other modes of transportation, are also blocking cases. So is <cite>Caltex</cite>, where the flow of oil through a pipeline was disrupted.
<p>
<i>England and the U.S.</i><br>
England has had an uncharacteristically quiet history of decisions in these cases. The only reported decisions are of lower courts; as such there is no leading English case to examine as a statement of the law in that country. However, the consistency of the approach of the decided cases, as well as the approach to the issue taken by higher English courts in other areas of relational economic loss, leave little doubt as to which side of the exclusionary rule debate the Appeal Courts or the House of Lords would come down on in this debate. <cite>The Anglo-Algerian S.S. v. Holder</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> and <cite>The Maindy Manor</cite><sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> are two of the reported lower court decisions. In <cite>Anglo-Algerian</cite>, the
defendant's ship damaged a series of canal locks; the plaintiff's ship arrived and was delayed two and a half days while repairs were effected. The court refused to grant a claim for losses suffered as a result of this delay, on the grounds that the defendant owed a duty to no one but the owner of the property. Similarly, in <cite>The Maindy Manor</cite> a river was blocked by the negligent grounding of the defendant's ship; again claims for losses by those ships which were delayed until the ship could be removed were denied.
<p>
The U.S. has arrived at essentially the same position in its doctrine, but on the basis of a large number of decided cases. This is due to the U.S. courts having been extremely consistent in denying blocking case claims on the basis of <cite>Robins</cite>. Recent cases continue to invoke this rule. For example, in <cite>General Foods v. U.S.</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup> a regular bridge user's claim for costs incurred when the bridge was damaged was denied. A similar claim for lost wages by railway employees who lost work hours due to rerouting around a bridge damaged by the defendant's negligence was also denied in <cite>The Northern King</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> In <cite>The Testbank</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> the majority of the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal recognized that the plaintiff may indeed have been reasonably foreseeable, but stated that this was irrelevant as <cite>Robins</cite> denied recovery in any circumstance.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup>
<p>
There are signs, however, that even U.S. courts are beginning to have second thoughts about the application of <cite>Robins</cite> in this area. The first such sign was the decision of the Second Circuit Court of Appeal in <cite>Re Kinsman Transit Co.</cite>,<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> known as <cite>Kinsman II</cite>. The claims arose when a negligently moored ship freed itself from its moorings during a winter storm. It collided with and freed another ship; both ships then drifted down river to collide with a drawbridge in the city of
Buffalo. The effect was to block the river with ice, causing extensive flooding upstream. The <cite>Kinsman I</cite><sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> consisted of claims for physical damages which were allowed against the defendant as being reasonably foreseeable.
<p>
The <cite>Kinsman II</cite> case consisted of claims for economic loss, including two claims by shippers who were delayed as a result of the blockage of the river. One vessel had been prevented from making a delivery upriver from the blockage and claimed for costs incurred in finding alternate sources of supply for its customer; the other had been delayed in loading operations by the ice caused by the blockage. The trial judge denied both claims on the basis of <cite>Robins</cite>. The Court of Appeal agreed with the result, but held that a tort analysis was preferable to the exclusionary rule in these circumstances. On this analysis, the two claims still failed, but only because they
were held to have been too remote.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup>
<p>
The reasoning in the <cite>Kinsman II</cite> decision has had far-reaching implications for the theory of relational economic loss in the U.S.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> Other circuit courts of appeal have expressly adopted its reasoning as their method for analysis in a number of cases.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> It was also relied on in the dissenting opinion of Wisdom J. in <cite>The Testbank</cite>; the contrasting judgments in that case have been referred to as the starting point for any understanding of the current debate over <cite>Robins</cite> in American law.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup>
<p>
One must conclude, therefore, that both England and the U.S. can be relied upon to continue the application of the <cite>Cattle</cite> and <cite>Robins</cite> principles in the near future. While the U.S. may be showing some signs of weakening in this position and adopting instead a tort-based analysis of economic losses in blocking cases, this has yet to achieve broad and regular acceptance as overruling <cite>Robins</cite>. The relative certainty in the position of both jurisdictions is in sharp contrast with the current situation in Australia and Canada.
<p>
<i>Australia and Canada</i><br>
The law regarding blocking cases in both Australia and Canada currently suffers from the difficulty that recent high court decisions in the area have provided little definite direction to parties wanting to understand their potential liability. As was discussed above, both <cite>Caltex</cite> and <cite>Norsk</cite> are blocking cases; the reasoning in these cases is therefore directly relevant to this area of the law. But as was also noted above, neither case provides definitive guidelines for analyzing economic loss situations. The only certainty as a result of these decisions is that in blocking cases, both jurisdictions appear to be perfectly willing to reject the exclusionary rule and examine individual situations on the basis of tort analysis to determine liability. Concentrating on Canadian jurisprudence prior to <cite>Norsk</cite>, it can be seen that this recent position is not a dramatic change from that of previous decisions. In fact, Canadian courts appear to have been much more open to avoiding the exclusionary rule in these circumstances as they have been in, for example, charterparty cases. Given the limited blocking situation in <cite>Norsk</cite>, however, how far will its reasoning be extended in subsequent decisions?
<p>
The major Canadian blocking cases prior to <cite>Norsk</cite> have already been discussed in detail above, as such cases have been among the few maritime relational economic loss cases decided in Canada. These cases are <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite>,<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> <cite>Bethlehem Steel</cite>,<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> and <cite>The Atlantic Splendour</cite>.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup> <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite> was a similar case to <cite>Norsk</cite>. Railway traffic had been blocked by a damaged bridge. The court held that the appropriate approach was one based on duty and reasonable foreseeability, not strict exclusion of liability. While recovery was still rejected in that case, it was due
to a lack of proximity. In <cite>Bethlehem Steel</cite>, the situation was a more conventional blocking case in that the defendant blocked a waterway and the claims were for economic damages to other vessels delayed as a result. The court in that case took a much harder line against applying an exception to the exclusionary rule in blocking
cases, stating that this was not an area for such an exception. The tort analysis was again used in <cite>The Atlantic Splendour</cite>, however, and it was on this test that recovery was permitted. While this case may be unique from a tort perspective in that it involved a continuous act of blocking over 17 days with the plaintiffs' vessel standing by, it still represents a departure from the exclusionary rule.
<p>
<cite>Norsk</cite>, therefore, was decided against a backdrop of already confusing jurisprudence on this issue, and <cite>Norsk</cite> did not help to resolve the situation. The majority judgment accepted the need for exceptions to the exclusionary rule in these cases, and affirmed the use of tort principles to determine liability for economic loss. It cannot be ignored, however, that the majority imposed on the analysis policy considerations against recovery as set out under the second branch of the test in <cite>Anns</cite> and <cite>Nielson</cite>. In addition, the eventual decision to award recovery in the case rested on the extreme proximity of the plaintiff and the injured property; they
were held to have constituted a `common adventure.' The facts of the case were also distinguishable from those of the waterway blocking cases involving a large number of plaintiffs, such as <cite>Bethlehem Steel</cite>. Finally, the strong dissent on the part of La Forest J. suggests that a similar case might receive different treatment if it came before a slightly different court.
<p>
In the end, <cite>Norsk</cite> only drives the Canadian law deeper into uncertainty. The `common adventure' reasoning of the majority makes it doubtful that plaintiffs in blocking cases such as <cite>Bethlehem Steel</cite> would have a stronger chance of recovery, as most blocking cases are comprised of plaintiffs with no interest whatever in property the defendant has damaged. In fact, on its reasoning, <cite>Norsk</cite> does not even directly contradict <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite>, in that none of the railways in that case appear to have had the
relationship with the bridge that the court would now  require. Yet, it does reject the exclusionary rule against economic losses, opting instead for a case-by-case approach. In Canada, then, a claimant for relational economic losses caused by blocking can expect to have to satisfy an easier test than a similar claimant in England or the
U.S., but only marginally so; the principles of duty, proximity, and reasonable foreseeability are likely to be applied with extremely high thresholds.
<p>
<i>Analysis</i><br>
It is difficult to criticize the court's concern for indeterminate liability in cases such as these; the possible number
of parties affected by a blockage of the St. Lawrence Seaway, for example, could hardly be more indeterminate. Moreover, if the practice of awarding damages in individual claims were to become prevalent, the number of such claimants could be expected to increase exponentially in comparison to the number of claimants seen in the
current cases.
<p>
It may very well be that the correct policy decision to avoid these situations is to apply the exclusionary rule against all such claims. This would provide certainty of liability to all parties involved, who could then make provision against the potential for such losses. The cost of this approach, however, can be injustice to the plaintiff in the individual action. The major difficulty with a rule excluding recovery for all claims is the desire of individual courts to get around the rule to prevent injustices in their decisions.
<p.
There are possible alternatives. One alternative would be distinguishing between the different varieties of blocking cases. As shown, the situation in <cite>Norsk</cite> and <cite>Caltex</cite> is much different from <cite>Kinsman II</cite>, for example, especially in terms of the possibility for indeterminate liability. Perhaps it would be possible to differentiate between the two situations, with the exclusionary rule applying only to the latter. The difficulty would, of course, be establishing the parameters for such a distinction. The physical differences between the location of the potential plaintiffs would not suffice. While the `bridge cases' of <cite>Norsk</cite> and <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite> involved a small defined set of potential claimants in the users of the damaged bridge, it would be equally possible for a busy highway bridge to be damaged in the same way; the number of potential claimants could possibly exceed even those of the seaway blocking cases. Instead, perhaps the number of potential claimants itself could be the key; where they are contained in a small defined set, such as railway bridge users, the exclusionary rule should be avoided.
<p>
Yet a closer examination of the jurisprudence on blocking cases reveals that special alternate theories or approaches may be entirely unnecessary. Instead, the solution may be to abandon the exclusionary rule altogether in all blocking cases, in favour of general application of negligence doctrines. The recent trend towards a tort analysis for blocking cases appears to hold promise as a viable alternative to the exclusionary rule. Despite a number of decisions applying standards of duty, foreseeability, and proximity to blocking cases, there has been no opening of the floodgates to liability. Instead, the approach of the courts has been to set the thresholds for these tests at such a high level that potential liability is restricted to reasonable limits. Cases such as <cite>Kinsman II</cite> and <cite>Gypsum Carrier</cite> demonstrate that a relaxation of the exclusionary rule in favour of a tort analysis will often create the same result as if the exclusionary rule still applied.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> It does, however, give the courts the flexibility to address perceived injustices. This flexibility simply does not exist under a strict rule against recovery.
<p>
On this approach, there would only be two areas for concern, both of which are not unique to blocking cases: the loss of certainty provided by the exclusionary rule; and the determination of the exact threshold for the negligence doctrines of proximity or foreseeability. Both of these issues are common to all of the areas of maritime economic loss which this article has addressed; their treatment will therefore be left to the conclusion.
<p>
<h3>IV.  The Not-So-Limited Significance of Limited Liability</h3>

IV.1   INTRODUCTION
<p>
Up to this point, relational economic loss and maritime law have been discussed in terms of the initial establishment of liability in tortfeasors. It has been argued that instead of blindly applying the exclusionary rule against liability for relational economic loss damages, the rule can be relaxed in certain situations on the basis of considerations unique to maritime law. Liability may instead be determined on a case-by-case basis with the standard for recovery being determined by a form of negligence analysis, as if the damages experienced had been related to physical or personal injuries and not solely economic losses. The result would be that a tortfeasor would be liable for the damage actually done by his or her act, and would not be able to escape liability solely on the basis of the nature of the relationship between the parties to which he or she has caused losses.
<p>
In making this argument, it has been assumed for simplicity that a tortfeasor would be liable in full for whatever damages were awarded by the courts. This assumption is in fact the basis of Cardozo C.J.'s fear of indeterminate liability, one of the driving factors behind the exclusionary rule. In any other sphere of the common law this
would indeed be the case: the liability of the tortfeasor is limited only by the size of the damage awards permitted by the court. It is on this point that the common law and maritime law differ in dramatic fashion. One of the unique features of maritime law is that it gives certain defendants, including shipowners, the ability to limit their liability.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> The implication of this feature is that, apart from the arguments explored above, it raises serious questions about the justification for a rule excluding recovery for relational economic loss in maritime law.
<p>
IV.2   HISTORY OF LIMITED LIABILITY
<p>
The concept of limiting the liability of shipowners for the actions of their vessels is hundreds of years old.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup> Its widespread adoption in Europe originated in the desire to promote shipping and
the investment in ships during the colonial periods of the European powers. It was deemed to be unfair to shipowners, and therefore bad for the shipping business, that shipowners could be held liable in tort for any and all damages his ship may negligently cause on its voyages. The unfairness stemmed from the fact that the negligence
would most often be caused by the crew of the ship and not by the shipowner personally; yet the latter would be liable for all damages. These damages could easily result in the bankruptcy of the shipowners.<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> To make investment in owning and operating ships attractive, it was therefore necessary to do something to reduce this unpredictable and sizable risk. To deal with this problem, European countries quickly moved to adopt a system for limiting liability for shipowners. In 1733, England passed legislation which limited liability in certain situations; but it was not until the 19th century that this protection was extended to liability created by collisions.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> 
<p>
In modern times, this principle has been retained as a matter of convenience. Modern communication technology now means that shipowners no longer send ships to sea without any control whatsoever over their activities. As well, the countries which originally passed such legislation are no longer concerned with encouraging ship
building as a function of empire-building. The driving force behind the retention of the concept of limited liability has been the convenience of the rule in the insurance market. The attractiveness of the system of limited liability to shipowners and their insurers is that the total potential liability of a vessel can be calculated by the parties in advance. This arrangement permits the parties to have some certainty regarding the risk involved in insuring the
vessel.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> Without such certainty, the process of obtaining insurance for a vessel would unquestionably be more difficult and less efficient. It is these practical considerations in the efficient operation of the world maritime insurance market which have been the motivation behind a number of international conventions limiting liability of shipowners in negligence,<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> including
the <cite>International Convention for the Unification of Certain Rules Relating to the Limitation of Liability of Owners of Seagoing Vessels</cite>,<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup> the <cite>International Convention Relating to the Limitation of Liability of Owners of Seagoing Ships</cite>,<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> and the <cite>1976 Convention on Limitation of Liability for Maritime Claims</cite>.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> 
<p>
These conventions set out a system for determining who has access to the ability to limit losses, when this right can be exercised, and how the limitation amount is calculated and distributed. For years the 1957 Convention set these standards globally: most maritime nations, including Canada, were signatories (Canada has not ratified the Convention but has instead given effect to its provisions through amendments to the Canada <cite>Shipping Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup>). Under this Convention, shipowners are able to limit liability for damages in tort or contract if they can establish that the act in question occurred without the owner's `actual fault or privity.'<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> If the shipowner is successful, their total potential liability is limited to a maximum amount. Any and all claims for damages are then paid out of this amount: if the aggregate claims exceed this total, the claims are paid on a pro rated basis. Two such limitation amounts are calculated. The first amount relates to damages from loss of life or personal injury. The second amount relates to damages arising from damage to property. The basis for these calculations is the gross tonnage of the shipowner's vessel: the larger the vessel, the greater the shipowner's liability before it can benefit from any limitation. The formula for calculating the exact amount of liability is extremely complex; the end result in Canada under the <cite>Shipping Act</cite> is a maximum liability for loss of life and personal injury of $310 per ton, and a maximum liability for property  damage of $100 per ton.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup>
<p>
Up to the middle of this century, liability for damages was readily awarded by common law courts around the world. Plaintiffs faced an `almost impossible task' of showing the necessary level of owner involvement to avoid limited liability.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> Extreme results in a number of decisions at that time, however, began to change attitudes. Courts in England and Canada became much more reluctant to grant limited liability to shipowners.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> In fact, Canadian jurisprudence took a dramatic enough dislike to limited liability that it could be argued the doctrine was dead in Canada.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup>
<p>
One of the reasons put forward for this reluctance was the perception that the amounts set under the 1957 Convention were too low. The trend in the jurisprudence away from limited liability exerted pressure within the industry to revise the standards in its availability and calculation. The result of this pressure was the 1976 Convention noted above. Under this convention a new balance between liability and limitation was struck.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> Article 4 provides that limitation of liability is now only unavailable where the losses can be proven to have resulted from the personal act or omission of the shipowner, committed either with the intention to cause the loss or recklessly with the knowledge that the loss may occur. The result is that it is now much easier for defendants to benefit from limited liability.<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup> For the benefits of plaintiffs, however, the threshold for limitation of liability is now much higher.<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> While neither Canada not the U.S. are signatories to this 1976 Convention and have not
adopted its terms, there are indications that Canada may do so before the turn of the century.<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup>
<p>
IV.3   LIMITATION OF LIABILITY AND RELATIONAL ECONOMIC LOSS
<p>
In the context of economic loss, the availability of limited liability immediately raises an important question: what
purpose is served by applying an exclusionary rule against such losses?  As has been discussed above a number of times, the <cite>Cattle</cite> principle of excluding economic loss was founded on the principle of avoiding liability of the defendant to an indeterminate number of parties for an indeterminate amount because of a single act
of negligence. Yet if shipowners and other defendants in maritime economic loss cases have the potential to limit their liability through other statutorily-approved means, the principal reason for the exclusionary rule disappears. People with statutorily limited liability have no need for a protection against unlimited liability. In other words, application of the exclusionary rule to relational economic loss claims in maritime law against shipowners is a
duplication of protection. Even if the exclusionary rule is removed and replaced with a negligence standard which applied no stricter test to economic losses than to physical or personal losses, shipowners will in most circumstances never suffer exposure to Cardozo C.J.'s `indeterminate liability.' Their total liability instead will be fixed and determinable ahead of time, meaning most importantly that they will still have full access to insurance for
their losses.
<p>
Surprisingly, this factor has received little consideration in the jurisprudence. Despite the fact that the cases focus on negligence and the recovery of damages, the cases rarely spend much, if any, time discussing the fact that the defendant shipowner most likely has access to the protection of limited liability.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> Even in the larger cases, the presence of limited liability means that awarding complete
recovery for all property and relational economic loss damage claims would only result in a right to a <i>pro rata</i> portion of a fund. It would have no effect upon the total liability of the defendant. It might be expected that this fact would alleviate court fears of indeterminate liability, as it quite simply prevents the shipowner from ever being so exposed. 
<p>
There are, however, a number of possible explanations for this failure to consider limited liability. Most cases focus upon the establishment of the initial liability, which is most often refused; therefore the question of whether the defendant would have access to limited liability never arises. In addition, it may simply be recognized by all the parties involved that any recovery will only be a portion of what is being claimed and, as such, it is not an issue
between them at trial. In other circumstances, there may be sufficient resources in the liability fund to cover the economic losses claimed. Finally, in Canada and the U.S. at least, where the 1976 Convention has not been adopted, the courts have recently made it increasingly difficult for shipowners to qualify for limited liability; therefore it may not be a factor in most cases at all.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup>
<p>
There may be another justifiable reason for not awarding economic loss damages even in the presence of limited liability. Not awarding such damages may be required to protect claimants for physical damages against having their recovery reduced, perhaps significantly, if claims for economic loss were permitted to rank with them in the distribution of the limited liability fund. The more claims allowed against the liability fund of a shipowner, the lower the amount that each claimant takes on a <i>pro rata</i> basis. Wholesale permission of economic loss claims has the potential to substantially reduce the recovery of the owners of the property with which the action originated. If these parties are prevented from recovering sufficient amounts to pay for repairs to the property damaged, and those repairs are delayed or foregone as a result, then the economic loss damages caused by the accident would only be exacerbated. It may therefore be in the interest of all parties to permit at least particular property claimants to recover as much of their damages as possible. Yet there are two points on which to question this approach. The first is that it characterizes economic loss claims as secondary or subservient to those for physical damage, an idea which is not supported in the jurisprudence. Secondly, granting every kind of claim equal standing with in relation to the liability fund results in a situation which is no different from other areas of the law where the assets available do not satisfy all the judgments against a defendant.
<p>
The shipowners' access to limited liability raises issues in economic loss which are faced only in maritime law. By providing a ceiling on the total liability payable by a defendant, limited liability appears in many ways to duplicate the protection provided by the exclusionary rule against the recovery in economic loss developed at common law.
By doing so, it provides another reason for arguing that, at the least, the protections of the exclusionary rule can be relaxed in maritime law.
<p>
<h3>V.  Conclusion</h3>

Until relatively recently, any party suffering economic loss enjoyed a state of relative certainty regarding their prospects of recovery: there were no such prospects at common law. All common law jurisdictions applied the exclusionary rule against such losses, alternatively formulated in <cite>Cattle</cite> or <cite>Robins</cite>, with
strict regularity. Their main motivating factor was the avoidance of indeterminable liability for huge numbers of claims which could theoretically arise from the same transaction. The strict application of the exclusionary rule provided, at least in theory, the parties who would be susceptible to such losses with the motivation to protect themselves against the losses, through vehicles such as insurance.
<p>
The cost of this certainty, however, was the injustice it could create in individual cases, or in certain situations. As we have seen, the situations of time and voyage charterers, other third parties contractually related to a vessel, and those affected by the blocking of transportation routes all have varying potential to render the application of the exclusionary rule unjust to those suffering the loss. This injustice in the application of the global rule to individual situations has been the motivation for courts to attempt to avoid the rule and to seek alternatives on a case-by-case
basis. As a result, one of the major difficulties with the exclusionary rule has been inconsistency in its general application by courts who do not like its particular results>

In searching for these alternatives, courts in the U.S., Canada, and Australia have discovered that it is possible to abandon the exclusionary rule without opening the floodgates to indeterminate liability. Instead of strictly disallowing liability, these courts have been gradually and nominally adopting the same standards for assessing liability for relational economic damages as for physical damages in negligence: duty, foreseeability, and proximity.
Admittedly, these courts and others have only been able to agree that different or modified standards of these tests need to be applied to maintain the balance between recovery and indeterminate liability. As yet, they have not been able to formulate a threshold test which has gained approval by even a slim majority of judges. Yet this does not
mean that such a test does not exist, and even if one is never found, it may simply indicate that there should be different tests for different fact situations. It is not appropriate, however, to `throw the baby out with the bath water' as the House of Lords attempted to do in <cite>Murphy</cite>, by attempting to end the debate with a strict reversion to the exclusionary rule. 
<p>
In any other area of the common law, the relaxation of the exclusionary rule would result in dramatically increased uncertainty about the liability generated from any given act of negligence. Even if high thresholds for the elements of negligence were introduced, to protect the defendant from being unfairly victimized as a result of others' losses, this liability could still be extensive and unpredictable. In maritime law, access to limited liability alleviates this problem. It separates the liability actually proven against the defendant from the amount that the defendant will
actually have to pay. The latter is the only concern of the maritime law defendant once the limitation threshold has been reached. After that point, further findings of liability only determine the number of parties who have access to that limitation amount. The advantage of the system is that this amount will still be determinable ahead of time with the same certainty as it is today, making insurance equally determinable. Removing the exclusionary rule will therefore not cause the defendant to suffer increased financial uncertainty regarding the liability for damages. Instead, the uncertainty will relate to the size of the share of this fund collected by claimants who would have no recovery under the exclusionary rule. 
<p>
In conclusion, the maritime context presents enough unique considerations to justify reconsidering the application of the common law bar to recovery of economic losses in this context. Yet it is apparent that the problems and issues posed by economic loss in the maritime context will not be resolved quickly by anything short of the establishment of an international convention and subsequent adoption of its rules by all common law countries. While legislation on the topic in individual jurisdictions may at least improve certainty in the area, it will most likely only confuse the marine operator regularly operating between such jurisdictions. As it stands now, marine operators still generally expect not to recover for claims for economic losses in the U.S., England, Canada, or Australia. The chance of success is greater now than it was a decade ago, however, especially in the latter two countries, and it may be that in the near future we will see recovery for relational economic losses become a regular occurrence in maritime law.
<p><br>
<hr><p>
