<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h2>Fraud, the Consumer, and the Banks: The (un-) Regulation of Electronic Funds Transfer<p>
ROBERT HAYHOE</H2>
<center><h3>ABSTRACT / <a  href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/utlr53-2/hayhoe.htm">Fulltext</a></h3></center>
<p>
Consumer electronic funds transfer is increasingly important. Despite assurances to the contrary by financial
institutions, the risk of fraud is genuine.  In Canada, this risk is entirely on the customer.  Due to the small amounts involved, the common law does not provide a useful remedy.  This comment examines the solutions attempted in the United States and Australia.  While the substance of the two solutions is similar and both produce an acceptable result, the Australian `soft law' approach would be preferable in Canada.
<p>
Le virement bancaire &eacute;l&eacute;ctronique devient de plus en plus utilis&eacute;.  Malgr&eacute; les assurances qu'il soit une m&eacute;thode de paiement s&ucirc;r, il y existe un risque de fraude consid&eacute;rable.  Ce risque est port&eacute; enti&egrave;rement par le consommateur canadien. Les recours connus &agrave; la &quot;common law&quot; ne sont pas realistes &agrave; cause des montants inconsid&eacute;rables d&eacute;fraud&eacute;s.  L'auteur pr&eacute;sente les solutions invent&eacute;es aux &Eacute;tats-Unis et en Australie. Bien qu'il y a une similarit&eacute; entre l'essentiel des deux solutions, l'auteur indique que l'approche australien sera plus convenable au contexte canadien.
<p>
<hr>
