<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 53 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1>Comments</h1>
<h2>Fraud, the Consumer, and the Banks: The (un-) Regulation of Electronic Funds Transfer<p>
ROBERT HAYHOE<a href="#note">*</a></H2>

<i>Consumer electronic funds transfer is increasingly important. Despite assurances to the contrary by financial
institutions, the risk of fraud is genuine. In Canada, this risk is entirely on the customer. Due to the small amounts involved, the common law does not provide a useful remedy. This comment examines the solutions attempted in the United States and Australia. While the substance of the two solutions is similar and both produce an acceptable result, the Australian `soft law' approach would be preferable in Canada.
<p>
Le virement bancaire &eacute;l&eacute;ctronique devient de plus en plus utilis&eacute;. Malgr&eacute; les assurances qu'il soit une m&eacute;thode de paiement s&ucirc;r, il y existe un risque de fraude consid&eacute;rable. Ce risque est port&eacute; enti&egrave;rement par le consommateur canadien. Les recours connus &agrave; la &quot;common law&quot; ne sont pas realistes &agrave; cause des montants inconsid&eacute;rables d&eacute;fraud&eacute;s. L'auteur pr&eacute;sente les solutions invent&eacute;es aux &Eacute;tats-Unis et en Australie. Bien qu'il y a une similarit&eacute; entre l'essentiel des deux solutions, l'auteur indique que l'approche australien sera plus convenable au contexte canadien.</i>
<p>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

Point of sale electronic funds transfer (EFT-POS) transactions are an increasingly popular means of consumer payment in Canada.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> Similarly, automated teller machines (ATMs) are now widely used.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> While the volume of consumer electronic funds transfer (EFT) transactions does not yet rival the volume of cheque transactions,<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> the moment is approaching. However, despite the convenience and efficiency of EFT, under the present legal framework the consumer might well be advised to be wary of the use of it. 
<p>
It will be shown that there is a clear need for regulation of risk allocation in cases of consumer EFT fraud in Canada. While the common law appears inadequate to the task, there are several possible models for the regulation of EFT. Keeping the two goals of a secure banking system and an efficient amount of loss compensation in mind, this paper looks at the solutions attempted in both the United States and Australia before moving to a brief analysis of which approach is more suited to the Canadian situation.
<p>
<h3>Cheque Fraud</h3>

Before examining EFT fraud, it is appropriate to gloss over the corresponding situation with respect to cheques. There are two basic types of forgeries which can be performed with cheques. These are alterations to the body of the cheque, such as an increase in the amount payable or a change in the name of the payee, and forged signatures. The signature forged can be that of the drawer or can be an endorsement. For the purposes of comparison, only the
forgery of the drawer's signature is relevant.
<p>
Cheques, as a means of payment, are regulated by the <cite>Bills of Exchange Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> The general rule under the <cite>Act</cite> is that the bank bears the risk of fraud. Section 49(1) of the <cite>Act</cite> is designed to protect the purported drawer from forgery and provides that a forged signature is wholly inoperative. Later subsections modify this slightly by requiring notice of the forgery within one year and by permitting ratification of an unauthorized signature which does not amount to a forgery.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> Thus, when a customer's signature is forged on a cheque, subject to the requirement of reasonable notice and the common law estoppel which may operate against the customer by virtue of his negligence,
the bank<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> bears the risk and is not entitled to debit the customer's account.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>EFT Fraud</h3>

By contrast, consumer EFT is largely unregulated in Canada. The rights and responsibilities of the parties are subject only to the contract between them. The result is that the risk of fraud and forgery rests almost entirely on the consumer.
<p>
EFT fraud is surprisingly simple. The most common scheme runs as follows. The criminal waits in a vehicle or at some other vantage point near an ATM and observes (perhaps through binoculars) the bank customer entering the PIN. Alternatively, a video camera could be located near the ATM. The criminal records the PIN. If at the end
of the transaction, the customer drops the printed transaction receipt to the ground, the criminal notes the time and picks up the accumulated transactions records a short time later. This receipt will record the time and may, depending on bank policy, record the card number and the account balance. If the card number is recorded on the slip, the technology to encode cards is relatively simple; given the card number, a sophisticated criminal can easily obtain an encoded card. Having obtained a number of `forged' cards and their corresponding PINs, the criminal is free to proceed with the actual fraud. This is usually done over a long weekend, when the account holder is less likely to detect the fraud. Subject to the daily withdrawal limit, the criminal and his associates then proceed to
empty a number of accounts. By the first business day following the long weekend, when presumably the fraud is detected, the criminals are generally in another country, beyond the effective reach of Canadian criminal law.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> In England, several other variations have been reported. Thieves have built dummy fronts to cover the PIN keyboard, allowing recording of the PIN. There are even records of dummy ATM machines being built and designed to keep the card and record the PIN attempted.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup>
<p>
It may also be possible to penetrate the system electronically. There are no publicly recorded instances of success, but one must question if the banks might be tempted to handle such a breach of security internally, in view of the possible negative consequences of the adverse publicity. Michael Oke, a bank security expert, stated in 1989 that &quot;(t)he potential for large scale frauds is significant and will become enormous when global funds transfer and retail EFT/point of sale systems become widespread.&quot;<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> Both of these are now a reality. The solution to this danger is advanced computer encryption, a subject outside the current legal
analysis.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup>
<p>
While the above discussion deals primarily with fraud related to ATM cash machines, the problem is only exacerbated with relation to EFT-POS transactions. While ATM user etiquette demands a certain distance between customers in a line (thus minimizing the opportunity to view another customer's PIN), no such distance is possible in the typical EFT-POS transaction. The retail clerk is often close enough to see the customer entering the PIN. The clerk also has temporary access to the customer's card, allowing the card number to be viewed and memorized. The store employee could then obtain a forged card and use it in the manner outlined above, either at an ATM or in
fraudulent EFT-POS transactions. 
<p>
EFT-POS also makes electronic fraud easier. The physical security of an ATM is generally high, making it difficult to tap into the proper communication lines. By contrast, the typical EFT-POS terminal is composed of a card reader and PIN keypad wired to a base unit by exposed telephone cable. It would be a simple matter for a computer-literate criminal to tap the telephone cable and obtain the required information from a wiretap under the counter of the sales desk.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>The Relative Difficulty of Cheque and EFT Fraud</h3>

Having examined some of the types of fraud which can be perpetrated with cheques and with ATMs, let us now examine the relative difficulty. Cheque fraud requires a blank cheque, either stolen from the customer or forged. At one time, a signature sample of the drawer was required, but the present clearing system, where the drawee bank is likely to provisionally pay on the cheque without ever comparing it to a signature sample,<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> reduces the requirement for a signature sample. The most common form of EFT-POS fraud requires only the ATM receipt and an opportunity to view the PIN being entered. Some equipment is also
needed to duplicate the card. The conclusion to be drawn from this comparison is that cheque fraud is relatively easy to perform on a small scale, while electronic fraud requires a larger amount of technology and organization. 
<p>
However, banks today generally practice conservative banking practices to reduce cheque fraud (holding a cheque depositor's funds, only cashing cheques for customers, etc.) in order to reduce the amount of fraud which is successful. One reason why banks take these precautions is that the <cite>Bills of Exchange Act</cite> puts
almost all of the risk of cheque forgery on the bank. The bank, as a profit-maximizing enterprise, is motivated to reduce the amount of cheque fraud because it alone bears the cost.
<p>
<h3>Canadian Legislation Dealing with EFT Fraud</h3>

In the case of EFT fraud, there is no federal statutory allocation of the losses from fraud,<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> although there is some provincial legislation. Using British Columbia as an example,
there is the <cite>Consumer Protection Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> which at one
time was assumed by lawyers to apply to some EFT transactions. In the case of theft or loss of a credit card, s. 31 of the <cite>Act</cite> limits the liability of the card holder to fifty dollars for any unauthorized transactions prior to notification of the issuer, and excuses the holder entirely from liability for any unauthorized transactions entered into after the issuer has been notified. &quot;Credit card&quot; is defined in the act to be:
<blockquote>
a card, document or similar instrument, or a replacement or renewal of any of them, by which on a continuing basis and from time to time goods and services or credit may be obtained on deferred payment, or by any means of which cash may be obtained, whether or not there is any cost of borrowing or default charge for the credit or cash.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This definition would appear to cover ATM and EFT-POS transactions.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> However, the former British Columbia County Court considered just this issue in <cite>Plater v. Bank of Montreal</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> In that case, the customer lost his wallet which contained both his Master Card and PIN. The Master Card had arrived unsolicited. Before he had the opportunity to notify the bank, several cash advances were obtained using ATMs. In a decision almost devoid of analysis, the court considered the application of the <cite>Consumer Protection Act</cite> and decided that: &quot;[t]he use (and misuse) of the credit card-PIN combination is an operation separate and distinct from the use of the credit card alone to obtain goods or services, or cash advances . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> and that, as a result, s. 31 of the <cite>Act</cite> was not applicable to EFT. The court proceeded to apply the liability provision of the cardholder agreement. In doing so, the court relied on <cite>Villemure v. Master Card (Division Banque de Montreal)</cite><sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> where the court declined to apply the Quebec equivalent of the <cite>Consumer Protection Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup>
<p>
Even if the <cite>Act</cite> were changed in an attempt to make it clearly applicable to consumer EFT transactions, there remains a constitutional issue. In so far as the Act might be applied to ATM transactions, it is probably <i>ultra vires</i> the province. The power to regulate banking is an exclusively federal power.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> The federal government was also given the power to regulate all of the payment
mechanisms in existence at the time of Confederation.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> A broad and purposive reading of the Constitution would extend these powers to the regulation of new payment modes.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> While the provincial power to regulate creditor-debtor relationships could be used to permit some provincial legislation in the area, federal law would be paramount.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> It might be argued that federal regulation would not apply to provincial institutions like credit unions or trust companies, but this is a confusion of the financial institution and the payment system within which the institution operates.
<p>
<h3>The Common Law of EFT Fraud</h3>

In the absence of federal regulation, the rights of the parties are left to the common law and are covered by the contract between the bank and the customer. As one might expect from standard form or adhesion contracts,<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> these allocate the risk to the customer. The most common provision is one which makes the customer liable for all unauthorized withdrawals made before the notification of the bank.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> In practice, this means that the customer is liable for the full amount of his bank balance, plus any overdraft facilities, as the criminal in the scheme outlined above would be able to empty the account over the long weekend before the customer would even be aware of the use of the forged card. The only possible mitigating factor for the customer would be the possibility that the bank might be willing to absorb the loss in the interest of good customer relations.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> It might be expected that this would most often occur if the client was a long-term client with substantial dealings with the bank. The banks certainly can be expected to rely on their legal rights and remedies in a large number of cases of unauthorized transactions.
<p>
Faced with the institution's refusal to make good her loss or its insistence that she repay the unauthorized overdraft, the customer will have to fall back on her common law rights. There are several general problems with relying on the common law in these types of situations. The first difficulty stems from the sums of money involved. Since few people keep more than a few thousand dollars in their current account and banks generally have withdrawal limits on ATM or EFT-POS transactions, any individual's loss from consumer EFT fraud is likely to be small. This means
that the consumer is unlikely to be able to retain counsel for an amount commensurate with the possible recovery. As a result, the consumer will have to present her own case. In view of the common law rules to be discussed, a consumer faced with counsel from the bank would be in a difficult position. 
<p>
Another problem is that these amounts place the case within the monetary jurisdiction of the small claims court in most jurisdictions.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> With respect, many small claims judges have limited exposure to banking and commercial law matters and rely on counsel to provide guidance. In the absence of counsel for the customer, the only guidance will come from counsel for the financial institution---hardly the ideal from the customer's perspective. The small claims court jurisdiction will generally also result in the decision not being reported. This means that a body of precedent will not develop, leaving each successive case to be built on first principles.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> There are also some difficult problems of evidence. When the bank controls all of the documentary evidence of the relevant transactions, it is very difficult for the litigant customer to do any more than assert that he did not make the impugned withdrawal.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> While this problem could be avoided by the proper use of discovery and interrogatories<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup>, one must question the ability of a lay litigant to use these devices.
<p>
The second problem arises from the scope of actual common law remedies available. For ease of analysis, assume that the fraud complained of was perpetrated using a card number governed by the Bank of Nova Scotia Cashstop/Transaction Cardholder Agreement. While terms may vary from institution to institution, this agreement
is broadly representative of those used by other banks. In the event of any fraudulent use of the card, the bank will rely on clause 9 of the agreement to shift all of the liability to the card holder. This clause provides that:
<blockquote>
You are liable for all indebtedness, withdrawals and account activity resulting from your use of the card including all indebtedness, withdrawals and account activity by persons to whom you have made the card and/or PIN available. You are liable for all unauthorized use of the Card and/or PIN (including indebtedness, withdrawals and account activity arising from unauthorized use of the Card and PIN where the Card and the PIN have been kept together or in such a manner as to make them available for use together) until we have received notice of loss, theft or unauthorized use. You will notify us immediately of the loss, theft or any unauthorized use of the Card or the PIN. Your liability will cease only when notice of loss, theft or unauthorized use is received by us.
</blockquote>
If a court upholds this clause, the customer is liable for any unauthorized withdrawals. It might be possible to attack the whole agreement on the basis of non-disclosure or unconscionability.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> Although the applicant signs that he has received the agreement, this is not necessarily the case. If the customer is prepared to swear that he was never given the agreement,<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> a court might be willing to decline to apply the clause under the <i>non est factum</i> doctrine.
<p>
If the court could be persuaded not to enforce the written agreement, either on the basis of <i>non est factum</i> or general unconscionability,<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> the customer would then have to argue that
the loss was caused by the bank's negligence. He would have to assert that the bank was negligent in designing the ATM terminal or EFT-POS keypad in such a way as to allow the criminal to see the PIN and negligent in providing a full paper record of the card number.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> Even if this were possible, it would still lead to a finding of contributory negligence, at least under the ATM fraud outlined above, as the customer should have kept his transaction record in order to prevent the fraud. If the fraud took place as a result of an EFT-POS transaction, it might be easier to avoid a finding of contributory negligence.
<p>
Given the likelihood of lay litigants, these sorts of common law remedies are not satisfactory. Even if the law were such that a successful case could be made for the customer (and it is not at all clear that this is so), the difficulty of presenting such arguments would often prevent the unrepresented customer's success. Consumers are assisted to some degree by the relaxation of procedure in small claims court, but this is not enough.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> The complexity of the substantive common law itself is a barrier to access, as is the need for litigation.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> There is clearly a need for some other mechanism. The consumer would be better protected by a clear right. If there were definite legislation, the bank would pay the claims (or some statutory portion thereof) directly to the customer, and litigation would be avoided. This would be in the bank's best interest as well. Surely, banks must be unhappy with paying $400 to defend a $500 claim in small claims court, where legal costs may not be recoverable.
<p>
<h3>The American Legislative Model of EFT Regulation</h3>

There are several jurisdictions where consumer EFT is regulated. Turn first to the American statutory solution to the problem of risk allocation with respect to electronic funds transfer fraud. In 1978, Congress passed the <cite>Electronic Funds Transfer Act</cite> or <cite>EFTA</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> The <cite>Act</cite>, which purports to cover all electronic financial transactions, has several provisions dealing specifically with ATM and EFT-POS fraud. The <cite>EFTA</cite> also allowed the creation of regulations in the area, including Regulation E which covers consumer EFT.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup>
<p>
The <cite>EFTA</cite> is the result of pressure from American consumer advocates, who stressed the need for protection against the power of financial institutions to contractually limit their risk exposure. American financial industry representatives, of course, took the position that regulation was unnecessary and that unauthorized use
was always the result of negligence on the customer's part.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> Despite the lobbying efforts of the financial services sector, the final legislation was generally favourable to the consumer advocate's position.
<p>
Section 1693g of the <cite>EFTA</cite> provides that the consumer is liable for unauthorized transactions made with the card and some means of identification (with present technology, a PIN). However, this liability is limited to the lesser of fifty dollars or the sum withdrawn before the customer notifies the financial institution of the loss of the card or of the existence of unauthorized transactions. If the customer does not report the loss of the card within two days of knowledge, or does not report unauthorized transactions within sixty days, he may be liable for greater amounts.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<p>
The American courts have since interpreted the statute and regulation liberally to give wide protection to the consumer. In <cite>Russell v. First Am. Bank-Mich., N.A.</cite>,<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> the court held that the bank could not contractually expand the customer's liability beyond the <cite>EFTA</cite>. In that case, the customer wrote the PIN down and gave it to her daughter with the card. The daughter told her mother that the card had been stolen. When Mrs. Russell reported the theft to the bank $310 had already been debited. The court held that neither the plaintiff's nor her daughter's negligence would deny the plaintiff recovery. Not even the plaintiff's breach of the cardholder contract (which provided that the card was not to be kept with the PIN) could
prevent the customer's recovery of funds from the bank.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup>
<p>
The importance of the availability of evidence has already been noted. The <cite>EFTA</cite> provides that the burden of proof is on the financial institution throughout. If a customer questions the validity of a transaction, the onus shifts to the bank to prove that the transaction was authorized.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>The Australian `Soft Law' Approach to EFT Fraud Regulation</h3>

Another possible model for the regulation of EFT fraud is the Australian model.<sup><a href =  "#forty6">46</a></sup> The same concerns enumerated above led the Australian federal government to form a &quot;Working Group Examining the Rights and Obligations of Users and Providers of Electronic Funds Transfer
Systems.&quot;  In conjunction with the Consumer Affairs Ministers of the various states, the Federal Government Working Group issued a report recommending changes in the law governing EFT.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> Their approach is very different, at least in form, from the American one. 
<p>
Consider the form of the recommendations. The Working Group did not recommend legislation, but gave the banks a list of suggestions to guide their contractual interactions with their customers. A Code of Conduct was released by the federal and state governments, with the strong suggestion that legislation would follow if the recommendations in the code were not met.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> The Code of Conduct is periodically reviewed to
allow for new developments.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> This system appears to have been successful in Australia. Of the approximately 430 million transactions in 1990, about 6,000 complaints were made about unauthorized transactions. Of these complaints, over half were settled in the customer's favour.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>
<p>
Consider next the substance of the Australian recommendation on fraud. A consumer should not be liable for any loss over fifty dollars, unless she contributes to that loss. If she contributes, she is responsible for the actual loss.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> The imposition of this limited liability on the consumer, even if no contribution to the loss is shown, is defended on the ground that it provides an incentive for the consumer to take
care not to lose the card.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> The Australian Trade Practices Commission has also provided a dispute resolution mechanism for the settlement of EFT disputes.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>Analysis of the Suitability of These Models to the Canadian Situation</h3>

Given that the present situation in Canada is unsatisfactory from the perspective of the informed consumer, which
of the several possible alternative risk allocation schemes is preferable?<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> The <cite>Bills of Exchange Act</cite> cheque analogy would suggest putting all of the risk on the financial institution. However, this is less than satisfactory, at least from the institution's point of view, because of the differences in the technology. Assume that regulation is desirable if it improves efficiency in the economist's sense. In the case of a cheque, the bank is theoretically able to compare a forged cheque with a sample signature and detect forgery. Thus, it is arguably efficient to make the bank bear the risk because this will encourage the bank to prevent the forgery. With EFT, a fraudulently obtained PIN or electronic signature is identical to a bona fide PIN. If the bank is to use technically efficient online verification, the PIN is necessary<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> and the risk of
unauthorized use cannot be completely prevented by the bank. While this paper has generally adopted a consumer perspective, the banks have legitimate system security interests which must be protected. The earlier discussion of the methods of fraud available make it clear that the banks' claim that all EFT fraud is the result of the customer's collusion or negligence is not valid. However, a portion of the control over the physical security of the system is in the customer's hands.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> The responsibility for electronic security rests entirely on the financial institution. Therefore, like the control over security, the risk should be shared between the customer and the institution. Presumably this will result in an efficiently<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> low amount of fraud.
<p>
This risk-sharing should be an arbitrary split. If the risk is shared according to a fault standard, the problems of litigating small sums will simply recur in more definite form. There is a need for an essentially nonjudicial risk allocation.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> Because of the barriers to access, a common
law judicial system of loss compensation is not suitable.
<p>
The American and Australian approach of limiting customer risk to fifty dollars is a good one. This places a sufficiently high onus on the customer to encourage him to safeguard his card and PIN. At the same time the remaining risk encourages the bank to take more security measures. For example, omitting part of the card number on the transaction receipt would prevent the execution of the most popular EFT fraud scheme. Yet only some of the
financial institutions surveyed by the author have taken this simple step, and their customers are still at risk when they use other banks' machines. As well, a small plastic shield makes it considerably more difficult for the criminal to observe the PIN being entered, yet few banks have taken this step. Putting part of the risk on the bank would provide the necessary impetus for these and other measures, as they become necessary. In the event that litigation becomes necessary under this system, the American approach of shifting the burden of proof to the bank is  reasonable, given the bank's control over the evidence, and should be adopted. There is no need to create a new dispute settlement body as was done in Australia. With a code of conduct in place, the rights and obligations of the parties will be clear and little litigation will be necessary. The small amount which will arise can certainly be
handled by the various small claims courts.
<p>
As a practical matter, the fragmentary nature of the American banking system made legislation necessary there. However, in Australia, with a Canadian style branch banking system, the government was able to use moral suasion on the small number of banks to convince them that the time was ripe to remove liability from the consumer. If possible, this soft law approach would seem to be preferable because it provides more flexibility and allows the easy introduction of new technology.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> The only question remains the willingness of the banks to be persuaded. The traditional position of the Canadian banks is that virtually all EFT fraud is the result of negligence or collusion on the part of the card holder.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> However, using the Canadian Bankers Association and the Canadian Payment Association, it is possible that the federal
government could persuade the banks to change their practices voluntarily, especially in the face of threatened legislation. If the threat is not sufficient, then the government should proceed to implement the same recommendations through legislation and regulation.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

Despite the need for a more efficient system to regulate the losses arising from consumer EFT fraud in Canada, no progress has been made toward this goal. The previous examination of the Australian and American systems of `soft law' and legislation leads to the conclusion that the federal government should begin negotiating with the financial institutions about the contents of a Canadian Code of Conduct. The government should insist that the Code contain a set division of liability. Only then will the informed consumer be comfortable carrying a bank card.
<p><br>
<hr>
<p>
