<li><a name="thirty4">This situation may be common.</a>  When the author requested a copy of the agreement at a local branch of the Bank of Nova Scotia, the clerks were not aware of its existence. After some delay, a copy of the agreement was found in a storage room.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty5">Since either of these findings</a> would require a certain degree of ignorance or even disability on the part of the customer, they are not very practical remedies. Fridman, <i>supra</i> note 26 at 288, 344.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty6">The bank may argue</a> that a full record is needed for the customer's purposes. This is a spurious argument. The card number could allocate numbers to customers based only on the first three sets of numbers, keeping the last set for an on-card code, which would not be recorded on the transaction record. This is now done by some financial institutions. Other institutions (Canada Trust, for example) now give users of their ATMs the option of not getting a paper transaction record.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty7">R. Cranston,</a> <cite>Consumers and the Law</cite>, 2nd ed. (London: Weidenfeld and Nicolson, 1984) at 92.
