<p>
<li><a name="fifty5">This ignores handprint I.D. and other esoteric technological proposals.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty6">In an ATM transaction,</a> the customer can keep his transaction record, rather than drop it on the floor. However, in the hypothetical involving the store clerk viewing the EFT-POS transaction, the customer is not realistically able to prevent the card number and PIN from being seen (short of crawling under the
counter to perform the transaction!).
<p>
<li><a name="fifty7">Fraud will be efficiently low</a> in the sense that both the bank and the customer will take preventative measures until the marginal cost of avoidance exceeds the benefits. At first glance, recommending a set $50 amount appears to offer a less efficient way of encouraging fraud prevention than a fault standard.
However, the problems of litigating small sums, or to be more theoretical, the addition of transaction costs, intervene to make a fixed amount more efficient.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty8">Greguras, <i>supra</i> note 31 at 410.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty9">One of the features</a> which has contributed to the flexibility of the Australian system
is the periodic review procedure which has allowed changes to be made as needed. If it becomes evident that some part of the code is not working, then to the extent that the code is not incorporated into the account-holder's contract, it can simply be ignored (with the knowledge of the Treasury and the Trade Practices Commission). Under the rule of law, legislation cannot be ignored even when it is obviously obsolete or inappropriate.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty">M. Ballard,</a> &quot;On the Safe Side: Security and Automated Banking Machines&quot; (1989) 96:1 Canadian Banker 64. Mr. Ballard was Vice President, Security of the Canadian Bankers' Association at
the time.
