<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 53 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#2">Volume 53 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Book Review</h1>

<h2>MICHAEL FARAGO<a href="#note">*</a></h2>

<h3>Didi Herman, <cite>Rights of Passage: Struggles for Lesbian &amp; Gay Legal Equality.</cite>  Toronto: University of Toronto Press; 1994. 198 pp. $60.00 cloth. $19.95 paper.</h3>

In the past decade, activists within the lesbian and gay rights movement have turned increasingly to the courts and
legislatures to seek protection and affirmation of their existence. Human rights codes have been used to protect gays and lesbians from discrimination, and where sexual orientation is not included as a prohibited ground of discrimination, these codes have been challenged using the equality provision in s. 15 of the <cite>Charter of Rights
and Freedoms</cite>.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> While individual cases and issues have attracted the attention of legal scholars,<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> no one has explored the construction of  &quot;rights&quot; to the extent that Didi Herman does in <cite>Rights of Passage: Struggles for Lesbian &amp; Gay Legal Equality</cite>.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> In this work, Herman further develops some of the themes she introduced in an earlier article, &quot;Are We Family?: Lesbian Rights and Women's Liberation&quot;.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> These include the social construction of the family, the relative efficacy of rights-based litigation, and the characterization of sexual orientation in human rights jurisprudence.
<p>
Herman is concerned about how rights are constructed in human rights legislation, and the extent to which the law is open to receiving new constructions. She is also interested in comparing the tactics of what she terms the &quot;New Christian Right&quot; (NCR) with the struggles waged by lesbian and gay legal reformers. As a lawyer and sociologist, Herman investigates a number of different aspects of the lesbian and gay rights movement,  including the use of feminist ideology, expert testimony in courts, and the reactions of legislators and jurists to the rights movement. In her research, Herman incorporates extensive interviews, case studies, and personal anecdotes which are influenced by her own &quot;Jewish, lesbian, socialist feminist&quot;<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> perspective. This holistic approach breathes life into a number of abstract concepts and issues, so that even to one not familiar with the surrounding academic debate, <cite>Rights of Passage</cite> offers a meaningful insight into the legal process. It is extremely well researched and provides a well-written analysis of
some of the main issues in the current lesbian and gay rights movement.
<p>
Herman begins her work by situating lesbian and gay identity in current political and legal discourse. She traces the history of the use of human rights legislation and litigation under the <cite>Charter</cite> to advocate legal recognition of sexual orientation as a ground of discrimination. She argues that the paradigm of legal liberalism has strongly influenced the way that lesbian and gay rights reformers structure their claims. 
<p>
Human rights legislation is founded on a liberal ideology which emphasizes the equality of individuals.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> The principle of equality is premised on the idea that within the population, some minority groups suffer from discrimination. In order for these discrete minorities<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> to fully participate in society, the state is required to act as a &quot;neutral protector&quot;<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> by enforcing public rights documents.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> Gays and lesbians have been able to use this model successfully by positioning themselves as a minority group in a majority heterosexual population. With this approach, litigants have been able to show that human rights legislation is underinclusive where it does not include protection against discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup>
<p>
As Herman points out, however, there are difficulties with the traditional liberal approach, as embodied in the <cite>Charter</cite> and human rights codes. When applied to sexual orientation, this view implicitly reinforces heterosexuality as the unquestioned norm, while gays and lesbians find themselves characterized as a homogeneous group with immutable sexual characteristics over which they have little or no control.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> Gays and lesbians are relegated to the status of sexual minority and there is no acknowledgement of alternative theories, such as the existence of a spectrum of human sexualities. This approach further marginalizes others, including bisexuals, transsexuals and the transgendered, who may not fit into the traditional liberal categories.
<p>
Ultimately, Herman hopes to see a wholesale change in the way courts view sexual relations between individuals. The use of a traditional minority/majority analysis serves to entrench the notion of heterosexuality as a norm against which sexual minorities are measured. As a result, individuals who differ from the norm find themselves classified into groups; their efforts at making connections with other disadvantaged groups are impeded, and they find that the effectiveness of remedies under human rights legislation is consequently reduced.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> Feminists like Herman critique the social construction of gender roles and the imposition of sexual hierarchies in society.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> Herman suggests that, in order to oppose this liberal framework, lesbians and gays could make rights claims on the basis of their political position, rather than their sexual difference.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> Throughout her book, Herman considers the benefits of, and the constraints inherent in, challenging the heterosexual norm. In the short term, however, she
acknowledges the importance of the political achievements that have come from characterizing lesbians and gays as an immutable minority. For example, she cites greater visibility in the media, greater political awareness, and increasing societal acceptance of lesbians and gays as important achievements in the struggle for equality.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> An additional advantage is the raising of social consciousness and solidarity among lesbians and gays around the idea of a political movement.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
<p>
<cite>Rights of Passage</cite> uses the campaign over Bill 7<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> in Ontario as a case study through which to examine the construction of rights by all sides in the debate. This legislation added &quot;sexual orientation&quot; as a prohibited ground of discrimination in the Ontario <cite>Human Rights Code</cite><sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> in 1986. The author argues that
&quot;in this specific struggle, a liberal equality paradigm was hegemonic.&quot;<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> She traces the use of rights in the debate by examining the statements of legislators, the media, gay and lesbian activists, and their opponents from right-wing Christian groups. In this way, she discovers how the concept of rights can be used to serve the purpose of the group that uses it.
<p>
Legislators who advocated amending the <cite>Code</cite> to include sexual orientation tended to appeal to the public's sense of tolerance and the principle of pluralism.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> At the same time, there was an implicit recognition that the proposed changes would have relatively minor effects.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> Gay and lesbian political activists generally bought into the liberal rights paradigm, even though many of them were well aware of the limited impact that the addition of sexual orientation as a prohibited ground of discrimination would have. For them, it was most important to use Bill 7 as a step in the
process toward achieving equality, even though the amendment to the <cite>Human Rights Code</cite> would not result in equality or liberation in itself.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup>
<p>
While a sufficient social consensus developed to see the bill passed, Herman is very concerned with the implications of the fact that liberal legal concepts so effectively dominated the debate. There was little discussion of the inherent limitations of using the Ontario Human Rights Commission as a vehicle for social change.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> Also, those who spoke out in favour of Bill 7 tended to base their positions on a very narrow spectrum of analysis. Evelyn Gigantes, the M.P.P. responsible for the amendment, is cited as being unique
in injecting a feminist perspective into the discussion. Herman identifies her as the only person in the Ontario legislature to speak about heterosexism as a source of homophobia.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup>
<p>
Herman next examines the politics of the New Christian Right and their response to the progress made by lesbian and gay rights reformers. By &quot;New Christian Right,&quot; Herman means a loose assortment of organizations which adhere to a conservative, evangelical type of Christianity.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup>  In particular she focuses on the work of the Salvation Army, Focus on the Family (Canada), and REAL Women. She chose these organizations because they formed part of the coalition which intervened in the case of <cite>Mossop</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> By making
references to some of their published literature and to interviews with some of their members, Herman examines their construction of sexual politics.
<p>
In general, these groups perceive the <cite>Charter</cite> as entrenching the concept of liberal equality in society, as a result of which gay rights have gained a certain institutional legitimacy.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> They sense a clear bias in the media and the judiciary against their view of traditional Christian morality and in favour of a secular humanist approach.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> NCR organizations therefore feel forced to put forward their own Christian-based message in <cite>Charter</cite> litigation by taking a stance against the prevailing liberal views.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> In fact, Herman writes that the group REAL Women &quot;views the <cite>Charter</cite> as an unqualified evil which they argue about only because they have to: `instead, we say, get rid of the <cite>Charter</cite>.'&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup>
<p>
Other NCR organizations criticize &quot;rights-oriented&quot; litigation because it places too much emphasis on the individual, while losing sight of the privileges and the responsibilities of members of society.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> They advocate less focus on the individual and more on the family. The &quot;family&quot; is presented as a centre of good Christian life, which is being explicitly threatened as more individual rights are conferred on gays and lesbians outside of the family setting.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> For all of these reasons, these groups are somewhat reluctant to use rights rhetoric to express their positions on <cite>Charter</cite> issues. At the same time, however, Herman suggests that rights
could be used by the NCR as a way of advocating their position based on the principle that the views of religious minorities must be protected.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
<p>
Herman's dissection of the Bill 7 episode provides an instructive analysis for rights activists. It demonstrates how the heat of a political campaign can force groups to quickly line up on either side of a particular issue. This process does not easily allow for the presentation of novel or refined arguments, and it can lead to the concept of  &quot;rights&quot; taking on a different meaning according to how it is used in political discourse. Even the
parties most affected by the issues may find that they lose control over the nature and direction of the debate.
<p>
The second major case study in <cite>Rights of Passage</cite> uses the <cite>Mossop</cite> case as its focus. This case began as a challenge by Brian Mossop against his employer, the federal government, for refusing his request for a day of leave to attend the funeral of his partner's father. His partner did not fall under the category of
&quot;immediate family&quot; covered by the bereavement leave provision of his union's collective agreement. As the <cite>Canadian Human Rights Act</cite><sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> does not include sexual orientation as an enumerated ground of discrimination, Mossop tried to challenge it by attacking the definition of &quot;family.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup>
<p>
A coalition of conservative Christian groups intervened in order to present their view of what constituted a family. They attempted to explain why it was so important for the court to uphold the traditional view, and they expressed concern that the federal Attorney General's Office was not making a sufficient effort to present an alternative to Mossop's functional approach to the meaning of family.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup>
<p>
Herman uses the <cite>Mossop</cite> case as a means by which to analyze how the politics of the New Christian Right have been affected by the process of <cite>Charter</cite> litigation. As the NCR organizations have adopted the language of equality rights, their Christian focus has been co-opted or ousted by the legalism of their lawyers, or alternatively, they are deliberately cloaking their true politics with respectable language. Herman sees this same process occurring when feminist organizations formulate their position on an issue. She notes that when feminist groups draft legal submissions, they do not necessarily reveal the radical politics of the lesbian feminists who are involved in the writing process.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a><sup>  This comparison of two very different social movements illustrates the power that <cite>Charter</cite> -oriented arguments can exert on all types of political strategies.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup>
<p>
In the course of her interviews with key members of the NCR organizations involved in the <cite>Mossop</cite> litigation, the author finds a real sense of marginalization. In one case, one of the subjects even compares her feelings as a Christian to those of closeted lesbians and gay men who suffer from the same kinds of  persecution.<sup><a href  = "#thirty9">39</a></sup>  Herman is able to conclude that &quot;the NCR and its opponents . . . share similar yet irreconcilable views of their social worlds. Each believes the other (or some `other') controls society's major institutions. They share a fear and distrust of the other . . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup>
<p>
This insight is fascinating, for it illustrates a rare link between groups entrenched on opposite sides of the liberal &quot;centre&quot; occupied by the courts. In presenting this view, the author balances her feelings of empathy with a deep distrust. As she cautions in the first chapter of <cite>Rights of Passage</cite>:
<blockquote>
The interviews I conducted provided me with a very different &quot;take&quot; on a group of people I would previously have dismissed as religious fanatics. I could not escape the fact that they were nice <i>towards me</i>, that they did their utmost to assist my research, and that they rather poignantly expressed gratitude that &quot;at least someone is interested in what we have to say. . . .&quot; At the same time, I knew that the interviewees were utterly opposed to everything I believed in.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Herman acknowledges her own perspective at the same time that she identifies some common ground with the NCR leaders. She successfully gains insight into her political opponents while maintaining the integrity of her position. 
<p>
One of the unfortunate aspects of <cite>Rights of Passage</cite> is the fact that it has come out during a period of great transition in the lesbian and gay rights movement. As such, it fails to address some of the important emerging issues in the movement.
<p>
Attention has recently turned away from the campaign to recognize sexual orientation in human rights legislation, as the limitations of this approach are becoming apparent. The goal of achieving protection from discrimination in public spheres is no longer viewed as one that will provide true equality. Instead, lesbians and gays tend to be seeking greater acknowledgement and acceptance of their existence by major societal institutions.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> In continuing the litigation process where <cite>Mossop</cite> left off, lesbian and gay couples are coming to court in increasing numbers to demand spousal benefits. Among the most famous cases is
<cite>Egan</cite>,<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> which involves a challenge to the <cite>Old Age Security Act</cite><sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> under s. 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite> on the grounds that it discriminates against same-sex spouses. The case was argued before the Supreme Court in the fall of 1994. By challenging the definition of &quot;spouse,&quot; the <cite>Egan</cite> case raises the stakes in the struggle for equality by lesbians and gays. While earlier efforts sought to extend the application of human rights legislation to lesbian and gay individuals, the <cite>Egan</cite> case strikes more closely at the very definition of a family. A broader interpretation of the word &quot;spouse&quot; would help to validate lesbian and gay relationships in the minds of the public and it would further chip away at the traditional concept of family that the NCR has fought hard to uphold.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
<p>
The summer of 1994 saw a political debate in Ontario which had striking similarities to the fight for Bill 7. Bill 167<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> would have recognized same-sex couples as spouses under provincial legislation.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> It was fought over by a large, organized segment of the gay and lesbian community, and strongly opposed by religious groups---particularly the Catholic Church.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> In contrast to the debate in 1986, this time the proposal was defeated in the Ontario legislature. Herman's depiction of the fight for Bill 7 is still instructive despite the failure of Bill 167, however, for the way it sets up a comparison of the rights debate and the positions of the parties involved. By tracing the development of the use of rights-based litigation from the time it was deployed over Bill 7, it is possible to see what the future holds for the use of the <cite>Charter</cite> by gays and lesbians to advance their rights.
<p>
The most compelling message to be derived from <cite>Rights of Passage</cite> is that gay and lesbian activists need to develop new political strategies that try to expand the traditional notions of the family and of sexual relations. There is a limit to the benefit of tailoring human rights-based notions of equality to include sexual minorities. As Herman says, &quot;the undermining of heterosexuality, and eventually the deconstruction of gender itself, is a necessary part of any larger project of social transformation.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup>  Herman recognizes that in the short run, radical arguments about the construction of sexuality in society may not be accepted. However, she identifies the importance of putting such ideas before
the judiciary so that future litigators can argue for a better conception of social relations. While the <cite>Mossop</cite> case was not decided in favour of gays and lesbians, the use of novel legal arguments has met with success elsewhere. For example, in <cite>R. v. Butler</cite><sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>, the Supreme Court formulated a test for obscenity which adopted a feminist analysis of pornography, based on the harm it causes to women.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup>
<p>
By analyzing campaigns and strategies from the past, Herman presents a valuable insight to those litigating cases under the <cite>Charter</cite>. Thus, while the book is structured around two specific political and legal campaigns in Canada, by holding a mirror to the gay and lesbian rights movement Herman's work provides the basis for understanding how rights are constructed in these contests. For those engaging in political campaigns and <cite>Charter</cite> litigation, it can most usefully serve as a caution about how the meaning of rights is constructed. For all of these reasons, <cite>Rights of Passage</cite> is a welcome addition to a growing literature on the subject of lesbian and gay legal issues. As Herman notes in her conclusion, however, there are many connections between the lesbian and gay rights movement and the struggles of other equality-seeking groups.
Ultimately, <cite>Rights of Passage</cite> tries to demonstrate how organizations seeking social change have an interest in formulating joint strategies. With her thoughtful analysis of rights issues, Herman presents a strong argument for the use of a co-ordinated effort in struggles yet to come.
<p><br>
