<title>UTLR Vol. 53 No. 1: Abstract 1</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol52#1">Volume 53 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1><b><cite>Sparrow</cite>'s Promise: Aboriginal Rights in
the B.C. Court of Appeal</b>
<p>
 ANDREA BOWKER</h1>

<center><h3>ABSTRACT / <a  href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/utlr53-1/bowker.htm">Fulltext</a></h3></center>

In its groundbreaking decision of <cite>R. v. Sparrow</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada explored for the first time the scope and strength of s. 35(1) of the <cite>Charter</cite> as &quot;a promise to the Aboriginal peoples of Canada.&quot;  In the course of examining s. 35(1)'s theoretical and political context, the Court set
out a framework by which to consider both the nature and content of Aboriginal rights, and their constitutional limitations.  In June of 1993, the British Columbia Court of Appeal rendered judgment on a series of cases, including <cite>Delgamuukw v.  British Columbia</cite>, in which the strength of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s promise to invigorate and secure constitutional Aboriginal rights was tested. The author argues that by allowing controversy over commercial fishing rights, as well as stereotyped conceptions of Aboriginal culture, to govern its decision-making process, the majority of the Court failed to uphold that promise.
<p>
Dans l'arr&ecirc;t <cite>R. c. Sparrow</cite>, la Cour supr&ecirc;me du Canada a explor&eacute; pour la premi&egrave;re fois l'&eacute;tendue et la force de la `promesse aux peuples autochtones du Canada' qui se
trouve dans l'art. 35(1) de la <cite>Charte</cite>.  En consid&eacute;rant les contextes th&eacute;orique et politique de l'art. 35(1), la Cour a &eacute;tabli une structure par laquelle elle allait consid&eacute;rer aussi bien le contenu et l'essence des droits autochtones que leur limitation constitutionnelle.  En juin 1993, la Cour d'appel de la
Colombie-Britannique a rendu une s&eacute;rie de d&eacute;cisions, y compris <cite>Delgamuukw c. Colombie-Britannique</cite>, o&ugrave; l'arr&ecirc;t <cite>Sparrow</cite>, qui promettait de garantir des droits constitutionnels aux autochtones, a&eacute;t&eacute; mis a l'&eacute;preuve. L'auteure argumente qu'en permettant &agrave; la pol&eacute;mique sur les droits commerciaux de p&ecirc;che et aux st&eacute;r&acute;eotypes de la culture autochtone d'influencer le processus d&eacute;cisionnel, la majorit&eacute; de la Cour a manqu&eacute; &agrave; cette promesse.
<p>
<hr>
