<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review Vol. 53 No. 1</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v53n1.htm">Volume 53 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1><b><cite>Sparrow</cite>'s Promise: Aboriginal Rights in
the B.C. Court of Appeal</b>
<p>
 ANDREA BOWKER<sup><a href="bowker.htm #note">*</a></sup></h1>

<i>In its groundbreaking decision of </i>R. v. Sparrow<i>, the Supreme Court of Canada explored for the first time the scope and strength of s. 35(1) of the </i>Charter<i> as &quot;a promise to the Aboriginal peoples of Canada.&quot;  In the course of examining s. 35(1)'s theoretical and political context, the Court set
out a framework by which to consider both the nature and content of Aboriginal rights, and their constitutional limitations. In June of 1993, the British Columbia Court of Appeal rendered judgment on a series of cases, including </i>Delgamuukw v. British Columbia<i>, in which the strength of  </i>Sparrow<i>'s promise to invigorate and secure constitutional Aboriginal rights was tested. The author argues that by allowing controversy over commercial fishing rights, as well as stereotyped conceptions of Aboriginal culture, to govern its decision-making process, the majority of the Court failed to uphold that promise.
<p>
Dans l'arr&ecirc;t </i>R. c. Sparrow<i>, la Cour supr&ecirc;me du Canada a explor&eacute; pour la premi&egrave;re fois l'&eacute;tendue et la force de la `promesse aux peuples autochtones du Canada' qui se
trouve dans l'art. 35(1) de la </i>Charte<i>. En consid&eacute;rant les contextes th&eacute;orique et politique de l'art. 35(1), la Cour a &eacute;tabli une structure par laquelle elle allait consid&eacute;rer aussi bien le contenu et l'essence des droits autochtones que leur limitation constitutionnelle. En juin 1993, la Cour d'appel de la
Colombie-Britannique a rendu une s&eacute;rie de d&eacute;cisions, y compris </i>Delgamuukw c. Colombie-Britannique<i>, o&ugrave; l'arr&ecirc;t </i>Sparrow<i>, qui promettait de garantir des droits constitutionnels aux autochtones, a&eacute;t&eacute; mis a l'&eacute;preuve. L'auteure argumente qu'en permettant &agrave; la pol&eacute;mique sur les droits commerciaux de p&ecirc;che et aux st&eacute;r&acute;eotypes de la culture autochtone d'influencer le processus d&eacute;cisionnel, la majorit&eacute; de la Cour a manqu&eacute; &agrave; cette promesse.</i>
<p>
When the Supreme Court of Canada decided <cite>R. v. Sparrow</cite>, <sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> it resolved a great many outstanding issues concerning the nature of Aboriginal rights. Expressing itself in broad, affirmative terms, the Court indicated that the idea that Aboriginal rights were only `politically enforceable' and legally meaningless was no longer acceptable, and that the Court's intention was to ensure that the constitutional law of Canada take Aboriginal rights seriously. <sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> Not only did the Court synthesize existing judicial views on the meaning of s. 35(1) of the <cite>Constitution Act</cite><sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> in a way that sought to give meaningful content to the constitutional `recognition and affirmation' of these rights, it also attempted to set out a framework by which to reconcile the seemingly intractable competing interests affected by the recognition of Aboriginal rights. Given the difficulty of such an ambitious project, it is not surprising that we should find some loose ends left hanging from the Court's conception of Aboriginal rights. What might surprise us more would be to find the retrenchment of views rejected by the Supreme Court about the nature of Aboriginal rights and their meaning in our legal system.
<p>
It is the loose ends of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s judicial fabric that I intend to explore in this article.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> In particular, I will focus on the interpretation of  <cite>Sparrow</cite> in the British Columbia Court of Appeal's recent decisions on Aboriginal fishing rights: <cite>R. v. Van der Peet</cite>,<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> <cite>R. v. Gladstone</cite><sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> and <cite>R. v. Nikal</cite>.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> These cases, and the more prominent <cite>Delgamuukw v. The Queen</cite>,<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup>  will most likely represent the Supreme Court of Canada's first opportunity to restate and clarify its decision in <cite>Sparrow</cite>.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup>  It is therefore highly relevant to examine them closely for their treatment of that case, as well as of Aboriginal rights in general.
<p>
In order to evaluate these cases, I propose first to briefly outline the context in which <cite>Sparrow</cite> was decided and the aspects of the decision which I consider to be the most important for present purposes, and to describe the `loose ends' which the case leaves outstanding. Although <cite>Sparrow</cite> has been discussed many times before in academic contexts, the British Columbia Court of Appeal decisions offer us an opportunity to re-visit this important decision with the knowledge of the way in which it has been interpreted by a later high court. In this way, we can see <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s sometimes vague pronouncements about Aboriginal rights in a new light. It is the thesis of this paper that the British Columbia Court of Appeal majority chose to rely on old-fashioned, narrow, `safe' visions of Aboriginal rights instead of taking up the challenge of giving real meaning to the open-ended phrases of <cite>Sparrow</cite>, even as it invoked these very phrases.
<p>
I will divide my analysis of <cite>Sparrow</cite> along the same lines as did the Court. The first section will explore the nature and content of Aboriginal rights. The second section will examine the Court's analysis of what constitutes a violation of these rights, and how such violations may be justified. Following this revisitation of
<cite>Sparrow</cite>, I will move to a discussion of the British Columbia Court of Appeal decisions in a parallel structure. First, <cite>Van der Peet</cite> and <cite>Gladstone</cite> offer an opportunity to examine the British Columbia Court of Appeal's vision of Aboriginal rights themselves. Second, <cite>Nikal</cite> and <cite>Gladstone</cite> set out the majority's view of violation and justification. Intertwined throughout will be references to other cases that deal with Aboriginal rights, such as <cite>R. v. Agawa</cite><sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup>  and <cite>Four B Manufacturing v. United Garment Workers of America</cite>,<sup><a href = #eleven">11</a></sup>  in order to show the genesis and context of the Supreme Court's thinking on these rights. Finally, I will set out Lambert J.A.'s consistently dissenting vision of Aboriginal rights in order to show that there is an alternative to the majority's viewpoint. While this alternative may not be the best answer, it is far superior than the majority approach, because in setting out his own vision, Lambert J.A. at least makes a real effort to adopt the vision of the Aboriginal rights-holders themselves. And since this very perspective is one of the strongest directions offered in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, this brief introduction brings us back to where I would like to begin.
<p>
<center><h3>Part One: <cite>Sparrow</cite></h3></center>

Ronald Sparrow was charged with fishing with an over-long drift net contrary to the <cite>British Columbia Fishery (General) Regulations</cite>.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> In concluding that the regulations did infringe s. 35, the Court addressed two main issues: first, the nature of Aboriginal rights and the appropriate interpretive principles to apply to them, and second, whether Aboriginal rights are absolute within the Canadian constitutional framework, or are limited according to certain principles. 
<p>
<b>1. Aboriginal Rights and Section 35(1)</b>
<p>
As the Court had done in its early <cite>Charter</cite><sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> decisions, Dickson C.J.C. and La Forest J. write in broad and purposive terms about the meaning and importance of constitutionally protected rights. They cast their discussion against the backdrop of the law's failure to recognize Aboriginal claims to land and, indeed, the law's general failure to acknowledge or uphold Aboriginal peoples' rights within Canada at all.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> The Justices conclude that s. 35(1) is the &quot;culmination of a long and difficult struggle in both the political forum and the courts for the constitutional recognition of aboriginal rights.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> Where, in the early <cite>Charter</cite> cases, the Court spoke eloquently about the nature of the rights protected by the <cite>Charter</cite>, the Court in <cite>Sparrow</cite> was not similarly able to comment on the rights protected by s. 35(1). Section 35(1) protects undefined Aboriginal rights, while the <cite>Charter</cite> enumerates broad, but specific, rights and freedoms. It is impossible, and inappropriate, to try to describe the substance of `Aboriginal rights' in any general way. 
<p>
As a result, instead of commenting at length on the content of the right asserted by Mr. Sparrow, the Court sets out some broad considerations that a court should take into account when contemplating Aboriginal rights. From a substantive point of view, the Justices observe that in the context of Musqueam life, &quot;the salmon fishery has always constituted an integral part of their distinctive culture,&quot;<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> giving future
courts some idea of the significance to Aboriginal culture that a particular practice or activity should have in order to warrant constitutional protection under s. 35(1). The Court also gives some guidance in selecting the appropriate interpretive principles. It emphasizes, for example, that courts must avoid defining the content of Aboriginal rights by sole reference to legal concepts that do not flow from Aboriginal culture. The Court notes that: 
<blockquote>
[f]ishing rights are not traditional property rights. They are rights held by a collective and are in keeping with the culture and existence of that group. Courts must be careful, then, to avoid the application of traditional common law concepts of property as they develop their understanding of ... the &quot;<cite>sui generis</cite>&quot; nature of aboriginal rights.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup>
 </blockquote>
The Court goes on to say that &quot;[w]hile it is impossible to give an easy definition of fishing rights, it is possible, and, indeed, crucial, to be sensitive to the aboriginal perspective on the meaning of the rights at stake.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> In my view, this approach to perspective and to the substance of Aboriginal rights is appropriate in order to ensure that these rights are not lost in the legal shuffle, as they had been &quot;for many years.&quot;<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> These are, of course, not the only possible tools for the constitutional treatment of Aboriginal rights. For the purposes of this article, however, I will be referring to them frequently since they are the principles which the British Columbia Court of Appeal took to be definitive.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup>
<p>
FROZEN RIGHTS
<p>
In contemplating the purpose and implications of s. 35(1), the Court rejected the suggestion that s. 35(1) only  protects Aboriginal rights as they existed in regulated form in 1982.<sup><a href="#twentyone">21</a></sup> Having proposed that the Aboriginal perspective on the right is crucial, it seems doubtful that the Court could have accepted the notion of `frozen rights.'  Adopting this theory would mean assuming that Aboriginal rights may be defined by reference to federal and provincial regulations rather than by reference to the society and culture in which they are rooted. This approach is fundamentally inconsistent with the principle of adhering to the Aboriginal perspective when considering these rights. It would be odd to suggest that non-Aboriginal laws could determine what was &quot;integral to their distinctive culture.&quot;
<p>
The Court's explicit reason for rejecting the theory, however, is that it would make a mess of the Constitution. Following Blair J.A.'s view in <cite>Agawa</cite>, and Professor Slattery's comments on the subject,<sup><a href="#twentytwo">22</a></sup> the Court holds that &quot;the notion of freezing existing rights would incorporate into the Constitution a crazy patchwork of regulations,&quot;<sup><a href="#twentythree">23</a></sup> and that constitutional integrity demands a principled approach. The Court adds that &quot;far from being defined according to the regulatory scheme in place in 1982, the phrase `existing aboriginal rights' must be interpreted flexibly so as to permit their evolution over time.&quot;<sup><a href="#twentyfour">24</a></sup>
<p>
The Court's rejection of the frozen rights theory is a crucial aspect of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>, and illustrates the multi-layered nature of s. 35(1). The fallacy of frozen rights has the potential to operate both in interpreting s. 35(1) itself, through the word &quot;existing,&quot; and at the more fundamental level of where the content of the rights
themselves is determined. As a result, <cite>Sparrow</cite> imposes a further constraint on a court's powers of definition, and literally liberates the rights s. 35(1) protects. The rights are freed from being determined by reference to government action. The court is also prevented from relying solely on the content of an Aboriginal
right at a particular point in time. Although I have suggested that rejecting `frozen rights' is an inevitable consequence of adopting an Aboriginal perspective under s. 35(1), the British Columbia Court of Appeal's treatment in the cases discussed in this article reveals a resistance to the total liberation of the rights from the regulations.
<p>
In the cases I will be discussing, a key aspect of the rights asserted is that they are seen to be `different,' to varying degrees, from the practices exercised prior to the assertion of British sovereignty. The Court's view in <cite>Sparrow</cite> that Aboriginal rights are not restricted to some primaeval form is the starting point
for contemplating how different a `modern' Aboriginal right is from a `traditional' one or, indeed, whether it is different at all. Second, the rights asserted in these cases exist, as the Court notes in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, within a web of regulation so thick that it is difficult, at times, to determine what the right actually is. The difference between Aboriginal rights and <cite>Charter</cite> rights makes it easier to confuse Aboriginal rights with the regulations. It goes without saying, for example, that freedom of religion is guaranteed to every Canadian not because legislation grants it to us, but because of  &quot;the centrality of the rights associated with freedom of
individual conscience both to basic beliefs about human worth and dignity and to a free and democratic political system.&quot;<sup><a href="#twentyfive">25</a></sup> It may be more difficult for a court to understand the nature of a constitutionalized Aboriginal right to fish, existing outside the present regulatory scheme, when most Canadians exercise `rights' to fish only with the government's permission. Both the source and the scope of the rights protected under s. 35(1) have the potential to be obscured by regulation. <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s rejection of the concept of frozen rights, however, <i>requires</i> a court to extricate its perspective from the regulations, and to resist the
gravitational pull toward determining the content of an Aboriginal right by reference to the legislative scheme by which it is constrained. 
<p>
FISHING RIGHTS
<p>
In order to lay a foundation for discussion of the British Columbia Court of Appeal's decisions in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, <cite>Gladstone</cite> and <cite>Nikal</cite>, which all concern fishing rights, it is worth examining the Court's description of British Columbia's fishing regime in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. The Court notes that the Province's fishery has become highly regulated and controlled, so much so that fishing is prohibited to everyone but licence holders.<sup><a href="#twentysix">26</a></sup> Before British Columbia entered Confederation, however, the fishery was not regulated  &quot;in any significant way.&quot;<sup><a href="#twentyseven">27</a></sup> At that time, the Court observes, &quot;[c]ommercial and sport fishing were not ... of any great importance.&quot;<sup><a href="#twentyeight">28</a></sup> Later regulations, beginning in 1878, imposed limits on fishing in general, and Indian fishing in particular. The 1878 regulations provided that Indians were free to catch fish as they wished, as long as they did not use drift nets or spears. These fish could not be offered for sale or barter. The Court remarks that the &quot;[t]he Indian right or liberty to fish was thereby restricted.&quot;<sup><a href="#twentynine">29</a></sup> It was
further restricted by its conversion from a `liberty,' to a permitted activity, and &quot;[u]ltimately, in 1917, the power to regulate even food fishing [was exercised] by means of conditions attached to the permit.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> The Court identifies the result of this progression as &quot;the Indian right to fish for food,&quot; pursuant to which &quot;an Indian could fish for food under a `special licence' specifying method, locale and times of fishing.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtyone">31</a></sup> Needless to say, this 'right' had come a long
way from the original liberty. 
<p>
It is vital to recognize that the definition of this &quot;Indian right to fish for food&quot; evolved in lockstep with increased non-Indian participation in the fishery. The right provided for by the regulations was defined by reference to the needs of the non-Indian commercial and sport fishery, not by reference to Aboriginal societies and cultures. While the Court does eventually reject the argument that the rights were extinguished by the regulations, it is
not quite so clear that it succeeded in rejecting the role of the regulations in defining the rights. At the beginning of the Court's analysis, it notes that Indians were free to fish as they chose; at the end, the Court makes casual reference to the &quot;aboriginal right to fish for food purposes,&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtytwo">32</a></sup>and the &quot;aboriginal right to fish for food and social and ceremonial activities.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtythree">33</a></sup> But where does this latter characterization of the Aboriginal right come from?  The phrase appears to have been coined by the British Columbia Court of Appeal in its decision in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. The Supreme Court  describes, and adopts, the Court of Appeal's conclusion that: 
<blockquote>
... the aboriginal right was to fish for food purposes, but that purpose was not to be confined to mere subsistence. Rather the right was found to extend to fish consumed for social and ceremonial activities. The Court of Appeal thereby defined the right as <i>protecting the same interest as is reflected in the government's food fish policy.</i> In limiting the right to food purposes, the Court of Appeal referred to the line of cases involving the interpretation of
the <i>Natural Resources Agreements and the food purpose limitation placed on the protection of fishing and hunting rights by the Constitution Act, 1930.</i><sup><a href="#thirtyfour">34</a></sup> [emphasis added.]
</blockquote>
Even though the Court says, just a few lines later, that &quot;historical policy on the part of the Crown is ... incapable of, in itself, delineating that right,&quot; and that &quot;[t]he nature of government regulations cannot be determinative of the content and scope of an existing aboriginal right,&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtyfive">35</a></sup> it is difficult to accept that the Court was not, in fact, highly influenced by the federal regulatory scheme in defining the Musqueam right to fish. The Court proposes, for example, to leave discussion of commercial aspects of the right to fish until another day, since the &quot;case at bar was not presented on the footing of an aboriginal right to fish for commercial or livelihood purposes.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtysix">36</a></sup> In doing so, the Court concludes that there exists a Musqueam right to fish for food and for ceremonial and social purposes that exists separately from a Musqueam right to fish for sale or barter, and that these rights may be treated separately. This division closely patterns what the Musqueam are presently permitted and not permitted to do under the regulatory scheme. But is there any justification, flowing from <cite>Musqueam</cite> culture and society, for conceiving of separate rights to fish for food and for commercial purposes? Indeed, is there any reason for contemplating a `right to fish' rather than a `right to survive' or, for that matter, a `right to regulate fishing?'  In my view, the only justification the Court
presents is one that flows from the regulatory scheme. At the very least, the right the Court considers the Musqueam to have is too much a product of the Court's contemplation of the regulatory scheme for us to comfortably say that the Court did not fall into the very trap that it counselled future courts to avoid.
<p>
The fact that the Supreme Court could say, on the very same page, that Aboriginal rights must not be defined by reference to government policy, but then conclude that the Musqueam right is appropriately defined by government policy's conception of it, shows the difficulty of the task facing courts dealing with s. 35(1) claims. <cite>Sparrow</cite> presents courts with the challenge of attempting to put themselves in the place of the Aboriginal people asserting the right, and then determining, from this perspective, what is integral to an Aboriginal people's distinctive culture. The Supreme Court of Canada, while enunciating these principles, may not have managed to coherently apply them. In adjudicating s. 35(1), however, a court has the power to define both the legal rights of the Aboriginal people who assert them, and their history and culture. This is not a task to be taken lightly. Judges must break free of their own imagination of Aboriginal culture and the network of regulation resting upon and constraining Aboriginal rights, even if it is difficult. These requirements are the challenge of <cite>Sparrow</cite>. 
<p>
<b>2. Limitations Under s. 35(1)</b>
<p>
In addition to setting out an approach for describing the content of Aboriginal rights, the Supreme Court developed an analysis of limitations of these rights similar to the framework used under s. 1 of the <cite>Charter</cite>. The British Columbia Court of Appeal, in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, had opted for a weak justificatory standard:
&quot;s. 35(1) ... protects the aboriginal right only when exercised for food purposes and permits restrictive regulation of such rights whenever `reasonably justified as being necessary for the proper management and conservation of the resource or in the public interest.'&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtyseven">37</a></sup>The Court had
arrived at this conclusion after evaluating the various conceptions advanced regarding s. 35(1)'s effect, which ranged from the intervenors' argument that rights protected under s. 35(1) could not be limited at all, to the province's assertion that s. 35(1) did not offer any protection from governmental action because it merely
stated &quot;an assurance of good intentions.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirtyeight">38</a></sup> When the Supreme Court contemplated limitations, then, it had a variety of views from which to choose, and it is important to note that none of them, except the intervenors' argument, has much grounding in the text of s. 35(1) itself. The limitation that the Supreme Court eventually settled on has its source not in s. 35(1) but in the Court's conception of the Constitution as a whole. 
<p>
SOURCE OF THE LIMITATIONS
<p>
Dickson C.J.C. and La Forest J. hint at their eventual conclusion at the beginning of the decision, when they quote the Court of Appeal's remark that &quot;s. 35(1) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite> does not purport to revoke the power of Parliament to act under Head 12 or 24. The power to regulate fisheries, including Indian access to the fisheries, continues ...&quot;<sup><a href ="#thirtynine">39</a></sup> The key passage in which the Court introduces its view of limitations is as follows:
<blockquote>
There is no explicit language in the provision that authorizes this Court or any court to assess the legitimacy of any government legislation that restricts aboriginal rights. Yet we find that the words &quot;recognition and affirmation&quot;  incorporate the fiduciary relationship referred to earlier and so import some restraint on the
exercise of sovereign power. Rights that are recognized and affirmed are not absolute. Federal legislative powers continue, including, of course, the right to legislate with respect to Indians pursuant to s. 91(24) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite>. These powers must, however, now be read together with s. 35(1). In other words, federal power must be reconciled with federal duty and the best way to achieve that reconciliation is to demand the justification of any government regulation that infringes upon or denies aboriginal rights.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Court here introduces restrictions on Aboriginal rights that are not rooted in the text of s. 35(1), but in a vision of constitutional integrity. If the Constitution entrenches a subject matter---Aboriginal rights---that must be protected from government incursion, and at the same time gives power over Aboriginal people and the subject matters in respect of which they may exercise Aboriginal rights to the federal and provincial governments under ss.
91 and 92, neither the governmental power nor the protection of Aboriginal rights can be absolute. It is this conflict of power that underlies the Supreme Court's introduction of limitations, rather than any of the pragmatic reasons to which the British Columbia Court of Appeal refers in its decision regarding the increasingly complex world in which Aboriginal rights exist.<sup><a href="#fortyone">41</a></sup>These pragmatic concerns may well inform the <i>ways</i> in which the rights are limited, but they are not the <i>source</i> of the limitation. In this sense, it
is not so much a matter of limiting Aboriginal rights under s. 35(1). Both Aboriginal rights and legislative power are limited by each other, to the extent that they interfere with each other. It is a mutual limitation. Policing the border between Aboriginal rights and governmental power is, in the Court's view, the fiduciary obligation,<sup><a href="#fortytwo">42</a></sup> which gives rise to the Court's `test' for justifying infringements of s. 35(1).
<p>
NATURE OF THE LIMITATIONS
<p>
Dickson C.J.C. and La Forest J. propose that a court must ask &quot;certain questions&quot; in determining whether Aboriginal rights have been interfered with: 
<blockquote>
[f]irst, is the limitation unreasonable?  Second, does the regulation impose undue hardship?  Third, does the regulation deny to the holders of the right their preferred means of exercising that right? ... [T]he test involves asking whether either the purpose or the effect of the restriction on net length unnecessarily infringes the interests protected by the fishing right.<sup><a href="#fortythree">43</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This standard does not need to be very high---the Court refers to the demonstration of  &quot;some negative effect.&quot;<sup><a href ="#fortyfour">44</a></sup> Under a broad and generous interpretation of s. 35(1), which views the right with sensitivity &quot;to the aboriginal perspective ... on the meaning of the rights at stake,&quot;<sup><a href="#fortyfive">45</a></sup> a court should not encounter a great deal of difficulty finding that requiring an Aboriginal person to travel to the nearest licensing bureau in order to be permitted to fish, rather than allowing that person to simply put his net in the water when he wishes, denies that person his preferred means of exercising the right.<sup><a href="#fortysix">46</a></sup> Further, if one considers <i>prima facie</i> interference with Aboriginal rights in the light of fiduciary principles, it becomes clear that the threshold must not be very high at all. 
<p>
To outline how fiduciary principles come into play under s. 35(1), I return to the idea stated above that it is the Crown's fiduciary obligation that polices the border between Aboriginal rights and governmental power. The fiduciary obligation means that when the government exercises its power, it must do so in a way that upholds its duty to act in a &quot;trust-like, rather than adversarial&quot; manner;<sup><a href="#fortyseven">47</a></sup> federal power must be reconciled with federal duty. When considering the `test' for <i>prima facie</i> interference under s. 35(1), it is important to consider what the beneficiary of a fiduciary obligation, in private law, must show when she alleges a breach of that obligation. In particular, a beneficiary need not even show that she has been harmed
by the breach. As La Forest J. pointed out in <cite>Lac Minerals v. International Corona Resources</cite>, &quot;[f]iduciary law, being concerned with the exaction of a duty of loyalty, does not require
that harm in the particular case be shown to have resulted.&quot;<sup><a href="#fortyeight">48</a></sup> I will discuss
below why the Court determined that, in the case of s. 35(1), a rightholder must show some harm, but my point here is that since fiduciary law does not generally require any harm to be shown, the threshold that the Court proposes should be interpreted to be quite low.
<p>
The Court phrases certain aspects of this test of  <i>prima facie</i> infringement in terms that suggest that s. 35(1) requires more than a showing that an Aboriginal right has been interfered with: the Justices refer to &quot;unreasonable,&quot;  &quot;undue&quot; and &quot;unnecessary&quot; infringements of Aboriginal rights. The Court seems to be suggesting that the plaintiff has the responsibility for showing that the infringement is unreasonable or unnecessary, which is entirely out of keeping with the adjudication of rights.<sup><a href="#fortynine">49</a></sup> Under the <cite>Charter</cite>, for example, the plaintiff only has to show the effect the impugned legislation has on <i>him</i>, not whether this effect can somehow be justified in the grand scheme of things.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> The Court cannot be taken to be holding that under s. 35(1), the plaintiff must show the unnecessariness or the unreasonableness of the regulation in question simply to get into court in the first place. Not only would such an approach place a heavy burden on the plaintiff just to get through the door, but the evidence required to show &quot;unreasonableness&quot; is likely to be in the government's possession, not the
plaintiff's.<sup><a href="#fiftyone">51</a></sup> &quot;Unnecessary&quot; and &quot;unreasonable,&quot;  then, must be
taken to be words attempting to prevent frivolous or vexatious uses of s. 35(1), and not to be imposing standards of justification.
<p>
The Court supports this interpretation later in its judgment when, in rejecting the `public interest' justification of infringements of s. 35(1), it comments that &quot;the fact that the objective is of a `reasonable' nature cannot suffice as constitutional recognition and affirmation of aboriginal rights.&quot;<sup><a href="#fiftytwo">52</a></sup>  It cannot be the law that while `reasonableness' is <i>insufficient</i> to justify an infringement of an Aboriginal right,
`reasonableness' <i>is</i> sufficient to pre-empt the justification analysis in the first place. Such a result could hardly be consonant with s. 35(1)'s purpose of reversing the problem of ignoring and failing to honour Aboriginal rights.<sup><a href="#fiftythree">53</a></sup> It is worth keeping in mind, however, that the Court's use of the word &quot;unreasonable&quot;  here, given that s. 1 of the <cite>Charter</cite> uses the word <cite>reasonable</cite> as the touchstone for a justifiable limit, has the potential to blur the two stages of analysis.
<p>
JUSTIFYING LIMITATIONS: THE PUBLIC FIDUCIARY STANDARD
<p>
Dickson C.J.C. and La Forest J. write that: 
<blockquote>
the honour of the Crown is at stake in dealings with aboriginal peoples. The special trust relationship and the
responsibility of the government vis-&agrave;-vis aboriginals must be the first consideration in determining whether the legislation or action in question can be justified.<sup><a href="#fiftyfour">54</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The fiduciary obligation, then, is the primary reference point for justification, and must inform the entire process.
Immediately following this strong statement, however, the Court notes that this presents a problem in the context of the government's legislative power: &quot;[t]he constitutional recognition and affirmation of aboriginal rights may give rise to conflict with the interests of others given the limited nature of the resource.&quot;<sup><a href="#fiftyfive">55</a></sup> In raising these two points together, the Court identifies the problem implicit in the concept of infusing government action with a fiduciary duty: how can the government, whose role is to act in the interests of all, also act with a duty of utmost loyalty toward Aboriginal people?  
<p>
The Court relies on its earlier decision in <cite>Guerin</cite> in contemplating the government's fiduciary obligation. In that case Dickson J. found that land surrendered to the federal Crown for sale or other disposition, under s. 18(1) of the <cite>Indian Act</cite><sup><a href="#fiftysix">56</a></sup>, was impressed with a fiduciary obligation. This obligation is rooted in the Royal Proclamation which, in asserting European sovereignty
over lands traditionally occupied by Aboriginal peoples, interposed the Crown between Aboriginal holders of title and third parties. If a band sought to dispose of its land, as the Musqueam Band sought to do in <cite>Guerin</cite>, it first had to surrender title to the Crown, and the Crown would then have the discretion to dispose of the land as it saw fit. As Dickson J. stated, &quot;... Parliament has conferred a discretion upon the Crown to decide for itself where the Indians' best interests really lie.&quot;<sup><a href="#fiftyseven">57</a></sup> While Dickson J.'s formulation of the obligation is rather paternalistic in this passage, he underlines the Crown's power in
this relationship. It is the broad power of the Crown that is reined in by the fiduciary obligation.
<p>
When considering the evolution of the fiduciary concept from the circumstances of  <cite>Guerin</cite> to those in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, at least one crucial difference is obvious. When the Musqueam surrendered their land to the Crown for lease in <cite>Guerin</cite>, there was no reason for any broader public interest to inform the Crown's actions because it was simply acting in the place of the Band in dealing with the golf club. The Crown's role was very similar to that of a private trustee, and its role was to act solely in the interests of the Band. In <cite>Sparrow</cite>, however, as noted above, the legislature cannot act with utmost loyalty because the public
interest <i>is</i> implicated in the regulation of the fisheries. As such, the nature of the fiduciary duty discussed in <cite>Sparrow</cite> must be different from the duty breached in <cite>Guerin</cite>, even though the source is the same: the government's assumption, through the assertion of sovereignty, of rights that historically inhered in
Aboriginal peoples themselves.
<p>
The concept of justification is not itself incompatible with fiduciary principles. For example, a beneficiary &quot;is perfectly free to permit&quot; a fiduciary's conflict of interest, so long as the fiduciary proves that he fully informed the beneficiary of the circumstances.<sup><a href="#fiftyeight">58</a></sup> In <cite>Sparrow</cite>, the government-as-fiduciary is clearly in a conflict of interest, because in regulating the fishery for the benefit of the public at large, it
is seeking to further an objective other than the benefit of Aboriginal people and, in doing so, is purporting to act both for an Aboriginal people <i>and</i> for the other group---a classic conflict of interest situation.<sup><a href="#fiftynine">59</a></sup>
<p>
In dealing with this problem, Dickson C.J.C. and La Forest J. allow for three adjustments of standard fiduciary principles. First, the prerequisite of a <i>prima facie</i> infringement requires that some effect on an Aboriginal group be shown before requiring the fiduciary to answer for it. Second, the Crown is permitted to hold an interest
other than that of the beneficiary (the Aboriginal group) to be of primary import. Instead of demanding strict loyalty from the Crown, the Court allows the public interest to be taken into account when considering legislative action, and finds that conservation measures must take priority over Aboriginal interests.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> Third, the Court imposes a duty of consultation on the Crown. In this way, the Court takes the possibility of justification under fiduciary principles, and the <cite>Charter</cite> justification analysis with which it is familiar, and creatively synthesizes them to protect both Aboriginal rights and the public interest.
<p>
While the standard the Court imposes is very strict,<sup><a href="#sixtyone">61</a></sup> it is important to note that it is not as strict as the standard demanded from fiduciaries in private law. It resembles, instead, a half-way point between the fiduciary standard and the `good faith' standard,<sup><a href="#sixtytwo">62</a></sup> and I will refer to it as the `public fiduciary standard.'  The standard is higher than good faith, because the Court clearly conceives that the legislature must make positive efforts to preserve Aboriginal rights, as opposed to simply having regard for them; further, while the `good faith' standard can apply to adversaries in a bargaining context, the Crown here is expressly
forbidden from acting as an adversary.<sup><a href="#sixtythree">63</a></sup> The Court goes on to give examples of questions to be asked when considering the validity of legislation: is the Aboriginal right minimally infringed?  has fair compensation been awarded in the case of an expropriation?  has consultation occurred?<sup><a href="#sixtyfour">64</a></sup> The Court emphasizes that this is not an exhaustive list. Different circumstances of the exercise of legislative power will give rise to different issues to be addressed. The general principle of the &quot;honour of the Crown,&quot; however, suggests that fiduciary standards should be observed whenever possible, to be reduced to the public fiduciary standard only when circumstances make it impossible to uphold such a high level of loyalty. 
<p>
The duty of consultation is, in my view, an appropriate means by which the government's duty to the public may be reconciled with its duty to Aboriginal peoples. The fiduciary obligation is rooted in the Crown's assertion of control over something that rightfully belongs to Aboriginal people. In the context of <cite>Guerin</cite>, for example, the interposition of the Crown between the Musqueam and the Shaughnessy Golf Club has taken away the Musqueam's own ability to simply sell or otherwise dispose of their interest in land. This ability, recognized in cases such as <cite>Calder v. Attorney-General (British Columbia)</cite>, is not an interest &quot;depend[ent] on treaty, executive order or legislative enactment.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixtyfive">65</a></sup> Similarly, in extending the fiduciary obligation to the government's legislative power, the Supreme Court recognized the fact that were it not for the assertion of Crown sovereignty, Aboriginal people themselves would exercise a similar power over their lives today. The fiduciary obligation attaches because of the &quot;historic powers and responsibility assumed by the Crown&quot; over Aboriginal peoples.<sup><a href="#sixtysix">66</a></sup>
When the Court imposed a duty of consultation on the government, it recognized this assumption of power and that the government was in a compromised position in having to uphold both its fiduciary obligation to the Musqueam as well as its obligation to act in the public interest. 
<p>
By requiring the government to consult with the Aboriginal groups whose rights will be affected by a legislative measure, the Court is reducing the conflict of interest situation entailed by the government's position by enabling Aboriginal people to have a say in the protection of their rights under s. 35(1). Consultation, then, is a crucial aspect of the discharge of the Crown's fiduciary duty and must be meaningful.
<p>
To summarize this treatment of <cite>Sparrow</cite>, I would like to emphasize two aspects of the decision that face future courts. The first is that a court must give significant weight to the perspective of the Aboriginal group asserting the right, so as to give meaning to the phrase &quot;integral to their distinctive culture.&quot;  In doing so, it must avoid looking at the right from a majoritarian perspective, or through the distorting lens of existing regulations. The second aspect is that while the Court determines that Aboriginal rights cannot be absolute in their constitutionalized form, a rigorous test of justification must be applied to legislation or regulation attempting to curtail their exercise. A simple claim that the `public interest' demands it is insufficient: the government must
demonstrate that it has upheld its duty as a `public fiduciary.'  The list of questions the Court proposes is not exhaustive, nor cast in stone, but the duty of consultation is a vital element in ensuring that the government has discharged its fiduciary duty.
<p>
<center><h3>Part Two: The British Columbia Court of Appeal and <cite>Sparrow</cite></h3></center>
<b>1. Introduction</b>
<p>
This part of the article will explore the British Columbia Court of Appeal's approach to these two aspects of <cite>Sparrow</cite>. My thesis is that after setting itself on a potentially powerful direction in the early parts of <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>, the majority of the Court lost its way by overlooking the substance behind the
phrases &quot;integral part of their distinctive culture&quot; and &quot;honour of the Crown.&quot;  Each of the cases I will be discussing addresses a different facet of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s challenge, with <cite>Van der
Peet</cite> dealing with the content of Aboriginal rights, <cite>Nikal</cite> concerning infringement of and limitations on rights, and <cite>Gladstone</cite> touching on both. Before discussing these cases, I will
briefly deal with <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> which, while not the subject of this article, set an important foundation for the fishing rights cases in adopting <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s interpretive lens.
<p>
DELGAMUUKW
<p>
The subject matter of this case is of enormous moment, and gave rise to correspondingly wide-ranging decisions from both the British Columbia Supreme Court and Court of Appeal. The Court of Appeal accepted that Aboriginal rights to the land were not extinguished by the colonial instruments known as the `<cite>Calder</cite> XIII,'<sup><a href="#sixtyseven">67</a></sup> but rejected the claim that these rights amounted to ownership, on the grounds that previous case law had conclusively determined that Aboriginal title could not constitute ownership<sup><a href="#sixtyeight">68</a></sup> because it did not amount to exclusive occupation.<sup><a href="#sixtynine">69</a></sup> The Court also rejected the Gitksan Wet'suwet'en's assertion of governmental power on similar grounds, holding that the
trial judge was correct to have concluded that the plaintiffs were asserting legislative power, and since the division of powers between the federal and provincial governments was exhaustive, it was &quot;inconceivable&quot; that an Aboriginal power of government could have survived.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup>
<p>
The only comment I would like to make on <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> concerns its treatment of  &quot;the Aboriginal perspective&quot; and the determination of Aboriginal rights by reference to &quot;that which is integral to their distinctive culture.&quot;  I suggested above that these phrases are the touchstones arising from the <cite>Sparrow</cite> decision to be used by courts in considering Aboriginal rights. In <cite>Sparrow</cite>,
however, these phrases only come up in passing commentary by the Court, and are not discussed in much detail. Instead, it is in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> where the phrases are seized upon by the British Columbia Court of Appeal and transformed into the defining characteristics of Aboriginal rights, with Macfarlane J.A. emphasizing and repeating that  &quot;[t]he nature and content of an aboriginal right is determined by asking what the organized <i>aboriginal society regarded</i> as `an integral part of their distinctive culture'.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventyone">71</a></sup> [Emphasis added.]
<p>
If these phrases are considered with a view to taking Aboriginal rights seriously, they have the potential to give meaningful protection to Aboriginal rights. Macfarlane J.A.'s adoption of these phrases, then, could constitute a significant advance in providing this protection. <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> itself, however, gives some clue about how the Court of Appeal majority chose to apply these phrases as a `test' for Aboriginal rights. For example, under the heading of  &quot;Ownership,&quot; Macfarlane J.A. deals with the trial judge's treatment of the proof of ownership the plaintiffs had provided, noting that &quot;he discounted them considerably because of the process
by which they were prepared: these affidavits incorporated the opinions of members of the plaintiffs' community which have been exposed over the years to heated and biased discussion about the land claims controversy. This cast doubt on their utility in establishing a reputation of the plaintiffs' use and ownership of the territory.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventytwo">72</a></sup>
<p>
If a court is able to discount the worth of the evidence provided by the Aboriginal people concerned because it is `biased,' it is difficult to see how appropriate weight could ever be given to their perspective, as suggested by <cite>Sparrow</cite>. Indeed, it seems suspicious to discount Aboriginal evidence due to `bias':  how could
<i>any</i> of the witnesses involved in a case such as <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> be un-`biased,' given the philosophical and political challenges it presents?  The Court compounds this problem, in the very next paragraph, with its treatment of the evidence of a non-Aboriginal settler. In adopting McEachern C.J.S.C.'s view on ownership, the Court repeats his finding that:
<blockquote>
it is impossible to infer a community reputation for an interest in land when a prominent, life-long resident in the area like Mr. Shelford, a member of the legislature for many years, and a Cabinet minister for a time, who acknowledges hearing about general land claims for a long time, has never heard until very recently of claims of ownership or jurisdiction, or claims to specific lands, including his own, by chiefs whose family he has known personally for most of his life.<sup><a href="#seventythree">73</a></sup>
</blockquote>
What is it that makes Mr. Shelford's evidence <i>un</i>biased and the Gitksan-Wet'su-wet'en's evidence biased?  The Court appears to be suggesting that Mr. Shelford is somehow an uninterested observer, and, since he is a prominent member of the community (whose?), a Cabinet minister, and has lived there his whole life, he is a superior witness. Yet McEachern C.J.S.C. notes that Mr. Shelford's <i>own</i> land is the subject of the action. How can accepting the evidence of one non-Aboriginal settler over the evidence of a group of Aboriginal plaintiffs have anything to do with  &quot;be[ing] sensitive to the Aboriginal perspective&quot;?
<p>
This small passage from <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> is an example of the general problem of characterization that the Court of Appeal must deal with in the three cases I will be discussing here, because the Court is in the position of defining Aboriginal culture for legal purposes. Adjudicating s. 35 involves exercising the power of characterization: above, we have the characterization of some witnesses as `biased'; in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, the Court characterized the Musqueam right as a right to fish for  &quot;food, social and ceremonial purposes.&quot;  Many other questions are created by Macfarlane J.A.'s conception of Aboriginal rights. When is something &quot;integral&quot;? What makes Aboriginal culture &quot;distinctive&quot;?  When is an asserted right an &quot;evolved&quot; form of a &quot;traditional&quot; Aboriginal right, that may be protected by s. 35, and when is an asserted right a `new' right that is not?  What <i>is</i> Aboriginal culture?  Is it something that must be considered in isolation from all external influences (and what would make these influences `external'?), or does it encompass all aspects of the life of people who call themselves Aboriginal?  
<p>
It goes without saying that these are not simple questions to answer, and the context of litigation is not a particularly fortuitous one in which to try. <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s implication that the Aboriginal perspective is the relevant one constitutes an attempt to deal with these questions unencumbered by non-Aboriginal views on Aboriginal culture. <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s holding that rights must not be limited to their present-day regulated form is another expression of this objective, in that regulations imposed by non-Aboriginal governments on all Canadians have nothing to do with Aboriginal society. Compounding this challenge is the fact that the Canadian judiciary's experience in `defining' Aboriginal culture prior to s. 35's entrenchment is rooted in the `Indianness' test forwarded in the cases dealing with s. 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>. In order to see the similarity in thought process, yet dramatic difference in context, between determining `Indianness' and determining the content of Aboriginal rights, it is useful to consider s. 88.
<p>
THE LEGACY OF SECTION 88
<p>
Since s. 91(24) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite><sup><a href="#seventyfour">74</a></sup> provides the federal
government with exclusive jurisdiction over  &quot;Indians and land reserved for Indians,&quot; provincial laws concerning, for example, motor vehicle or fishing regulation cannot apply on reserve land. Section 88 provides for the application of provincial laws to Aboriginal people if they are &quot;laws of general application.&quot;  To
determine whether a law is of general application, a two-stage test was developed in the Supreme Court: first, the court must decide whether the law impinges on `Indianness' or the status and capacity of being an Indian, and second, it must decide whether the law's policy or intent was to alter or affect this core of `Indianness.'<sup><a href="#seventyfive">75</a></sup> Although these cases do not squarely raise questions of the content of Aboriginal rights,
they did put the Court in a position of deciding, for legal purposes, what characteristics of Indian life are considered to be `truly Indian.'  The Court determined that `traditional' Indian activities were considered to be at the core of Indianness, such as certain hunting practices in <cite>Kruger and Manuel</cite>, while activities seen to be non-Indian in nature, such as manufacturing in <cite>Four B Manufacturing</cite>, were ruled to be outside this core.
<p>
Four B Manufacturing was a company, owned by the Brant brothers, operating a shoe factory on the Tyendinaga reserve at the Bay of Quinte. The United Garment Workers of America had been certified by the Ontario Labour Relations Board as the exclusive bargaining agent for the factory's employees, and Four B sought to have the
certification order quashed, arguing that the <cite>Ontario Labour Relations Act</cite> could not apply to the company's activities because it impinged on federal jurisdiction under s. 91(24). In the heart of the decision, Beetz J. makes two points: first, because the context here is not restricted to the Mohawks but also includes the rights of
non-Indian workers, as well as labour relations in general in the province, Four B's enterprise cannot be considered to be solely relating to Indians. Second, even if  &quot;the situation is <i>considered from the sole point of view of Indian employees</i> and as if the employer were an Indian, neither Indian status is at stake nor rights so closely connected with Indian status that they should be regarded as necessary incidents of status such for instance as
registrability, membership in a band, the right to participate in the election of chiefs and band councils, reserve privileges, etc.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventysix">76</a></sup> [emphasis added.]
<p>
The second point is of great concern. Beetz J. suggests that he is considering the situation from the point of view of the Mohawk employees, and yet his view of what makes an Indian an Indian is informed solely by the terms of the <cite>Indian Act</cite> itself: he relies on matters related to `Indian status' under that Act. I think it is important to keep this slippery vantage point in mind. Even if it was in any way valid, in 1979, to consider `Indianness' to be
determinable by reference to laws creating the status of `Indian,' it is clearly unacceptable to do so now, given <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s conclusion that the rights recognized and affirmed in s. 35(1) are not defined by their present regulated state. Further, the idea that a particular aspect of Indian life cannot be &quot;so closely connected&quot; to being an Indian must be regarded as a highly controversial one, and <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> and the companion cases can be properly seen as part of an ongoing struggle for the power of definition. <cite>Sparrow</cite>, however, firmly asks the question: if we are to view Aboriginal rights from the perspective of the Aboriginal rightholders, how is it legally valid to take away the ability of self-definition from the Aboriginal people involved?  `Leakage' from pre-<cite>Sparrow</cite> law, such as the ideas contained in the s. 88 cases, should concern us.
<p>
<b> 2. The Content of Aboriginal Rights: Van der Peet and Gladstone</b>
<p>
FISHING RIGHTS REVISITED
<p>
A few comments about the concept of commercial rights to fish are in order, since all of the cases deal with fishing, all but one involve the sale of fish products, and the cases are all cast against the backdrop of `illegal' trade in fish by Aboriginal people.<sup><a href="#seventyseven">77</a></sup> Control over the fisheries is a highly controversial issue. It may be that the only way to effectively resolve the issue of who has the ability to sell fish and with what priority is through negotiation. Regardless of the eventual answer to the question, commercial fishing pushes a court, perhaps more than other issues, to give meaning to <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s promise that Aboriginal rights be taken seriously, that they be viewed through the eyes of the Aboriginal claimants involved, and that they not be defined by reference to their present regulated state. The fishery is highly regulated in present-day British Columbia. As a result, when one looks at commercial fishing, one is forced to look at it through many layers of regulation, because the non-Aboriginal commercial fishery has always been regulated. There is a danger that the courts may reason that because the activities giving rise to these cases are illegal <i>today</i>, there cannot be an Aboriginal right to engage in them.<sup><a href="#seventyeight">78</a></sup> The fact remains, however, that <cite>Sparrow</cite> requires a court to strip away the layers of non-Aboriginal regulation and view the right in its original form.<sup><a href="#seventynine">79</a></sup>
<p>
 A. <cite>Van der Peet</cite>
<p>
Dorothy Van der Peet's case raises highly controversial issues from very modest circumstances: she was charged under the <cite>British Columbia Fishery (General) Regulations</cite> when she sold two salmon to a friend. At trial, she raised her Aboriginal rights as a member of the Sto:Lo Nation in her defence. Scarlett P.C.J. rejected this defence, holding that the Sto:Lo had no such Aboriginal right. On appeal to the British Columbia County Court, Selbie J. reversed, finding that Mrs. Van der Peet was exercising a `modernized' form of the Sto:Lo's traditional Aboriginal rights. The Crown appealed, and the Court of Appeal, in a narrow majority, agreed with the trial judge's decision that the Sto:Lo had no Aboriginal right to sell fish. This case engages the first part of <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s analysis, as outlined above: what does s. 35 protect?  It also takes a step beyond <cite>Sparrow</cite>, since in Mrs. Van der Peet's case, there was significant disagreement over the historical
evidence required to prove the right.
<p>
In <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>, Macfarlane J.A. noted the danger that old, inappropriate legal concepts could be unconsciously applied to Aboriginal cases in a way that would fail to uphold the purposes of s. 35(1).<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> In contemplating what might be occurring &quot;unconsciously&quot; in a decision, it is important to consider the language judges use, or do not use, to describe the concepts and issues raised in a case.<sup><a href="#eightyone">81</a></sup> One notable aspect of the Court's decision in <cite>Van der Peet</cite> is that although Macfarlane J.A. emphasizes that &quot;the Aboriginal perspective&quot; is crucial in resolving s. 35(1) issues in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>, he does not mention this perspective at all in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>.<sup><a href="#eightytwo">82</a></sup> Indeed, he does not mention the concept of perspective once in the entire decision,
implying that there is somehow an objective point of view from which to adjudicate Mrs. Van der Peet's rights. His acceptance of the trial judge's view that when Mrs. Van der Peet's ancestors began trading with the British, they were engaging in something &quot;clearly different in nature and quantity from aboriginal activity&quot;<sup><a href="#eightythree"> 83</a></sup> underlines this notion, and makes it necessary to examine exactly what made it so obvious for the trial judge that Mrs. Van der Peet was not exercising an Aboriginal right.
<p>
<i>At trial</i>
<br>
The &quot;unconscious&quot; workings of Scarlett P.C.J.'s mind in <cite>Van der Peet</cite> are perhaps best encapsulated by his use of the troubling phrase &quot;aboriginal times,&quot; which Macfarlane J.A. also uses.<sup><a href="#eightyfour">84</a></sup> He writes that &quot;no regularized trade in salmon existed in aboriginal times. Such trade as took place was either for ceremonial purposes or opportunistic exchanges taking place on a casual basis. Such trade as did take place was incidental only.&quot;<sup><a href="#eightyfive">85</a></sup> Now, what exactly are &quot;aboriginal times&quot;? While the phrase may simply serve the relatively harmless purpose of identifying the pre-contact era, it suggests that we are no longer in Aboriginal Times. It suggests that we are now in `European times,' and that Aboriginal culture is now to be defined by reference to the pre-contact era <i>only</i>, which was not the Supreme Court's view in <cite>Sparrow</cite>.<sup><a href="#eightysix">86</a></sup> The Supreme Court firmly rejected the `frozen rights' theory partly because it imposed an arbitrary time limit---1982---on the development of Aboriginal rights.<sup><a href="eightyseven">87</a></sup> Relying on the assertion of sovereignty as the `cut-off' for
the development of these rights imposes a similarly arbitrary limit, and is just as external to Aboriginal culture as was the date on which s. 35(1) was entrenched. It also accords, in my view, an overstated importance to the arrival of European settlers, similar to McEachern C.J.S.C.'s preference of Mr. Shelford's evidence over that of the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en, that is inconsonant with the idea of viewing the practice from the perspective of the Aboriginal people involved. Such an attitude is also not in keeping with <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s holding that Aboriginal rights must be allowed to `evolve' and must be affirmed in a contemporary manner.
<p>
In addition to imposing this arbitrary cut-off, Scarlett P.C.J. performed some intriguing characterization operations on the right Mrs. Van der Peet asserted. He held that whatever trade the Sto:Lo might have engaged in prior to contact, it was merely &quot;opportunistic&quot; and not &quot;regularized.&quot;  In <cite>Sparrow</cite>, the
Supreme Court did not provide a very compelling reason for defining the right as one to fish for &quot;food, social, and ceremonial purposes&quot; rather than, for example, as a `right to fish.'  Here, Scarlett P.C.J. also exercises the court's power of definition: by calling the trade in fish &quot;opportunistic,&quot; he suggests that it was insufficient to constitute an Aboriginal right. But this holding simply begs the question. How does he know, for example, that the Sto:Lo do not have a right to `trade opportunistically' in fish, whatever that might mean?  Why does the trade need to have been extensive?  More importantly, how can he state categorically that what Mrs. Van der Peet, and the Sto:Lo Nation in general, do today cannot constitute a `modern' form of their Aboriginal right to trade in fish, however it is defined?  Scarlett P.C.J. says that the practice, in &quot;aboriginal times,&quot; was &quot;clearly different&quot; from their post-contact activity.<sup><a href="#eightyeight">88</a></sup> But if all Mrs.
Van der Peet did was sell two fish to her friend, is this act not an &quot;opportunistic&quot; sale, totally in keeping with the judge's characterization of the right?  Similarly, why is it that the arrival of hungry White settlers on the British Columbia coast cannot be characterized as the biggest opportunity for trade the Sto:Lo had ever encountered?
<p>
Scarlett P.C.J.'s decision also underlines courts' seeming inability to manage the evidence that might be adduced to demonstrate the meaning of the right, which may differ from the evidence to which they are accustomed.<sup><a href="#eightnine">89</a></sup> Essentially, Mrs. Van der Peet is faulted because her ancestors did not keep records sufficient to satisfy the trial judge. Scarlett P.C.J. deals with the evidence provided on behalf of Mrs. Van der Peet, saying at the outset that &quot;[c]aution had to be exercised in weighing the evidence of Natives which relied upon childhood
experience and recollection and expert opinion derived from subjective observation and analysis of such
recollection,&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> and concluding that &quot;[w]hile such evidence is always interesting and often fascinating, it embodied heresay [sic] often unrelated to or at variance to such historical record as was available.&quot;<sup><a href ="#ninetyone">91</a></sup> To suggest that the oral history related to the Sto:Lo witnesses contradicted the &quot;historical record&quot; is to suggest that oral history is not history at all. It is the evidence of the anthropological experts that sways the court.<sup><a href="#ninetytwo">92</a></sup> And yet every expert who testified, according to Scarlett P.C.J., said that the Sto:Lo <i>did</i> trade in salmon, and it is not clear what, other than the arrival of the Hudson's Bay Company, makes that trade so different from the modern-day sale of fish. 
<P>
<i>On Appeal: Macfarlane J.A.'s Majority Opinion</i>
<br>
Macfarlane J.A. fails to resolve any of these difficulties, and this failure must be considered all the more
serious given his emphasis on adopting the Aboriginal perspective in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>. In <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, one might have expected some commentary on Scarlett P.C.J.'s treatment of the evidence of the
Sto:Lo witnesses, as compared to that of the expert witnesses, especially given that the summary appeal judge thought that Scarlett P.C.J.'s opinion was coloured by irrelevant considerations.<sup><a href="#ninetythree">93</a></sup> While appeal courts consistently decide that they should not overturn a trial court's finding of fact, I believe that it would have been highly appropriate for Macfarlane J.A. to make some comment about the trial judge's approach to the facts before him. That said, however, Macfarlane J.A.'s own view of the issue is even more problematic
because of what he adds and takes away from the <cite>Sparrow</cite> analysis.
<p>
One aspect of Macfarlane J.A.'s decision that is immediately notable is the revival of the frozen rights fallacy. He asks whether &quot;there [is] a commercial aspect to the aboriginal right to fish which was an integral part of the distinctive culture of the Sto:lo people?&quot;<sup><a href="#ninetyfour">94</a></sup> This formulation is accurate, but he then adds that he 
<blockquote>
put[s] the question that way because this case is not about the casual disposal of surplus food fish. In essence, it is about an asserted Indian right to sell fish allocated for food purposes on a commercial basis. The result would be to give Indian fishers a preference or priority over other Canadians who seek a livelihood from commercial fishing.<sup><a href="#ninetyfive">95</a></sup>
</blockquote>
By defining the right in this way---to sell fish, allocated for one purpose, for another purpose---Macfarlane J.A. reads the regulation into the right. The Aboriginal right to fish, while it may have aspects of self-regulation, is not about `allocation': that is the sole creation of the Department of Fisheries and Oceans (DFO). What is it that makes fish &quot;surplus food fish&quot;?  If the sale of fish is necessary to the Sto:Lo's survival, for example, then it is
not `surplus': it is only surplus because the numbers have exceeded the DFO allocation for the Sto:Lo fishers. But allocation has little to do with the Aboriginal right. This characterization of the right, performed with no attempt to extricate himself from the heavily-regulated fisheries context, aids Macfarlane J.A. in finding that the Sto:Lo have no such right. This conclusion is not surprising, however, because he has basically suggested that the Sto:Lo are asserting a right to be law-breakers, rather than a right to observe the dictates of their own culture.<sup><a href="#ninetysix">96</a></sup>
<p>
At bottom, the issue in {\itl Van der Peet} and the other commercial fishing cases is whether the dramatic increase in Aboriginal trade in fish following the arrival of European traders, even if it were shown that the Europeans are the `cause' of present-day Aboriginal trade in fish, can be determinative of Aboriginal rights protected by
s. 35(1). The issue is fundamentally about characterization. Is the &quot;opportunistic&quot; trade practised prior to the arrival of the Europeans <i>different</i> from the trade with the Hudson's Bay Company and other settlers?  The key to Macfarlane J.A.'s response to this question is his holding that &quot;[i]t is ... necessary to separate those traditions from practices which are not a unique part of Indian culture, but which are common to Indian and non-Indian alike.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninetyseven">97</a></sup> He says:
<blockquote>
The summary appeal judge was of the opinion that social changes altered the content of the aboriginal right; and that the occasional and rudimentary practice of exchanging fish in the aboriginal community blossomed, with the arrival of the British, into a full blown right to fish to supply a non-Indian market. I recognize that the arrival of the Europeans brought new customs, new ways and new incentives; but that does not mean the unique nature of
aboriginal traditions had to conform to the practices of the British, or what they encouraged the Indians to do would shape and construct a new right for the Indians. As a practical consequence the aborigines probably began to adjust to those changes. Undoubtedly they began to sell fish on a commercial scale. But that practice, which had not
been integral to the organized society and its distinctive culture, and which was induced and driven by European influences ought not, in my opinion, to qualify for protection and priority as an aboriginal right.<sup><a href="#ninetyeight">98</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This passage indicates Macfarlane J.A.'s total subscription to the &quot;aboriginal times&quot; notion, and thus, his adoption of a `frozen' attitude toward Aboriginal rights. To say that &quot;the unique nature of aboriginal traditions [did not have] to conform to the practices of the British&quot; is to suggest that they had a choice to remain in &quot;aboriginal times&quot; and because they did not, they gave up their ability to further `modernize' their culture. Furthermore, it is to find that Aboriginal trade with the British was solely a product of British culture and could therefore not have anything to do with Aboriginal practices. Yet trade, by its very nature, requires two sides, and to say that it was &quot;induced and driven by European influences&quot; is to overlook Aboriginal peoples' role in the inception and success of the trading posts. Macfarlane J.A.'s conclusion above is driven by his concept that a practice which is a part of European culture cannot be part of an Aboriginal right <i>even if</i> the practice is common to both Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal culture. 
<p>
This attitude flows from Macfarlane J.A.'s initial approach to the `test' of what is integral to Aboriginal people's distinctive culture. He appears to have interpreted this to mean that if something is integral to a culture other than that of Aboriginal people, it cannot be part of Aboriginal people's <i>distinctive</i> culture, because that which makes Aboriginal culture distinctive is that which differentiates it from non-Aboriginal culture. This view is, to put it bluntly, wrong, and it is wrong for several reasons. 
<p>
First of all, it is wrong on purely textual terms: Macfarlane J.A. is mentally substituting the word &quot;distinct&quot; for &quot;distinctive.&quot;  In the Concise Oxford English, for example, &quot;distinctive&quot; is defined as &quot;distinguishing or characteristic.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninetynine">99</a></sup> &quot;Distinct,&quot; on the other hand, is defined as &quot;1: (<i>often followed by `from'</i>) a. not identical, separate, individual; b. different in kind or quality; unlike.&quot;<sup><a href = #hundred">100</a></sup> [Emphasis added.]  While &quot;distinct&quot; mandates comparison and evaluation from a separate vantage point, &quot;distinctive&quot; requires the object to be observed on its own. While describing an object's &quot;distinctive&quot; qualities may entail describing how the object is different from others (that is,
&quot;distinguishing&quot;), there is nothing in the term that <i>requires</i> it to be different. To give a trivial example, when one describes a deerstalker cap's distinctive features, one is likely to refer to its ear flaps. But this does not mean that no other hat has such a distinctive feature, or that this fact makes the deerstalker any less a deerstalker. All that &quot;distinctive&quot; entails is identification, not differentiation. 
<p>
Second, in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, where the phrase was coined, the Supreme Court emphasized that one of the purposes of s. 35(1) was to bring Aboriginal rights into the constitutional framework and to give these
rights legal force. The Court reiterated this attitude of integration and recognition when it indicated that &quot;general principles of constitutional interpretation&quot; were appropriately applied to s. 35(1).<sup><a href="#hundredone">101</a></sup> The Court's description of the political process of getting Aboriginal rights taken seriously strongly suggests, in my view, that the Court's intention was to recognize the distinctiveness of Aboriginal rights while, at the same time, integrating them into the constitutional framework. In short, the Court's view relied on the idea of integration, not separation, even as it recognized and affirmed `unique' rights. It was certainly not <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s intention to define Aboriginal culture as that which is left over after one takes away non-Aboriginal culture, which brings me to the final reason for rejecting Macfarlane J.A.'s view.
<p>
As described earlier, part of the reason for rejecting the `frozen rights' approach in <cite>Sparrow</cite> was that Aboriginal rights could not be defined by reference to regulations, because these are external to Aboriginal culture. Saying that what is common to both Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal culture must necessarily be non-Aboriginal and <i>not</i> Aboriginal is, to say the least, an overly Eurocentric approach. As Lambert J.A. later points out, presumably the European settlers had previously fished for food in Europe, but no one has suggested that Aboriginal people cannot hold a right to fish for food as well.<sup><a href="#hundredtwo">102</a></sup> Simply put, what is it that requires the common elements to disappear from the Aboriginal culture, rather than from non-Aboriginal culture? More importantly, why can distinctive features not be shared among cultures in s. 35(1) analysis?  
<p>
In suggesting that it is the Aboriginal practice which loses its identity, Macfarlane J.A. is not stating anything mandated by the nature of Aboriginal rights, but rather is enunciating a majoritarian attitude toward rights that denies the equality of peoples. We might consider this point as follows: why is it that the Sto:Lo and Sheshaht, for example, can both have an Aboriginal right to fish for food, but the Sto:Lo cannot have an Aboriginal right to trade fish because such trade is common to both Sto:Lo and European culture? The Sto:Lo culture is distinctive, and distinct from the Sheshaht culture, even though they are both Aboriginal cultures. But the magical effect European influences appear to have on the rights of the Sto:Lo, an effect that other Aboriginal cultures do not have, suggests that it is not the Aboriginal culture Macfarlane J.A. is looking at, but the presence of Europeans. He defines `Indian' as `that which is not non-Indian.'  Just as he invents the requirement of `difference,' Macfarlane J.A. also invents a new vantage point for Aboriginal rights: they are whatever is left over following a comparison between Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal culture. This conclusion is a direct descendant of s. 88's legacy of defining Aboriginal culture through the perspective of non-Aboriginal sources, for which there is no normative justification in the context of
s. 35(1). Instead, the concept of taking Aboriginal rights seriously, the broad and generous approach offered by the Supreme Court in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, and the need to refer to an Aboriginal people's perspective on rights, which was emphasized in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>, all provide a normative justification for doing the very opposite of what Macfarlane J.A. and the trial judge do. I have suggested here that Macfarlane J.A.'s application of the `integral-to-the-distinctive-culture test' is thoroughly wrong, even if the `test' itself has merit. But at bottom, <cite>Sparrow</cite> still leaves us with a basic problem of characterization: how is a court able to know when something <i>is</i> integral?  Is there any principle underlying such characterizations, or will courts always
simply favour one characterization over another?  The problem lies, in my view, in the majority of the British Columbia Court of Appeal's decision to focus on practices and traditions, such as fishing for one purpose or another, rather than on something more profound. In short, the majority decided to focus on the &quot;integral parts,&quot;
rather than the &quot;distinctive culture.&quot;  Focusing on discrete parts of a culture, and separating these from the culture in which they are rooted, may enable a court to more easily translate the interests s. 35(1) protects into rights-talk, but it does not do justice to the purposes of s. 35(1). For this and other reasons, Lambert J.A. dissents from the majority opinion in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, and proposes instead a &quot;social theory&quot; of right.
<p>
<i>On Appeal: Lambert J.A.'s Dissent</i>
<br>
Lambert J.A. recognizes that the whole issue is one of characterization, and he echoes the Supreme Court's view that the right should be characterized in a way that accords with the rightholders' point of view.<sup><a href="#hundredthree">103</a></sup> He then suggests some possible approaches to Aboriginal rights, and evaluates each of them according to how well they fit in with the Aboriginal perspective in question. In his view, a particular activity could be described according to the purpose the custom served, or the way in which the custom was regulated, or according to the role the custom played in the culture in question.<sup><a href =#hundredfour">104</a></sup> He deals with the first two alternatives very briefly, rejecting the first because it would accord more with observing the culture in
question from the perspective of the settling nation rather than that of the Aboriginal group itself, and the second because while it may attempt to view the practice from the appropriate perspective, it does not recognize the underlying significance of the practice or the reason why it should be considered to be integral.<sup><a href="#hundredfive">105</a></sup>
<p>
Lambert J.A. chooses the third alternative for a variety of reasons. He believes that this theory was &quot;foreshadowed&quot; in <cite>Sparrow</cite> when the Court wrote of protecting the &quot;integral parts of their distinctive culture&quot;; that it is in keeping with Dickson J.'s analysis of the history of the fishery in <cite>Jack</cite> and that the theory is consonant with the approach taken by the American courts in adjudicating the fishing rights of Aboriginal peoples closely related to Aboriginal peoples of the west coast of British Columbia.<sup><a href ="#hundredsix">106</a></sup> He also makes the decidedly common-sense point that if the Sto:Lo have a right to fish for food, it makes no sense in the present day to confine them to eating nothing but fish; they should be able to sell the fish in order to buy other nourishment.<sup><a href = #hundredseven">107</a></sup>
<p>
In contemplating these alternatives, I think an analogy to the <cite>Charter</cite> is useful. One way of characterizing the scope of <cite>Charter</cite> protection is to say that s. 2(b), for example, does not seek to protect particular manifestations of the freedom of expression, but to protect the ability to express. While an
individual's rant on a street corner is protected by s. 2(b), the freedom is not conceptualized as the protection of all of its possible manifestations (for example, speaking in public, speaking in class, writing in a newspaper), but as the protection of the fundamental purposes for which one might express oneself. In this sense, the speech itself is actually the third layer of s. 2(b) protection; at the core, there are the goals of individual self-realization, political activity, etc., for which freedom of expression is protected; around that is the idea that these goals may be furthered by protecting expression in general; finally, there is the actual expression chosen by a particular individual at a
particular time. If we compare this structure to the opinions expressed in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, we find that Macfarlane and Wallace JJ.A. are seeking to protect only the outermost layer of the right, while Lambert J.A.'s theory chooses to protect the inner layers and <i>therefore</i> the outermost layer as well, to the extent that it is a manifestation of something more profound. 
<p>
While this conception of the <cite>Charter</cite> may not be acceptable to all, I think it is undeniable that the values inhering in the <cite>Charter</cite> are necessarily multi-layered and multi-faceted. This aspect of `<cite>Charter</cite> thinking' must be brought into contemplation of s. 35(1), even if a liberal conception of individual rights is inappropriate to s. 35(1). The Supreme Court could not outline the interests protected by s. 35(1) in the same fashion as it had done with the <cite>Charter</cite>, because of the undefined nature of s. 35(1). But Lambert J.A.'s view is that in proposing the key phrase &quot;integral parts of their distinctive culture,&quot; the Supreme Court was coming as close as it could to outlining a general principle regarding the purpose of the section, one that would accord Aboriginal rights the same protection as <cite>Charter</cite> rights, even as they flow from a different source. To the extent, then, that s. 35(1) may be informed by <cite>Charter</cite> thinking, it must also be seen as protecting not a series of individualized practices or customs, but the distinctive culture of which these practices and customs are a manifestation. If we look at Aboriginal rights in this manner, combined with Lambert J.A.'s reasoning, I think that he does provide a <i>principle</i> to guide the process of characterization.
<p>
At the end of his opinion, Lambert J.A. finds that Scarlett P.C.J.'s approach, and therefore Macfarlane J.A.'s, was incorrect because it misconceived the meaning of an Aboriginal right. He therefore does not address some of the difficulties in Scarlett P.C.J.'s analysis that I have outlined above, because his theory simply does not entail
asking questions such as `is this culture a band or a tribal culture?' or `was there or was there not regularized trade?'  He adds, however, that even if he had applied a `purpose' test to the circumstances of the case, he would have found that Mrs. Van der Peet's sale was protected by s. 35(1) because he has no difficulty concluding that the historical evidence of trade proves the existence of a system of exchange that was the precursor to present-day sale of fish,<sup><a href="#hundredeight">108</a></sup> and that such a finding is in keeping with <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s direction that aboriginal rights are not to be frozen in time. 
<p>
Lambert J.A.'s application of the `purpose' theory, however, when compared to the `social' theory, is much less satisfactory. There does not seem to be any underlying principle, so that even if one agrees with Lambert J.A.'s characterization of the present-day practice as `the same' as the historical practice, the identification is still nothing more than a label. He suggests that if a group of Aboriginal people began to trade with the English as soon as the
opportunity was available, then they could be said to be `evolving' their traditional practices. This formulation has the advantage of focusing on an Aboriginal group's view of the trade rather than on the Europeans', but it is still mired in an analysis of individual practices rather than an entire culture, and still seems to be imposing arbitrary time limits. For example, if the Sto:Lo had waited for fifty years following contact before deciding to trade
with the British, even though the opportunity had presented itself much earlier, why should that decision not be an `evolution' of an existing custom rather than the introduction of a new practice?  The fact that even Lambert J.A. cannot apply the purpose theory convincingly suggests to me that it is simply the wrong approach to take.
<p>
In the end, it is not clear whether Lambert J.A.'s `social theory' will actually avoid all of the problems identified in Scarlett P.C.J.'s analysis: for example, does the social theory make it any easier to evaluate historical evidence, whether in the form of oral history or in actual written records?  Does the time of European settlement matter?  Lambert J.A. does not offer us a way out of the problem that judges have the power of definition: it is still up to
them to decide what is and what is not an Aboriginal right when the issue comes to court. But Lambert J.A. does, at least, recognize this power, and in formulating an approach that he believes best accords with the idea of viewing the rights from the perspective of the rightholders, he is attempting to limit the influence of judges' own whims and biases in the definition of cultures most of them know little about. In summarizing his opinion, he notes in response to a comment from Wallace J.A.<sup><a href="#hundrednine">109</a></sup> that:
<blockquote>
I do not say that ``the scope and nature of aboriginal rights will vary depending upon the particular method of analysis chosen.&quot; I say that the description of the aboriginal right, though not the right itself, is affected by the perspective from which the right is viewed. I prefer a social perspective to a purpose perspective.<sup><a href="#oneten">110</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In describing the function of characterization in this way, Lambert J.A. clearly recognizes that judges have no power to <i>change</i> Aboriginal rights: all they can do is describe and attempt to define them. This attitude, in my view, best accords with the idea of `recognizing and affirming' Aboriginal rights under s. 35(1). More importantly, it emphasizes that the rights are in no way a product of the government, of judges or, as Wallace J.A. appears to cynically believe, of Aboriginal peoples' present-day material desires. They flow from Aboriginal peoples' prior occupancy and sovereignty. 
<p>
Even if one were not convinced by <cite>Van der Peet</cite> that the project Macfarlane J.A. sets for himself is a highly perilous one, <cite>Gladstone</cite> confirms it.<sup><a href="#oneeleven">111</a></sup> In order to see the problem in more vivid detail, it is important to recall why Macfarlane J.A. rejected Mrs. Van der Peet's claim: he believed that the right she was asserting could not be considered to be an Aboriginal right because it was `created' by European influences. In <cite>Gladstone</cite>, because extensive trade of the nature engaged in by the Gladstones existed long before the arrival of the Europeans, such a characterization is not available. Nonetheless, Macfarlane J.A. denies the existence of the right. His treatment of the right, then, is worthy of some analysis although I should warn at the outset that he offers very little to analyze in the mere twelve paragraphs he writes on the Gladstones' rights.
<p>
<i> B. Gladstone</i>
<p>
The Gladstones, members of the Heiltsuk Band, were arrested and charged with attempting to sell herring spawn on kelp contrary to the <cite>Pacific Herring Fishery Regulations</cite> when they were found with 4200 pounds of spawn in a U-Haul truck. It is useful to look at the evidence marshalled in the Gladstones' favour regarding the trade in spawn on kelp. In this case, unlike <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, the appellants were able to find persuasive anthropological evidence that the West Coast Indians, including the Heiltsuk, had engaged in extensive trading of this particular food. The expert witness noted that while some Aboriginal groups had access to spawn and others did not, it only made sense that they would trade. And trade they did: Hutcheon J.A. quotes from a report measuring the trade in &quot;tons,&quot; with &quot;flotillas&quot; of canoes travelling along the coast.<sup><a href="#onetwelve">112</a></sup> Similarly, Lambert J.A. quotes passages from English traders' diaries, in which they described the trade in herring spawn on kelp amongst Aboriginal people on the Coast, and with the Europeans themselves.<sup><a href ="#onethirteen">113</a></sup> There was little dispute that the Heiltsuk, along with other Aboriginal groups, had engaged in a burgeoning trade in herring spawn, even if this trade had waned during certain years.<sup><a href="#onefourteen">114</a></sup>
<p>
The trial judge held, however, that while the Heiltsuk may have had an Aboriginal right to trade and barter, this &quot;surreptitious&quot; attempt to sell a large amount of spawn was not in keeping with that right, and that the regulations were justified limitations on it. The summary appeal court judge, in similar fashion, also accepted the
existence of an Aboriginal right to trade in spawn, but held that this was not an &quot;absolute and unfettered right to harvest herring spawn in any quantity and to sell the spawn so harvested commercially.&quot;<sup><a href="#onefifteen">115</a></sup> The requirement of a licence for commercial sale was therefore found not to interfere with the Aboriginal right. Regardless of their conclusions, both judges determined that the Gladstones <i>were</i> exercising an Aboriginal right when they attempted to sell the herring spawn. The majority of the British Columbia Court of Appeal, however, overturned these findings and held that there was no such right.
<p>
This change of judicial mind is nothing short of mysterious. Macfarlane J.A. deals briefly with the lower court decisions and concludes that, in spite of their findings that the appellants were exercising Aboriginal rights, &quot;[i]t is clear that the trial judge and the summary appeal judge did not view the activity in question as
being an integral part of the distinctive culture of the Heiltsuk people. I agree that the activity is different in nature and quality than the aboriginal right identified by the evidence.&quot;<sup><a href="#onesixteen">116</a></sup> In support of this conclusion, Macfarlane J.A. notes that the trial judge did not believe that &quot;inter-tribal trade in herring
spawn was very extensive or very significant in the affairs of the Heiltsuk Band,&quot;<sup><a href="#oneseventeen">117</a></sup> although he does not offer any evidence that this was, indeed, the trial judge's view or,
more importantly, what would be required to demonstrate that the trade <i>was</i> integral.
<p>
Considering the importance Macfarlane J.A. put on the lack of evidence of pre-sovereignty trade by the Sto:Lo in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, one would have thought that the comparatively voluminous evidence provided by the appellants in this case would at least merit comment. But he does not once mention the extensive evidence of
trade in spawn long before sovereignty. Instead, he notes, as if searching for the necessary `foreign' element that can take all Aboriginality away from an Aboriginal practice, that the commercial herring spawn fishery &quot;<i>first</i> developed in British Columbia in the early 1970s in response to a demand for the product in
Japan&quot;<sup><a href="#oneeighteen">118</a></sup> [emphasis added], thereby denying the relevance of all the other historical evidence. His decision rests, in the end, on the simple assertion that &quot;[t]he regulation in question controls commercial activity, which is not integral to aboriginal culture, and therefore cannot be said to infringe an
aboriginal right,&quot;<sup><a href ="#onenineteen">119</a></sup> a conclusion that rests, in turn, on the earlier declaration that: 
<blockquote>
the quality and character of the activity in aboriginal times was quite different from that disclosed by the evidence in this case. The aboriginal activity was rooted in a culture which gave significance to sharing a resource, to which one nation had ready access, while other Indian peoples did not.<sup><a href="#onetwenty">120</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This chain of reasoning is mysterious because it puts forward the idea that in &quot;aboriginal times,&quot; what the Heiltsuk did was to provide herring spawn for those who had no access to the resource, but what they are doing now is different; it is `commerce.'  But what is `commerce' but trading one thing, be it money or goods, for
another?  Macfarlane J.A. seems to be suggesting that the activity disclosed by the evidence somehow had cultural and political significance only, and the fact that the traders were meeting their material needs had nothing to do with the trade in herring spawn. Perhaps a definition of `commerce' and an explanation of why it is different from what the Gladstones' ancestors had participated in scores of years earlier would have been helpful, but none is provided
by Macfarlane J.A., save the scanty reasoning presented above. But how much closer could an Aboriginal group come to demonstrating that a present-day practice was a `modernized' form of a historical practice than the Gladstones did in this case?<sup><a href="#onetwentyone">121</a></sup>
<p>
Macfarlane J.A.'s reasons in <cite>Gladstone</cite> are completely infused with the idea that Aboriginal rights protect `what Indians do' so long as it is not the same as `what non-Indians do.'  While non-Aboriginal people may engage in commerce, the Heiltsuk's activity is defined as &quot;sharing a resource, to which one nation had ready
access, while other Indian peoples did not,&quot; and therefore not commerce. It is entirely possible that Macfarlane J.A., although he does not state as much, believes that the Aboriginal right is limited to this &quot;sharing&quot; only with other Aboriginal peoples, such that the attempted sale to a Japanese buyer was outside the protection of s. 35(1). But this is a simply absurd interpretation of Aboriginal rights. It gives no weight to the idea that Aboriginal rights may `evolve' in response to changing circumstances, and further, evinces no appreciation for the Heiltsuk perspective on the rights. To quote Macfarlane J.A., &quot;this is not the course set by
<cite>Sparrow</cite>.&quot;<sup><a href ="#onetwentytwo">122</a></sup>

One of the ways that <i>was</i> set by <cite>Sparrow</cite> is that the infringement of Aboriginal rights demands strict justification, since the protection of Aboriginal rights is impressed with a fiduciary obligation. The next part of this article will examine the British Columbia Court of Appeal's understanding of when an Aboriginal right is infringed and how such infringement may be justified. <cite>Nikal</cite> and <cite>Gladstone</cite> provide the context for determining whether the promise of <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s second branch was fulfilled any better than the first.
<p>
<b>3. The Limitation of Aboriginal Rights: Nikal and Gladstone</b>
<p>
The second aspect of  <cite>Sparrow</cite> addressed by the British Columbia Court of Appeal in this series of cases is the infringement of Aboriginal rights and the test for justification of those violations. In <cite>Nikal</cite>, the majority of the Court accepted that Aboriginal rights did exist as asserted, and moved directly to consider their violation. As I will discuss, even though <cite>Sparrow</cite> set a low threshold for violation, and a high standard for justification, the Court determined that Nikal's rights were not violated by the requirement that the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en hold a licence in order to fish. In <cite>Gladstone</cite>, Hutcheon J.A. (unlike Macfarlane J.A.) decided that the Gladstones had proved a commercial fishing right, and that it had been violated, and went on
to consider whether the violation was justified. These cases provide an opportunity to follow the growth of both branches of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s infringement analysis at the Court of Appeal. 
<p>
<i>A. Nikal</i>
<p>
<cite>Nikal</cite> raises an issue touched on in <cite>Sparrow</cite> but left unresolved: whether the special licences issued to Aboriginal people violate their fishing rights. Jerry Nikal, a member of the Moricetown Band of the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en, was charged with fishing without a licence after he was photographed gaff fishing in the Bulkley River. He raised two defences: first, that the Moricetown Band by-law governed fishing in the river and
that he had not breached it by not having a licence; second, that the licence requirement infringed his Aboriginal right to fish according to the customs and laws of his own people rather than those of the DFO. I will not deal with the first defence, since it was treated by all of the judges as an issue of traditional property law and interpretation rather than one of Aboriginal rights,<sup><a href="#onetwentythree">123</a></sup> and I will focus instead on the second one. It is important to note that the controversy in <cite>Nikal</cite> is not whether the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en have a right to fish or whether they have a right to regulate this fishing, since Macfarlane J.A. apparently accepts that they have a right to `self-regulate,' but whether this right is infringed by s. 4(1) of the <cite>British Columbia Fishery (General) Regulations</cite>. As a result, <cite>Nikal</cite> engages the second branch of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>---determining when a right is infringed and whether this infringement may be justified.
<p>
Macfarlane J.A. quotes from Mr. Nikal's factum in order to describethe right asserted: 
<blockquote>
104. Self-regulation of the fishery is part of the s.35(1) right. This does not deny the Crown's overriding authority to manage the fishery. It simply requires the government to justify any interference with the right of self-regulation.
<p>
99. It is submitted that in order for the right to fish to have any substance it must include the right to carry on the fishery as it has traditionally been carried on with the people making the necessary decisions under the direction of their hereditary leaders as to when, where, how, what and for whom they would fish.<sup><a href="#onetwentyfour">124</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Several aspects of this description are noteworthy. First of all, Mr. Nikal is not arguing that the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en right is <i>beyond the reach</i> of federal regulation, but that it exists within it and that incursions into it must be justified. The right is thus framed exactly within <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s paradigm where the Court wrote that &quot;there was from the outset never any doubt that sovereignty and legislative power ... vested in the
Crown,&quot;<sup><a href="#onetwentyfive">125</a></sup> and held that the Crown would nonetheless have to justify its interferences with Aboriginal rights. Second, the suggestion that the right involves continuing to practise fishing &quot;as it has traditionally been carried on&quot; does not refer to traditional methods or purposes, but to the historical ability of the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en to govern how fishing was to be carried out. Lambert J.A.'s `social theory' is in accord with this description of the right, in that he too attempted to describe the right at a lower level of particularization, from which flow specific manifestations (`when, where, how, what, and for whom') of the right.
<p>
The most notable aspect of this conception of the right is that  Macfarlane J.A. does not comment at all on the passages he quotes; instead, he moves straight on to discuss infringement and justification. It may be that Macfarlane J.A.'s view in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>, that &quot;[n]o declaration by this court is required to
permit internal self-regulation in accordance with aboriginal traditions, if the people affected are in agreement&quot;<a href="#onetwentysix">126</a></sup> is the source for this conclusion in <cite>Nikal</cite>. The conclusion has much in common with Lambert J.A.'s view in <cite>Van der Peet</cite> that if a right is recognized and affirmed by s. 35(1), the institutions under which that right is protected are also protected, including the ability to self-regulate and self-govern.<sup><a href="#onetwentyseven">127</a></sup> At any rate, Macfarlane J.A.'s view, if unstated, is that the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en right to fish carries with it the right to regulate this fishing.<sup><a href="#onetwentyeight">128</a></sup>
<p>
Macfarlane J.A.'s conclusion in relation to the right may have been a positive one, but in my view, his analysis of whether the right was infringed shows his complete failure to try to understand the meaning of the right from the rightholders' perspective. His conclusion that the licence requirement does not even constitute a <i>prima facie</i>
infringement of the fishing right is so furtive that it merits a thorough discussion here. 
<p>
The first move Macfarlane J.A. makes is to suggest that <cite>Sparrow</cite> has already resolved the issue of whether the licence requirement infringed Aboriginal fishing rights. He comments that:  
<blockquote>
[a]lthough the licensing scheme, with which we are dealing in this appeal, was discussed by Dickson C.J.C. and La Forest in <cite>Sparrow</cite> ..., and although it was argued on behalf of Mr. Sparrow that &quot;the holders of aboriginal rights may exercise those rights according to their own discretion,&quot; ... and &quot;that the right to
regulate is part of the right to use the resource in the band's discretion&quot; ... , it was not suggested that licensing by itself constituted a <i>prima facie</i> infringement of s.35(1) of the Constitution Act, 1982.<sup><a href="#onetwentynine">129</a></sup>
</blockquote>
While this attempt at judicial dispatch may be admirable, part of the reason that licensing was not considered to be contrary to s. 35(1) in <cite>Sparrow</cite> was that the issue was not argued.<sup><a href="#onethirty">130</a></sup> Mr. Sparrow only argued that the conditions of the Musqueam licence, in imposing a particular net length, infringed
his right. Further, even if the licensing regime <i>had</i> been found not to interfere with the Musqueam right, Macfarlane J.A. himself noted in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> that &quot;[t]he scope and content of aboriginal rights may vary from context to context in accordance with distinct patterns of historical occupancy and use of
land.&quot;<sup><a href="#onethirtyone">131</a></sup> The rights of the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en may well differ from those of the Musqueam, but by attempting to apply <cite>Sparrow</cite> directly to Mr. Nikal's case, Macfarlane J.A. forecloses discussion of this issue.<sup><a href="#onethirtytwo">132</a></sup>
<p>
Macfarlane J.A. then comments that: 
<blockquote>
[a]t the heart of the submission on behalf of Mr. Nikal is the proposition that any government action affecting the right of self-regulation must be justified. If that is correct then the first question is not whether a <i>prima facie</i> infringement has been established by the holder of the right, but whether the Crown can justify its action. That is not the course set by <cite>Sparrow</cite>.<sup><a href="#onethirtythree">133</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Even though the above reasoning is founded on an unresolved &quot;if,&quot; he never contemplates that Mr. Nikal could be suggesting something <i>other</i> than this reasoning. &quot;Ifs&quot; are not a particularly sturdy foundation for the denial of a constitutional right. This is especially true given that the factum refers to
&quot;interference,&quot; not &quot;effect,&quot; such that, as described above, it is only mirroring the <cite>Sparrow</cite> justification process. But more importantly, Macfarlane J.A.'s view that Mr. Nikal is asserting an absolute right overlooks the nature of the right described above. If the right to fish also contains a right to regulate, as Macfarlane J.A. has apparently accepted, then it is very difficult to see how <i>any</i> regulation enacted by the federal government does not constitute a <i>prima facie</i> interference with the right, since the power to regulate the fisheries and the asserted right to self-regulate occupy the very same field, insofar as federal laws may affect the Moricetown Band. Any government action regarding the Band's fishing would, <i>by definition</i>, affect and interfere with the right of self-regulation.
<p>
Another notable &quot;if&quot; in Macfarlane J.A.'s reasoning arises in his treatment of Millward J.'s analysis of infringement. This &quot;if&quot; indicates that Macfarlane J.A. has run the two stages of <cite>Sparrow</cite> together, determining <i>prima facie</i> infringement and justification at the same time. Millward J. had held that &quot;it is important to note also that the aboriginal right includes the right, not the privilege but the right, to follow the directions of the traditional leaders of the band in conducting the fishery,&quot; and he then enumerated a number of means by which this right might manifest itself.<sup><a href="#onethirtyfour">134</a></sup> Following from
this conception of the right, Millward J. concluded that the licence requirement was a <i>prima facie</i> infringement of the right. Macfarlane J.A., after quoting this passage from Millward J.'s reasons, writes that &quot;[i]f that means to say that a right of self-regulation is an absolute right, and that any government action
affecting it is a <i>prima facie</i> infringement of s.35(1) then I disagree. It is contrary to <cite>Sparrow</cite>.&quot;<sup><a href="#onethirtyfive">135</a></sup>
<p>
This commentary is, of course, almost indistinguishable from Macfarlane J.A.'s treatment of Mr. Nikal's argument, as quoted above. Here, as above, he appears to believe that Millward J.'s conception of the right and its <i>prima facie</i> infringement is an attempt to foreclose the justification branch of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>. But even if one could somehow interpret the appellant's factum to be proposing such a view, it is impossible to view Millward J.'s reasons in the same way. The oral decision from which Macfarlane J.A. quotes was a separate judgment concerned <i>solely</i> with the nature of the right, rendered several months before argument on justification was even heard.<sup><a href="#onethirtysix">136</a></sup> It is completely baffling, then, that Macfarlane J.A. could conclude
that Millward J. was suggesting that the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en possessed an absolute right, because the commentary was expressly confined to the infringement, and had nothing to do with justification. Just as confusing is his own understanding of  &quot;<i>prima facie</i> infringement&quot; of an Aboriginal right.
<p>
The Supreme Court offered three preliminary questions to be considered: is the limitation on the right unreasonable?  does the limitation cause undue hardship to the Aboriginal people affected? does the limitation deny them their preferred method of exercising their right?  Based on Macfarlane J.A.'s outline of Mr. Nikal's claim, it is not clear whether his case relied on one of these questions in particular, or all three, or whether he advanced new questions for the Court to ask. In any case, Macfarlane J.A.'s treatment was very spare. In my discussion, I will focus on the
first question of `reasonableness,' with an eye to some of the problems I outlined above in my discussion of <cite>Sparrow</cite>. 
<p>
It is worth noting, however, that if Mr. Nikal <i>did</i> raise a concern of undue hardship in his defence, Macfarlane J.A. did not think much of it, dismissing the entire question with the remark that &quot;in most circumstances, it ought not to constitute an undue hardship.&quot;<sup><a href="#onethirtyseven">137</a></sup> Macfarlane J.A.'s treatment of this question indicates a problem coursing through every part of  <cite>Nikal</cite>: the majority judges have failed to examine Mr. Nikal's rights and his situation as a specific case, relying instead
on conclusions about licences in general, Aboriginal rights in general, and government action in general. His answer that it &quot;ought&quot; not to cause undue hardship most of the time is unsatisfactory.
<p>
The sum total of Macfarlane J.A.'s analysis of whether the licence denies to the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en their preferred means of exercising their rights is his assertion that the licence requirement does not &quot;deny a right to  fish.&quot;<sup><a href="#onethirtyeight">138</a></sup> This observation is beyond doubt. It is also completely beside the point. No one in the case is suggesting that a licence requirement <i>denies</i> anyone the ability to fish; Mr. Nikal's objection is to the fact that in the present regulatory scheme, it is the regulation that <i>enables</i> him to fish legally. Mr. Nikal's claim is that being required to ask the DFO's permission before exercising the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en right to fish denies the Band its preferred means of exercising this right. It seems self-evident that they would prefer to exercise their right under a regulatory regime that does not negate the very source of the right---the people, not the DFO.
<p>
After all this, it is hard to imagine that there is an aspect of Macfarlane J.A.'s decision in <cite>Nikal</cite> that is <i>less</i> understanding of  <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s meaning, but his treatment of the first question---&quot;is the limitation unreasonable?&quot;---shows that his decision has truly failed to appreciate it or attempt to resolve any
of its difficulties. As described above, the British Columbia Court of Appeal is not solely to blame for the confusion over this branch of the test; the Supreme Court's own choice of words is less than fortuitous. I have described the problem that arises if one considers the word `reasonable' in this branch of  <cite>Sparrow</cite> to
have the same meaning as &quot;reasonable limits&quot; under s. 1 of the <cite>Charter</cite>: the burden of proof becomes reversed and the plaintiff, instead of demonstrating the effect of the regulation on himself, must somehow demonstrate that the regulation is unreasonable on some global basis. 
<p>
In <cite>Nikal</cite>, there is every indication that this is exactly how Macfarlane J.A. interprets this word. The most vivid clue to this effect is his reference to the Ontario Court of Appeal's decision in <cite>Agawa</cite> and the Nova Scotia Court of Appeal's decision in <cite>Denny, Paul and Sylliboy v. The Queen</cite><sup><a href="#onethirtynine">139</a></sup> in support of his conclusion. In those cases, the Courts of Appeal determined that
because licensing serves a conservation purpose, it is `reasonable.'
<p>
It is not immediately obvious how cases about the inland fishery in Ontario and fishing on the Atlantic Coast are relevant to whether or not the British Columbia licensing system is `reasonable,' an obscurity that is compounded by the fact that <cite>Agawa</cite> deals with provincial, rather than federal, legislation, but it seems that Macfarlane J.A.\ is invoking these cases for their talismanic effect: they were approved by the Supreme Court in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. This assessment may seem cynical, but it is important to note that several cases, including <cite>R. v. Joseph and Underwood</cite>,<sup><a href="#oneforty">140</a></sup> <cite>R. v. Archie</cite>,<sup><a href="#onefortyone">141</a></sup> <cite>R. v. Joseph</cite>,<sup><a href="#onefortytwo">142</a></sup> <cite>R. v. Ellsworth</cite><sup><a href="#onefortythree">143</a></sup> and <cite>R. v. Bones</cite>,<sup><a href="#onefortyfour">144</a></sup> all of which (except for <cite>Joseph</cite>, which was decided in the Yukon Territory) were decided by British Columbia courts <i>after</i> <cite>Sparrow</cite>. These cases provided a wealth of different approaches to licences in British Columbia. Macfarlane J.A.'s failure to even consider these cases becomes all the more striking when one considers
exactly what was decided in the cases to which he does make reference, particularly <cite>Agawa</cite>.
<p>
The passages from these cases with which the Supreme Court agreed have nothing to do with licensing.<sup><a href="#onefortyfive">145</a></sup> Instead, the Court approved of <cite>Agawa</cite>'s treatment of the term &quot;existing,&quot; and of <cite>Dennym</cite>'s discussion of the appropriate priority to be accorded to Aboriginal fishing rights. Most importantly, both <cite>Agawa</cite> and <cite>DennyM</cite>, decided as they were before <cite>Sparrow</cite>, may have contributed in various ways to the `stringent' test enunciated in that case, but neither one of them actually applies it. Once <cite>Agawa</cite>, in particular, is viewed in this light, it is clear that when Macfarlane J.A. allows the Ontario Court of Appeal's view that s. 12(1) of the <cite>Ontario Fishery
Regulations</cite> &quot;constitutes a reasonable limitation on the Batchewana Band's treaty right to fish and, therefore, does not infringe s. 35(1) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>&quot;<sup><a href="#onefortysix">146</a></sup> to govern his own conclusions about the licence restriction imposed on Mr. Nikal, he is actually circumventing the <cite>Sparrow</cite> test altogether. 
<p>
In <cite>Agawa</cite>, the Court accepts the British Columbia Court of Appeal's decision in <cite>Sparrow</cite> entirely, including the `public interest' view of regulation that the Supreme Court expressly rejected in favour of the more stringent test of justification. The Supreme Court also adopted the priority list set out in <cite>Jack</cite> which the Ontario Court of Appeal, in the passage immediately following the one cited by Macfarlane J.A. in support of his view, <i>did not</i>.<sup><a href="#onefortyseven">147</a></sup> The end result of Macfarlane J.A.'s
treatment of <cite>Agawa</cite> and the term `reasonable' employed in that case is that he denies Mr. Nikal the benefit of the legal ground broken in <cite>Sparrow</cite> and subjects him, instead, to a form of the `public interest' test, in which not even the priority of the Aboriginal right to fish, much less the existence of a right to
self-regulate, is considered. This approach to Aboriginal rights, if it is not downright sneaky, cannot be said to be in keeping with <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s mandate that Aboriginal rights be taken seriously.
<p>
Macfarlane J.A.'s decision that licences do not even constitute a <i>prima facie</i> infringement of the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en right to regulate their own fishing is highly problematic. Not only is it analytically unsound, it reflects poorly on the Court's understanding of Aboriginal rights in the following sense.
<p>
I have discussed earlier the mandate, in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, that a court be sensitive to the perspective of the Aboriginal person or people asserting a right when contemplating the content and scope of that right. It may seem self-evident to state that having regard for this perspective also requires the court to recognize the fact that
the rights have as their source the Aboriginal people asserting them, not an act of the state. This simple idea is embodied in Judson J.'s remarks about Aboriginal title, in <cite>Calder</cite>, when he said that &quot;it is clear that Indian title in British Columbia cannot owe its origin to the Proclamation of 1763, the fact is that when the
settlers came, the Indians were there, organized in societies and occupying the land as their forefathers had done for
centuries.&quot;<sup><a href="#onefortyeight">148</a></sup> Judson J. recognized this fact even as he rejected the argument that Aboriginal title still existed in British Columbia. It is astonishing, then, that the majority of British Columbia Court of Appeal, in the series of cases in which Judson J.'s conclusions about extinguishment are overturned, at the same time appears to ignore his observation about the source of Aboriginal rights.
<p>
The British Columbia fishing regulations in force at the time that Jerry Nikal was photographed gaff fishing on the Bulkley River subject both Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal people to the same licence requirement provided by s. 4(1) of the regulations: 
<blockquote>
Unless otherwise provided in the Act or in any Regulations made thereunder in respect of the fisheries to which these regulations apply or in the <cite>Wildlife Act (British Columbia)</cite>, no person shall fish except under the authority of a licence or permit issued thereunder.<sup><a href="#onefortynine">149</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The regulation establishes an absolute prohibition on fishing in the province, with exceptions provided for those who hold licences. Further, permission to fish is considered to flow from the authority of the licence itself. Through this mechanism, the state grants what is clearly classifiable as a fishing `privilege' to all fishers in British Columbia, in the same way that the province grants licences to motorists or to restaurants wishing to serve alcohol.
Section 27(1.1) of the regulations underlines the nature of the Indian food fishing licence, in particular, in even more dramatic terms: it provides that &uqot;<i>The Minister may</i> issue an Indian food fish licence to an Indian or a band for the sole purpose of obtaining food for that Indian and his family or for the band.&quot;<sup><a href="#onefifty">150</a></sup> [emphasis added.]
<p>
The licence, then, is not even considered to flow `as of right' from the Aboriginal right, so to speak; issuance is still at the discretion of the Minister in the same way that the Minister of Indian Affairs has the ability to disallow by-laws enacted under s. 81 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>. When one views it in this light, the regulatory scheme established by the <cite>Fisheries Act</cite> does not sit comfortably with the concept of Aboriginal rights. Considering that the prohibition embodied in s. 4(1) has existed since at least 1888,<sup><a href="#onefiftyone">151</a></sup> a time long before Aboriginal rights were recognized in this province, this is not surprising. What is surprising, however, is that the majority judges in <cite>Nikal</cite> do not appear to turn their minds to this problem, accepting without much analysis that licences, in and of themselves, do not infringe the rights of the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en.
<p>
Lambert J.A., on the other hand, flatly states that the Supreme Court did not resolve the issue of licences in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, writing that Mr. Nikal's 
<blockquote>
aboriginal right to fish is not dependent on holding a licence. Requiring him to hold a licence, is, in itself, an
interference with his right to fish. And photographing him while he is fishing and prosecuting him for the offence, indicates the severity of the interference.<sup><a href="#onefiftytwo">152</a></sup> 
</blockquote>
Lambert J.A.'s easy finding that there was a <i>prima facie</i> interference is, in my view, more in keeping with the low threshold which the Supreme Court must be taken to have established in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. Further, by spending so little time on determining whether the right was infringed, Lambert J.A. is able to devote more time to the `real' issue in this case, which is whether licences can be justified as infringements of Aboriginal rights and,
if so, why?  In broaching this subject, Lambert J.A. reflects the same approach to justification as did Mr. Nikal in his factum when he recognized the federal government's over-arching power to manage
the fishery:
<blockquote>
As we struggle towards a sensible solution in this difficult area, the final outcome, it seems to me, must incorporate a system of regulation of the fishery in order to ensure conservation and the continuance of the supply of fish both at sea and in the river. That system must be controlled, in my opinion, by one single organization with power to make decisions for the whole length of the river system, and at sea, so as to control conservation of the resource throughout the system. And that body should consult with all the users of the resource throughout the system to endeavour to secure a consensus and voluntary compliance with agreed or otherwise fairly determined conservation goals. Such a scheme may well require a form of licensing in order to ensure reporting and to enforce catch limitations and if it includes licensing for fishers in the ocean and in the lower reaches of the river it might well also require licensing for those engaging in the highest fishery on the river.<sup><a href="#onefiftythree">153</a></sup>
</blockquote>
While licensing may be necessary and reasonable to serve the goals of conservation, Lambert J.A. holds that because the licensing regime presently in place does not recognize the existence of Aboriginal rights in the first place, it is impossible that it could be considered to meet the standard of justification set out in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. Lambert J.A. points out that in 1986, when the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en Chiefs began to refuse to apply for licences, they did so in a decidedly confrontational and negative atmosphere. The federal government refused to recognize any Aboriginal rights to fish, and later argued that the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en's acceptance of
licences in the past constituted the implicit surrender of these rights. The Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en asserted such rights to fish and therefore refused to recognize the authority of the DFO.<sup><a href="#onefiftyfour">154</a></sup> This scheme, he says, cannot possibly be described as a regime that recognized Aboriginal rights to fish and it certainly could not give rise to any effective consultation. He concludes that the test of justification is not met.
<p>
The nature of Mr. Nikal's case forecloses discussion of the factors that <i>might</i> meet the test of justification. The majority judges determine that no justification is necessary because the right is not infringed, and Lambert J.A. holds that no justification is possible because of the nature of the regime that infringes the right. In <cite>Gladstone</cite>, however, there is discussion of justification, both from a majority judge---Hutcheon J.A.---and Lambert J.A., since they agree that the Gladstones' Aboriginal right was infringed. This decision will be the last one in this journey through the British Columbia Court of Appeal decisions, as it raises the issues of the final part in <cite>Sparrow</cite>---justification and the public fiduciary standard.
<p>
<i>B. Gladstone</i>
<p>
I have described earlier the treatment of the Gladstones' right by the majority judges, and my view that it is entirely out of keeping with <cite>Sparrow</cite>. Macfarlane J.A. concludes, however, that &quot;[a]lternatively, if there was a <i>prima facie</i> infringement of an aboriginal right it was justified,&quot;<sup><a href ="#onefiftyfive">155</a></sup> thus accepting Hutcheon J.A.'s justification analysis. This latter analysis is unfortunately no more satisfactory than Macfarlane J.A.'s treatment of the right. 
<p>
In order to understand why this is the case, it is important to recall the points made earlier about <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s institution of a public fiduciary standard for justification of infringements, and
the reasoning underlying this high standard. The Supreme Court held that the infringement of an Aboriginal right was a serious matter, and even though &quot;it does not promise immunity from government regulation in a society that, in the twentieth century, is increasingly more complex, interdependent and sophisticated, and where exhaustible resources need protection and management, it does hold the Crown to a substantive promise,&quot;<sup><a href="#onefiftysix">156</a></sup> and even though &quot;the justificatory standard to be met may place a heavy burden on the Crown,&quot;<sup><a href="#onefiftyseven">157</a></sup> the &quot;honour of the Crown is at stake in dealings with aboriginal peoples.&quot;<sup><a href="#onefiftyeight">158</a></sup> <cite>Gladstone</cite> provides us
with an opportunity to observe just how much the British Columbia Court of Appeal believes that honour is worth.
<p>
The two key aspects of justification that arise in <cite>Gladstone</cite> are the allocation of priorities in the herring spawn fishery, and whether the Heiltsuk people were consulted when the regulations were put in place.<sup><a href="#onefiftynine">159</a></sup> In considering these factors, it is worth recalling Lambert J.A.'s view in <cite>Nikal</cite> that any regulation put in place prior to the government's recognition of Aboriginal rights in British Columbia could not be in keeping with the honour of the Crown, because the regulations would be rooted in the notion that Aboriginal people fish at the permission of the Crown, not as of right. In <cite>Gladstone</cite>, Hutcheon J.A., who held in <cite>Nikal</cite> that <cite>Sparrow</cite> had already decided the issue of the validity of licensing in general,<sup><a href="#onesixty">160</a></sup> does not consider the Heiltsuk Band's licence, issued in 1988, to be unjustifiable solely because of when it was issued. Instead, he goes on to consider the questions the Supreme Court had set out. 
<p>
The appellants argued that the Heiltsuk had not been consulted when the licence was issued. In <cite>Sparrow</cite>, the Supreme Court did not outline what it thought `consultation' looked like, and therefore
does not give much guidance in this respect. Above, I have proposed what I believe to be a compelling reason for this duty of consultation: the DFO is holding the Heiltsuk Band's ability to act on its own behalf in regulating its fishing activities in `safekeeping' under the aegis of a fiduciary duty, until the Band's ability to represent itself is returned. The Crown's compromised position in this situation, as a fiduciary for the Heiltsuk who is nonetheless responsible for the interests of all users, gives rise to the requirement for the Crown to consult the Band and allow it to represent its own interests.
<p>
Hutcheon J.A.'s response to this requirement does not do much to further the understanding of why there is a duty of consultation, or of the nature of the Crown's responsibility toward the Heiltsuk interests. Instead, he simply concludes that &quot;in the application for the 1988 Category J licence, the Heiltsuk Band Council named a
representative to speak on its behalf. Consultation with that representative is sufficient to meet the requirement of consultation discussed in <cite>R. v. Sparrow</cite>.&quot;<sup><a href="#onesixtyone">161</a></sup> Nowhere in Hutcheon J.A.'s opinion is there any indication that this representative was actually consulted; he or she is not even named in his reasons. Additionally, the Category J licence does not permit the sale of the catch, which is the very issue of this case, so it is hard to see how the Heiltsuk's Aboriginal rights, especially concerning commerce, could have even been considered. Indeed, as alluded to above, if the Crown did not recognize any Aboriginal rights in 1988, it seems inconceivable that if the Heiltsuk representative had been consulted, the nature of the discussion would have had much to do with upholding the Heiltsuk's rights. Instead, the naming of a representative appears to be the routine filling-in of a blank, and Hutcheon J.A. does not discuss what the role of that person was intended to be even within the narrow scope of the existing regulations.
<p>
The honour of the Crown is no better upheld in Hutcheon J.A.'s discussion of the allocation of priorities in the spawn fishery. He refers to a meeting that took place at some undisclosed date, possibly in 1975 or 1976, in which all licence holders, of which the Heiltsuk were one, were brought together to &quot;discuss plans for those
holders.&quot;<a href="#onesixtytwo">162</a></sup> Again, there is no indication of whether the Heiltsuk were actually consulted; however, in this case, given that there was an actual meeting, it seems more likely. Hutcheon J.A., however, describes the attendees as 16 non-Aboriginal licence holders and 12 Aboriginal licence holders. It is worth asking what would have happened, in 1975 or 1976 (which even predated <cite>Jack</cite>), the Heiltsuk had claimed Aboriginal rights to the spawn fishery. Would anyone have listened to them?  Would the meeting have
simply collapsed in disarray?  Further, and perhaps this is more important, if this meeting could be considered `consultation' pursuant to <cite>Sparrow</cite>, it is difficult to see how the Crown's fiduciary duty to Aboriginal peoples could be met by treating Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal fishers in exactly the same fashion.
<p>
Finally, in dealing with the assertion that the allocation to the Heiltsuk Band was unjustifiable, Hutcheon J.A.\ refers to a letter that was sent to all licence holders, in which the plan for 1988 was set out. He quotes the part of the letter in which the allocations were tabled, and concludes that: 
<blockquote>
[a] fair inference from the evidence is that the allocation was made following consultation with the Category J licence holders including the representative of the Heiltsuk Band Council. In my opinion, the Crown met the burden of proof of justification at this stage and it was for the defence to show in what way the allocation
was improper.<sup><a href="#onesixtythree">163</a></sup>
</blockquote>
He adds that &quot;priority is always assured to the Indian people for food purposes,&quot; and then refers to the actual percentages of the herring-spawn fishery allocated to the Aboriginal fishers, noting that they are quite high.<sup><a href="#onesixtyfour">164</a></sup> This chain of reasoning merits several comments. First of all, in the above discussion of fiduciary principles under <cite>Sparrow</cite>, it is quite clear that it is the duty of the fiduciary to show the righteousness of his actions, not the duty of the beneficiary to demonstrate that they are improper. To suggest that because it may be &quot;fairly inferred&quot; from the evidence that there was consultation with the Heiltsuk the Crown has met its &quot;heavy burden&quot; is to ignore these principles, particularly when the only evidence Hutcheon J.A. provides for this inference is a numerical table that does not even
mention Aboriginal people's allocation.<sup><a href="#onesixtyfive">165</a></sup> Perhaps there was other evidence for his conclusion, but one might have expected, given the seriousness of the burden on the Crown, that he would have reproduced it in his opinion. Further, Hutcheon J.A. refers to the fact that priority is always given to Aboriginal people <i>for food purposes</i>, which, according to the terms of a Category J licence, does not permit sale of the catch. There is no discussion of whether the right of the Heiltsuk people to trade in herring spawn has been contemplated, and no discussion of where commercial rights might fit into the `priority list' established in <cite>Jack</cite> and accepted in <cite>Sparrow</cite>.<sup><a href="#onesixtysix">166</a></sup>
<p>
Instead of following the test of strict justification set out by <cite>Sparrow</cite>, it is my view that Hutcheon J.A. is simply applying a variation of the &quot;necessary and reasonable in the public interest&quot; test, which the Court of Appeal had earlier offered in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, which was rejected by the Supreme Court in that case,
but which was resurrected by Macfarlane J.A. in <cite>Nikal</cite>. 
<p>
He relies in large part on the fact that the allocations for Aboriginal fishers appear to be generous, quoting the percentages of the fishery to which they have access. By doing so, he appears to be suggesting that the allocation is reasonable and the Heiltsuk have nothing to complain about. Now, if the duty of consultation actually had been met, the allocation may have been no different: for all we know, the Heiltsuk may have received a smaller slice of the fishery. But in fiduciary law, process is everything, as is evidenced by the fact that the beneficiary need not show actual harm resulting from a breach. It is irrelevant, then, that the Heiltsuk's allocation seems generous. What <i>is</i> relevant is that the Heiltsuk  representatives, if they were consulted at all, were lumped in with
non-Aboriginal spawn fishers. The form of consultation accepted by the Court does not require the Crown to act in the Heiltsuk interest; the Crown's actions on the evidence provided by Hutcheon J.A. bespeak a `public interest' test. <cite>Sparrow</cite> demands a much higher standard. After enumerating the &quot;Crown's responsibility toward Aboriginal peoples&quot; as one of the considerations for the Court, Hutcheon J.A.'s failure to mention this responsibility even once, and the three concurring judges' failure to speak up about this is perhaps indicative of the British Columbia Court of Appeal majority's view of the value of Aboriginal rights. The Court has placed an extraordinarily low value on the &quot;honour of the Crown,&quot; and in doing so, similarly devalues the project of taking Aboriginal rights seriously.
<p>
Indeed, Hutcheon J.A.'s rather vapid treatment of the objective and justification in this case becomes all the more noticeable when one compares it to Lambert J.A.'s analysis, in which he finds that, on the evidence, even the <i>first</i> stage of justification was not met, holding that no conservation purpose was served by the licensing
system. At this point, Lambert J.A. appears to have tired of attacking his brothers' findings, and instead reviews different evidence altogether. He notes the evidence of an expert witness, who said that the licensing system served an allocation function more than a conservation function, and whose evidence was not challenged. Lambert J.A. concludes that: 
<blockquote>
in regulating the stock, there is no conservation imposed on the herring spawn on kelp fishery and no need for such conservation in the circumstances which existed in 1988. The conservation each year is entirely dealt with by regulating the 94% of the total of spawn and roe which are from fish that are netted and killed for their roe.<sup><a href="#onesixtyseven">167</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The only other possible reason for issuing licences, according to Lambert J.A., is for reporting purposes and, as he notes, a complete prohibition on the exercise of the Aboriginal right is an inappropriate means of serving this goal given that there is no conservation purpose underlying it.<sup><a href="#onesixtyeight">168</a></sup> In framing the issue this way, Lambert J.A. again underlines the majority judges' total failure to recognize the significance of a licensing system that requires Aboriginal people to get the government's permission to exercise rights that flow not from the government but from the people themselves. He thus shows the huge gap between <cite>Gladstone</cite> and the Court's initial promise in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite> to attempt to view the rights from the perspective of the Aboriginal people asserting them. The British Columbia Court of Appeal majority covered a lot of ground between these two cases, and much of this ground lay far behind what the Supreme Court had attempted to achieve in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. The Supreme Court will have, in my view, much work to do to set the contemplation of Aboriginal rights back on a meaningful level of discussion.
<p>
<center><h3>Conclusion</h3></center>

Although the Supreme Court avoided discussion of licences and commercial fishing in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, at some point it will be called upon to evaluate issues such as those presented in the cases I have discussed in this article. These are hard questions. At the same time, the judges of the British Columbia Court of Appeal have
asserted, as have I, that various arguments or treatments of Aboriginal rights are &quot;not the course set by <cite>Sparrow</cite>.&quot; It will fall upon the Supreme Court, then, to clarify exactly what the course of <cite>Sparrow</cite> is. 
<p>
In this article, I have tried to point out some of the strong points and ambiguities that the Supreme Court opened up in <cite>Sparrow</cite>. In particular, the Court sought to invigorate Aboriginal rights as a legal concept by asking future courts to be sensitive to the perspective of the people holding them, rather than seeing the issues solely through a majoritarian lens. Second, the Court set out a strict test of justification, contemplating what I have referred to as a `public fiduciary standard.'  At the same time, the Court emphasized that the <cite>Sparrow</cite> analysis should not be applied mechanically to all following cases, thus challenging future courts to mould the analysis to particular cases to give real meaning to <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s promise that Aboriginal rights be taken seriously. In this sense, the Court set out a framework for contemplating Aboriginal rights, and challenged future courts to turn their minds to the difficult task of describing the rights in a fashion that is comprehensible in Canada's Anglo-European judicial system.
<p>
The majority of the British Columbia Court of Appeal did not meet this challenge. By transforming the phrase &quot;integral to their distinctive culture&quot; into an incantation invoked without much thought, the majority turned analysis of Aboriginal rights back to the Eurocentric vision of `Indianness' expressed in <i>Four B</i>.
And by initiating a notion of Aboriginal rights that implies that their content is limited to that which is absent in non-Aboriginal culture, the Court sets s. 35(1) analysis on a dangerous course, potentially depriving Aboriginal rights of legal protection if they appear to diverge too far from their incarnations in &quot;Aboriginal times.&quot;  Further, the Court's view of what a <i>prima facie</i> infringement of, or a justifiable incursion on, an Aboriginal right looks like, as evidenced in <cite>Nikal</cite> and <cite>Gladstone</cite>, wanders drastically from the strict test set out in </cite>Sparrow</cite>. Viewing a name on an application form as sufficient to give meaning
to the Gitksan-Wet'suwet'en's historical power to govern themselves can hardly be said to be meeting the &quot;heavy burden on the Crown.&quot;
<p>
Lambert J.A.'s `social theory' of Aboriginal rights, on the other hand, constitutes a significant effort to take the rightholders' perspective as paramount and yet describe the right in a way that is comprehensible to Anglo-Canadian courts. I have suggested that the `social theory' has much in common with a theory of <cite>Charter</cite> rights: both Aboriginal and <cite>Charter</cite> rights are multi-layered and analysis will change depending on how deeply a Court plumbs into the content of the right. The <cite>Charter</cite> should in no way be determinative of rights-analysis under s. 35(1). But the Supreme Court's original conception of s. 35(1) in <cite>Sparrow</cite> owes a great deal to the early <cite>Charter</cite> analysis, and further contemplation of the meaning of <cite>Charter</cite> rights could aid the Court in returning s. 35(1) to the way set by <cite>Sparrow</cite>.
<p>
Whatever else the Court does, however, I think that it is imperative that it follow through on its promise to attempt to view Aboriginal rights from the perspective of the people who hold them, and to consider limitations on these rights from that same point of view, because to do otherwise would create an inexplicable disjuncture between s. 35(1) and other rights-affirming documents in Canada, once again treating Aboriginal people as `different' for no apparent reason. The decisions of the British Columbia Court of Appeal amply demonstrate that it is unsatisfactory to deny protection to asserted rights simply by identifying them as `different.'
<p>
Finally, given the controversy surrounding Aboriginal commercial fishing rights and licences in British Columbia, I underline that the Court will also have to hold itself strictly to its own view, in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, that a `public interest' justification is insufficient to justify a limit on constitutional rights. If such rights are found to exist, the proper course is to manage the claims of competing users of the fishery through consultation and negotiation. The proper course is not to sense impending controversy and solve the problem by denying that the rights exist in the first place. Such an approach would have too much in common with the `political rights' concept that the Court has already rejected. It would also utterly fail to uphold <cite>Sparrow</cite>'s promise that Aboriginal rights will be taken seriously.
<p>
