<p>
<li><a name = "fortytwo">The</a> fiduciary obligation as manifested in Aboriginal-Federal relations was first analyzed in <cite>Guerin v. The Queen</cite> (1984), 13 D.L.R. (4th) 321 (S.C.C.) [hereinafter
<cite>Guerin</cite>]. In essence, a fiduciary obligation arises when one party stands in a position of trust to another, and is vested with power to affect that party's interests. The fiduciary is expected to act with the utmost loyalty to the beneficiary in exercising power over the beneficiary's interests. For discussion of fiduciaries, see
E. Weinrib, &quot;The Fiduciary Obligation&quot; (1975) 25 U.T.L.J. 1; T.G. Youdan, <cite>Equity, Fiduciaries and Trusts</cite> (Toronto: Carswell, 1989); J.C. Shepherd, <cite>The Law of Fiduciaries</cite> (Toronto: Carswell, 1981).
