<li><a name = "fiftynine">The</a> Court notes this conflict; see <i>supra</i> note 55.
<p>
<li><a name = "sixty"><i>Supra</i></a> note 1 at 414.
<p>
<li><a name = "sixtyone">As</a> the Court notes, &quot;[w]e acknowledge the fact that the justificatory
standard to be met may place a heavy burden on the Crown.&quot; <i>Ibid</i>. at 416.
<p>
<li><a name = "sixtytwo">These</a> standards of conduct are borrowed from Finn's article, <i>supra</i> note 48 at 4ff, and I use them here in the same sense as he did. The (un)conscionability standard prevents a person who is acting solely in her own interests from behaving in an &quot;excessively self-interested or exploitative&quot; manner; this standard is familiar from contract law. A good faith standard requires a person, again acting in his own interests, to have some regard for the legitimate interests of the other party even as he attempts to secure his own best interests. Finally, the fiduciary standard, as I have alluded to above, requires a person to act not at all in her own interests but <i>solely</i> in the interests of the beneficiary.
