<li><a name = "seventytwo"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 134.
<p>
<li><a name = "seventythree"><cite>Delgamuukw</cite></a> v. <cite>British Columbia</cite>, [1991] 3 W.W.R. 97 at 442 (B.C.S.C.), quoted in <i>ibid.</i> at 134.
<p>
<li><a name = "seventyfour">(U.K.),</a> 30 &amp; 31 Vict., c. 3.
<p>
<li><a name = "seventyfive">See,</a> for example, <cite>Kruger and Manuel v. The Queen</cite> (1977) 75 D.L.R. (3d) 434 (S.C.C.); <cite>Four B Manufacturing</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 11; and <cite>Dick v. The Queen</cite> (1985), 23 D.L.R. (4th) 33 (S.C.C.).
<p>
<li><a name = "seventysix"><cite>Four B Manufacturing</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 11 at 397.
<p>
<li><a name = "seventyseven">The</a> charges from which the cases arise are as follows: Mrs. Van der Peet was charged with selling salmon contrary to s. 27(5) of the <cite>British Columbia Fisheries (General) Regulations</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 12; the Gladstones were charged with selling herring spawn on kelp contrary to s. 20(3) of the <cite>Pacific Herring Fishery Regulations</cite>, SOR 84/324; and Mr. Nikal was charged with fishing without a licence contrary to s. 4(1) of the <cite>British Columbia Fisheries (General) Regulations</cite>.
<p>
<li><a name = "seventyeight">The</a> trial judges' interest, in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, <cite>NTC Smokehouse</cite>, and <cite>Gladstone</cite>, in `illegal fish trade' and how the challenged regulations serve to control it suggests that they have accepted that Aboriginal sale of fish is by definition illegal, and there cannot be an Aboriginal right that protects commercial fishing. In particular, the provincial court judge's view in <cite>NTC Smokehouse</cite>, that &quot;[n]o doubt there were potlatches and meetings and exchanges of gifts of salmon but these do not constitute an aboriginal right to sell the allotted fish contrary to the Regulations,&quot; reflects this possibility. See <cite>R. v. NTC Smokehouse</cite>, oral reasons of McLeod P.C.J., quoted by Wallace J.A. in <cite>NTC Smokehouse</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 7 at 172. Lambert J.A., on the other hand, observes in <cite>Gladstone</cite> that &quot;[t]o say that an attempt by William Gladstone and Donald Gladstone to avoid the regulations proves that the regulations are justified is a circular argument and is, for that reason, fallacious.&quot; <i>Supra</i> note 6 at 154.
<p>
<li><a name = "seventynine">It</a> is also worth noting that all of these cases are at their third level of appeal, having already gone through the Provincial and the Supreme or County Court systems. Given that most of the cases were tried before <cite>Sparrow</cite> was decided by the Supreme Court of Canada, it is quite possible that the trial decisions encompass much of the thinking that was rejected in that case. The British Columbia Court of Appeal does not seem to consider this a problem.
<p>
<li><a name = "eighty">&quot;There is</a> a tendency, operating at times unconsciously, to render that title conceptually in terms which are appropriate only to systems which have grown up under English law. But this tendency has to be held in check closely.&quot;  Macfarlane J.A. is here quoting from <cite>Amodu Tijani v. Southern Nigeria (Secretary)</cite>, [1921] 2 A.C. 399 (P.C.) at 403.; <i>supra</i> note 8 at 127.
<p>
<li><a name = "eightyone">The trial</a> decisions in many of these cases were brief oral judgments which, as one might expect, may not be the most well-explained reasons which a judge is capable of providing. But this aspect of the judicial process does not change the fact that no matter how opaque a trial decision is, it does form the basis for appeal, and the fact finding process in many of these cases is the key to the later decisions.
<p>
<li><a name ="eighytwo">Although he</a> does mention that Aboriginal rights must be considered by reference
to the practices of the specific Aboriginal group raising them, he does not say <i>whose</i> perspective is to be adopted in considering those practices. See <i>supra</i> note 5 at 84--5.
<p>
<li><a name = "eightythree"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 88, quoting from <cite>R. v. Van der Peet</cite>, [1991] 3 C.N.L.R. 155 at 160 (B.C. Prov. Ct.).
<p>
<li><a name = "eightyfour">Ibid</i>.</a> at 160. Macfarlane J.A. uses it at <i>supra</i> note 5 at 85. Lambert J.A. also employs this unfortunate term, in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 5 at 115.
<p>
<li><a name = "eightyfive"><cite>Van der Peet</cite>,</a> at trial, <i>ibid.</i>
<p>
<li><a name = "eightysix">Hutcheon J.A.,</a> in his dissenting opinion, identifies a possible source for this notion when he observes that the Crown, in its speaking notes, had said that &quot;Aboriginal rights describe pre-contact life,&quot; and went on to say that since commerce was a product of contact, it could not be part of an Aboriginal
right. Hutcheon J.A. rejects this idea, simply stating that &quot;I know of no authority for the proposition that `Aboriginal rights describe pre-contact life.'&quot; <i>Supra</i> note 5 at 129.
<p>
<li><a name = "eightyseven"><i>Supra</i></a> note 1 at 396--7.
<p>
<li><a name = "eightyeight">Wallace J.A.'s</a> opinion in this case is also riddled with bare assertions that modern-day Aboriginal practices are &quot;plainly different&quot; from historical practices. He holds, for example, that Mrs. Van der Peet's sale was &quot;unrelated to&quot; and  &quot;differed materially&quot; from &quot;specific traditional aboriginal practices,&quot; <i>supra</i> note 5 at 103, and that to consider the sale to be the exercise of an Aboriginal right would be to &quot;distort&quot; its true scope and nature (at 100).
<p>
<li><a name = "eightynine">McEachern C.J.S.C.</a> exhibited similar discomfort with the evidence adduced at trial in <cite>Delgamuukw</cite>. Leslie Hall Pinder, one of the lawyers for the plaintiffs, describes the difficulty she and her clients encountered in presenting the oral history of the people in a manner that was acceptable to the court. See <cite>The Carriers of No: After the Land Claims Trial</cite>, Discussions About Law \#2 (Vancouver: Lazara Press, 1991) at 4--8.
<p>
<li><a name ="ninety"><i>Supra</i> note 83 at 157.
<p>
<li><a name = "ninetyone"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 160.
<p>
<li><a name = "ninetytwo">This evidence includes</a> the somewhat mysterious conclusion that the Sto:Lo were not a `tribe' but a `band' so that the trade could not have been regularized. <i>Ibid</i>. at 160. One may well wonder what classifications imposed by anthropologists might have to do with the Sto:Lo's perspective on fishing.
<p>
<li><a name = "ninetythree"><i>Supra</i></a> note 83 at 165--6.
<p>
<li><a name = "ninetyfour"><i>Supra</i></a> note 5 at 85.
<p>
<li><a name = "ninetyfive"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name = "ninetysix">Wallace J.A.'s</a> opinion is afflicted still more by the confusion of rights with
regulations. He writes:
<blockquote>
I pause here to point out the obvious: namely, that every resident of British Columbia, native and non-native, has the
right to fish in British Columbian waters and dispose of their catch commercially. This right, however, is limited and controlled by a variety of regulations which require that the fishers hold licences permitting them to engage in commercial fishing. The regulations impose restrictions and controls respecting the place, time, method of fishing and quotas which limit the volume of fish caught by particular methods, and sold in the commercial market. <i>Ibid</i>. at 98.
</blockquote>
Not only is this conception of the fishery not obvious, it is plainly wrong, because under s. 4(1) of the <cite>British Columbia Fishery (General) Regulations</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 12, <i>no</i> non-Aboriginal British Columbian has the <i>right</i> to fish under the present regime: fishing is prohibited outright, and those who fish do so under a licence. Aboriginal people, however, may be able to prove a right to sell fish that is protected under s.
35(1). By suggesting that everyone has the <i>same</i> right to sell fish, and that this is merely restricted by the fishing regime, Wallace J.A. effectively dismisses s. 35(1)'s purpose of recognizing the uniqueness of Aboriginal rights.
<p>
It is perhaps worse, from the perspective of avoiding `frozen rights' thinking, that Wallace J.A. writes the majority opinion in <cite>NTC Smokehouse</cite>, and at the outset announces that what s. 35(1) protects is not the &quot;integral parts of their distinctive culture,&quot; but that which is &quot;integral to the Band's cultural and traditional way of life.&quot; <i>Supra</i> note 7 at 164.
<p>
<li><a name= "ninetyseven"><i>Supra</i></a> note 5 at 86.
<p>
<li><a name= "ninetyeight">Ibid</i>.</a> at 88--9.
<p>
<li><a name= "ninenine"><cite>The Concise Oxford Dictionary of Current English</cite>,</a> eighth edition, R.E. Allen, ed. (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1990) at 340.
<p>
<li><a name = "hundred"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<P>
<li><a name = "hundredone"><i>Supra</i></a> note 1 at 406--7.
<p>
<li><a name= "hundredtwo"><i>Supra</i></a> note 5 at 125--6.
<p>
<li><a name = "hundredthree"><i>Ibid.</i></a> at 111.
<p>
<li><a name= "hundredfour"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 111--12.
<p>
<li><a name="hundredfive"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name = "hundredsix"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 112--15. Although Lambert J.A. does not explain why he finds this rationale so persuasive, he is implicitly recognizing the artificiality of separating `American Indian culture' from `Canadian Indian culture,' because the U.S.-Canadian border has nothing to do with Aboriginal culture itself. Wallace J.A., however, criticizes Lambert J.A.'s view, writing that:
<blockquote>
while harmony in the treatment of aboriginal rights on both sides of the border between Canada and the United States may be desirable---and I express no opinion in that regard---where the law of one jurisdiction is based on interpreting the United States Indian policy and resulting treaties from the nineteenth century, and the law of the other is based on determining the scope and nature of aboriginal rights recognized by the common law at sovereignty, such harmony may not be possible or even desirable. (at 101)
</blockquote>
Considering that Canadian law on Aboriginal issues is largely grounded in the Marshall trilogy (<cite>Fletcher v. Peck</cite>, 10 U.S. (6 Cranch) 87 (1810); <cite>Johnson v. M'Intosh</cite>, 21 U.S. (8 Wheat.) 543 (1823); <cite>Worcester v. Georgia</cite>, 31 U.S. (6 Pet.) 515 (1832)), and also considering Canadian courts' eagerness to use American constitutional law as a
guide for the development of our own jurisprudence, I think Wallace J.A.'s view is questionable.
<p>
<li><a name= "hundredseven"><cite>Van der Peet</cite>,</a> <i>ibid.</i> at 115.
<p>
<li><a name= "hundredeight"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 119.
<p>
<li><a name= "hundrednine">Wallace J.A.</a> describes the social theory as &quot;perhaps more aptly described as the `livelihood' descriptive method of ascertaining the scope and nature of aboriginal activities. Under this approach, the activities are viewed as being directed to furthering the livelihood interests of the aboriginal community in whatever modern entrepreneurial form best serves that objective.&quot; <i>Ibid</i>. at 100.
<p>
<li><a name="oneten"><i>Ibid</i>. at 125.</a>
<p>
<li><a name = "oneeleven">In this case, Hutcheon J.A.</a> wrote the majority opinion. I discuss Macfarlane J.A.'s opinion to continue an analysis of his view of the content of Aboriginal rights.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwelve"><i>Supra</i></a> note 6 at 140.
<p>
<li><a name= "onethirteen"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 148--9.
<p>
<li><a name= "onefourteen">It is fascinating</a> to note that the Crown had argued in this case (Lambert J.A. calls it the Crown's main argument) that because the trade in spawn was scanty between 1955 and 1974, the Aboriginal right had been abandoned and therefore ceased to exist. <i>Ibid</i>. at 150. It goes without saying that this idea puts a very low value on Aboriginal rights and makes them inexplicably contingent and variable, as compared to <cite>Charter</cite> rights, for example. The assertion becomes all the more curious when one compares it to <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, in which the Court held that an Aboriginal right could not have arisen over the
twenty-five years between the arrival of the Hudson's Bay Company and the assertion of sovereignty over British Columbia. It is rather insulting that the Crown should have argued that while an Aboriginal right may not be gained in twenty-five years of `use,' it may be lost over nineteen years of `disuse.'  Specious as this argument is, however, it may be that Macfarlane J.A. accepted it, since in his view, the trade in spawn began in the 1970s.
<p>
<li><a name= "onefifteen"><cite>R</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Gladstone</cite>, [1991] B.C.W.L.C. 2104 at 20--21 (B.C. Prov. Ct.), quoted <i>ibid.</i> at 140.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixteen"><i>Supra</i></a> note 6 at 145. It is worth noting Lemiski P.C.J.'s comments that the Gladstones were attempting &quot;to sell a relatively large quantity of spawn in a surreptitious manner to a foreign buyer in a location far removed from the Heiltsuk Band's region.&quot;  Quoted in Hutcheon J.A.'s reasons, <i>ibid.</i> at 139. He commented again on the illicit nature of the sale, saying that it was &quot;not dissimilar
to the manner in which criminals transport and sell narcotics.&quot; <i>Ibid</i>. at 141. These comments raise the question, in my view, of whether the reason Lemiski P.C.J. found that the Gladstones' activity was `different' from the activity evidenced by the historical record was because what they were doing was `illegal,' unlike the historical activity, which was above-board. Hutcheon J.A., quite properly, writes, <i>ibid.</i> at 141, that this is completely beside the point, because whether or not something is illegal today has nothing to do with the content of the right.
Macfarlane J.A. makes no comment on this aspect of Lemiski P.C.J.'s decision.
<p>
<li><a name="oneseventeen"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 144.
<p>
<li><a name = "oneeighteen"><i>Ibid.</i></a> at 144.
<p>
<li><a name = "onenineteen"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 145.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwenty"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name ="onetwentyone">Wallace J.A.'s</a> support of Macfarlane J.A.'s conclusion on this point may serve to answer this question, since he forwards, in <cite>Van der Peet</cite>, the most restrictive view of what it means to affirm Aboriginal rights in a contemporary form. He writes that: 
<blockquote>
[b]y evolution, the original scope and nature of the right is altered such that it can no longer be said to be an integral
component of the natives' traditional way of life or culture save in the most general sense, i.e. earning a livelihood. The absence of the requisite relationship between a traditional aboriginal practice and a present commercial activity is exemplified, for instance, by the remote connection between the aboriginal practice of gaming and the commercial operation of a gambling casino.<p>
In contrast, the modern manner of exercising a traditional right does not involve a distortion of the scope and nature of the aboriginal right; rather, it permits the right to remain, as it was at the time of sovereignty, an integral part of the native culture and traditional way of life. It is the manner of exercising the right which may take a contemporary form such as hunting, fishing, gathering and farming with modern equipment. <i>Supra</i>, note 5 at 156--7.
</blockquote>
How Wallace J.A. can be so sure of what may be a &quot;distortion&quot; of an Aboriginal right, or that operating a gambling casino is unrelated to gaming, remains unexplained.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentytwo"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 256.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentythree">In the end,</a> the disposition of this defence turned on whether the words &quot;on the reserve&quot; in s. 81(o) of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 56, could encompass the Bulkley River, which runs alongside the Moricetown reserve but is not within its borders.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentyfour"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 255.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentyfive"><i>Supra</i></a> note 1 at 404.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentysix"><i>Supra</i></a> note 8 at 151.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentyseven"><i>Supra</i></a> note 5 at 110.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentyeight">Wallace J.A.,</a> on the other hand, characterizes the regulatory aspect of the right asserted to be a claim for legislative powers, and concludes that because the division of powers under the Constitution is exhaustive, there can be no power of legislation left for Aboriginal peoples to exercise. <cite>Nikal</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 7 at 268.
<p>
<li><a name = "onetwentynine"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 255--6.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirty">Lambert</a> J.A. makes the point that in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, the Musqueam had
voluntarily obtained a Band fishing licence, had fished under the authority of that licence, and were not challenging it. <i>Ibid</i>. at 277--8.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtyone"><i>Supra</i></a> note 8 at 128.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtytwo">He also</a> conflates diverse Aboriginal cultures into one---`Indian'---an operation that may be related to his view that `Aboriginal culture' is different from `European culture' but that the various Aboriginal cultures are not to be differentiated. See text accompanying note 102, <i>supra</i>.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtythree"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 256.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtyfour"><cite>R</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Nikal</cite>, [1991] 1 C.N.L.R. 162 at 167--8 (B.C. S.C.) (oral ruling on 12 July 1990).
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtyfive"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 257.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtysix"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> Millward J. held, at 168, that &quot;the requirement is unreasonable and <i>prima facie</i> constitutes an undue hardship and that the first requirement under the ruling in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, therefore, that the onus set out in that procedure has been met and a <i>prima facie</i> infringement is shown.&quot;  The final judgment itself was rendered 24 October 1990.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtyseven"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 257.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtyeight"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 257.
<p>
<li><a name = "onethirtynine">(1990), 55</a> C.C.C. (3d) 322 (N.S.C.A.) [hereinafter <cite>Denny</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name = "oneforty">[1990] 4 C.N.L.R.</a> 59 (B.C.S.C.).
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortyone">[1991] 4 C.N.L.R.</a> 107 (B.C.S.C.).
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortytwo">(7 February 1991),</a> Whitehorse Yukon Registry No. 89--02802 (Y. Terr. Ct.)  [hereinafter <cite>Joseph</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortythree">(16 March 1992),</a> Victoria Registry No. 49395--C (B.C.S.C.).
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortyfour">(27 June 1990),</a> Williams Lake Registry No. 11110 (B.C. Prov. Ct.).
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortyfive">Additionally,</a> <cite>Agawa</cite> did not even deal with Aboriginal rights, but treaty rights in the context of s. 88 of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>. To the extent that we may conclude that a treaty right is different from an Aboriginal right, having its source in a historical agreement that may or may not protect an Aboriginal right, rather than the people, <cite>Agawa</cite> appears to be particularly <i>unlike</i> Mr. Nikal's situation.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortysix"><i>Supra</i></a> note 10 at 122.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortyseven">&quot;It is almost unnecessary</a> to add that this decision is based upon the facts established in this case. Counsel for the respondent did not pursue in argument the submission made in his factum that Indian fishing rights constitute a prior claim on fishery resources. In support of this argument the factum quoted a passage from the judgment of Dickson J. in <cite>Jack</cite> ... where he said that he agreed with &quot;the general tenor of this argument&quot; that &quot;the burden of conservation measures should not fall primarily upon the Indian fishery.&quot; The adjustment of priorities, where required in appropriate cases, between Indian fishermen based on their treaty rights and other fishermen must be left for another day.&quot; <i>Ibid.</i> at 122--3.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortyeight"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 328.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefortynine"><i>Supra</i></a> note 12.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefifty"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftyone">In <cite>Jack</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 30 at 258, Dickson J. refers to the 1888 <cite>Salmon Fishery Regulations for British Columbia</cite>, which expressly prohibited all salmon fishing not carried out under the authority of a licence.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftytwo"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 278.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftythree"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 279.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftyfour"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 279--80.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftyfive"><i>Supra</i></a> note 6 at 146.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftysix"><i>Supra</i></a> note 1 at 410.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftyseven"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 416.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftyeight"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 413.
<p>
<li><a name = "onefiftynine">There does</a> not seem to have been much debate over whether licensing serves a valid conservation purpose, which is the first `test' under <cite>Sparrow</cite>. <i>Supra</i> note 6 at 141. Hutcheon J.A.'s analysis, which sets out three questions --- whether there is a valid legislative objective; whether there has been consultation with respect to the allocation; and whether the Crown has met its responsibility toward Aboriginal people --- is also somewhat different from the Court's analysis in <cite>Sparrow</cite>, which proposes that the honour of the Crown is supposed to inform all questions of justification, and is not to be contemplated separately.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixty"><i>Supra</i></a> note 7 at 284.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtyone"><i>Supra</i></a> note 6 at 141.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtytwo"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 142.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtythree"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 143.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtyfour"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtyfive"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 142--3.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtysix">In fact,</a> given that <cite>Jack</cite>'s `list' refers only to &quot;Indian fishing&quot; and not fishing for any particular purpose, one might expect that commercial fishing by Aboriginal people would receive priority over all other forms of fishing as well, but the Court does not discuss this point at all.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtyseven"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 155--6.
<p>
<li><a name = "onesixtyeight"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 156. Lambert J.A. also disagreed with the majority's treatment of the evidence of consultation, and he holds that the only consultation that was proven was with the Native Indian Brotherhood of British Columbia, whose representative may or may not have considered the interests of the Heiltsuk in particular. He strongly rejects Hutcheon J.A.'s inference-drawing, holding that &quot;no inference of
adequate consultation can be drawn from the fact that the Heiltsuk Band itself holds a Category J Licence with a representative nominated for the purpose of that licence, certainly not an inference that would discharge the heavy burden of justification as described in <cite>Sparrow</cite>.&quot; <i>Ibid</i>. at 157.
</ol><p><br>
