<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review Vol. 53 No. 1</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v53n1.htm">Volume 53 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>A Comparative Study of the Exclusionary Rule and Its
Standing Threshold in Canada, the United States, and New York State:
The Relation of Purpose to Practice
<p>
PAUL DENIS GODIN<sup><a href="#note">*</a></sup></h1>

<i>The author argues that the evidentiary exclusion rule should be firmly grounded in principles that coherently guide its development. This rule is compared across three jurisdictions, revealing a complex interplay of purposes which define the boundaries of the rule: deterring police misconduct; remedying the violation of constitutional rights; maintaining judicial integrity; and maintaining the integrity of the justice system as a whole. Problems in the development of the rule result from shifting views of its dominant purpose, and from the tensions between these views. Case law within each jurisdiction exhibits this tension, but nevertheless is generally consistent with the accepted purpose of the rule. The author suggests that differences between jurisdictions represent, in part, differences in their approaches to rights.
<p>
Contradictions remain, however, between the purpose and practice of the rule. Primarily, the narrow rule of standing is inconsistent with the principles underlying the exclusionary rule, regardless of the accepted purpose. The author advances a model to reconcile thresholds for standing with the purpose of the exclusionary rule.
Finally, the ambiguity as to which factors affect the fairness of the trial, and why, must be resolved, as these considerations play a central role in the development of the exclusionary rule in Canada.
<p>
L'auteur pr&eacute;tend que la r&egrave;gle d'exclusion de la preuve devrait &ecirc;tre fond&eacute;e sur des principes qui dirigeraient son d&eacute;veloppement d'une fa&ccedil;on coh&eacute;rente. Il compare la r&egrave;gle &agrave; travers trois juridictions. Une relation complexe s'&eacute;tablit entre les objectifs qui d&eacute;terminent la limite de la r&grave;gle: dissuader la mauvaise conduite polici&egrave;re; rem&eacute;dier &agrave; la violation d'un droit constitutionnel; et maintenir l'int&eacute;grit&eacute; judiciaire. Des changements d'opinion quant au principal objectif, et des tensions entre ces opinions, r&eacute;sultent en des difficult&eacute;s
dans le d&eacute;veloppement de la r&egrave;gle d'exclusion. Ces tensions se retrouvent dans la jurisprudence de chacune des trois juridictions, mais elle est n&eacute;anmoins fid&egrave;le aux objectifs. L'auteur sugg&egrave;re que les diff&eacute;rences entre les juridictions refl&egrave;tent en partie des distinctions dans la conception des droits.
<p>
Toutefois des contradictions existent encore entre l'objectif et l'application de la r&egrave;gle. L'interpr&eacute;tation restrictive du </i>locus standi<i> est incompatible avec les principes de la r&egrave;gle
d'exclusion, sans &eacute;gard &agrave; l'objectif articul&eacute;. L'auteur pr&eacute;sente un mod&egrave;le afin de reconcilier la r&egrave;gle d'exclusion avec le </i>locus standi<i>. Cependent il est n&eacute;cessaire de
clarifier l'ambigu&iuml;t&eacute; quant aux facteurs qui influen&ccedil;eront l'&eacute;quitabilit&eacute; d'un proc&grave;s, car ceux-ci occupent une place pivotale dans le d&eacute;veloppement de la r&egrave;gle d'exclusion au Canada.</i>
<p>
<h3>I: Introduction</h3>

Comparative study of the treatment of illegally obtained evidence by courts in Canada, the United States, and New York reveals that each region has evolved quite distinct regimes in this respect, each with its own areas of contention. The exclusionary rule is defined very much in terms of its purpose and these jurisdictions present contrasting views of both the principles behind the rule and the process whereby exclusion of evidence is considered. Whereas the American jurisdictions employ a categorical exclusionary rule with various judge-made exceptions,<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> Canada has a more discretionary approach, requiring the Court to balance various factors before excluding evidence. <sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> Four primary foundations for the rule have been put forward with varying degrees of acceptance over the years, including a) the need to deter police misconduct, b) the need for a remedy which is inferable from the constitutional guarantee of the right which was violated, c) judicial integrity, and d) the need to maintain the integrity of the justice system as a whole. Canadian and American approaches to the exclusionary rule differ significantly with respect to which of these underlying principles guides the rule.
<p>
Debate continues in both countries between those who favour a strong exclusionary rule and those who fear its impact on effective law enforcement.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> Comparing and contrasting the evolution of case law in these three jurisdictions may point to worthy alternative approaches as well as to dangers that should be avoided. This comparison is particularly crucial for Canadian criminal procedure, which changed dramatically with the introduction of the <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> in 1982, and has begun in the last five years
to swing towards a more exclusionary rule. Certain criteria, if fulfilled, will now lead to nearly categorical exclusion, regardless of the balance of other factors. 
<p>
Any analysis of the American rule, however, must consider the differences between state and federal versions of the
exclusionary doctrines. Although this paper emphasizes the federal rule, New York provides an illuminating state perspective for two reasons. First, it is a major border state, hence it serves to emphasize certain fascinating cross-border differences, differences that persist despite a great cultural similarity on many levels. Second, due to its State Constitution, New York has departed from the federal interpretation of the exclusionary rule in some innovative
and significant ways. Indeed, some commentators, as discussed below, feel that state constitutions may be the last stronghold of an exclusionary rule which has been increasingly weakened at the federal level.
<p>
Many differences in the approach to an exclusionary rule relate to variations in the legal basis and purpose of the
exclusionary powers of the Court in each jurisdiction, and the relationship of the rule to the constitution. For example, the `categorical rule with exceptions' which characterizes American law reflects the absolute nature of many American constitutional rights, whereas the balancing approach used by Canadian courts is consistent
with constitutional recognition that <cite>Charter</cite> rights are not absolute. Other differences relate to the distinct evolution of the common law regarding illegally obtained evidence in Canada as compared to the United States.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> The guiding constitutional law or common law is often ambiguous, however, and
some distinctions may be related as much to v ariations in public and judicial opinion as to jurisdictional differences. 
<p>
Of all aspects of the exclusionary rule, the one most in need of reform (in all three jurisdictions) is standing law, the
threshold one must pass before a Court will consider an application on its merits. The effect of the exclusionary rule depends in large part on its breadth, with the rule's impact weakened by limiting the situations in which violations are found to have occurred, or by limiting standing to invoke the rule. Comparison of these three jurisdictions indicates a surprising degree of similarity regarding `standing', an area of the law that actually raises some of the
greatest contradictions between purpose and practice. This contradiction is especially important in Canada because the Supreme Court has yet to rule directly on this issue. That Court has the chance to avoid entrenching a standing threshold that is inconsistent with the substantive purpose of the exclusionary rule, and with this fact in mind, I shall present a model of standing law which reconciles the principle, or principles, behind the rule with the standing threshold itself. Defining the ideal boundaries of the exclusionary rule raises complex issues which shall be addressed in detail, but only after first reviewing the basis for exclusionary powers, the expressed purpose of those powers, and finally the general criteria considered in each jurisdiction before excluding illegally obtained evidence. Finally, some alternatives to the exclusionary rule will be briefly discussed.
<p>
<h3>II: The Basis and Purpose of Exclusionary Powers</h3>

UNITED STATES (FEDERAL)
<p>
In federal courts, the exclusionary rule has a long and varied history,<sup><a href =  "#five">5</a></sup> with several justifications for its existence appearing over time. The Supreme Court in recent years has consistently approved only one of these justifications, that being its role as a general deterrent against Fourth Amendment violations. In <cite>Mapp v. Ohio</cite>,<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> the first case to apply the federal exclusionary rule to state jurisdictions, the majority of the Court was divided in its reasoning as to why the exclusionary rule applied. The majority judgment grounded the power in the Constitution as a remedy necessarily implied to give substance to the
rights.
<blockquote>
This court has ever since required of federal law officers a strict adherence to that command which this court has held to be a clear, specific, and constitutionally required---even if judicially implied---deterrent safeguard without insistence upon which the Fourth Amendment would have been reduced to `a form of words.'<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution (1791) reads:
<blockquote>
The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated, and no Warrants shall issue, but upon probable cause, supported by Oath or affirmation, and particularly describing the place to be searched, and the persons or things to be seized.
</blockquote>
In addition to the implied remedy argument, some commentators<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> describe <cite>Mapp</cite> as saying that the power to exclude is rooted in a need for the &quot;judicial integrity so necessary in the true administration of justice.&quot;<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> Akin to the language in the Canadian <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>, Justice Clark's judgment seems to suggest that excluding
illegally obtained evidence is necessary to preserve the integrity of the justice system, from the level of the individual to the level of the Court itself.
<p>
Unfortunately, these two arguments were not supported by a complete majority of justices<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> or by later decisions of the Supreme Court, leaving a third major argument as the sole survivor---the deterrence incentive. Recent decisions have gone as far as to state that the exclusionary rule is &quot;a <i>judicially created</i> remedy designed to safeguard Fourth Amendment rights generally through its deterrent effect, rather than a personal constitutional right of the party aggrieved.&quot;<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> This move away from a clear grounding in the Constitution has caused considerable debate; in the absence of a constitutional foundation, the exclusionary rule can no longer be applied to states (which would have to devise their own statutory or constitutionally-derived rules). Some critics believe that by &quot;basing exclusion solely upon deterrence (and not seriously considering judicial and governmental integrity), the Court has dismantled the rule.&quot;<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup>
<p>
At the moment, the dominant and possibly sole purpose of the exclusionary rule is general deterrence of future constitutional violations. Protection of personal rights plays no role in exclusions. As we shall see, this characterization of the purpose leads to a much more limited exclusionary rule than in either of the following two jurisdictions.
<p>
NEW YORK STATE
<p>
As noted above, the United States Constitution serves as the ground for extending the federal exclusionary rule to New York State, but state courts are free to implement their own version of the exclusionary rule, which in some areas is stricter than the federal rule. In fact, the jurisprudence is not entirely clear as to how far the State Constitution protects individual rights by exclusion. State courts tend to interpret state constitutional provisions resembling federal constitutional provisions along lines following federal decisions, although they can develop their own independent reasoning if they wish.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> Some commentators have urged such independent rule-making in light of the weak federal position regarding exclusion of illegally obtained evidence.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> In New York, early jurisprudence on exclusion rejected such a rule at common law, claiming that the State Constitution, once it had been introduced, did not change the common law.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> Until forced to follow <cite>Mapp v. Ohio</cite>, the New York Court was historically reluctant to exclude evidence at all, and as recently as 1982 in <cite>People</cite> v. </cite>Young</cite>, the Court expressly stated that the &quot;underlying purpose of the exclusionary rule is not to redress the injury to the accused's privacy for that privacy once invaded, may never be restored. Rather, the rule's
primary objective is to deter future unlawful police conduct and thereby effectuate the Fourth Amendment's proscription against unreasonable searches and seizures.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
<p>
<cite>People v. Johnson</cite> is perhaps the closest the Court has come to suggesting that exclusion may be a personal remedy for the violation of individual rights, but a more accurate reading is that the Court was merely echoing the federal view that exclusion protects rights generally by deterrence of future misconduct. As
noted in <cite>Johnson</cite>:
<blockquote>
the proscription against unlawful searches and seizures contained in N.Y. Constitution, article 1, S 12 conforms with that found in the 4th Amendment, and ... this identity of language supports a policy of uniformity between State and Federal courts ... Certainly, when the Supreme Court has not addressed a specific issue or provided guidance for such an analysis in its 4th Amendment rulings, we may, as we have in the past, choose to judge the lawfulness of the police conduct by the standards of our State Constitution ... [in this appeal,] the aims of predictability and precision in judicial review of search and seizure cases and <i>the protection of the individual rights of our citizens</i> are best promoted by applying State constitutional standards.<sup><a href ="#seventeen">17</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This reliance on the State Constitution, with its aspect of individual rights protection, has enabled New York to maintain an exclusionary rule with fewer exceptions<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> than the federal rule, which denies the existence of any personal rights guarantee under the Fourth Amendment.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> 
<p>
Although the exclusionary rule has not been elevated yet to a personal remedy for rights violations, the emphasis on protecting individual rights has definitely lead to stricter enforcement of the rule. In <cite>Bigelow</cite> and <cite>Johnson</cite>, the New York courts have added individual protection of rights as another <i>factor</i> to be considered, in addition to deterrence, when deciding if an exception to the rule is warranted. Such a factor only makes sense, however, if there is a constitutional basis for it. Whether the Court moves to the next logical step, expressly recognizing a personal remedy as a necessary implication of the constitutional rights, remains to be
seen.
<p>
CANADA
<p>
Canada, prior to the introduction of the <cite>Charter</cite>, there was very limited common law power to exclude illegally obtained evidence. In the <cite>Queen v. Wray</cite>, Martland J. held that apart from a limited discretion to exclude evidence where it would operate unfairly against the accused, &quot;the function of the court is to determine the issue before it, on the evidence admissible in law, and it does not extend to the exclusion of admissible evidence for any other reason.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> Just before
the advent of the <cite>Charter</cite>, the Supreme Court in <cite>Rothman v. The Queen</cite><sup><a href = #twenty1">21</a></sup> first considered the possibility that police actions bringing &quot;the administration of
justice into disrepute&quot; might justify exclusion of evidence. Lamer J. (as he then was, concurring with the majority for different reasons) and Estey J. (dissenting with Laskin C.J.)  proposed such tests<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> but the majority of the Court followed the common law as established in <cite>Ibrahim v. The King</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> It was the <cite>Charter</cite> that opened the door on
more profound changes.
<p>
One of the primary differences between the American and Canadian jurisdictions is that the Canadian Constitution <i>expressly</i> allows a court to exclude evidence obtained in violation of <cite>Charter</cite> rights. In <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Therens</cite>,<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> the Supreme Court concluded that evidence should be excluded under s. 24(2) rather than s. 24(1),<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> a finding
later confirmed in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Collins</cite>, the case which set the foundation for the Canadian exclusionary rule. Despite this clear constitutional basis for its exclusionary power, the Canadian Court has been criticized both for taking liberties with the text to expand the rule, and for not going far enough in applying the rule in some areas.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup>
<p>
The Supreme Court of Canada adopted a view of the purpose of the exclusionary rule which, on its face, is radically different from that adopted by the United States Supreme Court. Acting with knowledge of the American situation, the Court in <cite>Collins</cite> held that:
<blockquote>
It is whether the admission of the evidence would bring the administration of justice into disrepute that is the applicable test. Misconduct by the police in the investigatory process often has some effect on the repute of the administration of justice, but s. 24(2) is not a remedy for police misconduct, requiring the exclusion of
evidence if, because of this misconduct, the administration of justice was brought into disrepute. Section 24(2) could well have been drafted in that way, but it was not. Rather, the drafts of the <cite>Charter</cite> decided to focus on the admission of the evidence in the proceedings, and the purpose of s. 24(2) is to prevent having the
administration of justice brought into further disrepute by the admission of the evidence in the proceedings. This further disrepute will result from the admission of evidence that would deprive the accused of a fair hearing, or from judicial condonation of unacceptable conduct by the investigatory and prosecutorial agencies. It will also be necessary to consider any disrepute that may result from the exclusion of the evidence. It would be inconsistent with the purpose of s. 24(2) to exclude evidence if its exclusion would bring the administration of justice into greater disrepute than would its admission. Finally, it must be emphasized that even though the inquiry under s. 24(2) will necessarily focus on the specific prosecution, it is the long-term consequences of regular admission or
exclusion of this type of evidence on the repute of the administration of justice which must be considered.<sup><a href="#twenty7</a>27</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Exclusion of evidence as a deterrent against police misconduct seems to be ruled out by the initial words of this
passage, but a deterrence dimension to the rule was clearly retained in the final words. Nevertheless, Canadian courts are primarily required to look at the disrepute arising from the use of any evidence in each particular trial, a principle of judicial, or justice system, integrity. The remedy of exclusion is also, to some extent, a personal constitutional right <i>if</i> the appropriate criteria are met (in the view of the Court), thus differing from the
U.S. position.
<p>
The decision in <cite>Collins</cite> is guided by the text of s. 24(2), and in part perhaps by learning from the difficulties encountered with the rule in its long history in American courts. By avoiding reliance on a deterrence argument, the Court has given the rule both stability and flexibility; crucial evidence may be admitted where necessary, even if investigatory violations deserve to be punished. 
<p>
The interpretation of s. 24(2) also demonstrates elements of judicial creativity. The requirement of &quot;further disrepute&quot;, which minimizes the role of exclusion as `punishment' for police misconduct, is not derived from the text of s. 24(2), for example, nor does the idea that evidence should be admitted if its exclusion would bring further disrepute. A final point of interest is that Justice Lamer's equation of &quot;judicial condonation of unacceptable conduct&quot; with &quot;disrepute&quot; evokes Justice Clark's discussion of  &quot;judicial integrity&quot; as the basis (now rejected) for the American rule in <cite>Mapp v. Ohio</cite>.
<p>
The Canadian view of the exclusionary rule's purpose, then, is more flexible than that of the United States federal system, and somewhat more flexible than the New York view. It is not limited to certain delineated exceptions. Whether it is actually more or less exclusionary is hard to say without a very broad-based empirical study of cases involving suppression issues. How the difference in principles plays out in the characterization of the rule in practice will now be examined in some detail. 
<p>
<h3>III: Characterization of the Exclusionary Rule</h3>

UNITED STATES (FEDERAL)
<p>
The federal exclusionary rule can be described as generally mandating exclusion if there has been a violation of the
Constitution, unless the situation fits within a number of judicially-approved exceptions. Any evidence obtained in violation of the Fourth, Fifth, or Sixth Amendments is to be excluded, but as Justice Holmes stated in <cite>Silverthorne Lumber Co. v. United States</cite>, &quot;this does not mean that the facts thus obtained become sacred and inaccessible.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> In fact, the Supreme Court has outlined a number of circumstances that justify admission of evidence despite violations. 
<p>
Evidence derived from illegal conduct, if classified as the &quot;fruit of the poisonous tree&quot; (that is, causally connected to the violation), will also be excluded. The test for this exclusion is outlined in <cite>Segura v. United States</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> If the evidence would not have been discovered, &quot;but for&quot; the illegality, it may be excluded, though not necessarily so if the circumstances come under one of the exceptions.
<p>
Rather than concentrate solely on the known exceptions, however, one should consider the underlying rationales as well, because only a few important ones account for most of the exceptions to the exclusionary rule, and will lead to the most crucial future developments in the law. These rationales include:
<ol>
<li>Evidence will only be excluded to the extent that the exclusion leaves the police (and the defendant) &quot;in the same, not a <i>worse</i>, position than they would have been in if no police error or misconduct had occurred.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> This reasoning lies behind<br>
a) the independent source doctrine;<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup><br>
b) the inevitable discovery doctrine;<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> and to some extent,<br>
c) the attenuation of causal connection doctrine;<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> and,
<p>
<li>Evidence will not be excluded if the general deterrence effect on future constitutional violations is outweighed by the social cost of excluding undeniably probative evidence.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> If deterrence will have no effect on a similar fact situation in the future, the evidence will likely be admitted.<sup><a href ="#thirty5">35</a></sup> This rationale forms the basis of:<br>
d) the good faith exception.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup><br>
It can also be extended to cover cases where deterrence of police action would be an undesirable result, as in the case of:<br>
e) the emergency/exigent circumstances exception.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup>
</ol>
Balancing of various factors can occur in the federal exclusionary rule, depending on the context, but the factors to be valued and balanced are primarily the benefit of deterring police misconduct and negligence, the social cost of exclusion (given great emphasis in many cases), and to some extent, the effect on the trial (if a harmless effect, no change will be made).<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> The balance is guided by the rationales listed above, and as will be demonstrated, is potentially much narrower in scope than the balance in New York and Canada. In addition, the federal rule may give much higher weight to the social cost of exclusion<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> than the rule in Canada, at least on the surface.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> Before moving on to discuss the exclusionary rule in
other jurisdictions, however, the five main exceptions listed above will be briefly reviewed.
<p>
a) <i>The Independent Source Doctrine</i>:
<br>
This doctrine was first defined in <cite>Silverthorne Lumber Co.</cite>, when Justice Holmes stated that if &quot;knowledge of [facts gained by illegal means] is gained by an independent source they may be proved like any others, but the knowledge gained by the Government's own wrong cannot be used by it in the way
proposed.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> Recent cases like <cite>Nix v. Williams</cite> and <cite>Murray v. United States</cite> indicate that the Court will not allow agents of the government to place themselves in a better situation by illegally obtaining evidence, but neither will courts place them in a worse situation than they would have been in absent the illegality.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> In <cite>Murray</cite>, the leading case on independent source doctrine, a warrant for a search was obtained following the illegal entry of a warehouse. In the initial search, the warehouse was found to contain bales of marijuana, but the police did not use
or rely on the evidence from the illegal search in obtaining the warrant.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup>  Under the
circumstances, the Supreme Court held that the evidence from a second search (with the warrant) was obtained <i>independent</i> of the original illegality.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> Even if the warrant was based in part on illegally obtained evidence, the Court would still uphold the warrant if it could have been validly issued in any case on the basis of the remaining untainted evidence.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
<p>
b) <i>The Inevitable Discovery Doctrine</i>:
<br>
Similar to the doctrine above, if illegally obtained evidence would have been discovered regardless, to exclude it would place the police in a worse position than they would have been in absent the illegality. The courts refuse to punish police in this way.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> Instead, if police can &quot;establish by a preponderance of the evidence that the information ultimately or inevitably would have been discovered by lawful means ... then the deterrence rationale has so little basis that the evidence should be received.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> The police need not even prove an absence of bad faith, because the Supreme Court felt that this would risk placing the police in a worse situation than that in which they would have been.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> In practice, the burden of proving inevitable discovery may be quite low since courts have routinely accepted that certain procedures such as proper searches would have been used in due course.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup>
<p>
The difficulty with the inevitable discovery doctrine, permissible under the &quot;no worse position&quot; rationale, is that it is really an oracular fiction---although there is <i>definitely</i> police misconduct, there need only be a &quot;preponderance of evidence&quot; that discovery would have resulted in any case. To admit evidence in such cases may excuse &quot;bad faith&quot; by failing to consider it as a factor at all. As long as the inevitable discovery doctrine is retained, it seems that the first rationale cited above takes precedence over the second. This doctrine also impacts indirectly on the second rationale by reducing the deterrent force of the exclusionary rule generally, making it more likely that evidence will also be admitted under that rationale in the future.
<p>
c) <i>Attenuation of Causal Connection</i>:
<br>
According to the Court in <cite>Wong Sun</cite>, if the evidence was obtained in a manner that was sufficiently distinguishable from the illegality as to be &quot;purged of the primary taint&quot; (i.e. the causal connection was broken), it will be admissible.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> Determining whether the causal chain has been broken will vary on a case by case basis but three factors should certainly be considered.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> These include: (a) the\break temporal proximity of the illegality and the evidence;<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> (b) the  resence of intervening circumstances;<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> and particularly (c) the &quot;purpose and flagrancy of the official misconduct.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup>
<p>
d) <i>The Good Faith Exception</i>:
<br>
The basis of this exception is that no deterrent value will result from excluding evidence if officers were relying in good faith upon a warrant,<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> or operating under a law<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> which they honestly believed to be valid at the time. Similarly situated officers in the future, unaware that they were operating under a false assumption, would not be deterred from acting. In <cite>United States v. Leon</cite>, the Supreme Court held that officers acting under a facially valid warrant were acting in good faith and that the evidence they obtained should not be excluded.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup>
<p>
The Court in <cite>Leon</cite> opened up a large possible exception with this ruling, but also set up certain safeguards that must be observed before deference to the magistrate's warrant is acceptable. As we shall see in the discussion of Canadian jurisprudence, good faith on the part of police is one of the most common justifications put forward by the prosecution to remove the taint from evidence. The <cite>Leon</cite> ruling set four limits on when a warrant will be objectively reasonable (in light of the fact that probable cause is normally evaluated using a totality of the circumstances test).<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> Deference to the magistrate's decision will not be given if (a) the warrant was based on the knowing or reckless falsity of an affidavit;<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> (b) the magistrate was not &quot;neutral and detached;&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> (c) there was no substantial basis for determining the existence of probable cause under the totality of circumstances;<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> or (d) there was no objectively valid reason for the officers to believe the warrant was facially valid.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> Whether these safeguards will be sufficient to maintain the deterrent force of the exclusionary rule, however, is questionable.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup>
<p>
e) <i>Emergency/Exigent Circumstances</i>:
<br>
In <cite>U.S. v. Chadwick</cite>, the Court recognized certain exigent circumstances as exceptions to the exclusionary rule. These circumstances include danger to the public or the officers, as well as a need to preserve evidence in danger of imminent removal or destruction.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> The presence of such factors is defined largely by the context.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
<p>
Many of the concepts discussed above have their counterparts in New York State law, but as the following discussion will show, there are significant differences, most of which can be traced back to a desire to provide greater protection for constitutional rights in New York State.
<p>
NEW YORK STATE
<p>
Many of the principles of state law mirror developments in the federal exclusionary rule, but in several cases New York has enforced a stricter version of the rule. The underlying rationales behind New York's exceptions to the general rule defined in <cite>Mapp v. Ohio</cite> differ somewhat from federal rationales. The
first rationale listed above is unchanged, but after <cite>People v. Johnson</cite> and <cite>People v. Bigelow</cite>, the second rationale should be rephrased. In New York, evidence will only be excluded if the benefit obtained by deterring state misconduct <i>and protecting individual  rights</i><sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> offsets the social cost of excluding relevant evidence. Other factors such as judicial integrity and abusiveness of police misconduct have also been mentioned by New York courts, though with
less frequency.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup>
<p>
How much weight the state courts will give to the factor of individual rights protection remains uncertain at this time. At one end of the spectrum is the federal rule, which presently views general deterrence as the only relevant means of protecting rights. At the other end is the view that any infringement of a personal right requires a punitive exclusionary remedy. New York, like Canada, occupies a middle position, and as yet, courts in New York have not given clear weight to this factor. Two main choices face the Court, either (a) a rule that excludes illegally obtained
evidence in <i>all</i> cases, except when it would put the state in a <i>worse</i> position than it would have been in if not for the error (a categorical version of rationale number one, above; this direction may be the one taken in <cite>Bigelow</cite> when the Court rejected <cite>Leon</cite>), or (b) a rule that emphasizes rationale number two, above, and balances various factors even if it does put the police in a worse position (as in Canada). The implications of such shifts for each of the major federal exceptions should be reviewed.
<p>
<cite>People v. Knapp</cite><sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> established a &quot;fruit of the poisonous tree&quot; doctrine in New York, and exceptions similar to federal ones have followed.
<p>
a) <i>The Independent Source Doctrine</i>:
<br>
The doctrine in New York mirrors that in the federal jurisdiction and does not appear to be affected by <cite>Bigelow</cite> and <cite>Johnson</cite>, unless the Court decides to give priority to the balancing (second) rationale rather than to the &quot;no worse position&quot; (first) rationale.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
<p>
b) <i>The Inevitable Discovery Doctrine</i>:
<br>
In <cite>People v. Acevedo</cite>,<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> the Court followed <cite>Nix v. Williams</cite> in adopting the federal position on inevitable discovery.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> The Court may even have effectively <i>lowered</i> the burden of proof required to establish inevitability of discovery. A warrant was issued for a search between six a.m. and nine p.m., but the search occurred at 4:15 a.m.; the Court said no evidence suggested there would have been any change in circumstance between 4:15 and the proper time for legal use of the warrant (six a.m.), therefore search products were admitted. This phrasing seems less onerous than the need for a preponderance of evidence required in <cite>Nix</cite>. More disturbing, if it were truly &quot;inevitable&quot; that there would have been no change in circumstances, why did the officers feel the need to begin two hours early when they had a valid warrant for six a.m.?
<p>
The possibility that the second rationale (balancing of factors) may take precedence over the first rationale (&quot;no worse position&quot;) appears in a recent case. <cite>People v. Brandon</cite><sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> suggests there is authority for refusing to apply the inevitable discovery doctrine to evidence obtained directly, as opposed to indirectly, from the illegality. Such reasoning might have resulted in a different holding in <cite>Acevedo</cite>.
<p>
c) <i>Attenuation of Causal Connection</i>:
<br>
The test in New York, developed in <cite>People v. Martinez</cite>,<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> generally follows the federal position established in <cite>Brown v. Illinois</cite> and has not
been affected by the changes noted above.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> Nevertheless, an indication of interpretive differences between the state and federal method of applying the test can be seen in <cite>New York v. Harris</cite>.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> With probable cause related to a murder, police entered the accused's apartment without a warrant, gave him <cite>Miranda</cite> warnings and began an interrogation resulting in an admission of guilt. This entry of the home was held to be unconstitutional<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> (evidence gathered at the home was suppressed as the fruit of illegality). After transfer to the precinct, a second interrogation occurred one hour later (after a second <cite>Miranda</cite> warning) in which the defendant again admitted guilt.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> The New York Court of Appeals found that the short time between the illegality and the second statement was insufficient attenuation. The statement was deemed the &quot;fruit&quot; of the illegal entry. At the Supreme Court, however, the decision was reversed in a five to four decision (Marshall, Brennan, Blackmun and Stevens, JJ. dissenting). The Supreme Court majority placed weight on the fact that probable cause to detain the suspect existed, therefore the interrogation at the precinct was inevitable anyway;<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> it held that the constitutional <cite>Payton</cite> violation ended when the suspect was removed from the site of the illegal entry. In addition, the Court indicated that enough deterrence was gained by excluding all evidence seized at the home, rendering further exclusions unnecessary.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> The dissent rejected the home/precinct distinction and insisted on applying the three
factors set out in <cite>Brown</cite>, reaching the same conclusion as the Court of Appeals, that the second confession was not sufficiently attenuated.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> The Supreme Court decision implies that the statement could have been obtained legally in any case (the first rationale), whereas the New York Court of Appeals applied a stricter rule, concentrating on whether the events in the home produced the fruit of the second confession.
<p>
d) <i>Good Faith Exception</i>:
<br>
Relying on the State Constitution, New York courts have rejected applying <cite>Leon</cite>'s good faith exception both to searches without a warrant<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> and searches with a warrant believed valid.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> The Court in <cite>Johnson</cite> rejected the federal test of probable
cause, defined in <cite>Illinois v. Gates</cite><sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> as sufficient cause under the &quot;totality of circumstances.&quot;  Instead, the more rigorous two-pronged test of the <cite>Aguilar-Spinelli</cite> rule was retained as the standard.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> The alternative of a good faith exception was expressly rejected &quot;as a matter of State constitutional law&quot; in <cite>Bigelow</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup>
<p>
It appears that New York State courts are considering more than just the deterrent effect in making suppression decisions. Unfortunately, the cases to date have not made it entirely clear what other factors are considered and what weight they should be given. A clear statement of the rule is lacking.
<p>
e) <i>The Emergency/Exigent Circumstances Doctrine</i>:
<br>
As with the federal doctrine, there are general principles which justify warrantless searches in cases where an officer
&quot;reasonably perceives that [an] emergency situation exists,&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> so long as the search is related in time and extent to the circumstances validating the arrest.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
Justifications for this exception include securing the safety of the public<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> and the officer (hence its relevance to search incident to arrest),<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> and protection of evidence from destruction or concealment (hence its extension to mobile items such as automobiles and their  contents).<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> One specialized branch of the exception is referred to specifically as the `automobile exception.'<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup>
<p>
Having seen that New York's exclusionary rule seems to have given a greater role than the federal rule to factors other than deterrence, an examination of the Canadian rule is in order.
<p>
CANADA
<p>
The Supreme Court of Canada, in <cite>Collins</cite>, outlined a set of relevant factors to be considered and balanced during exclusion motions, no single factor initially being held sufficient on its own to grant admission or exclusion.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> Unlike in the United States, even after evidence is shown to be illegally obtained, the onus is on the accused to show that admission of the evidence will bring the administration of justice into disrepute.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> Defining disrepute &quot;requires the judge to refer to what he conceives to be the views of the community at large,&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> though only in an abstract sense (and only when that community's mood is reasonable), guided by the factors set out in <cite>Collins</cite>. Three main classes of factors were specified by Lamer J. (as he then was)---those relating to:<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup>
<blockquote>
a) the fairness of the trial; <br>
b) the seriousness of the <cite>Charter</cite> violation; and <br>
c) the effect of excluding the evidence.
</blockquote>
Significantly, in Canadian law, there is no underlying rationale limiting exclusion if it would &quot;put the police in a worse position.&quot;  Instead, any piece of evidence could theoretically be excluded if the balance of factors weighs against it. As a result, judges in Canada have greater flexibility in dealing with the factual circumstances of each case than their American counterparts. On a positive note, balancing allows judges to be more sensitive to the
different weights given to factors such as the probative value of and need for evidence in different contexts. On a negative note, such a broad discretionary range may be a licence to make case law that is based primarily on the facts of each case and not on coherent principles. The latter problem is most apparent in search and seizure cases when the evidence to be excluded is generally both highly probative and necessary for a conviction. Sympathies will not often lie with the accused in such cases, particularly if serious crimes are involved. Rights protection may take second place behind crime control.
<p>
Despite this apparent difference between the United States and Canada, there are actually many similarities between the factors balanced in Canada and the factors and exceptions considered in the United States. The primary distinction is in the role played by each factor. Good faith, for example, is a blanket exception in the federal U.S. system, and is not an exception at all in New York, whereas it is one of many factors that are balanced in Canada, its
weight varying from case to case depending on the circumstances. Consideration of the <cite>Collins</cite> factors in more detail will illuminate the distinctions even more.
<p>
<i>Fairness of the Trial</i>
<br>
Since the Supreme Court's decision in <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, where fairness of the trial is affected, the evidence will likely be excluded without regard to the other circumstances, making violations of this factor lead to near-categorical exclusion.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> Even before <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, any effect on the fairness of the trial was given strong, but not conclusive weight.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> Prior to  <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, however, the Court held that real evidence &quot;obtained in a manner that violated the <cite>Charter</cite> will rarely operate unfairly for that reason alone,&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> as opposed to inculpatory statements which would almost certainly affect trial fairness. That situation appears to have changed.
<p>
To understand why the nature of the evidence is now less conclusive a factor, one must ask how fairness of the trial is initially defined. In <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Genest</cite>, Dickson C.J.C. asked the question: &quot;would the admission of the evidence change the balance of the trial because of the nature of the particular <cite>Charter</cite> infringement in that case?&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup> This concept of changing the balance of the trial reflects the first rationale listed for the American federal system: do not exclude, if it will put the state in a worse position than it would have been in without the misconduct. In Canada, however, the rationale is best stated: do not <i>admit</i> evidence if it would not have been found but for the violation (i.e. do not put the state in a better position than it would have been in). This line of thought seems to lie behind both <cite>Mellenthin</cite> and the &quot;preliminary question&quot; (or &quot;discoverability&quot;) doctrine outlined recently by the Supreme Court in <cite>R. v. Dersch</cite>.<sup><a href="#hundred">100</a></sup> In <cite>Dersch</cite> the Court said &quot;the preliminary question one must ask is whether the evidence obtained would have been discovered had the <cite>Charter</cite> violation not occurred.&quot; That case built on <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, which in turn built on <cite>Thomson Newspapers Ltd. v. Canada</cite>, a case which gave new weight to statements made by Lamer C.J.C. in <cite>Collins</cite>.
<p>
Defining fairness of the trial in this fashion (by discoverability in the absence of a <cite>Charter</cite> violation) forms a more coherent doctrine than the pre-<cite>Mellenthin</cite> view. There are now four main sub-factors under the fairness of the trial area:
<dl>
<dt>a) the nature of the evidence obtained;<sup><a href="#hundred1">101</a></sup>
<dd>Real evidence <i>was</i> generally admitted whereas evidence created by the misconduct was excluded (especially statements or other forms of self-incriminating evidence). 
<dt>b) the nature of the right violated;<sup><a href="#hundred2">102</a></sup>
<dt>c) whether the evidence could have been obtained without a violation;<sup><a href="#hundred3">103</a></sup>
<dd>This factor has not previously been stressed, but with the advent of <cite>Mellenthin</cite> and <cite>Dersch</cite>, this factor may be the seed for a Canadian version of the inevitable discovery and
independent source doctrines. Already, the case of <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Grant</cite> appears to provide a rationale similar to the latter doctrine. In <cite>Grant</cite>, a warrant based in part on information from an earlier illegal search was upheld on the basis that other information given for the warrant would have been sufficient in any
case. The inevitable discovery doctrine seems to be mirrored in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Colarusso</cite>, in which blood sample analyses wrongfully seized by police were admissible on the basis that they <i>could</i> have been legally seized in any case with a proper warrant, had the wrongful seizure not taken place. Note that the facts are similar to those in <cite>Dersch</cite>, wherein the analyses were excluded. However, in <cite>Colarusso</cite> the blood had already been legally sampled by the coroner (though not for police use)
whereas in <cite>Dersch</cite>, the doctors involved breached their duty of confidentiality in giving police the samples.
<p>
There is a tension in this factor that is discussed below in more detail. Despite similarities with American doctrines, these factors may not be sufficient on their own to decide the exclusion issue, depending on the balance of other factors.
<dt>d) whether the accused was conscripted against himself<sup><a href="#hundred4">104</a></sup>
<dd>This factor was not one of the factors initially stressed in <cite>Collins</cite>, but it came to the forefront in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Ross</cite>. Lineup evidence after a violation of s.10(b) of the <cite>Charter</cite> (right to counsel) was excluded because the accused was &quot;conscripted against himself since he [was] used as a means for creating evidence for the purposes of the trial.&quot; This concept may have been the beginning of the reasoning in <cite>Mellenthin</cite> and <cite>Dersch</cite>. 
</dl>
If the evidence obtained has probative value and low prejudicial effect (in the sense that it does not lead the jury to
irrational conclusions), is fairness of the trial really being affected?  What the Court seems to be measuring is the taint on the fairness of the judicial process as a whole, beginning with police investigations; taint carries over into the trial. Misconduct in the former throws the latter into disrepute, but does not render the <i>trial</i> unfair unless the Court refers to some fictional &quot;pre-existing balance&quot; of evidence to which each side would have had access in a world that lived according to the <cite>Charter</cite>, as suggested in <cite>Genest</cite>. 
<p>
Certainly the nature of the evidence is itself not conclusive and should not affect the fairness of the trial. Even
inculpatory statements, if they meet common law standards of admissibility,<sup><a href="#hundred5">105</a></sup> will not necessarily have any less probative value or any greater prejudicial effect if they are obtained by a violation of <cite>Charter</cite> rights. If the reliability of the statement is affected, there may be prejudicial effect. However, if reliability is not affected, and in particular if the statement is later corroborated, the fact that it is a statement should not have any effect on trial fairness. Some observers may respond that an illegally obtained statement violates the right to full answer and defence<sup><a href="#hundred6">106</a></sup> by forcing the accused to breach their right to silence in defence and by breaching the right against self-incrimination. However, the same is true of statements not obtained by police misconduct. 
<p>
The difference, and perhaps a crucial one, is that in the case of misconduct, the inculpatory statement may not have been given voluntarily if the rights had been respected (in particular the right to counsel); voluntary statements, absent misconduct, may be presumed to be waivers of the right to silence. Following the logic of the preliminary question doctrine, one could conclude that inculpatory statements that might/would not have been given but for the
misconduct will affect the fairness of the trial. Statements that would have been given in any case would not affect the fairness of the trial but would potentially still bring the administration of justice as a whole into disrepute by affecting the fairness of the investigatory system. 
<p>
The best rationale of exclusion, then, would be based solely on the <i>manner</i> of obtaining the evidence, and not on the nature of the evidence, contrary to the view expressed by Lamer J. in <cite>Collins</cite>.<sup><a href="#hundred7">107</a></sup> Such a route would avoid much of the confusion surrounding how to classify various types of evidence, as if calling it &quot;real evidence&quot; is a magical boundary that once crossed, justifies admission of the evidence.<sup><a href="#hundred8">108</a></sup> It would also be a test that judges could still apply with some precision, especially if evidence on discoverability is led by both sides.
<p>
As pointed out by Paciocco,<sup><a href="#hundred9">109</a></sup> however, cases like <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Duarte</cite><sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> and <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Wiggins</cite><sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> appear to involve conscription of defendants against themselves (statements that would not have been heard but for the violation), yet the Court admitted the evidence largely on the basis that police acted in good faith (for example, on the basis of a facially valid law). Either good faith is capable of trumping the
trial fairness factor in some cases, or there is no trial unfairness in those cases. If the latter is true, it might be explained by assuming that police would have followed <cite>Charter</cite> ideals had they known the law was invalid, therefore they would have obtained a warrant and inevitably have obtained the same evidence anyway. This may be a subtle form of inevitable discovery logic, although the Court does not phrase it this way.
<p>
One final ambiguity that may need to be resolved is that <cite>Mellenthin</cite> suggests that fairness of the trial is affected when evidence would not have been found but for the participation of the accused and a violation of their rights. It is not clear why participation of the accused is crucial. Mellenthin helped the officer in that case search his bag, but would there have been any less unfairness to the trial if the officer had just walked along the street and randomly probed through Mellenthin's car when Mellenthin was elsewhere? Surely the doctrine set out in <cite>Mellenthin</cite> should be clarified to read: any evidence which could not have been obtained but for the violation of someone's (not necessarily the accused's) <cite>Charter</cite> rights, will affect the fairness of the
trial.
<p>
<i>Seriousness of the Charter Violation</i>
<br>
The four main factors considered under this grouping include:
<ol>
<li>seriousness of the violation;<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup>
<li>the deliberate, willful or good faith character of police action;<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup>
<li>urgency and necessity;<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> and,
<li>whether other means were available to obtain the evidence.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup>
</ol>
Although no one factor is sufficient to decide the issue of exclusion, good faith and the reasonableness of the violation (e.g. a reasonable rather than an abusive search) have consistently been used as major justifications for admitting evidence.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup>
<p>      
<i>Effect of Exclusion</i>
<br>
The factors concerning the effect of exclusion are analogous to the American view of the &quot;costs&quot; of excluding relevant evidence, although Canadian courts tend to enunciate more expressly the component elements of the cost. These component factors include:
<ol>
<li>the seriousness of the charge;<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup>
<li>how essential the evidence is to the case;<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> and
<li>the availability of other remedies short of exclusion.<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup>
</ol>
As discussed above, courts in the United States expressly give great weight to the cost of exclusion in defining their balance. Canadian courts do not always emphasize the factor expressly; in fact, they often downplay it.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup>
<p>
Since the seriousness of the crime and the key nature of the questioned evidence seem to be such strong factors to the American courts, and likely to the general public as well, I reviewed a sample of recent exclusion cases with <cite>Charter</cite> violations<sup><a href="one21">121</a></sup> to see if any trends appeared. The survey is not
intended to be conclusive or statistically accurate because even reported cases are pre-selected for certain reasons; rather it is intended to give a quick impression of how these factors <i>may</i> impact on exclusion decisions by taking the first small step beyond theory to look at the actual practice of the courts. To make a more accurate assessment of trends, a comparison of a random sample of actual trials dealing with exclusion questions would be required (working from transcripts to gain an objective view of the weight given to various factors). 
<p>
Of 53 Canadian cases noted, only 20 resulted in exclusion of the evidence (thirty-eight per cent). Of those 20 exclusions, only two occurred in a murder case (statements and related conduct), and the Court upheld the conviction directly in one of those cases anyway due to the strength of other evidence.<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> The rest were predominantly narcotic or impaired driving offences, with one assault
and one break and enter. 
<dl>
<dt><i>Murders</i>:<dd>Of seven murder cases in the sample, only one effectively resulted in exclusion affecting
the trial. 
<dt><i>Statements</i>: <dd>Six of thirteen statements were excluded (forty-six per cent).
<dt><i>Real Evidence</i>: <dd>Only seven of twenty-two pieces of real evidence in issue were excluded (thirty-two per cent) (not counting breath and blood sample evidence).
</dl>
Comparing the Canadian cases to a sample of New York cases<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup> reveals some differences, although the smaller sample size makes conclusions tenuous at best. Of 15 cases with rights violations, only six exclusions resulted (forty per cent), similar to the Canadian ratio. Of the six exclusions, one was a murder case involving statements.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> The rest were possession offences (weapons or narcotics). In New York, half of the excluded pieces of evidence (three of six) were statements, as compared to only twenty-six per
cent in Canada.
<dl>
<dt><i>Murders</i>: <dd>one of two resulted in exclusion.
<dt><i>Statements</i>: <dd>three of four were excluded (seventy-five per cent---much higher than in Canada)
<dt><i>Real Evidence</i>: <dd>three of nine excluded (thirty-three per cent, similar to Canada)
</dl>
Several possible generalizations suggest themselves from this brief survey. First, Canadian courts may give more weight to the seriousness of the offence and the probative value of the evidence than they are saying (although it should be noted that there are simply far fewer murder cases in the system than impaired driving cases, for example; there are murder cases in which evidence was excluded that did not fall in the random sample).<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> Of seven murders, only one crucial piece of evidence was excluded. Second, statements are more readily excluded than real evidence in both jurisdictions, particularly in New York. New York courts, then, may be looking at the nature of the evidence even though they do not expressly say so. Again, hasty conclusions should be avoided, because it may simply be that statements are not usually as crucial to the case as real evidence, and the cost of excluding statements is therefore lower. Third, overall, the chances of succeeding with a suppression motion are not markedly different in the two jurisdictions, but this fails to consider a) variations in types of crimes dealt with,<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> and b) the possible difference in filtering of exclusion claims at the level of defining whether a right was ever violated.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup>
<p>
One factor largely ignored is the effect of increased probative value. For example, blood tests and DNA analyses in
particular may be highly probative. To exclude evidence of such a high probative value as a DNA match might be more difficult for a court than the exclusion of more ambiguous evidence; at the very least it might affect the balance of factors more than other types of evidence.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup>
<p>
<i>Tensions</i>
<br>
Several internal tensions are set up within the balance of factors without a clear resolution. Both the `seriousness of the offence' and the `possibility of obtaining evidence by another manner' could weigh either for or against exclusion. The seriousness of the offence, as indicated, is often downplayed, but may favour admission more than is granted. However, as <cite>Collins</cite> points out, the more serious the offence, the greater the consequences to the accused, therefore it should favour exclusion, at least where fairness of the trial is in question.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> In practice the courts may have come down on the side of admission, regardless of whether the evidence affects the fairness of the trial, but it remains unclear. 
<p>
If evidence could have been obtained by another means, obtaining it by a <cite>Charter</cite> violation suggests disrespect for the <cite>Charter</cite> and exclusion is mandated under the &quot;seriousness of the violation&quot; category, however, in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Grant</cite> and <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Colarusso</cite>, the Supreme Court seems to have approved admission of tainted evidence largely <i>on the basis</i> that it could have been obtained in any case.<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> In those cases and in <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, inevitable discoverability and independent sources for obtaining evidence suggest that under the first category, fairness of the trial will not be affected. It is not clear how this tension is to be resolved without overruling or clarifying either <cite>Collins</cite> or <cite>Mellenthin</cite> on this single point. 
<p>
COMPARISON
<p>
The Canadian balance of factors expressly considers three factors that American courts either fail to address or give low weight---the nature of the evidence, the conscription of the accused against himself, and the seriousness of the rights violation. Regarding the former two factors, the Canadian courts appear to be moving towards the American position, looking less at the type of evidence and more at whether the evidence would have been discovered without the violation. Regarding the third factor, Canadian courts continue to take a harsh view of abusive police conduct. Many if not most exclusions involve cases of willful or abusive rights violations.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> In the United States, abusive conduct is occasionally mentioned as a possible factor, but rules such as the inevitable discovery doctrine potentially condone abusive or willful misconduct. In Canada, which has no categorical exceptions, there is a greater deterrence check on police misconduct since misconduct weighs heavily in the balance of factors.
<p>
There are both advantages and disadvantages to having a balance of factors rather than a more categorical rule with fixed exceptions. One advantage is that judges have more flexibility in weighing concerns on a case by case basis. Canadian courts also do the balancing more expressly than American courts, which often merely state their conclusions. This allows lawyers, other judges, and the public generally to see the balance and get a sense for the weight of the different factors. Public opinion can track judges' behavior and provide feedback. This is more important in Canada than in the United States because s. 24 expressly requires a determination as to whether the administration of justice will be brought into disrepute.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup> The drawback of a balance is that it may just provide a broad discretion for judges to concentrate more on the facts of each case than on underlying principles. For example, the seriousness of the charge may become a disproportionately emphasized factor, psychologically, while other factors serve as a mask to justify any decision made. If one trusts the judiciary, a balance may be appropriate, otherwise bright-line rules and exceptions might lead to a more principled approach.
<p>
The Canadian approach has distinct advantages over the American approach in two senses. First, the jurisprudence mandating protection of individual rights is firmly rooted in the text of the constitutional exclusionary rule, hence there is no real danger of the Court extinguishing the exclusionary rule. In the United States, however, there is a real danger that a conservative `crime-control' court could (or may already have) undermined the rule by refusing to
recognize a constitutional imperative for rights protection via the exclusionary rule. The only resort for due process proponents, if the trend continues, may be through strengthened state exclusionary rules, based independently on state constitutions, as in New York.
<p>
The second advantage of the Canadian experience is the genuine flexibility of the <cite>Collins</cite> balance. While it leaves a great deal of discretion in the judge's hands, in the last ten years the courts have proven their willingness under the <cite>Charter</cite> to go far beyond pre-<cite>Charter</cite> jurisprudence in excluding evidence, rapidly building a case law foundation that explicitly and implicitly tries to balance elements of rights protection, police regulation, crime control and attention to community morality. Even the elements of the <cite>Collins</cite> test themselves show a concern for this broad range of interests, and the factors that courts seem to have stressed most in recent years (fairness of the trial, good faith on the part of police, the type of right infringed, and the seriousness of the crime) demonstrate a balance that at the very least does not prejudice rights to other interests. The Court has even recently required that police advise suspects in breathalyzer cases of a
1-800 number that Ontario has made available for duty counsel assistance. There was no constitutional requirement that the program be set up initially but since it has in fact been put in place, the Supreme Court has ruled that it must be made <i>effectively</i> available otherwise evidence of test results may be excluded. 
<p>
The <cite>Mellenthin</cite> case may even have further strengthened the <cite>Collins</cite> test for the accused by stating that if fairness of the trial is affected, evidence will be excluded, regardless of the other factors. However, <cite>Mellenthin</cite> also ushered the inevitable discovery doctrine into Canadian law, providing a new tool for both the accused and the Crown to justify admission or exclusion. In many cases it may work to the disadvantage of the accused. Are inculpatory statements now no longer going to affect fairness of the trial if the Crown can show
that they would have been uttered in any case, for example?
<p>
One advantage of the American system which may be useful is the assignment of definite weight to certain factors such as good faith and inevitable discoverability. Many Canadian decisions spend very little time discussing the weight assigned to <cite>Collins</cite> factors in a given case, perhaps because it is not clear what weight
they <i>should</i> be assigning. Making the weight clearer eliminates fears of arbitrariness in the law and one can establish clear guidelines without necessarily laying down rigid categorical rules. Since the <cite>Charter</cite> exclusionary rule only arrived in Canada just over a decade ago, the courts may still be leaving the questions open somewhat. More likely however is that they have reached a stable balance and are now adapting slowly to new
situations as they arise. Given the balance noted above, such a strategy is appropriate and not inconsistent with the purpose of the exclusionary rule in Canada. The American rule is relatively consistent with its stated purpose, but as noted, that purpose itself is threatened, particularly as concern with crime control in the United States continues to grow. 
<p>
An area in which rapid change is needed in all of the jurisdictions, however, is in the threshold requirements of standing law, which presently bar many people from the protection of the rule no matter how flagrant the violation of the right.
<p>
<h3>IV: Standing</h3>

A crucial element of any study of the exclusionary rule is the standing threshold which must be crossed before a suppression motion can even be considered on its merits. Examination of standing jurisprudence in the three jurisdictions reveals major contradictions between the substantive principles behind the exclusionary rule and
the standing threshold as presently defined. In order to reconcile principle and practice, an alternative standing regime will be presented and evaluated at the end of this section. First, however, I shall briefly review the present law in each jurisdiction.
<p>
UNITED STATES (FEDERAL)
<p>
The federal standing rule has evolved considerably in the past thirty years,<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> beginning with the Supreme Court's decision in <cite>Katz v. United States</cite><sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> which marked a major change from Fourth Amendment exclusionary claims based on property/possessory interests to one based on a &quot;legitimate expectation of privacy.&quot;  Since this change, standing law has evolved along lines paralleling suppression requirements in search and seizure, beginning with <cite>Alderman v. United States</cite><sup><a href ="#one35">135</a></sup> in which the Court followed a deterrence rationale in deciding not to extend standing to other defendants.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> One could only urge suppression
of evidence if one's rights were violated by the search itself and not merely by the introduction of evidence at trial.<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> The cases of <cite>Rakas v. Illinois</cite><sup><a href="#one38</a>138</a></sup> and <cite>United States v. Salvucci</cite>[a href="#one39</a></sup> effectively closed the door on significant expansion of the standing doctrine, rejecting Justice Fortas' dissent in <cite>Alderman</cite>, which advocated extension of standing to at least those who were targets of searches, if not to anyone against whom the evidence was to be used.<sup><a href="one40">140</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Rakas</cite>, the Supreme Court outlined two criteria that must be met before standing will be granted: &quot;first, whether the proponent of a particular legal right has alleged `injury in fact,' and, second, whether the proponent is asserting his own legal rights and interests rather than basing his claim for relief upon the rights of third parties.&quot;<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup>To assert such a right, a defendant can no longer simply rely on possessory interests because <cite>Katz</cite> was construed to mean that &quot;the protection of the Fourth  Amendment depends not upon a property right in the invaded place but upon whether the person who claims the protection of the Amendment has a legitimate expectation of privacy in the invaded place.&quot;<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup> Not even ownership of the object seized is of any assistance in establishing standing, without the expectation of privacy.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> One is then led to wonder why, if proprietary interests are not\break `sufficient,' they should still be `necessary' if the Amendment is really about protecting people not places.
<p>
Prior to <cite>Salvucci</cite>, there had been a limited `automatic standing' rule for defendants in possession cases, because establishing standing would require the assertion of a possessory interest, thereby amounting to self-incrimination.<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> The Court granted relief for the same dilemma in non-possessory cases in <cite>Simmons v. United States</cite><sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> (bank robbery) by holding that suppression hearing testimony could not be used against the defendant at trial on the actual charge. Acting on <cite>Simmons</cite>, the Supreme Court in <cite>Salvucci</cite> held that there was no longer any reason to
grant automatic standing as the paradox had been resolved. Indeed, the Court went so far as to say that both a possessory interest <i>and</i> an expectation of privacy in the invaded area were necessary.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup> The same case also indicated that there was no legal contradiction in having prosecutors argue that there was no possessory interest at the suppression hearing and argue the opposite view at trial.<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup>
<p>
In cases citing Fifth and Sixth Amendment violations, there is also a clear reluctance to extend standing to third party defendants, whose rights were not directly violated. Following the <cite>United States v. White</cite>,<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> the Court in <cite>Bellis v. United States</cite><sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup> denied standing to a law partner with respect to the suppression of firm financial records. The defendant, as &quot;an individual cannot rely upon the privilege to avoid producing the
records of a collective entity which are in his possession in a representative capacity, even if these records might incriminate him personally.&quot;<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup> This decision may turn on the facts of the case, given that the defendant's right was not violated directly and the corporation itself (the direct victim) had no rights to protection from self-incrimination as it was not a &quot;natural individual.&quot;<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup> Later cases such as <cite>United States v. Fortna</cite><sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup> and <cite>United States v. Robinson-Munoz</cite>,<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup> however, clearly indicate that even direct violation of a co-defendant's rights cannot be used by a defendant to bar evidence from that defendant's trial.
<p>
The great difficulty with the Court's approach in recent years has been the malleability of the standard of a &quot;legitimate expectation of privacy.&quot;  Expectation of privacy is defined in a way that makes it very hard for defendants to establish such an expectation. For example, there was no expectation of privacy regarding evidence:
<blockquote>
a) Seized from a friend's purse;<sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup><br>
b) Seized from a co-defendant's home;<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup><br>
c) Seized from a car when the defendant was a passenger;<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup><br>
d) Found by a helicopter overview of private property;<sup><a href="#one57">157</a></sup><br>
e) Seized from an acquaintance's apartment;<sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup><br>
f) Seized from garbage;<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup>
</blockquote>
From the picture that emerges, many people might contest the Court's view as to when an expectation of privacy exists. While many might concede that there is no expectation of privacy in garbage left by the street or in a strange apartment (not yours) when the door is left ajar,<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup> most would likely strongly protest that they should not be subject to warrantless aerial fly-overs when they have made their intention to maintain privacy clear by putting up high fences. Nor would they acknowledge that they have given up an expectation of privacy in something placed in a friend's purse (except with respect to that person). 
<p>
Two problems lie at the heart of the Federal Courts' jurisprudence---first, it has defined expectation of privacy in a
debatable manner generally, as noted above, and second, it has not defined the expectation of privacy specifically in relation to agents of the state. There is no reason why one's expectation of privacy with regard to state officers is decreased at all when one keeps something in a friend's apartment or a friend's bag. It is only decreased with respect to the friend or others the person expects to have access to it.<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup> The state should not be in that class of persons. As the discussion of New York and Canada will show, all three jurisdictions have similar problems, as well as conflicts between the rationale for their exclusion rule and the operation of the standing rule, problems which shall be addressed at the end of this section by a new model for standing in such cases.
<p>
NEW YORK
<p>
In most ways, the criteria for standing in New York State are the same as those in the federal jurisdiction, varying little except in terms of the facts of each case when it comes to establishing a legitimate expectation of privacy. <cite>People v. Hansen</cite>,<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup> for example, and <cite>People v. Ponder</cite><sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup> mirror the decisions in <cite> Jones</cite> and <cite>Salvucci</cite> respectively.<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup> In <cite>Ponder</cite>, the state Court declined to broaden the federal rule on standing, following <cite>Katz</cite>, <cite>Mancusim v. DeForte</cite>,<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup> and <cite>Rakas</cite>, to require a legitimate expectation of privacy before standing would be granted. 
<p>
In <cite>People v. Rodriguez</cite>, the Court outlined the nature of the privacy threshold test. &quot;The number of times a person stays in a particular place, the length and nature of the stay, the indicia of connectedness and privacy, like change of clothes or sharing expenses or household burdens, are all factors which may alone or in combination with other factors support a reasonable expectation of privacy which is protected by the Fourth Amendment.&quot;<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup> These factors may be irrelevant, however, to one's expectation of privacy with respect to agents of the state. Practically, the Court has found no expectation of privacy in such cases as:
<blockquote>
a) the search of a car owned and operated by the defendant's girlfriend;<sup><a href="#one67">167</a></sup><br>
b) the search of stolen jeep;<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup><br>
c) the search of someone else's apartment;<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup><br>
d) the search of a relative's schoolbag.<sup><a href="#one70">170</a></sup>
</blockquote>
These cases are all dependent, however, on the factual context, what I shall call a `contextual expectation of privacy.' The Court did find a reasonable expectation of privacy, for example, when contraband was recovered from an apartment in which the defendant was a daily occupant, took naps and meals, admitted people to the apartment, was present during the search, and had a key. Where any Court will draw the line depends on the facts and the
Court's view of one's expectation of privacy, at best conjecture, at worst a fiction.
<p>
Like the Supreme Court, the New York courts have decided<sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup> that deterrence is the primary purpose of the exclusionary rule, but that the deterrence value of giving standing to &quot;third parties&quot; whose legitimate expectations of privacy were not directly violated is insufficient to offset the harm to society. If we examine Canadian law now, it seems that the standing issue is still unsettled, but seems to favour the American view somewhat. 
<p>
CANADA
<p>
The Supreme Court has yet to rule directly on how far standing extends with respect to s. 24(2) petitions, but in <cite>Collins</cite>, Lamer C.J.C. asked the following question with respect to the requirement that the applicant's rights or freedoms had been infringed or denied: 
<blockquote>
There are at least two problems [remaining to be decided by later cases]: must the rights or freedoms infringed or denied under the second prerequisite be those of the applicant, and must the applicant be the accused?  For example if the admission of evidence obtained as the result of the unreasonable search of a third party's home could bring the administration of justice into disrepute, could the accused (if for example his right to a fair hearing was thereby
infringed) or the third party move under s. 24(2) for the exclusion of the evidence?<sup><a href ="#one72">172</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The open-ended nature of the question could imply that the Supreme Court will be bound less by the strict text of s. 24 than by the spirit of the section. At the very least, it leaves open the possibility that admission of illegally obtained evidence would affect the fairness of the trial of a third party (s. 11(d) of the <cite>Charter</cite> or a s. 7 liberty interest), thereby establishing standing. Such a view would be more consistent with the Court's position on fairness of the trial outlined above<sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup> in <cite>Mellenthin</cite> than the present position taken at various courts of appeal.
<p>
Several provincial courts of appeal have understood s. 24(2) to limit standing to &quot;anyone whose rights or freedoms, as guaranteed by this <cite>Charter</cite>, have been infringed or denied,&quot; reading s. 24 as a whole quite literally. If no personal right is infringed directly, one has no standing. Such an approach, however, seems to conflict with the underlying rationale of the exclusionary rule in Canada; apparent condonation of the violation of third party rights is as inconsistent with saving the administration of justice from disrepute as it is with the American rationale of deterrence. 
<p>
To date, the leading cases have come from the courts in Alberta and British Columbia. <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Leaney</cite><sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup> was one of the first cases to deal with a petition to have
evidence obtained from a co-defendant's home excluded under s. 24(2). Like American courts, the Alberta Court of Appeal limited standing to those personally affected by the rights violation. Based on <cite>Hunter v. Southam Inc</cite>.,<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup> the Court held that &quot;the right protected by s. 8 of the Canadian <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> was personal, and that s. 8 protected an individual's `reasonable expectation of privacy.' There is nothing peculiar in the circumstances to suggest that Leaney had a reasonable expectation of privacy with regard to any of the searches.&quot;<sup><a href  = "#one76">176</a></sup> Rawlinson, the co-defendant whose home was searched, did not question the validity of the search and the Court took note of this fact in its decision. 
<p>
The Alberta test, which echoes the American standing rule in many respects, was moderated somewhat in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Montoute</cite>,<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup> a case of conspiracy to traffic in
narcotics in which intercepted private communications between a co-conspirator and a police agent were not authorized by court order. Contrary to the holding in <cite>Leaney</cite>, the majority of the Court stated that even though the defendant's s. 8 rights had not been violated, he was still entitled to have the evidence excluded under
s. 24(2) if to admit the evidence would bring the administration of justice into disrepute; this holding, however, seems contingent on the fact that it was a conspiracy charge, which brings certain unusual hearsay exceptions into play that would normally not be available.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> The dissenting judge did not expressly differ on the question of availability of standing, differing only in his view that no such disrepute had arisen on the facts of this case.
<p>
 In British Columbia, on the other hand, <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Fraser</cite><sup><a href="#one79">179</a></sup> held that the &quot;language of s. 24(1) makes it clear that the applicant for relief must be the person whose rights were infringed.&quot;<sup><a href="#one80">180</a></sup> Section 24(2) was then linked to s. 24(1) because the text
of s. 24(2) refers to ``proceedings under subsection (1).&quot;<sup><a href="one81">181</a></sup> The comments by Lamer C.J.C. in <cite>Collins</cite>, noted above, were interpreted as no more than &quot;a statement that the infringement of the rights of one might also constitute an infringement of the rights of another,&quot;<sup><a href="#one82">182</a></sup> which is a very narrow reading. In <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Clymore</cite>,<sup><a href="#one83">183</a></sup> evidence seized from the defendant's father's car gave no standing to the defendant as there had been no reasonable expectation of privacy on his part. Similarly, in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Arason</cite>,<sup><a href="#one84">184</a></sup> the Court of Appeal refused standing because the premises searched had been leased
to someone other than the accused and that person would have consented to the search. British Columbia, then, has a narrower approach to standing under s.24(2) than Alberta at this time.
<p>
In Ontario, the only other jurisdiction to grapple with the standing question, there is no clear ruling. The leading case of <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Pugliese</cite><sup><a href="#one85">185</a></sup> denied the defendant standing to quash a warrant for a search because he had no proprietary interest in the apartment (though he owned the building) or in the drug-related paraphernalia found. However, the Court expressly distinguished the absence of standing to
quash a warrant (which is like a replacement for the property owner's permission to enter) from the ability to get standing to challenge the admissibility of evidence obtained by the warrant. 
<blockquote>
When an accused, such as the appellant, asserts at his trial that there has been a breach of his s. 8 <cite>Charter</cite> right to be secure from unreasonable search or seizure, he is asserting a particular right to privacy which may, on occasion, be unrelated to any recognized proprietary or possessory right. Section 8 of the
<cite>Charter</cite> is directed to the protection of the security of the person, not the protection of his property, and it is the appellant's personal exposure to the consequences of the search and seizure that gives him the right to challenge, not the search warrant itself, but the admission into evidence at his trial of the fact of the search and the account of what was seized.<sup><a href="#one86">186</a></sup>
</blockquote>
While the comments regarding standing of third parties may be <i>obiter</i> on the facts of the case, they clearly point to a more expansive view of standing than that proposed by courts in Alberta and British Columbia. Unfortunately for defendants, that expansive view has been retracted in the recent case of <cite>R</cite>.
v. <i>Edwards</i><sup><a href="#one87">187</a></sup> in which the majority of the Ontario Court of Appeal held that a
third party had no privacy interest in a girlfriend's apartment, and since no right had been infringed, that person had no standing. A dissent by Abella J.A., however, would have granted standing on the basis that a contextually-defined privacy interest did exist (though not one defined solely by proprietary or possessory circumstances)
because of his association with the apartment in question (key, clothing, overnight stays, etc.). Abella's dissent echoes the New York jurisprudence on the degree of connection to the site, and does not really follow the same principle set out in <i>obiter</i> in <cite>Pugliese</cite>. In any case, it seems that the Supreme Court may
soon make a final ruling on this issue.
<p>
How the Supreme Court will actually fill the gap in standing law remains to be seen, particularly since several of the major cases to date involve consent or probable consent on the part of the person whose rights were directly affected, and therefore possibly no rights violation at all. Jonathon Dawe, in a recent paper addressing the standing dilemma,<sup><a href="#one88">188</a></sup> suggests that the Court would do well to learn from the American &quot;mistakes&quot; and embrace a broader standing rule in which the interpretation of both the right (s.8 in his paper) and of s. 24 itself are undertaken in light of <cite>Charter</cite> values. While Dawe looked only at search and seizure cases, his point that the American example should not be followed in Canada is a valid one. The American rule is based on a deterrence principle, one which is rejected as the primary purpose of s. 24(2) (and as I point out below, a narrow standing rule is equally inconsistent with the American rationale behind the rule). Whereas Dawe uses a largely normative evaluation of standing law (much of with which I agree), the analysis below concentrates in large part on ensuring a rational connection between the purpose of the exclusionary rule and its practice. In particular, Dawe suggests that the purpose behind the Canadian rule should be to protect the integrity of the judicial system as a whole rather than just the integrity of the judiciary. Such a view would incorporate some elements of police regulation while emphasizing the importance of rights protection. In effect, however, the factors of the <cite>Collins</cite> test itself show that the Court <i>has addressed</i> more than mere judicial integrity <i>per se</i>. Using the <cite>Collins</cite> test, the Court has defined judicial integrity in a manner that considers elements of rights protection (the type of right, fairness of the trial generally), police regulation (good faith, seriousness of the violation, other means available, urgency/necessity), crime control/community standards (necessity of evidence, seriousness of crime, etc.) and societal protection (urgency/necessity). Judicial integrity is only preserved if this field of values, which often conflict, is properly balanced and reconciled. Therefore, while the Court's approach to s. 24(2) <i>is</i> balanced on the whole, it need only reconcile this vision of the substantive law of the exclusionary rule with its vision of standing. Keeping this need in mind, contradictions in standing law are presented below, followed by a new model that may solve some of those problems.
<p>
TOWARDS A NEW MODEL OF STANDING LAW
<p>
Standing rules in the United States, which limit standing to people directly aggrieved, are inconsistent with both the
deterrence and the `judicial integrity' rationales for exclusion. It would be consistent to some extent with the personal constitutional remedy theory of exclusion, but that doctrine is the one soundly rejected by the Supreme Court in <cite>Leon</cite> and <cite>Calandra</cite>. In Canada as well, where the primary rationale is to avoid bringing the administration of justice into disrepute by a balance of relevant factors, a standing rule which admits evidence unless obtained in direct violation of the defendant's rights would also be inconsistent with the <cite>Charter</cite>.
<p>
In both the U.S. `deterrence v. cost' balance and the Canadian s. 24(2) balance, the only way to justify such a narrow
standing rule (which excludes third parties to the violation) is if the proportionality of factors is such that: a) in the United States, the loss of extra deterrence value is more than offset by the prevention of greater costs to society and b) in Canada, significantly less disrepute arises from using the fruit of a third party violation than the fruit of a direct violation of someone's rights. Both arguments are hard to justify. The more people encompassed by the exclusionary rule, the greater the deterrence. Similarly, it seems odd that disrepute in using tainted evidence
depends on who suffers the violation. Judicial condonation of  <i>any</i> violation seems inconsistent with the Court's interpretation of s. 24(2). It would be odd to say that a minor infraction against a defendant's rights might lead to exclusion of probative evidence, but that a flagrant and abusive violation of a third party's rights would not, due to the standing threshold. Indeed, violation of an innocent person's rights to get at a guilty party seems even more reprehensible than violation of a guilty party's rights directly.
<p>
In Canada, a categorical standing rule is even harder to justify because the only way to <i>know</i> if the administration of justice is brought into disrepute is to <i>do</i> a s. 24(2) balance. The present standing law prevents one from ever getting to that stage. 
<p>
Arguments in Canada against extending the standing rule depend on the text of s. 24(2). There are two possible
interpretations of that section. If the text in s. 24 is strictly adhered to, as in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Fraser</cite>, one may first have to cross the threshold of proving that one's rights have been violated, regardless of the amount of disrepute that may result from admission of the evidence. A second interpretation, more in keeping with the spirit of the <cite>Charter</cite> as a whole, is that s. 24(2) provides that whenever an application is brought for a remedy under s. 24, once the &quot;court concludes that evidence was obtained in a manner that infringed or denied <i>any</i> rights or freedoms guaranteed by this <cite>Charter</cite>,&quot;<sup><a href="#one89">189</a></sup> the threshold for standing is not whether one's rights were directly violated (as set out in s. 24(1)) but whether the
administration of justice would be brought into disrepute by admission of the evidence. Section 24(2) should be seen as going beyond s. 24(1) to provide its own remedy threshold when a case of illegally-obtained evidence is in question. Such a view would provide internal consistency in the law by bringing the law of standing into line with the substantive law of s. 24(2), a result that seems more appropriate than the narrow reading in <cite>Fraser</cite>.
<p>
In the United States, there must be a violation of the defendant's rights to establish standing. In Canada, one can
establish standing in the same way, or possibly by showing that the administration of justice has been brought into disrepute by violation of a third party's rights or freedoms.<sup><a href="#one90">190</a></sup> There are two main ways to establish standing on the first basis (that a right of the accused has been violated under search and seizure provisions): 1) by showing that the defendant had a reasonable expectation of privacy; and/or 2) by showing that the right to a fair trial will be affected.<sup><a href="#one91">191</a></sup>
<p>
The latter possibility was discussed not only in the Canadian context but in the United States as well. <cite>U.S. v. Merkt</cite><sup><a href="#one92">192</a></sup> held that a &quot;defendant may assert her own Fifth Amendment right to a fair trial as a valid objection to the introduction of statements extracted from a non-defendant by coercion or other inquisitional tactics.&quot;<sup><a href="#one93">193</a></sup> The threshold for unfairness is a high one, however, as the defendant must establish that the &quot;government's investigation  methods resulted in a fundamentally unfair trial,&quot;<sup><a href="#one94">194</a></sup> a burden that was not met in
<cite>Merkt</cite>. In that case, access to counsel was barred by police while third parties were questioned, the resulting statements being the impugned evidence. Because their testimony in person at the defendant's trial was similar to their statements (with inconsistencies, however), there was held to be no fundamental unfairness to Merkt. 
<p>
Since <cite>Merkt</cite>, no signs of life in this reasoning have been seen in the United States, nor, however has it been expressly rejected. Its role in Canada remains uncertain, although the Court in <cite>Fraser</cite> also suggested in <i>obiter</i> that a judge could &quot;exclude evidence of a witness who at the time of testifying was
under threat, drugged or had recently been beaten. Such conduct would be a breach of the accused's right to a fair
trial.&quot;<sup><a href="#one95">195</a></sup> More recently, the Ontario Court of Appeal, in the case of <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Paolitto</cite>,<sup><a href="#one96">196</a></sup> has held that the accused's right to a fair trial is not infringed by admission of evidence when standing is refused to a third party. If the ruling in  <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, however, is interpreted to mean that &quot;evidence which would not have been discovered but for a <cite>Charter</cite> violation affects the fairness of the trial&quot; in the context of a s. 24(2) consideration of the merits of the case, it would be very difficult to say that such evidence affects the fairness of the trial any less, simply because the right violated was that of someone other than the defendant. If this view is valid, then fairness of the trial (a right of the defendant) is affected even if the defendant was not technically affected by the initial violation; violation of the right to a fair trial then gives the defendant standing even under a strict interpretation of s. 24(1). To hold otherwise would be to risk a grave and inexplicable contradiction between the substantive definition of what &quot;affects fairness of the trial&quot; in terms of a s. 24(2) analysis of the merits as compared to a standing analysis. In any case, a new model of standing is needed to resolve the confusion in all three jurisdictions.
<p>
<i>A New Model of Standing</i>
<br>
In cases of search and seizure of goods from a third party, there are two main factors affecting the legitimate expectation of privacy. The first is whether one has a possessory/proprietary interest in the object seized or in the place invaded. The second is whether or not the third party subjected to the search consented to it. One must ask not only &quot;is there an expectation of privacy?,&quot; but &quot;with respect to whom?&quot;  One may have a low expectation of privacy with respect to a friend to whom one has given something or in whose apartment one has left something. Likewise one may have a low expectation of privacy regarding regular foreseeable visitors to
that apartment, or regarding the friend's friends, depending on the circumstances (which can be defined in court). One is unlikely to have much lower an expectation of privacy with respect to the police however, than if the object was in one's own bag or apartment. In <cite>Rawlings</cite>, for example, the very fact that Rawlings placed the
object in the purse could be evidence that he was seeking a higher expectation of privacy than by leaving it in the open. Other factors such as visibility of the evidence to the public (for example, plain view in an automobile), and warnings or special instructions to the third party, will also affect the level of expectation of privacy if defined in this way.
<p>
The issue of consent of the third party in allowing the search is a difficult one. On the one hand, it may render the search entirely reasonable; at the very least it indicates police were operating in good faith, unless there is evidence police knew the sought-after material did not belong to the third party (for example searching a car in which the real target is a passenger). On the other hand, should a third party be allowed to consent when he/she has taken on an obligation?  Certainly, it seems that third party consent, in general, will render the search reasonable.  
<p>
As long as the search subject's choice is an informed and non-coerced one, the only quarrel of the defendant should be with the third party's frame of mind and not with police conduct. An informed choice implies at a minimum that the standard in <cite>Florida v. Bostick</cite><sup><a href="#one97">197</a></sup> is met---that subjects are told they can refuse a search. To be fair, subjects should also be given <cite>Miranda</cite> rights or at least advised of the right to counsel in such situations, although this goes further than the American jurisprudence. In Canada, given the wide definition of detention,<sup><a href="#one98">198</a></sup> the courts should require a
strict standard for informed consent to searches.
<p>
Nevertheless, even with consent, the defendant could still have a legitimate expectation of privacy in the evidence, but there will have been no unreasonable search. There may however have been an unreasonable <i>seizure</i>. Can the police seize items that do not belong to the subject of the search? Should they be under a duty to ask whether items belong to people searched, and, if they belong to someone else, should the police be allowed to seize the evidence in any case?  If they do seize items in such a case, the defendant's rights may still be <i>directly</i> violated as an unreasonable seizure (though not an unreasonable search), as long as the Court finds that the defendant still had a legitimate expectation of privacy <i>regarding the police</i>. This last fact depends on the
context, as discussed above.
<p>
To simplify the application of standing rules, I shall consider several general circumstances as defined by the two main factors set out above.
<ol>
<li><i>Defendant has a possessory/proprietary interest in the evidence or in the place searched.</i><br>
<dl>
<dt>a) Third party consents:
<dd>i) if informed consent was given, the search is presumptively reasonable, although the Court may still hold that the seizure was not. Standing depends on the Court's view of the latter point.
<dd>ii) if no informed consent was given, the search was presumptively unreasonable; the defendant retained a legitimate expectation of privacy with respect to the police, concerning both the search and the seizure (unless other factors as discussed above indicate there was no subjective expectation of privacy). If there was a legitimate expectation of privacy, standing should be granted to the defendant.
<dt>b)  Third party does not consent:
<dd>i) the same result as in 1(a)(ii) above. Standing should be granted.
</dl>
<li><i>The defendant has <b>no</b> possessory/proprietary interest in the evidence or the location of the search (or the violation is of another person's right to counsel, etc.)</i><br>
The defendant has no expectation of privacy personally, therefore the standing rule depends on one's rationale for the exclusionary rule. The two rules should follow consistent parallel lines.
<dl>
<dt>a) Third party consents:
<dd>i) if it is an informed choice, there is no violation and therefore no standing under any rationale;
<dd>ii) if it is not an informed choice, it is presumptively as if there had been a violation, with results similar to those under 2(b) below.
<dt>b)  Third party does not consent:
<dd>i) If the purpose of the rule is <i>to promote deterrence</i>, standing should be granted as there has been a violation of &quot;general rights,&quot; and exclusion from related actions as well as actions involving the actual subject, would provide a much greater deterrence effect. To refuse standing would be tantamount to giving the police a licence to go fishing for evidence by random stops of automobiles and other searches in the knowledge that evidence can be used against those not directly affected. Ironically, such an incentive would increase the incidence of searches against <i>innocent</i> friends and associates of suspects, resulting in the very intrusion that the
Fourth Amendment and s.8 of the <cite>Charter</cite> were designed to curtail. Particularly in a society in which random stops seem to have a deeply disturbing disproportionate effect on racial minorities, such a licence to search should not be permitted.
<dd>ii) If the purpose of the rule is to <i>avoid bringing into disrepute judicial integrity or the administration of justice</i>, standing should be granted. A violation by the state of someone's rights has occurred, and to refuse standing and admit the evidence would be to condone the violation by acquiescence, regardless of its severity. The Court should balance the factors discussed with regard to s. 24(2) and reach the same result on standing as on the
substantive question as to whether there would be disrepute. Evidence is not less tainted if obtained in violation of another's rights. Indeed, if the defendant was the sole target of the search (as discussed above), then obtaining evidence by deliberately violating an innocent party's rights should bring an even greater taint to the evidence. 
<dd>iii) If the right to a remedy is related to <i>a personal right</i> to be safe from rights violations, one is not necessarily precluded from using the rationales in 2(b)(i) and (ii) to grant standing. In addition, standing can be granted on the basis that one's right to a fair trial has been violated. One could use either the strict test outlined above in <cite>Merkt</cite> and <cite>Fraser</cite>, or a more lenient test such as that used in s. 24(2) generally. In Canada, the latter would be more consistent with s. 24(2) jurisprudence. To determine if the right to a fair trial has been violated under that test, a useful guide is the &quot;but for&quot; test:<sup><a href="#one99">199</a></sup> if the evidence would not have been obtained <i>but for</i> the violation of the third party's rights, it probably renders
the defendant's trial unfair.
</dl>
</ol>
Whatever the rationale chosen, it would seem that standing rules in all three jurisdictions should be opened to potentially include people not directly affected by such searches.
<p>
<h3>V: Alternatives to an Exclusionary Rule</h3>

Judges and commentators alike have explored numerous alternatives to the exclusion of evidence in an attempt to uphold the rights of individuals without imposing the cost on society of excluding clearly probative evidence. Among these suggestions are civil damages aimed at police, reduction in sentences, and contempt citations for rights violators. None of these solutions, however, have been able to avoid the inevitable tradeoff---preventing societal costs in the courtroom means incurring societal costs to the underlying constitutional rights. Letting criminals go is the &quot;`price' our society pays for enjoying the freedom and privacy&quot; that was constitutionally guaranteed.<sup><a href="#twohundred">200</a></sup> As Brennan J. said while dissenting in <cite>U.S. v. Leon</cite>, &quot;it is not the exclusionary rule, but the Amendment itself that has imposed this cost.&quot;<sup><a href="#two01">201</a></sup>
<p>
One question that has often been asked in U.S. jurisdictions is whether the exclusionary rule imposes any
significant cost on society in terms of lost convictions, or has any deterrence effect on police conduct at all. Numerous studies have indicated that there may be relatively low loss of convictions related to the exclusionary rule,<sup><a href="#two02">202</a></sup> but on the whole, the studies seem inconclusive.<sup><a href="#two03">203</a></sup>
Similarly, some studies show a small deterrence effect related to exclusion<sup><a href="#two04">204</a></sup> but
others suggest there is no effect at all.<sup><a href="#two05">205</a></sup> All of these studies are subject to the problems inherent in using statistics to describe trends that could be related to any number of complex social and legal changes, and the results are inconclusive or ambiguous for the most part.<sup><a href="#two06">206</a></sup> Are rising crime rates related to the exclusionary rule, increased violence in the media, increasing unemployment, or more likely to some combination of inter-related factors?  No single statistical study will decide this issue.
<p>
Deterrence of police misconduct can occur both at the level of officer education and briefing, and at the level of police practice in the field. Developments in the law will no doubt be communicated to officers, but changes must also be studied at the ground level. Judicial requirement of warrants has not greatly decreased the number of warrantless searches being conducted, for example.<sup><a href="#two07">207</a></sup> There may be no deterrent effect at all if officers are not in some way affected by failure to comply with the exclusionary rule. Police in some forces
may see their role as mainly to &quot;bring people in,&quot; and blame any problems with the exclusionary rule on the prosecutor's office, as &quot;more administrative red tape.&quot;
<p>
Unless police see themselves as responsible for the lost conviction and feel the hurt, there is little deterrent value in
excluding evidence. Such connection between the rule and police conduct could come through supervision of conduct, and reports on failure to comply with the Constitution.<sup><a href="#two08">208</a></sup> Officers with poor records of upholding constitutional rights in the course of their work should perhaps be subjected to work penalties. Other commentators have suggested more direct penalties, including civil damages.<sup><a href="#two09">209</a></sup>
<p>
CIVIL DAMAGES
<p>
Civil damages as an alternative to the exclusionary rule suffer from several major weaknesses. First, they are reactive, coming into play after the damage to one's rights or freedoms has already been done. More importantly, they come after the damning evidence has been discovered. Once brought to light, the probative value of such evidence carries immense public sympathy and is difficult to override. Second, in light of the probative evidence
found, the public is most likely going to favour the police, who were `just doing their job' in an effort to protect the public. Little juror sympathy is likely for plaintiffs whose guilt seems visible from the evidence discovered. For this reason, even if damages were awarded they would likely be low. Even a trial by judge alone might have similar results.<sup><a href="#two10">210</a></sup>
<p>
REDUCED SENTENCES
<p>
This option, pursued in several Saskatchewan cases,<sup><a href="#two11">211</a></sup> adopts an interesting compromise position. It involves a form of personal remedy, but not exclusion. The cost to society is less than if evidence were excluded, but higher than if sentence were not reduced. It has a much lower deterrence effect,
given that police will still obtain convictions as a result of their actions. In addition, since discretion in sentencing is available to judges in any case, it may be that judges would simply play a numbers game to end up with sentences similar to those the defendant would normally have obtained anyway (start high and then `reduce' to a
normal level).
<p>
In compromising between the various positions, one may lose most of the deterrent effect, retain most of the taint on `judicial integrity,' and abandon the principled basis for the exclusionary rule. Such a solution could only be upheld on principle if the right to a constitutional remedy is a personal one, as suggested by Brennan J. in <cite>U.S. v. Leon</cite>.<sup><a href="#two12">212</a></sup> Whether s. 24(2) guarantees a personal remedy of this sort
is uncertain. One could argue, however, that mitigating on sentence alleviates any taint that would arise from admitting the evidence.
<p>
CONTEMPT
<p>
The benefit of a contempt sanction is that &quot;the courts could directly and efficiently punish the misconduct while at the same time permitting reliable evidence to be used at trial.&quot;<sup><a href="#two13">213</a></sup> This proposal has been supported by many commentators, including Dean Wigmore,<sup><a href="#two14">214</a></sup> as one responsive to the public's interest, both in terms of preventing rights violations and preventing criminals from going free. Difficulties with criminal contempt proceedings include the high burden of proof and the possible reluctance of juries or judges to impose stiff sentences on police officers.<sup><a href="#two15">215</a></sup> Kinasz dismisses standard civil contempt as an impractical remedy, despite its lower burden of proof, because of the indeterminate nature of the penalty, the strain on judicial resources and the questionable deterrent value.<sup><a href="#two16">216</a></sup> Instead, Kinasz proposes a variant of criminal contempt based on a judicial order specifying police duties under the Fourth Amendment.
<p>
Such a judicial order, however, would be most difficult to frame, given the great debate that still surrounds the Fourth Amendment in the United States and the evolution of s. 24(2) in Canada. Most police duties are evaluated <i>ex post</i> on a case by case basis, and attempts to regulate police conduct in advance might fail badly. Alternatively, if the Court sets too flexible a net, it might result in no police misconduct being caught at all.
<p>
Although contempt may deter police conduct, it will not eliminate any disrepute resulting from the admission of evidence into the proceedings. Contempt <i>would</i> provide a form of personal remedy, however, since the particular wrong-doers would be punished directly rather than through indirect deterrence. Such a personal
remedy would be available both to innocent victims of rights violations and culpable ones, unlike the exclusionary remedy which only comes into play with those who are taken to trial. Under the present system, innocent victims have no recourse other than a civil suit, with its many disadvantages and financial costs. As a result, collateral damage to innocent citizens may go unaddressed, limiting deterrence effects considerably.
<p>
IMPLICATIONS
<p>
No matter which of the above remedies is chosen, there will be some costs to society or to the rights of individuals within society. If the justice system admits tainted evidence, it condones the violation. Contempt and damages punish police directly, but they also punish society indirectly in the same way that the exclusionary rule does. If police <i>are deterred</i>, they will not conduct searches in situations that they would have before; as a result,
probative evidence will not be uncovered, and the parties involved will never go to trial, if they are arrested at all.<sup><a href="#two17">217</a></sup> The exclusionary rule, in attempting to return the parties to a world in which <cite>Charter</cite> rights are respected by police, just does in retrospect what deterrence would do in advance. In either situation, convictions will be lost, because as Brennan J. stated, it is the price we pay for the right, not for
the rule.<sup><a href="#two18">218</a></sup>
<p>
The most effective method would likely be a combination of an exclusionary rule with internal police disciplinary regulation related to the treatment of constitutional rights and freedoms. Penal sanctions may be going too far when police in most cases do believe that they are acting in the best interest of society. A more reasonable sanction that retains deterrent force is work sanctions. Relating work sanctions (demotion, re-assignment, suspension, etc.) to
performance of duty, in an atmosphere where constitutional duties are <i>effectively</i> communicated to police forces by an educational officer, would prevent many incidents without putting undue pressure on police forces. It would also capture violations affecting innocent parties rather than just ones who go to trial. The exclusionary rule would serve both as the final screen to protect constitutional rights and as a measure of police performance with regard to those rights.
<p>
<h3>VI: Recommendations and Conclusions</h3>
Although the three jurisdictions differ in terms of their primary justification for the exclusionary rule, four justifications run as undercurrents in each jurisdiction: deterrence of police misconduct, maintenance of judicial integrity, maintenance of the integrity of the justice system as a whole, and the sense that where there is a constitutional right, there should be a remedy. In the United States and New York, deterrence is the primary justification, although New York has strengthened the rule relative to the federal jurisdiction, making it harder to justify exceptions. Elements of a personal right, as advocated by Brennan J. in <cite>Leon</cite>, creep
subtly into the New York decisions but deterrence remains the primary principle, despite its weak constitutional foundation. In Canada, preventing &quot;the administration of justice&quot; from falling into disrepute is the primary principle, one grounded firmly in the text of the Constitution.<sup><a href="#two19">219</a></sup> The right could still be classed as a personal one, however, in that s. 24(2) comes into play after the violation of an individual's rights, and if evidence stemming from that violation would bring the administration of justice into disrepute (discretion of Court), it &quot;shall be excluded&quot; (no discretion).
<p>
All three jurisdictions employ a form of proportionality test in deciding whether or not to exclude evidence, although the tests differ somewhat. In the American jurisdictions, the balance pits deterrence value (which arguably leads to protection of societal rights) against the cost to society of excluding probative evidence. New York, on the basis of its State Constitution, is more reluctant to diminish the deterrence force of the rule by creating more exceptions, but neither jurisdiction explains the balance in great detail.<sup><a href="#two20">220</a></sup> Canadian
courts, on the other hand, expressly balance all or most of the <cite>Collins</cite> criteria in making their decisions, although fairness of the trial seems to be becoming a dominant factor, leading to categorical exclusion if infringed in some contexts.
<p>
Balancing of criteria should be encouraged in Canada, where the Constitution expressly recognizes that rights are not absolute; balancing leads to more flexible laws than absolute rules or exceptions, as the latter can become rigid and arbitrary, unresponsive to contextual differences and the underlying purpose of the constitutional rights. The dangers of judge-made law should be curtailed, however, by clear expressions of principle and overt balancing with an emphasis on coherent reasoning. American courts, working with a more absolute view of rights, may not be able to justify flexible balancing, but should nonetheless be more explicit when balancing is done. No matter what the text of the constitution in question, judges always retain a range of discretion in interpretation, discretion which should be used wisely and scrutinized carefully. Ambiguities should be resolved as much as possible. For example, the definition of what affects fairness of the trial in Canada is left somewhat muddied by the decision in <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, and should be clarified. Distinctions based on the type of evidence discovered should be replaced by concerns with the manner in which evidence was obtained: any evidence which could not have been obtained but for the violation of someone's (not necessarily the accused's) <cite>Charter</cite> rights, should be presumed to affect the fairness of the trial.
<p>
Of all the principles behind the American exclusionary rule, the least compelling theoretically, as well as practically, is the deterrence rationale. The constitutional background for such a rationale is weak at best, whereas there are strong arguments supporting the personal constitutional remedy theory embraced by some members of the Court in <cite>Mapp v. Ohio</cite>.<sup><a href="#two21">221</a></sup> Judicial integrity, as espoused by Brandeis J.<sup><a href="#two22">222</a></sup> and Holmes J.,<sup><a href="#two23">223</a></sup> is less clearly related to the text of the U.S. Constitution but is certainly in line with its spirit. Whatever rationale or rationales are chosen, the application to exclusion law should be internally consistent.
<p>
Standing, therefore, should generally be extended to allow one to contest evidence obtained in violation of constitutional rights, even if the rights violated were those of third parties. A new model of standing, as set out <i>infra</i>, should be developed, emphasizing consistency between a) the substance and purpose of the exclusionary rule; and b) the standing threshold.
<p>
To strengthen the exclusionary rule and dampen criticism of its lack of deterrent effect, the failure to comply with the Constitution should be brought directly home to police forces. Rather than criminal or civil sanctions, however, a mandate should be emplaced to create constitutional education in police forces and tie workplace penalties to failure to comply. Convictions will still be lost, by deterrence of certain searches, but the cost is more than
offset by the greater freedom from unwarranted state interference with constitutional rights.
<p>
Each jurisdiction's exclusionary rule is driven primarily by its underlying constitutional rationale. Insofar as these differ, there may be limits on how much similarity there can and should be in the rule from jurisdiction to jurisdiction. Nevertheless, the concerns which arise in one are inevitably felt as currents in the other, though perhaps of different strength. In the end, it seems that the American federal rule is the least exclusionary, the hardest on defendants. Canada, with its balancing, may be more or less exclusionary than New York, although the rejection of a `good faith exception' by New York and the strong weight given to `good faith' by Canadian courts suggest that New York may provide the most protection for its constitutional rights. Of course, only a broad empirical study would resolve this last issue with any certainty. This study can make no hard claims about the relative strengths of the rule in each jurisdiction, because the very nature of the discretionary balancing makes the relation between theory in the cases and practice in the courts difficult to ascertain.
<p>
<hr>
<center><h2>Endnotes</h2></center>
<a name="note">* The author</a> is indebted to Kent Roach for advice and guidance, to Marty Friedland for instilling in me a love of all things criminal, to Phaedra Livingstone for help beyond description, and to numerous reviewers whose comments have greatly improved this paper.
<p>
<ol>
<li><a name="one">The high water</a> mark of categorical exclusion was reached in such cases as <cite>Olmstead v. United States</cite>, 277 U.S. 438 (1928) [hereinafter <cite>Olmstead</cite>], and <cite>Mapp v. Ohio</cite>, 367 U.S. 643 (1961) [hereinafter <cite>Mapp</cite>] with intermittent and subsequent departures from such a broad rule in such cases as <cite>Wolf v. Colorado</cite>, 338 U.S. 25 (1949) [hereinafter <cite>Wolf</cite>], and <cite>United States v. Leon</cite>, 104 S.Ct. 3405 (1984) [hereinafter <cite>Leon</cite>]. In this paper, I shall concentrate mainly, but not exclusively, on the rule's application to the Fourth Amendment.
<p>
<li><a name="two">The set of</a> criteria involved in the balance are outlined initially in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Collins</cite>, [1987] 1 S.C.R. 265, 33 C.C.C. (3d) 1, 56 C.R. (3d) 193 [hereinafter <cite>Collins</cite> cited to S.C.R.]. Later decisions have built on <cite>Collins</cite> with little departure.
<p>
<li><a name="three">Advocates for eliminating the exclusionary</a> rule include not only academic writers but governments as well, in particular, the Reagan-Bush Justice Department (Office of Legal Policy, U.S. Dept. of Justice, Truth in Criminal Justice Series, Report No. 5, The Judiciary's Use of Supervisory Power to Control Federal Law Enforcement Activity (1986), reprinted in (1989) 22 U. Mich. J.L. Reform 773).
<p>
<li><a name="four">Canadian law, up until the</a> <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>, was extremely permissive, admitting real evidence and even corroborated parts of confessions that were obtained by flagrant violations of rights: <cite>Queen v. Wray</cite>, [1971] S.C.R. 272. In the United States, such evidence would have been deemed the &quot;fruit of the poisonous tree&quot; (i.e. the fruit of the violation of the right) and excluded, even as early as 1920: <cite>Silverthorne Lumber Co</cite>. v. <cite>United States</cite>, 251 U.S. 385 (1920) [hereinafter <cite>Silverthorne</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="five">Beginning as far back</a> as <cite>Boyd v. United States</cite>, 116 U.S. 616 (1886) (a civil case), the exclusionary rule came into prominence in <cite>Weeks v. United States</cite> 232 U.S. 383 (1914). The constitutional foundation of the rule was put in doubt in <cite>Wolf</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 28, 33, but the Court's power to exclude was revived under its supervisory power in <cite>Elkins v. United States</cite>, 364 U.S. 206 (1960) [hereinafter <cite>Elkins</cite>]. With the decision in <cite>Mapp</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 1, the Court outlined a new constitutional basis for its powers, one now threatened.<p>
 Since <cite>Elkins</cite>, the supervisory power (developed in <cite>McNabb v. United States</cite>, 318 U.S. 332 (1943)) as a basis for extending the exclusionary rule to states has been considered and rejected; see B. Wilson, &quot;The Origin and Development of the Federal Rule of Exclusion&quot; (1982) 18 Wake Forest L. Rev. 1073. See also Sara Beale, &quot;Reconsidering Supervisory Power in Criminal Cases: Constitutional and Statutory Limits on the Authority of the Federal Courts&quot; (1984) 84 Colum. L. Rev. 1433.
<p>
<li><a name="six"><i>Supra</i></a> note 1.
<p>
<li><a name="seven"><cite>Mapp</cite>, <i>supra</i></a> note 1 at 648, Clark J.
<p>
<li><a name="eight">See e.g. L. Crocker,</a> &quot;Can the Exclusionary Rule be Saved?&quot; (1993) 84 J. Crim. L. and Criminology 310 at 314. This idea has also been called the &quot;extended violation&quot; argument.
<p>
<li><a name="nine"><cite>Mapp</cite>, <i>supra</i></a> note 1 at 660.
<p>
<li><a name="ten">Two justices (Stewart and Harlan)</a> dissented and would have followed <cite>Wolf</cite>, whereas Black J. concurred but for a different reason, meaning that there were not five Justices supporting the majority reasoning on this issue. Black J. relied on a combination of the Fourth and the Fifth Amendments, indicating that a violation of the Fourth Amendment alone was not enough to give the Court exclusionary power. <cite>Mapp</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 661--662.
<p>
<li><a name="eleven"><cite>United States</cite></a> v. <cite>Calandra</cite>, 414 U.S. 338 at 348 (1974)  [emphasis added] [hereinafter <cite>Calandra</cite>]. This proposition was affirmed in <cite>Leon</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 3411--3412.
