<li><a name="twelve">K.A. Fabi,</a> &quot;The Exclusionary Rule: Not the `Expressed Juice of the Woolly-Headed Thistle'&quot; (1986) 35 Buff. L. Rev. 937 at 939. See also Crocker, <i>supra</i> note 8; Crocker suggests that there is still an implicit &quot;essential sanction&quot; in the Fourth Amendment which can save the rule. See also J. Kaplan, &quot;The Limits of the Exclusionary Rule&quot; (1974) 26 Stan. L. Rev. 1027; Y. Kamisar, &quot;Does (Did)(Should) the Exclusionary Rule Rest on a `Principled Basis' Rather than an `Empirical
Proposition'?&quot; (1983) 16 Creighton L. Rev. 565.
<p>
<li><a name="thirteen">Note:</a> &quot;Developments in the Law---The Interpretation of State Constitutional Rights&quot; (1982) 95 Harv. L. Rev. 1324.
<p>
<li><a name="fourteen">See Fabi,</a> <i>supra</i> note 12.
<p>
<li><a name="fifteen">In the case of</a> <cite>People v. Loria</cite>, 179 N.E.2d 478 at 480 (N.Y. 1961), the Court followed the recent binding decision of <cite>Mapp</cite>, noting that it would have followed pre-existing jurisprudence otherwise. Those earlier cases, beginning with <cite>People v. Adams</cite>, 192 U.S. 585 (1904) and <cite>People v. Defore</cite>, 242 N.Y. 13, <i>cert. denied</i> 46 S.Ct. 353 (1926) [hereinafter <cite>Defore</cite>], held that the manner in which evidence was obtained was not relevant to its admissibility. Justice Cardozo rejected a rule that would mean &quot;[t]he criminal is to go free because the constable has blundered,&quot; because it would give a lowly constable the capacity to
give &quot;immunity&quot; to the most savage criminal (<cite>Defore</cite>, <i>supra</i> at 21--24). In fact, <cite>People v. Richter's Jeweler's</cite>, 51 N.E.2d 690 (N.Y. 1943) expressly states that the state
constitution did not change the law as it was before its adoption, a finding that was effectively overruled by <cite>People v. Johnson</cite>, 497 N.Y.S.2d 618 (1985). After <cite>Loria</cite>, <cite>Sackler v. Sackler</cite>, 203 N.E.2d 481 (N.Y. 1964) limited <cite>Mapp</cite> to cases involving state actions against individuals.<p>
The more recent trend towards harsh treatment of police misconduct, intentional or otherwise, began in <cite>People v. Elwell</cite> 428 N.Y.S.2d 655 at 658 (1980) (amendment to protect &quot;innocent and guilty alike&quot;) and continued in <cite>People v. Belton</cite>, 447 N.Y.S.2d 873 (1982) (limiting the automobile search exception) and <cite>People v. Gokey</cite>, 469 N.Y.S.2d 618 (1983) (limiting circumstances of search incident to arrest).
<p>
<li><a name="sixteen">449 N.Y.S.2d 701 at 704 (1982).</a>
<p>
