<li><a name ="fifty"><cite>Wong Sun</cite>, <i>supra</i></a> note 33 at 488. In this case, a statement obtained from one accused closely following an illegal entry was held not to be &quot;sufficiently an act of free will to purge the primary taint of the unlawful invasion&quot; (<i>ibid.</i> at 486), whereas a statement made by Wong Sun, who came back to the police voluntarily <i>several days after</i> an unlawful arrest, was ruled admissible. <i>Ibid.</i> at 491. Note that <i>some</i> causal connection still existed in the latter case as it is unlikely the evidence would have been obtained without the violation, because the police had insufficient reason to suspect him of any crime.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty1"><cite>Brown</cite></a> v. <cite>Illinois</cite>, 422 U.S. 590 at 603--604 (1975) [hereinafter <cite>Brown</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="fifty2"><i>Ibid.</i></a> at 603. In this case, proximity between arrest and confession was two hours, too close to be unconnected. A second statement was ruled to be the &quot;fruit&quot; of the first and also inadmissible. <i>Ibid</i>. at 604--605.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty3"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 603--604. For example, reading <cite>Miranda</cite> rights may but need not necessarily be such a factor (it was not in this case). See <cite>United States v. Daniel</cite>, 932 F.2d 517 at 521 (6th Cir. 1991) (second confession admitted due to move to second location, giving of <cite>Miranda</cite> warning, and change in interrogating officer).
<p>
<li><a name="fifty4"><cite>Brown</cite>,</a> <i>ibid</i>. at 604. In <cite>Brown</cite>, it was a &quot;purposive illegality&quot;, a fishing expedition. The courts treat this criteria with a fair degree of strictness; <cite>United States v. Recalde</cite>, 761 F.2d 1448 (10th Cir. 1985) as compared to <cite>United
States v. Sheppard,</cite> 901 F.2d 1230 (5th Cir. 1990).
