<li><a name="eighty8">In <cite>People</cite></a>  v. <cite>Kane</cite>, 573 N.Y.S.2d 729 (N.Y. App. Div. 1991), the Court applied the three-part test of <cite>People v. Mitchell</cite>, 383 N.Y.S.2d 246 (1976) and refused to suppress evidence gathered when police searched an apartment after explosives had been found and linked to the accused's apartment. The search of the apartment was &quot;completely justified as
an emergency.&quot;  <cite>Kane</cite>, <i>supra</i> at 730.
