<p>
<li><a name="ninety1"><i>Ibid</i>.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety2">Note,</a> however, that interference with the &quot;fairness of the trial&quot; appears to be sufficient reason to grant exclusion now, regardless of the balance of other factors. <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Mellenthin</cite> (1992) 76 C.C.C. (3d) 481 at 491 (S.C.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Mellenthin</cite>]. The <cite>Collins</cite> list is not closed.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety3"><cite>Collins</cite>, <i>supra</i></a> note 2 at 280 (from the phrase &quot;if it is established that&quot; in s. 24, <i>supra</i> note 25).
<p>
<li><a name="ninety4"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 281--282. Public opinion polls are rejected as a guide.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety5"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 284.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety6"><cite>Mellenthin</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 92 at 491, Cory J.: &quot;It is clear that the admission of the evidence would render the trial unfair and there is no need to consider the other factors referred to in <cite>Collins</cite> ... [t]hat is really a sufficient basis for dealing with the issue.&quot;  However, Cory J. did go on to consider the seriousness of the violation, and the holding may be limited to the facts of the case (i.e. a random stop---illegal questioning and search with neither consent nor probable grounds). The holding may actually be an attempt to limit the Supreme Court's decision in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Ladouceur,<cite> (1990), 56 C.C.C. 3d) 22 (S.C.C.), another random stop case which upheld random stops as constitutional, even if not part of a R.I.D.E. program. The dissent in <cite>Ladouceur</cite> worried specifically that permitting such stops would lead directly to the type of abuse which occurred in <cite>Mellenthin</cite>. Given that prior to <cite>Mellenthin</cite>, real evidence such as narcotics tended to be admitted in most cases, some means of constraining </cite>Ladouceur</cite> was needed. Only a clear decision excluding real evidence would
deter police abuse of random stops, and deterrence is certainly necessary given the evidence that random stops may often affect minority groups in a disproportionate way. See also <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Dersch</cite> (1994), 85 C.C.C. (3d) 1 (S.C.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Dersch</cite>], and <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Acciavatti</cite> (1993), 80 C.C.C. (3d) 109 (Ont. C.A.) which follow <cite>Mellenthin</cite>.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety7"><cite>Collins</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 2 at 284--285.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety8"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at 284.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety9">(1986),</a> 45 C.C.C. (3d) 385 at 403 (S.C.C.)
<p>
<li><a name="hundred"><cite>Dersch</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 96 at 4. <cite>Thomson Newspapers Ltd. v. Canada</cite> (1990), 54 C.C.C. (3d) 417 at 511--514 (S.C.C.). See also the discussion of <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Meddoui</cite> (1990), 61 C.C.C. (3d) 345 (Alta. C.A.) [hereinafter <cite>Meddoui</cite>] in C. Davison, &quot;Connecting Real Evidence and Trial Fairness: The
Doctrine of `Discoverability'&quot; (1993) 35 Crim. L.Q. 493.
<p>
<li><a name="hundred1">See</a> <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Black</cite> (1989), 50 C.C.C. (3d) 1 (S.C.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Black</cite>] (inculpatory statements were excluded after violation of right to counsel, and &quot;evidence relating to the appellant's conduct in retrieving the knife as well as any words she may have uttered ought to be excluded,&quot; but the knife, the discovery of which was derived from the statement, was admitted as real evidence. <i>Ibid</i>. at 20). See also <cite>Wray</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 4 and <cite>Collins</cite>, <i>supra</i> notes 2 and 94.
<p>
<li><a name="hundred2">For example,</a> courts have been very strict when violations of the right to counsel are involved, <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Manninen</cite> (1987), 34 C.C.C. (3d) 385 (S.C.C.); <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Ross</cite> (1989), 46 C.C.C. (3d) 129 (S.C.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Ross</cite>]; <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Brydges</cite>, [1990] 1 S.C.R. 190, but much less strict with violations of s.8 of the <cite>Charter</cite> (search and seizure).
<p>
<li><a name="hundred3">See</a> <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Grant</cite> (1993), 84 C.C.C. (3d) 173 (S.C.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Grant</cite>]; <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Colarusso</cite> (1994), 87 C.C.C. (3d) 193 (S.C.C.).
<p>
<li><a name="hundred4"><cite>Ross</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 102 at 140.
<p>
<li><a name="hundred5"><cite>Ibrahim</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 23.
<p>
<li><a name="hundred6"><cite>R</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Oakman</cite> (1993), 81 C.C.C. (3d) 560 (Man. Q.B.).
<p>
<li><a name="hundred7"><i>Supra</i></a> note 2 at 284. &quot;The factors relevant to this determination [whether fairness was affected] will include the nature of the evidence obtained as a result of the violation and the
nature of the right violated and not so much the manner in which the right was violated.&quot;  <i>Ibid.</i>
<p>
<li><a name="hundred8">For example,</a> in <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Wise</cite> (1992), 70 C.C.C. (3d) 193 (S.C.C.) tracking evidence from a beeper installed in violation of s. 8 of the <cite>Charter</cite> was classified as real evidence which could have been obtained in any case. The Court in <cite>Dersch</cite> debated whether or
not blood sample analyses were real evidence, deciding that if it was separated from the accused without state interference (the `but for' test?) it was not conscripted from the accused.
<p>
<li><a name="hundred9"><i>Supra</i></a> note 26 at 360--362.
<p>
<li><a name="one10"><cite>R</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Duarte</cite>, [1990] 1 S.C.R. 30 [hereinafter <cite>Duarte</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="one11">[1990] 1 S.C.R. 62</a> (participant surveillance without a warrant).
<p>
<li><a name="one12">A more serious</a> violation will point towards exclusion. <cite>Collins</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2. <cite>Pohoretsky v. R</cite>., [1987] 1 S.C.R. 945 at 949--50 (serious breach when blood sample taken without consent).
<p>
<li><a name="one13">Traditionally,</a> the courts have given great emphasis to the presence of good faith on the part of police acting under a facially valid law (<cite>Seiben v. The Queen</cite>, [1987] 1
S.C.R. 295; <cite>Simmons v. The Queen</cite>, [1988] 2 S.C.R. 495), or according to long-standing facially legal practice (<cite>Duarte</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 110; <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Wong</cite>, [1990] 3 S.C.R. 36 [hereinafter <cite>Wong</cite>]), or a facially valid warrant (<cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Wiley</cite> (1993), 84 C.C.C. (3d) 161 (S.C.C.)), generally admitting evidence under the circumstances. Note that unlike the American federal doctrine, good faith is not necessarily sufficient. While the good faith doctrine is consistent with a
deterrence rationale, it is equally consistent with a `judicial integrity'/`avoidance of disrepute' rationale.
<p>
<li><a name="one14">See</a> <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Therens</cite>, [1985] 1 S.C.R. 613 at 652 [hereinafter <cite>Therens</cite>]; <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Silveira</cite> (1994) 6 O.R. (3d) 786 (C.A.).
<p>
<li><a name="one15">This factor</a> weighs both for and against admission. See <i>supra</i> note 103 and text for a discussion of the view in favour of admission. In <cite>Collins</cite>, Lamer C.J.C. indicated that availability of other means also aggravates the seriousness of the violation, by indicating a &quot;blatant disregard for the <cite>Charter</cite>.&quot;  <i>Supra</i> note 2 at 285.
<p>
<li><a name="one16"><cite>Wong</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 113. See also, <cite>Cloutier v. Langlois</cite> (1990), 53 C.C.C. (3d) 257 (S.C.C.), and <cite>Duarte</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 110.
<p>
<li><a name ="one17"><cite>Collins</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 2 at 286, discussed in greater detail below. Fairness of the trial trumps seriousness of the offence---&quot;if the admission of the evidence would result in an unfair trial, the seriousness of the offence could not then render that evidence admissible.&quot; <i>Ibid</i>.
<p>
<li><a name="one18"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name="one19">Though rarely considered,</a> some courts have utilized a reduction in sentence due to the misconduct (<cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Charles</cite> (1987), 36 C.C.C. (3d) 286 (Sask. C.A.) [hereinafter <cite>Charles</cite>], and <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Stannard</cite> (1989), 52 C.C.C. (3d) 544 (Sask. C.A.) [hereinafter <cite>Stannard</cite>]), or considered the availability of civil damages (<cite>Crossman v. R</cite>. (1984), 12 C.C.C. (3d) 547 (Fed. T.D.)). In general, however, such compromise measures have not been used, and have not been approved by the Supreme Court, except in principle, in <cite>Collins</cite>.
<p>
<li><a name="one20">See e.g.</a> <cite>Black</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 101 at 17, (noting that the Court had &quot;repeatedly held that the mere fact that an accused is charged with a serious offence provides no justification for admitting the evidence where there has been a serious <cite>Charter</cite> violation&quot;). But see <cite>Grant</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 103.
