<p>
<li><a name="one53">961 F.2d 300 (1st Cir. 1992).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one54"><cite>Rawlings</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 143. However, the defendant stated he did not believe the purse was free from government intrusion, perhaps the decisive factor in the case.
<p>
<li><a name="one55"><cite>United States v. Hawkins</cite>,</a> 788 F.2d 200 at 203 (4th Cir. 1986), <i>cert. denied</i>, 479 U.S. 850 (1986).
<p>
<li><a name="one56"><cite>United States</cite></a> v. <cite>Cardona</cite>, 955 F.2d 976 (5th Cir.), <i>cert. denied</i>, 113 S.Ct. 381 (1992).
<p>
<li><a name="one57"><cite>Florida v. Riley</cite>,</a> 109 S.Ct. 693 (1989) (contents of a greenhouse could not be discerned from the ground); see also <cite>California v. Ciraolo</cite>, 476 U.S. 206 (1986) (similar aerial view over property surrounded with large ten foot fences); contrast however with <cite>United States v. Cuevas-Sanchez</cite>, 821 F.2d 248 (5th Cir. 1987), in which extended video filming <i>from the ground</i> of a similarly fenced property violated a legitimate expectation of privacy.
<p>
<li><a name="one58"><cite>United States v. Burnett</cite>,</a> 890 F.2d 1233 (D.C. Cir. 1989)
(defendant was only a casual visitor). Other cases have emphasized various indicia of interest in apartments such as the presence of changes of clothing (<cite>United States v. McNeal</cite>, 955 F.2d 1067 (6th Cir. 1992)), frequency and length of stay, and the right to exclude others.
<p>
<li><a name="one59">See</a> <cite>California v. Greenwood</cite>, 108 S.Ct. 1629 (1989) (Brennan J., dissenting).
<p>
<li><a name="one60"><cite>United States v. Dodds</cite>,</a> 946 F.2d 726 (10th Cir. 1991).
<p>
<li><a name="one61">In</a> <cite>Rakas</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 138, Justice White and three other justices dissented, noting that &quot;[t]hough there comes a point when use of an area is shared with so many that one simply cannot reasonably expect seclusion ... short of that limit a person legitimately on private premises knows the others allowed there and, though his privacy is not absolute, is entitled to expect that he is sharing it only with those persons and that governmental officials will intrude only with consent or by complying with the Fourth Amendment.&quot; <i>Ibid</i>. at 164.
<p>
<li><a name="one62">377 N.Y.S.2d 461 (1975)</a> <i>rev'd subnom.</i> <cite>People v. Ponder</cite>, 445 N.Y.S.2d 57 (1981) (automatic standing rule) (overruled in <cite>Ponder</cite>).
<p>
<li><a name="one63"><cite>Ponder</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 162 at 59. The defendant lacked standing to question the search of his grandmother's home, even though she had not consented to the search.
<p>
<li><a name="one64"><i>Supra</i></a> notes 144 &amp; 139 respectively.
<p>
<li><a name="one65">392 U.S. 364 (1968).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one66">513 N.Y.S.2d 75 at 78 (1987).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one67"><cite>People v. Brown</cite>,</a> 593 N.Y.S.2d 624 (N.Y. App. Div. 1993).
<p>
<li><a name="one68"><cite>People v. Cacioppo</cite>,</a> 479 N.Y.S.2d 264 at 265--266 (N.Y. App. Div. 1984) (noting that stolen property is not an interest designed to be protected by the constitution).
<p>
<li><a name="one69"><cite>People v. Sanchez-Reyes</cite>,</a> 569 N.Y.S.2d 539 (N.Y. App. Div. 1991) (apartment was rented to someone else, and defendant did not reside there, or keep clothes or personal property there; furthermore it was minimally furnished).
<p>
<li><a name="one70"><cite>People v. Reilly</cite>,</a> 593 N.Y.S.2d 275 (N.Y. App. Div. 1993) (follows <cite>Rawlings</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 143; note: the son who owned the bag freely consented to divulge its contents to police. Those contents were admissable against the father who placed them in the bag).
<p>
<li><a name="one71">The courts followed</a> <cite>Alderman</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 135.
<p>
<li><a name="one72"><i>Supra</i></a> note 2 at 276--277.
<p>
<li><a name="one73">See,</a> <i>supra</i> notes 96--111 and accompanying text on trial fairness. If evidence would not have been found but for the violation, it affects fairness of the trial. This is certainly true for the direct victim of the violation, and should be equally true of use of the evidence in a third party's trial, although one could argue that the third party was not &quot;conscripted against&quot; himself/herself.
<p>
<li><a name="one74">(1987), 38 C.C.C. (3d) 263 (Alta. C.A.)</a> rev'd in part on other grounds (1989), 50 C.C.C. (3d) 289 (S.C.C.) (robbery and break and enter charges) [hereinafter <cite>Leaney</cite> cited to 38
C.C.C.].
