<p>
<li><a name="one84">(1992), 78 C.C.C. (3d) 1 (B.C.C.A.).</a>  The more recent case of <cite>R</cite>. v.
<cite>Sandhu</cite> (1993), 82 C.C.C. (3d) 236 (B.C.C.A.)  sheds little light on standing, as three judges denied standing to a co-defendant but with no consistent reasons beyond the result.
<p>
<li><a name="one85">(1992), 71 C.C.C. (3d) 295 (Ont. C.A.).</a>  An earlier case, <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>McDonough</cite> (1988), 44 C.C.C. (3d) 370 (Ont. Dist. Ct.), is not directly on point either, in that it held the appropriate remedial provision on the facts of that case was s. 52 (to strike down the law) and not s. 24.
<p>
<li><a name="one86"><cite>Pugliese</cite>,</a> <i>ibid</i>. at 301.
<p>
<li><a name="one87">(1994), 91 C.C.C. (3d) 123 (Ont. C.A.).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one88">J.Dawe,</a> &quot;Standing to Challenge Searches and Seizures under the Charter: The Lessons of the American Experience and Their Application to Canadian Law&quot; (1993) 52 U.T. Fac. L. Rev. 39. Dawe suggests that the Court can use this opportunity to pay more attention to the `police deterrence' rationale for the rule, a rationale which has been de-emphasized by the Canadian courts. While the expressed rationale of the Canadian rule may be judicial integrity, a survey of cases involving s. 24(2) analyses reveals that courts are actually giving great and often decisive weight in the balance to &quot;good faith&quot; and the seriousness of the violation, factors which concern themselves almost entirely with police conduct.
<p>
<li><a name="one89">Section 24(2),</a> [emphasis added]. Contrast `<i>any</i> rights' in s. 24(2) with `anyone whose rights' in s. 24(1). `Any rights' could modify the phrase in s. 24(1) but could also indicate a broader view of standing when illegally obtained evidence is involved than when it is not. <i>Supra</i> note 25.
<p>
<li><a name="one90">See</a> <cite>Montoute</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 177.
<p>
<li><a name="one91">See</a> the discussion in <cite>Collins</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2 and in Paciocco, <i>supra</i> note 26.
<p>
<li><a name="one92">764 F.2d 266 (5th Cir. 1985).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one93"><i>Ibid</i>. at 274.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one94"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name="one95"><i>Supra</i> note 179 at 555.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one96">Unreported case of the Ont. C.A.,</a> June 3rd, 1994 [1994] O.J. No. 1220 (QL).
<p>
<li><a name="one97">111 S.Ct. 2382 (1991).</a>  The Court held that no probable cause for a search existed, but the defendant was told that he could refuse. The majority held that it was acceptable, although four justices dissented, saying that the circumstances were effectively coercive since police boarded the bus in uniform, with
weapons visible (though not drawn). Contrast with <cite>Florida v. Jimeno</cite>, 111 S.Ct. 1801 (1991), in which a warrantless car search, with some probable cause, was acceptable even though the defendant was not told he could refuse to allow it. Two justices dissented, saying consent to search the car in plain view was not
consent to search closed containers within the car.
<p>
<li><a name="one98">See <cite>Therens</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 114 at and <cite>R</cite>. v. <cite>Hufsky</cite> (1988), 40 C.C.C. (3d) 398 (S.C.C.). Control over the movement of the subject by an officer of the state which may have possible legal consequences for the subject is sufficient to qualify as a detention.
<p>
<li><a name="one99">See</a> <i>supra</i> notes 96--111 and accompanying text on fairness.
<p>
<li><a name= "twohundred">See</a> <cite>Leon</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 3436 (Brennan J., dissenting).
<p>
<li><a name="two01"><i>Ibid</i>. at 3433.</a>  See generally, Kamisar, <i>supra</i> note 12.
<p>
<li><a name="two02">T. Davies,</a> &quot;A Hard Look at What We Know (and Still Need to Learn) About the `Costs' of the Exclusionary Rules: The NIJ Study and other Studies of Lost Arrests&quot; (1983) Am. B. Found. Res. J. 611. See also J. Fyfe, &quot;Enforcement Workshop, The NIJ Study of the Exclusionary Rule&quot; (1983) 19 Crim. L. Bull. 253.<p>
At the level of arrests in California, six per cent of abandoned cases are due to exclusion problems, compared to sixty per cent due to witness/victim problems. At the level of the prosecutor, approximately five per cent are dropped for exclusion reasons. Finally, at trial, 5.6% are dropped due to exclusion reasons. Most (&gt;seventy per cent) of the lost convictions are drug offences, with only six per cent related to burglary, rape, robbery and murder
charges (Fyfe at 256--257). This makes sense if one considers that in drug related offences, the drug evidence seized will be the main foundation of the charge. Certainly, exclusion seems to rank low on the list of problems in proceeding to conviction, when compared to witness and victim problems, but there does seem to be some cost.
<p>
<li><a name="two03">See F.E. Inbau,</a> &quot;Public Safety v. Individual Civil Liberties: The Prosecutor's Stand&quot; (1962) 53 J. Crim. L. &amp; Criminology 85 (pointing to increased crime since the rule was established).
<p>
<li><a name="two04">B. Canon,</a> &quot;The Exclusionary Rule: Have Critics Proven that It Doesn't Deter Police?&quot; (1979) 62 Judicature 398.
<p>
<li><a name="two05">J.F. Spiotto,</a> &quot;Search and Seizure: American Empirical Studies of the Exclusionary Rule and its Alternatives&quot; (1973) 2 J. Legal Stud. 243. See the general discussion in Fabi, <i>supra</i> note 12, and Y.-M. Morissette, &quot;The Exclusion of Evidence under the Canadian <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>: What to Do and What Not to Do&quot; (1984) 29 McGill L.J. 521 at 532--3.
<p>
<li><a name="two06">See for example Y. Kamisar,</a> &quot;Public Safety v. Individual Liberties: Some `Facts' and `Theories'&quot; (1962) 53 J. Crim. L. &amp; Criminology 171, and the discussion in Morissette, <i>supra</i> note 205.
<p>
<li><a name="two07">See Kamisar,</a> <i>supra</i> note 12.
<p>
<li><a name ="two08">See also J. Kaplan,</a> &quot;The Limits of the Exclusionary Rule&quot; (1974) 26 Stanford L. Rev. 1037 at 1051--1053.
<p>
<li><a name="two09">See F.A. Gilligan,</a> &quot;The Federal Tort Claims Act: An Alternative to the Exclusionary Rule&quot; (1975) 66 J. Crim. L. &amp; Criminology 1.
<p>
<li><a name="two10">In Canada,</a> see <cite>Mill v. The Queen</cite> (1986), 26 C.C.C. (3d) 481 (reluctant to consider a damages award); <cite>Crossman</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 119.
<p>
<li><a name="two11"><cite>Charles</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 119; <cite>Stannard</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 119 (reduction of sentence due to <cite>Charter</cite> violations was allowed).
<p>
<li><a name="two12"><cite>Leon</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 3433.</a>
