<p>
<li><a name="two20">When the American courts</a> (state and federal) do actually carry out an overt balance, the balancing often seems like a defence or attack on the rule itself rather than a neutral balance. See <cite>Stone v. Powell</cite>, 426 U.S. 465 (1976).
<p>
<li><a name="two21"><i>Supra</i> note 1.</a> See also Kamisar, <i>supra</i> note 12.
<p>
<li><a name="two22"><cite>Olmstead v. United States</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 1 at 485 (Brandeis J., dissenting). &quot;In a government of laws, existence of the government will be imperilled if it fails to observe the law scrupulously. Our Government is the potent, the omnipresent teacher. For good or for ill, it teaches the whole people by its example ... If the Government becomes a lawbreaker, it breeds contempt for law; it invites every man to become a law unto himself; it invites anarchy.&quot; <i>Ibid.</i>
<p>
<li><a name="two23"><i>Ibid</i>. at 470.</a>  &quot;We have to choose and for my part I think it a less evil that some criminals should escape than that the Government should play an ignoble part.&quot;
