<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review Vol. 53 No. 1</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v53n1.htm">Volume 53 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Real Estate Investment Trusts: An Analysis of the Investment Vehicle
and Income Tax Implications
<p>
 JASON MERETSKY<sup><a href="#note">*</a></h1></sup>

<i>As the market trend in real estate finance is shifting away from private transactions and towards public markets,
real estate investment trusts (REITs) offer an ideal vehicle through which real estate can be securitized and equitized. REITs represent a highly regarded financial instrument for future ownership of commercial real estate in Canada. With the recent decline in real estate values and the lack of liquidity in the marketplace, investors have been frustrated by their inability to exit syndicated real estate investments. The REIT vehicle affords the investor liquidity and as well enables large and small investors to access the real estate market. The topic of REITs raises interesting legal issues in the area of tax law. This paper examines the nature and characteristics of the REIT investment; the benefits and risks associated with this type of investment; provides a detailed analysis of the current Canadian tax rules applicable to REITs and considers proposed legal reform.
<p>
Dans un contexte o&ugrave: le financement public de biens immobiliers joue un r&ocirc;le croissant, au d&eacute;triment des transactions priv&eacute;es, les fonds de placement immobilier (FPI) offrent un v&eacute;hicule par lequel un investisseur peut prendre une participation sous forme d'unit&eacute;s dans un bien immobilier. Les FPI repr&eacute;sentent un instrument financier des plus respect&eacute;s pour faciliter l'acc&egrave;s &eacute;ventuel &agrave; la propri&eacute;t&eacute; d'immeubles commerciaux au Canada. Suite au d&eacute;clin r&eacute;cent de la valeur des propri&eacute;t&eacute;s et &agrave; l'absence de march&eacute; secondaire, les investisseurs se sont vu incapables de se retirer des investissements immobiliers en soci&eacute;t&eacute;. Les FPI procurent aux grands et petits investisseurs un acc&egrave;s au march&eacute; de l'immobilier. Le sujet des FPI comporte d'int&eacute;ressantes questions d'ordre l&eacute;gal dans le domaine de la fiscalit&eacute;. Ce texte analyse la nature et les caract&eacute;ristiques des investissements dans les FPI; les b&eacute;n&eacute;fices et les risques associ&eacute;s &agrave; ce type d'investissement, les implications fiscales existantes, ainsi que les r&eacute;formes propos&eacute;es.</i>
<p>
<h3>INTRODUCTION</h3>
<blockquote>
Securitization is the linchpin for the growth of the real estate asset class.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The real estate investment trust (&quot;REIT&quot;) vehicle is a topic of current interest to investors in and portfolio holders of real estate. With the recent decline in real estate values, investors have been frustrated by their inability to exit syndicated real estate investments.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> The REIT vehicle affords liquidity. This investment vehicle is, at present, highly regarded as a financial instrument for public institutional ownership of real estate. It is as well an attractive format that enables small investors to participate in the ownership of substantial real estate investments usually available to only corporate or more affluent and sophisticated investors.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup>
<p>
A REIT is an entity organized to consolidate the capital of a large number of investors for the purpose of investment in real estate, either through direct equity acquisition or in real estate-secured mortgage loans. As an investment vehicle, the REIT combines the best features of real estate and stocks. It affords the investor a practical and efficient mechanism to include professionally managed quality real estate in an investment portfolio. The REIT investor receives a security, in the form of a share or unit, which entitles the investor to an unspecified proportionate share of the assets in the REIT trust. Most of the U.S. REITs and all of the Canadian REITs trade on a listed exchange.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup>
<p>
In recent months in Canada and for the last several years in the United States<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup>, REITs have generated considerable attention in the equity and real estate markets. In Canada there has been a recent marked increase in REIT activity and the emergence of portfolio owners interested in forming REITs and investors interested in the purchase of REIT units. This activity is influenced by a variety of factors. The impressive performance of the stock markets in the past few years has renewed investor confidence and interest in public markets. The recent low interest rates have caused REITs to become attractive in terms of current yield.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> The dearth of capital for real estate and the increasing need for asset liquidity has influenced acceptance of this vehicle by developers, property managers and institutional investors. Lastly, favourable tax rules
relating to REITs have resulted in higher after-tax yields.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup>
<p>
This paper analyzes the attractiveness of REITs as a vehicle for investing in real estate. It is the author's opinion that, despite the current level of uncertainty in the capital markets, the prospects for the introduction of REITs to the Canadian marketplace are quite promising. As the market trend in real estate finance is shifting from private transactions to public markets, REITs offer an ideal vehicle through which real estate can be securitized and
equitized. Subject to some structural differences, it is anticipated that the development of the Canadian REIT industry will parallel that of the more mature and established U.S. market.
<p>
The topic of real estate securitization raises interesting legal issues in the areas of real estate law, securities law and tax law. As a publicly traded instrument, REITs must comply with securities legislation designed to ensure full, true and plain disclosure in the marketplace. Accurate disclosure of the value of the underlying asset of a REIT is often difficult to quantify due to the lack of liquidity of the underlying real estate assets. Although the real estate properties are appraised on an annual basis, market value cannot accurately be determined except where the real estate is sold in the marketplace. In addition to the issue of liquidity, the value of REIT units will be influenced by prevailing market conditions, investors' acceptance of this form of security instrument and the ability of REITs to generate attractive yields.
<p>
The structure of the REIT has relevant tax implications. Canadian issuers have employed two structures---open-end funds, which provide investors with a right of redemption and closed-end funds, which do not. Depending on the structure selected, the REIT must concern itself with Part XII.2 Tax, a tax levied in connection with trust distributions made to non-residents of Canada, the 21-year deemed disposition rule of capital property held in a trust entity, and different rules relating to Registered Savings Plan eligibility, Capital Cost Allowance, and recapture allocation and land transfer tax. Recent Revenue Canada proposals to amend the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> provisions relating to REITs should greatly promote their use as a favourable format for the holding of institutional real estate. This paper contains a detailed analysis of the tax rules applicable to the open-end and closed-end REIT structures. 
<p>
Since Canadian REITs are structured as trust entities, they do not, unlike the corporate structure, provide limited liability to the investor. This issue is particularly relevant with respect to environmental matters and, to a much lesser extent, debt exposure. There is risk that the trust, and indirectly the unit holders, could incur general liability for environmental harm. This paper considers this issue and the steps taken by the REIT entity to insulate the investor from exposure to environmental liability.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup>
<p>
The information in this paper is organized into three parts. Part I examines the nature of a REIT and the characteristics associated with this form of investment vehicle. Part II deals with the public markets for investing in REITs. This section contains a detailed analysis of the benefits and risks associated with this type of investment. Although reference is made to the U.S. REIT market and its history, primary emphasis is given to existing and emerging Canadian REITs. Finally, Part III considers the Canadian tax rules applicable to REITs and, where relevant, legal reform and other significant legal issues are addressed.
<p>
<h3>Part I: Nature of the Real Estate Investment Trust Vehicle</h3>

1. GENERAL DESCRIPTION
<p>
A REIT is an entity that aggregates the capital of many investors to acquire a portfolio of income-producing properties or, in the case of mortgage REITs, to provide financing in the form of real estate-secured mortgage loans. A REIT is similar to a mutual fund that restricts its investments to real estate. A REIT is owned by unit holders who acquire shares, which in the case of publicly-traded REITs, are listed on a major stock exchange.
<p>
REITs provide a suitable investment vehicle for investors of limited financial means who can pool their resources and invest in real estate properties without the major commitment of time and capital required for direct ownership. The investment offers liquidity, especially if publicly traded, and diversification can be achieved through a mixed portfolio of various types of income-producing properties located in different geographic areas.
<p>
REITs are an investment vehicle that originated in the United States initially to overcome restrictions on collective real property ownership and, in due course, to comply with the requirements of the <cite>Internal Revenue  Code</cite><sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> and other favourable legislation.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> Canadian tax
law does not contain specific REIT provisions and the applicable provisions of the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite><sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> are not identical to the <cite> Internal Revenue Code</cite>. As a consequence, the features and characteristics of Canadian REITs differ somewhat from their American counterparts. Most of the differences can be attributed to the differences in tax treatment between the two jurisdictions.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup>
<p>
The term REIT &quot;has been adopted by the Canadian real estate industry to refer generally to a publicly traded, tax-efficient, high yield, low leverage, real estate security.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> Canadian REITs were initially introduced as closed-end publicly listed real estate investment funds. The underlying concept of a closed-end fund is that the units are not redeemable on demand and are not offered on a continuous basis. Recently, a modified open-end mutual fund trust was to have been introduced to the marketplace. This open-end fund intended to provide for the redemption of units on demand with the modification that such redemption will take place at a pre-specified discount to market value.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> At present, the tax treatment of the open-end vehicle approximates that of U.S. REITs whereas the closed-end real estate investment fund does not.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup>
<p>
2.  U.S. REITS
<p>
<i>(i)   Overview</i>
<br>
The REIT vehicle first originated in the 1800's in Massachusetts under the name &quot;Massachusetts business
trust.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> This alternative form of collective ownership of real estate was created
to avoid state legislative restrictions on collective ownership of real estate for investment purposes. Following the enactment of federal income tax law in the U.S., utilization of the business trust vehicle as a form of collective ownership of real estate accelerated rapidly as U.S. courts consistently held, until 1935, that this trust vehicle did not attract corporate income tax. Use of REITs ended abruptly after 1935 as a result of a United States Supreme
Court ruling that such a business trust was sufficiently similar to a corporation that it should be subject to the same federal taxation rules.
<p>
The current REIT vehicle was created in 1960 as a result of amendments to the U.S. <cite>Internal Revenue Code</cite>. The tax amendments were introduced to enable flow through treatment of real estate income, losses through a business trust, and also to create a mechanism for small investors to access or participate in the ownership of substantial real estate holdings that previously were available by direct acquisition to only large corporate or very
affluent and sophisticated investors. The key feature of the U.S. REIT is that income or capital gains distributed to its shareholders are exempt from federal taxes. In addition, investors retain the benefit of limited liability associated with traditional corporate investments.
<p>
<i>(ii)   Qualifications of U.S. REITS</i>
<br>
To qualify as a REIT for U.S. tax purposes, a number of stringent requirements must be met.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> The extensive requirements of tax, securities and other legislation have resulted in REITs having many common organizational features and characteristics:
<ul>
<li>A REIT must be organized as a corporation, business trust or association and it must be treated as a corporation for tax purposes;<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup>
<li>Management of a REIT must be carried out by an elected board of directors or trustees.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> In most states, a majority of the directors must be independent;
<li>REITs often employ independent property managers or ground lease their property assets to others, as the tax provisions place limitations on direct management;
<li>A REIT is primarily a real estate entity, as most of its assets must be invested in real estate and most of its gross
income must be generated from rental income or mortgage interest. A minimum of seventy-five per cent of the entity's assets must be invested in real estate with at least seventy-five per cent of the entity's income derived from property rental income or mortgage interest.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> No more than thirty per cent of the entity's income may be from the sale of real property held for less than four years or securities held for less than six
months;<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup>
<li>REIT securities are required to be widely held. Beneficial ownership must be held by at least 100 persons for at
least 335/365th of a taxation year.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> Ownership cannot be concentrated such that more than fifty per cent of the value of the REIT is owned by 5 or fewer individuals.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> This structure promotes a broad base of institutional and non-institutional investment regardless of whether the investors are taxable or tax-exempt;
<li>A REIT must distribute at least ninety-five per cent of its taxable income without regard to capital gains each
year.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> The REIT will only be subject to federal tax at the corporate level on  undistributed income. To the extent that the REIT does not distribute the capital gain on the sale of a property, there are provisions which enable the gain to only be taxed at the investor level;
<li>REITs generally hold income producing, low leverage real estate. REITs are not permitted to speculate on real estate, but rather, must hold their underlying assets for long periods of time;
<li>The investor's interest in a REIT is represented by a security certificate; and
<li>Regardless of whether a REIT is privately or publicly owned, its shares must be freely transferable, often on a
public exchange.
</ul>
<i>(iii)   Characteristics of U.S. REITs</i>
<br>
The resurgence of REIT activity in the U.S. has led to the emergence of a wide variety of new types of REITs, hereinafter identified, which offer increased diversity to the investor community. These new REITs can be categorized by the type of real estate in which they invest and by their structural features. 
<p>
Three basic categories of REITs have evolved in the U.S., characterized primarily by the nature of their underlying
investments.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> <i>Equity REITs</i>, which are the most common form, invest exclusively in equity interests in real estate, through outright ownership of real property interests. The assets of an equity REIT may be <i>diversified</i> or <i>specialized</i> and may be leveraged or unleveraged. <i>Diversified REITs</i> invest in a number of different types of property, in terms of both product type and geographical location, while <i>specialized single-purpose REITs</i> invest in a single property or several properties of the same type (for example, health care facilities).<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> <i>Mortgage REITs</i>, as their name implies, invest in mortgage loans secured by real estate. The assets of mortgage REITs include participating mortgages, convertible mortgages, wrap-around mortgages and REITs which own pools of residential mortgages acquired in the secondary market.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> Finally, the assets in <i>hybrid REITs or combination REITs</i> contain a combination of ownership and security interests in various types of real estate. U.S. REITs are also commonly classified according to their particular structural features. These
include:<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup>
<dl>
<dt><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif"> <i>Closed-End vs. Open-End</i>
<dd>Closed-end REITs have provisions which restrict the issuance of shares to the initial offering. In contrast, open-end REITs may raise additional capital through the issuance of securities.
<dt><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif"> <i>Finite-Life vs. Nonfinite-Life</i>
<dd>A finite-life REIT has a predetermined schedule for the sale or liquidation of all the assets and the subsequent distribution of the proceeds to security holders. Conversely, nonfinite REITs have no fixed wind-up schedule or liquidation.
<dt><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif"> <i>Self-Liquidating vs. Perpetual</i>
<dd>A self-liquidating REIT distributes all cash flow from property sales or financing to security holders as it is collected. In contrast, a perpetual REIT reinvests the surplus proceeds from sales or financing. Both forms must, as is the case with REITs, distribute ninety-five per cent of their taxable income to preserve their REIT status.
<dt><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif"> <i>Fully Specified vs. Blind Pool</i>
<dd>A fully specified REIT invests only in real property or mortgages permitted by the documents establishing the REIT at the time funds are initially raised. In a blind pool offering, capital is raised first and then suitable investments are determined.
</dl>
One form of REIT which has recently achieved considerable acceptance in the U.S. marketplace is the closed-end, finite-life, self-liquidating, fully specified, equity REIT.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> The benefits from this form of REIT include: increased predictability of returns, as there is no risk of dilution of security holder's interest; a guarantee that security holders will receive the current benefits of property ownership, as all cash flow is distributed; and, the ability of security holders to participate in any appreciation in the portfolio properties on a current basis.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup>
<p>
3.  CANADIAN REITS
<p>
<i>(i)   Overview</i>
<br>
Problems experienced by existing real estate based mutual funds in late 1992 gave impetus to the emergence of the Canadian REIT industry.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> In Canada, real estate mutual funds have traditionally been structured as mutual fund trusts for income tax purposes.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> While the tax treatment of an open-end mutual fund approximates that of a U.S. REIT (to the extent that the trust entity is not subject to tax when all income and capital gains are distributed on an annual basis), the redemption entitlements inherent in mutual fund trusts gave rise to their demise.
<p>
The redemption provision in mutual fund arrangements, a condition for qualifying as a mutual fund trust, created an
asset/liability mismatch.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> The fundamental problem is that, while the units of the mutual fund trust are highly liquid, the underlying real estate assets can at various times be illiquid. A consequence
of this dichotomy is that mutual fund trusts are obliged to effect sales of their underlying assets in weak real estate markets and/or at disadvantageous prices for the simple purpose of financing unit redemptions. A further complicating problem associated with redemptions was the fact that unit redemption prices were based on the appraised value of the underlying real estate. In unstable markets, appraisals are usually overly optimistic and very often not reliable. As a consequence, the redeeming unit holder is placed in a more favourable position than unit holders whose interests are redeemed upon a liquidation of the trust (where properties are sold at a discount to market value).<sup><a href="#thrity4">34</a></sup>
<p>
The sharp decline in Canadian real estate values during the past several years resulted in an increased demand for redemptions. Whereas prior to the recession, open-end mutual fund trusts could easily satisfy or offset redemption requests by the sale of units, the rapid decline in real estate values compromised the overall solvency of the funds. Rather than liquidate real estate assets at depressed prices in an unstable marketplace, recourse to the redemption feature was suspended and the mutual fund trusts were restructured.
<p>
Those Canadian mutual funds that suspended redemptions include North American Real Estate Fund, Metfin Real Estate Growth Fund and Counsel Real Estate Fund.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> These mutual fund trusts have been converted to REITs. North American Real Fund now trades on the Toronto Stock Exchange as RealFund (symbol RFN.UN), Metfin now trades as Canadian Real Estate Investment Trust or CREIT (symbol REF.UN) and Counsel Real Estate Fund began trading on March 10, 1994 as Counsel Real Estate Investment Trust (symbol REI.UN).
<p>
<i>(ii)   Qualifications of Canadian REITs</i>
<p>
Canadian tax law does not contain specific REIT legislation.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> Notwithstanding the absence of legislation, two REITs emerged in 1993 and one REIT has been introduced in 1994.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> The present objective in forming a REIT is twofold: to create a real estate investment vehicle which has liquidity, and therefore attraction to an investor (as its units are traded on a stock exchange), and to
provide investors with both a return in excess of market interest rates and the potential for capital appreciation.
<p>
In Canada, most REITs are being structured as commercial trusts which are closed-end funds. The closed-end funds do not permit redemption on demand; however, in some cases, the units may be redeemed on demand over a defined period up to established limits.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> Canadian closed-end funds do have shortcomings which include potential tax liabilities and unlimited liability concerns.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup>
<p>
A recent advance tax ruling by Revenue Canada<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> with respect to the Lantower REIT's open-end format may have set an important precedent. Revenue Canada ruled that a redemption feature which
allows units to be redeemed at eighty per cent of their current trading price (to be paid in either cash or three-year subordinated debt, at the option of the REIT) be qualified as a mutual fund trust for tax purposes. The tax treatment of this modified open-end mutual fund trust structure approximates that of U.S. REITs and thereby resolves the inherent tax difficulties associated with closed-end funds. There remains, however, the issue of unlimited liability for holders of open-end fund units.
<p>
<i>(iii)   Characteristics of Canadian REITs</i>
<br>
As introduction of REITs in the Canadian marketplace has only recently occurred, it is perhaps premature to identify or speculate as to what combinations of traditional REIT characteristics will emerge in the future. Notwithstanding the foregoing, several common organizational features and characteristics have been identified with Canadian REITs:<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup>
<ul>
<li>REITs pay out all income, the majority of which is sheltered due to capital cost allowance (CCA) and interest deductions inherent in real estate. A REIT is essentially a tax-sheltered yield-producing instrument;
<li>A REIT itself does not pay tax at the fund or trust level. It is a tax-efficient structure for investors wanting the tax shelter opportunities from the CCA and interest deductions;
<li>To date, the Canadian REIT market has focussed exclusively on income property portfolios. These equity REITs contain only income producing, low leverage real estate;<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<li>Primarily as a result of their limited capital base, but also to maximize overall return expectations, REITs have
generally invested in secondary or &quot;B&quot; class properties, as opposed to the more prestigious and expensive &quot;A&quot; class buildings;<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup>
<li>Two of the early Canadian REITs, RealFund and Counsel Real Estate Investment Trust, provide no redemption
provisions. A third, Canadian Real Estate Investment Trust, provides limited redemption rights. Due to the tax benefits associated with the modified open-end structure adopted by Lantower Real Estate Investment Trust, it is anticipated that this structure will become prevalent in the future;
<li>Regardless of whether redemption rights are provided to unit holders, the REIT vehicle is much more liquid than direct investment in real estate or investment in limited partnerships or other syndicated structures. The reason for this liquidity is the fact that REIT units are listed and traded on a major stock exchange. To date, all Canadian REITs are listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange; and
<li>In the Canadian market, due to their relatively small size, most REITs will be managed through advisory
relationships. In contrast, the trend in the U.S. has been for REITs to convert to self-advised status.
</ul>
<h3>Part II:   The Market for Investing in REITs</h3>

1.  BENEFITS OF A REIT INVESTMENT
<p>
In addition to their liquidity and the favourable tax treatment afforded to REITs, there are other features associated with this investment vehicle that can make it attractive to investors. For example, REITs:
<ul>
<li>permit portfolio diversification into real estate;
<li>generate attractive after-tax yields;
<li>invest in high quality real estate and contain low debt levels;
<li>are professionally managed; and
<li>are structured efficiently to acquire real estate holdings.
</ul>
<i>(i)   Liquidity</i>
<br>
The ability to divest oneself of a real estate investment is an attractive feature for both large institutional investors and small private investors. As Canadian REITs are publicly traded on a major stock exchange (presently only the Toronto Stock Exchange), investors can easily convert their indirect real estate investment into cash. The lack of capitalization in the marketplace and thin trading volumes may, however, be limiting factors.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(ii)   Diversification</i>
<br>
Traditional wisdom suggests that an investment portfolio be balanced and therefore include a real estate component. This theory assumes that real estate provides a hedge against inflation as rents, and therefore values, rise in an inflationary environment.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> However, during the current decade, inflation is expected to remain low and, as a consequence of the oversupply of income-producing properties of all categories, effective rental growth is expected to be marginal.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> Any material increase in interest rates during this period of oversupply and low inflation will minimize or defeat the hedge value of real estate.
<p>
Current market conditions make real estate investments very attractive. Properties can be purchased at historically high capitalization rates and financed with historically low interest rates.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> This combination enables real estate to deliver attractive yields to investors. Many analysts believe that real estate values are now at or near the bottom after an unprecedented five year decline from 1989 to 1993. As a result, the potential for growth in the value of real estate may now exist.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup>
<p>
The REIT vehicle permits smaller investors (institutional and private) to participate in the real estate investment marketplace and to access top quality substantial real estate properties formerly available only to large institutional investors or more affluent and sophisticated investors who would make direct purchases of such properties. As well, diversification of product acquired by the REIT, through property type and geographical location, will provide
improved risk-return trade-offs.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iii)   Attractive After-Tax Yields</i>
<br>
REITs provide attractive after-tax yields by distributing all income to their unit holders on a periodic
basis.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> The existing Canadian REITs distribute operating income on a quarterly basis and realized capital gains on an annual basis. Income from the REIT is generally subject to tax at the investor level and in most cases, little or no income tax liability will arise because of the capital cost allowance (CCA) and interest deductions inherent in real estate.
<p>
The attractive yields from REITs result from the positive net cash flow and appreciation of value of properties within the fund. An increase in yield can be generated either internally or externally. Internal growth can be derived from such factors as increases in rental rates, declining vacancy rates, decreasing interest costs, reducing operating costs and property re-development or expansion.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> External growth is generated primarily by taking advantage of the spread between available returns on the acquisition of real estate and the REIT's current cost of capital.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iv)   High Quality Real Estate</i>
<br>
Because REITs are essentially a yield instrument, the properties acquired by REITs must produce sufficient rents and, as a consequence, sufficient net income to generate the required yields. Speculative properties, undeveloped properties, raw land and distressed real estate are therefore not appropriate assets for REIT acquisition. Suitable properties are limited to well located, mature, income-producing real estate such as leased shopping centres, high rise residential buildings, and quality industrial and office buildings.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> As a result of
limitations on their capital base and partly as a reflection of overall return expectations, Canadian REITs to date have generally invested in secondary or &quot;B&quot; class properties rather than the more suitable and expensive &quot;A&quot; class properties.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup>
<p>
Canadian REITs generally invest in low leverage real estate. They are conservative regarding debt borrowing and usually employ long-term fixed rate debt financing, which is appropriate for the long-term nature of the leases that provide the REITs' cash flow. Most REIT documentation restricts borrowing in excess of a fifty per cent debt to total asset ratio.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> This is substantially less than the seventy-five per cent (or greater) debt to total asset ratio that has been typical of debt levels in the real estate industry.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(v)   Corporate Governance</i><sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup>
<br>
Publicly-held REIT securities enjoy the benefit of professional management, overseen by a board of directors or
trustees. When investors acquire a REIT security, their investment has the benefit of professional management of the underlying assets, and the investor is the beneficiary of fiduciary obligations owing from senior management of the public entity.
<p>
A REIT's performance is monitored on an on-going basis by independent directors of the REIT, independent analysts, independent auditors, and the business and financial media. This scrutiny provides the investor with both a measure of protection and a barometer of the REIT's financial condition and performance.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> A further measure of protection afforded the REIT investor is the market mechanism. Yields and
performance dictate the value of the investor's security relative to other investments. Investors who feel the fund is under-performing may liquidate their interest and invest the proceeds in an alternative investment. The competition between investment alternatives is healthy and, in its own way, should provide stability and afford a REIT investor with a level of protection. 
<p>
<i>(vi)   An Efficient Ownership Vehicle for Real Estate Investments</i>
<br>
In acquiring real estate investments, various legal entities may be used. The common formats include: direct ownership of real property, partnership, co-tenancies, limited partnership structures and direct acquisition of share capital in real estate companies or open-end mutual funds.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> Each of the foregoing have
inherent limitations for those with minority interests. The REIT format appears to be a most efficient format for participation in the ownership of substantial real estate properties, particularly for non-controlling interests.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> The limitations referred to are as follows:
<dl>
<dt><i>Direct Investments</i>
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">The types of commercial properties available in
small dollar amounts are limited;
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Requires property management which is time consuming; and
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Diversification of investment portfolio is
difficult as significant capital may be tied up in one property.
<dt><i>Partnerships, Co-tenancies, &amp; Limited Partnership Structures</i>
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Generally sold as tax shelter deals and lack
on-going yield and investment value;
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Liquidity is limited by the provisions of the
partnership, co-owners or limited partnership agreement; and
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Typically lack strong asset management.
<dt><i>Common Equity Investments in:</i>
<dt><i>Real Estate Companies</i>
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Subject to partial double taxation;
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Typically highly leveraged;
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Low or non-existent dividend rates; 
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Often inordinately high administrative and
management fees; and
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Usually include a large component of
non-income-producing assets, such as land.
<dt><i>Open-End Mutual Funds</i>
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Very few funds to chose from;
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">The redemption feature is only available in theory
and, as a practical matter, unavailable where there is a material decline in real estate values; and
<dd><img src = "http://www.law.utoronto.ca/icons/blueball.gif">Pricing of units does not always reflect market
conditions.
</dl>
Conversely, REITs are income producing, as a result of the type of real estate they own and the requirement to distribute the majority of their income, tax efficient as CCA and interest deductions flow directly to the investor, liquid, efficiently managed and conservative regarding debt.
<p>
2.  RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH REITS
<p>
While there are many advantages to the REIT vehicle, investors must also consider the risk factors associated with REIT ownership. Many disadvantages of a REIT investment are included in the following summary:
<ul>
<li>REITs are subject to the usual risks of real estate ownership;
<li>REITs are exposed to general changes that occur in the public security markets. For instance, trading volumes may be low, dilution may occur for new security issues and unit prices may fluctuate with changes in financial markets;
<li>REITs are a passive form of real estate investment. Potential conflicts of interest arise between REIT
investors and management;
<li>The management of REITs is often dependent on key personnel;
<li>The performance (that is, tax equivalent yield) of REITs may decline over time, as CCA deductions will decrease if additional properties are not purchased to enhance the depreciation pool;<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup>
<li>Depending on the structure of the REIT, certain adverse tax rules are applicable such as Part XII.2 Tax and Land Transfer Tax (subject to proposed amendments to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite>);<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> and
<li>As Canadian REITs are structured as trusts, they do not offer limited liability.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup>
</ul>
<i>(i)   Real Property Ownership</i>
<br>
All real property investments are subject to a certain degree of risk. They are affected by various factors including
general economic conditions, local real estate markets, demand for leased premises, and competition from other available investment opportunities. The value of any income-producing property interest will very much depend on the financial integrity and stability of the tenants. REITs often will be very careful in tenant selection even at the cost of rent maximization.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup>
<p>
Real property equity investments are relatively illiquid. This lack of liquidity restricts the REIT from expeditiously making changes to its portfolio in response to changes in economic or investment conditions. In the event a REIT was forced to liquidate material portions of its real estate holdings, the proceeds of disposition may be significantly less than fair market value.
<p>
REITs are exposed to risks associated with debt financing. There is a risk that existing mortgage indebtedness cannot be refinanced, or that financing cannot be obtained on favourable or market terms. The financial strength of the REIT and quality and value of the assets that must be financed are pivotal. To minimize this risk, some REITs will be structured so that the timing for renewal of major tenant leases will coincide with the refinancing.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(ii)   Public Market for Units and Unit Prices</i>
<br>
As REITs have fallen in and out of favour over the years in the U.S. and are only a recent phenomenon in Canada, there is the risk that an active public market for REITs will not develop or will not be sustainable. If trading volumes are low, liquidity will be compromised. In the event of a small market float, larger investors seeking to dispose of real estate security may be obligated to sell the security in small increments to avoid a negative impact on the market price.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup>
<p>
One of the significant factors influencing the trading volume of REIT units is yield. Increases in interest rates will prompt potential purchasers of REIT units to demand a higher annual yield causing an adverse impact on the market price of the units. Finally, there is concern that the public markets do not properly value the specific underlying real estate assets and, as a consequence, the securities trade at a discount having regard to fair market value of the real estate assets.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iii)   Potential Conflict of Interest with Trust and Related Parties</i>
<br>
Various conflict of interest situations may arise as a result of the REIT's management and other related parties being
engaged in a wide range of real estate and other business activities. For instance, where only a percentage interest in a property is owned by the REIT, and the non-REIT co-owner is also engaged as the manager of the REIT, there is an obvious conflict regarding decisions to sell the asset. The manager's personal and/or corporate circumstances, preparedness to forego management fees, and suitability of time for a sale, will conflict with the course of conduct that serves the best interest of the REIT.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup>
<p>
The structure of the remuneration schedule for the manager of the REIT contains possible conflicts of interest. In general, the REIT manager will be entitled to an annual management fee based on the adjusted unit holders' equity in the trust, leasing fees, and a percentage fee based on the total acquisition price of any purchase or total disposition price of any sale of real property from the REIT.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup> The monetary incentives in place for management to acquire and dispose of real estate may adversely impact the timing of such transactions.
<p>
<i>(iv) Future Performance of REITs</i><sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup>
<br>
The future performance of a REIT may be dependent on management's ability to source and acquire quality real estate and effectively administer the assets. The loss of services of talented personnel could adversely affect the REIT. The timely acquisition of assets will also affect the performance of REITs. If additional properties are not acquired from time to time, a decline in pre-tax yields will likely occur as a consequence of erosion of the CCA base
over the years.
<p>
<i>(v)   Legal and Tax Related Risks</i>
<br>
Potential tax exposure and liability concerns are risks attendant upon Canadian REITs. Depending on whether the REIT is structured as an open-end or closed-end investment trust, Part XII.2 Tax<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> is levied on non-resident beneficiaries, and Land Transfer Tax<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> may be applicable. Because REITs are trusts, they do not offer unlimited liability.<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> This issue is particularly relevant with respect to environmental matters as the trust and indirectly the unit holders could be held liable for the costs of removal or remediation of hazardous or toxic substances, and for general damages that such materials may cause to adjoining properties.
<p>
3.  MARKET PERFORMANCE
<p>
<i>(i)   United States REIT Market</i>
<br>
It is instructive to examine the market performance of U.S. REITs to predict the acceptance of this vehicle in the Canadian marketplace. The present investor interest in REITs can be attributed to a number of factors, including low interest rates which have contributed to high REIT yields relative to other income-oriented investments. The lack of financing from traditional sources has prompted the organization of REITs as an alternative source of funding of investments. In addition, investors foresee a growth opportunity through a secular recovery in the real estate industry.
<p>
The U.S. REIT industry is comprised of approximately 275 REITs of which 186 are publicly traded.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> By far the most common form of REIT is the equity REIT, representing eighty-one per cent of the total industry capitalization.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> The U.S. REIT market is specialized and diversified. There are separate REITs for different property categories---regional shopping centres, community shopping centres, health care facilities, nursing homes, industrial complexes, and even a REIT for mobile homes.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> In addition to property type specialization, some REITs have specialized geographically according to a particular region, state, or city.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup>
<p>
The historical performance of REITs in the U.S. over the past twenty years compares favourably to other corporate indices. While all REITs on an aggregated basis underperformed the S&amp;P 500 index by approximately eighty-five per cent, equity REITs actually outperformed the S&amp;P 500 by about twenty-five per cent.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> During the period 1972--1993, equity REITs averaged an annual total return of 14.7% or 170 basis points higher than the S&amp;P 500 index. Further, when accounting for the fact that REITs distribute a much greater portion of their earnings immediately to shareholders, U.S. equity REITs earned on average 410 basis
points over the S&amp;P 500 over this period.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup>
<p>
In spite of the positive overall trend, the REIT industry has experienced significant periods of underperformance. We are currently experiencing the third boom in the history of REITs, the previous two being in 1968--1972 and 1985--1986.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> These growth periods were followed by significant periods of restructuring in the real estate sector.
<p>
The current boom period has witnessed substantial growth in equity REITs. Over the past two years, 1992 and 1993, $14.8 billion (U.S.) has been raised for equity REITs, $10 billion (U.S.) of which was forthcoming for initial public offerings.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> The size of initial public offerings has increased substantially from $115 million to $195 million on average.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> Despite this phenomenal growth, the REIT
industry remains relatively immature with a market capitalization of $34 billion. To provide some perspective, the capitalization of the entire REIT industry is roughly equal to companies such as General Motors ($45 billion) or Microsoft ($24 billion).<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup>
<p>   
<i>(ii)  Canadian REIT Market</i>
<br>
<i>(a)   Market Returns</i>
<br>
The Canadian REIT market is in its infancy. As of November 1, 1994, there are three REITs in Canada---RealFund, Canadian Real Estate Investment Trust (CREIT), and Counsel Real Estate Investment Trust. RealFund commenced trading on August 3, 1993, CREIT on September 13, 1993, and Counsel REIT on March 10, 1994. All three of
these REITs trade on the Toronto Stock Exchange. Together these funds have assets worth $302 million<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> and a net asset value of  $246.6 million.<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup>
<p>
Given the recent emergence of the Canadian REIT market, it is difficult to project market yields for the entire industry. A REIT's distribution is primarily based on cash flow and not earnings. An individual taxpayer is taxed based on the investor's proportionate share of the REIT's net income and the balance of the distribution is treated as a return of capital. The deferral of income tax increases substantially the fully taxable yield equivalent of the equity
REIT.<sup><a href  = "#eighty6">86</a></sup> For example, with a REIT yielding 7.00% on a dividend which represents an eighty-five per cent return of capital, the pre-tax interest yield would be 13.72% (assuming a fifty-three per cent tax rate).<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup> This yield is substantially greater than several REIT substitutes.
<p>
In Canada, the recent instability in the marketplace, combined with interest rate increases, have adversely affected the share price of the three REITs which currently trade. Consequently, Counsel REIT, RealFund, and CREIT are currently trading at higher yields than originally expected at the time of their equity issues.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> As yield vehicles, REITs are interest rate sensitive, and with the increases in interest rates
in 1994, their prices have correspondingly fallen. All three REITs currently trade at a significant discount to market value. In addition to market uncertainty, the inherent tax liability associated with recapture of CCA in closed-end funds partly accounts for this discount.<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> 
<p>
<i>(b)   Market Growth</i><br>
Depending on favourable market conditions, the Canadian REIT market is expected to grow in the next few years.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> It was intended that the following REITs would be introduced in the last
half of 1994: Lantower Real Estate Investment Trust, Orlando Real Estate Investment Trust, and Confederation Property Fund. These REITs were to have assets worth approximately $720 million and net assets of  $545 million.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> The market introduction of each of these three REITs has now been
terminated due to unfavourable market conditions.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> Market instability caused by rising interest rates, and investor concern over market performance, led to an investment climate not conducive
to REIT offerings.
<p>
Despite their termination, the conclusions drawn in this paper regarding the open-end REIT format that Lantower REIT was pioneering are still valid. The advanced tax ruling<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> obtained by Lantower REIT will serve as a valuable precedent for future REIT offerings. The Canadian REIT market has focused entirely on income-producing portfolios (i.e. equity REITs). The structure adopted by the first three REITs has been the closed-end trust format. In the case of CREIT and Counsel REIT, no redemption rights are granted to unit
holders. RealFund, on the other hand, has elected to provide limited redemption rights at a discount to the trading value of the units, but subject to a monthly cap of $20,000 worth of redemptions.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> One of the terminated REITs was to be structured as an open-end trust vehicle. Lantower REIT intended to provide the unit holder with a right to redeem the unit at a twenty per cent discount to the current trading price, with the proceeds payable in cash or a three-year subordinated debenture at the option of the trust.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup>
<p>
It is expected that the Canadian REIT market will grow to a size which will provide ample liquidity. There is a global trend in financial markets towards securitization.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> Canada lags far behind the United States in real estate securitization. The U.S., in turn, is only one-tenth as securitized in commercial real estate as are the U.K. and France.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> Given the Canadian real estate industry's need
to recapitalize and the ability of REITs to provide necessary new capital and liquidity, securitization of the Canadian real estate market is expected to accelerate. There appears to be no shortage of potential issuers of REITs. Public and private real estate companies, financial institutions, governments and corporate owners of large real estate portfolios are all candidates for the marketing of REITs.
<p>
4.  VALUATION OF THE REIT INVESTMENT
<p>
In the U.S. marketplace, the value of a REIT is primarily a function of yield.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> The
yield is measured by dividing the current or following year's projected distributable income by the price of the REIT. To determine distributable income all costs of operating the REIT, including interest, leasing commissions, tenant inducements and structural reserves are deducted from the amount of net operating income. Generally, the CCA and interest costs substantially shelter the distributable income from tax liability.
<p>
The value of a REIT will be derived from the REIT's ability to deliver distributable income on a consistent basis and capital appreciation in the underlying real estate assets.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup> Where interest rates are low and there is little expectation of capital appreciation, a REIT's value will be based on yield. Taxable investors will be interested in the pre-tax equivalent yield<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup>, while the non-taxable investor will focus on pre-tax yield. When interest rates increase, the emphasis will switch to capital appreciation of the underlying assets and, as a consequence, discount or premium to net asset value will be of greater importance to
investors.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup>
<p>
Investors frequently make the mistake of focusing on the dividend yield to the exclusion of the underlying fundamentals of the real estate. Dividend valuation involves more than comparing current payout ratios as high yields may not be sustainable and low yields may not accurately reflect the growth potential in a portfolio.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup>
<p>
In addition to comparing yields and analyzing net asset value, there are additional factors which impact upon the valuation of a REIT. The significant factors include:<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup>
<ul>
<li>Quality of portfolio properties;
<li>Quality of management;
<li>Management fees;
<li>Other fund costs;
<li>Level of total debt;
<li>Exposure to interest rate fluctuations;
<li>Exposure to lease roll-overs;
<li>Investment criteria for new properties; and
<li>Amount of cash reserves held by REIT.
</ul>
5.  INVESTORS IN REITS
<p>
Investors generally should have a keen interest in REITs. Taxable investors will be attracted by the fact that REITs generally distribute their income on a quarterly basis and their capital gains annually. This enables the taxpayer to avoid the double taxation that often arises at the conduit level. Investors requiring higher yielding investments or wishing to diversify their portfolio should consider investing in REITs as this vehicle represents a simple and efficient way for smaller investors to gain market exposure to substantial real estate properties.
<p>
In the U.S., larger investors such as pension funds and mutual funds are increasingly investing in REITs. At present, mutual funds and financial institutions are purchasing fifty per cent to seventy per cent of REIT initial public offering shares.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> Once the market capitalization for Canadian REITs
increases, this trend is expected to be replicated in the Canadian marketplace. In addition to institutional and retail investors, the sponsor or management of the REIT is maintaining a significant ownership position of approximately ten per cent to thirty per cent.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>Part III: Taxation of REITs and Related Legal Issues<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup></h3>

1.  TYPE OF STRUCTURE: OPEN-END VS. CLOSED-END
<p>
It should be recalled from the analysis on the Canadian REIT market contained in Part II of this paper that two structures can be employed---open-end and closed-end funds. The distinguishing feature is whether or not the REIT affords the unit holder the right to require redemption of their units.
<p>
The structure of the fund has relevant tax implications.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup> Should the REIT provide unit holders with redemption rights and satisfy other requisite conditions, it will obtain favourable tax status as a mutual fund trust.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> Where the right of redemption does not exist or, in the unlikely event that other requisite conditions for qualifying as a unit trust or mutual fund trust are not satisfied, the REIT will be characterized as a commercial trust for tax purposes.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup>
<p>
The structure of the fund also has relevant investor implications. If attendant with redemption rights, liquidity is
available by access to the right of redemption and as well by access to the marketplace. If the REIT does not provide redemption rights, unit holders must rely only on the market to obtain liquidity.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup>
<p>
RealFund and Counsel REIT eliminated all redemption rights when they were converted from mutual fund trusts to REITs.<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> Consequently both REITs will be taxed based on the relevant rules for commercial trusts. CREIT, which was also converted from a mutual fund trust, elected to retain limited redemption rights at a twenty-five per cent discount to the trading value of the units, but subject to a monthly cap of  $20,000 worth of redemptions.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup> It is uncertain whether CREIT will continue to qualify as a mutual fund trust with restrictions on the redemption right in place. The information circular for this REIT is perhaps misleading to the extent it avoids any reference as to whether or not the fund continues to qualify as a mutual fund trust.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> Since the REIT does not provide unrestricted redemption rights to unit holders, it should not be classified as a mutual fund trust, and therefore should be taxed as a commercial trust. Orlando REIT and Confederation Property Fund, which have been terminated, were structured similar to RealFund and Counsel REIT.
<p>
In contrast to the aforesaid five REITs, the structure of Lantower REIT is innovative and will likely become the preferred structure for future REITs.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> Lantower REIT was structured to provide a right of
redemption to unit holders, subject to a twenty per cent discount to the trading value of the units with the redemption price to be paid, at the option of the REIT, in either cash or by issuance of three-year subordinated debt.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> An advanced income tax ruling was obtained from Revenue Canada
which qualified Lantower REIT as a mutual fund trust for tax purposes.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> Despite the termination of this offering, the conclusions drawn with respect to this &quot;modified&quot; open-end format continue to apply.
<p>
2.  CLOSED-END TRUST STRUCTURE
<p>
<i>(i)   Overview of the Tax Rules</i>
<br>
In Canada, most REITs have been structured as commercial trusts which are closed-end funds. No redemption rights are provided to unit holders. A closed-end REIT (as would a commercial trust) will be subject to the following Canadian tax consequences:
<ul>
<li>Capital cost allowance (CCA) is claimed by the trust entity;
<li>Beneficiaries of the trust are subject to tax on any recapture arising from the sale of property;<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup>
<li>Losses incurred by a trust cannot flow through to beneficiaries;<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup>
<li>The trust can designate net taxable capital gains in favour of beneficiaries;<sup><a href="one19">119</a></sup>
<li>The preferred beneficiary election is not available to allocate undistributed trust income to beneficiaries;
<li>The 21-year deemed disposition rule will be applicable;<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup>
<li>The fund will be subject to tax on any &quot;designated income&quot; under Part XII.2 of the <cite>Act</cite>;
<li>The fund may not qualify as a registered investments for RRSPs, RRIFs and DPSPs;<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup>
<li>There is no rollover format available for the transfer of assets to a commercial trust, a unit trust, or a mutual
fund trust;<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup>
<li>Purchasers of units on an exchange could potentially be liable for tax if they acquire units from a
non-resident vendor who does not have a certificate indicating that the tax with respect to the sale has been paid;<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup>
<li>Income derived from the trust is subject to the alternative minimum tax;<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup>
<li>The fund is not subject to capital tax;<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> and
<li>The fund is not subject to large corporations tax.<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup>
</ul>
<i>(ii)   Tax Treatment of a Commercial Trust</i>
<br>
The term &quot;commercial trust&quot; is not defined in the <cite>Act</cite>. It is generally used to describe a trust which is not a personal trust. The conditions for a personal trust are set out in subsections 248(1) of the <cite>Act</cite>. Commercial trusts are taxed according to the same rules as ordinary <i>inter vivos</i> trusts,
which are found in subdivision k of Division B in Part I of the <cite>Act</cite>.
<p>
A trust is considered to be an individual for taxation purposes. As the REIT is resident in Canada it will be subject to tax on its income from sources inside and outside Canada.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> In computing its income (including capital gains), a trust may deduct amounts payable in the year to a beneficiary, subject to limitations with respect to income payable to non-residents.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup> Where income is retained by the trust entity it will incur tax at the top marginal federal rate (that is, twenty-nine per cent) combined with the provincial rate.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> A trust is not entitled to claim personal credits when computing tax payable.<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iii)   Tax Treatment of a Beneficiary</i>
<br>
To the extent that income (including capital gains) is paid out or is currently payable<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> to beneficiaries of a trust, the income will be subject to tax in the hands of the beneficiary.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup> The beneficiary of the trust (REIT unit holder) will be required to include REIT payments in income for the year as income from a business or property with the exception of amounts deemed to be a taxable capital gain. A capital gain may also arise where the unit holder sells the REIT unit for proceeds in excess of the holder's adjusted cost base. The beneficiary is taxed on income and taxable capital gains according to their marginal federal rates.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iv)   Particular Tax Considerations for Closed-End Structures</i>
<br>
<i>(a)   Capital Cost Allowance and Recapture</i>
<br>
Capital Cost allowance<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> (CCA) is claimed at the trust level. The REIT will be
entitled to deduct CCA with respect to any depreciable property held within the year. As REITs predominantly own real property interests, the applicable CCA rates are four per cent or five per cent, depending on whether the property is a class one or class three asset.<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup> A trust is subject to the rental property restriction in that it cannot use CCA to offset other rental income of beneficiaries.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> A trust may annually take CCA on the undepreciated capital cost (UCC) base<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> of the property to the lesser of the maximum prescribed rate or the amount of income generated by the property.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup>
<p>
By way of contrast, a mutual fund trust (or open-end REIT) is entitled to designate a portion of its inherent tax liability for recaptured CCA<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> to unit holders who are redeeming their units.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> However, in the case of closed-end structures that trade on an exchange, there is no mechanism to pass on the deferred liability to unit holders who sell their units. The inherent tax liability within the fund for recaptured CCA will simply continue to accumulate and may or may not be reflected in the price at which the units will trade on an exchange. This represents a latent liability which may impact a purchaser of units without the
investor's knowledge.
<p>
<i>(b)   21-Year Deemed Disposition Rule</i>
<br>
To prevent the accumulation of capital in a trust on a tax-free basis, there is a notional deemed disposition of all capital property every 21 years.<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> The accrued gain will be subject to tax within the trust at the top marginal rate.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup>  The 21-year rule, although applicable to commercial
trusts, does not apply to unit trusts or mutual fund trusts.
<p>
The 21-year period may be calculated from the date that the fund was first created and not from the date that the fund ceased to qualify as a unit trust or mutual fund trust. This may be disadvantageous to those REITs, such as RealFund, CREIT and Counsel, which were formerly structured as open-end real estate mutual fund trusts.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> It should be noted that the impact of a deemed disposition of assets may not be harmful if none of the fund's properties have in fact appreciated in value.
<p>
<i>(c)   Part XII.2 Tax</i>
<br>
A closed-end trust is liable for Part XII.2 tax, which is a tax on designated income on certain trusts, unless it can certify that during the year none of the unit holders were &quot;designated beneficiaries.&quot;<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> The legislation defines a &quot;designated beneficiary&quot; of a trust as a non-resident or non-taxable investor who acquires a unit from a taxable investor.<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> Part XII.2 tax is
levied at a rate of thirty-six per cent on the trust's &quot;designated income,&quot; which includes income from real property and capital gains arising from the disposition of Canadian property.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup>
<p>
As a result of taking capital cost allowance, most existing Canadian REITs do not anticipate having any designated income in the short term.<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup> However, if a fund does incur Part XII.2 tax, taxable Canadian resident beneficiaries are permitted to claim their <i>pro rata</i> share of the tax paid by the fund as a credit against their ordinary tax obligation, whereas non-resident beneficiaries would not receive any credit. Certain tax-exempt entities may claim a similar refund for the Part XII.2 tax paid. In reality, for Canadian residents, Part
XII.2 tax simply represents a timing difference, as most unit holders can claim a credit in computing their annual or quarterly tax liability equal to their proportionate share of the Part XII.2 tax the REIT has paid.
<p>
All the existing Canadian closed-end REITs contain provisions prohibiting non-resident unit holders.<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> However, as a practical matter, a REIT is a publicly traded vehicle and it is virtually impossible to ensure that the fund does not become tainted by &quot;designated beneficiaries.&quot;  The existing closed-end REITs are currently indemnifying new unit holders who participate in their special warrant issues against Part XII.2 tax for approximately two years.<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup> Recent proposed amendments to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite>, introduced on 27 May 1994, appear to resolve this issue.<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(d)   Registered Savings Plan Eligibility</i>
<br>
In contrast to mutual fund trusts, the closed-end REIT structure must qualify as a registered investment under Part X.2 of the <cite>Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup> The fund must meet the following  qualifications:<sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup>
<ul>
<li>the fund must have a sole corporate trustee who is licensed under federal or provincial laws to carry on a business as a trustee;
<li>the fund must not have less than 20 beneficiaries which are either RRSPs or RRIFs;
<li>at least eighty per cent of its property (measured by fair market value at the time of acquisition) must be
held in shares, bonds, mortgages, marketable securities, cash or equity in real property held for the purposes of producing income;
<li>the value of any share, bond, mortgages or other securities of any one corporation or debtor (excluding
government debt) must not exceed ten per cent of the fair market value of all its properties in excess of debt owing on account of the acquisition of real property;
<li>the fair market value at the time the acquisition of any one real property less any debt owing on account
of the acquisition of such property must not exceed ten per cent of the fair market value of all properties; and
<li>not less than ninety-five per cent of income must be derived from the investments described in (c) above.
</ul>
The requirements for a closed-end fund to be eligible for a registered savings plan (RSP) are stringent and must be satisfied on an on-going basis. All the Canadian REITs except Lantower must satisfy the conditions for being a &quot;registered investment&quot; in order to retain their RSP eligibility. In the case of Lantower REIT, it is
structured as a mutual fund trust and would thereby qualify as a registered investment.<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup> Recent proposals by Revenue Canada will enable real estate trusts to qualify as mutual fund trusts and, therefore automatically qualify as RSP eligible investments.
<p>
<i>(e)   Dispositions by Non-Residents</i><sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup>
<br>
Units of a closed-end structure do not qualify as &quot;excluded property&quot; for the purpose of section 116 of the <cite>Act</cite>. The units will constitute taxable Canadian property, with the result that any non-resident vendor would be required to obtain a certificate indicating that taxes either have been paid or arrangements to pay are in place prior to the sale.<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup> Any purchaser of units on an exchange is potentially subject to liability if the vendor has not obtained the certificate, unless, after reasonable inquiry, the purchaser had
no reason to believe the vendor was not resident in Canada.<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup> As a consequence of this potential liability, all the Canadian REITs that are structured as closed-end funds prohibit non-residents from legally or beneficially owning units.<sup><a href="#one57">157</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(f)   Provincial Land Transfer Tax</i><sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup>
<br>
If a fund owns real property in Ontario and ceases to qualify as a mutual fund trust, then a transfer of units would no
longer be exempt under the current provisions of the <cite>Land Transfer Tax Act</cite> (Ontario). The sale of a closed-end real estate trust unit is considered to be a transfer of a beneficial interest in real estate and is subject to land transfer tax.
<p>
This tax would be very difficult to administer as units freely trade on an exchange and buyers and sellers are unknown. As a practical matter, enforcement appears impossible. The tax is not being paid on transfer and the taxing authorities do not appear to be monitoring this issue.<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup>
<p>
3.  OPEN-END REIT STRUCTURES
<p>
<i>(i)   Overview of the Tax Rules</i>
<br>
To date, only one Canadian REIT, Lantower, was structured so as to qualify as a mutual fund trust for taxation
purposes.<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup> Mutual fund trusts are given favourable tax treatment in the following respects:
<ul>
<li>A mutual fund trust is not taxable if it distributes all income and capital gains annually, provided that
appropriate designations are made;
<li>Tax paid on capital gains of the trust will be refunded as units are redeemed;<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup>
<li>Capital gains of the trust can be designated as capital gains of non-resident beneficiaries;<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup>
<li>The units are qualified investments for RRSPs, RRIFs and DPSPs;<sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup>
<li>The 21-year deemed disposition rule is not applicable;<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup>
<li>Part XII.2 tax, which gives rise to a thirty-six per cent tax on designated income (real estate income and
capital gains) does not apply to a mutual fund trust;<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup>
<li>Units of mutual fund trusts are exempt from land transfer tax;<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup>
<li>Units of mutual fund trusts are excluded property for the purposes of the certificate requirements under
section 116 for dispositions by non-residents;<sup><a href="#one67">167</a></sup>
<li>Income received from the trust is not subject to the alternative minimum tax;<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup>
<li>The fund is not subject to capital tax;<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup> and
<li>The fund is not subject to large corporation tax.<sup><a href="#one70">170</a></sup>
</ul>
<i>(ii)   Qualifications for a Mutual Fund Trust</i>
<br>
A mutual fund trust is a specific form of unit trust.<sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup> The basic requirement of a unit trust is that it be an <i>inter vivos</i> trust, having the interest of each beneficiary described by reference to units of the trust.<sup><a href="#one72">172</a></sup> In the case of an open-end unit trust, there must be conditions attaching to the units, requiring the trust to accept, at the demand of the unit holder, the surrender of the unit. At least ninety-five per cent of the fair market value of the units must be redeemable or retractable based on the appraised value of the assets.<sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup>
<p>
A mutual fund trust must be a unit trust which satisfies several additional conditions. The trust must be resident in Canada. Its undertaking must be limited only to the investing of funds of the trust and dispersal of ownership of its units. Public trading of the units must comply with conditions prescribed by regulation.<sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup> The prescribed conditions require the trust to have issued units to the public pursuant to a prospectus or similar procedure, and to have a minimum of 150 unit holders each owning one block of units with an aggregate fair market value of at least $500.<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iii)   Tax Treatment of Mutual Fund Trusts</i>
<br>
Subject to certain exceptions, the rules governing the determination of income (including capital gains) and taxable income of a unit trust (and therefore, a mutual fund trust) are the same as those applying to ordinary trusts.<sup><a href="#one76">176</a></sup> The exceptions are that the 21-year deemed disposition rule of capital property is made expressly inapplicable and a unit of a unit trust will generally be treated as capital property, analogous to the share of a corporation, in order to avoid difficulties on the sale of transferable units.<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup>
<p>
Similar to other types of trusts, to the extent that income (including capital gains) is payable in the year to beneficiaries, subject to exceptions involving non-resident unit holders and designated beneficiaries, it is taxed in the hands of the individual and not the trust.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> There are flow-through provisions which enable capital gains and capital cost allowance to pass through to the beneficiaries. With mutual fund trusts, capital gains that are not distributed in the year in which they are earned cannot be subsequently distributed other than by redemption of units in order to recover the tax paid at the trust level on such gains.<sup><a href="#one79">179</a></sup>
<p>
To the extent that income (including capital gains) is retained in the trust, it is subject to a flat rate of tax equal to the top federal marginal rate of twenty-nine per cent.<sup><a href="#one80">180</a></sup> When provincial taxes of fifty-eight
per cent are included, the overall rate of tax levied on income in the trust is 45.8% (ignoring surtaxes). A trust is not entitled to claim personal credits when computing the tax payable.<sup><a href="#one81">181</a></sup>
<p>
<i>(iv)   Tax Treatment of Unit Holders</i>
<br>
To the extent that income (including taxable capital gains) of a unit trust, including a mutual fund trust, is currently
distributed or currently distributable,<sup><a href="#one82">182</a></sup> it will not be subject to tax in the hands of the trust but rather, will be treated as income of the particular unit holder.<sup><a href="#one83">183</a></sup> A unit holder would be required to include this amount in his income for the year from a business or property except any amount deemed to be a taxable capital gain. The taxable capital gains of the individual are aggregated and offset against any accumulated capital losses before being subject to tax. A capital gain can also arise when the unit holder disposes of a unit for proceeds of disposition in excess of the unit's adjusted cost base. The income and the net taxable capital gain (that is, three-quarters of capital gains less accumulated capital losses) will be subject to tax at the individual's marginal rate.<sup><a href="#one84">184</a></sup>
<p>
Non-residents are permitted to own mutual fund trust units. Distributions of income by a resident trust to a non-resident unit holder are subject to withholding tax of 25% (subject to Treaty deduction).<sup><a href="#one85">185</a></sup> If, however, the distributed amount is deemed to be a taxable capital gain of the non-resident unit holder, no withholding tax will be imposed.<sup><a href="#one86">186</a></sup> Where a non-resident unit holder owns less than twenty-five per cent of the issued units in the five years prior to disposition, the unit will not constitute taxable Canadian property, and therefore, no withholding tax is exigible on the proceeds of the sale.<sup><a href="#one87">187</a></sup>
<p>
4.  SELECTING BETWEEN OPEN-END AND CLOSED-END STRUCTURES
<p>
In addition to tax implications associated with the REIT structures, there are significant business issues that must be
considered prior to selection of the appropriate structure. The choice of structure involves various trade-offs. Where a closed-end trust structure is utilized, REITs do not offer a right of redemption to unit holders. The liquidity that arises from a closed-end REIT will be solely derived from the market. To the extent that trading volumes are thin, liquidity will suffer. Open-end or modified open-end trust structures afford the unit holder the right to redeem
the security. This affords the unit holder additional liquidity beyond that offered by the market. However, to protect the REIT from the risk of becoming insolvent, which may arise as a result of recourse to redemption rights in a concentrated time frame by a substantial number of unit holders, the REIT builds in a mechanism whereby redemption occurs at a steep discount to market value. As an added protective measure, the REIT may wish to specify the form of payment as being either cash or a subordinated debenture of a specified duration, to be determined at the option of the REIT. The steep discount and the ability to specify the timing of and form of
payment will discourage unit holders from exercising their redemption rights, and will therefore impact on the liquidity of the unit. Inclusion of an unrestricted redemption feature (the open-end structure) affords investors a more favourable income tax treatment.
<p>
Ignoring the different tax implications of the two REIT structures, issuers will prefer the closed-end structure as it denies investors the right to require the issuer to redeem their shares. Investors in closed-end REITs must resort to the marketplace to sell their securities. Investors will clearly prefer the open-end structure as it affords them additonal liquidity, since they may sell their shares in the marketplace or exercise their right of redemption and require the issuer to purchase their shares.
<p>
5.  UNLIMITED LIABILITY CONCERN<sup><a href="#one88">188</a></sup>
<p>
Since Canadian REITs are structured as trust entities, they are not afforded the limited liability benefits that are commonly associated with U.S. REITs or Canadian corporations. The inability to offer limited liability gives rise to investor risk, predominantly with environmental issues and, to a much lesser extent, debt exposure.<sup><a href="#one89">189</a></sup>
<p>
Environmental and ecological legislation and policies have become more prevalent and onerous in recent years. Under various federal and provincial legislation, the REIT could become liable for the costs of removal or remediation of certain hazardous or toxic substances on or in its properties, and at common law, for consequential general damage to adjoining property owners. Failure to remove or remediate such substances will adversely impact the owner's ability to sell the real estate or borrow using the real estate as collateral and further, could potentially result in financial damage claims against the owner.
<p>
To protect the unit holders, all Canadian REITs carry environmental insurance.<sup><a href="#one90">190</a></sup> Prior to acquisitions of real estate or conversion to a REIT status, Phase One environmental assessments (which are an
&quot;unintrusive&quot; initial analysis of environmental problems) are performed as a precautionary measure.<sup><a href="#one91">191</a></sup> Depending upon the use provisions, new leases require tenants to carry adequate environmental insurance. In addition, the management of REITs have commenced the practice of periodic
inspections of tenant premises where the tenant's use of the premises or lands adjacent thereto may subject the property to environmental contamination or harm.
<p>
Personal liability may also arise with respect to contractual obligations of the trust. The possibility of this liability arising is remote as most of the REITs' obligations arise by contract, and non-contractual risks are generally insurable. Furthermore, REITs minimize their liability to unit holders through the use of non-recourse debt.<sup><a href="#one92">192</a></sup>
<p>
6.  PROPOSED INCOME TAX AMENDMENTS
<p>
Although Canada does not have specific REIT legislation, sustained lobbying activity by the Canadian Institute of Public Real Estate Companies (CIPREC) on behalf of many large financial institutions such as pension funds, life insurance companies, trust companies, and banks has influenced Revenue Canada to propose minor changes to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite>. These changes will clarify certain issues and remove certain ambiguities affecting Canadian REIT structures. This proposal would provide for a &quot;clean&quot; closed-end REIT structure and would obviate the need for enactment of specific REIT legislation.
<p>
The Finance Department of Canada, in a <cite>News Release</cite> dated 27 May, 1994, announced proposed changes to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> that would facilitate the holding of real estate investments by
mutual fund trusts.<sup><a href="#one93">193</a></sup> Under the existing income tax provisions, a real estate trust
cannot qualify as a mutual fund trust unless the trust allows for the redemption of its units by  unitholders.<sup><a href="#one94">194</a></sup> The proposed changes would permit real estate trusts whose units are publicly traded to qualify as mutual fund trusts.
<p>
Under subsection 108(2), there are two ways to qualify as a unit trust, which is a prerequisite to qualifying as a mutual fund trust. First, where the shares have a right to redeem, such as in the case of the open-end REIT structure, the security will qualify as a unit trust.<sup><a href="#one95">195</a></sup> Alternatively, shares which do not permit
a right to redeem may still qualify as a unit trust provided they hold certain specified assets.<sup><a href="#one96">196</a></sup> The proposed changes to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> entitle a closed-end trust to now hold real property situate in Canada, provided at least eighty per cent of the real property is located in Canada, and qualify as a mutual fund trust without having to offer the investor a right of redemption.
<p>
It is expected that this legislation will be enacted sometime in 1995. Institutions planning to market a REIT cannot obtain an advanced income tax ruling as to the tax status of their offering since the legislation has not been enacted. Revenue Canada is, however, prepared to provide an opinion that the foregoing changes will be introduced and will have the aforementioned effect on the tax status of the offering. Because of the present uncertainty, parties intending to issue a REIT may decide to delay their introduction until these changes are enacted so as to avoid a temporary interim period when the closed-end fund does not qualify as a mutual fund trust.<sup><a href="#one97">197</a></sup>
<p>
As previously noted, there are favourable tax implications that are associated with the mutual fund trust status. The closed-end REIT will now be exempt from Part XII.2 tax, a tax levied in connection with trust distributions made to investors not resident in Canada. The 21-year deemed disposition rule will not apply to a mutual fund trust. Finally, units of a mutual fund trust automatically qualify as eligible investments for retirement savings plans. Unfortunately the issue of unlimited liability of unit holders still remains, although the risk of exposure can largely be minimized.
<p>
<h3>Concluding Remarks</h3>

The history of REITs in the U.S. marketplace will offer guidance and a valuable framework for the development of this vehicle in Canada. The recent increased popularity of REITs among both investors and issuers represents a fundamental shift in the way substantial quality real estate is owned and financed. The REIT vehicle offers the investor liquidity, and also provides attractive yields, the opportunity for growth, and permits large and small
investors to access the real estate market sector. From the issuers' perspective, REITs represent an efficient form of equity financing as many traditional sources of capital for real estate have retrenched. For some issuers, REITs represent a vehicle to enable issuers to sell assets for cash or minimal financing in circumstances where direct or
indirect future benefit is derived from such assets through receipt of management fees pursuant to arrangements with the REIT.
<p>
It is the general conclusion of this paper that REITs have the potential to become a key feature in Canada's real estate and capital markets. The same factors influencing acceptance in the U.S. marketplace---need for equity, need for liquidity and search for higher yields by investors---prevail in Canada. Small investors collectively represent an enormous capital pool. The REIT mechanism enables small investors to now enter the securitized real estate marketplace.<sup><a href="#one98">198</a></sup> REIT issuers and the security industry in general have their own incentive to tap this capital pool. 
<p>
The recently proposed amendments to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> which, in effect, sanction a &quot;clean&quot; closed-end REIT structure will greatly encourage the use of the REIT format for the holding of
institutional real estate. As a result of the proposed legislative reform, the closed-end REIT structure should emerge as the preferred structure.
<p>
Market acceptance of the REIT vehicle in Canada will also depend on the liquidity in the capital markets and on the REIT's ability to generate sufficient growth to provide investors with a risk-adjusted total return sufficient to compensate for the inherent equity risk.<sup><a href="#one99">199</a></sup> As the number of REITs introduced to the marketplace increases, there is added risk that the lack of market reception or very poor performance of one REIT may, in the short run, taint the entire investment class.
<p>
