<p>
<li><a name="fifty2">Most growth within the REIT</a> fund is a result of positive leverage as the fund is able to acquire the depressed real estate at capitalization rates in the nine to eleven per cent range, while financing the acquisitions at the weighted average cost of capital in the five to eight per cent range. Should strong growth for REITs continue, it is expected that demand for particular property types will exceed supply, causing prices to rise
and thereby reducing the arbitrage opportunity. See Young, <i>supra</i> note 4 at 5.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty3"><i>Supra</i> note 41 at 4.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty4">Young, <i>supra</i> note 4 at 4.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty5">RealFund,</a> Canadian REIT, Counsel REIT, Lantower REIT, Orlando REIT and  Confederation Property Fund have all restricted their debt borrowings to fifty per cent of asset value. See RealFund, Prospectus, December 20, 1993 at 7 [hereinafter RealFund Prospectus]; Canadian Real Estate Investment Trust, Prospectus, November 16, 1993 at 18 [hereinafter CREIT prospectus]; Counsel Real Estate Investment Trust, Preliminary Prospectus, December 16, 1993 at 9 [hereinafter Counsel REIT Prospectus]; Lantower REIT, <i>supra</i> note 40; Orlando Real Estate Investment Trust, Preliminary Prospectus, January 14, 1994 at 9
[hereinafter Orlando REIT prospectus]; Confederation Property Fund, Preliminary Prospectus, March 25, 1994 at 6 [hereinafter Confederation REIT prospectus] (sources are on file with author).
<p>
<li><a name="fifty6"><i>Supra</i> note 41 at 4.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty7">It is beyond the scope</a> of this paper to provide a detailed discussion on corporate
governance issues. The information provided in this section is of a summary nature and is intended to highlight the corporate governance benefits associated with the REIT investment.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty8">Real Estate Investment Trusts,</a> brochure (Washington D.C.: National Association of Real Estate Investment Trusts Inc., February, 1993) at 11.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty9">It is beyond the scope</a> of the paper to provide a detailed examination of the various legal vehicles available for owning commercial real estate interests. For an analysis of the legal, tax and financial aspects of the various structures for acquiring and holding real estate see Sheldon Silver, &quot;Vehicles for Acquiring and Holding Real Estate&quot; <cite>Report of Proceedings of the Forty-First Conference Report</cite>, vol. 4 (Toronto: Canadian Tax Foundation, 1988) 1--19.
