<li><a name="eighty6">Young,</a> <i>supra</i> note 4 at 18.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty7">The 13.72% pre-tax</a> equivalent yield is taxed as follows: 85% of 13.72% @53% =  5.73% for income plus 15% of 13.72%  @ 53% @ 75% = 0.76% for capital gains. This results in a pre-tax yield of 6.50%.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty8">RBC Dominion Securities,</a> <i>supra</i> note 85..
<p>
<li><a name="eighty9">Discussed</a> in III(2)(iv)(a) of this paper.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety">In addition to REITs,</a> there are a number of other real estate initial public offerings that will be introduced by the summer of 1994. These include Centrefund Realty Corporation and Frum Property Corporation. These funds are structured as real estate mutual fund corporations and have, in some cases, very different characteristics and/or tax treatment than real estate investment trusts. The scope of this paper is restricted to examining the REIT vehicle. For information regarding the tax treatment of mutual fund corporations, see &quot;Conduit Corporations and Trusts&quot; <cite>Ward's on Taxation</cite> vol. 5, 18:71--91.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety1">Lantower REIT Prospectus,</a> <i>supra</i> note 40 at 54; Orlando REIT Prospectus, <i>supra</i> note 55 at 24; Confederation REIT Prospectus, <i>supra</i> note 55 at 25.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety2">By press release dated March 12, 1994, the promotors and investment dealers for the Lantower REIT terminated the offering as they felt that current market conditions would not guarantee a successful marketing of this security. There was no mention as to whether the promotors would be inclined to re-market the security at a later date should ideal market conditions prevail. See Barry Critchly &quot;Lantower IPO on Ice&quot; <cite>Financial Post</cite> (12 March 1994) 19.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety3">Lantower REIT Prospectus,</a> <i>supra</i> note 40 at 45.
<p>
