<p>
<li><a name="one33">The marginal federal</a> rates are contained in s. 117 of the <cite>Act</cite>, <i>Ibid</i>. Prior to February 22, 1994, any capital gains earned with respect to the disposition of shares of REITs were entitled to be offset by the $100,000 lifetime capital gains exemption under s. 110.6 of the <cite>Act</cite>, <i>Ibid</i>., to the extent that the exemption was available.
<p>
<li><a name="one34">Capital cost allowance is a</a> notional account created by Revenue Canada to adjust for depreciation in the value of a capital asset. In order to be eligible for capital cost allowance on depreciable property, the taxpayer must have either title to the asset or all the incidents of title such as possession, use and risk.
<p>
<li><a name="one35">The CCA rates</a> are contained in Schedule II of the <cite>Income Tax Regulations</cite>. A building that is acquired before 1990 falls into class three and is entitled to take CCA at a maximum of five percent a year. All other properties constitute class one assets and are entitled to a four percent CCA rate.
<p>
<li><a name="one36"><cite>Act</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 11 at Reg. 1100.
<p>
<li><a name="one37">The undepreciated capital</a> cost base represents the value of the capital asset that has not been subject to capital cost allowance.
<p>
<li><a name="one38">An exception</a> is made for multiple-unit residential buildings or MURBs (Class 31 or Class 32 assets). A MURB has the effect of permitting the creation of a loss with CCA which can be used to offset other sources of income within the trust. This exception has very limited relevance as no new MURBs have been
registered since 1981 and most of the CCA has already been deducted from these properties.
<p>
<li><a name="one39">The tax system requires</a> the inclusion in income of recapture of capital cost allowance where the capital cost allowance deductions have resulted in an undepreciated capital cost that is less than the proceeds of disposition of the asset. The role of the recapture concept in the capital cost allowance system is to provide for a deduction for tax purposes of the full decline in value of assets over the period of their use. Thus, capital cost allowance will be recaptured when proceeds of disposition exceed the undepreciated capital cost, that is, when assets in a class have been over-depreciated relative to the disposal value. See R.E. Beam &amp; S.N. Laiken, <cite>Introduction to Federal Income Taxation in Canada</cite>, 13 ed. (Toronto: CCH Canadian Limited, 1992) at 178.
<p>
<li><a name="one40"><cite>Act</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 11 at s. 132.1.
<p>
<li><a name="one41"><i>Ibid</i>.</a> at ss. 104(4) and (5).
<p>
<li><a name="one42">In the case of depreciable assets,</a> the trust is deemed to dispose of the property and then reacquire it at the mid-point between the fair market value and the undepreciated capital cost of the assets in each class (s. 104(4), <i>Ibid</i>.). For non-depreciable property, the trust is deemed to have disposed of and subsequently reacquired the assets at fair market value (s. 104(5), <i>Ibid</i>.).
<p>
<li><a name="one43">Prior to the creation</a> of the REIT structure, these investment portfolios were not publicly traded and were structured as open-end mutual funds.
<p>
<li><a name="one44">The provisions</a> of Part XII.2 Tax are contained in ss. 210, 210.1, 210.2, and 210.3, <cite>Act</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 11.
