<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol53#1">Volume 53 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Restitution, `Passing On,' and the Recovery of Unlawfully Demanded Taxes: Why <b>Air Canada</b> Doesn't Fly<p>
PAUL MICHELL</h1>

<center><h3>ABSTRACT / <a  href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/utlr53-1/michell.htm">Fulltext</a></h3></center>

There is an emerging doctrine in the law of restitution that taxes paid under an unlawful statute may be
recovered as of right.  The Supreme Court of Canada has been reluctant to fully accept this principle, however.  In <cite>Air Canada v. British Columbia</cite>, and in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines v. British Columbia</cite>, the Court accepted a `passing on' defence.  The defence allows public authorities to argue that any enrichment they received in the form of taxes did not come at the expense of the taxpayer, because it `passed on' the cost of taxes so paid to its customers.  More recently, lower courts have disagreed over the proper scope of the `passing on' defence.  The author argues that the `passing on' defence should not be accepted, because it is inconsistent with the law of unjust enrichment, it reduces the ability of commercial taxpayers to recover tax payments from public authorities, thus undermining important constitutional principles, and it is economically misconceived.  The better approach is to refuse the `passing on' defence, but in some cases to require a commercial taxpayer to hold any moneys recovered on constructive trust for those of its customers who paid the tax.
<p>
Une tendance &eacute;merge dans le droit de la restitution selon laquelle les taxes acquitt&eacute;es en vertu d'une loi ill&eacute;gitime peuvent &ecirc;tre r&eacute;cup&eacute;r&eacute;es &agrave; titre de droit.  La Cour supr&ecirc;me du Canada a tout de m&ecirc;me h&eacute;sit&eacute; &agrave; accepter compl&eacute;tement ce principe.  Dans les arr&ecirc;ts <cite>Air Canada c. Colombie-Britannique</cite> et <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines c. Colombie-Britannique</cite>, la Cour a accept&eacute; une d&eacute;fense selon laquelle l'enrichissement dont a b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute; le gouvernement s'est fait au d&eacute;triment de tiers parties et non au d&eacute;triment des plaignants.  Ce moyen de d&eacute;fense permet aux autorit&eacute;s publiques de soutenir que tout enrichissement re&ccedil;u sous la forme d'une taxe n'&eacute;tait pas aux d&eacute;pens du contribuable, puisque ce dernier a fait supporter le fardeau des taxes ainsi acquitt&eacute;es &agrave; ses clients. R&eacute;cemment, les juridictions inf&eacute;rieures se trouvaient en d&eacute;saccord sur le domaine d'application de ce moyen de d&eacute;fense. L'auteur soutient que cette d&eacute;fense ne devrait pas &ecirc;tre accept&eacute;e, car elle est incompatible avec le droit de l'enrichissement injustifi&eacute;; elle diminue la capacit&eacute; des contribuables commerciaux de r&eacute;cup&eacute;rer des autorit&eacute;s les taxes pay&eacute;es, minant ainsi certains principes constitutionnels importants.  De plus, elle serait mal con&ccedil;ue du point de vue &eacute;conomique.  La meilleure approche est de rejeter ce moyen de d&eacute;fense, et d'exiger dans certains cas d'un contribuable commercial qu'il garde toute somme re&ccedil;ue en fiducie par interpr&eacute;tation pour les clients qui ont acquitt&eacute; la taxe.
<p>
