<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review Vol. 53 No. 1</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v53n1.htm">Volume 53 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Restitution, `Passing On,' and the Recovery of Unlawfully Demanded Taxes: Why <b>Air Canada</b> Doesn't Fly<p>
PAUL MICHELL<sup><a href="#note">*</a></sup>
</h1>
<i>There is an emerging doctrine in the law of restitution that taxes paid under an unlawful statute may be
recovered as of right. The Supreme Court of Canada has been reluctant to fully accept this principle, however. In </i>Air Canada v. British Columbia<i>, and in </i>Canadian Pacific Airlines v. British Columbia<i>, the Court accepted a `passing on' defence. The defence allows public authorities to argue that any enrichment they received in the form of taxes did not come at the expense of the taxpayer, because it `passed on' the cost of taxes so paid to its customers. More recently, lower courts have disagreed over the proper scope of the `passing on' defence. The author argues that the `passing on' defence should not be accepted, because it is inconsistent with the law of unjust enrichment, it reduces the ability of commercial taxpayers to recover tax payments from public authorities, thus undermining important constitutional principles, and it is economically misconceived. The better approach is to refuse the `passing on' defence, but in some cases to require a commercial taxpayer to hold any moneys recovered on constructive trust for those of its customers who paid the tax.
<p>
Une tendance &eacute;merge dans le droit de la restitution selon laquelle les taxes acquitt&eacute;es en vertu d'une loi ill&eacute;gitime peuvent &ecirc;tre r&eacute;cup&eacute;r&eacute;es &agrave; titre de droit. La Cour supr&ecirc;me du Canada a tout de m&ecirc;me h&eacute;sit&eacute; &agrave; accepter compl&eacute;tement ce principe. Dans les arr&ecirc;ts </i>Air Canada c. Colombie-Britannique<i> et </i>Canadian Pacific Airlines c. Colombie-Britannique<i>, la Cour a accept&eacute; une d&eacute;fense selon laquelle l'enrichissement dont a b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute; le gouvernement s'est fait au d&eacute;triment de tiers parties et non au d&eacute;triment des plaignants. Ce moyen de d&eacute;fense permet aux autorit&eacute;s publiques de soutenir que tout enrichissement re&ccedil;u sous la forme d'une taxe n'&eacute;tait pas aux d&eacute;pens du contribuable, puisque ce dernier a fait supporter le fardeau des taxes ainsi acquitt&eacute;es &agrave; ses clients. R&eacute;cemment, les juridictions inf&eacute;rieures se trouvaient en d&eacute;saccord sur le domaine d'application de ce moyen de d&eacute;fense. L'auteur soutient que cette d&eacute;fense ne devrait pas &ecirc;tre accept&eacute;e, car elle est incompatible avec le droit de l'enrichissement injustifi&eacute;; elle diminue la capacit&eacute; des contribuables commerciaux de r&eacute;cup&eacute;rer des autorit&eacute;s les taxes pay&eacute;es, minant ainsi certains principes constitutionnels importants. De plus, elle serait mal con&ccedil;ue du point de vue &eacute;conomique. La meilleure approche est de rejeter ce moyen de d&eacute;fense, et d'exiger dans certains cas d'un contribuable commercial qu'il garde toute somme re&ccedil;ue en fiducie par interpr&eacute;tation pour les clients qui ont acquitt&eacute; la taxe.</i>
<p>
<h3>1. Introduction</h3>

The legal framework regulating the recovery of taxes paid under an unlawful statute has recently undergone a major upheaval. The main thrust of these developments has been welcome: there is an emerging rule mandating the recovery of taxes paid under an unlawful statute. Yet there is concern that this nascent rule will be undermined by the ill-considered adoption of particular defences to such claims for recovery. The taxpayer's suit against the government is an important testing ground for the general principle of unjust enrichment<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> The subject has been under discussion for decades in Canada.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> Regrettably, the considerable optimism which has accompanied the more general development of the law of restitution in Canada must be dimmed on this point. The Canadian law with regard to the
recovery of taxes paid under an unlawful statute is unsatisfactory, due in large measure to the Supreme Court of Canada's ambiguous acceptance of the `passing on' defence.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup>
<p>
According to its adherents, the `passing on' defence may be advanced by a public authority when sued by a taxpayer in unjust enrichment. In the paradigm case, the plaintiff is a firm which has made tax payments to a government. The legal authority requiring such payments is later declared to be unlawful (that is, <i>ultra vires</i>, unconstitutional, or misapplied).<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> The plaintiff then brings a suit seeking
restitution of its money. The public authority argues that it would not be unjust for it to retain the tax payments because although the plaintiff paid the taxes, it `passed on' the cost of doing so to its customers in the form of higher prices. It is argued that it would be unjust to order the return of the taxes to a plaintiff who has recovered fully from its customers. In effect, the plaintiff would be awarded a windfall. At first blush, the defence may carry some
intuitive appeal. This initial impression must be resisted. More careful analysis demonstrates that in most instances the `passing on' defence should not be recognized for three reasons. First, the `passing on' defence is founded on a misunderstanding as to the nature of the unjust enrichment principle. Second, an uncritical acceptance of the `passing on' defence threatens the courts' acceptance of a broader constitutional principle requiring public
authorities to return tax payments collected without lawful authority. Finally, the `passing on' defence is based on unsound economic reasoning. The `passing on' defence is bad law and unsound policy.
<p>
An explanation of the problem cannot be divorced from an account of more general developments in the law of restitution. After much temporizing,<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> the common law world has now largely accepted that unjust enrichment forms a unified category of civil obligation distinct from tort and contract.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> Canadian<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> and Australian<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> courts played a vanguard role in the assertion of a general principle of unjust enrichment, and there can be no doubt that unjust enrichment is now recognized as a principle in Canadian law.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> For the most part, Canadian courts make use of a broad conceptual framework so that the
law of restitution may unfold in an ordered and incremental fashion.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> The danger is that the law governing the recovery of unlawfully collected taxes is out of step with more general developments in the law of restitution. In the past three years, there have been rapid developments in the law of restitution in England, with the belated judicial recognition of a general principle of unjust enrichment.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> The English law, after years of denial, has now vaulted ahead of the Canadian law.
<p>
In a landmark decision, <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite>,<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></cite> the House of Lords established a general right to restitution of taxation payments made to a public authority under <i>ultra vires</i> regulations.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> A building society (&quot;Woolwich&quot;) had made a tax payment of almost $57 million to the Revenue under protest. Woolwich argued that the demand for the payment was <i>ultra vires</i> and thus void. Woolwich sought judicial review of the tax regulations, and it was determined by the House of Lords that the regulations had been <i>ultra  vires</i>.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> The Revenue then decided to return the full amount of tax which had been paid. However, the Revenue argued that this repayment had been made at its discretion alone, that Woolwich had no right to this repayment, and resisted paying interest on the $57 million. Woolwich brought an action in unjust enrichment in order to establish that it had a right to repayment of the taxes, so that the Court could award interest on the money (which amounted to some $6,730,000) in addition to the return of the initial sum. The majority of the House of Lords upheld the decision of the Court of Appeal that Woolwich was entitled to recover the tax payment as of right, and thus, with interest.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup>
<p>
<cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite> is a revolutionary decision, remarkable for its ambition and refreshing in its willingness to advance the common law.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> It reversed a century of equivocal jurisprudence which had muddied a formerly clear constitutional prohibition<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> against taxation without legal authority.<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> A recent English case has embraced this rule,<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> and its importance for constitutional and administrative law has been recognized.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> Unfortunately,
Canadian courts have as yet been unwilling to adopt the principle advanced in <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup>   Nevertheless, the decision has met with general
favour from legal academics,<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> and it will provide a strong impetus for the Supreme Court of Canada to reconsider the scope of restitution against public authorities for tax payments made
under an unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i> statute. The logic of <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite> is compelling, and it is both desirable and necessary that the Supreme Court of Canada
revisit the issue in light of that decision. Indeed, <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite> calls into question the correctness of its recently stated views.
<p>
Despite the Supreme Court of Canada's clouded exposition of the right to restitution for tax payments unlawfully collected, there is no question that unjust enrichment as a general principle has a solid grounding in Anglo-Canadian law. In recent years, the structure of the law of restitution has changed dramatically. The shift has been from a system which places limits upon the forms of action which will lead to a successful restitutionary claim towards a structure in which a broad general principle of unjust enrichment is limited by various defences.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> Courts have always harboured a concern about encouraging too much restitution. Formerly, they were content to allow the forms of action themselves to limit the scope of restitutionary claims. Now, it is the defences to the general principle which must limit restitutionary liability, and it is the defences which will become the focus of litigation over the coming years. This is why the need for courts to delineate the extent of
defences to the general principle of unjust enrichment has become so pressing. These defences include change of position,<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> estoppel,<sup><a href  = "#twenty5">25</a></sup>
limitation,<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> bona fide purchase,<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> and illegality,<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> among others.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> Not surprisingly, the `passing on' defence has received only limited attention, given that the right to recover taxes paid under an unlawful statute has only begun to emerge.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup>
<p>
Until only recently, English cases discussed the `passing on' defence only in <i>dicta</i>,<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> although a version of the defence is recognized by statute in England.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> More recently, the `passing on' defence was considered and rejected in England in the context of the `swaps' litigation.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> In <cite>Kleinwort Benson</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> the plaintiff merchant bank had entered into
several interest-rate swaps agreements with the defendant Council. Trouble arose when the Divisional Court (and later the Court of Appeal and the House of Lords) determined that swaps contracts were <i>ultra vires</i> local councils.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> Four of the five swaps contracts were incomplete at the time of this determination. However, under the incomplete contracts, the plaintiffs had advanced funds to the defendants, and the plaintiffs had not received an equivalent amount in return from the defendants at the time that the contracts were declared void. The plaintiffs brought an action in restitution for recovery of the difference between what they had advanced to the Council and what they had received.
<p>
The Council attempted to advance a defence of `passing on.' Essentially, it argued that as the plaintiffs had hedged their liability under the relevant contracts, they had succeeded in recouping from third parties any losses they might have suffered from the failure of the swaps contracts with the Council, and thus any enrichment enjoyed by the Council had not come at the plaintiffs' expense. Hobhouse J. unequivocally rejected the Council's argument:
<blockquote>
What contracts or other transactions or engagements the plaintiffs may have entered into with third parties have nothing to do with the principle of restitution. Therefore it suffices in the present case for the plaintiffs to show that they were the payors of the relevant money, that the defendants were unjustly enriched by the payments and that there is no obstacle to restitution.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It is submitted that this is the proper course for Canadian law to follow. Hobhouse J. noted, however, that in the context of taxation, different considerations might apply. In my view, the approach which Hobhouse J. applied to the question of recovery of moneys paid under a void contract is equally applicable to the recovery of moneys paid under an invalid tax.
<p>
The `passing on' defence was similarly rejected in Australia by Windeyer J. in <cite>Mason v. New South Wales</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> In that case, the High Court of Australia allowed the recovery of licence fees exacted from road carriers under an <i>ultra vires</i> statute. Windeyer J. dismissed
the State's attempt to mount a `passing on' defence by showing that the plaintiffs had `passed on' the expense of permits to their customers. To the contrary, his understanding was that the law of unjust enrichment does not require the plaintiff to demonstrate that he has suffered a deprivation which mirrors the defendant's enrichment. On this account, it is immaterial to the restitutionary action against the public authority whether the plaintiff may have
`passed on' to his customers the expense of a tax imposed on him.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> More recently, however, there have been signs that the `passing on' defence may have found favour in Australia.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> It will be seen, then, that the issue is in a state of flux.
<p>
The `passing on' defence figured prominently in two decisions of the Supreme Court of Canada, <cite>Air Canada</cite><sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> Its availability is intimately linked with the ability of taxpayers to recover tax payments made to public authorities under a mistake of fact or law. For reasons set out below, it is my view that the majority judgment in <cite>Air Canada</cite> erred in admitting the `passing on' defence in that case, whereas in  <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, the Court was correct in implicitly rejecting the defence on the one hand, but allowing it to be advanced on the other. The confusion which has resulted stems directly from the Supreme Court's inconsistent approach to the defence. The recent decision of the British Columbia Court of Appeal in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite><sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> is indicative of the uncertainty which the combination of <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> has engendered. In my view, the Court of Appeal in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> erroneously allowed the `passing on' defence to be raised in that case. The better approach was expressed by Oliver J. at trial in the British Columbia Supreme
Court,<sup><a href="forty3">43</a></sup> where the proper test was applied and the `passing on' defence
rejected.
<p>
This article begins, in Sections Two and Three, with a discussion of the major Canadian cases on the `passing on' defence (<cite>Air Canada</cite>, <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, and <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite>). It then outlines, in Sections Four and Five, a legal and economic model of the `passing on' defence in order to demonstrate that the current law is unsatisfactory. Sections Six and Seven consider the European and American experiences with the `passing on' defence, with a view to extracting principles to guide
the development of the law in Canada. In Sections Eight and Nine, these principles are applied to a model for the application of the `passing on' defence. Some brief conclusions are set out in Section Ten.
<p>
<h3>2.  The Canadian `Passing on' Rule: <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite></h3>

The leading Canadian case concerning the `passing on' defence is the complicated decision in <cite>Air Canada</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> Three airlines brought an action for restitution of
gasoline taxation payments made between 1974 and 1976 to the government of British Columbia under a provincial statute<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> which was subsequently held to be unconstitutional because it mandated indirect taxation.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> The <cite>Act</cite> was amended in 1976 in an effort to correct its perceived deficiencies. However, in 1981, legislation was passed purporting both to apply the 1976 changes retroactively to the 1974--1976 period, as well as to confiscate the taxes which had been paid during that period. Three issues were presented for the Supreme Court's consideration. First, was the original  <cite>Gasoline Tax Act</cite> constitutionally valid as imposing a direct tax within the province?  Second, if the <cite>Gasoline Tax Act</cite> was <i>ultra vires</i> the Province, could the 1981 legislation retroactively impose the tax as well as permit the retention of the payments which had been made under the old invalid legislation?
Finally, could the tax paid under an <i>ultra vires</i> statute be recovered by the taxpayers, apart from statute?
<p>
All of the judges agreed that the original (pre-1976) <cite>Gasoline Tax Act</cite> provisions were <i>ultra vires</i> the province. They also agreed that the 1976 legislation remedied the deficiencies of the original legislation. Finally, all agreed that the province possessed the authority to impose a tax with retroactive application.
The disagreement arose over the province's ability to use the 1981 legislation to confiscate the taxes which had been paid between 1974 and 1976 under the invalid pre-1976 legislation. Beetz and McIntyre JJ. held that the 1981 legislation was valid in its entirety, and denied recovery to the airlines on this basis, so they did not express an opinion on the third issue. They agreed, however, that if necessary, they would have adopted La Forest J.'s views on the rule as to the recovery of taxes paid under an <i>ultra vires</i> statute. La Forest J. (with whom Lamer and L'Heureux-Dub&eacute; JJ. concurred) wrote the leading judgment. For him, the real question in the case
was whether the 1981 legislation was <i>ultra vires</i> because its confiscatory provisions coloured its retroactive taxing provisions, with the result that the entire enterprise was invalid. His view was that the confiscatory provision, while clumsy, was merely the Province's chosen method of putting into effect the retroactive tax
provisions. The fact that the amount owing under the retroactive provisions was identical to the amount confiscated did not give him cause for concern.
<p>
Having answered the second question in the affirmative, five of the six judges (Wilson J. dissenting) decided the case on the basis that the 1981 legislation was valid and thus denied recovery to the airlines. However, La Forest J. went on to consider a framework to deal with the third issue, namely the rules to regulate the recovery of taxes paid under an unlawful statute. It should be noted that these views are technically <i>obiter dicta</i>, but are important
because the issues involved were considered at some length. La Forest J. held that as a general rule, money paid under mistake of law should be recoverable.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> In so doing, he adopted the minority position of Dickson J. (as he then was) in <cite>Hydro-Electric Commission of the Township of Nepean v. Ontario Hydro</cite>, which had strongly criticized the distinction between mistake of law and mistake of fact as a basis for regulating recovery.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> <cite>Air Canada</cite> has been discussed elsewhere primarily for its rejection of this distinction, and the accompanying rule barring recovery for payments made under a mistake of law.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> But as we shall see, it is an open question whether in eliminating the mistake of fact/mistake of law distinction on the one
hand, La Forest J. resurrected it with the other. This question arises because La Forest J. also held that there were certain exceptions to this general principle which should apply here to deny recovery of the tax payments by the plaintiff airlines.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> Two special policy considerations, namely the `passing on' defence, and the potential disruption to the public finances which might be caused by repayment,<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> precluded recovery of the taxation payments, even though the statute in question was admittedly unconstitutional.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
<p>
While La Forest J. had no doubt that British Columbia had been enriched by receipt of the taxes, he considered the question of whether the province had been enriched <i>at the expense of the plaintiff airlines</i> to be of central importance. He accepted British Columbia's argument that the airlines had been able to `pass on' the tax to their passengers, such that the province's enrichment came at the expense of the passengers, and not the airlines themselves. La Forest J. did not deny that an action in restitution might still lie against British Columbia, only that it could not be brought by these particular plaintiffs (namely, the airlines). It may be inferred that `passing on' does not provide the defendant public authority with a general defence: it asserts only that the enrichment came at the expense of a third party, namely the plaintiff's customers. 
<p>
For their part, the airlines argued that the `passing on' defence could apply only when the tax had been explicitly charged by the airlines to their passengers, ``so as to make those parties [the passengers] the true taxpayers.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> The mere fact that the airlines had attempted to recover the cost of the tax from their passengers should not bar the airlines' recovery of the tax payments from the province.
The airlines advanced an economic argument, which is examined in some detail below:<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> that as they were forced to raise the ticket prices charged to passengers in order to cover the cost of the gasoline tax, their sales revenues were likely adversely affected, which would in turn result in decreased profits. Although this is not, strictly speaking, a restitutionary argument---it is more properly a claim in tort---it does reveal that the allegation that the airlines could simply `pass on' the cost of taxes to their customers without suffering adverse effects themselves is misconceived.
<p>
In outlining the `passing on' defence, La Forest J. turned to the American experience for assistance. He cited with approval a passage from Professor George Palmer's <cite>The Law of Restitution</cite> to the effect that unless it could be demonstrated that the burden of a tax had not been shifted to others, then &quot;it seems preferable to leave the enrichment with the tax authority instead of putting the judicial machinery in motion for the purpose of shifting the same enrichment to the taxpayer.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> In my view, this is an argument of convenience, not one of principle. Certainly, it may be difficult and complicated to determine who has
borne the expense of the government's unjust enrichment. Yet it should not follow from this that the government is entitled to retain the enrichment. An unjust enrichment must be disgorged if there is no valid juridical reason why it should be retained.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> Furthermore, it is unclear why the complexity of the economic consequences of asserting a `passing on' defence should fall in favour of the defendant public authority, who is, after all, the party advancing the defence. It seems more appropriate, if the defence is to be allowed at all, that the burden of asserting it should fall upon the defendant. La Forest J. held that if it were necessary, he would have allowed the defence of `passing on' to be advanced in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, as the airlines had, on the evidence, `passed on' the burden of the tax to their passengers. But as I discuss below,<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> this is of course what all firms must do: `pass on' the cost of their inputs (as much as possible) to their consumers. La Forest J. concluded his analysis of the `passing on' defence by stating that &quot;[t]he law of restitution is not intended to provide windfalls to plaintiffs who have suffered no  loss.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> Yet an examination of the economic difficulties associated with `passing on' of a tax by a firm to its customers demonstrates that this conclusion is wrong on two counts. First, it is very likely that the plaintiffs in <cite>Air Canada</cite> did suffer a loss. Second, the view misconceives what a `loss' is in restitution. There can be no question but that the airlines paid the tax to the government. 
<p>
Brief mention must also be made of the second basis upon which La Forest J. denied recovery to the airlines in <cite>Air Canada</cite>. He stated that even if the airlines had been able to demonstrate that they had borne the burden of the tax, he would still have denied recovery. Indeed, La Forest J. indicated that this second basis
would have been the ground upon which he would have dismissed the airlines' action. Since <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite> seriously undermines this second ground (to say nothing of the main ground of decision in <cite>Air Canada</cite>), however, `passing on' may remain as the sole ground of decision in <cite>Air Canada</cite>. La Forest J. raised the familiar concern that it might be severely disruptive to public finances to require a public authority to repay moneys received under a tax statute which was subsequently found to be
illegaL.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> A brief survey of the experience of other jurisdictions lent support
to his argument that ``there are solid grounds of public policy for not according a general right of recovery in these circumstances, and ... this prohibition exists quite independently of the law of restitution.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup>
<p>
While there has been some debate on this point,<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> in my view, this argument is unconvincing as a general proposition.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> There may of course be some cases in which the amount of money at issue would be so large that to require restitution would cause a crisis in the public finances.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> But most cases are unlikely to be of this sort, so that a blanket prohibition upon recovery is inappropriate. The particular circumstances of each case, taking into account factors such as the amount of money at stake, the size and resources of the public authority, the nature of the tax regime, and the public authority's ability to raise funds, must all be considered. One must also ask why public authorities should be treated any differently from private individuals in this regard.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> There are many instances where <i>A</i> has been unjustly enriched at the expense of  <i>B</i> and a large sum of money is at stake. In such cases, it will often be onerous to require <i>A</i> to return the money to <i>B</i>. Yet in the absence of a valid defence, it must be returned. 
<p>
Of course, private defendants have the defence of `change of position' available to them, and public authorities may also be able to advance this defence.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup> The burden of proof rests with the defendant, however, and it seems unlikely that a public authority---perhaps with the exception of a small public authority, such as a municipal council<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> ---would be able to discharge this
burden.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup>  Professor Beatson views this as a reason why there
should be some sort of rule granting special protection for public authorities against actions in restitution.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> The Law Commission has taken a similar view.<sup><a href =  "#sixty9">69</a></sup> On the other hand, it may be argued that if there is to be a different rule for public authorities than for private individuals, rule of law considerations suggest that the former should be held to a stricter standard of conduct, not a lesser one.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> Clearly, there may be some limits placed upon the ability of taxpayers to recover in actions for unjust enrichment from public bodies.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> Defences must not become so broad that they undermine the integrity of the underlying cause of action, and thus amount to crude barriers which prevent recovery in standard cases. In my view, there is little to recommend a blanket `disruption of public finances' rule to limit recovery against public authorities.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> It may be that legislatures will think it essential that for particular taxes, there should be a statutory framework to regulate recovery. And indeed, the constitutional considerations outlined in <cite>Amax Potash</cite> suggest that provinces would be prudent to enact statutory regimes to regulate the recovery of taxes.<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> But in the absence of such a
framework, the presumption must be one of recovery as of right.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> Any legislation which derogates from this common law standard must do so specifically. 
<p>
Thus, La Forest J. was of the view that where taxes are paid under legislation which is later determined to have been unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i>, there is a policy rule against recovery. Conversely, where the tax payment has been received due to the misapplication of an otherwise valid statute or regulation, the general principles of restitution should apply. This distinction is made largely with an eye to the potential magnitude of repayment which might arise under the respective situations. It is unlikely that a large amount of money could be collected through the consistent misapplication of an otherwise valid statute, so recovery would be allowed in such situations. By way of comparison, it seems possible that money could be collected under a tax statute for years before it was determined that the statute in question was unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i>. The problem with La Forest
J.'s approach is that it resuscitates the mistake of fact/mistake of law distinction which <cite>Air Canada</cite> itself purports to lay to rest.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> Where a statute is deemed to be valid but misapplied, there has likely been a mistake of fact involving a single taxpayer or a small group of taxpayers. Under La Forest J.'s rule, recovery is permitted in such circumstances. Where taxes are found to have been collected
under a statute which is subsequently determined to have been unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i>, however, there is likely to have been a mistake of law. Yet La Forest J.'s rule would preclude recovery in such circumstances. The rule's sole purpose is to exclude the possibility of fiscal disruption for public authorities, no matter how remote. As Maddaugh and McCamus note, &quot;The more severe the legislator's error, the less likely it is that the taxpayer will recover.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> This result is highly unsatisfactory. As we have seen, there are other methods by which legislatures can ensure that their finances are not disrupted. The rule against recovery in the case of <i>ultra vires</i> or unconstitutional statutes amounts to the rebirth of the mistake of law/mistake of fact distinction, with all of its unfairness and arbitrary results. It severely undercuts any general
right of recovery.
<p>
Wilson J.'s dissent in <cite>Air Canada</cite> provides the basis for a more principled way to regulate the recovery of payments made under an unlawful statute. She agreed that the <cite>Gasoline Tax Act</cite> was <i>ultra vires</i> the Province in 1974 and remained so until corrected by the 1976 amendments, after which the <cite>Act</cite> was <i>intra vires</i> the Province. But she departed from the majority by objecting to the constitutionality of the 1981 legislation, which in her view imposed a retroactive tax to cover the 1974--1976 period
in order to confiscate the payments which had been made under the original unconstitutional version of the <cite>Act</cite>. Wilson J. believed this to be a colourable attempt on the part of the Province &quot;to achieve indirectly what it could not achieve directly, namely the imposition of an <i>ultra vires</i>  tax,&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> in direct contradiction to the <cite>Amax Potash</cite> principle.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> It was not the retroactive application of the tax which aroused her ire, but the combined effect of the retroactive tax with the confiscatory provision which indicated that the 1981 legislation was merely an
attempt to give legal effect to an unconstitutional statute.
<p>
Wilson J. was less concerned than La Forest J. with removing the rule against recovery for payments made under a mistake of law, because she did not believe that the plaintiffs' right to recovery was based upon this ground. In her view, the mistake of law doctrine should apply only to mistaken payments made under &quot;perfectly valid legislation,&quot; but not here, where payments were made under unconstitutional legislation &quot;quite properly presumed by the taxpayer to be constitutional.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> The unjust factor, on her account, was the very fact that the legislation was unlawful. Wilson J. would have allowed recovery for all payments made under a legally invalid tax provision. Not surprisingly, she refused to adopt La Forest J.'s broad exceptions to this general principle of recovery, which in her view undermined the integrity of the general principle. She held that governments should not be put in a privileged position as compared with private litigants: there should be no exception for public authorities to the general right to recovery. A `fiscal chaos' defence would place the burden of the government's errors upon individual taxpayers, which would be particularly inappropriate, because in most cases taxpayers make payments in the innocent belief that government demands have a legal foundation. The better approach would be to spread the cost of repaying the taxes across all taxpayers. She did not accept La Forest J.'s distinction between recovery for misapplied but otherwise valid legislation and recovery where the statute was <i>ultra vires</i> or unconstitutionaL.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup>
<p>
Wilson J. also rejected La Forest J.'s application of the `passing on' defence. She disputed the majority's claim that to allow recovery of the taxes would amount to a &quot;windfall&quot; for the airlines, even if the airlines had `passed on' the cost of the taxes to their customers. In response to La Forest J.'s assertion that the plaintiffs had been unable to show that the unjust enrichment was at their expense as opposed to that of their customers, she stated:
<blockquote>
In my view, there is no requirement that they be able to do so. Where the payments were made pursuant to an unconstitutional statute there is no legitimate basis on which they can be retained.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup>
</blockquote>
To allow the provincial legislature to retain the tax payments would be, according to Wilson J., to sanction the use of unlawful taxation statutes. Commentators for the most part suggest that Wilson J. got the better of this exchange.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> 
<p>
On the same day that judgment was handed down in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada decided a companion case, <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> In that case, the plaintiff airlines sought to recover social service tax<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> wrongly paid on aircraft parts and equipment. One of the plaintiffs (&quot;Air Canada&quot;) also sought recovery of social service tax paid on alcoholic beverages sold to passengers in flight. The social service tax was imposed as a percentage of the purchase price on the sale of tangible personal property within the province. The legislation deemed the airlines to be agents of the Minister for the purposes of collecting the tax from the airlines' customers. The Court held that the social service tax did not apply to the airlines' aircraft and parts, and that they could recover the tax payments made under the statute on the aircraft parts and equipment. The Court also held that the social service tax could not apply to alcoholic beverages consumed in flight. Nevertheless, it denied recovery of these latter tax payments on the basis that the tax had been imposed upon the passengers who had consumed the beverages, and not upon the airline.<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> Even Wilson J., who had strongly
dissented in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, accepted La Forest J.'s view on this point in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>. She distinguished this case from <cite>Air Canada</cite> on the basis that in the latter case, the
tax was imposed on the airlines, whereas here the tax on the sale of alcoholic beverages was imposed on the passengers themselves.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup>
<p>
Some degree of uncertainty has now arisen as to what the law is regarding the `passing on' defence. <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> appear to come to opposite conclusions. Recovery would have been precluded on the basis of `passing on' in <cite>Air Canada</cite>. Yet in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, `passing on' seemed to apply to the social service tax on alcoholic beverages, but not to the aircraft parts and equipment. The distinction between the two cases (and the two taxes in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>) is not immediately apparent. As the next section indicates, the confusion resulting from the Supreme Court's misapplication of the `passing on' defence has been reflected by conflicting interpretations of the defence in the lower courts.
<p>
<h3>3.  Confusion Reigns: The Progeny of <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite></h3>

<cite>Air Canada</cite> has been interpreted by the lower courts to stand for the proposition that the recovery of taxes paid under a mistake of law should as a general rule be governed by the law of restitution.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup> Attempts to reconcile <cite>Air Canada</cite> with <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> have proven intractable, however. This difficulty is demonstrated by a recent decision, <cite>Allied Air Conditioning Inc. v. British Columbia</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> in which the British Columbia Court of Appeal reversed the earlier judgment of the British Columbia Supreme  Court.<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> A group of air conditioning and heat pump contractors brought an action in unjust enrichment against the Province of British Columbia for recovery of social service tax payments which the plaintiffs alleged were wrongfully collected.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> The same statute, it will be recalled, was the subject of litigation in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>. The contractors had replied to private tenders for construction projects with lump sum bids to install air conditioning and heat pump equipment. The prices submitted in these lump sum bids included all labour, equipment, and applicable taxes, including the provincial social service tax. The invoices sent by the plaintiffs to their customers did not set out the amount of tax paid by the plaintiffs on each contract. 
<p>
Both parties agreed that the plaintiffs had paid taxes due to a misapplication of the <cite>Social Service Tax Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> While the <cite>Act</cite> was not <i>ultra vires</i> the
province's legislative powers, it had been mistakenly applied to the transactions in question.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> As a `misapplied but otherwise valid statute' case, and not an `unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i> statute' case, the `fiscal chaos' policy rule from <cite>Air Canada</cite> could not apply to preclude recovery. The issue was whether the tax payments made under the <cite>Act</cite> were recoverable. British Columbia argued that although it may have been unjustly enriched by the payments, it was not unjustly enriched <i>at the expense of the contractors</i>. Oliver J. noted that in <cite>Air Canada</cite> the airlines' claim had been rejected because the airlines had not demonstrated that the province's unjust enrichment had been at their expense, as opposed to at the expense of their customers: &quot;The airline [sic] recovered the expense of the tax by passing it on to its customers and thus could not claim to have been deprived.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup>
<p>
British Columbia argued that the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Air Canada</cite> had set out two propositions. First, it had rejected the airlines' argument that the `passing on' defence should be available
only where the tax has been specifically charged to other identified parties so as to make those parties the true taxpayers. Second, it affirmed that the onus is on the taxpayer to demonstrate that it actually bore the burden of the tax. The fact that the taxpayer had nominally paid the tax is insufficient evidence alone to prove the second restitutionary requirement of a deprivation. Thus, British Columbia argued that the `passing on' defence is available to a public authority whenever the taxpayer does not displace the presumption that it has `passed on' the tax burden to its customers. Moreover, the `passing on' defence applies whether or not the tax was `passed on' directly and specifically to customers as a separate charge, or was included in the general price charged to the plaintiffs' customers.
<p>
Not surprisingly, the contractors rejected this interpretation of <cite>Air Canada</cite>. They argued that <cite>Air Canada</cite> must be viewed in conjunction with <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> in order to properly understand the Supreme Court of Canada's view of the `passing on' defence. The contractors suggested that in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, the Supreme Court had implicitly accepted that the distinction between different forms of taxation was relevant for the `passing on' defence. Taxes directly and specifically `passed on' to customers (such as the tax on alcoholic beverages) should not be recoverable by the firm, whereas taxes not directly and specifically `passed on' (such as the tax on aircraft parts and equipment) should be recoverable. By allowing recovery of the taxes paid for the aircraft parts and equipment, the Supreme Court must have rejected the application of the `passing on' defence to that part of the airline's claim. The taxes were not `passed on' to the
airline's customers directly and specifically, but instead were included along with other costs in the general price charged to consumers. The contractors in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> argued that the tax imposed upon their contracts was analogous to the tax upon aircraft parts and equipment in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>
(indeed, both cases concerned the social service tax), and thus that it was recoverable.
<p>
Oliver J. accepted the contractors' interpretation of the `passing on' case law, stating that: 
<blockquote>
the requirements of unjust enrichment are satisfied where the taxpayer can show that it has not `specifically and directly' passed on the burden of tax to its customers. Only where such tax expense has been directly passed on to the customers, making them the `true taxpayers,' can the passing-on defence apply.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Applying this to the case at bar, Oliver J. ordered recovery of the tax payments from the province. The contractors had invoiced their customers for lump sum payments, so the contracts did not set out a separate sum indicating the amount of tax payable. In these circumstances, the Court held that the tax is not `passed on' to the taxpayers. 
<p>
Oliver J. also distinguished <cite>Air Canada</cite> from <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> on the basis that in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, the taxes were not payable because they were levied under an <i>ultra vires</i> or unconstitutional statute, whereas in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, the tax statute was valid, but had been erroneously applied to the airlines. Following La Forest J.'s rule in <cite>Air Canada</cite> (unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i> taxes are not recoverable in an action in unjust enrichment due to policy reasons &quot;quite independent of the law of restitution&quot;), Oliver J. allowed recovery here, because the statute had been misapplied to the heat pumps and air conditioning equipment. According to this theory, the `passing on' defence has potential application only in cases where the taxing statute is valid but mistakenly applied. The defence is
redundant where the tax statute is unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i>, as there can be no recovery due to `policy reasons' in such cases. If, as I have argued, La Forest J.'s distinction between unconstitutional/<i>ultra vires</i> tax statutes and misapplied tax statutes cannot be sustained, then the application of the `passing on' defence must be rethought. Indeed, one also wonders how comfortable the Supreme Court of Canada is with the <cite>Air Canada</cite> rule: it is intriguing that La Forest J. felt obliged to discuss the `passing on' defence in such detail in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, given that his decision ultimately did not rest upon it. Even if La Forest J. was correct on the unconstitutional/<i>ultra vires</i> point---and with respect, I do not accept that he was---he was surely in error on the `passing on' point.
<p>
The Court of Appeal reversed. Legg J.A. rejected Oliver J.'s interpretation of <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> which permitted the taxpayer to recover where it could demonstrate that the burden of the tax had been included generally in the price charged to customers, as opposed to being specifically and directly `passed on' through representation of the tax to customers as a separate charge. Legg J.A. interpreted La Forest J.'s decision in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> to hold that since the social service tax did not apply to the airlines' aircraft parts and equipment, and since the province could not resist recovery of the tax payments on the basis that the plaintiffs had made a mistake of law, the plaintiffs were entitled to recover the taxes erroneously paid on the aircraft parts and equipment. But Legg J.A. noted that &quot;[t]he decision does not explain how this result was reached.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> He held that <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> could be reconciled through a single interpretation: that in the latter case (at least with regard to the tax on aircraft parts and equipment), La Forest J. had found not only that the province was unjustly enriched, but that the airline had borne the burden of the enrichment. &quot;Given La Forest J.'s description in <cite>Air Canada</cite> of the exception to the general rule against recovery, these conclusions follow by necessary implication.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup>
<p>
Legg J.A. rejected Oliver J.'s view that the `passing on' defence is unavailable where the burden of the tax has not been directly and specifically `passed on' to the plaintiffs' customers, but instead has been included generally in the calculation of the price of goods or services sold to the customers. To the contrary, he held that &quot;[i]f a tax expense has been included generally in the calculation of the price to a customer, the tax has been `passed on' and the taxpayer has not shown that he has borne the burden of the tax.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> Furthermore, Legg J.A. interpreted La Forest J.'s judgment in <cite>Air Canada</cite> to place the onus on the plaintiffs to demonstrate that they, and not their customers, had borne the burden of the tax. On this test, the plaintiffs in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> had not discharged their onus. He thus held that the Province's appeal should be allowed, and that the trial court's order requiring restitution of the tax payments to the plaintiffs should be reversed.
<p>
Taylor J.A., with whom Proudfoot J.A. concurred, wrote a brief judgment concurring with that of Legg J.A. In his view, the main issue was whether the contractors had demonstrated that they had suffered a deprivation at the hands of the defendant province, or whether the deprivation had been `passed on' to the contractors' customers. He explained the result in <cite>Air Canada</cite> as having turned on the Supreme Court of Canada's determination that the airlines had `passed on' the fuel tax burden &quot;in the sense that the airline recovered it, as an operating cost, from its passengers.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> Taylor J.A. distinguished <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> on the basis that in that case, British Columbia had never advanced the `passing on' defence with regard to the tax payments on aircraft parts and equipment. Also, with respect to the tax on alcoholic beverages in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, the airline never actually paid the tax in question, but instead acted only as a collection agent for the province as required by statute. Taylor J.A. rejected the trial
judge's view that the tax in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> was more analogous to the tax on aircraft parts and equipment than to the tax on alcoholic beverages in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>.
<p>
While he reached the same result as Legg J.A., Taylor J.A. reconciled <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> on a different basis. He argued that the Supreme Court of Canada had allowed recovery for the taxes paid on aircraft parts and equipment in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>---and by implication rejected the application of the province's `passing on' defence---on the basis that aircraft parts and equipment were capital assets &quot;for the continuous use by the airline for the purpose of generating income.&quot; As such, taxes on these assets &quot;could not be said to be then `passed on' to passengers as part of their ticket  price.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup> This situation could be contrasted, not with the tax
on alcoholic beverages, which Taylor J.A. did not view as `passing on,' but instead with the fuel tax in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, the recovery of which the Supreme Court of Canada had denied to the airlines because it had been allegedly `passed on' to the airlines' passengers. The distinction was based on the fact that fuel is not a capital asset; instead, fuel costs are &quot;direct, or actual daily operating expenses&quot; recovered by passing them on to
customers.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> Taylor J.A. was of the view that <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> provided an even better example of the operation of the <cite>Air Canada</cite> rule than <cite>Air Canada</cite> itself. Here, the fact that the tax on air conditioning and heat pump equipment had been included in the calculation of bid prices demonstrated that the burden of the tax had been `passed on' to the plaintiff's consumers.
<p>
<cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> reveals the confused state of the Canadian version of the `passing on' doctrine. Legg J.A.'s approach is based on the same faulty economic premise (namely, that a tax may simply be shifted by a firm to its customers) which La Forest J. adopted in <cite>Air Canada</cite>. Moreover, <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> demonstrates how a `passing on' defence which places an onus upon the plaintiff to show that it has not `passed on' the economic burden of a tax to its customers will frustrate efforts to recover unlawfully collected taxes. Taylor J.A.'s attempts to explain <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> by distinguishing between taxes on capital assets and taxes on operating expenses is similarly unhelpful. The economic cost of taxes on capital assets is almost invariably shifted to consumers by inclusion
in the general price of a firm's goods or services, as opposed to representing a separate and distinct charge to customers. But the same may be said for many operating expenses as well, such as the taxes on aviation fuel in <cite>Air Canada</cite>. Oliver J.'s approach at trial to this question is the better one. 
<p>
The substantial disagreement over the proper interpretation of the `passing on' defence has been reflected in other recent Canadian decisions. In <cite>Sobeys</cite>,<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> a supermarket chain sought recovery of provincial sales tax which it had paid on butchering and fish processing equipment. It argued that the equipment was exempt from tax under the relevant provincial legislation, and was successful at trial. On appeal, the Nova Scotia Court of Appeal held that on the wording of the statute, the equipment was not exempt, and the Attorney General's appeal was allowed. Nonetheless, comments made by Jones J.A. in <i>obiter</i> suggest that had there been an exemption for the equipment, he would have allowed recovery of the taxes.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup> More recently, in <cite>Liquor Control Board of Ontario</cite>,<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> the Court held that the LCBO had been collecting liquor taxes from airlines to which it was not entitled and ordered repayment. The airlines sold liquor to their passengers at a loss because they believed that competitive pressures demanded it. There was no relationship between the price charged to passengers and the cost of the liquor to the airlines. The LCBO argued that the airlines had `passed on' the cost of the LCBO mark-ups and fees to their customers. Saunders J. held that the evidence was to the contrary:
<blockquote>
Ticket prices and charges for liquor are a function of competitive conditions and are entirely independent of the cost of liquor. The economic burden of the mark-up and fees was not shifted to the passengers.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In spite of such cases as <cite>Sobeys</cite> and <cite>Liquor Control Board of Ontario</cite>, the interpretation of the `passing on' defence set out by the Court of Appeal in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> seems to be predominant.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> In the following sections, I set out arguments demonstrating that the approach adopted by the Court of Appeal in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> is mistaken, and that this error stems directly from the manner in which the Supreme Court of Canada formulated the `passing on' defence in <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>. The essential error of the `passing on' defence is that it misconstrues the function of the law of restitution.
<p>
<h3>4.  `Passing on' and the Structure of Unjust Enrichment</h3>

An evaluation of the `passing on' defence must be based on an understanding of the basic principles of unjust enrichment. The general test for unjust enrichment in Canada was outlined by Dickson J. (as he then was) in <cite>Pettkus</cite>.<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> Three elements must be present in order to ground an action in unjust enrichment: an enrichment; a corresponding deprivation; and the ``absence of any juristic reason for the enrichment.&quot;  A valid defence to an action in unjust enrichment (other than a procedural defence, such as the invocation of a limitation period) must nullify one of these elements, such that defences may be usefully divided into three categories corresponding to the elements of the <cite>Pettkus</cite> test. One type of defence
refutes the assertion that the defendant gained an enrichment. A second type of defence stipulates that while the defendant may have gained an enrichment, it did not come at the expense of the plaintiff, so there is no &quot;corresponding deprivation.&quot;  The third type of defence goes to the &quot;unjust&quot; element of the equation, and suggests that there is a &quot;juristic reason&quot; for the enrichment, or alternatively, the lack of a juristic reason why the enrichment should now be disgorged.
<p>
The `passing on' defence arises in cases in which a public authority has been unjustly enriched at the expense of a taxpayer.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup> `Passing on' cannot arise in disputes between private parties.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> In <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite>, for example, the tax payments were made under the erroneous understanding that the <cite>Social Service Tax Act</cite> applied to the
transactions. The first requirement of the <cite>Pettkus</cite> test---that the defendant public authority must have been enriched---is generally made out with little difficulty. A tax payment is usually made in the form of money, which by definition cannot be &quot;subjectively devalued&quot;<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> by the defendant public authority. The defendant cannot claim that it has not been enriched by the receipt of money, because receipt of money <i>always</i> constitutes an enrichment. Instead, the `passing on' defence goes to
the second and third requirements of the <cite>Pettkus</cite> test. 
<p>
The main foundation for the `passing on' defence appears to be the concern that a plaintiff not be awarded a &quot;windfall.&quot;  This proposition can be divided into two related arguments. The first, which would appear to be related to the third element of the <cite>Pettkus</cite> test, is the concern that the plaintiff not be overcompensated by receiving repayment of taxes where it has suffered no loss. In <cite>Air Canada</cite>, for example, it is clear that La Forest J. believes that the airlines have suffered no loss. Yet as Professor Woodward notes, this analysis cannot provide an adequate explanation of the defence, because if it did, plaintiffs would be
compensated up to their demonstrated loss.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> Moreover, a concern about the so-called overcompensation of plaintiffs has not exerted much influence on the law of restitution. Several cases indicate that a plaintiff may recover from a defendant who has been unjustly enriched even where the plaintiff has suffered no demonstrable loss.<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup>
<p>
The second, stronger base for the defence is the argument that the plaintiff's customers were the real payers of the tax. As such, the real plaintiffs in the cases for the recovery of tax should be the customers, and not the firm, which is, in practice, only an intermediary. The issue, on this account, is not whether the government was unjustly enriched, but at whose expense the enrichment took place: the second branch of the <cite>Pettkus</cite> test. It would be inappropriate to take money belonging to customers from the government and award it to the plaintiff firm. This argument suggests that the `passing on' defence only postpones the government's day of reckoning. If the defence is upheld, the implication is that while the government has been enriched, it was not unjustly enriched <i>at the expense of this plaintiff</i>, because it has been demonstrated that <i>this plaintiff</i> did not pay the taxes in question. Thus, it would seem that the persons who <i>were</i> the bearers of the tax burden would be able to launch their own action in restitution against the public authority for repayment of the taxes. 
<p>
Put this way, the `passing on' defence seems uncontroversial. If the plaintiff did not actually make the taxation payments in question, why should a court require that the public authority disgorge the tax payments to this plaintiff?  While the defendant public authority has unquestionably been unjustly enriched, it may be even more unjust to order that the moneys be given to a plaintiff who seems not to have suffered a loss. But this simplicity is deceptive. The difficulty arises in the need to accurately define the scope of the `passing on' defence. This difficulty is compounded by the knowledge that when the plaintiff is a firm, its natural response is to view a tax
imposed on it as a cost of carrying on business. Much like any other tax payment made by a firm---for example, unemployment insurance premiums, payroll tax, municipal charges, and so on---the cost of a tax is spread out over the firm's customers through incorporation into the price of the firm's products or services. At first blush, it
would appear that a firm <i>never</i> bears the full burden of a tax, because the cost of any tax is `passed on' to the consumers of its products or services.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup> In England, the Law Commission has noted that in theory, the `passing on' defence could be raised in <i>any</i> action for restitution where the plaintiff has attempted to make up its loss by raising the prices which it charges to its customers.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> Yet to adopt so broad an approach is to misunderstand the principle of unjust enrichment.
<p>
Where a firm has made a tax payment to a public authority under an unlawful statute, and it sues for restitution of the payment, the court is caught between two compelling claims. On the one hand, it seems unjust that the government should retain a taxation payment to which it has no legal right. (That is, the retention is `unjust'
according to the law of restitution, although it is also unsound constitutional policy). To allow the `passing on' defence to be advanced would be to allow the government to retain the ill-gotten gains of taxation payments made to it under an unlawful statute. At the same time, courts are apprehensive about awarding &quot;windfalls&quot;
to plaintiffs who seem to have `passed on' the economic burden of the disputed tax to their customers. As between the government and a firm which may appear not to have borne the economic burden of a tax, courts may exhibit a reluctance to require the public authority to disgorge the tax payments. A court may take a dim view of a plaintiff who wants to recover tax payments for its own private benefit, as opposed to a public authority which may intend to spend the tax payments on the provision of public services. (Although it is by no means clear that the more responsible course is to leave the funds with the government). Faced with this dilemma, what should the
courts do?
<p>
The courts should narrowly circumscribe the application of the `passing on' defence. For three reasons, a public authority which has been enriched should be required to disgorge the tax payment. The primary reason is that on a proper theory of unjust enrichment, only a narrow interpretation of the `passing on' defence is supportable. This article is informed by a conception of the law of restitution as fundamentally concerned with the prevention of unjust enrichment.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> Unlike in tort, a plaintiff in an action in restitution need not demonstrate that she has suffered a loss, only that the defendant has been unjustly enriched at her
expense. Of course, in many cases of unjust enrichment, the plaintiff will have suffered a tangible loss corresponding directly to the defendant's enrichment. If <i>A</i> mistakenly deposits $100 into <i>B</i>'s bank account, <i>B</i>'s enrichment is equal to <i>A</i>'s deprivation. But in other cases, the relationship between the
plaintiff's loss and the defendant's enrichment may not be so clear. Imagine a breach of fiduciary duty case, in which a trustee has taken money from the beneficiary's trust fund, invested it, made a large profit, and returned the original sum to the trust fund, while retaining the profits for himself. The beneficiary may have suffered no demonstrable loss. Yet an action in restitution still lies in such a case, and the trustee must account for his profits to the beneficiary. A similar result may be seen in the leading cases on the taking of corporate opportunities.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> Indeed, some of the most famous cases in the law of restitution---such as <cite>Reading v. Attorney-General</cite><sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> and the `Great Onyx Cave' case<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup> ---demonstrate that the measure of recovery in restitution is the defendant's benefit, and not the plaintiff's deprivation. A common law claim for restitution seeks not only to compensate for a loss, but also to deprive a party of a benefit which he unjustly retains.
<p>
More specific to the issue of `passing on,' the plaintiff in these cases has paid the taxes to the public authority, in the technical sense that it has transferred them to the public authority. As between the plaintiff firm and the public authority, the plaintiff's claim must be stronger, because the public authority has no basis for retaining the moneys so paid to it. Our desire to do justice to the plaintiff's customers, which accounts for the intuitive appeal of the `passing on' defence, should not cloud the determination of rights as between the plaintiff and the defendant public authority. In particular, it must not lead to the conclusion that the plaintiff should not recover at all. The plaintiff has paid the taxes to the public authority and is thus entitled to sue to recover them. That the plaintiff may have entered into contracts or have restitutionary obligations to its customers with regard to the taxes cannot affect
the &quot;at the expense of&quot; part of the restitutionary equation against the public authority. Thus, the `passing on' defence is inconsistent with the proper account of both the second and third elements of the
<cite>Pettkus</cite> test, and should be rejected as a defence.
<p>
Second, there are compelling constitutional reasons against allowing the government to retain unlawfully-collected tax payments, reasons suggested by Wilson J. in her dissent in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, averted to by Lord Goff in <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite>,<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> and set out more extensively by Professor Birks in his several commentaries on the subject.<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> It is important to understand that the principle at issue consists not only of the invocation of the rule of law, although it does contain that element. The struggle for supremacy between King and Parliament had its historical focus upon the ability of the monarch to levy taxes without the consent of Parliament. Parliament won this battle, and its supremacy was confirmed by the Bill of Rights, which provided that the Crown could not levy taxes without Parliamentary consent.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> To modern citizens, such a principle may seem arcane. But there can be little doubt that it is an essential foundation of Anglo-Canadian constitutional government.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> As Professor Hogg explains, the principle enshrined in the Bill of Rights &quot;ensures not merely that the executive branch is subject to the rule of law, but also that the executive branch must call the legislative branch into session to raise taxes (and vote supply).&quot;<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> Indeed, this principle takes on increased importance in the modern regulatory state, because it ensures that acts of the executive and administration which purport to impose taxes or other charges on citizens must have a legal foundation based on an act of the legislature. A broader version of the constitutional principle is that public authorities must not be permitted to benefit from unlawful conduct. In essence, to permit the government to retain taxes unlawfully collected is to sanction unlawful government conduct. There is no more powerful disincentive to unlawful government conduct than to prevent public authorities from gaining from such conduct. In the tax context, this necessarily implies that taxes collected under a statute which is invalid or misapplied---that is, taxes collected without a legal foundation---must be returned to the taxpayers.
<p>
The third reason to question the `passing on' defence is that the plaintiff firm is likely to have suffered &quot;collateral damage&quot; from the government's unlawful imposition of taxes upon it. The imposition of taxes will have adversely affected the plaintiff's business by causing it to raise its prices, reducing the volume demanded for its products or services, and thus reducing its revenue and profits.<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup> The plaintiff may also have suffered costs associated with the imposition of a tax, such as hiring lawyers and accountants, and the cost of time spent completing documentation, reconfiguring equipment, and so on. Of course, these losses stem from the wrongful imposition of the tax, a loss which should be distinguished from the deprivation caused by payment of the tax itself. An action for recovery of the former loss would be in tort,
not unjust enrichment. The particular cause of action in tort is as yet unrecognized: it would be a form of economic loss which we might call `wrongful taxation.'  The fact that the plaintiff has suffered this first type of loss should weigh heavily in the court's balancing of the equities when it comes to deciding whether to order restitution of the tax payments, however. Restitution of the tax payments made by the plaintiff to the public authority may partially
or fully compensate the plaintiff for these losses. 
<p>
The `passing on' defence appears to be closely tied to the argument that plaintiffs are under a duty to mitigate their losses. While a duty upon the plaintiff to mitigate its loss has never been recognized in the law of restitution, Professor Burrows has argued that the courts should impose such a duty.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> It is entirely unclear how this would work in practice. A duty to mitigate would require the plaintiff to undertake reasonable steps to reduce the extent of its loss.<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> Yet in the context of restitution for taxes unlawfully collected, mitigation would require a plaintiff to `pass on' the burden of its deprivation to its customers. While there is a natural incentive for a plaintiff to `pass on' the tax burden, it is unclear why it should be <i>required</i> to do so. Burrows suggests that a mitigation defence is &quot;preferable&quot; because it would let the so-called `windfall' lie with the defendant, a state of affairs which &quot;minimizes legal intervention and litigation.&quot;<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> As a matter of legal principle there is little to recommend this approach. A duty to mitigate would ensure that public authorities would never be required
to disgorge tax payments received under an unlawful statute, because plaintiff firms would be required to `pass on' the cost of the unlawful tax payments to their customers. As I outline in Section Five, it is often much more difficult for a business to `pass on' tax burdens to their customers than the courts have been prepared to admit. But more importantly, a duty to mitigate would allow public authorities to refrain from disgorging unlawfully collected tax payments.
<p>
In an action in unjust enrichment against a public authority for recovery of a tax payment made under an unlawful statute, a plaintiff should be under no duty to mitigate his or her deprivation because it is misleading to think of this deprivation as a `loss' in the tort or contract sense of the term. Compare the position of a firm which has suffered a tort at the hands of another party. Certainly, the firm is under an obligation to minimize the loss which results from the wrongful act, and must take all reasonable steps to do so. But a loss may remain despite the plaintiff's efforts. In the case of a firm, it may then attempt to make up the loss by `passing on' the cost of the loss to its customers in the form of higher prices. The customers may or may not choose to pay the higher prices. If enough customers do choose to pay the higher prices, so that the firm is able to `pass on' the cost of its loss to them, no one could argue that the defendant would not remain liable for the full cost of the loss caused by his wrongful act. Similarly, in restitution, the fact that the plaintiff may have `passed on' to others the amount by which he or she has been deprived by the defendant is not relevant in considering whether the defendant has been unjustly enriched at the
expense of the plaintiff. Mitigation has no place in the law of restitution.
<p>
<h3>5.  An Economic Model of `Passing On'</h3>

Economic analysis provides a critical objection to the `passing on' defence, suggesting that the economic logic underlying the `passing on' defence is unwieldy.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> The legal structure of
restitution must be informed by an awareness of the likely economic effects of particular legal rules. The economic analysis outlined in this section buttresses the legal arguments developed above against the `passing on' defence. The difficulty lies primarily in determining the extent to which the burden of a tax payment has actually been `passed on.'  To this end, an essential distinction must be drawn. Clearly, a public authority may make a person
statutorily liable for paying a tax. It does not necessarily follow from this, though, that the person on whom a tax is imposed bears the economic burden of the tax, because the burden may be shifted to other persons. Notwithstanding this, the person on whom the tax was initially imposed almost invariably suffers some residual impact of the tax, because a tax may be `passed on' to others only at some cost to the person on whom it was originally imposed.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup> The person (or persons) on whom the economic
burden finally falls is said to bear the incidence of the tax.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> It is this distinction, and the analysis which follows, that render the existing approach to the `passing on' defence in the law of restitution, as set out in <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, of dubious authority.
<p>
The Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Air Canada</cite> assumed that the plaintiff airlines could simply add the cost of the tax which had been imposed on them to the price charged to their customers, and thus suffer no loss because the tax had been `passed on.'  When a firm has a tax imposed on it by a public authority, it will attempt
to `pass on' the cost of that tax to its customers by raising the price which it charges to them for its products or services to take into account the cost of the tax. This process is not as simple as the Supreme Court has suggested. A firm's ability to `pass on' the economic burden of a tax is dependent on the relative elasticities of supply and demand for the firm's product or service. Elasticity is a measure of responsiveness of quantities supplied and demanded to changes in price.<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> It is a commonplace observation that a rise in the price of a good or service will likely reduce consumer demand for it, and above a certain level, will adversely affect the firm's profits. Thus, a firm is likely to be harmed by the imposition of the tax even if it is able to `pass on'
the nominal amount of the tax to its customers by raising its prices. Only in certain rare situations will an increased price charged to consumers not affect their demand for the product or service. This result occurs when volume of demand for a product or service is perfectly inelastic, and customers will purchase the same amount of product or service regardless of the price charged. But a good or service for which demand is perfectly inelastic is really only an economist's abstraction; few economists can point to such a product or service in the real world.
<p>
Conversely, where demand for the firm's products or services is perfectly elastic---where the quantity demanded is immediately and radically connected to the price---the firm will be unable to `pass on' <i>any</i> of the tax burden to its customers. For if it raises its prices at all, its sales will drop to zero. Of course, few goods or services have demand curves which are perfectly elastic (or inelastic). The vast majority of goods and services have demand
elasticities which are either relatively elastic (price sensitive) or inelastic (more immune to price changes). Not to be forgotten are elasticities of supply: relatively elastic supply will force more of the economic burden of a tax onto the buyer, whereas relatively inelastic supply will force more of the tax burden onto the seller. Overall, then, as demand becomes more inelastic, or as supply becomes more elastic, the buyer will bear more of the burden of a tax. As demand becomes more elastic, or as supply becomes more inelastic, the seller will bear a greater proportion of the burden. The burden of a tax will be shared between a buyer and seller according to the ratio of elasticity of supply to elasticity of demand.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> The simple conclusion is that for almost all products and services, an increase in price will adversely affect the quantity demanded. The difficulty lies in determining exactly how the imposition of a tax on a firm affects its sales and profits. Few courts have recognized
this difficulty: most are content to state that if the taxpayer has been adversely affected by the imposition of a tax, it should be able to demonstrate this to the satisfaction of the court.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup> The reality is considerably more complicated, as some courts have recognized.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> Professor Birks states that La Forest J.'s adoption of the `passing on' defence in <cite>Air Canada</cite> commits the court to &quot;an impossible inquiry.&quot;<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup>
<p>
The economic model also suggests that the incidence of a tax may be `passed up' as well as `passed on.'<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup> In addition to attempting to shift the economic burden of a tax onto its customers, a firm may also attempt to shift some or all of the burden of a tax `up' to its suppliers in the form of reducing the amount of money it is willing to pay them for inputs.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> Yet this process also has its limits. Few firms will be able to `pass up' the entire burden of a tax to their suppliers. In most situations, a firm will attempt to `pass on' some of the cost of a tax to its customers, and some of the cost to its suppliers. In most
cases, then, the burden of a tax is likely to be shared between the business, its customers, and the firm's suppliers. But exactly how much is `passed on' to each may be difficult to determine, and in many cases competitive pressures will ensure that only a portion of the total burden is `passed on.'  Moreover, the economic model suggests that a firm's profits may be adversely affected by the imposition of a tax on it, even if it is able to transfer the entire burden of the tax to its customers in the form of higher prices. Itbis facile, therefore, to suggest that a firm which has `passed on' thebburden of a tax to its customers has suffered no loss. 
<p>
An American case, <cite>Twentieth Century Sporting Club v. United States</cite>,<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> highlights these concerns. The plaintiff (a boxing and wrestling promoter) collected a federal admission tax from attendees at its matches and transmitted the tax revenues to the government. The plaintiff sought recovery of overpayments made of the federal tax, claiming that instead of being applied to the base price of the ticket (without state taxes), the federal tax had been applied erroneously to the ticket price on top of state taxes, so that tax had been paid on tax. The statute regulating recovery permitted an action to be brought by
a &quot;taxpayer.&quot;  The Court of Claims held, however, that the plaintiff had merely collected the tax from its customers on behalf of the government. No action for recovery could lie because the promoter had never actually paid the tax in question.
<p>
Nevertheless, the promoter sought to show that it had in fact borne the burden of the taxation. While it may not have paid the impugned tax itself, it was economically harmed by the imposition of the tax. It is unfortunate that the plaintiff confused matters by not distinguishing between the &quot;burden&quot; of having to pay the tax and the &quot;burden&quot; of being economically harmed by the tax through decreased demand and lower profits. (Recall that an action to recover the first loss would be in restitution, whereas the second would require an action in tort which is as yet unrecognized, so-called `wrongful taxation'). The promoter argued that the maximum price it could charge its customers was $11.50 per ticket, including all taxes, because demand for tickets would fall rapidly if the price of tickets was set above $11.50. As a result, the burden of the federal government's erroneous computation of taxes was not `passed on' to customers (which would have driven the price up to $11.54) but was absorbed by the promoter. In order to ensure that the final consumer price did not go above $11.50, the promoter absorbed the excess federal tax; it paid the tax out of its profits by reducing its initial ticket price so that the final price remained the same.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> An example closer to home demonstrates that this is not an unusual situation. Before the imposition of the GST in Canada, <cite>The Toronto Star</cite> charged $0.50 for a weekday edition of the newspaper. After the imposition of the GST, the base price was reduced to $0.47 so that with GST, the final price to the consumer would remain at $0.50. Both the promoter in <cite>Twentieth Century Sporting Club</cite> and the proprietors of  <cite>The Toronto Star</cite> recognized that consumers do not want to be bothered with irregular prices, and that competition requires that prices remain low. Yet the Court of Claims in <cite>Twentieth Century Sporting Club</cite> held that the promoter had <i>chosen</i> to bear the burden of the federal government's tax error; it had not been compelled to do so. It thus dismissed the application.
<p>
The economic analysis in this section suggests that `passing on' is not the simple process that the Supreme Court of Canada has implied. A variety of economic factors conspire to ensure that when a tax is imposed on a firm, the economic burden of the tax will be shared by several parties in varying degrees, depending on the elasticities of
supply and demand for the firm's products or services, and other factors in a competitive marketplace. In most cases, the burden of a tax will be shared between the firm, its suppliers, and its customers. In almost all cases, the imposition of the tax on a firm forces it to raise its prices and harms its revenues and sales, causing economic losses. Moreover, as cases such as <cite>Twentieth Century Sporting Club</cite> demonstrate, customers' resistance to
increased prices may require firms to absorb much or all of a tax increase. Yet few common law courts have recognized this reality. It is time that they did.
<p>
<h3>6.  The European Cases: A Principled Approach</h3>

The economic model outlined in the previous section has been reflected in the European Court of Justice's treatment of the `passing on' defence. Particularly valuable are the views of the Court and the European Commission as to the placement of the onus of demonstrating whether or not the plaintiff firm has in fact `passed on' the economic burden of a tax to its customers. Following earlier decisions which outlined a nascent right to recovery of levies determined to be illegal under Community law,<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> the European Court first tackled the `passing on' defence in <cite>Hans Just I/S v. Danish Ministry for Fiscal Affairs</cite>.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> A Danish alcohol producer and importer brought an action for recovery of overpayment of Danish excise taxes. It challenged the excise tax provisions on the grounds that they taxed imported products at a higher rate than domestic products and violated art. 95 of the <cite>Treaty of Rome</cite> (specifically, the principle of non-discrimination).<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> In addition, the plaintiff sought repayment of what it alleged to be overpayments of excise tax under the Danish scheme. One question posed to the Court was whether European Community law contained any rules governing the repayment of
taxes deemed to be inconsistent with art. 95. More specifically, was it relevant that the producer could establish that it had suffered a loss as a result of the tax?
<p>
The Court held that the impugned excise tax legislation violated art. 95 of the <cite>Treaty of Rome</cite>. Moreover, the Court found that the relevant Danish law of unjust enrichment required that the plaintiff must demonstrate that he or she has suffered a loss in order to merit repayment of the impugned taxes. Danish law does not allow a claim to succeed against a public authority where it could be demonstrated that the economic burden of the taxes in question had been `passed on' to the business' consumers.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup> Denmark argued that in such a situation, to require the repayment of taxes would unjustly enrich the plaintiff.
The Court held that Member States could design their own legal regimes for the repayment of taxes found to violate Community law, as long as the repayment regime was no less favourable to nationals from other Member States than to domestic nationals. Community law does not prevent national legal regimes from taking into consideration
whether the burden of the charges which have been unlawfully levied has been `passed on' to  others.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> <cite>Hans Just</cite> suggests that under European law, Member States may preclude reimbursement of taxes where it can be demonstrated that the burden of the taxes was `passed on' to the plaintiff's consumers.
<p>
Given this deferential approach to national law, in later cases the European Court was not concerned with whether Member States could impose conditions---such as a statutory `passing on' defence---on the repayment of taxes collected under illegal statutes. Yet the Court carefully outlined the requirements which a national scheme must meet in order to be compatible with Community law. <cite>Hans Just</cite> was soon followed by <cite>Amministrazione delle Finanze dello Stato v. San Giorgio SpA</cite>,<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> the case which contains the most sophisticated understanding of the economic forces at work in the `passing on' defence. A dairy argued that health inspection charges imposed by Italy on the transit of
animals, meat, and related products violated Community law. Italian law provided that payments of an illegal tax could not be recovered where the business had `passed on' the cost of the payments to its consumers, and that there was a presumption that such `passing on' had in fact taken place. Italy's constitutional court allowed the application, held that the charges were illegal, and ordered restitution of the payments to San Giorgio. 
<p>
The European Court's consideration of the issue focused upon San Giorgio's right to recovery of the taxes from the Italian authorities. The Court was faced with two main questions: first, whether a national law could predicate the recovery of taxes paid to a public authority under an illegal statute on certain conditions, such as the requirement that the taxpayer demonstrate that the taxes had not in fact been `passed on.'  Second, the Court considered whether the Italian legislation's requirement that the taxpayer provide documentary proof that the taxes had not been `passed on' rendered ``the exercise of rights which national courts are under a duty to protect virtually impossible.&quot;  Following its decision in <cite>Hans Just</cite>, the Court reiterated its view that Community law does not prevent Member States from implementing national schemes to regulate the repayment of taxes paid under illegal statutes. These national schemes could consider whether the taxpayer has `passed on' the cost of the taxes to its customers. Nevertheless, the Court held that national regulatory schemes were subject to the dictates of Community law. The central issue in <cite>San Giorgio</cite> was the burden of proof as to whether the taxes in question had or had not
been `passed on.'  The Court held that Community law does not permit a Member State to create an irrefutable presumption that a charge or tax has been `passed on' by the taxpayer to its customers. Nor can Member States impose the burden of proof on the taxpayer: it must be the responsibility of public authorities to demonstrate that the
taxes have in fact been `passed on' by the taxpayer to its consumers. Further, the Court held that the standard of proof must not be so high as to make it impossible for the taxpayer to demonstrate that it did not in fact `pass on' the economic burden of an impugned tax or charge. In so doing, the Court was acutely aware of the economic
difficulties in determining what proportion, if any, of the tax had actually been `passed on.'<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> The complexity of the economic calculations, in the Court's opinion, require that the burden of proof not be imposed on the taxpayer. Otherwise, the vast majority of taxpayers would be effectively prevented from receiving repayment of taxes levied contrary to Community law. The Court concluded that Member States are prohibited by Community law from making the repayment of illegal charges conditional on the production of documentary evidence by the plaintiff showing that the charges were not `passed on' to its customers.
<p>
The conclusions of Mancini A.G. in <cite>San Giorgio</cite> are of particular interest, as they reinforce the economic model of `passing on' which was developed above.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup> Mancini A.G. took issue with the `passing on' defence as examined in both <cite>Hans Just</cite> and in <cite>San Giorgio</cite>. To allow such a defence, he argued, would make it all but impossible for taxpayers to recover
from the government. Mancini A.G. recognized that the price paid by consumers for goods or services is composed of a number of factors, including taxes, the exact composition of which is difficult to determine. In such circumstances, it would be folly to isolate one element of the price of the good or service as being attached to a
tax paid by the plaintiff. It would also render impracticable attempts at recovery by subjecting plaintiffs to an almost insuperable task.<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup>
<p>
The European Court confirmed this position in two subsequent cases. In <cite>Re Repayment of Illegal Taxes</cite><sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> the Court examined an Italian decree-law<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup> which provided that repayment of taxes and charges made under legislation which was subsequently found to have been illegal was dependant on taxpayers furnishing documentary evidence that the charge or tax had not been `passed on' to other persons. The legislation was similar to that considered in <cite>San
Giorgio</cite>.<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup> The European Commission applied to the European Court for a declaration that the provisions were contrary to European law because the onus which they imposed on
taxpayers seeking repayment of taxes collected under illegal statutes was too severe. Slynn A.G. suggested that the Italian scheme violated the principles set down by the Court in <cite>San Giorgio</cite> for two reasons. First, the scheme imposed the onus on the taxpayer to prove that it had not `passed on' the burden of the taxes to its customers. Second, the scheme's requirement of documentary evidence made the threshold for recovery all but insurmountable.<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup> The Court agreed. This position was reiterated in <cite>Les Fils de Jules Bianco S.A. v. Directeur G&eacute;n&eacute;ral des Douanes et Droits Indirects</cite>,<sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup> in which the Court considered the status of French taxes on fuel oil. The plaintiffs, French fuel oil distributors, paid the impugned taxes and subsequently challenged their legality. French legislation provided that the taxes could be recovered only where the taxpayer could demonstrate that the taxes had not been passed on to a customer. The Court held that the plaintiffs needed only to prove that the tax statute in question was unlawful and that they had paid it. The Court held:
<blockquote>
a member-State is not entitled to adopt provisions which make the repayment of charges levied contrary to Community law conditional upon the production of proof that those charges have not been passed on to the purchasers of the products that were subject to the charges and to place the burden of adducing such negative proof entirely on the natural or legal persons claiming repayment.<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Thus, the European Court, while allowing Member States to preserve the `passing on' defence as an element of their domestic law of unjust enrichment, has required that the burden of proof and evidentiary considerations not conspire to make it effectively impossible for taxpayers to recover payments made under unlawful statutes. Canadian courts would do well to adopt these principles in Canadian law.
<p>
<h3>7.  The American Cases: Defining the Scope of `Passing on'</h3>

The `passing on' defence has had a long history in the United States, largely because the American Constitution provides broad grounds for challenging the legality of tax statutes, whereas most other common law countries do not possess a similar constitutional structure.<sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup> American courts have been generally receptive to the `passing on' defence, claiming in many cases that the plaintiff business has likely passed
on the economic burden of the tax to its customers, and that it would receive a windfall if it were allowed to recover the tax payments from the government. But as we shall see, despite this initial reluctance to allow plaintiffs to recover, some glimmers of hope have emerged. A word of caution must be said about the American cases: many of them involve the interpretation of a statutory provision defining the circumstances and procedures by which a claim for restitution of payments made under an unconstitutional statute, or overpayments under a valid statute, may be initiated. Many of these statutory regimes include a `passing on' provision.<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup> Notwithstanding this <i>caveat</i>, some broader lessons can be drawn from the decisions. For the most part, the U.S. courts have given a wide scope to their pronouncements, and have not limited their holdings to narrow questions of statutory interpretation confined to the individual case. In any event, in the absence of a well-developed common law in Canada on the `passing on' defence, some guidance may be gained from the U.S. decisions. 
<p>
This dominant strain in the U.S. law is manifest in <cite>Bacchus Imports, Ltd</cite>. v. <cite>Dias</cite>.<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup> Four wholesalers sold liquor to retailers at a base price
plus a 20 per cent state excise tax. They challenged the constitutionality of the tax and sought restitution of $45,000,000 which they had paid to Hawaii under it. The U.S. Supreme Court held that the tax statute was unconstitutional.<sup><a href="#one57">157</a></sup> Hawaii contended that there should be no refund to the wholesalers because they had `passed on' the ``economic incidence&quot; of the tax to their customers through a separate addition to the price that their customers were legally obligated to pay within a certain time. Furthermore, the State argued that the retailers, and not the wholesalers, bore the legal obligation to pay the tax. By contrast,
the wholesalers claimed that they were liable to pay the tax, regardless of whether their customers had paid their bills on time. They also put forward a variant of the economic argument against `passing on' outlined above:<sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup> that the effect of the tax (that is, having to charge a price 20 per cent higher) was more complicated than simply `passing on' the cost of the tax to retailers. The U.S. Supreme Court viewed restitution as a matter for the State Court to decide and remanded the case for trial. Dissenting on other grounds, Stevens J. (joined by Rehnquist and O'Connor JJ.), was skeptical as to the ability of the wholesalers to
demonstrate that the discriminatory tax had had an adverse impact on their business. While the wholesalers challenged the entire regulatory scheme by arguing that these exemptions were discriminatory, the dissent was convinced that wholesalers had `passed on' the economic burden of the tax to their customers. The case demonstrates that the American courts have been keen to ensure that where a plaintiff is seeking restitution against the government for illegal taxation payments, the plaintiff is not awarded a &quot;windfall.&quot;<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup> Courts are reluctant to award restitution in cases in which the plaintiff firm collects taxes from its customers on behalf of a public authority.
<p>
A similar result was reached in <cite>Jefferson Electric</cite>.<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup> The Court held that the proper interpretation of a legislative provision regulating the refund of certain automobile taxes was that a prospective recipient of a tax refund had to demonstrate that the burden of the tax had not been `passed on' to its customers. In the Court's view, while the government had likely been unjustly enriched by receipt of the tax
payments, to allow a refund in these circumstances would be unjust enrichment of a different sort. Van Deventer J. stated that &quot;we cannot assent to the view that a court may give a judgment awarding a taxpayer a refund without inquiring whether he has borne the burden of the tax or has reimbursed himself by collecting it from the
purchaser.&quot;<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup> 
<p>
It is useful to turn to a series of older Illinois cases in which the `passing on' defence was examined in some detail. The defence was approved in <cite>Chicago Motor Club v. Kinney</cite>,<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup> where the applicant sought a declaration that an Illinois motor fuel tax was unconstitutional. The legislation provided a refund of two cents per gallon of tax which would otherwise be payable, if the gasoline were used &quot;for any purpose other than operating a motor vehicle upon the public highways.&quot;  The tax was imposed on distributors and refiners of motor fuel. The Supreme Court of
Illinois held that the statute was unconstitutional, but refused to allow recovery of taxes paid under the statute because the tax &quot;is merely one of the items of cost to the distributor and it enters into the cost to the ultimate consumer just as any other item does.&quot;<sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup> The State, which
would ordinarily be required to disgorge the payments made under an invalid statute, was not required to do so because the Court considered that the distributors had likely `passed on' the cost of the tax to their customers. 
<p>
This rule was followed in a series of cases arising out of the determination that the Illinois motor fuel legislation was
unconstitutional. In <cite>Richardson Lubricating Co. v. Kinney</cite>,<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup> two motor fuel distributors sought restitution of tax payments made under the
invalidated Illinois statute, but were refused on the grounds that they had not borne the burden of the tax. The Court was unimpressed that the distributors had not offered to return the tax payments to their customers should they be awarded a refund. In a companion case,<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup> the Court again allowed the `passing on' defence to be advanced. In denying recovery of the tax payments from the State, the Court held that the motor fuel distributor: 
<blockquote>
acted merely as an intermediary between its customers and the department of finance. It paid the tax, not out of its own funds, but by the collections from its customers for the particular purpose. It now seeks to recover what it has not refunded, and does not intend to refund to its customers.<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In <cite>Standard Oil Co. v. Bollinger (No.2)</cite>,<sup><a href="#one67">167</a></sup> the petitioning oil company objected to this characterization, arguing that it had agreed with certain of its customers, to whom it had `passed on' the unconstitutional tax in question, to attempt to recover the taxes so paid on their behalf and to return the tax payments to the customers on a <i>pro rata</i> basis. Again, the Supreme Court of Illinois denied recovery and condemned what it viewed as the petitioner's opportunistic behaviour on the part of the petitioner. In all of the Illinois motor fuel tax cases the Court was clearly apprehensive about awarding what it saw
as a windfall to distributors, and allowed the `passing on' defence to be advanced to prevent this.
<p>
In a final case in the series, <cite>Benzoline Motor Fuel Co. v. Bollinger</cite>,<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup> the Court moderated its refusal to allow recovery. There, the petitioning fuel
company had held a conference with its customers soon after the impugned act went into effect. Furthermore, the company kept accurate records of the amount of fuel sold to its customers, along with their names, addresses, and the amount of tax each had paid. The Court held that here the customers had agreed that the taxes should be paid by the fuel company under protest, and that records were maintained by the plaintiff  &quot;in order that it would be able to make full and proper returns of tax money in the event the money was returned to it by the  state.&quot;<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup> This situation was different from the earlier cases concerning recovery of the fuel tax. The Court ordered restitution of the tax payments, declaring that the State director of finance: 
<blockquote>
is in control of money that in equity and good conscience he has no right to retain, inasmuch as the avenue for the return of the tax money in full to the customers of complainant, without any deductions, is straight and broad.<sup><a href="#one70">170</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Court was prepared to reject the `passing on' defence, and order restitution to a business which had `passed on' the burden of a tax, where there was a continuing relationship between the firm and its customers, and where the business had kept adequate records which would enable it to return the tax payments to its customers. 
<p>
Conversely, the `passing on' defence was also upheld in <cite>Shannon v. Hughes &amp; Co.,</cite><sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup> in which an ice cream manufacturer challenged the constitutionality of a Kentucky tax of seven cents per quart on the sale of ice cream. The plaintiff had collected the tax from its customers and forwarded it to the State, as required by the statute. The case is analogous to the tax on
alcoholic beverages in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite>, in that the plaintiff in both cases was under a statutory obligation to collect the tax from its customers on behalf of the government. The State asserted that even if the tax statute was unconstitutional and void, the plaintiff, having recovered the tax from its customers, should
not be able to recover the tax payments from it. The Court found that the plaintiff &quot;added the tax to the price charged for its products, and thus collected the tax from its vendees and shifted to them the economic burden of its imposition.&quot;<sup><a href="#one72">172</a></sup> The Court followed <cite>Jefferson Electric</cite><sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup> in holding that the State may require the plaintiff to demonstrate that it has not `passed on' the burden of the tax to its customers as a pre-condition for recovery of
taxes unlawfully collected.
<p>
The Court, stating that &quot;[t]he doctrine of unjust enrichment has received a wide application in tax cases even without the aid of a statute,&quot; followed the Illinois motor fuel cases discussed above, and denied recovery to the plaintiff. Although the plaintiff was under a duty to collect the tax in question on behalf of the State, it could not be considered a &quot;taxpayer&quot; for the purpose of the statutory recovery provision, which stated that the customers alone could recover. Rees J. stated:
<blockquote>
the sellers of ice cream who paid the tax into the state treasury should show that the amounts they seek to recover do not include collections made by them from their customers ... [t]o hold otherwise would be manifestly unjust and would result in the unjust enrichment of the one seeking to recover the tax from the [state] and supported by no outlay on his part. Indirectly it would allow him to take money wrongfully paid into the treasury of the [state] by another through himself acting as collector, and leave the actual payer of the tax with a bare cupboard.<sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The plaintiff put forward the economic argument discussed above,<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup> arguing that the imposition of the tax had injured its business due to a drastic decline in volume of sales,
such that it should be permitted to sue the State in order to recoup these losses, given that the impugned statute had been deemed to be unconstitutional. The Court quickly dismissed this suggestion on the grounds that this would be to allow an action against the State for losses stemming from the effects of taxation. But it is unclear why
this should be a bar to an action when the tax statute was entirely invalid and unconstitutional. Moreover, the tax here was not set out as a &quot;specific charge&quot; to customers, but was included in the total undifferentiated price. I argue below that the `passing on' defence is considerably weaker in situations where a tax was not
&quot;specifically charged&quot; to customers as a distinct item.
<p>
The pessimism which emerges from a reading of these cases is allayed considerably by a line of cases beginning with <cite>123 East Fifty-Fourth Street</cite>,<sup><a href="#one76">176</a></sup> in which the majority rejected the application of the `passing on' defence. A restaurant at that address in New York City sought recovery of a federal excise tax which had been levied against it in error. A 5 per cent surcharge was levied separately on all admission, refreshment, service, and merchandise charges on which the restaurant had collected tax from its
customers and paid to the federal government. The statutory provision did not limit recovery of tax payments illegally collected to taxpayers who had borne the burden of the taxes paid. For its part, the federal government argued that Congress could not have intended that the restaurant should secure the &quot;windfall&quot; which
would result if the tax payments were returned to it. The restaurant was liable under statute for the payment of the taxes, regardless of whether they were actually recovered by it through `passing on' to its customers. The Court held that although the restaurant's customers had undoubtedly paid more for food, drink, and entertainment than they would have had there had never been a tax, the fact that the restaurant had `passed on' the tax to its customers
meant that when the higher price (including the `passed on' tax) was paid, &quot;that price became the plaintiff's money.&quot;<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup> As a result, the majority held that the customers would have no right of action against the plaintiff for their overpayments. Chase J. allowed the restaurant to recover on
the basis that the money belonged to it when it was transmitted to the government.
<p>
Learned Hand J. issued a strong dissent in this case. He made a distinction between two forms in which the tax might have been presented to customers by the plaintiff. It could be inferred that the restaurant had charged its customers by presenting them with a bill indicating the amount payable, with the tax added on as a separate and distinct charge. He contrasted this with the situation (which he did not believe had occurred here) in which the restaurant might have presented its customers with a `lump sum' bill showing a single sum payable with all taxes included. He regarded the distinction between the two cases as &quot;crucial&quot;; if the latter situation obtained, Learned Hand J. suggested that he would have agreed with the majority that the customers had no claim to the
money, and would have allowed recovery for the plaintiff. If, however, as he believed was the case here, the former situation had transpired, and the restaurant had represented the tax to its customers as a separate and distinct charge on top of the regular price, it would be &quot;understood to be a statement that it [the restaurant] was obliged to pay it as a tax&quot; on behalf of the customers to the government. That is, it could be implied that the restaurant had agreed to accept the tax payments from its customers only on the condition that it be forwarded to the government in fulfillment of statutory obligations. Learned Hand J. would have held that the payments should be returned to the plaintiff and held on constructive trust by it for the benefit of its customers. The restaurant could not recover unless it could locate the customers who had paid the tax and repay the money to them.
<p>
This distinction of form is determinative, and shows that <cite>Shannon</cite> was wrongly decided.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> (Recall that in that case, the Court denied recovery to the plaintiff even though the tax had not been specifically charged to customers.)  The manner in which the tax was presented to the customers should affect whether the plaintiff firm recovers the payment from the government, and whether the plaintiff can keep the money outright or must hold it under a constructive trust. If the customers knew that a discernible portion of the price which they were paying for the plaintiff's goods or services was a tax, it can be logically inferred that they agreed to pay the plaintiff's price plus the tax, and paid the tax on the condition that it be actually forwarded to the government by the plaintiff. If it were subsequently determined that the tax was unlawful, then the moneys recovered should be returned to the plaintiff and held on constructive trust for those of its customers who paid the tax. If, however, the plaintiff's price was presented to the customer as an undifferentiated lump sum---as in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite>---it becomes far more difficult to argue that the customer should have a
claim on the portion of the price which actually (but unbeknownst to the customer) consisted of the `passed on' tax payment, because it may be safely inferred that the plaintiff's customers would have paid that lump sum price regardless of whether they knew that it included a tax charge. In the latter case the customer was not making a tax
payment <i>qua</i> tax payment, and the plaintiff firm should recover from the government, but be under no obligation to advance the proceeds to its customers. 
<p>
Suppose that on the facts of <cite>Air Canada</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada had allowed the airlines to recover on the basis of unjust enrichment. Could passengers who had paid a portion of the tax (because the airlines had likely `passed on' at least part of the cost of the impugned fuel tax to them) then launch their own action
in unjust enrichment against the airlines?  <cite>Wayne County Produce Co</cite>. v. <cite>Duffy-Mott Co</cite>.<sup><a href="#one79">179</a></sup> provides an answer to the problem which arises when a party to whom the cost of a tax has been `passed on' seeks recovery of that burden from a business which has successfully recovered tax payments from the government. The plaintiff had purchased more than 157,000 gallons of sweet cider from the defendant. The plaintiff had paid the defendant both a base price as well as a 10 per cent war tax, which the defendant had transmitted to the federal government. The U.S. Treasury Department's application of the war tax to sweet cider was subsequently determined to have been erroneous. The defendant demanded and received a refund of the taxes from the government. The plaintiff then sought recovery of the tax payments which it had made to the defendant. Cardozo C.J. ordered recovery for the plaintiff. He distinguished an early New York decision, <cite>Moore v. Des Arts</cite>,<sup><a href="#one80">180</a></sup> where the tax in question had been paid by the producer and &quot;absorbed in a total or composite price to be paid at all events.&quot; In <cite>Moore</cite>, the tax had been paid by the business on an input, and then the cost of that tax had been `passed on' to the business' customers. In such a situation, a buyer in the position of the plaintiff would be without a remedy, even through ``the annulment of the tax may increase the profit to the seller.&quot;  Interestingly, this is exactly the situation in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, where La Forest J. did not allow recovery.<sup><a href="#one81">181</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Duffy-Mott</cite>, the tax was entirely distinct from the cider; it was a per gallon tax payable by the consumer through the producer, who would forward the taxes thus paid to the government. The Court held that the contract between the parties was an essential consideration. The consumer was obligated to pay the taxes for which
the seller was liable, on the implied condition that if the tax was later determined not to be payable, the tax payment should be returned by the seller to the consumer. If the seller had not &quot;specifically charged&quot; the tax as a distinct sum, the customer could not have recovered. In a situation where the firm recovered a tax from the government, it has no valid defence against an action from one of its customers for restitution of the portion of the tax which the customer actually paid. The <cite>Duffy-Mott</cite> approach, combined with the reasoning of Learned Hand J. in his dissenting judgment in <cite>123 East Fifty-Fourth Street</cite>, contains principles
which lead us to a solution to the `passing on' problem.
<p>
<h3>8.  A Solution?</h3>

An innovative solution to the problems raised by the `passing on' defence is contained in the judgment of Traynor J. of the Supreme Court of California in the <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite><sup><a href="#one82">182</a></sup> case. A tax upon the sale and installation of carpeting was miscalculated, so that a carpet vendor collected sales tax from its customers, and overpaid to the State in excess of $4,300,000. The vendor sought recovery of this money, and was granted it at trial on the basis that it was retained in error by the State. That the vendor had no intention of returning the overpayments recovered from the State to the customers who had actually paid it did not concern the trial court. But on appeal, the State contended that the vendor would be unjustly enriched if it were allowed to keep the tax overpayments.
<p>
In an effort to balance the competing considerations at issue, Traynor J. adopted Learned Hand J.'s dissent in <cite>123 East Fifty-Fourth Street,</cite> and held that the State should return the tax overpayments to the vendor, but that the vendor must hold the overpayments on trust for the customers who had actually made the payments. This approach is useful, as it requires the State to disgorge payments which would be unjust for it to retain. Yet it
avoids a &quot;windfall&quot; for the plaintiff by requiring that the vendor hold the payments on constructive trust for the customers who bore the burden of the tax. Traynor J.'s decision was no doubt assisted by the trial testimony of the president of the vendor firm that it had retained invoices showing the names and addresses of all 882 customers who had paid the sales tax overpayment. Indeed, the case was remanded to the trial court &quot;with directions to enter judgment for plaintiff only if it submits proof satisfactory to the court that the refund will be returned to plaintiff's customers from whom the excess payments were erroneously  collected.&quot;<sup><a href="#one83">183</a></sup> In these circumstances, it would be a relatively easy matter to return the overpayments to the customers, and the result seems just and enlightened. But it is also evident that such information may be available in only a few cases, possibly limiting the applicability of the <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite> approach. On the facts of <cite>Shannon</cite>, for example, involving many thousands of customers about whom there may be very little information, and a relatively small amount of money paid by each customer, the <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite> approach would certainly be much more difficult to apply. Similarly, on the facts of <cite>123 East Fifty-Fourth Street</cite>, it is unclear how a requirement that the restaurant hold the tax payments in question on trust for those customers who had made them would help resolve the situation, because in all likelihood there would be no way to trace any of the customers who had paid the tax. 
 <p>
<h3>9.  Re-Ordering `Passing On'</h3>

The potential application of the `passing on' defence may arise in three different ways. I argue that in all three situations, the plaintiff taxpayer should recover against the government, but certain conditions may apply to this recovery. My later discussion examines what should happen after the plaintiff firm recovers from the public authority, and analyzes the proper relationship between the plaintiff and its customers. In all of these cases, we must suppose that the government has received tax payments from the plaintiff firm under a statute which has subsequently been ruled <i>ultra vires</i> or unconstitutional. The first situation involves cases in which the plaintiff firm has acted as a tax collection agent for the government. In such cases, a public authority has imposed a
statutory obligation on the plaintiff firm to collect the taxes and forward the proceeds to it. Such a tax (a sales tax) usually applies to the final product produced by the firm, and the firm applies it as a surcharge on the bills given to its customers. In this type of case, the courts should apply the <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite> solution, which is to order that the government return the tax payments to the plaintiff firm, but that the plaintiff must hold these  payments on constructive trust for those of its customers who actually paid the tax. A constructive trust is imposed because it would be unjust enrichment as between the customers and the firm for the tax payments to be retained by the firm alone. A constructive trust is imposed to prevent unjust enrichment.<sup><a href="#one84">184</a></sup> As a corollary, the <cite>Duffy-Mott</cite> rule must also apply. Customers of the plaintiff who actually paid the tax in question must be able to sue the plaintiff firm to recover their portion of the tax moneys recovered.
<p>
This approach views the plaintiff firm as a conduit through which the tax payments may be returned to the customers who bore the economic burden of the tax.<sup><a href="#one85">185</a></sup> It ensures both that the public authority does not retain the enrichment to which it has no entitlement, and also that the moneys are returned to the parties who actually made the payments. It could be objected that it would be unfair to impose the responsibility of a constructive trust on the plaintiff firm. Yet in situations where it is feasible to impose a constructive trust, it is feasible precisely because accurate records are available and the customers who paid the
tax may be identified, as in <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite>, and thus, the burden would not be particularly onerous. In any event, it was not unfair for the government to impose the trust relationship on the plaintiff in the first place,<sup><a href="#one86">186</a></sup> so it is not clear why it would now be unfair for the court to impose such a trust relationship as a remedy. Another concern is that the firm would seem to face little incentive
to bring actions for recovery of tax where they would not benefit from any recovery because obliged to hold the proceeds on constructive trust for their customers. There are two responses to this. First, the constructive trust should not be of indefinite duration. After some reasonable period of time, the plaintiff should be entitled to retain unclaimed funds which it is holding on trust, and keep them for its own benefit. Second, it may be that the firm
has bargained with some or all of its customers to press their claim, so it may be compensated by them for doing so.<sup><a href="#one87">187</a></sup> Thus, firms are likely to face incentives to bring actions against the government for recovery of taxes even where they must hold the proceeds on constructive trust for their customers for a period of time. Furthermore, given these incentives, the plaintiff firm is likely to be a more efficient agent to return the tax payments to the customers than is the public authority.
<p>
The second class of cases are those in which, as in the first class, the plaintiff firm has acted as a tax collector for the government. But here, either the tax was not presented to the customers as a separate item on their bills or invoices, or else other factors ensure that the <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite> solution of a constructive trust is impracticable. As was outlined above,<sup><a href="#one88">188</a></sup> in many situations, the favourable factors present in <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite> ---such as a small number of identifiable customers, and a relatively large amount of tax paid by each customer---will be absent. Of the cases which we have examined, the alcoholic beverage tax in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> and the ice cream tax in <cite>Shannon</cite> are of this type. At first blush, this class of cases presents grave difficulties, such that a plaintiff may avoid making a claim in unjust enrichment at all.<sup><a href="#one89">189</a></sup> It is unlikely that there will be adequate information on the customers who actually paid the tax, making it potentially arduous to return the tax payments to
individual customers. Further, although the total amount of the tax payments may be considerable, the amount of money at stake for any given consumer who paid the tax may be small, so that individual consumers will have little incentive to seek recovery of their portion of the total tax payment. Nevertheless, it is my view that the <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite> remedy should still apply. Even where it may seem unlikely that the ultimate customers will `get their money back,' and that the plaintiff firm will receive a &quot;windfall,&quot; restitution should still be ordered. 
<p>
Three factors support this argument. First, the rules of civil procedure in several provinces permit class action suits to be brought,<sup><a href="#one90">190</a></sup> which ensures that if the total amount of money at stake is substantial, then there will be an incentive for a litigant representing the class of customers who paid the tax to seek
restitution from the plaintiff firm who has recovered from the government. This would be the case even if the amount of tax paid by any one customer is relatively small. Thus, the <cite>Duffy-Mott</cite> situation could apply even where litigants are relatively dispersed, and have a small individual interest in the litigation. Second, the
policy considerations motivating Wilson J. in her dissent in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, and Professor Birks in his writing on the subject---that there are overwhelming constitutional reasons why a government must not benefit from illegal taxation statutes by remaining unjustly enriched despite a finding of illegality---are compelling and should
make courts lean to a presumption of restitution in cases concerning tax payments to public authorities under invalid statutes. In this vein, the Law Commission in England has noted that the likely result of allowing a `passing on' defence is to enrich the government despite its having acted unlawfully.<sup><a href="#one91">191</a></sup> If awarding the occasional &quot;windfall&quot; to plaintiff firms is the price which must be paid to support this fundamental constitutional principle, then perhaps it is not an undue one. 
<p>
Professor Arrowsmith has argued that the `passing on' defence should be allowed only in situations where the enrichment was gained through &quot;duress&quot; on the part of the defendant public authority.<sup><a href="#one92">192</a></sup> As a result, she approves of the application of the defence by the majority in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, presumably on the grounds that <cite>Air Canada</cite> did not involve duress. She would not allow the defence to be advanced where the public authority's enrichment arose through duress, as in <cite>Mason</cite>.<sup><a href="#one93">193</a></sup> This argument is untenable. First, on the facts of the case, it may be argued that there was in fact duress (or reasonable apprehension thereof) in <cite>Air Canada</cite>. The broader point is that duress however, is generally an unhelpful concept in explaining cases for recovery of unlawful tax. More fundamentally, the thrust of the most recent developments in the law of restitution for payments made to public authorities under an <i>ultra vires</i> or unconstitutional statute, as exemplified by
<cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite>, is that the relationship between public authorities and private citizens should be governed by the requirement that the government must not be permitted to retain the fruits of unlawful action. If one adopts this view, then the problem involved in determining whether duress applies in a
particular situation---and the artificiality of implying duress into particular transactions---disappears. This is particularly true where the dispute centres around the imposition of a tax by a public authority: one need not be a libertarian to believe that &quot;the power to tax involves the power to destroy.&quot;<sup><a href="#one94">194</a></sup>
<p>
Third, as suggested above,<sup><a href="#one95">195</a></sup> the imposition of the illegal tax has likely had an adverse effect on the plaintiff's business, even if the plaintiff has not actually borne the burden of the tax, either because it acted as a tax collection agent, or else `passed on' the burden to its customers. Allowing recovery from the government can go some way toward compensating, if only roughly, for this loss. Strictly speaking, of course, there may be only an indirect relationship between the value of the taxation payments at stake, and the plaintiff's losses due to the imposition of an illegal tax, so that it might be argued that the plaintiff should instead pursue two separate actions: first, an action in unjust enrichment for recovery of the tax payments made to the public authority under the invalid statute (even if these amounts subsequently become the object of a restitutionary action launched by the firm's customers as in <cite>Duffy-Mott</cite>); and second, an action against the government in tort to recover for losses suffered by it due to &quot;wrongful taxation.&quot;<sup><a href="#one96">196</a></sup> It will be recalled that it is extremely difficult to determine the exact loss caused to a firm stemming from having an illegal tax imposed on it. A rule requiring the public authority to disgorge the entire tax payment would have a
valuable dual effect. It would compensate the plaintiff for its loss (even if the risk of overcompensation remained), thus avoiding difficult, expensive and often fruitless attempts to determine the precise loss caused to the plaintiff. Second, it would provide a powerful affirmation of the constitutional principle that public authorities must not benefit from unconstitutional acts.
<p>
The third class of cases are exemplified by the situation in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, in which the government imposed a tax on an input in the plaintiff's business. In <cite>Air Canada</cite>, this was a tax on aviation fuel. The province did not charge the tax on a per customer basis; the tax was charged to the plaintiff airlines on the aviation fuel alone. When the airlines invariably `passed on' the cost of the tax to their customers, the tax was not presented as a separate charge to customers. Similarly, the tax on aircraft parts and equipment in <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> was of this type. In such a situation, the court should <i>always</i> order restitution,
even though to do so may in effect provide a &quot;windfall&quot; to the plaintiff. But note that ordering restitution provides a &quot;windfall&quot; only <i>as between the plaintiff and its customers</i>. As between the government and the plaintiff, the government has unquestionably been unjustly enriched at the plaintiff's expense.
The fact that the plaintiff may have `passed on' the burden of the tax to its customers is irrelevant as between the two parties in the lawsuit. It may of course be very relevant in a lawsuit brought by the customers against the firm for recovery of the tax payments, but that is another matter.<sup><a href="#one97">197</a></sup> In part, the impulse behind the `passing on' defence is a valid one, namely a concern that the plaintiff's customers may ultimately have a better claim on the payments than the plaintiff itself. But this does not change the fact that as between the plaintiff firm and the public authority, the latter's claim pales.
  <p>
The use of a constructive trust imposed on the funds returned to the plaintiff by the government raises an important question. What should be done with funds which remain after the plaintiff has made good faith efforts to return them to its customers?  The issue was considered by the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals in <cite>Illinois Bell Telephone Co</cite>. v. <cite>Slattery</cite>.<sup><a href="#one98">198</a></sup> The U.S. Supreme Court had previously determined that the telephone company had made illegal overcharges and ordered it to repay these amounts to its customers.<sup><a href="#one99">199</a></sup> The telephone company made good faith efforts to locate its customers in order to pay the refunds, but because some customers could not be located, some unrefunded moneys remained. When the limitation period expired, the telephone company sought both to be discharged from the obligation to make any more refunds, and also to retain the money for its own use. The State of Illinois argued that the remaining funds must be retained in trust for the unlocated customers, or else be forfeited to the State as <i>bona vacantia</i>, under which personal property without an owner reverts to the sovereign. But the Court rejected the application of the doctrine here, on the basis that the customers were creditors of the telephone company, and that the debts dissolved on the expiration of the limitation period. The remaining funds were held to be the property of the telephone company.
<p>
However, in a California case, concerning moneys resulting from a determination that a streetcar company in San Francisco had been unlawfully charging a seven cent fare instead of a six cent fare, it was held that the moneys should revert to the city, and not the company. In <cite>Market Street Railway Co</cite>. v. <cite>Railroad
Commission</cite>,<sup><a href="#twohundred">200</a></sup> the illegal fare resulted in a surplus of some $705,000 over what would have been collected under a legal fare. Of this, almost $12,000 was returned to customers, leaving $693,000 in an uncertain state. The streetcar company, relying on <cite>Illinois Bell Telephone Co</cite>.,<sup><a href="#two01">201</a></sup> sought a declaration that the unrefunded moneys were its property. The Court held that the moneys should be given to the city, in the belief that this was the most effective way to return the money to &quot;the people of the city.&quot; Edmonds J. in dissent argued that the customers had abandoned the excess fare to the streetcar company by not seeking refunds within the limitation period. In my view, <cite>Illinois Bell Telephone Co.</cite> is the preferable approach. Where there are remaining moneys after good faith efforts to return tax payments to customers, the moneys should be retained by the plaintiff firm who recovered them from the government.<sup><a href="#two02">202</a></sup> This approach provides an incentive for plaintiffs to press suits against the government, while ensuring that where appropriate customers are permitted to recover against the plaintiff firm.
<p>
The European cases point to a final consideration: the burden of proof. The Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> and the British Columbia Court of Appeal in <cite>Allied Air Conditioning</cite> were all of the opinion that the plaintiffs in an action for restitution of taxes unlawfully collected bear a burden of demonstrating not only that the enrichment in question has been at their expense, but that in addition, they did not `pass on' the burden of the tax to their customers. Clearly, it is my view that `passing on' has little merit as a defence. But at the very least the courts should create a rebuttable presumption that a payment of tax to a public authority under an illegal or <i>ultra vires</i> statute is a deprivation on the part of the person who paid the tax. Under this approach, it would be incumbent upon the public authority advancing the `passing on' defence to demonstrate that the burden of the tax payments had actually been borne by the plaintiff's customers through direct and specific `passing on.'  As cases such as <cite>Hans Just, San Giorgio, Re Repayment of Illegal Taxes,</cite> and <cite>Fils de Jules Bianco</cite> make clear, the onus should be placed on the government to demonstrate `passing on,' because the imposition of the burden of proof on the plaintiff seeking
restitution is all too often a burden which is extremely difficult to discharge. It must be remembered that it is the public authority which has &quot;received payments which it was not entitled to demand and presumptively to retain.&quot;<sup><a href="#two03">203</a></sup> It is the public authority which should bear the burden of advancing its defence. If a broad scope is given to the `passing on' defence, the emerging principle that a public authority must not retain tax payments acquired under an unconstitutional or <i>ultra vires</i> statute will be seriously compromised.
<p>
<h3>10.  Conclusion</h3>

The law regulating the recovery of unlawfully collected taxes is in danger of diverging from the general principles of unjust enrichment. This unsound development is due largely to the acceptance of defences such as `passing on,' and should be resisted. A primary culprit has been the Supreme Court of Canada's willingness to embrace the `passing on' defence. The Supreme Court's own decisions in <cite>Air Canada</cite> and <cite>Canadian Pacific Airlines</cite> appear contradictory, and have led to considerable confusion, as <cite>Allied Air  Conditioning</cite> and other recent decisions indicate. In my view, the `passing on' defence should be rejected, because it undermines general restitutionary principles, has an unsound economic basis, and strikes at the heart of constitutional government. The European and American experience make this clear. The better approach would be for the Supreme Court of Canada to reject the `passing on' defence altogether, and enunciate a clear general right
of recovery for taxes collected without a legal basis, as the House of Lords did in <cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite>. In certain limited situations it will be appropriate to require that a tax refund be held on constructive trust for the plaintiff firm's customers. But concern for the plaintiff's customers should not allow the government to retain the tax payments in the first place, to which it has no valid claim whatsoever. Only in this way will the values of restitution be upheld, as well as the important constitutional principles which militate against the government's retention of unlawfully collected taxation.
<p>
