<li><a name="sixty"><cite>Air Canada</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 21 at 1204, La Forest J.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty1">McCamus, <i>supra</i> note 2 at 254--260; Palmer, <i>supra</i> note 55, at 246--258;
O. Field, &quot;The Recovery of Illegal and Unconstitutional Taxes&quot; (1932) 45 Harv. L. Rev. 501 at 516.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty2"><i>See</i> Birks,</a> <cite>An Introduction to the Law of Restitution</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 298. Note that Professor Birks appears to have reconsidered his earlier position: P.B.H. Birks, &quot;Restitution from Public Authorities&quot; (1980) 33 Curr. Leg. Probs. 191 at 204--205. He now
argues that &quot;[t]he courts must give priority to the rule of law, not to expedient measures to meet fiscal inconveniences ...&quot; <i>see</i> P. Birks, <cite>Restitution---The Future</cite> (Sydney: Federation Press, 1992) at 72; also S.J. Stoljar, <cite>The Law of Quasi-Contract</cite>, 2d ed. (Sydney: The Law Book Co., 1989) at 72--73.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty3">In <cite>Air Canada</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 21 at 1204--1205, La Forest J. discusses the difficulties which arose in the United States after a provision eliminating the mistake of law/mistake of fact distinction was inserted into the recovery section of the Internal Revenue Code. In <cite>United States v. Butler</cite>, 297 U.S. 1 (1936), the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the <cite>Agricultural Adjustment Act</cite>, which would have led to almost $1 billion in restitutionary claims against the federal government. Congress then passed a statute which allowed recovery only where the plaintiff could demonstrate that it had not `passed on' the cost of the tax to its customers, which severely limited recovery. The difficulty in Canada, as La Forest J. notes, is that the rule in <cite>Amax Potash</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 52, would seem to preclude provinces from resorting to this legislative solution in cases of potential `fiscal chaos.'  This may be so, which
should encourage provincial governments to enact some of the other measures suggested in the text, such as limitation periods, to regulate recovery of unlawful taxes. The great irony, as Professor Arrowsmith notes (&quot;Restitution and Mistake of Law in Canada [Case Comment]&quot; (1990) 106 L.Q.R. 28 at 32) is that <cite>Amax Potash</cite>'s strong rule against legislatures attempting to secure the fruits of invalid action by other means, ends up justifying the draconian limits on the right to recovery of unlawful taxes by seeming to preclude the legislative option in cases where recovery would be severely prejudicial to the public finances.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty4">Indeed, the decision</a> of the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Storthoaks</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 24, makes no mention of a special `fiscal chaos' defence open to public authorities.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty5"><cite>Lipkin Gorman</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 11 at 580, Lord Goff: &quot;the defence is available to a person whose position has so changed that it would be inequitable in all the circumstances to require him to make restitution, or alternatively, to make restitution in full.&quot;  La Forest J. recognized the
potential application of a change of position defence in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 21 at 1201.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty6"><cite>R</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Tower Hamlets London Borough Council, ex p. Chetnik Developments Ltd</cite>., [1988] A.C. 858 (H.L.).
<p>
<li><a name="sixty7">Burrows,</a> <cite>The Law of Restitution</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 358; Goff &amp; Jones, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 552. Graham Virgo argues that the change of position defence should be available to a public authority only where it can show an &quot;extraordinary expenditure&quot;: G. Virgo, &quot;The Law of Taxation is Not an Island---Overpaid Taxes and the Law of Restitution&quot; [1993] Brit. Tax
Rev. 442 at 459.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty8">&quot;Restitution of Taxes,&quot;</a> <i>supra</i> note 22 at 429.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty9">See The Law Commission,</a> <cite>Restitution of Payments Made Under a Mistake of Law</cite> (Consultation Paper No. 120) (London: HMSO, 1991) at 107--115, which suggests various alternative
rules for limiting the liability of public authorities to actions in restitution for repayment of taxes. These include a `no retrospective effect' rule (recovery would be restricted to those plaintiffs who had sought recovery of the payments before the payments were held to be invalid), a change of position defence, short limitation periods, or legislation precluding recovery. Woodward, <i>supra</i> note 30 at 929, suggests that in certain cases, courts should allow public authorities to repay in installments in order to minimize fiscal disruption.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy">See Collins,</a> <i>supra</i> note 2 at 429--437. The suggestion that it would be an
indirect burden on taxpayers if public authorities were required to return unjustly retained tax payments could equally be applied to deny governmental liability in tort and contract. Any time that the government must make a payment to a private person, such funds must come from general revenues.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy1">Estoppel was recently confirmed</a> by the Supreme Court of Canada as a defence against actions in unjust enrichment: <cite>Kenora (Town) Hydro Electric Commission v. Vacationland Dairy Co-Operative Ltd</cite>., [1994] 1 S.C.R. 80. Others have suggested a statutory limitation period (<cite>Woolwich Equitable Building Society</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 12 at 174, Lord Goff), with two years being a commonly-cited length of time within which to bring an action. See Virgo, <i>supra</i> note 67 at 461; Collins, <i>supra</i> note 2 at 435. La Forest J. in <cite>Air Canada</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 21 at 1206, noted a limitation period as a possibility but believed, rightly, that it was for the legislatures and not the
courts to design such a scheme.
