<li><a name="one03"><cite>Air Canada</cite></a> v. <cite>Ontario (Liquor Control Board)</cite> (March 1994), (Ont. Gen. Div.) [unreported] [hereinafter <cite>Liquor Control Board of Ontario</cite>]. At the time of writing, the case is on appeal to the Ontario Court of Appeal: <cite>The Globe &amp; Mail</cite> (3 November 1994) at B9.
<p>
<li><a name="one04">[<cite>Liquor Control Board of Ontario</cite>], <i>ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a naem = "one05">See e.g.</a> <cite>Sunbeam Corporation (Canada) Ltd. v. The Queen</cite> (1994), 2 G.T.C. 7013 at 7022 (F.C.T.D.): &quot;Even if it could be considered that the Crown here received a
benefit, that was not at the expense or deprivation of the plaintiff. Where the economic burden of the tax is shifted to others, for example where it is passed on to customers through sales prices, then the plaintiff does not establish that any gain to the Crown was at its expense.&quot; (citing <cite>Air Canada</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 21 at
1202--1203).
<p>
<li><a name="one06"><cite>Pettkus</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 7.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one07">There is some dispute</a> as to whether the `passing on' defence may also apply where the defendant is not a public authority. Burrows, <i>supra</i> note 28 at 59, indicates that `passing on' &quot;has been advocated exclusively for public authorities.&quot;  Yet in <cite>The Law of Restitution</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 476, Burrows interprets the majority decision in <cite>Air Canada</cite> to hold that `passing on' is a valid defence for public authorities &quot;although apparently not confined to such a defendant.&quot;  In my view, the `passing on' defence may be raised by public authorities alone because only they are in a position to impose a trust-like obligation on a business in requiring it to collect tax payments from its customers for the public authority's benefit.
<p>
<li><a name="one08">A case which seems to</a> suggest that `passing on' is available to private parties as a defence in a restitutionary action is <cite>Linz v. Electric Wire Co. of Palestine</cite>, [1948] A.C. 371 (P.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Linz</cite>]. The plaintiff purchased shares in the defendant company and later sold them at a loss to a third party. It was then discovered that the company resolution under which the shares had been issued had been invalid. The plaintiff sought recovery of the money she had paid for the shares, arguing that she had received no consideration from the defendant for her money. She also made it clear that if she recovered from the defendant, she did not intend to relinquish the money she had received when she sold her shares to the third party.
The plaintiff's claim was dismissed on the grounds that she had received consideration for her initial outlay of money in the form of the money she had received when she finally sold the shares, albeit at a loss. Lord Simonds noted that the plaintiff's rights against the company &quot;must be the same whether she sold them [the shares] at
their par value or for more or less&quot; (at 377). On one view, the case can be seen as endorsing the position that a party who has suffered a loss, but had `passed on' the loss to a third party, should not be able to bring an action in restitution against the party who was enriched at her expense. Commentators, however, have been very critical of <cite>Linz</cite>, on the grounds that it relies on a defective `no consideration' form of reasoning: see Birks, <cite>An Introduction to the Law of Restitution</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 248; Goff &amp; Jones,  <i>supra</i> note 6 at 402. It does not provide a strong ground for the argument that a `passing on' defence is
available to private defendants.
<p>
<li><a name="one09">&quot;Subjective devaluation&quot;</a> embodies the idea that benefit may be a subjective concept. For example, if A cleans B's car, B may argue that she has not been enriched because she prefers to drive a dirty car. If A mistakenly leaves $100 in B's car, however, B cannot dispute that she has been
enriched, because by definition as a medium of exchange, money cannot be subjectively devalued: Birks, <cite>An Introduction to the Law of Restitution</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 109--114. See <cite>B.P. Exploration Co. (Libya) Ltd. v. Hunt (No. 2),</cite> [1979] 1 W.L.R. 783 at 799, Robert Goff J.
<p>
<li><a name="one10">Woodward,</a> <i>supra</i> note 30, 873 at 888 (&quot;If the principle that a plaintiff
should not be overcompensated were behind the defence, then the court would have inquired into the plaintiff's actual loss resulting from the imposition of the illegal tax, and the court mught have permitted a refund up to that amount. We do not find this analysis in the cases, however.&quot; [footnote omitted]).
