<p>
<li><a name="one16">[1951] 2 A.C. 507 (H.L.)</a> [hereinafter <cite>Reading</cite>]. The plaintiff, a British Army officer, was paid to accompany civilian trucks carrying smuggled liquor. He wore his uniform so that the trucks would not be inspected by the military police. When caught, the money he had received was seized. He later brought an action in unjust enrichment for recovery of the money. The House of Lords held that he could not recover, even though the Crown had &quot;lost no profits or suffered no damage.&quot; Lord Porter held that &quot;[i]t is the receipt and possession of the money that matters, not the loss or prejudice to the master [<i>i.e</i>. the Crown]&quot; (at 516).
<p>
<li><a name="one17"><cite>Edwards</cite></a> v. <cite>Lee's Administrator</cite>, 96 S.W. 2d 1028 (Kentucky C.A. 1936) [hereinafter <cite>Edwards</cite>]. The defendant discovered a cave with magnificent rock formations under his land and charged tourists for admission to it. The plaintiff, an adjoining landowner, brought suit, alleging that part of the cave was under his land, such that the defendants had been unjustly enriched. He sought an accounting of the defendant's profits. The Court ordered recovery, even though the plaintiff had suffered no loss.
