<li><a name="one49">A decree-law is</a> provisional legislation of limited duration which expires unless
converted into a statute.
<p>
<li><a name="one50"><i>Supra</i> note 144.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one51"><cite>Re Repayment of Illegal Taxes</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> note 148 at 29.
<p>
<li><a name="one52">Cases 331/85, 376/85</a> and 378/85, [1988] E.C.R. 1099, [1989] 3 C.M.L.R. 36 (E.C.J.) [hereinafter <cite>Fils de Jules Bianco</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="one53"><i>Ibid.</i> at 49.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one54">C.L. Pannam,</a> &quot;The Recovery of Unconstitutional Taxes in Australia and the United States&quot; (1964) 42 Texas L. Rev. 777; O.P. Field, <i>supra</i> note 61.
<p>
<li><a name="one55">For example,</a> Internal Revenue Code provisions, 26 U.S.C.A. s 6415--6416, and cases cited therein.
<p>
<li><a name="one56">468 U.S. 263,</a> 104 S.Ct. 3049 (1984).
<p>
<li><a name="one57">The statute discriminated</a> in favour of Hawaii liquor products, and was thus a
violation of the Commerce Clause of the U.S. Constitution (U.S. Constitution, s. 8, para. 3: &quot;The Congress shall have power ... To regulate Commerce ... among the several States.&quot;).
<p>
<li><a name="one58">See Section 5.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one59">See also</a> <cite>Division of Alcoholic Beverages v. McKesson Corp.</cite>, 524 So.2d 1000 (S.C. Fla. 1988). Wholesale distributors of alcoholic beverages challenged the validity of a Florida tax which granted preferential treatment to products made from Florida agricultural products. The Court agreed that the impugned taxation statute was unconstitutional, but declined to order the State to refund the payments, suggesting that if given a refund, the wholesalers &quot;would in all probability receive a windfall, since the cost of the tax has likely been passed on to their customers.&quot; (at 1010).
<p>
<li><a name="one60"><i>Supra</i> note 132.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one61"><i>Ibid</i>. at 448, Van Devanter J.</a>
<p>
