<p>
<li><a name="one75">See Section Five.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one76"><cite>123 East Fifty-Fourth Street, Inc.</cite></a> v. <cite>United States</cite>, 157 F.2d 68 (2d Cir. 1946) [hereinafter <cite>123 East Fifty-Fourth Street</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="one77"><i>Ibid</i>. at 70, Chase J.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one78">A similar distinction</a> of form argument was considered by the U.S. Supreme Court in <cite>Jefferson Electric</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 132. There, the Court held that the manner in which the plaintiff had represented the tax in question on its invoices to its customers should determine whether it should recover the tax payments from the government once the controlling statute was held unconstitutional.
<p>
<li><a name="one79"><cite>Wayne County Produce Co</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Duffy-Mott Co</cite>., 155 N.E. 669 (N.Y.C.A. 1927) [hereinafter <cite>Duffy-Mott</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="one80">1 N.Y. 359 (1848)</a> [hereinafter <cite>Moore</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="one81">See also</a> <cite>Heckman &amp; Co</cite>. v. <cite>Dawes &amp; Son Co</cite>., 12 F.2d 154 (App. D.C. 1926) (Customer denied recovery because tax deemed to have been `paid' by the firm to
the government, and not by the customer.)
<p>
