[1990] 1 S.C.R. 70, 65 D.L.R. (4th) 161 at 184, McLachlin J. (the constructive trust is a &quot;general remedy for unjust enrichment.&quot;); <cite>Hunter Engineering v. Syncrude Canada Ltd</cite>., [1989] 1 S.C.R. 426.
<p>
<li><a name="one85">Compare</a> <cite>Sabena Belgian World Airlines v. Gulf Products Co</cite>. (1992), 132 A.R. 229 (Q.B.).
<p>
<li><a name="one86">Indeed,</a> all sales taxes rely on the vehicle of a trust imposed on the vendor by statute, requiring that it collect tax revenues from its customers and forward the payments to the government. See <cite>The Queen in Right of British Columbia v. Henfry Samson Belair Ltd.,</cite> [1989] 2 S.C.R. 24, 59 D.L.R. (4th) 726.
<p>
<li><a name="one87">As in</a> <cite>Benzoline Motor Fuel Co. v. Bollinger,</cite> <i>supra</i> note 168.
<p>
<li><a name="one88">In the discussion of</a> <cite>Decorative Carpets</cite>, <i>supra</i> at text accompanying notes 182--183.
<p>
<li><a name="one89"><cite>Sebel Products Ltd</cite>.</a> v. <cite>Commissioners of Customs and Excise</cite>, [1949] 1 Ch. 409, [1949] 1 All E.R. 729, provides a good illustration. The manufacturer of a rocker swing sought a declaration that its product was a &quot;swing&quot; and thus exempt from purchase tax. The Commissioners disputed this, and the manufacturer paid the tax. In the interim, the manufacturer sold some of the rocker swings to customers at a price including the disputed purchase tax. The customers could no longer be traced. The manufacturer brought an action seeking recovery of the purchase tax which it had paid, but only sought to recover the tax attributable to the unsold rocker swings. The issue of passing on was thus neatly avoided, in that the plaintiff sought recovery only for those tax payments which it had not passed on to its customers. The manufacturer was awarded recovery.
<p>
<li><a name="one90">In Ontario,</a> see <cite>Class Proceedings Act, 1992</cite>, S.O. 1992, c. 6; also Rules of Civil Procedure, r. 12 (Class Proceedings).
<p>
<li><a name="one91"><i>Supra</i> note 69 at 116.</a> However, the Law Commission concluded that &quot;in principle there would appear to be no reason why such a defence should not apply to cases where the authority can prove on the balance of probabilities that the payer would be unjustly enriched because the charge has been passed on.&quot; <i>Ibid.</i>, at 118. In my view, this gloss undermines the statement quoted in the main body of the  text.
<p>
<li><a name="one92">Arrowsmith,</a> &quot;Mistake and the Role of the `Submission to an Honest Claim'&quot; in Burrows, <cite>Essays on the Law of Restitution</cite>, at 21.
<p>
<li><a name="one93"><i>Supra</i> note 37.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one94"><cite>McCulloch</cite></a> v. <cite>Maryland</cite>, 17 U.S. (4 Wheaton) 316 at 431 (1819), Marshall C.J.
<p>
<li><a name="one95">See Section Five.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one96">The problem is that</a> such an action is not recognized under existing law. <i>See</i> Committee of the JUSTICE-All Souls Review of Administrative Law in the United Kingdom, <cite>Administrative Justice: Some Necessary Reforms</cite> (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1988) at 344.
<p>
<li><a name="one97">See</a> <cite>Restatement of the Law of Restitution,</cite> s 141(1):
<blockquote>
A person who has taken from the possession of another, or has received from or on account of another, things in which a third person has an interest which is superior and antagonistic to the interest of the other, cannot defeat the claim of the other for restitution merely because of such superior interests.
</blockquote>
<li><a name="one98">102 F.2d 58</a> (7th Cir. 1939) [hereinafter <cite>Illinois Bell Telephone Co</cite>.]. An analogous Canadian situation was the subject of <cite>Bell Canada v. Canada (CRTC)</cite>, [1989] 1 S.C.R. 1722. The CRTC had allowed Bell to make an interim rate increase, but later determined that the increase was not merited and ordered Bell to refund the amounts collected to its customers. The case before the Supreme Court concerned the CRTC's jurisdiction to make such orders, and the issue of restitution did not arise. Note, however, that the CRTC allowed Bell to make a one-time refund to its customers, rather than enter into the
complexities of determining which of its customers had actually been deprived of which amount.
<p>
<li><a name="one99"><cite>Lindheimer et al. v. Illinois Bell Telephone Company</cite></a>, 292
U.S. 151 (1934).
<p>
<li><a name="twohundred">28 Cal. 2d 363,</a> 171 P.2d 875 (S.C. Cal., 1946).
<p>
<li><a name="two01"><i>Supra</i> note 198.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="two02">Hand J.'s dissent in</a> <cite>123 East Fifth-Fourth Street</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 176 at 71, supports the view that the government should not be permitted to retain the tax payments merely because it fears that the plaintiff firm may be &quot;truant&quot; in its obligation to hold the payments on constructive trust for its customers and make efforts to return the moneys to them.
<p>
<li><a name="two03">G. Jones,</a> &quot;The Law of Restitution: The Past and the Future&quot; in Burrows, <cite>Essays on the Law of Restitution</cite>, at 9; Jones, <i>supra</i> note 30 at 45.
