<html>
<head>
<title>UTLR Vol. 52 No. 2: Abstract 1</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol52#2">Volume 52 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>The Change of Position Defence in Restitution
<p> 
JONATHAN DAWE</h1>

<center><h3>ABSTRACT / <a  href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/utlr52-2/dawe.htm">Fulltext</a></h3></center>

Although almost all common law jurisdictions now allow claims in restitution (or &quot;unjust  enrichment&quot;) to be resisted by a &quot;change of position&quot; defence, considerable disagreement exists
with respect to the defence's conceptual basis. As long as the principle underlying the defence remains unclear, the law will be uncertain. In order to determine who can invoke the defence, and in what situations, it is necessary to have an understanding of why the defence exists and what it is supposed to accomplish. In this paper, the author considers the two leading understandings of the defence: the idea that the defence is based on considerations of equity and fairness between the parties, and the alternative view that the defence is rooted in the nature of the defendant's enrichment. The author argues that while neither explanation is completely free of problems, the enrichment-based understanding provides a more coherent and logical basis for the change of position defence.
<p>
Bien que, dans presque tous les ressorts de common law, le fait d'avoir modifi&eacute; sa situation constitue un moyen de d&eacute;fense contre une action en restitution, les avis sont partag&eacute;s quant aux assises th&eacute;oriques de cette d&eacute;fense. Aussi longtemps que les principes sous-jacents demeureront incertains, l'&eacute;tat du droit le sera &eacute;galement, car on ne peut d&eacute;terminer, ni les personnes qui peuvent invoquer cette d&eacute;fense, ni les situations dans lesquelles elle peut &ecirc;tre soulev&ecute;e, si on ne comprend pas sa raison d'&ecirc;tre et les finalit&eacute;s qu'elle vise. Dans cet article, l'auteur traite des deux principales th&eacute;ories de ce moyen de d&eacute;fense, &agrave; savoir: celle selon laquelle la d&eacute;fense cherche &agrave; &eacute;tablir des conditions &eacute;quitables ou justes entre les parties, et celle qui tourne autour de la nature de l'enrichissement dont le d&eacute;fendeur a b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute;. Selon l'auteur, ni l'une ni l'autre de ces explications ne sont id&eacute;ales. Entre les deux, cependant, l'analyse de la nature de l'enrichissement a l'avantage d'&ecirc;tre plus coh&eacute;rente et logique.
<p><br>
<hr>
