Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Saturday, 17-Aug-96 07:16:42 GMT
Content-length: 89160
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v52n2.htm">Volume 52 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1>The Change of Position Defence in Restitution<a href="#note">*</a>
<p> 
JONATHAN DAWE</h1>
<p><br>
<i>Although almost all common law jurisdictions now allow claims in restitution (or &quot;unjust  enrichment&quot;) to be resisted by a &quot;change of position&quot; defence, considerable disagreement exists
with respect to the defence's conceptual basis. As long as the principle underlying the defence remains unclear, the law will be uncertain. In order to determine who can invoke the defence, and in what situations, it is necessary to have an understanding of why the defence exists and what it is supposed to accomplish. In this paper, the author considers the two leading understandings of the defence: the idea that the defence is based on considerations of equity and fairness between the parties, and the alternative view that the defence is rooted in the nature of the defendant's enrichment. The author argues that while neither explanation is completely free of problems, the enrichment-based understanding provides a more coherent and logical basis for the change of position defence.
<p>
Bien que, dans presque tous les ressorts de common law, le fait d'avoir modifi&eacute; sa situation constitue un moyen de d&eacute;fense contre une action en restitution, les avis sont partag&eacute;s quant aux assises th&eacute;oriques de cette d&eacute;fense. Aussi longtemps que les principes sous-jacents demeureront incertains, l'&eacute;tat du droit le sera &eacute;galement, car on ne peut d&eacute;terminer, ni les personnes qui peuvent invoquer cette d&eacute;fense, ni les situations dans lesquelles elle peut &ecirc;tre soulev&ecute;e, si on ne comprend pas sa raison d'&ecirc;tre et les finalit&eacute;s qu'elle vise. Dans cet article, l'auteur traite des deux principales th&eacute;ories de ce moyen de d&eacute;fense, &agrave; savoir: celle selon laquelle la d&eacute;fense cherche &agrave; &eacute;tablir des conditions &eacute;quitables ou justes entre les parties, et celle qui tourne autour de la nature de l'enrichissement dont le d&eacute;fendeur a b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute;. Selon l'auteur, ni l'une ni l'autre de ces explications ne sont id&eacute;ales. Entre les deux, cependant, l'analyse de la nature de l'enrichissement a l'avantage d'&ecirc;tre plus coh&eacute;rente et logique.</i>
<p><br>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

Over the past century, courts throughout the common law world have gradually come to recognize restitution as an independent branch of private law, distinct from tort and contract and grounded in the concept of unjust enrichment. In many jurisdictions, recognition of the law of restitution has been followed by the adoption of what is generally referred to as a defence of &quot;change of position.&quot;  The defence permits recipients of benefits who would
otherwise be liable to claims in restitution to resist such claims in whole or in part, on the ground that events that have transpired since the benefit was received make it impossible for them to make full restitution without placing themselves in a worse position than they were in before the benefit was received. While it is most often invoked in cases involving mistaken payments of money, the defence can also arise in cases where the benefit is non-monetary, or in cases where the transfer of the benefit was induced by a third party. A change of position defence was set out in the 1937 American <cite>Restatement of Restitution</cite>,<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> while in Canada the Supreme Court recognized the defence's legitimacy in its 1975 decision in <cite>Rural Municipality of Storthoaks v. Mobil Oil Canada Ltd.</cite><sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> More recently, in the 1991 case of <cite>Lipkin Gorman v. Karpnale Ltd.</cite><sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> the English House of Lords followed suit and approved of the change of position defence, thereby bringing the law in England into line both with the weight of academic opinion<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> and with the position taken by North American courts. In light of these developments, the defence now appears to be firmly established as an important component of the law of restitution in the common law world.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup>
<p>
In the face of this apparent triumph of the change of position defence, it is somewhat surprising to discover that both its conceptual basis and its relation to the principles of restitution have yet to be fully analysed, either by the courts or by academic writers. Many commentators characterize the defence as flowing from considerations of equity. For example, Fridman and McLeod take the position that &quot;[o]ne situation which would appear to render it
inequitable for the defendant to be required to disgorge a benefit received from the plaintiff in the absence of any wrongdoing on the part of the defendant would be if he has changed his position for the worse as a result of the receipt in question.&quot;<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> The nature of the inequity that would be caused by
making the defendant provide full restitution, however, has remained largely unexplored. In <cite>Lipkin Gorman</cite>, Lord Goff declared:
<blockquote>
[I]t is right that we should ask ourselves: why do we feel that it would be unjust to allow restitution in cases such as these [where the defendant has changed his or her position]?  The answer must be that, where an innocent defendant's position is so changed that he will suffer an injustice if called upon to repay or to repay in full, the injustice of requiring him to repay outweighs the injustice of denying the plaintiff restitution.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup>
</blockquote>
As an explanation for the defence, this is unsatisfactory. It merely restates the underlying problem: if the basis of the
defence is the injustice of requiring repayment in these circumstances, why is it that the law considers the injustice full repayment would cause to the defendant to be greater than the injustice of denying the plaintiff full restitution?
<p>
It has been suggested<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> as an alternative that the defence can best be
understood in an entirely different way: rather than seeing it as motivated by considerations of fairness between the parties, it is possible to envision the change of position defence as a corollary to the principles underlying the claim in restitution in which it arises. Resolving the question of the defence's basis is important not only in terms of our theoretical understanding of the law of restitution, but will also ultimately have significant consequences for the practical operation of the change of position defence, since the contours of the defence will inevitably be shaped to reflect courts' understandings of its purpose.
<p>
It is useful to consider the problem in terms of the definition of unjust enrichment set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Pettkus v. Becker</cite>:<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup>
<blockquote>
[T]here are three requirements to be satisfied before an unjust enrichment can be said to exist---an enrichment, a
corresponding deprivation and absence of any juristic reason for the enrichment.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Assuming that the second requirement---that the plaintiff has suffered a deprivation corresponding to the defendant's enrichment---is satisfied,<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> the defence of change of position has two potential bases. The first possibility is that a change of position by the defendant affects the first factor---the defendant's enrichment. That is, in some cases the defendant may have consumed or disposed of part of the original
enrichment in some fashion, so that by the time the plaintiff makes his or her claim the defendant's &quot;enrichment&quot; (as recognized by law) has wholly or partially dissipated. Under this line of reasoning, the principles of restitution might thus require only that the defendant remit to the plaintiff the lesser amount or
&quot;enrichment,&quot; however defined, that remains. A second possibility is that the defence of change of position has its origins in the third branch of the test---the requirement that there be an absence of juristic reason for the retention of the enrichment by the defendant. In other words, even if the defendant is thought to remain &quot;enriched&quot; there may be some countervailing juristic reason triggered by a change of position that entitles him or her to retain a portion of the enrichment. The juristic reason could, for instance, be based on considerations of fault, or implied representations by the plaintiff, or it might depend on some other set of factors.
<p>
In what follows, these two alternative bases for the change of position defence will be explored in more detail, and an attempt will be made to discover the preferable manner of approaching the problem. Before embarking on this course of action, however, it is necessary as a preliminary step to consider in more detail what is meant by a &quot;change of position.&quot;
<p>
<h3>&quot;Change of Position&quot; Defined</h3>

How is it that recipients of benefits can change their position in such a way that they would suffer if forced to disgorge them?  Suppose, for the sake of simplicity, that the benefit in question is a monetary payment mistakenly conferred. With the excess money in hand, the recipient may alter his or her spending patterns, and spend part or all of the mistaken payment on goods or services that he or she would not have purchased if the mistaken payment had
not been made. If called on to repay the money under a claim for restitution, it may be impossible for the recipient to return himself or herself to the position he or she occupied before the payment was made: purchased goods or services may have been irretrievably consumed, or they may have depreciated in value. Either way, forcing the recipient to return the full amount of the initial mistaken payment would leave the defendant worse off than he or she was at the outset, notwithstanding the fact that the recipient obtained some benefit from the goods or services consumed.
<p>
Although this point is to some extent self-evident, it is of such importance to the discussion of the change of position defence that it is worth examining in some detail.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> Suppose that
prior to receiving a mistaken payment a defendant has a certain initial income. If there is a range of uses to which he or she can put that money (i.e., spending it on goods and services, saving it, or giving it away) he or she will distribute it among those alternatives by allotting specific amounts to each one. This will be done in such a way as to maximize the utility the defendant derives from the expenditures.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup>
<p>
Now, suppose that the defendant receives a mistaken payment, which elevates his or her income to a higher level. The defendant will plan to distribute this new amount among the alternatives in a new manner that maximizes utility at this new level.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> What happens if, after having expended some or all of the money on this new distribution, the defendant is presented with a claim for restitution of the mistaken payment?  If the defendant can return his or her spending allocations to the initial distribution he or she will suffer no loss of utility by being made to return the money. This will be possible if no irretrievable expenditures that differ from
the first utility-maximizing distribution have yet been made. For instance, a defendant will suffer no loss if he or she has simply put the mistaken payment in the bank and not yet otherwise altered his or her spending patterns, or if he or she has spent some of the money buying a Rembrandt that he or she can resell at the price she paid for it. 
However, if some of the expenditures that differ from the original distribution are not recoverable, the defendant will, in general, experience an overall decrease in utility if he or she is made to return the entire mistaken payment:  it will be impossible for the defendant to return to the initial distribution, which by assumption was the distribution
that maximized utility at the initial level of income.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> This will be the case even though the defendant may have gained <i>some</i> utility from the non-optimal expenditures.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
<p>
The defendant's loss of utility from misallocating his or her expenditures as a result of the mistake stems from the fact that people are generally not indifferent to alternative ways of allocating their resources. As a simple example, suppose X lives in a world where the only two commodities are bread and jam. If she has $10, suppose that she will choose to divide it evenly between bread and jam, on the assumption that this distribution of her resources maximizes her utility at this level of income. X derives a certain amount of utility from having $5 worth of bread
and $5 worth of jam, and gains even more utility if she can have the two together and indulge her fondness for jam sandwiches. Suppose, now, that she is the recipient of a mistaken payment of $2. She may now decide to distribute her new higher income by spending $6 each on bread and jam.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> If she
spends $6 on jam, and is then made to repay the $2 (before she has been able to buy bread) she will have only $4 remaining to spend on bread. The utility X can obtain will, as a result, be diminished---although she will gain some utility from having the extra dollar's worth of jam, this is worth less to her in and of itself than an additional dollar's worth of bread. Her overall utility is further decreased by the fact that she will now be able to make fewer jam sandwiches than could be made under her initial distribution of $10.
<p>
Receiving a mistaken payment can also cause a defendant to change his or her position in a related, but distinct manner. With the mistaken payment in hand, the recipient may choose to forgo income-earning opportunities in favour of leisure or some other activity. For example, after receiving a mistaken payment a defendant may decide not to volunteer for additional hours of overtime, choosing instead to go home and read a book. By being forced to return the money, the recipient can be affected in exactly the same way as if he or she had irretrievably spent an equivalent amount of the payment---from an economic point of view, the two situations are indistinguishable.
<p>
From this discussion, a few general observations can be extracted. To begin, it can be seen that in cases involving changes of position, whatever caused the benefit to be conferred---for instance, a mistake of fact or law or the actions of a third party---creates a net decrease in the well-being of the two parties. Although the defence
of change of position may or may not be conceived of as having as its <i>purpose</i> the allocation of this loss between the parties, it is useful to bear in mind that the <i>effect</i> of the defence, however understood, will be to distribute the loss between the parties in some way. As a second observation, it can be noted that there is nothing in the above analysis that suggests that only expenditures that deviate radically from the recipient's usual spending  patterns produce a change in position---when combined, a series of incremental changes in expenditure can have the same effect as a single extraordinary outlay.
<p>
There is, of course, an enormous practical difficulty that arises when applying this utility-based understanding of &quot;change of position&quot; to actual cases. Although the idea of a person's &quot;utility&quot; is a useful conceptual device, it is impossible to measure and difficult even to estimate. As a result, a court attempting to compute a change of position in terms of utility would be faced with the difficult problem of converting an abstract
detrimental change in utility to a concrete monetary figure. For example, if a defendant spent some portion of a mistaken payment on a trip to Europe, the above analysis suggests that the court should attempt to determine not only how much was spent on the trip, and whether the defendant would have gone on the trip in any case, but also the benefit he or she in fact received from the vacation. (Even if the person would not have gone were it not for the mistaken payment he or she will generally experience <i>some</i> benefit from it.)  This is, admittedly, a daunting prospect. Nevertheless, these practical difficulties do not invalidate the utility-based approach to the problem. Although the difficulties involved in analysing changes of position in terms of utility are indeed thorny, they are in essence evidentiary problems. When assessing damages in tort cases, courts are often confronted with problems that are as difficult or worse, which they manage to resolve, however imperfectly. It can be argued that the benefits that the utility-based approach provides by clarifying our understanding of the underlying problem of changes of position outweigh the practical complexities it creates. In any case, courts that consider themselves capable of estimating the value of a tort plaintiff's lost limb cannot legitimately shirk from attempting to estimate the utility of a trip to Europe.
<p>
<h3>Conceptual Bases for the Change of Position Defence</h3>

Having set out the issues and considered the meaning of the expression &quot;change of position,&quot; the central question can now be asked: what are the possible explanations underlying the change of position defence?  As noted earlier, two main alternative points of view exist. Some authors have suggested that the defence of change of position is based in some way on ideas of equity---that is, the defence is available in situations where it would be in some sense unjust to require the defendant to make full restitution. Alternatively, it has been argued that the defence is rooted in the concept of enrichment, and that its purpose is to restrict the defendant's obligation to the amount by which he or she was actually &quot;enriched.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> In what follows,
each of these approaches to the problem will be discussed in turn, and an attempt will be made to determine the strengths and weaknesses of each position.
<p>
&quot;FAIRNESS- AND EQUITY-BASED&quot; EXPLANATIONS
<p>
A number of commentators have advanced explanations of the change of position defence based on the idea that when the recipient of a benefit changes his or her position as a result, it would be unfair to make him or her disgorge the entire benefit and absorb the ensuing loss. The origins of this position are often said to be found in the case of <cite>Moses v. McFerlane</cite>.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> In that case, in the course of discussing the nature of an action for money had and received, Lord Mansfield stated:
<blockquote>
[The defendant] can be liable no further than the money he has received; and against that, may go into every equitable defence, upon the general issue; he may claim every equitable allowance; etc.; in short, he may defend himself of every thing which shows that the plaintiff, <i>ex aequo et bono</i>, is not entitled to the whole of
his demand, or to any part of it.<sup><a href ="#twenty">20</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This statement has often been interpreted as a declaration that the right of restitution is &quot;essentially
equitable&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> notwithstanding its common law origins, and that &quot;whenever the defendant can show that in equity and good conscience he ought not to repay, the obligation to repay should no longer exist, even if it did exist prior to the time when the defendant's equitable defence arose.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup>
<p>
The idea that changes of position can act as a defence by altering the balance of equities between the parties has been expressly adopted in several jurisdictions. In New Zealand, for instance, statute dictates that in cases of mistake restitution is to be denied in whole or in part
<blockquote>
if the person from whom the relief is sought receives the payment in good faith and has so altered his position in reliance on the validity of the payment that in the opinion of the Court, having regard to all possible implications in respect of other persons, it is inequitable to grant relief, or to grant relief in full, as the case may be.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Many U.S. courts<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> and commentators have taken a similar view. Probably the most notable American proponent of the &quot;equity-based&quot; defence is the <cite>Restatement of the Law of Restitution</cite>, which states:
<p>
&#167;142
<blockquote>
(1) The right of a person to restitution from another because of a benefit received is terminated or diminished if, after the receipt of the benefit, certain circumstances have so changed that it would be inequitable to require the other to make full restitution.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Although it is debatable whether in this instance the <cite>Restatement</cite>'s position actually reflects a true consensus among U.S. courts as to the state of the law,<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> there is no doubt that the authors' formulation of the change of position defence has been very influential in promoting the
&quot;balancing equities&quot; understanding of it.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup>
<p>
If the change of position defence is conceptualized in terms of the balancing of equities between plaintiff and defendant several difficult questions arise. In attempting to strike an &quot;equitable&quot; balance, what considerations should a court view as relevant, and on what basis should the court weigh different factors that might
affect the &quot;equities&quot; of the situation?  To repeat Lord Goff's words, how is a court to decide when &quot;the injustice of requiring [the defendant] to repay outweighs the injustice of denying the plaintiff
restitution&quot;?<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> Moreover, if it so happens that the  &quot;equities&quot; in a particular case are equal, what should the result be?
<p>
The <cite>Restatement</cite> addresses the first of these questions by introducing considerations of fault into the analysis:
<p>
&#167; 142
<blockquote>
(2) Change of circumstance may be a defence or a partial defence if the conduct of the recipient was not tortious and he was  no more at fault for his receipt, retention or dealing with the subject-matter than was the claimant.
<p>
(3) Change of circumstance is not a defence if--- 
<blockquote>
(a) the conduct of the recipient in obtaining, retaining, or dealing with the subject-matter was tortious, or 
<p>
 (b) the change occurred after the recipient had knowledge of the facts entitling the other to restitution and had an opportunity to make restitution.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup>
</blockquote></blockquote>
From the point of view of &quot;balancing the equities,&quot; considering the relative fault of the two parties undoubtedly makes some sense. Since a decision to allow or not to allow the change of position defence to succeed will result in one or the other of the parties absorbing the loss that the mistake and resulting change of position has
created,<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> the question of which of the parties bears more of the responsibility
for creating the state of affairs that led to the loss does seem to have some intuitive connection with the &quot;fairness&quot; of allowing the defence to succeed. If, for example, it was the plaintiff's carelessness that caused a mistaken payment to be made, it seems unfair to make the defendant suffer as a result.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> There are, however, significant problems involved in translating this intuitive sense of fairness into a consistent legal rule.
<p>
<i>Problems with the Fault-Based Approach</i><br>
Introducing considerations of fault into the change of position defence creates several difficulties. To begin, it is
uncertain what degree of fault the authors of the <cite>Restatement</cite> believe is necessary to trigger the scrutiny of the court. Is some minimum level of fault required, and, if so, does the degree of fault needed differ from the negligence standard in tort law?  Moreover, does the fact that the <cite>Restatement</cite> differentiates between &quot;tortious&quot; conduct and mere &quot;fault&quot; imply that &quot;fault&quot; is intended to refer to some degree of blameworthiness less serious than negligence, or does the difference lie only in the fact that tort liability is dependent on the existence of a duty of care as well as an unreasonable standard of conduct?  The authorities on this point are ambiguous---the Comment on &#167; 142 by the authors of the <cite>Restatement</cite> speaks only of a &quot;fail[ure] to exercise care,&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> while in his textbook Palmer states that &quot;[w]hen fault can fairly be attributed to either or both parties, relative fault is a fact to be taken into account&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
without identifying the degree of fault to which he is referring. As Cohen points out, American case law suggests that a much lower standard of fault than that found in tort law is generally applied:
<blockquote>
The law of torts furnishes a whole exegesis of the word &quot;negligence&quot;; and within the limits of that subject the word can be used with precision. Unfortunately, it bears no definable relation to the notion in quasi-contracts which is also termed negligence. It is different procedurally, for the decisions do not require a jury
to answer whether either party failed to observe reasonable care. It is different substantively, for the theory does not limit the court to significant inquiry into due care. The opinions do not make inquiry into the facts to determine whether given conduct meets <i>standards</i>. They content themselves with showing that the party ruled against made the mistake, and with asserting that he was the one who should have avoided it.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The <cite>Restatement</cite> thus appears to indicate that courts are to determine the availability of the change of position defence by attempting to decide which of the parties was more to blame, without analysing their blameworthiness in relation to an objective standard of unreasonableness or, for that matter, to any other threshold of culpability. This approach is arguably rooted in distributive justice principles: courts are to determine which of the two parties is the least &quot;deserving&quot; within a limited moral framework defined by the parties' responsibility for the underlying mistake, and then allocate the loss arising out of the mistake accordingly. The
authors of the <cite>Restatement</cite> endorsed this loss allocation-based conception of &#167; 142 in the Comments accompanying the section, where they state:
<blockquote>
The rule stated in this Section is an application of the underlying principle of this Subject that restitution is granted
only where it is equitable so to do. Where events are such that a loss must be suffered by one of the parties, either with or without the ability to obtain reimbursement from a third person, justice does not require that the recipient should bear the loss, where he is guilty of no greater fault than that of the claimant.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Viewed in isolation, there is not necessarily anything objectionable about such a loss allocation approach. Any decision to allow or disallow the change of position defence will indeed result in the loss caused by the mistake being assigned to one or the other of the two parties; consequently, a rule based on allocating the loss on the basis of some set of normative factors may be defensible. Nevertheless, taking this approach to be the basis of the change of
position defence leads to inconsistencies when the defence is considered in the context of the law of restitution and its underlying principles.
<p>
If the purpose of the change of position defence is to allocate the loss brought about by the mistake on the basis of the parties' responsibility for causing the mistake, the question can be asked: why should the analysis of relative fault be restricted to the plaintiff and the defendant?  The problem can be seen most clearly in cases where a third party plays a crucial role in the conferral of the benefit on the defendant. For example, in <cite>Jones v. Waring &amp; Gillow</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> both the plaintiff and the defendant were deceived by the &quot;rogue&quot; Bodenham. Bodenham tricked the plaintiff company into giving a cheque for  &#163;5000 to the defendant by leading it to believe that it was buying an interest in an automobile franchise business. In reality, neither the business nor the automobiles existed. The defendant was under the impression (also induced by Bodenham) that the payment it received was related to a debt owed to Bodenham, that he was transferring to it. After receiving the money, the defendant leased some expensive furniture to Bodenham on a hire-purchase contract. Eventually the truth of Bodenham's activities emerged and the defendant repossessed the furniture, but not before it had suffered irreparable harm.
<p>
If this case is to be analysed with a view to allocating the loss caused by the change of position on the most blameworthy party, there is an obvious candidate to bear the loss: Bodenham, the rogue. The restitutionary action in which the change of position defence arises, however, is a two-party process, involving only the defendant and
the plaintiff. This seems to suggest that if fault-based loss allocation is used to decide the issue of the defence considerations will be introduced to the problem that are alien to the underlying principles of the claim itself.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> If this is so, the resulting law is likely to be incoherent. 
<p>
In reply to this criticism it might be argued that the absence of Bodenham as a party to the proceedings is not fatal to the loss allocation model: the rogue, after all, is usually insolvent, and will thus escape shouldering the loss no matter how much he or she might deserve to bear it. As a result, even if all the parties were present, a court attempting to allocate the loss on the basis of fault would, presumably, be forced to identify the next most
blameworthy candidate and pin the loss on him or her. Moreover, if Bodenham had been able to pay, the plaintiff in this case would probably have sued him directly rather than involving the defendant. Therefore, it might be said the absence of Bodenham in this case is immaterial, since if he had been capable of bearing the loss he, and not the defendant, would be the subject of the action. Even if the theory behind the loss allocation approach suggests he should be present and accountable, it may be that no real harm will be done by his absence.
<p>
This counter-argument may be somewhat effective in situations like <cite>Jones</cite>, where the &quot;missing person&quot; is clearly the most blameworthy and is insolvent. It breaks down, however, when it is applied to situations where the third party is not such an obvious villain, or is not particularly villainous at all. As an example,
suppose that A ships goods to B by rail. The shipment never arrives, but B mistakenly pays A for the goods. Later, B sues A in restitution to recover the mistaken payments.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> The facts might reveal that the railway was, in fact, the most &quot;blameworthy&quot; of the three parties, even if all three were in some manner responsible for the mistake. Nonetheless, even if the railway were solvent the case might still arise as an action in restitution between buyer and seller, since the cause of the mistake might not be known before the action was brought. If the concept of placing the loss on the most blameworthy party is to be taken seriously as the central motivation of the defence, it evidently makes no sense to leave the railway out of the picture. The fact that the action in restitution does so suggests that a fundamental inconsistency might exist between the law of restitution and a defence of change of position that is conceptualized as a loss allocation device.
<p>
It is, moreover, no answer to this problem to say that whoever of the two parties is made to absorb the loss in the above situation will have a cause of action against the railway, so that the loss will eventually be shifted where it &quot;belongs.&quot;  The third party (in the example, the railway) may not have been enriched, so an action in
restitution against it might be impossible (for example, suppose the railway did not retain the goods, but instead delivered them to the wrong address). It is true that in some cases an action against the third party might lie in tort, but there is no guarantee that such an action would succeed. For instance, even if it is assumed that the &quot;blameworthy&quot; railway in the above example owed a duty of care to the losing party in the restitutionary action, it is quite possible that the railway, although more at fault than anyone else, was nonetheless not negligent in the more rigorous tort law sense (as noted earlier, the standard of fault applied in American change of position cases has been considerably lower than the standard of unreasonableness found in tort law). Consequently, the failure to include the railway in the initial loss allocation problem can have a real impact on where the loss finally falls. The incoherence that exists between the logic of the loss allocation model of the change
of position defence and the structure of the two-party action makes it impossible to achieve the result that the model suggests should be attained.
<p>
The interaction described above between the loss allocation model of the change of position defence and tort standards can be seen as an aspect of a larger conceptual problem that the existence of tort law poses for the loss allocation approach to the change of position defence. Like the change of position defence, however conceived,
one of the <i>effects</i> of a decision in tort law is the placing of a loss on one or the other of the parties in the case. Tort law does not, however, operate on the basis of loss allocation. Rather, it analyses problems in terms of the relationship between the parties, deciding cases on the question of whether, in the circumstances, the
defendant breached a duty owing to the plaintiff to take reasonable care to avoid creating the loss that ultimately ensued.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> Under this approach, it is perfectly possible (and self-consistent) for a plaintiff to bear a loss even if the defendant was &quot;more to blame&quot; for its occurrence, as long as the relative &quot;fault&quot; of the defendant falls short of the legal standard of unreasonableness. Without taking a position on the relative merits of tort law over other possible legal regimes, it can still be argued that it is inconsistent to apply different conceptions and standards of fault to two problems that, while not identical, are at least similar in their crude outlines. Both tort law and the change of position defence as conceptualized in the <cite>Restatement</cite> deal with problems that have the same general form: A does something that causes B to suffer a loss. Yet the loss allocation-based change of position defence suggests that the two problems should be treated quite differently, without explaining why this should be. Put another way, if fairness and justice dictate that the loss caused by a mistaken payment should fall on the party whose &quot;fault,&quot; no matter how slight, led to the mistake, why do these same considerations not require that the Long Island Railroad bear the loss suffered by Mrs. Palsgraf when the scales fell on her head?<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> The accident was, after all, more the railroad's fault than hers, even if the railroad was not so much at fault as to have been negligent. If the
issue in each case is the fault of the parties, consistency would seem to require that a similar approach be taken to the question of fault in each instance, even though one case arises as a defence to a restitutionary action and the other as an action in tort.
<p>
In response, however, it might be argued that in spite of certain similarities to tort law the change of position defence is an altogether different creature. The change of position defence is, after all, merely a defence: it gives the defendant no positive right to bring an action, but merely allows him or her to resist partially a plaintiff's claim. This difference, it might be argued, is enough to make the analogy between the defence and tort law break down---it
need not be the case that the standards of fault necessary to raise a defence be the same as those required to establish an independent legal claim.
<p>
A similar position has been taken by Birks, in a somewhat different (although related) context. Birks has argued that a defendant should be able to defeat by estoppel a claim for restitution of money paid as a result of a mistake when the plaintiff owed a duty to the defendant to make accurate assessments of the amount the defendant was entitled to receive.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> He states, however, that &quot;[t]his duty need bear no
relationship to the duty of care required to constitute tortious liability in negligence. We are not here concerned with tortious liability but with the conditions necessary to constitute a defence.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<p>
On one level, this argument is hard to dispute---there is, indeed, no absolute necessity that all defences in law apply the same standards as related forms of positive action, nor an absolute requirement that defences and forms of action be consistent with one another. Nonetheless, although not required, consistency and coherence between various areas of the law are goals worth striving for. The fact that the loss allocation-based explanation of the change of position defence creates inconsistency and contradiction is sufficient reason to doubt the adequacy of the model, particularly when there exist alternative explanations (as discussed below) in which these problems do not arise to the same extent. Moreover, even if symmetry between claims and defences is not an absolute requirement, it is a feature of many areas of the law. For example, in tort cases based on negligence where the defendant can argue as a defence that the plaintiff was contributorily negligent, essentially the same standard is applied in judging the plaintiff's conduct as is used in judging the defendant's.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> Consequently, the fact that the &quot;equity&quot;-based change of position defence relies on a new standard of fault may, indeed, be grounds for rethinking the rationale that suggests the need for the new standard in the first place.
<p>
<i>Situations Where &quot;Fault&quot; Is Absent</i><br>
Aside from the question of the merits of introducing the issue of fault into the analysis of the change of position defence, a further problem arises under the &quot;equity&quot;-based approach. In many cases where the change of position defence is likely to be invoked it will be impossible to ascribe any meaningful degree of fault to either the plaintiff or the defendant.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> The general consensus in American law (including the <cite>Restatement</cite>) appears to be that in this situation the defendant should nonetheless be allowed to invoke his or her change of position as a defence. It is far from clear, however, that this rule can be
justified on the basis of the &quot;balance of equities&quot; between the parties. Cohen has argued that in cases of this sort it is impossible to make a determination based on &quot;moral&quot; considerations. As he writes:
<blockquote>
Is it true that a genuine moral judgment is possible in what the commentators treat as the usual case of change of position?  It seems to this writer at least that the problem as they posit it really furnishes no moral alternatives with which to weight a decision. To consider a concrete case. <i>P</i> pays to <i>D</i> money which, through the fault of neither, both believe is owing. In fact, <i>X</i> is the debtor, but this is not discovered until the Statute of Limitations has run against <i>D's</i> remedy against <i>X</i>. Can there be any moral, as distinguished from ethical, <i>ought</i> in this case?  To require <i>D</i> to repay the money paid to him under mistake is to ignore the fact that he irrevocably changed his position in reliance on the mistaken payment. Yet to deny <i>P</i> a recovery is to change his position irrevocably, if only by virtue of the denial, and to make indefeasible in <i>D</i>
a title which he did not originally have. The claims of each party to sympathetic attention are so obvious that it is nothing short of shocking that the question should be approached as if the dictates of good conscience could furnish a satisfactory answer. That the moral alternatives are equally attractive, that either horn of the dilemma pricks the good conscience with identical sharpness, would seem clear. Though regrets for the abandoned alternative may be deeper, the choice does not differ materially from that which makes the rule of the road.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Indeed, proponents of the defence who support it on &quot;moral&quot; grounds have generally been unable to articulate anything more than an imprecise intuition that when neither party is at fault the defendant should be protected. Even the economics-oriented authors. Beatson and Bishop admit that in supporting the rule they &quot;rest [their] choice frankly on grounds of moral intuition&quot;<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> that they cannot articulate in concrete terms. It may be the case that most people do, in fact, share this intuitive response, and believe that the defendant should be protected from the consequences of the mistake. It is
debatable, however, whether such a vague intuitive belief can provide a sound basis for a legal rule.
<p>
Although it may be impossible to articulate a concrete &quot;moral&quot; reason for favouring the defendant, a related argument can be made, based on the claim that the change of position defence is in essence an equitable device that should be governed by general equitable principles. In particular, it might be argued that the equitable
maxim &quot;he who seeks equity must do equity&quot; applies to prevent a plaintiff from fully enforcing his or her right to full restitution if to do so would unduly harm the defendant. On this view, the conscience of a court of equity prevents it from acting as the agent by which an inequity is committed, even if the result of inaction is to make the plaintiff suffer an equivalent loss that is not necessarily morally justified. As Lord Greene M.R. stated in
<cite>Re Diplock</cite>:<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup>
<blockquote>
[E]quity intervenes not to do what might be thought to be absolute justice to a claimant but to prevent a defendant from acting in an unconscionable manner ... . If this limitation on the power of equity results in giving to a plaintiff less than what on some general idea of fairness he might be considered entitled to, that cannot be helped.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The idea that such equitable considerations should be relevant in restitution is often traced to the comments of Lord
Mansfield in <cite>Moses v. McFerlane</cite> quoted earlier.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup>
<p>
This argument, however, has several drawbacks. From an historical point of view, the law of restitution developed from the common law action of <i>indebitatus assumpsit</i> rather than from equity. In any case, there is disagreement over whether the change of position defence was traditionally recognized by equity itself.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> As a result, any argument promoting an equitable conception of the change of position defence must go beyond a discussion of traditional equitable maxims and provide compelling reasons explaining why the approach <i>should</i> be adopted in the restitutionary context. This may not be an impossible task---it could be argued, for instance, that courts should never as a rule act in a way that harms &quot;morally innocent&quot; parties. This approach, however, fails to explain what courts should do in cases where the
&quot;equities&quot; are unequal. In such a case, it seems inevitable that considerations of fault will have to be brought back into the analysis. The result is a rather cumbersome two-part explanation for the defence---if some sort of moral fault can be established, loss allocation principles will dictate where the burden of the loss falls, but if no moral distinction can be drawn between the parties a decision not to allow full restitution will be based on essentially unrelated policy grounds concerning the proper role of the court. Faced with this unwieldy explanation for the defence, one has to wonder whether it is not possible to find a more persuasive rationale for its existence.
<p>
To summarize, it appears that attempts to justify the change of position defence on &quot;equitable&quot; grounds stumble on a number of hurdles. Attempting to &quot;balance the equities&quot; between the parties seems to lead inevitably to the introduction of considerations of relative fault into the analysis---considerations that do not always
fit in well with the overall two-party structure of the restitutionary action, and that create problems of consistency with other areas of law (in particular, tort law). Moreover, when fault cannot be ascertained it becomes necessary to look elsewhere for a reason to prefer one party over the other. On the whole, the &quot;equitable&quot; conception of the change of position defence is unsatisfactory. Fortunately, an alternative approach to the problem can be found, which avoids at least some of the problems raised by the equitable model. The alternative approach, as noted earlier, focuses on the <i>enrichment</i> of the defendant rather than on the justice or injustice of its retention.
<p>
&quot;ENRICHMENT-BASED&quot; EXPLANATIONS
<p>
As the Supreme Court of Canada has stated, the modern law of restitution is based on the concept of unjust
enrichment.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> There is, however, a degree of uncertainty involved in the term
&quot;enrichment&quot;: how is enrichment to be measured, and at what time is the measurement to be made?  It has been suggested that the definition of enrichment lies at the heart of the defence of change of position. As Klippert puts it:
<blockquote>
A logical defence to an unjust enrichment claim would be to plead that the defendant has not been enriched. His enrichment may have been only temporary, so that by the time he has notice of the claim he is no longer in a position to disgorge the benefit. The aim of the unjust enrichment action is to require benefits to be disgorged; if there is no longer a benefit to be disgorged, the court should not go further and require the impoverishment of an innocent defendant to compensate the plaintiff.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Birks has analysed the problem in a similar way, although the details of his approach differ slightly. As he conceives it, claims in restitution necessitate a four-step inquiry:
<blockquote><ol>
<li>Was the defendant enriched?
<li>If so, was it at the expense of the plaintiff?
<li>If so, was the enrichment actionably &quot;unjust,&quot; in the sense that it was in the circumstances
reversible as a matter of positive law?
<li>Is there any defence or other countervailing factor requiring restitution nonetheless to be denied
in whole or part?<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup>
</ol></blockquote>
Although Birks sees the issue of change of position as falling under the fourth stage of the inquiry rather than the
first, he nonetheless argues that the conceptual basis for the defence is the effect of a change of position on the defendant's enrichment. After noting that there are three possible types of expenditure that might lead to a change of position---unrequested expenditures, expenditures made at the behest of the plaintiff, and expenditures prompted by a request of a third party<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> ---Birks goes on to assert that:
<blockquote>
[C]hange of position ... is an effective defence because it bears directly on the measure of the defendant's enrichment in that there is a direct causal nexus between the plus received and the minus laid out ... [I]t follows that our three cases can all be treated as one, for the same idea will explain each: they can all be seen as enrichment-based changes of position in which the causal nexus between plus and minus requires that the enrichment represented by the plus be adjusted to allow for the minus.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In spite of the differences in their approaches, both Birks' and Klippert's formulations of the change of position
defence rest on the same underlying conception: namely, the idea that a defendant who detrimentally changes his or her position is to that extent no longer enriched, and should only be liable in restitution for the amount of enrichment that has been retained.
<p>
The &quot;enrichment-based&quot; explanation has a number of distinct advantages over the &quot;fairness-based&quot; approach. By relating the availability of the defence to the principles underlying the initial
restitutionary claim, the need to import into the analysis external considerations of blameworthiness or fault can be avoided, so the problems and inconsistencies such importation creates do not arise. Under the enrichment-based view, the change of position defence is simply another aspect of the concept of unjust enrichment itself. Plaintiffs in restitution cannot, after all, claim compensation from defendants for <i>any</i> loss they might have suffered; rather, there must be a connection between the loss and the defendant's gain---if there is no corresponding enrichment, restitution grants no remedy. The enrichment-based change of position defence simply extends this logic one step further, declaring that the amount of restitution is to be limited to the extent of the defendant's true
enrichment.
<p>
It might be argued, however, that the symmetry of the restitutionary action and the enrichment-based understanding of the change of position defence is achieved only by submerging the problems encountered in the  &quot;equitable&quot; approach in the definition of &quot;enrichment.&quot;  The suggested connection between a defendant's change of position and his or her enrichment can be made only if the concept of enrichment is understood in a particular way---that is, if a person's enrichment from the receipt of a benefit is thought of as
relating to the utility he or she derives from it, rather than to the benefit's face value. Such a conceptualization is by no means inevitable. If the decision to adopt such an understanding of enrichment was purely result-driven---that is, intended solely to facilitate the existence of the change of position defence, which one favoured on other grounds (such as an imprecise &quot;moral intuition&quot; that &quot;innocent&quot; defendants should be protected)---the apparent coherence of the enrichment-based approach with the rest of the law of restitution would indeed be illusory: the dilemmas plaguing the &quot;equitable&quot; approach would simply have been swept under the
carpet, and no real conceptual progress would have been made.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup>
<p>
The choice of a definition of enrichment that allows for a change of position defence, however, can arguably be justified on grounds other than the fact that it might protect defendants. Restitutionary cases have a certain structure, which in some important respects reflects the structure of actions in tort. In both situations a plaintiff who has suffered a loss seeks compensation from a defendant. The plaintiff is not, however, entitled to compensation from anyone he or she chooses---there must be a legally recognized connection between the plaintiff and a particular defendant that entitles the plaintiff to compensation from <i>that</i> defendant.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> In tort law, the required connection is that the plaintiff's loss be caused by the defendant, and that the defendant be at fault in respect of the injury that has materialized; similarly, in restitution the connection comes into being only if the defendant is enriched at the plaintiff's expense, in the absence of a juristic reason that would entitle him or her to retain the enrichment. In both regimes, once the conditions for liability have been established, the focus shifts to the extent of compensation that is required. In tort law, although a defendant is liable only for damages of a type that are foreseeable, within this limitation a tortfeasor &quot;takes his or her victims as he or she finds them&quot;: damages are calculated (at least in principle) on the basis of the loss of utility of the passive victim---the particular plaintiff in <i>that</i> case. For example, in personal injury cases a court assessing damages takes into account the particular situation of the plaintiff---his or her earning potential, for instance---and computes the quantum of damages accordingly.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> Whatever the defendant might have gained from his or her tortious conduct is irrelevant. Similarly, it can be argued, in restitution cases the quantum of compensation---the extent of the defendant's enrichment---should also be determined in terms of changes in utility. In restitution,<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> however, unlike tort, it is the <i>defendant</i> rather than the <i>plaintiff</i> who is the passive recipient of a change in utility (which happens to be positive rather than negative). As a result, it might be suggested, symmetry with tort law requires that the quantum of restitution also be calculated in terms of the change in utility (here, the increase) experienced by the passive party (here, the defendant).
<p>
Even if this argument in support of the enrichment-based approach to the change of position defence is accepted, a number of vexing questions still remain. If the defence operates by recognizing that in certain circumstances the extent of defendants' enrichment can be affected by events that make it impossible for them to return to their initial pattern of saving and consumption, a question arises: are there any limits on the type of intervening events that can
trigger the defence?  As an illustration, consider two defendants, A and B, who each mistakenly receive payments of $2,000. Suppose that both of them, motivated by their new-found wealth, alter their spending patterns by making substantial purchases that they would not have made but for the mistaken payment: A spends her money on a trip to Fiji, while B buys a new car, which is subsequently destroyed in an unfortunate accident. Assume that at the time restitutionary claims are made against them that both defendants would suffer if made to return the entire $2,000. Should the fact that B's inability to return to his initial position is at least in part a result of an intervening external event---the accident---affect the availability of the change of position defence in his case?
<p>
As Dawson has pointed out, in German law almost any intervening event that produces a loss can be enough to allow an &quot;innocent&quot; defendant to invoke the change of position defence. As he describes it:
<blockquote>
For [German judges] there is one short and simple rule: [defendants] cannot be required to surrender more than their
surviving net gain, or, as it is often expressed, they must under no circumstances be required to &quot;reach into their own pockets.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The scope of the defence is limited, however, by the fact that it is available only to &quot;innocent&quot; defendants---that is, to defendants who did not know that they were not entitled to keep the benefit they had received. Once a defendant has obtained actual knowledge, his or her liability to provide restitution becomes
fixed, and is not reduced even if he or she does not act in bad faith---for example, if the benefit is lost through some unavoidable accident before the defendant has the opportunity to grant restitution.
<p>
Dawson is highly critical of the German approach, which he characterizes as showing &quot;a basic though well-meaning confusion of thought.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> In his view, the German
defence &quot;rest[s] on the ... basic misconception, that the existence or the extent of liability to restore unjust enrichment should depend on the degree to which the person enriched was aware of his own moral fault.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> Dawson objects to this conception on the grounds that in most
restitutionary claims both the plaintiff and defendant were active participants in the transaction that led to the  conferral of the benefit, so there is no reason to favour the defendant.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup>
<p>
Although it is impossible in the limited space available here to respond fully to the detailed and extensive arguments put forward by Dawson, a few points can be made. While Dawson's hostility toward the German model appears to be based to a large extent on what he sees as a mistaken belief that equity dictates that &quot;innocent&quot; defendants be protected, his own criticisms are vulnerable to attack on the opposite grounds: he is arguably too quick to assume that defendants who are unaware that they are not entitled to retain a benefit are guilty of &quot;moral fault&quot; for not immediately recognizing this lack of entitlement. As Dawson recognizes, the duty to make restitution does not depend on active &quot;wrongdoing&quot; by the defendant; his use of the term &quot;moral fault&quot; in this context appears to mean simply the defendant's duty to remit to the plaintiff
an enrichment that it would be unjust to retain. It does not necessarily follow from the principles of restitution, however, that this duty attaches at the time the benefit is conferred (as Dawson appears to assume) rather than at the time the defendant becomes <i>aware</i> that he or she is not entitled to retain it. Dawson's view that it attaches at the earlier time is arguably based as much on an unfounded assumption about the moral position of defendants as
is the German position he criticizes---if the German rule can be attacked for making the unwarranted assumption that all defendants are &quot;innocent,&quot; Dawson can be criticized for assuming that they are all &quot;guilty&quot; instead.
<p>
That said, however, the German approach may still go too far. Although the concept of enrichment can be interpreted to allow defendants to reduce the amount payable to take into account changes in their spending patterns, it is less clear that the definition of enrichment can easily encompass the scope of protection offered to defendants
under the German rule. In effect, the German rule requires plaintiffs to insure &quot;innocent&quot; defendants against all manner of loss that occurs before the defendants learn of their duty to return a benefit. This may not be defensible---as Dawson points out, the defendant may not be so &quot;morally innocent&quot; that equity requires
the plaintiff to bear all the risk that accompanies a mistaken conferral of benefit. In the absence of a proprietary remedy, defendants are not generally required to disgorge additional gains that accrued from their temporary possession of the benefit, so it may not be unfair to make them shoulder the responsibility for certain types of risk as
well.
<p>
Moreover, although almost everyone would agree that defendants who wilfully change their position after obtaining a benefit to which they know they are not entitled should not be able to adjust the amount owing, if the knowledge of the defendant is the sole determinant of whether or not a loss can be deducted (as it is in German law) unusual results can sometimes ensue. Consider, for example, the following situation: two people are in a restaurant, and
one mistakenly places a $10 bill in the other person's coat pocket, having mistaken her friend's coat for her own. After leaving the restaurant the second person finds the money in his pocket, thinks it is <i>his</i> own, and puts it in his wallet. On the way home, he is mugged and his wallet stolen. Now consider the same set of events, with one variation: when the recipient finds the money, he realizes it belongs to his friend, and places it in his wallet with the
intention of returning it to her the next day. It is hard to see why in these two cases knowledge of the mistake should make any difference in the way the law treats the loss---common sense would seem to dictate that either both hypothetical recipients should be entitled to a defence or neither of them should be, but that a defence should not be available to one and not the other.
<p>
Several authors<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> have addressed these problems by suggesting that only certain types of changes to a defendant's utility can be used to raise the change of position defence. As Birks conceives it, there must be a &quot;causal nexus&quot; between the initial conferral of a benefit and the subsequent
change of position that would lead to the defendant suffering a loss if full restitution is ordered. In other words, the change of position must in some sense have resulted from the conferral of the benefit. As an example, Birks considers a contractor who has received a cash payment in advance for building a house. The money is subsequently destroyed in a fire. Birks asks:
<blockquote>
Has the builder suffered an enrichment-related change of position?  It is very difficult to say that he has, because,
contrary perhaps to first appearances, there is no causal nexus between the plus and the minus. It is irrelevant that among his losses were the very notes received. The situation would be exactly the same if they alone had survived. He has simply suffered a fortuitous supervening loss, much as though, the day after receiving the payment, a
company in which he had previously invested had collapsed, or he had crashed his car and broken his legs, or his Picasso had been stolen. Supervening poverty does not necessarily erase enrichment. This is not a genuine paradox, but merely a semantic trick. The condition of having been enriched is undone by causally related outlay, not by
the causal onset of poverty. Job, for example, if he received any mistaken payments or other unjust enrichment, remained thereby enriched even after the Devil had stripped him of all his earthly wealth.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The notion that a causal link must exist between the receipt of the benefit and the defendant's change of position before the change can give rise to a defence is in many ways an appealing one. It does, however, present problems of its own. As is the case in other areas of law, the problem of causation in change of position cases can be an enormously difficult one to resolve. In terms of simple &quot;but for&quot; causation, for instance, a distinction actually can be drawn in the above example between the builder's loss of the cash and the other types of loss that Birks mentions: unlike the other examples, the money would not have been destroyed had it not been for the payment---the payment was responsible, as it were, for the money being in the wrong place at the wrong time. This type of crude &quot;but for&quot; causation is, presumably, not what Birks has in mind in imposing his causation requirement.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> Arriving at a more sophisticated definition of causation is, however, no simple task. It is some consolation that the problem is probably no more difficult than the corresponding issues of causation that arise in tort and criminal law, for example, which courts have been able to deal with even if they have not been able to resolve them conclusively.
<p>
Birks has also raised the possibility that the enrichment-based explanation for the change of position defence may not be able to cover all the situations where such a defence might be appropriate. He points out that in some cases defendants might be unable to establish &quot;a causally determined minus to set against the plus&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> yet would suffer hardship if forced to return the full amount of the benefit. As an
example, he presents the case of a poor schoolteacher who receives a mistaken overpayment in his salary. By the time his employer discovers the error and demands the money back, the defendant's financial condition has worsened and he would experience hardship if made to return the money, although he can point to no particular
expenditure made in reliance on the extra income. Birks then asks the following questions: &quot;[I]s there to be a hardship related defence of change of position distinct from an enrichment-related defence?  If yes, what kind of hardship, and what other facts will it require?&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup>
<p>
It is debatable, however, whether Birks' hypothetical example truly presents a new problem that cannot be dealt with under the framework of the enrichment-based change of position defence. The hardship that Birks pictures his schoolteacher suffering is not, after all, simply the realization that his windfall has to be returned, as would be the case if the defendant had simply put the mistaken payment in the bank. Rather, Birks posits a situation where
the money has been spent, but where the defendant is unable to identify a specific expenditure that would not otherwise have been made.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup> In order for the example to make sense, however, it must be the case that the mistaken payment has not simply gone towards an expenditure that
would otherwise have been made---if it had, then by definition the defendant would have an equivalent surplus remaining (which, it is assumed, he does not). Instead, the defendant must have increased his overall spending patterns to include his new-found income, although he may have done so in a way that is difficult to identify:
for example, he may have purchased slightly higher-quality groceries.
<p>
What Birks fails to recognize is that the defendant's difficulty in identifying a specific &quot;causally determined minus&quot; that can be deducted from the amount owing is in essence an <i>evidentiary</i> problem rather than a <i>conceptual</i> problem. As discussed earlier, the series of incremental changes in expenditure in this case can cause just as significant a change in the defendant's position as he or she would have experienced if the money had been spent on a single major act of consumption, such as a trip to an exotic locale---the only difference is that the first type of change of position may be more difficult for a defendant to prove. Consequently, a court would not appear to require recourse to any new conceptual mechanisms in order to allow the change of position to be
invoked in Birks' hypothetical example. Rather, what would be required is a more flexible approach to the evidentiary issue. This is not an insurmountable difficulty---in the proper case (including Birks' example), it might be possible for a court to infer from the surrounding facts that the defendant has, in fact, incrementally changed his or her position. 
<p>
Although on its facts the outcome in <cite>Storthoaks</cite><sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> may not be inconsistent with this approach, the Court can be criticized for the emphasis placed in its decision on &quot;special financial commitments&quot; as the hallmark of changes of position, since this suggests that changes of position only arise when extraordinarily large shifts in spending habits occur. As the above discussion indicates, this is hard to justify as a matter of principle. Rather, it can be argued that the Court should recognize that a series of incremental deviations from pre-benefit patterns of expenditure can also produce a change of position, and that the
significance of &quot;extraordinary&quot; expenditures are simply that they make changes of position easier to prove as matters of fact, not that they are essential as matters of law.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

The enrichment-based explanation of the change of position defence provides a more coherent and logical foundation for the defence than can be found under the fairness-based approach. A number of outstanding issues require further analysis, however, before the enrichment-based explanation will be entirely satisfactory. In particular, if the change of position defence is to be limited by a requirement that there be a &quot;causal nexus&quot; between a defendant's initial enrichment and his or her later change of position, the precise nature of the causal relationship needs further explanation. Nonetheless, the improvements in conceptual understanding that are gained by adopting the enrichment-based framework outweigh the drawbacks of the approach, especially when the more serious inadequacies inherent in the alternative ways of envisioning the defence are taken into account.
<p>
The <cite>Storthoaks</cite> decision was undoubtedly an important first step in the development of the defence of change of position in Canadian law. As a foundation for future development of the change of position defence, however, <cite>Storthoaks</cite> leaves something to be desired---although the Court recognized the existence of the defence, it did little to explain its underlying conceptual basis. This omission must be corrected if the defence is to be able to develop in a consistent and understandable manner.
<p>
The law of restitution is still in its infancy, at least in comparison with its older, more well-established private law
siblings, contract and tort. Consequently, it is neither surprising nor alarming that many important issues still await conclusive treatment by Canadian courts---in time, these issues will arise to be decided, and the blank areas on the map of the law of restitution will be filled in. In the case of the change of position defence, the courts will be faced with a difficult choice in deciding on a conceptual framework. It is to be hoped that they will approach the problem in a way that helps rather than hinders the goal of a clearly articulated and principled development of the law. Once drawn, lines on the map of restitution will be difficult to erase or change. It would be better if the courts get them right the first time.
<p><br>
<hr>
<p>
<center><h2>Endnotes</h2></center>
<ol>
<a name="note">* The author</a> wishes to thank McMillan Binch for its support of legal writing, including this paper, through the <cite>McMillan Binch Essay Fellowship</cite>.
<p>
<li><a name ="one"><cite>Restatement of the Law of Restitution: Quasi-Contracts and Constructive Trusts</cite></a> (St. Paul: American Law Institute, 1937), &#167; 142(2).
<p>
<li><a name="two">(1975), 55 D.L.R. (3d) 1 (S.C.C.)</a> [hereinafter <cite>Storthoaks</cite>]. The Municipality had granted Mobil certain oil and gas leases. Under the terms of the leases, Mobil was required to pay the Municipality royalties based on the production of oil and gas from the leased property. Mobil was entitled to
terminate any of the leases at any time. In 1964, Mobil decided to terminate two of the leases, and notified the Municipality of its intention. As a result of an unexplained error by Mobil's accounting department, however, the company continued to pay royalties relating to these properties for four more years. Eventually the mistake was
discovered, and Mobil sued to recover the mistaken payments. Martland J., writing for the Court, recognized the existence of a change of position defence, stating (at 13):
<blockquote>
In my opinion it should be open to the Municipality to seek to avoid the obligation to repay the moneys it received if it can be established that it had materially changed its circumstances as a result of the receipt of the money.
</blockquote>
On the facts of the case, however, he held that since there was no evidence that the Municipality had undertaken any special projects or special financial commitments as a result of the payments it had not established that it had  changed its position.
<p>
<li><a name="three"><cite>Lipkin Gorman (a firm) v. Karpnale Ltd. and another</cite></a> (1991), [1992] 4 All E.R. 512, [1991] 3 W.L.R. 10 (H.L.)  [hereinafter <cite>Lipkin Gorman</cite> cited to All E.R.]. Cass was a partner in Lipkin Gorman, a firm of solicitors. Over several months he embezzled more than &#163;300,000 from the firm. He was a compulsive gambler and lost much of the stolen money in the defendant Karpnale's casino. The
casino had no idea that Cass was not entitled to the money. Once the theft was discovered, Lipkin Gorman sued Karpnale, demanding return of the money. As a result of s.18 of the <cite>Gaming Act</cite> 1845 the gambling contracts between Cass and Karpnale were void, so Karpnale was prevented from arguing that it had given good consideration in exchange for the money. The question that then arose was whether Karpnale was entitled to plead change of position---that is, whether it could deduct from the money it had received from Cass the money it
had paid out to him on those occasions when he had won his bets. The House of Lords held that it could, thereby recognizing for the first time the existence of a change of position defence in English law.
<p>
<li><a name="four">See</a> <i>ibid.</i> at 532 (Goff L.J.).
<p>
<li><a name="five">Variants of the defence</a> have also been adopted in New Zealand and Western Australia; see R. Goff &amp; G. Jones, <cite>The Law of Restitution</cite>, 4th ed. (London: Sweet &amp; Maxwell, 1993) at 741 n. 18; P. Birks, &quot;The English Recognition of Unjust Enrichment&quot; [1991] Lloyds Mar. &amp; Comm. L.Q. 473 at 486 n. 58.
<p>
<li><a name="six">G.H.L. Fridman &amp; J.G. McLeod,</a> <cite>Restitution</cite>, 2d ed. (Toronto: Carswell, 1992) at 458.
<p>
<li><a name="seven"><i>Supra</i> note 3 at 533.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eight">See Birks,</a> <i>supra</i> note 5; G.B. Klippert, &quot;The Juridical Nature of Unjust Enrichment&quot; (1980) 30 U.T.L.J. 356.
<p>
<li><a name="nine">[1980] 2 S.C.R. 834.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ten"><i>Ibid.</i> at 273-274.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eleven">This will be</a> the situation in the vast majority of cases where the defence is invoked, since the defendant will usually have received some property belonging to the plaintiff. In many cases where it is arguable that the plaintiff has suffered no loss (such as <cite>Reading v. Attorney-General</cite>, [1951] A.C. 507 (H.L.)), the defendant will know that he or she is not entitled to his or her enrichment, and will be unable to invoke
the defence. Although it is possible to imagine situations where the plaintiff arguably suffers no loss and where the change of position defence might apply, such cases will be few and far between.
<p>
<li><a name="twelve">See also J. Beatson &amp: W. Bishop,</a> &quot;Mistaken Payments in the Law of Restitution: An Economic Analysis&quot; (Law &amp; Economics Workshop Series, Faculty of Law, University of Toronto, 1981) [unpublished] at 5ff. A later version of this paper with a somewhat less detailed discussion of
this issue was subsequently published as: J. Beatson &amp; W. Bishop, &quot;Mistaken Payments in the Law of Restitution&quot; (1986) U.T. L.J. 149 at 151ff, [hereinafter Beatson &amp; Bishop (2)].
<p>
<li><a name="thirteen">In mathematical terms,</a> the problem can be described as follows: the defendant has an initial income <i>I<sub>o</sub></i> which can be allotted between N choices by allotting amounts x<sub>1</sub> ...x<sub>N</sub> to each choice. The defendant distributes his or her income in
a way that maximizes his or her utility function,<p>
<center><img src="formula1.gif" alt="Mathematical formula"></center>
<p>
(where u<sub>n</sub>(x<sub>1</sub> ... X<sub>N</sub>) is the utility derived from the expenditure on the <i>n</i>th allotment), subject to the constraint
<p>
<center><img src="formula2.gif" alt= "Mathematical formula"></center> 
<p>
It should be noted that in order not to reduce the generality of this formulation it is necessary to express the
utility gained from buying the <i>n</i>th item as a function of the amounts allotted to each of the N expenditures. This reflects the fact that some expenditures are useful only if they are accompanied by corresponding spending on other items---for example, the utility one derives from owning a car will vary depending on whether one can
afford to buy gasoline. (Of course, in practice not every term will exhibit an actual dependence on every variable.)
<p>
<li><a name="fourteen">That is,</a> if the new income is designated <i>I</i><sub>1</sub>, the defendant will distribute this higher income among the N alternatives in a new way, <i>y</i><sub>1</sub> ... <i>y</i><sub>N</sub>, that produces a new utility <i>u</i>(<i>y</i><sub>1</sub> ... <i>y</i><sub>N</sub>).
<p>
<li><a name="fifteen">It is,</a> of course, possible that there was more than one initial distribution which could achieve this maximum utility, so it is conceivable that the defendant might be able to return to a new spending distribution that was also utility-maximizing. This would be a rather fortunate coincidence, and does not alter the basic point.
<p>
<li><a name="sixteen">See also S. Levmore,</a> &quot;Explaining Restitution&quot; (1985) 71 Va. L.Rev. 65  at 74ff.
<p>
<li><a name="seventeen">Again,</a> assume that this is the utility-maximizing distribution at this level of income.
<p>
<li><a name="eighteen">In addition,</a> it might be possible to formulate an explanation for the defence based on altogether different factors---for example, considerations of efficiency. Attempts to do so have not, however, been successful. For instance, Beatson and Bishop, in attempting to analyse the law of restitution on economic
grounds, conclude that at the present time efficiency arguments that attempt to distinguish between several alternative versions of the defence are &quot;artificial and speculative&quot;; the authors &quot;prefer to rest [their] choice frankly on grounds of moral intuition.&quot;  Beatson &amp; Bishop (2), <i>supra</i> note 12 at 155 n. 12.
<p>
<li><a name="nineteen">(1760), 2 Burr. 1005.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty"><i>Ibid.</i> at 1012.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty1">G.P. Costigan Jr.,</a> &quot;Change of Position as a Defence in Quasi-Contracts---The Relation of Implied Warranty and Agency to Quasi-Contracts&quot; (1907) 20 Harv. L. Rev. 205 at 205.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty2"><i>Ibid.</i> at 205.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty3">New Zealand</a> <cite>Judicature Act</cite> 1980, s. 94B as am. See Goff &amp; Jones, <i>supra</i> note 5 at 741.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty4">See generally,</a> H. Cohen, &quot;Change of Position in Quasi-Contracts&quot; (1932) 45 Harv. L. Rev. 1333.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty5"><i>Supra</i> note 1, &#167; 142.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty6">See J.P. Dawson,</a> &quot;Restitution Without Enrichment&quot; (1981) 61 B.U.L.Rev. 563 at 568ff.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty7">This is especially true</a> in the case of non-American commentators, who often (rightly or wrongly) treat the <cite>Restatement</cite>'s position as the monolithic &quot;American view&quot; on the issue. See, for instance, Fridman &amp; McLeod, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 459.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty8"><cite>Lipkin Gorman</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 533.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty9"><cite>Restatement of Restitution</cite></a>, &#167; 142, <i>supra</i> note 1. Many American courts have adopted this position, or one much like it; see Cohen, <i>supra</i> note 24 at 1356ff.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty">This will be the result</a> whether or not the defence's <i>purpose</i> is to allocate the loss in a particular way.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty1">Even before the defence</a> of change of position was recognized in English law, English courts on occasion discussed the unfairness that could result from granting full restitution (although they were not moved to do anything about it). For example, in <cite>R.E. Jones, Ltd. v. Waring and Gillow, Ltd.</cite>, [1926] A.C. 670 (H.L.) [hereinafter <cite>Jones v. Waring and Gillow</cite>] Lord Sumner remarked (at 695-696):
<blockquote>
The real grievance of the [defendants] is that it is hard to make them suffer because Jones, Ltd., made a mistake. If it is any satisfaction to them, I am willing to say that I think it is, but such is the law.
</blockquote>
The House of Lords did not, of course, allow the defendant to invoke the change of position defence in this case.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty2"><cite>Restatement of Restitution</cite> &#167; 142, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 574.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="thirty3">Palmer,</a> <cite>The Law of Restitution</cite>, vol. 3 (Boston: Little, Brown, 1978) at 524.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty4">Cohen, <i>supra</i> note 24 at 1356-1357 (emphasis in original).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="thirty5"><cite>Restatement of Restitution</cite></a> &#167; 142, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 568.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty6"><i>Supra</i> note 31.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="thirty7">It is well established</a> in most if not all common law jurisdictions that the issue of fault is irrelevant to the initial restitutionary claim: <cite>Kelly v. Solari</cite> (1841), 9 M&amp;W 54, 152 E.R. 24.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty8">This example</a> is a variation on the facts of  <cite>Clark v. Eckroyd</cite> (1885), 12
O.A.R. 425; in that case, however, it appears that the railway could not in fact be blamed for the mistake.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty9">See</a> <cite>Donoghue v. Stevenson</cite>, [1932] A.C. 562 (H.L.).
<p>
<li><a name="forty"><cite>Palsgraf v. Long Island Railroad Co.</cite></a>, 162 N.E. 99 (Ct. App. N.Y. 1928).
<p>
<li><a name="forty1">P. Birks,</a> &quot;The Recovery of Carelessly Mistaken Payments&quot; [1972] Curr. Leg. Prob. 179.
<p>
<li><a name="forty2"><i>Ibid.</i> at 187 n. 12.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty3">Atiyah argues,</a> however, that in practice defendants are held to a <i>higher</i> standard of care than is expected of plaintiffs---in his words, &quot;though there are authoritative dicta rejecting this approach, nobody familiar with the law reports can have any doubt that judges often find conduct to be
negligent which they would hesitate to stigmatize as contributory negligence.&quot;  P. Cane, <cite>Atiyah's Accidents, Compensation and the Law</cite>, 4th ed. (London: Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson, 1987) at 121.
<p>
<li><a name="forty4">For example,</a> in cases such as <cite>Lipkin Gorman</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 3, both plaintiff and defendant will be the unwitting victims of a rogue without either being appreciably careless. Even in cases of &quot;mistake&quot; it may at times strain the meaning of &quot;fault&quot; to apply it to either party.
<p>
<li><a name="forty5">Cohen, <i>supra</i> note 24 at 1351 (emphasis in original).
<p>
<li><a name="forty6">Beatson &amp; Bishop (2)</a>, <i>supra</i> note 12 at 156 n. 12. It should be noted, however, that they adopt this position only after failing to find an economic rationale for it.
<p>
<li><a name="forty7">[1948] 1 Ch. 465 (C.A.).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty8"><i>Ibid.</i> at 532.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="forty9"><i>Supra</i> note 20.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty">See G. Jones,</a> &quot;Change of Circumstances in Quasi-Contract&quot; (1957) 73
L.Q. Rev. 48 at 63.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty1">See</a> <cite>Deglman v. Guaranty Trust Co. and Constantineau</cite>, [1954] S.C.R. 725, [1954] 3 D.L.R. 785.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty2">Klippert, <i>supra</i> note 8 at 397.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty3"><i>Supra</i> note 5 at 475.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty4"><i>Ibid.</i> at 487-488.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty5"><i>Ibid.</i> at 488.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifty6">For example,</a> in German law the rule that a defendant is liable only for a surviving net gain is explicitly based on the view that &quot;protection of the `innocent' against loss through their own gain [is] a
mandate of transcendant equity:&quot; J.P. Dawson, &quot;Erasable Enrichment in German Law&quot; (1981) 61 B.U.L.Rev. 271 at 300.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty7">See E.J. Weinrib,</a> &quot;Causation and Wrongdoing&quot; (1987) 63 Chi.-Kent L. Rev. 407 at 414.
<p>
<li><a name="fifty8">See</a> <cite>Andrews v. Grand &amp; Toy Alberta Ltd.</cite> (1978), 83 D.L.R. (3d) 452 at 456 (S.C.C.).
<p>
<li><a name="fifty9">Note that we are dealing</a> only with situations where the change of position defence might arise---that is, cases where the defendant did not knowingly misappropriate the plaintiff's property.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty">Dawson, <i>supra</i> note 56 at 272.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty1"><i>Ibid.</i> at 314.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty2">Dawson, <i>supra</i> note 26 at 620.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty3">Dawson,</a> <i>supra</i> note 56 at 314. This is, of course, merely an outline
of Dawson's arguments.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty4">See Birks,</a> <i>supra</i> note 5 at 486ff. See also C.A. Needham, &quot;Mistaken Payments: A New Look at an Old Theme&quot; (1978) 12 U.B.C.L.Rev. 159 at 207ff.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty5">Birks, <i>ibid.</i> at 489.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty6">In other areas of law,</a> such as tort, simple &quot;but for&quot; causation is usually a <i>necessary</i> condition for liability to attach but not a <i>sufficient</i> condition---more sophisticated conceptions of causation are needed to establish &quot;cause in law.&quot;  If such an understanding of causation
is applied to the destroyed money case, the connection between the receipt of the money and its destruction would in all likelihood not be sufficient to establish legal causation. Such would be the case in tort law---as Weinrib has pointed out, &quot;Negligence law is concerned with the materialization of unreasonable risk, not whether the defendant has caused the plaintiff [or, in this case, the money] to be or not to be in a certain place at a certain time.&quot;  E.J. Weinrib, &quot;Right and Advantage in Private Law&quot; (1989) 10 Cardozo L. Rev. 1283 at 1283.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty7">Birks, <i>supra</i> note 5 at 489.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty8"><i>Ibid.</i> at 488.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixty9">It must also be assumed</a> that no intervening accident has occurred that would have caused the hardship in any event.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy"><i>Supra</i> note 2.</a>
</ol><p><br>
