<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v52n2.htm">Volume 52 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1>The Nunavut Land Claims Agreement and the Future of the Eastern Arctic: The Uncharted Path to Effective
Self-Government<a href="#note">*</a>
<p> 
KEVIN R. GRAY</h1>
<p><br>
<i>The</i> Nunavut Agreement <i>is the first comprehensive land claims agreement in Canada to extend aboriginal self-government over a vast region. It is not localized self-government, the jurisdiction of which is comparable to a municipality. Instead, Nunavut is unique for a land claim in that it guarantees political rights to self-government. However, self-government takes on a new meaning in Nunavut. It is a government system that is enshrined in democratic principles such as popular representation. Moreover, it becomes a recognized governing
region in Canada with a distinct cultural identity. &quot;Public government&quot; in Nunavut thus provides effective self-government, due to the huge Inuit majority of the population in the Eastern Arctic. Any omissions in the</i> Agreement <i>can be covered by an Inuit territorial government with broad administrative powers. Inuit
concerns become entrenched in the government agenda due to the majority status of the Inuit in Nunavut. However, public government does not liberate the Inuit from the hardships experienced in the communities. It is at the community level where significant change occurs. Therefore, newly acquired political rights will not resolve
problems, but only facilitate their solutions. Thus, while the future of the Eastern Arctic relies on factors that are yet to be determined, one constant will be the elevation of Inuit interests onto the government agenda and the preservation of Inuit culture, which can never be eroded in a land where no other group is a threat to become the majority.
<p>
L'</i> Entente Nunavut <i>est la premi&egrave;re entente de si grande envergure sur la question de propri&eacute;t&eacute; de terres ancestrales qui donne le droit &agrave; l'autonomie gouvernementale &agrave; un peuple autochtone dans un territoire aussi vaste. Il ne s'agit pas d'autonomie gouvernementale locale qu'on pourrait comparer &agrave; une municipalit&eacute;. Plut&ocirc;t, l'</i> Entente Nunavut <i>est unique en ce
qu'elle garantie des droits politiques. Par contre, l'autonomie gouvernementale prend un nouveau sense dans l'</i> Entente Nunavut.<i> L'</i>Entente <i>&eacute;tablit un syst&egrave;me gouvernemental en accord avec les principes d&eacute;mocratiques tels que la repr&eacute;sentation populaire. De plus, le Nunavut, qui est une r&eacute;gion avec une identit&eacute; culturelle distincte, devient une r&eacute;gion qui se gouvernera elle-m&ecirc;me. Donc, la repr&eacute;sentation populaire au Nunavut &eacute;quivaut &agrave; l'autonomie gouvernementale &eacute;tant donn&eacute; que la grande majorit&eacute; de la population dans l'est de l'Arctique
est d'origine Inuite. Les questions que l'</i> Entente <i>ne touchent pas peuvent &ecirc;tre decid&eacute;es par un gouvernement territorial Inuit qui est dot&eacute; d'un vaste pouvoir administratif. Etant donn&eacute; que le peuple Inuit est majoritaire au Nunavut, les questions d'importance pour ce peuple formeront n&eacute;cessairement le gros de l'agenda pour ce gouvernement. Par contre, cette nouvelle forme d'autonomie gouvernementale ne lib&eacute;rera pas automatiquement les Inuits des difficult&eacute;s qu'ils vivent dans leurs communaut&eacute;s.
C'est au niveau de la communaut&eacute; que les gros changements se produisent. Donc, les nouveaux droits politiques que les Inuits ont acqu&eacute;ris ne peuvent pas r&eacute;soudre les probl&egrave;mes auxquels les
Inuits font face dans leurs communaut&eacute;s; ces droits ne peuvent que faciliter les solutions. En effet, tandis que l'avenir de la r&eacute;gion et de l'Arctique d&eacute;pend des donn&eacute;es qui restent encore &agrave; d&eacute;terminer, une chose dont on peut &ecirc;tre certain c'est que les inter&ecirc;ts des Inuits font maintenant partie d'un agenda gouvernemental et que leur culture sera pr&eacute;serv&eacute;e puisque aucun autre groupe risque de devenir majoritaire dans ce territoire.
</i>
<p>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

One thing that emerged from the failure of the Charlottetown Accord was a realization among native Canadians that
constitutional entrenchment of an aboriginal right to self-government was still illusory. Moreover, the dialogue was not likely to be reopened for some time. As many First Nations returned to the bargaining table to pursue their interests independently of one another, there was a common perception that land claims agreements, sometimes referred to as &quot;modern treaties,&quot;<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> could better satisfy current aboriginal needs and settle outstanding grievances, as well as establish First Nations self-government. 
<p>
One such &quot;treaty&quot; is the <cite>Nunavut Land Claims Agreement</cite>.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> It is a product of over 20 years of exhaustive consultation among Inuit representatives and the federal and territorial governments. During that time, the Inuit did not perceive constitutional entrenchment of
general aboriginal rights as a viable alternative to a land claims settlement. Land claims are a useful vehicle for the Inuit to engage in a new relationship with the government. Although controversy surrounds any extinguishment of rights and title, which these agreements require, the impact of surrendering them may be overstated in the context of the Eastern Arctic. The <cite>Agreement</cite> contains a specific framework that governs many aspects of life in the Eastern Arctic including wildlife management, land and water use, and resource development. It creates a number of tribunals and agencies to enforce its provisions and guarantees Inuit representation on them. This is of great importance because it ensures Inuit participation in overseeing the development of the Eastern Arctic.
<p>
The most controversial component of the <cite>Agreement</cite> is the clause that extinguishes Inuit title and rights to traditional lands and water in exchange for financial compensation. The boundaries of the land claim encompass the traditional lands of the Inuit, but the Inuit have given up title to---and many corresponding
rights in---those lands. In addition, the extinguishment clause precludes the Inuit from taking any legal action against the government. The loss of their rights as titleholder to the land and the right to assert any other legal claims against the government may have serious ramifications when the payments from the government which are stipulated in the <cite>Agreement</cite> terminate.
<p>
However, to minimize the potential difficulties of the extinguishment clause, the <cite>Agreement</cite> delegates political control of Nunavut to the Inuit. Inuit government will ultimately extend beyond the local level, thus creating a wide scope of jurisdiction. This will be effected by a severance from the Northwest Territories in 1999 which will introduce Nunavut as Canada's third territory. Nunavut will have its own legislature, whose representatives will be elected from a population of which the Inuit are clearly the majority. This suggests that Inuit concerns will dominate the government agenda, mitigating the losses resulting from the extinguishment clause.
<p>
The purpose of this article is to explore the relationship of the <cite>Agreement</cite> to Inuit political development. It begins with an historical overview to provide a better understanding of the <cite>Agreement</cite>. It then examines the concept of self-government, the definition of which is mired in ambiguity, and a revision of this concept---known as public government---on which the <cite>Agreement</cite>
is based. It will be demonstrated that due to the realities of the Eastern Arctic, public government may be a more appropriate mechanism to satisfy Inuit aspirations. This is followed by a comparative analysis with other comprehensive land claims, and the problems encountered in them. The <cite>Agreement</cite>'s response to those problems will be highlighted to distinguish Nunavut from other land claims. 
<p>
This article also addresses whether the <cite>Agreement</cite> will facilitate solutions in areas that raise the most pressing issues for the Eastern Arctic---economic development, resource and land-water management, and community participation. A promising future may be highly dependent on variables the <cite>Agreement</cite> cannot control. The article concludes by examining the issue of community justice, the means by which Inuit aspirations will be fully met. Although the <cite>Agreement</cite> is silent on this issue, a future political accord
creating the Nunavut territory is expected to encourage local dispute resolution. What takes place at the local level will demonstrate how Nunavut will work. Any notion of self-government or self-realization for the Inuit ultimately relies not on the present wording in the <cite>Agreement</cite>, but on participation at the community level as well
as higher regional levels. The obstacles inherent in attaining Inuit objectives are abundant. However, the possession of government authority, complemented by constituents who are actively involved in their own government, creates the potential to overcome these obstacles.
<p>
<h3>The Inuit, Land Claims, and Aboriginal Rights</h3>
<p>
It is important to distinguish the Inuit experience from that of other First Nations. The Inuit are less disenchanted with the government than are other native peoples, which is attributable to their more recent exposure to non-native North Americans. Historically distinct, Inuit culture has been less undermined by the impact of Canadian expansion. Because the Inuit live in a profoundly different environment, their response to government initiatives is unique. Furthermore, the concept of aboriginal rights takes on a different meaning in the Eastern Arctic. Debate over native issues, such as the controversy surrounding land claims, must be viewed through the Inuit perspective.
<p>
The choice of resolving these issues through a land claims settlement, where First Nations would receive financial compensation, land ownership, participation in government, and administrative responsibility in exchange for the extinguishment of their aboriginal rights to traditional lands and waters, has touched off controversy.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> A loss of title to the land is equivalent to a loss of identity. The land plays a strong role in
native lifestyles; to remove title to it can weaken native culture.
<p>
Some argue that an individual agreement contributes little to the advancement of aboriginal constitutional
goals.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> On this account, aspirations of sovereignty and self-determination
cannot be met by any delegation of authority. This undermines any attempt by aboriginal peoples to &quot;live the way they wish.&quot;<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> In fact, the reverse may ensue; aboriginal peoples may eventually suffer from assimilation and, as a result, cultural erosion.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> The attraction of land claims with promises of greater accessibility to government institutions and increased participation in decision making can be construed as a vehicle for acculturation that operates by convincing aboriginal peoples of the merits of the Canadian political process.
<p>
The extent of what an extinguishment clause destroys is a source of confusion for First Nations.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> The clause in the <cite>Agreement</cite> does not preclude the Inuit from enjoying all
constitutional rights or government programs.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> The courts are continually expanding the parameters of aboriginal rights,<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> which might counterbalance what was given up in the <cite>Agreement</cite> since the rights surrendered under it relate primarily to the land.
Additionally, because land claim agreements are recognized in s. 35 of the <cite>Constitution</cite>,<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> entitlement to benefits flowing from aboriginal rights as well as government programs is constitutionally guaranteed.
<p>
Land claims agreements provide a concise and concrete outline of aboriginal rights and responsibilities for a specific area. This replaces the more general concept of &quot;aboriginal rights and title&quot; which is indisputably vague. The delineated transfer of economic and especially political power induces the &quot;enhancement of aboriginal rights, not the extinguishment.&quot;<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> The federal government's description of its land claims policy illustrates this point:
<blockquote>
The stated purpose of the federal government's comprehensive land claims policy ... is to provide certainty and clarity of rights to ownership and use of land and resources in those areas of Canada where Aboriginal title has not been dealt with by treaty or superseded by law... . Land claims negotiations should look to the future and should provide a means whereby Aboriginal groups and the federal government can pursue shared objectives such as
self-government and economic development.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Other observers have reaffirmed the comprehensive nature of the land claims agreements, which satisfy many objectives such as cultural protection and economic development of the area.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> The <cite>Agreement</cite> removes the Inuit from the constitutional discourse and alternatively presents them with a definitive framework for administering their lands. 
<p>
A general right to self-government may be incompatible with land claims agreements. The agreements laboriously set out the parties' rights, duties and responsibilities and specify how the administration will operate and how royalties and compensation funds will be handled. A blanket right to self-government over a settlement region is difficult to reconcile with the detailed terms of land claims agreements. It raises questions of interpretation more than it provides answers to the existing needs of the communities and the people's relationship with the land. Including this right in any agreement creates an ambiguity that can hinder progress for the land claims area. 
<p>
In addition, land claims agreements have some advantages over negotiating within a rights discourse. &quot;Aboriginal rights&quot; is a loose, generalized term that lacks any contextual meaning. Peter Ittunuar, a chief negotiator for the <cite>Agreement</cite>, comments:
<blockquote>
If there is one word that describes the legal status of the concept of aboriginal rights, that word is &quot;ambiguous.&quot;  During the last ten years almost every legal initiative taken to clarify the
concept has resulted in further ambiguities being created.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup>
</blockquote>
 &quot;Aboriginal rights&quot; is an abstract, Euro-Canadian legal term used to define a relationship with the land. By contrast, the <cite>Agreement</cite> establishes administrative and regulatory mechanisms to monitor use
of the land and its resources while addressing particular Inuit issues. Furthermore, rights must be confirmed in the judicial arena. Establishing Inuit rights in court requires patience to withstand the protracted litigation process. Moreover, litigation requires a tremendous financial commitment to cover necessary court and legal expenses. Consequently, this diverts attention and resources from the more immediate problems in the communities. The rights discourse, which proposes to ensure equality among all Canadians, is far removed from the daily interaction between individuals in northern communities. 
<p>
Rights are abstract legal concepts embedded in principles of individualism and personal liberty. Thus, the pursuit of aboriginal rights assumes that each aboriginal person is equal. As a result, all aboriginal peoples are deemed to be living in the same conditions and sharing the same ambitions. This perception of a unified native perspective has pervaded the constitutional dialogue, but it fails to appreciate regional and local aspirations.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> The needs of the Inuit may not correlate with the ambitions of aboriginal (Indian)
peoples in southern Canada. Purich comments:
<blockquote>
While the Inuit sought to attain many of the same goals as their Aboriginal counterparts, the Inuit came to the negotiating table with a very different perspective and history than the Indian and M&eacute;tis people. No reserves were ever created for the Inuit, as there had been for the Indian people. Nor had promises been made to
the Inuit, as there had been to the Indian people by way of treaty, or to the M&eacute;tis by the way of the Manitoba Act and Dominion Lands Act.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Inuit exposure to Canadian society has been a relatively recent phenomenon. Interest in northern development<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> emerged during an era in which treaties were no
longer pursued.<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> Canada's relationship with the Inuit has developed in a different context in which land claims have supplanted the treaties of the past. 
<p>
The presence of the Canadian government has been less intrusive on the Inuit lifestyle compared with Indians in southern Canada or even the Dene or M&eacute;tis, who have been, directly or indirectly, the subject of various federal and provincial legislation.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> Furthermore, the reserve system, which did not apply to the Dene and M&eacute;tis, has contributed to the erosion of traditional aboriginal culture. The relations between government and the Inuit may not be as acrimonious as those of other aboriginal peoples who are embittered by numerous treaty abrogations. A less painful history has engendered more trust in the government by the Inuit, which was apparent during the negotiation of the <cite>Agreement</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> 
<p>
Contributing to the differences between the Inuit and other First Nations are their intermittent conflicts with each other. Historically, there have been incidents of hostility and disgruntlement between Indians and the Inuit; these still exist, albeit in a more subtle form.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> Nunavut proposals have distanced the Inuit, a people with inherent social and cultural differences, from other First Nations in the Territories. Their political transformation is evident through Inuit organizations such as the Inuit Tapirisat of Canada, Nunavut Tungavik and Pauktuutit, as well as active participation at Inuit Circumpolar Conferences. Enshrining aboriginal rights such as self-government in the <cite>Constitution</cite> will not necessarily recognize these separate interests. It also fails to embrace the characteristics unique to the Arctic and its inhabitants. The aboriginal peoples' agenda is consolidated under the rubric of rights, guaranteed and equal. Its universality can lead to assimilation of the Inuit with other First Nations. Homogenizing an aboriginal identity in Euro-Canadian legal terms can induce cultural disintegration.
<p>
The <cite>Agreement</cite> appreciates rather than neglects the Inuit experience. Comprehensive land claims help foster a relationship with traditional lands. They can more easily accommodate the needs of a harmonious population, dispersed over a large region with similar ecological and climatic conditions. Inuit interests are amply reflected in an accord that they negotiated without the involvement of other First Nations. The promise of obtaining government powers over the Nunavut territory was incorporated into the <cite>Agreement</cite>. Although self-government was on the agenda during recent constitutional discussions, a redefinition that is amenable to the political environment of the Eastern Arctic could be formulated only by the Inuit.
<p>  
<h3>Self-Government vs. Public Government</h3>
<p>
Land claims settlements, generally encompassing a vast geographical area and diverse communities, usually do not contain explicit references to the right of self-government as it is currently known. Self-government is an essential aspect of First Nations' claims which include native sovereignty over their people. Many First Nations do not divorce land from self-government issues because they are interconnected.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> However, the ambiguity of the term &quot;self-government&quot; can exhaust land claims negotiators who attempt to define it. Opportunities to discuss a self-government arrangement occur
infrequently, but the countless questions about its operation can lead to the stagnation of the land claims dialogue. It becomes an attempt to achieve too much in a land claim and inevitably complicates the process. This problem was addressed during discussions of the <cite>Agreement</cite> in order to narrow the issues at the negotiating table.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> It was imperative to do so for the Eastern Arctic claim because of the size of the territory and the extensive administrative regime required to govern it.
<p>
The <cite>Agreement</cite>, however, does not abandon the issue of self-government but rather reworks it to fit current models of government in Canada based on democratic representation. Public government is legislative government that is democratic, based on regional and/or popular representation. What is unique in this situation is that the electorate is predominantly Inuit, which ensures that Inuit interests are accounted for in government decisions. Because of their majority status in the Eastern Arctic, public government is a viable option for the Inuit; it may not succeed in other parts of Canada. Inuit ambitions for self-government contrast with what other First Nations seek. Purich elaborates on the Inuit objective:
<blockquote>
Of course, there are some differences in what the Inuit seek in self-government and what other Aboriginal people seek. For the most part, the Inuit, be they in northern Quebec or the eastern Arctic, have looked to a public government to satisfy their aspirations for self-government. And in fact, Inuit spokesmen have often argued that what they are seeking is not self-government, but public government in which they will play a role appropriate to their numbers. The fact that the Inuit have chosen a public form of government rather than one which would serve Inuit people exclusively may well make it more palatable to non-Aboriginal communities.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup>
</blockquote>
For the Inuit, a people who are about to be a majority in a new Territory where they will be strongly represented in the bureaucracy, this form of self-government is more justified. Public government does not deviate from self-government principles as much as it contributes towards the establishment of a working relationship with government involving active Inuit participation. Instead of mono-ethnic self-government, public government transplants the Euro-Canadian system of popular representation into a jurisdiction where most of the citizenry are Inuit. The interests and rights of the majority are preserved by government. Protection of the Inuit is furnished not out of a need for special treatment due to historical disadvantage, but because they form a majority of the population.
<p>
Inuit concerns are more likely to be addressed, and Inuit aspirations to flourish, when the solution is acceptable to the government. Public government does not mandate self-government for the Inuit. It is only a logical extension of democratic principles to another jurisdiction of Canada. Consequently, this renders Nunavut a more acceptable model of self-government for the federal authorities because it &quot;gives Indians internal self-determination
without compromising fundamental traditional values.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> The <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>,<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> as part of the <cite>Constitution</cite>, is the supreme law of the land,<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> and consequently all public laws are subject to its provisions. By incorporating the right to self-government into the
<cite>Agreement</cite>, a constitutional &quot;exemption&quot; from the <cite>Charter</cite> would be granted under s. 25 for Nunavut laws.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup>
<p>
Although the <cite>Agreement</cite> declares the formation of a Nunavut legislature, its status is severed from other provisions.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> Therefore, the right to public government under the <cite>Agreement</cite> is not a constitutional right beyond the ambit of the <cite>Charter</cite>. Any such constitutional exemption would be unacceptable to the provinces, which must legislate according to <cite>Charter</cite> provisions. Thus, it is government preference to exclude the right to self-government from land claims agreements in order to maintain the universal applicability of the <cite>Charter</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> This position is manifest in the <cite>Agreement</cite> where all Inuit are guaranteed <cite>Charter</cite> rights.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> Public government does not grant immunity
from the reach of the <cite>Charter</cite>, but rather mirrors other governing authorities in the Canadian family.
<p>
Demands of sovereignty and nationhood, as legitimate as they might be, accomplish little except to isolate First Nations from the government position. In effect, Nunavut represents an adherence to the principles of sovereignty and self-determination, &quot;tempered by a measure of realism.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> The Inuit Tapirisat of Canada states:
<blockquote>
[T]he Inuit have always been an immensely practical people, since the dawn of time. We recognize the necessity of an agreement which will codify and respect our rights in the land. We recognize that this process will be painful, but necessary if we wish to reach a workable understanding with the rest of Canada.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The idea of public government may be easier for the Inuit and other aboriginal peoples in the north to accept due to their majority status in the overall population.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> Inuit representation in government already influences Territorial policy. Consequently, Northwest Territories legislators, who operate by consensus, consider the impact of every law on aboriginal rights. As a result, self-government is not perceived as
a method of escape from government control, as it may be by other aboriginal peoples.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> With the creation of a new territory in the Eastern Arctic and its own legislature,<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> the interests of the largest sector of the voting population in Nunavut will be protected in a public government system that democratizes rather than decrees self-government. 
<p>
The &quot;home rule&quot; system in Greenland, in place since 1979, with a 4-to-1 ratio of Inuit to Europeans, is similar to what Nunavut will be. The Inuit in Greenland run their government much like a Canadian province. Greenlandic issues are largely administered by a legislative assembly which is elected by residents of the island.
Home rule resembles the public government model, with the Inuit asserting a strong role in government affairs. Originally, this was criticized as not effecting a complete withdrawal from the Danish authorities. However, Greenlanders have asserted <i>de facto</i> control over social, cultural, and environmental matters without any
express powers or rights of self-government.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> This suggests that in Nunavut any Inuit concern, existing or future, that the <cite>Agreement</cite> fails to acknowledge can be remedied by the Nunavut administration. The legislative process can indirectly create a self-governing territory
for the Inuit. Consequently, the <cite>Agreement</cite> essentially guarantees much of what those who advocate native self-government seek to achieve.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup>
<p>
Before undertaking a thorough analysis of the <cite>Agreement</cite>, it is useful to refer to previous land claims settlements in Canada. Past experience has caused general discontent with comprehensive claims; thus, comparisons will help to determine how the <cite>Agreement</cite> differs from its predecessors. The negotiators
of the <cite>Agreement</cite> took heed of the problems in previous land claims agreements that occurred both before and after their signing. The major problems with the <cite>James Bay Northern Quebec Agreement</cite> (<cite>JBNQA</cite>) revolve around its inadequate implementation. The <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite>, although successful in its economic ventures and environmental management, falls short on political reform. The ultimate question becomes whether the errors of the past will be repeated. 
<p>
<h3>Other Comprehensive Land Claims Agreements in Canada</h3>

I.  THE JAMES BAY NORTHERN QUEBEC AGREEMENT
<p>
The circumstances that existed before the signing of the <cite>JBNQA</cite> are helpful in understanding the dissatisfaction felt by the Cree, Naskapi and Inuit in the region. Because of its own anticipated energy needs and an opportunity to acquire lucrative electricity contracts with some states in the northeastern United States, in 1991 Quebec decided to develop a massive hydro-electric operation. The project would produce dire environmental consequences for the region through the damming and diversion of major rivers and the resulting flooding of thousands of acres of land. This gravely threatened aboriginal livelihood in the area. After offers to negotiate by the Cree and the Inuit were ignored by the Quebec government, the parties pursued the matter in the courts. They
obtained a court injunction to suspend the dam construction until native claims over aboriginal title were settled.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> Quebec, the federal government, corporate business entities, and the aboriginal peoples affected then ushered in a hastily negotiated agreement, under a set deadline. 
<p>
The <cite>JBNQA</cite> provided for compensation, native responsibilities in environmental and wildlife management, economic and social development of the area, and hunting rights. Despite the comprehensiveness of the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, it lacked any legal obligation to clarify its provisions or regulate its operation.
Correspondingly, there were no provisions for sanctions for failure to implement the <cite>JBNQA</cite> or for any policing body to enforce it.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> The application of the <cite>JBNQA</cite> was also impeded by limited funds based on low financial estimates for the <cite>JBNQA</cite>'s implementation and administration. This shortsightedness may have been a consequence of hammering out an agreement under the pressure of a fixed deadline. The <cite>JBNQA</cite> did not arise from a spirit of cooperation, since the Quebec government felt compelled to consent in order to foreclose any further court action, which had already diverted too much of the province's attention and financial resources.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> The lack of goodwill may have influenced the province's reluctance to transfer the stipulated funding for requisite agencies, programmes, and services. As a result, implementation was slow and ineffective, and made the government
parties look dishonourable.
<p>
Compounding the implementation problems were the inherent ambiguities in the <cite>JBNQA</cite>. Wording and terminology are crucial to land claims settlements, but they are inevitably subject to a number of interpretations. The length of the <cite>JBNQA</cite> exacerbates that problem. It has fuelled constant disagreement between the parties as to the extent of their obligations. It has also invited attempts by the Quebec government to overlook its
commitments under the <cite>JBNQA</cite>. In response, natives in Northern Quebec have turned to the courts. 
<p>
The Quebec government has introduced proposals aimed to bypass environmental assessment requirements in the <cite>JBNQA</cite><sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> for the Eastmain Dam. Its construction could wreak further devastation on the land settlement's environment.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> Massive flooding of the area from hydro-electric development has significantly disrupted the ecological balance. This has had a severe impact on aboriginal subsistence activities. The alteration of caribou migration patterns in the area has made hunting more difficult.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> The weakness of the wording in the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, as judicially interpreted in <cite>Eastmain</cite>, has impaired the ability of the Cree, Inuit and Naskapi to control any interference with their lands.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> The rights of natives to participate in managing their lands were not sufficiently stated, by legal standards, in the <cite>JBNQA</cite>. 
<p>
The Inuit have experienced particular frustration from Quebec's failure to fulfil its obligations under the <cite>JBNQA</cite>. The <cite>JBNQA</cite> did address Inuit aspirations of local autonomy;<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> Inuit communities in northern Quebec have jurisdiction over standard municipal functions including zoning, policing, public health, pollution, and taxation. However, since 1981, the Quebec government has been more active in the delivery of municipal services. Its involvement has been intrusive and has fostered
resentment among the Inuit.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> There has been inadequate funding from the province for municipal and health services, which has necessitated the diversion of capital from <cite>JBNQA</cite> compensation payments.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> With insufficient resources, living conditions in some communities have worsened.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup>
<p>
As control at the community level has been undermined, the Inuit have also suffered from a pronounced language and cultural barrier in Quebec. The integration of Inuit values and ideals is problematic in a province that vigorously upholds the linguistic and cultural integrity of French Canada. Essentially the Inuit in Quebec are a &quot;minority within a minority&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> due to a greater familiarity with English customs, language and lifestyle. Achieving a working relationship is difficult when one party cannot comprehend the interests of the other because of divergent backgrounds. 
<p>
Aside from the implementation problems, &quot;many provisions of the agreement are working well.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> In comparison with the little attention that has been paid previously to native peoples in northern Quebec, their financial plight has improved; many trained Inuit and Cree are employed in bureaucratic positions and the various hunting and trapping regimes have been successful.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> The most significant gain was the realization of s. 9 of <cite>JBNQA</cite>, which stipulated an obligation to institute self-government for the Cree. This arrangement was proclaimed the <cite>Cree-Naskapi Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> and is more extensive than any form of municipal government. The Cree and Naskapi have authority to regulate natural resources, culture, health, and wildlife protection, which differentiates them from a prototype municipality.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> As a provision in the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, the <cite>Act</cite> has been afforded constitutional status under s. 35 of the <cite>Constitution</cite>.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup>
<p>
The Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> differs markedly from the <cite>JBNQA</cite> in a number of ways and attempts to address some of the problems that have occurred under the <cite>JBNQA</cite>. First, unlike the <cite>Cree-Naskapi Act</cite>, the Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> repudiates any connection between political authority and aboriginal rights.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> However, the <cite>Agreement</cite> does not provide for localized self-government.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> A government power based on a municipal model within a province can never give the Inuit the jurisdiction they need to govern themselves effectively. Nunavut will have an administration that encompasses a much larger territory and wider powers. The
creation of a new political entity lessens the importance of entrenching the Nunavut government into the <cite>Constitution</cite>. A broad jurisdiction enhances the perception of Nunavut as another order of government in Canada.
<p>
Second, the <cite>Agreement</cite> establishes a detailed framework for the Nunavut administration which will protect Inuit political power. The <cite>Agreement</cite> can thus be distinguished from the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, which suffered from numerous implementation problems. The <cite>JBNQA</cite> preceded the <cite>Constitution</cite>, thus depriving it of any overriding constitutional authority to challenge provincial unwillingness to meet <cite>JBNQA</cite> conditions. However, a land claims agreement's provisions are now responsibilities that are enshrined in s. 25 of the <cite>Constitution</cite>. Today, &quot;the lack of implementation would be tantamount to a violation of a constitutional right.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup>
 <p>
Third, the <cite>Agreement</cite> reflects the way in which the negotiating process and the parties differ from those in the <cite>JBNQA</cite>. To avoid the interpretation problems of the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, there are constitutional safeguards for First Nations, to ensure favourable interpretations of agreements or treaties with the
government in light of uncertain provisions.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> However, the Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> contains a waiver of this preference by eliminating &quot;any presumption that doubtful expressions in the <cite>Agreement</cite> be resolved in favour of Government or Inuit.&quot;<sup><a href="sixty">60</a></sup> This provides for neutrality in intepreting a comprehensive land claims agreement since the parties are deemed to be of equal bargaining power.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> Unlike the  <cite>JBNQA</cite>, the <cite>Agreement</cite> is a product of thorough consultations and dialogue between the
parties over a long period. Thus it is more likely to include carefully drafted terms that are fully understood by all parties. 
<p>
In addition, regardless of any constitutional protection, the Tungavik Federation of Nunavut (TFN), along with the territorial and federal governments, has responded to the complications experienced in the <cite>JBNQA</cite> by drafting an Implementation Program.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> This is an arrangement ancillary to the <cite>Agreement</cite> which establishes guidelines, defines terms, and provides funding and budget estimates. These guidelines are prepared for an Implementation Panel. They are not binding but merely provisional.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> The {\itl Contract} acts on the guarantee of &quot;timely and effective implementation of the <cite>Agreement</cite> with active Inuit participation,&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> which can preclude any initial acts of bad faith. The Implementation Panel will ensure the execution of the initial <cite>Agreement</cite> and the smooth transition involved in transferring the Territorial administration of the Eastern Arctic to Nunavut authorities. Complications from the transition will be addressed by
the Panel, which facilitates a speedy remedy to problems that may emerge.<sup><a href= "#sixty5">65</a></sup> Unlike the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, the <cite>Agreement</cite> transition period stretches over six years, which will enable all parties to recognize and surmount preliminary hurdles.
<p>
II.  INUVIALUIT FINAL AGREEMENT: WESTERN ARCTIC LAND CLAIM
<p>
The Inuvialuit Settlement Region in the Western Arctic was originally included in the Inuit proposal to the government.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> However, due to disagreements between Inuit leaders, two negotiating parties emerged: the Inuit Tapirisat of Canada (ITC) for the east and the Committee of People's
Entitlement (COPE). The <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite> contains provisions that transfer title and rights (including mineral surface rights) to Inuvialuit lands, guarantee exclusive harvesting rights, and promise strong involvement in environmental management and financial compensation. 
<p>
Astute management of the compensation has brought economic development to the Inuvialuit region. This has delivered financial rewards to the area and stimulated new business ventures. The Inuvialuit Regional Corporation (IRC) oversees Inuvialuit lands and subsidiary corporations which include an airline company (Aklak Air), a petroleum corporation with extraction operations in Alberta (Inuvialuit Petroleum Corporation), urban real estate, a shipping company, and the largest construction company in the western Arctic.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> It is due to this regional prosperity and a pivotal input to the land management process that the <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite> has been praised as a success for native peoples that may never be duplicated.
<p>
Noticeably missing from the <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite> are clauses addressing issues of taxation, absolute subsurface land rights, health and education which were present in a proposal tendered six years previously.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> While this might be attributed to reasons of political expediency,<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup> a more significant omission from the <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite> is the proposal for public government known as the <cite>Western Arctic Regional Municipality (WARM)</cite>. Although the Inuvialuit are promised equal treatment when governmental restructuring is implemented in the Northwest Territories,<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> the uncertainty of what this treatment implies, or when restructuring will occur, leaves the Inuvialuit well short of having any substantial guarantee of effective self-government.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup>
<p>
Following the signing of the Western Arctic Claim, COPE leaders expressed satisfaction with what the settlement
offered.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> The popular sentiment at the time downplayed the impact of the
extinguishment clause:
<blockquote>
Research conducted within the Inuvialuit Settlement Region indicates that the Inuvialuit do not feel any aboriginal rights have been extinguished. Rather, all the claims of land, self-government and cultural continuity are felt by COPE to be included in the Western Arctic Claim. Extinguishment, to COPE (Committee of People's Entitlement), means there will be no further land claims by the Inuvialuit. It extinguishes no other rights.<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup>
</blockquote>
However, there was no referendum indicating full Inuvialuit approval, which has divided Inuvialuit leaders from community members. This has become more pronounced during the recession in the early 1990s as the economic benefits from the land claims have been greatly reduced. The lack of political power has fuelled the debate between local and central administrators.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup>
<p>
In  contrast, Nunavut officials were careful to avoid any criticism that a centralized negotiation process had overlooked the needs of the communities, by obtaining popular support for the <cite>Agreement</cite> through a plebiscite. The administration of affairs over a vast area will require support from the different regions in Nunavut.
Enthusiasm in the communities is necessary for any effective change. A legislative body, in which local leaders can express the concerns of the community, will continue the interaction between community and Nunavut territorial leaders. Public government can assist in mediating the types of conflicts that may surface in Nunavut.
<p>
The <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite>, like its predecessor the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, may become the true measuring stick for future claims. Although both are highly useful for reference, any comparison with the <cite>Agreement</cite> cannot acknowledge Inuit history and development, the local political climate, and the particular needs in the Eastern Arctic. The Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> is an accomplishment independent of other arrangements. It is the conclusion of more than twenty years of work, which in itself separates it from other
agreements created over a much shorter period of time. Thus it is important to examine the particular terms of the Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> and how it can fulfil Inuit objectives. 
<p>
<h3>The Nunavut Agreement</h3>

I.  GENERAL CHARACTERISTICS
<p>
The Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> covers more than 2 million square kilometres and affects approximately 17,000 Inuit living in the area.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> Inuit land ownership encompasses approximately 352,000 square kilometres of land, with 36,300 of it including mineral rights (which have not been included in other settlements).<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> Inuit lands are granted to the Inuit in fee simple<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> which is alienable only in fee simple to the Territorial or Federal governments or to Nunavut municipalities.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> This is a restriction on the proprietary right of free alienation of land, but Canadian policy has always prohibited the disposition of native lands to private landholders under the <cite>Royal Proclamation</cite>.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> The Inuit are still able to lease or license the land or grant any other interest less than fee simple. Inuit Owned Lands, where aboriginal title is entrenched, are not under the jurisdiction of the <cite>Indian Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> since they are not lands reserved for Indians for purposes of the <cite>BNA Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup>
<p>
The <cite>Agreement</cite> is not as generous as the Inuvialuit claim, but it is still ample, providing about 15.5 square kilometres per person.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> Every Inuk, an individual Inuit person, has the right to remove up to 50 cubic yards of carving stone per year from Crown lands.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> Inuit also have an exclusive right to use any water that runs through their lands.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> The <cite>Agreement</cite> provides for free and unrestricted Inuit harvesting rights on the remaining Crown lands, park lands, water, and marine areas<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> in Nunavut.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> Any developer who encroaches on Inuit subsistence hunting rights is liable for any loss sustained. Harvesting rights are subject to laws of general application for public safety purposes, quotas set by the Nunavut Wildlife Management Board (NWMB), conservation purposes, Bilateral Parks and Conservation Areas Agreements, or land use activity authorized under the <cite>Agreement</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
<p>
Any claims contesting the infringement of harvesting rights are heard before an Arbitration Board,<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> which substitutes for the Canadian courts. The Board is composed of members agreed upon by the Government of Canada, the Territorial Government, and the Designated Inuit Organization (DIO).<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> Therefore, Inuit hunting, trapping and fishing rights will be a
constant consideration and are precluded from analysis under Canadian law.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> This process moves questions of Inuit cultural integrity into an arena where their
interests are understood. The Arbitration Board is an invaluable mechanism that avoids the waste of limited financial resources and the delays of the court system---hardships often incurred when pursuing aboriginal rights cases.
<p>
II.  THE DISTINGUISHING FEATURE
<p>
Although the Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> resembles many other land claims agreements in Canada, the requirement to create a new territory sets it apart. This was a strong incentive for the Inuit, who perceived the <cite>Agreement</cite> as opening an avenue for political empowerment and sovereignty that is absent in other settlements. The <cite>Agreement</cite> is final and protected under s. 35 of the <cite>Constitution</cite>, unless both parties agree to amend it. Articles 2.11.1 and 2.11.2 require consent and notice of the DIO<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> for any transfer of power between the federal and territorial governments. Although territorial and federal laws still apply, if they are incompatible with the <cite>Agreement</cite>, the  <cite>Agreement</cite> prevails.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> However, the <cite>Agreement</cite> is not as final as other land claims settlements because it anticipates a future enactment that will complement the powers already delegated in the <cite>Agreement</cite>. The federal and territorial governments and the Inuit have agreed that any subsequent accords concerning the creation of the Nunavut territory will be distinct from the <cite>Agreement</cite>. However, the <cite>Agreement</cite> and the creation of Nunavut are not divorced from each other. The connection between the two will surface once Nunavut becomes a territory in 1999. This is reinforced by Isaac:
<blockquote>
[B]ecause the creation of the territory is an integral part of the agreement, the territory itself will become constitutionalized. It is too early to say what the results of this would be, suffice it to say that once Nunavut is created, it could not be dismantled unilaterally by the federal government. To this extent, Nunavut represents something more than a traditional territory (like the Yukon) and something less than a province.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The history of negotiations has demonstrated that obtaining a Nunavut political territory was the primary consideration for surrendering unextinguished Inuit title.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> Aboriginal rights and political power may be mutually exclusive in the <cite>Agreement</cite>, but the <cite>Agreement</cite> and the future accord creating the Nunavut government will place a viable and culturally harmonious territory on the Canadian map.
<p>
Determining Nunavut's place in the Canadian family could be problematic. If Nunavut is acknowledged as a new Territory, comprised of devolved powers from the Northwest Territories, its constitutional validity could not be challenged by other provinces.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> However, if Nunavut is deemed to be a province, the process of its creation may have to comply with constitutional requirements of approval from seven of the ten provinces having a minimum of fifty percent of the country's population.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> This is of serious concern since two provinces, Quebec and Newfoundland, have their own Inuit populations who may increase their demands on their respective governments or suddenly migrate to Nunavut. This may suggest that these provincial governments mistreat their native populations, which would undermine their credibility in Canada. These considerations could influence Quebec, which, as the second most populous province, is a significant party in negotiating constitutional amendments.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> 
<p>
It is more likely that Nunavut will be a territory. A limitation on the jurisdiction of Nunavut is that most of its power
will be transferred from the territorial government, whose powers are less entrenched than those of the provinces.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> Delegated powers from a territory could not provide the jurisdiction that other provinces have. Isaac comments:
<blockquote>
On the face of it, the Nunavut territory would provide self-governing status to the Inuit who live in the settlement area to the extent provided by normal territorial government. This is laudable. However, a problem with this arrangement is that territorial governments do not have their own constitution and, because they are created by federal statute, are subject to federal legislative authority. It is submitted that this aspect of the agreement, the fact that Nunavut would be ultimately subject to federal jurisdiction seriously curtails Aboriginal (in this case, Inuit) aspirations for self-government. Notwithstanding the agreement, the territorial form of self-government places the Inuit under direct federal authority with no assurance of an adequate financial base (for government).<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Northwest Territories do not have exclusive powers as the provinces do under s. 92 of the <cite>BNA Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> Territorial powers are a product of federal legislation that can be amended unilaterally by the federal government. Although the <cite>Agreement</cite> cannot be altered without Inuit consent, Nunavut jurisdiction will always be subject to federal delegation. 
<p>
However, since Nunavut powers flow from territorial and federal sources, there will not be an encroachment on any provincial powers. Without any interference with provincial authority, a more prominent form of public government can emerge. This contrasts with southern First Nations, who must carve their autonomy out of provincial jurisdictions. The consignment of power from the Territories and Federal government will meet fewer obstacles than would be encountered with a province, which, unlike the Territories, holds ownership to Crown lands and natural resources.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> This has been a fundamental barrier to obtaining more jurisdiction in Quebec, which the aboriginal peoples under the <cite>JBNQA</cite> were forced to overcome.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup>
<p>
The anticipated formation of a new territory deepens the impression that Nunavut will be considered a distinct political entity, with its own governing institutions, in Canada.<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> Nunavut,
like the current provinces and territories, will be an archetype of public government grounded in representative democracy. Much like Quebec, Nunavut will be a socially and culturally identifiable entity in the Canadian federal system. As Canadian history has demonstrated, the federal government has continually accommodated the distinct nature of Quebec because of the strength of its cultural homogeneity. Nunavut, with an active Inuit majority, could be another culturally and ethnically distinct region that shares international connections outside Canada. Mirroring Quebec's ties to Francophone countries, the Inuit could align with other nations in the Arctic Circumpolar region such as Greenland, Russia and Norway. Similarly to the Quebec experience, Nunavut is not designed to undercut the fabric of Canadian unity but to enrich it.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> A government that represents a culturally homogeneous constituency has been referred to as &quot;ethnic self-government.&quot;<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> The explicit assignment of self-government in a land claim could never match the recognition Nunavut will have as an identifiably unique governing region in Canada.
<p>
The discourse on Nunavut's contribution to Canadian federalism fails to address how the <cite>Agreement</cite> and the Nunavut government will address the local needs of the Inuit. The issue of establishing mechanisms to ameliorate conditions in the communities and respond to future challenges will have to be resolved. The fundamental question is whether the <cite>Agreement</cite>, in terms of government policy, can &quot;contribute positively to a lasting solution of cultural, social and economic problems that for too long have kept the Indian and Inuit people in a disadvantaged position within the larger Canadian society.&quot;<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> Significant changes in three areas---namely economic development and employment, land-use management, and community participation---will be integral to a promising future for Nunavut. These are the major policy issues that are currently being discussed in the Northwest Territories today. In addition, an examination of community justice reveals how an Inuit response to social problems plaguing communities will help the Inuit begin the process of regaining full control over their lives and their people.
<p>
 <h3>Particulars of the Agreement</h3>

ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT AND EMPLOYMENT
<p>
Financing the new territory of Nunavut is an extremely expensive proposition in light of the low economic base in the region. Currently only a few communities are economically developed. Unemployment is rampant and job opportunities are scarce. A transformation of the Inuit economy will be a comprehensive task because of a widespread subsistence lifestyle that is funded through government assistance. A successful Nunavut economy with extensive employment opportunities is needed to lessen the social and economic reliance on the government. Without it, political power will become meaningless when eligibility for compensation expires.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup>
<p>
In the <cite>Agreement</cite>, the Nunavut Trust is responsible for managing income from royalties and compensation payments. The Nunavut Inuit have obtained larger benefits on land resource royalties than were given under the <cite>JBNQA</cite> and the <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite>.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> It is anticipated that revenue sharing, equity participation options and eventually resource jurisdiction will follow in any Nunavut constitution, rendering fiscal management more burdensome.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> How this money is administered will be crucial. Both the Inuvialuit Investment
Corporation (IIC) and the Makivik Corporation under the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, monitor land claim compensation and profits from their lands. Since their inception, both organizations have augmented their corporate portfolio, earning dividends that contribute to social and economic development in the communities. Their success has been attributed to sound fiscal planning.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> It is this type of management that can ensure lasting financial security for the Inuit and a healthy Nunavut economy. 
<p>
However, opportunities for short-term economic stability in the communities are limited. The community level is where employment must be available, providing individuals with an option to work and live at the same location. Economic planning must recognize that business and development should be allocated to all communities. Consolidating opportunities only in the larger administrative centres will encourage community members, who are dependent on or depended on by their families, to leave. According to the <cite>Scone Report</cite>,<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> there is only one Nunavut community, Nanisivik, a mining community with mostly
white residents, which is regarded as economically developed.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup>
Employment opportunities in the North have traditionally been created by the government. Therefore, private business and industry are needed to remove any dependence the Inuit would have on the public sector for employment.
<p>
Current economic reality dictates a reliance on federal and territorial funding. This dependence is probably more grave than in any have-not province in Canada.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> A majority of the Inuit in Nunavut are unemployed and therefore are overly dependent on government funding. This is an unfortunate consequence of the rapid transformation of Inuit life from one of subsistence, living among family units, to relocation in communities where education, housing, health care, social services, and other goods were freely available. The marginal feasibility of earning a livelihood through traditional hunting, fishing, and trapping activities, which have suffered from a dwindling fur trade market and seal hunting industry, also contributes to unemployment. The decreasing market for goods acquired from hunting has increased the need for government welfare assistance. More Inuit are being forced to seek employment in the modern economy, with a limited job
market.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup>
<p>
Subsistence livelihood has traditionally been a method of self-sufficiency. However, many young Inuk are not familiar with the essential hunting, fishing, and trapping techniques.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> The pervasiveness of Canadian culture, spread through television, transportation, and other aspects of modern life,
has substantially altered the community environment and as a result has removed the necessity for a young Inuk to live a traditional life.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> The availability of welfare has hastened the replacement of subsistence living with a monetary system. The hardships of being solely dependent on hunting and fishing act as a deterrent to a subsistence lifestyle when the conveniences and services that the state provides are easily obtainable. Furthermore, due to technological advances, it is more costly to equip hunters. This creates a situation in which individuals who can afford to hunt and fish do not have the time to do so because of work obligations, while the unemployed, with the opportunity to hunt and fish, cannot finance the equipment.<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup>
<p>
Economic planning in Nunavut must address the social problems evolving from massive unemployment and the inability to live off the land due to socio-economic transformation.<sup><a href="one18">118</a></sup> Solutions should attempt to abridge the old culture with the new. Jobs should be structured in a way that is flexible enough to prevent interference with seasonal hunting and fishing. Encouraging people to work is a difficult
enough proposition considering the availability of government assistance. Economic planning should offer incentives for people to work. Without a willing work force, economic development stagnates.
<P>
The <cite>Agreement</cite> creates numerous bureaucratic positions and includes the objective of representative Inuit employment in them.<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> The future administrators of the state are expected to emerge from a new generation of Inuit, thus satisfying the <cite>Agreement</cite>'s objectives of encouraging self-reliance and of increasing the cultural and social well-being of the Inuit.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> Education and training will be required for these roles, in addition to fluency in Inuktitut and an understanding of Inuit culture. However, contemporary data reveal there is no large pool of qualified Inuit currently available.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> The lack of interest in scholastic pursuits among
younger Inuit might be attributable to the absence of any perceived benefits of an education in communities where very little employment is available. This disincentive is reinforced by the accessibility to welfare payments without educational requirements.<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup>
<p>
From the younger generation of Inuit comes a group of potential employees who are unqualified and ill-prepared to work for the government.<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup> While qualifications for employment are unnecessary for various wildlife management boards and regional organizations in the <cite>Agreement</cite>, they will be necessary for the Nunavut administration's civil service. Without trained Inuit during the early days of Nunavut, it will be necessary to recruit Qallunaat (whites) to staff Nunavut positions.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> Nunavut legislative directives instituting affirmative action programs cannot compensate
for the lack of Inuit with professional skills.<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> To reduce this disparity, training and education programs must be engineered to effect a meaningful change in bureaucratic representation. Incentives should exist to attract individuals with local expertise to seek government jobs, thus taking control of their administration. Without it, the flourishing of Inuit aspirations in Nunavut will remain dormant, mirroring the previous era.
<p>
The current reliance on the government for social assistance should not be transposed to a reliance on government for employment. Facilitating private economic development might be a way to loosen the overdependence on government for employment as well as to reduce the government payroll.<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> Relying on the government for employment can lead to the stagnation of economic growth by dissuading the Inuit of the need for private initiative.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> However, the major difficulty for Nunavut economic development is the absence of an entrepreneurial tradition among the population.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup> Therefore, any stratagem must account for the cultural and psychological barriers to a &quot;business&quot; orientation. Cultivating an economic infrastructure, in both a traditional and modern sense, and in both private and public spheres, is untenable without an educated, skilled, or trained population in addition to an entrepreneurial spirit.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup>
<p>
LAND RESOURCE MANAGEMENT
<p>
Economic planning will have important implications for political stability in Nunavut. Decisions about economic development are necessarily related to resource management in the Eastern Arctic. Having to balance a project's economic opportunities with its impact on the region's natural resources will often put the Inuit in a precarious situation. However, what is more noteworthy is that the Inuit have an effective voice in these matters, because of shared administrative responsibility on numerous tribunals. Participation in this area is meaningful to the Inuit, who culturally identify themselves with their environment.
<p>
Incentives to develop the area must be offered to assist in improving the economic situation. Soliciting development has always been difficult in a land that is relatively inaccessible to the south and thus unattractive for companies due to the exorbitant operational costs involved. In addition, investors in the south have viewed the northern authorities as being too stringent environmentally, or as having created a process that is overregulated.<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> This problem has been inimical to economic development in the Northwest Territories, where overlap, duplication, and over-bureaucratization due to both federal and territorial government involvement have deterred developers from investing.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup>
<p>
The Nunavut regulatory regime amalgamates the three government systems into one process. A number of boards' decisions must still obtain ministerial approval, but the vertical structure used in the <cite>Inuvialuit</cite> region, with three different environmental assessment processes, has been replaced by a horizontal arrangement, in which a number of different boards operate concurrently. The simplification of the assessment process has resulted in growing optimism about future development in Nunavut.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup>
<p>
Determining the balance between the facilitation of non-renewable resource development and responsible environmental management will be problematic. The difficulty has already surfaced at the Cullaton Lake Mine, where the Inuit Development Corporation entered into a financial arrangement for compensation which the Inuit
Tapirisat of Canada perceived as being too accommodating to mine exploration and unchecked development.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> While this conundrum may plague every government, its ramifications are more serious for the Inuit, whose daily existence is linked with a healthy environment. The land
claims process has been criticized as issuing a <i>de facto</i> licence for natural non-renewable resource exploitation, since it is the underlying reason that the government consents to any land claims agreement.<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> This contrasts with Inuit values, in which cultural and spiritual identity is preserved by a healthy and sustainable environment.<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup>
<p>
However, natural resource development is not exclusively a government interest.
<blockquote>
The road to self-determination and self-government is paved with capital resources. With money comes power. With no money to carry out the desires of a self-determining, self-governing people, all the &quot;rights&quot; in the world will not effect any change in current conditions.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Inuit have historically integrated themselves into the Qallunaat's economic ventures in the north, such as trapping and whaling, which have provided economic benefits for the people. While there is little disagreement about the vast potential for northern prosperity and the corresponding need for economic integration, the Inuit have grown disillusioned by the repeated practice of businesses emigrating once the feasibility of the venture becomes suspect. Fuelling this disenchantment is the minimal reinvestment of the returns from these operations into the communities.<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> The historically transient nature of these operations could cause Nunavut administrators to be sceptical of development. Immediate economic rewards may be enticing, but project approval could also be made contingent on guarantees for long-term social, economic, and cultural protection.
<p>
One approach could be to encourage Inuk developers, contractors, and employees to participate in the resource industry. This could mitigate the reliance on natural resources development, which is usually directed by outside interests.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> Currently, there is very little Inuit participation in resource development. &quot;[S]haring the wealth&quot;<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> accrued from
settlement lands is at the heart of the Nunavut agenda. It would prevent situations where projects are managed by individuals who have no stake in the long-term interests of the area.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> A consolidated political voice in Nunavut could effectively lead to a fuller understanding of Inuit needs, and, incidentally, a better dialogue between Nunavut regulators and foreign companies. A useful example is the Inupiat of the North Slope of Alaska, under the <cite>Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> whose input into resource development in their area has led to modifications of
development operations.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup> The relationship is not intended to be
oppositional but rather a cooperative one based on respect for the people whose land is being used.
<p>
One possible way to compensate for the limited representation in development operations is to implement a public assistance program that funds Inuit-operated ventures. Subsidization of these projects could counterbalance the advantages developers wield in capital resources. Other approaches in the <cite>Agreement</cite> include a
government contract bidding process which is designed to favour Inuit businesses.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> In addition, if a project will have a socio-economic impact on the area, one constructive form of the compensation called for in the <cite>Agreement</cite> could be a direction to a developer to create employment opportunities for the Inuit.<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> However, this discretion should be exercised cautiously since quota systems for hiring in the past have been unsuccessful. Moreover, they have unnerved the mining industry.<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup>
<p>
Inuit involvement in the development process can manifest itself in other ways. The <cite>Agreement</cite> establishes numerous tribunals and boards, composed of equal numbers of Nunavut residents and government administrators, to manage the lands, water, and wildlife in the area.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup> The requirement of Inuit representation on these boards amply illustrates how far aboriginal rights have developed over the last 100 years. Instead of aboriginal peoples having a personal and usufructuary right, limited by the discretion of the Crown to extinguish it,<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup> the Inuit in the <cite>Agreement</cite> maintain regulatory power to manage and monitor non-native use of the land. They are also entitled to compensation for any development project in Nunavut, to be worked out prior to its commencement, that qualitatively or quantitatively affects the water in Inuit Owned Lands.<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> Access to Inuit lands or subsurface materials must be approved by the DIO.<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup> Furthermore, consultation with the Inuit is also required for all petroleum exploration on
Crown and Inuit lands in the Settlement Area.<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup> The days are past when Inuit concerns could be neglected or ignored.
<p>
Some of the stated objectives in the Agreement include the clarification of rights to ownership of land and resources, the provision of Inuit wildlife harvesting rights, and effective participation and involvement in decision making while exercising those rights.<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup> This is meaningful to a people whose source of cultural and social livelihood depends on a sound environment. However, the Nunavut environmental assessment process resembles a co-management scheme instead of self-management. Self-management is a system in which the monitoring of the land and renewable resources is done solely by users of the resources. The users become the stewards of the land, which accords with traditional aboriginal philosophy. Co-management entails shared responsibilities between two parties. It is often the case that the party that resides within the environment that is managed does not have final decision-making power. In a common co-management scheme a board's decisions are ultimately subject to government approval. This can fall well short of self-government ambitions.<sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup>
<p>
However, the Nunavut co-management scheme is not a polarized confrontation pitting two different value systems against each other. Although government and the Inuit are not unanimous about how the Arctic should be developed and protected, there are clear, mandated objectives establishing a consensus that crosses cultural lines. A Nunavut land use strategy will contain a list of objectives that are formulated and agreed upon at the outset. This was a concession that the Inuit were seeking. Peter Ittinuar comments:
<blockquote>
We are willing to accept the principle of a ministerial veto if the Inuit are given the power to make decisions in the first instance, and if the minister's right to overrule those decisions is subject to certain agreed-upon criteria.<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The <cite>Agreement</cite> stipulates that the government shares a concern with the Inuit to develop the area in an environmentally responsible manner, with a sensitivity to the importance of natural resources to the Inuit. The stewardship responsibilities toward the land are a joint venture. The fragility of the Arctic environment and its vulnerability to the effects of development and exploitation are the responsibility of all the affected parties. 
<p>
The Nunavut Wildlife Management Board (NWMB) illustrates a co-management system with a unified agenda. It will have nine members: four appointed by the DIO, with the remainder appointed by various government officials.<sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup> It is likely that more than four Inuk will serve on this board since the Inuit probably possess a better understanding of the issues involved than do outside bureaucrats. Furthermore, a fifth member of the Board, appointed by the Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development, must be ordinarily resident in Nunavut.<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup> The board must adhere to the harvesting interests of the Inuit and the need for a healthy renewable resource economy in every decision. It is obligated to recognize the importance of effective Inuit representation in wildlife management.<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup> The pronouncement of guidelines and mandatory Inuit representation ensures the acknowledgement of Inuit concerns at NWMB hearings. This makes environmental co-management of the Arctic ecosystem more harmonious, since the avenues for conflict have been narrowed. 
<p>
Enforcement of the environmental objectives through the <cite>Agreement's</cite> co-management scheme adds more protection to Inuit interests. Environmental monitoring of ongoing development continues well after the approval of projects. The Nunavut Impact Review Board (NIRB) will review public and private proposals.<sup><a href="#one57">157</a></sup> As projects proceed, the government, the Nunavut Planning Commission (NPC), and possibly the NIRB will be required to ensure that the conditions of a project approval are being met.<sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup> Enforcement of permits, certificates, or licences will be undertaken only by the
responsible government agency in conjunction with the NPC or NIRB.<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup> However, a DIO does have standing to seek a determination in court whether a term or condition is being fulfilled, to obtain a court order compelling a person to perform an obligation or prohibiting a developer from implementing a
term or condition of a NIRB certificate, and to seek judicial review of any decision or order.<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup> Therefore, a failure to comply with expressed requirements can be challenged by many parties. 
<p>
As well as being able to participate in the enforcement of environmental management, the Inuit will have access to the assessment process. A co-management framework that recognizes the value of traditional knowledge and experience, along with the scientific expertise of government officials, will allay the alienation Inuit can experience in the assessment process. Inuit knowledge of their environment is more instinctual and less reliant on scientific data.<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup> Traditionally, however, environmental assessment has been a fairly
regimented procedure in which copious research and exhaustive studies are conducted. This technical aspect of the regulatory process, as well as the operation of deadlines and timetables, has confused and estranged Cree and Inuit members of the various <cite>JBNQA</cite> wildlife management boards.<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup>
<p>
The contribution of hunters and trappers who constantly interact with the lands would lead to more responsive decision making and community involvement in the land management process.<sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup> Information from users of the land would be a primary resource. This process would restructure the methodology in environmental management, which is conventionally a scientific endeavour. The Nunavut Wildlife Harvest Study will incorporate local knowledge by collecting data from harvesters and
conducting interviews in each community.<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup> As Nunavut can be divided into different ecosystems, it is more logical to decentralize the process. 
<p>
<h3>Community Development and Participation</h3>

Northern communities are characterized by their isolation. There is always an inherent danger in a comprehensive land settlement to amalgamate community interests under a larger policy.<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup> The consolidation of the community interest under a Nunavut policy may not recognize that each community has
evolved independently of the others. Because the communities are so distant from each other, each community's concerns may be particular  to it. Their stages of development as well as their capabilities to deliver municipal services differ greatly. The involvement of the communities, and the community members, is essential to a functioning Nunavut government. In response, the <cite>Agreement</cite> proposes an alternative to municipal government that delegates to the community certain powers, such as wildlife management, which are relevant to
the daily activities existing at the local level. Involvement in community affairs will strengthen the community and instill a sense of purpose for many Inuit. 
<p>
Article 14 of the <cite>Agreement</cite> grants existing communities in Nunavut corporate municipal status.<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup> Community members are to vote in a referendum concerning the alienability of their municipal lands.<sup><a href ="#one67">167</a></sup> Municipal boundaries will
encompass lands used by the community for subsistence and recreational activities, which parallels southern communities where the home and the workplace coexist within a governmental region.<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup>
<p>
However, municipalities are redefined in Nunavut. Land use planning and zoning are normally designated as municipal powers; this type of authority is held exclusively by Nunavut municipalities.<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup> But environmental protection of municipal land is also imperative because hunting, fishing, and trapping activities are often done near the community. The <cite>Agreement</cite> guarantees consultation with the municipality on wildlife management issues and regional planning decisions<sup><a href="#one70">170</a></sup> as well as monitoring harvesting practices and techniques, and basic needs levels
through the auspices of communities' Hunters and Trappers Organizations.<sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup> Having a stronger community presence in environmental management reflects the nature of Arctic municipalities, which substantially differ from their urban counterparts. 
<p>
Nunavut municipalities will also acquire more government powers than municipalities usually have. Devolution of authority to the community level has been on the Territorial government's agenda for the last few years.<sup><a href="#one72">172</a></sup> With new powers, however, come additional expenses. This is a dilemma for a region with extremely limited resources and communities that lack the municipal infrastructure to deliver
government services. Providing adequate funding will place a heavy burden on the Nunavut treasury, even with federal and territorial support. There may be community transfer agreements, as proposed by the Territorial Government, but a logistical analysis must carefully calculate the capability of the communities to administer municipal responsibilities.<sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup> Simply funding local services is meaningless without experienced personnel or an established infrastructure to facilitate them. Furthermore, monetary solutions are always subject to periods of financial restraint. Contribution to community development may be more effectively made through other means such as transferring food, resources, or employment opportunities.<sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup> 
<p>
Focus on community problems will require a decentralized approach to government in Nunavut. It allows for an awareness of the local socio-economic conditions that exist at varying stages of development. Due to that diversity, government leaders can fail to comprehend the needs of each community. It is usually at this level that problems arise and that immediate action can be taken in response. Expressing community concerns in the Nunavut legislature
can integrate local needs into Nunavut policy. Moreover, it provides an outlet for reclaiming responsibilities in the communities by airing grievances to a government body that will listen. 
<p>
Community involvement and participation are essential for Nunavut. They have been the basis of the success of the <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite>.<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup> Over the years of negotiations for
the <cite>Agreement</cite>, there has been a healthy dialogue between the communities and the leaders.<sup><a href="#one76">176</a></sup> This could be a precursor for a more consensual style of government in Nunavut. However, the communities continue to look to outsiders for community solutions. Although social workers, management consultants, and land planners greatly contribute to local development, answers to community problems should originate from internal sources as much as from outside specialists. Essentially, community members carry a better understanding of community needs. Their involvement fashions direct and swift responses. Active participation in community affairs by members of the community should destroy the myth that only professionals or educators have the best solutions. As a result, this may be the impetus needed for communities to undertake more of their own responsibilities.
<p>
<h3>A Vehicle for Community Involvement: Community Justice</h3>

The administration of a community's affairs begins with its ability to manage local disputes and social problems. Community justice acts as a means of alleviating the local strife that disrupts community harmony.<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup> It is an area in which communities in Nunavut are anxious to become involved, in the hope of establishing a closer connection to tradition while assuming responsibility for social ills. In areas such as criminal law, family law, and civil disputes, local participation in the process could serve as a vehicle for community expression. Moreover, community justice can react to the dangers threatening the community while promptly addressing the wrong committed by the offender. A legal &quot;system&quot;, even under Nunavut direction, can overlook the particular characteristics of the individuals and their environment, as well as how the community itself views the situation. Decentralizing the process will allow each community to resume control of its own life.
<p>
Nunavut is based on fostering independence and self-esteem for the Inuit. It is hoped that renewed pride will engender a decrease in the crime rate in the Eastern Arctic, which is alarmingly high.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> Some conclude that the large incidence of anti-social behaviour is a by-product of exposure to white industrial society.<sup><a href="#one79">179</a></sup>However, a return to the pre-colonial era is unlikely. It would be impossible to negate the influences another culture has spread to the north, because they have reoriented Inuit life, especially for younger Inuit. These influences have created a fledgling generation of youth that is maladapted and uninvolved in community life. Trapped in a cultural abyss between traditional ways
and modern society, Inuit youth remain isolated from their own communities. This social and economic dislocation, compounded by a poor educational background and unfamiliarity with traditional practices, perpetuates repeated encounters with the justice system that are inextricably linked to substance and alcohol abuse.<sup><a href="#one80">180</a></sup>
<p>
Canadian law was introduced in the north as an act of sovereignty that protected Canadian explorers in the
area.<sup><a href="#one81">181</a></sup> Inuit community methods of dispute resolution, used for many centuries, were either supplanted or not respected. One prominent example is the story of Robert Janes, a trapper in Pond Inlet who, in 1921, began to unsettle the community with menacing behaviour.<sup><a href="#one82">182</a></sup> The Inuit perceived his actions to be a serious threat to their survival. He was subsequently murdered. The following year, the R.C.M.P. was sent to investigate and try three community members for their involvement in the murder. The jury was composed of a crew from a nearby patrol boat who had no
exposure to the community's affairs. One accused was convicted of manslaughter, one convicted for aiding and abetting, and one acquitted. As one of the first instances of the application of Canadian law in the Eastern Arctic, it started a pattern in which a community's disputes were judged under an external legal system that ignored the community's consensual dispute resolution methods.
<p>
Community justice systems in conjunction with other locally generated programs can be an effective and holistic means to combat local problems. Through its focus on the individual transgressor, the process addresses social ills at the source. Counselling for the offender is continued well after the trial has ended, while attempts are made to regain and maintain a harmonious environment. In discussing the Inumarit justice committee of Arctic Bay, Bourassa J.
stated:
<blockquote>
It is obvious to me that what has been said in evidence today, that the community is willing to act, the Inumarit is willing to act and Social Services are willing to act in this case, is not an empty promise. It is true. It is a fact. It is proven in the past by the very absence of crime or disturbance. This special part of Arctic Bay is something that I would be very sad to see, in any way, taken away or diminished. The very things that the Inumarit are trying to
do, rehabilitating the offender, reconciling the offender, the victim and the community, is done so that there is unity in the community and a program of education.<sup><a href="#one83">183</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Local solutions can uphold the principles of criminal law while strengthening the communities. The political and cultural affirmation of the Inuit in Nunavut should materialize locally. This can be realized through community directed action that treats offenders and heals the community. The application of Inuit norms and customs can allay the foreignness of the criminal law system by placing it in the community context. However, community methods have not been regularly used.
<p>
Criminal sentencing may be the most unfamiliar and thus confusing part of the legal process.<sup><a href="#one84">184</a></sup> This is due to the harsh consequences that conflict with traditional sanctions orchestrated to reincorporate the offender into the community. Community justice is sometimes employed in sentencing when the court consults with community members about the best form of treatment for the individual offender that will also recognize the interests of the collective. Trial courts may consult with community groups during sentencing proceedings, thus allowing for a convergence of the two value systems. Mediating disputes prior to trial can convince the court that normal punishment is contrary to the wishes of the community. However, those attempts can be subsequently undermined by higher courts who do not appreciate the dynamics at trial.<sup><a href="#one85">185</a></sup> Appeals are even more confusing for the Inuit when higher sentences are imposed after the original sentence has been served. At this point, the offender has already been rehabilitated and has been reintegrated back into the community, thereby concluding the matter in the community's opinion.<sup><a href="#one86">186</a></sup>  The imposition of higher sentences further distances the community's interests from the legal process.
 <p>
 The overturning of community oriented sentences illustrates the &quot;incorporation&quot; model of Canadian and Inuit justice systems. Aboriginal laws and customs are recognized as a valid way to resolve disputes only to the point where they do not contradict with Canadian law.<sup><a href="#one87">187</a></sup> This model
can overlook what has taken place since the offence, such as conciliation between the offender and the community. Most crimes in the Eastern Arctic involve violence, with a large proportion of them being sexual assault. These offences have been judicially recognized as socially condemnable, deserving of significant penal consequences.<sup><a href="#one88">188</a></sup> Community sanctions that fall short of the minimum sentencing requirements are vulnerable to appeal. Therefore, there may be limited application of community justice in cases of sexual or domestic violence, which comprise a majority of the offences in the Eastern Arctic. 
<p>
Community justice cannot be dispensed in the same fashion as was done prior to Euro-Canadian contact. The traditional sanctions employed to educate the offender and heal the community may not be as effective as before.<sup><a href="#one89">189</a></sup> Social ostracism, ridicule and gossip do not affect the offender as severely because influences of Canadian culture have reduced the interdependency of community members. Withdrawing support, food, and other provisions is a futile community sanction when those goods and services are readily available from the state. Traditional sanctions were honoured because of respect for the elders' decision. That deference has been undermined among younger Inuit, who question the wisdom of the elders, whom they perceive as not understanding their needs or the pressures they are experiencing.<sup><a href="#one90">190</a></sup>
<p>
The threat of penal servitude has not been an effective deterrent either. The cycle of violence and alcoholism continues. Law can isolate the individual problem by chopping down the tree, but the roots of these sociological problems run much deeper. As the Inuit population increases, a rise rather than a drop in the crime rate is likely.<sup><a href="#one91">191</a></sup> Community input into the judicial process affords the opportunity to reveal the underlying problems, thereby prompting collective action to prevent further harm. Treatment of the offence by the community is facilitated by group involvement which continues well after the trial has ended. This also enables the community to approach the specific offence holistically by attacking the underlying social causes. The trial acts as a starting point instead of the finish. 
<p>
However, there are some concerns about community justice. For example, any sanction on the offender must be meaningful; the offender should not gain the impression that he or she has benefitted from leniency and thus has no reason to change.<sup><a href="#one92">192</a></sup> Offenders must be committed to the community sentencing process or that process is futile.<sup><a href="#one93">193</a></sup>
<p>
Another concern is that community justice systems have traditionally been less attentive to the harm to the victim than to the problems of the offender or the injury to the community. A severe punishment may be directed when the offender is considered to be beyond redemption. Short of that, the offender will participate in rigorous consultation and community service, and publicly apologize to the victim. This approach appears to be more proactive and eliminates any notions of vengeance, but it fails to acknowledge that the victim must reside, while being intimidated, ashamed, and embarrassed, in the same community as the offender. This has been a problem for many Inuit women. Those who are victims of sexual and domestic violence often encounter a lack of support mechanisms in the community and therefore have to look to outside sources.<sup><a href="#one94">194</a></sup> The community may not take into account the presence or extent of the victims' psychological and emotional injuries. Inuit women therefore demand the same censure of domestic violence and sexual abuse that the law accords in other jurisdictions.
<p>
Compounding this problem is that traditional justice systems can tailor a penalty to the individual's importance to the community, fostering inequality and capriciousness. This suggests that for some, criminal behaviour is not as condemnable as for others. The community's dependency on the offender parallels the victim's familial dependency.<sup><a href="#one95">195</a></sup> In addition, there is always a concern that any judicial body will not fully represent the diversity in the community.<sup><a href="#one96">196</a></sup> Pauktuutit (Inuit Women's Association) has voiced some scepticism about the make-up of these organizations, which are often composed of known abusers.<sup><a href="#one97">197</a></sup>
<p>
Recognition of customary law and the concept of a separate aboriginal justice system are common topics in the political forum; however, for Nunavut it was not at the forefront of the debate. Other land claims discussions have centred on this issue, but the Inuit perhaps need a period of refinement in the nascent stages of Nunavut before an alternative justice system can be formulated.<sup><a href="#one98">198</a></sup> Nunavut communities must be prepared to take more control, but this might require a period of adjustment to a new administrative system. It may be more advantageous to design a justice system when the Inuit are more comfortable with their new political status. Aboriginal justice systems have been established in other parts of Canada; however, their strength and efficacy flows from the will of the community and the receptiveness of the government toward them.<sup><a href="#one99">199</a></sup> The Department of Justice has confirmed the potential of a grassroots community justice system in the north:
<blockquote>
In the Northwest Territories the majority of the population is native, and many native people maintain close ties to a traditional lifestyle. It should be possible here, of all places, to have a justice system which serves the needs of the native community.<sup><a href="#twohundred">200</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Nunavut communities remain relatively isolated and therefore can identify with traditional mores. Moreover, the
communities are predominantly mono-cultural; thus, a community-oriented approach to justice would reflect the majority interests. However, since Nunavut communities are at varying stages of development in justice administration, any decentralized process must recognize the differences in resources and the willingness of the communities to assume justice responsibilities.
<p>
Experimentation with community justice has occurred in other land claims agreements. The Cree and the Inuit in the <cite>JBNQA</cite> exhibit two different approaches in bringing justice closer to the people. For the Cree, the appointment in each community of a judge with a broader jurisdiction than a Justice of the Peace has been used
to integrate the community perspective into the legal process. However, this approach excludes someone without a Euro-Canadian legal background because of the complexity of the issues involved.<sup><a href="#two01">201</a></sup> This may also be an inappropriate approach for Nunavut because many Inuit do not want to reside in a community in which they are constantly judging others.<sup><a href="#two02">202</a></sup> But
maintaining the Justice of the Peace Court, with its limited jurisdiction, would only uphold the status quo which conflicts with Nunavut ambitions.<sup><a href="#two03">203</a></sup>
<p>
Statutory reform may be a more viable alternative to making procedural changes or broadening a court's jurisdiction. Potentially, the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> could be adjusted to adapt to the particular circumstances and customs of the Inuit. This was promised to Inuit consignees to the <cite>JBNQA</cite>.<sup><a href="#two04">204</a></cite> Criminal laws in Greenland, which essentially cover penal sanctions, advance a number of concessions that embrace community and cultural norms, including a prohibition against any increase of a
sentence in an appeal decision. Moreover, detention is necessary only when the safety of the community is threatened. The Greenland experience reveals a codification of community justice principles, which the Nunavut government could be empowered to implement. A consolidated proposal tabled by the Nunavut legislature could
pressure the federal government more effectively than the Inuit have been able to do in Quebec. 
<p>
Nunavut will face a great need for lawyers. The administration of criminal justice powers will require people who
understand the legal challenges involved. The contractual nature of the <cite>Agreement</cite>, as well as the many questions surrounding the status of Nunavut in Canadian federalism, also necessitates the employment of legal skills. In the communities, there will be more work for a Justice of the Peace or similar mediator who would
adjudicate over by-laws, summary conviction offences, and Nunavut laws, as well as the relevant provisions of the <cite>Agreement</cite>. Current participation of Inuit in the justice process is limited to the roles of court interpreters and Justices of the Peace. There are only two Inuk lawyers, which &quot;imposes real limitations on the
ability to move Inuit into court roles and to permit the majority of the population even to understand the language of the court.&quot;<sup><a href="#two05">205</a></sup> The federal government does offer scholarships for pre-law programs at the University of Saskatchewan and the University of Ottawa; however, transplanting an Inuk into a southern environment can pose tremendous hardships. Alternatively, there are plans for the establishment of a
Nunavut law school to be coordinated by Judge Beverley Brown of the Territorial Court.<sup><a href="#two06">206</a></sup> This may assist in melding the two systems to reflect the situation in the Eastern Arctic.
<p>
In the words of the Honourable Stephen Kakwfi, Minister of Justice, Northwest Territories, &quot;Assuming justice is part of a larger process of communities taking back responsibility over their own lives.&quot;<sup><a href="#two07">207</a></sup> Community justice mechanisms offer an opportunity for the community to resolve
local disputes. However, there are concerns about community justice committees, such as their composition, their effectiveness in deterring criminal behaviour, and their accessibility to the community. The presentation of this article was purposely designed to move from a consideration of general aboriginal policy in Canada to the pressing issues at the community level. It is here that real changes in the lives of the Inuit will be measured. The proliferation of community justice is of symbolic importance; it would demonstrate that the needs and ambitions of the Inuit are being realized through the incremental accomplishments of the community. Community justice not only serves to hark back to a prouder era, but also instills goals for the personal betterment of each Inuk. Evaluating the success of the <cite>Agreement</cite> on the basis of individual advancement is perhaps the most genuine indication of a successful future for the Eastern Arctic. 
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

Expectations of the perfect solution for the Inuit are unrealistic. Although the <cite>Agreement</cite> may not fully satisfy ambitions of sovereignty, self-determination, or even self-government according to some definitions, its mechanisms provide tremendous opportunity for the Inuit to manage the affairs of Nunavut. In 1999, the Nunavut government will be able to tackle public issues in a jurisdiction in which the population is predominantly Inuit. The
interchange of different viewpoints, stemming from various regions and communities, will stimulate a consensus-style government. Public government enables the Inuit to confront the problems that immediately affect the Inuit, both locally and throughout Nunavut, which is a more effective form of self-government than a strictly municipal or localized one.
<p>
However, governing an enormous territory will create considerable challenges for Nunavut. Taking responsibility will require diligent attempts to address the difficulties arising from the ongoing socio-economic transformation of the Eastern Arctic. Fostering economic development can assist in providing a sense of productiveness and self-worth for the Inuit. However, this will be difficult due to a limited economic infrastructure and a population
unfamiliar with the operation of a wage economy. Nunavut is on the verge of non-renewable natural resource development that can provide the Inuit with employment opportunities and lucrative revenue from royalties. An able work force and Inuit private investors can help the Inuit start to assume control over that development. These are the factors that will determine the success in the Eastern Arctic.
<p>
Nunavut policy should be imaginative and flexible due to the unique circumstances in the north. Initial gains will be moderate at best, with a real likelihood of miscalculations and setbacks. Moreover, there will be periods of frustration during the transition when there will be a need to depend on non-Inuit consultants. However, public government necessitates cooperation and patience, which the Inuit have demonstrated over the years of negotiations.
Difficult lessons must be learned, but experience will be the best educator. An awareness of previous mistakes will help future generations improve on the existing political framework. It must be remembered that inherent in any governing body is the propensity to err. This is a characteristic of self-government.<sup><a href="#two08">208</a></sup>
<p>
Any evaluation of the success of the <cite>Agreement</cite> must begin with each community. They are the essence of the Eastern Arctic, although some have survived better than others amidst the influences of Canadian culture. Involvement in government affairs and delivery of services at the local level can instill a sense of belonging. Control over Inuit affairs can bridge the old culture with the new, thwarting the dislocation many young Inuit are
experiencing in their own communities. The next generation may have increased opportunities, precipitating an incentive to pursue education and training programs. 
<p>
Aboriginal peoples across Canada will observe Nunavut carefully to determine its viability as a strong political aboriginal voice. Purich elaborates on how Nunavut will be seen as an experiment:
<blockquote>
Nunavut may represent a substantial breakthrough for Aboriginal people. Given current prospects, Nunavut will be the first Aboriginal government to have provincial-type powers. And as such it may be the answer to those critics who fear that an Aboriginal government may not work. Nunavut may well represent the first genuine power sharing with Aboriginal people. Its creation will serve as an example of what other Aboriginals can achieve. It is important to understand that the quest for Nunavut is part of the larger struggle by Aboriginals for justice and self-government.<sup><a href="#two09">209</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Other First Nations may not fit within the Nunavut framework, which requires a majority population in an extensive
region to implement the public government model. However, the relationship that Nunavut authorities nurture with the government can open new avenues of understanding. Consequently, other models of aboriginal self-government can establish themselves in the Canadian constitutional family, facilitated by an atmosphere of trust and cooperation.
<p><br>
<hr>
<p>
