<p>
<li><a name="six">B.A. Hochstein,</a> <cite>New Rights or No Rights?  COPE and the Federal Government of
Canada</cite> (MA Thesis, Univ of Calgary, 1987). See also Inuit Tapirisat of Canada, <cite>Parnagujuk: Basic Objectives of a Comprehensive Blueprint for the North</cite> (Ottawa: Inuit Tapirisat of Canada, 1981) at 21 [hereinafter ITC]; J.R. Ponting &amp; R. Gibbins, <cite>Out of Irrelevance: A Socio-Political Introduction to Indian Affairs in Canada</cite> (Toronto: Butterworths, 1980) at 265; P. Cumming, &quot;Canada's North and Native Rights&quot; in B. Morse, ed., <cite>Aboriginal Peoples and the Law: Indian, M&eacute;tis and Inuit Rights in Canada</cite> (Ottawa: Carleton University Press, 1985) at 724; J. Merritt &amp; T. Fenge, &quot;The Nunavut Land Claims Settlement: Emerging Issues in Law and Public Administration&quot; (1991) 15 Queens L.J. 255.
<p>
<li><a name="seven">The perception</a> that all aboriginal rights are waived by an extinguishment clause was held by the Dene/M&eacute;tis, fuelling their rejection of a 1990 comprehensive claim proposal. In turn, it appears this decision has bifurcated the Dene Nation. The Gwich'in, Sahtu, and Treaty 8 Dene are resolving their claims independently of one another while encountering internal dissension. The Dogrib have yet to do so. That lack of consolidated voice frustrates any efforts to form a counterpart to the Nunavut political territory, proclaimed as Dennedeh, meaning &quot;the land of the people.&quot;  See Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 136.
<p>
<li><a name="eight">The <cite>Agreement</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2 at Art. 2.7.3 (a),(b).</a>
<blockquote>
Nothing in the Agreement shall:
<blockquote>
(a) be construed so as to deny that Inuit are an aboriginal people of Canada or, subject to Section 2.7.1, affect their ability to participate in or benefit from any existing or future constitutional rights for aboriginal people which may be applicable to them;
<p>
(b) affect the ability of Inuit to participate in and benefit from government programs for Inuit or aboriginal people
generally as the case may be: benefits received under such programs as shall be determined by general criteria for such programs established from time to time... .
</blockquote></blockquote>
<li><a name="nine"><cite>R. v. Sparrow</cite></a>, [1990] 1 S.C.R. 1075, 70 D.L.R. (4th) 385 [hereinafter <cite>Sparrow</cite>, cited to D.L.R.], and <cite>Sioui v. Quebec</cite>, [1990] 1 S.C.R. 1025, 70 D.L.R. (4th) 427, are two of the major cases that have broadened the scope of aboriginal rights over the last few years.
<p>
<li><a name="ten"><cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>,</a> being Schedule B of the <cite>Canada Act, 1982</cite>, (U.K.), 1982, c.11 [hereinafter <cite>Constitution</cite>]:
<blockquote>
35(1) The existing aboriginal and treaty rights of the aboriginal peoples of Canada are hereby recognized and affirmed.
<p>
(2) In this Act, &quot;aboriginal peoples of Canada&quot; includes the Indian, Inuit and M&eacute;tis people of Canada.
</blockquote>
<li><a name="eleven">T.R. Berger,</a> <cite>Northern Frontier Northern Homeland: The Report of the Mackenzie Valley Pipeline Enquiry</cite>, revised edition (Vancouver: Douglas &amp; McIntyre, 1977, 1988) at 229.
<p>
<li><a name="twelve">Canada, Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development,</a> <cite>Comprehensive Land Claims Policy</cite> (Ottawa: Minister of Supplies and Services,1987) at 9.
The Land Claims Strategy was a method of reconciliation by the Liberals in 1973 who had rejected, four years previously, any idea of aboriginal rights. Canada, Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development, <cite>White Paper on Indian Policy</cite> (Ottawa: Minister of Supplies and Services, 1969). Subsequently, in light of the Supreme Court decision recognizing aboriginal title in <cite>Calder v. Attorney-General of British Columbia</cite>, [1973] S.C.R. 313, [1973] 4 W.W.R. 1, the government reassessed its position on the existence of native rights which brought it to the negotiating table.
<p>
<li><a name="thirteen">R. Bartlett,</a> <cite>Indian Reserves and Aboriginal Lands in Canada: A Homeland</cite> (Saskatoon: University of Saskatchewan, 1990) at 52.
<p>
<li><a name="fourteen">ITC,</a> <i>supra</i> note 6 at 48. There is also some uncertainty as to what aboriginal title can provide for the Inuit in light of the court's ruling in <cite>Baker Lake</cite>, <i>infra</i> note 15. It may be
extinguishable through mining regulations, it is not a proprietary right, and title does not encompass surface or subsurface rights. See ITC, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 15 and R. Pugh, &quot;Are Northern Lands Reserved for the Indians?&quot; (1981) 60 Can. Bar Rev. 36.
<p>
<li><a name="fifteen">Berger,</a> <i>supra</i> note 11; Hochstein, <i>supra</i> note 6. In <cite>Re Eskimos</cite>, [1939] S.C.R. 104, the Supreme Court concluded that the Inuit were Indians for the purpose of federal administrative responsibility under the <cite>Indian Act</cite>, R.S.C. 1985, c. I--7. This classification represented a legal perception that all First Nations, with the notable exception of the M&eacute;tis, were fundamentally similar and thus should be governed equally. In <cite>Baker Lake v. Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development</cite>, [1980] 1 F.C. 518, [1980] 5 W.W.R. 193, the legal concept of aboriginal title was extended to Inuit title on lands not under the ambit of the <cite>Royal Proclamation of 1763</cite>, R.S.C. 1870, App. 11, No. 1. (&quot;Indian&quot; title, in the Northwest Territories, was recognized in the <cite>Dominion Lands Act</cite> S.O. 1972, s. 42.)  This reinforced the perception of the sameness of Indians and Inuit, although the standards to establish aboriginal title were adjusted to appreciate the regional history of the Inuit. This is the only case in Canada where Inuit title was ever asserted. Section 35(2) of the Constitution, <i>supra</i> note 10, mirrors this perception although it posits the distinction among Inuit, Indians, and M&eacute;tis to illustrate who are Canada's aboriginal peoples.
<p>
<li><a name="sixteen">Purich,</a> <i>supra</i> note 3 at 97. Since they were never party to a treaty, the Inuit did not regard the international flavour of these agreements, where First Nations would contract with another
sovereign on an equal footing in international law, with much importance. Perhaps this explains why the Inuit rarely refer to themselves as a First Nation but more as a people. (This observation is based on numerous conversations between the author and various Inuit and Inuvialuit.)
<p>
<li><a name="seventeen">Hochstein,</a> <i>supra</i> note 6 at 10. The evolution of a united political voice
from the Inuit occurred over encroaching oil and gas development in the Arctic during the late 1960s and early 1970s. See also N. Graburn &amp; B.S. Strong, <cite>Circumpolar Peoples: An Anthropological Perspective</cite> (Pacific Palisades: Goodyear Pub., 1973). Due to the different dynamics existing in each community, it is erroneous to simplify Inuit opinions, as many regions and communities differ. However, there are enough similarities to support a unified position.
<p>
<li><a name="eighteen">Berger,</a> <i>supra</i> note 11 at 226. The Inuit living in the Mackenzie River Delta were invited to sign Treaty Number 11 in 1921 and 1922 because of oil discoveries in Norman Wells, but declined. See also Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 98.
<p>
<li><a name="nineteen">Berger,</a> <i>ibid.</i> at 226. See also P. Ittunuar, &quot;The Inuit Perspective on Aboriginal Rights&quot; in Boldt &amp; Long, <i>supra</i> note 4; P. Tennant, &quot;Aboriginal Rights and the
Penner Report&quot; in Boldt &amp; Long, <i>supra</i> note 4; W. Moss, &quot;The Implementation of the James Bay and Northern Quebec Agreement&quot; in Morse, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 685; Cumming, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 701; <cite>R. v. Sikyea</cite> (1963), 43 D.L.R. (2d) 150, 49 W.W.R. 306 (S.C.C.); <cite>Cardinal v. Attorney General of Alberta</cite>, [1974] S.C.R. 695, 13 C.C.C. (2d) 1; <cite>R. v. George</cite>, [1966] S.C.R. 267, 55 D.L.R. (2d) 386; <cite>Krueger and Manuel v. R</cite>., [1978] 1 S.C.R. 104, 15 N.R. 495; <cite>R. v. Eninew</cite> (1984), 10 D.L.R. (4th) 137 (Sask C.A.). There has been an absence of s. 35 litigation in the Northwest Territories, which suggests that it is more advantageous to resolve outstanding grievances in a land claim rather than through litigation. This may be attributable to the inability of the Territorial Government to legislate for Indians under Section 91 (24) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite> (U.K.), 30 &amp; 31 Vict., c. 3. [hereinafter <cite>BNA Act</cite>] except for gaming laws which cannot infringe aboriginal subsistence hunting rights. See <cite>Northwest Territories Act</cite>, R.S.C. 1985, c. N--27, s. 18.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty">Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 99.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty1">The plebiscite addressing</a> the proposed boundary between the eastern and western parts of the Territories on 4 May 1992 was decided in the affirmative by only a narrow majority (54% of the popular vote). Although there was strong support in the Eastern and Central Arctic, the Western Arctic population, with a high concentration of Dene and M&eacute;tis, was generally unsupportive. This opposition may have emanated from a disagreement over whether Nunavut territory infringes upon traditional Dene and M&eacute;tis lands (that is, Contwoyto Lake, Thelon Game Sanctuary), and from the concern that with a division, native peoples will no longer be a majority in the Territories, thus silencing the aboriginal voice in government affairs. See Purich, <i>ibid.</i> at 78, and Purich, <i>infra</i> note 67; G. Dacks, &quot;The Case Against Dividing the Northwest Territories&quot; (1986) 12 Canadian Public Policy 202. See also <cite>Benoanieu v. Canada (Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development)</cite>, [1993] 2 C.N.L.R. 97 where three Saskatchewan bands (the Fond du Lac, Black Lake and Hatchet Bands) as well as individual D&eacute;n&eacute;suline Indians, were denied an injunction to prevent the Nunavut </cite>Agreement's</cite> plebiscite. The bands asserted that Nunavut territory infringed on their traditional lands and thus unilaterally extinguished their title.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty2">Cassidy &amp; Bish, <i>supra</i> note 1 at 15.</a>
<p>
