<p>
<li><a name="thirty4">The Inuit,</a> as well as the Dene, M&eacute;tis and other First Nations, brandish political clout in the affairs of the Northwest Territories as they constitute the majority of the voting population. According to the 1991 census, the cumulative aboriginal population in the Northwest Territories is 35,302 compared with 22,347 non-natives. The Inuit make up close to half of the total population at 21,565 of the Northwest Territories but in Nunavut, the numbers are 18,359 Inuit and 3,116 whites. Northwest Territories, Bureau of Statistics, <cite>Population Estimates By Ethnic Group</cite> (Yellowknife: Territorial Printer, June 1991).
<p>
<li><a name="thirty5">Tennant,</a> <i>supra</i> note 19 at 322. See also B. Funston, &quot;The Impact of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms on Policy Development in the Northwest Territories&quot; (1992) 30 Osgoode Hall L.J. 605.
<p>
<li><a name="thirty6">Although the specific government framework</a> of the Nunavut territory is yet to be determined in Parliament pursuant to Art. 4 of the Agreement, <i>supra</i> note 2, it is proclaimed that legislative decision making will be the foundation of a public government in Nunavut. The Inuit tabled a proposal in 1983 in which the legislative assembly would have 25 members, with four elected from a distinct region and the remaining
nine from districts based on population numbers. See Nunavut Constitutional Forum, <cite>Building Nunavut</cite> (Yellowknife: Nunavut Constitutional Forum, 1983). Since the guarantee of a legislature is in the land claims settlement, the Inuit in Nunavut now enjoy a constitutional right to their own parliamentary institutions. See <cite>Constitution</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 10. However, future political accords structuring the Nunavut government are detached from the <cite>Agreement</cite> and thus do not have constitutional status. See the
<cite>Agreement</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 29.
