<li><a name="eighty2">Purich,</a> <i>supra</i> note 3 at 130. The Inuvialuit received 1,800 square kilometres of land, with surface and subsurface rights, with an additional 78,000 square kilometres of surface title as well
as ownership to sand and gravel. This works out to about 26 square kilometres per Inuvialuit. Moreover, the creation of a National Wilderness Park in Northern Yukon creates an area immune from economic development while preserving hunting, fishing and trapping rights. The Inuit have a similar arrangement with effective managerial and monitoring roles over three national parks (see the <cite>Agreement</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2 at Art. 8). By contrast, an Inuk in Quebec owns just under 1.6 square kilometres.
