<li><a name="eighty5">The allocation of rights</a> to marine areas is a first for a land claim, which recognizes the Inuit and their use of traditional off-shore areas and the importance the ocean has in their culture. See Merritt
&amp; Fenge, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 261; R. Bartlett, <cite>Aboriginal Water Rights in Canada: A Study of Aboriginal Title to Water and Indian Water Rights</cite> (Calgary: Canadian Institute of Resources Law, 1988).
<p>
<li><a name="eighty6">The <cite>Agreement</cite>,</a> <i>supra</i> at Art. 5.7.16. Exceptions to all lands in Nunavut are outlined in Art. 5.7.17 [lands for military or national security purposes, lands owned in fee simple or granted in fee simple after the <cite>Agreement</cite> (if less than one square mile), land subject to an agreement for sale at date of ratification, or a surface lease existing in October 27, 1981].
