<li><a name="one02">W. Moss,</a> <cite>Practically millionaires? A report on the Implementation of the James
Bay and Northern Quebec Agreement</cite> (Ottawa: Carleton University Press, 1981).
<p>
<li><a name="one03">Unlike the</a> <cite>JBNQA</cite> and the <cite>Inuvialuit Agreement</cite>, the Nunavut <cite>Agreement</cite> is framed in Articles rather than sections. This is a conventional practice in international law, which may imply that this Agreement maintains the treaty, nation to nation, or at least
government to government dichotomy that aboriginal peoples have always proclaimed as the proper mode of identification.
<p>
<li><a name="one04">Meritt,</a> <i>supra</i> note 94 at 110. Current political conditions may challenge this
view. However, the Inuit have never expressed any desire to secede from the rest of Canada.
<p>
<li><a name="one05">Western Arctic Regional Government Draft</a> of the Inuvialuit and Gwich'in Proposal for Reshaping Government in the Western Arctic, <i>supra</i> note 24 at 5. The author was fortunate enough to attend this conference in Inuvik concerning regional government in the Inuvialuit Settlement Region, during 19--20
November 1993. See also Jull, <i>supra</i> note 49 at 44.
<p>
<li><a name="one06">This statement</a> was expressed by the then Minister of Indian Affairs and Northern Development, Jean Chr&eacute;tien, in August 1973 in B. Morse, &quot;The Resolution of Land Claims&quot; in Morse, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 630.
<p>
<li><a name="one07">Under the <cite>Agreement</cite>,</a> the Inuit, through the auspices of the Nunavut
Trust, are awarded $1.173 billion in compensation over 14 years and the first 50% of the first $2 million and thereafter 5% of royalties earned from Nunavut lands (<cite>Agreement</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2 at Schedule 29--2). By comparison, the Inuvialuit received $152 million in compensation over 13 years but without any
entitlement to royalties. In the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, all aboriginal parties were granted $225 million in total compensation (the Quebec Inuit received $42,250,000 of that) over a period of 23 years.
<p>
<li><a name="one08">There were</a> no royalty payments from natural resource development in the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, which has been a source of contention in light of their inclusion in the <cite>Inuvialuit</cite> and <cite>Nunavut Agreements</cite>. See Moss, <i>supra</i> note 19 at 686. The Nunavut Inuit will receive royalties from resource development throughout the settlement, unlike their Inuvialuit counterparts who receive royalty payments only from their lands (<cite>Agreement</cite>, <i>supra</i> at Art. 25). The Inupiat of the North Slope of Alaska have acquired enormous wealth, but much of this has accrued from a taxation scheme imposed on huge oil development projects such as Prudhoe Bay. Taxation potential is limited in the <cite>Agreement</cite> by a prohibition on property taxes enforced against Inuit Owned Lands. See the <cite>Agreement</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2 at 22.2.1.
<p>
<li><a name="one09">R. Doering,</a> &quot;Natural Resource Jurisdiction and Political Development in the North: The Case of Nunavut&quot; in Canadian Arctic Resources Committee, <cite>National and Regional Interests in the North</cite> (Ottawa: CARC, 1986).
<p>
<li><a name="one10">Since 1984,</a> Inuvialuit land claims capital has grown to $230 million from an estimated $170 million, <i>supra</i> note 67 at 5. A reason for this increase, according to Jane Bicknell, Executive Director of the Inuvialuit Regional Corporation, is that a diversion of most investment (only compensation is invested, profits are primarily transferred to elders in the communities) goes into low risk projects. (Interview 19
November 1993). This financial shrewdness is not as evident in the Makvik Corporation. See Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 126.
