<p>
<li><a name="one77">The following discussion</a> is drawn from the author's experience as a judicial research assistant to the Supreme Court of the Northwest Territories. This opportunity enabled the author to observe the administration of justice in the communities.
<p>
<li><a name="one78">Crime rates in the Northwest Territories</a> are higher than anywhere else in Canada. Canada, Statistics Demography Division, <cite>Catalogue 85--205</cite> (Ottawa: Statistics Canada, 1993). Inuit
communities vary but collectively they contribute to the exorbitantly high numbers all across the north. On average, there is a 3 to 1 ratio between the population and number of crimes per year. Royal Canadian Mounted Police, <cite>Detachment Profiles</cite> (Yellowknife: November 1993) [unpublished].
<p>
<li><a name="one79">Berger, <i>supra</i> note 11 at 203;</a> Canada, Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development, <cite>Provisional Report on Crime, Socio-Legal Control and Problems of Change: A Legal Anthropological Study of Igloolik, N.W.T.</cite> by W.C.E. Rasing (Ottawa: Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development, 1989).
<p>
<li><a name="one80">S. Kay,</a> <cite>A Separate Native Justice System: A Real Alternative?</cite> (LL.B. paper, University of Windsor Law School, 1990). Rasing, <i>ibid.</i>, notes that a lack of money and a compelling
need for excitement drive many youths to this type of abuse, which in turn induces delinquent behaviour to obtain these substances. These findings were confirmed by the author's experiences in the Northwest Territories including some oral testimony raised in court. See <cite>R. v. Keyookta</cite> (25 Oct.-1 Nov. 1993), No. C.R. 01559 (N.W.T.S.C.).
<p>
<li><a name="one81">Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 24.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one82">For more information,</a> see Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 40; H. Brody, <cite>The People's Land: Eskimos and Whites in the Eastern Arctic</cite> (Markham: Penguin Books, 1975). The first trial of two Inuk occurred in 1917 in Edmonton, where two hunters were tried for the murders of two missionaries near Coppermine. See <cite>R. v. Sinnisiak and Uluksuk</cite> (14 August 1917) Edmonton (A.C.Q.B.). See also R.G.
Moyles, <cite>British Law and Arctic Men</cite> (Saskatoon: Western Producer Books, 1979); E.M. Keedy, &quot;A Remarkable Murder Trial: <cite>Rex v. Sinnisiak</cite>&quot; (1951) 100 U. Pa. L.Rev. 48. The author is grateful to Desmond Brice-Bennet, Legal Aid Director of the Maliganik Tukisiiniakvik in Pond Inlet, who informed the author of the Janes story, as well as of the current realities existing in Nunavut and specifically Pond Inlet.
