<li><a name="one84">Canada, Law Reform Commission of Canada,</a> <cite>Report of the Law Reform Commission of Canada: Aboriginal Peoples and Criminal Justice</cite> (Ottawa: Queen's Printer, 1991) (Chair: S.A. Cohen) at 66 (&quot;The impact of the justice system on Aboriginal persons is most apparent at the sentencing stage.&quot;).
<p>
<li><a name="one85">The Northwest Territories Court of Appeal</a> has often overturned the imposition of sentences that are light according to Canadian legal standards. See <cite>R. v. Green, Thrasher and Ruben</cite> (20 Oct 1993) No. CA 00417 (N.W.T.C.A.), rev'g (9 June 1993) No. CR 2112--2114 (N.W.T.S.C.); <cite>R. v.
Naqitaavik</cite>, [1986] N.W.T.R. 128 (C.A.). For contrast, see <cite>R. v. Ayalik</cite> (1960), 33 W.W.R. 377 (N.W.T.C.A.); <cite>Saila v. R.</cite>, [1984] N.W.T.R. 176, [1984] 1 C.N.L.R. 173 (N.W.T.S.C.).
<p>
<li><a name="one86">C.T. Griffiths &amp; A.L. Patenaude,</a> &quot;Application of the Criminal Law to Native Indians and Inuit in the Northwest Territories, Canada&quot; (1988) 22 Comp. L.Rev. 1.
<p>
<li><a name="one87">B. Morse,</a> &quot;Indigenous Law and State Legal Systems: Conflict and Compatibility&quot; in H.W. Winkler, ed., <cite>Proceedings of the Commission on Folk Law and Legal Pluralism</cite> (Ottawa: Department of Indian and Northern Affairs Canada, 1983).
<p>
<li><a name="one88"><cite>R. v. Sandercock</cite></a>, [1986] 1 W.W.R. 291, 22 C.C.C. (3d) 79 (A.C.A). For a &quot;major&quot; sexual assault, there is to be a three-year minimum sentence.
<p>
<li><a name="one89">For further discussion</a> on traditional Inuit Justice mechanisms see N. Hallendy, <cite>The Last Known Traditional Inuit Trial on Southwest Baffin Island in the Canadian Arctic</cite> (Yellowknife:1991) [unpublished].
<p>
<li><a name="one90">Kay,</a> <i>supra</i> note 180 at 19; Irwin, <i>supra</i> note 116; Rasing, <i>supra</i> note 179; Pauktuutit, Inuit Women's Association <cite>The Inuit Way, A Guide to Inuit Culture</cite> (1990). This is common among other First Nations in the Northwest Territories. See Northwest Territories, Department of Justice, <cite>Traditional Dene Justice Report</cite> (Yellowknife: Territorial Printer, 1993) (Chair: A. Brockilometresan).
<p>
<li><a name="one91">Irwin, <i>ibid.</i> at 16.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one92">Canada,</a> Department of Justice (Aboriginal Justice Directorate), <cite>Duelling Paradigms? Western Criminal Justice versus Aboriginal Community Healing</cite>, by R. Ross (Ottawa:1993) [unpublished]. The report suggests that some elders who are represented on these committees are not interested in enforcing their solutions. This has been a contributing factor to subverting the reverence and leadership that the elders once held in the community.
<p>
<li><a name="one93">T. James,</a> <cite>Circle Sentencing</cite> (LL.B. paper, University of Windsor, 1993) [unpublished]. Circle sentencing is one method of sentencing where community members and the court party surround the offender and work toward finding a consensual solution, thus commencing the healing process.
<p>
<li><a name="one94">Rasing,</a> <i>supra</i> note 179 at 57, in his study, uncovered instances where women who were victims of domestic violence were discouraged by elders committees from informing anyone, and encouraged to work out the problem within the home.
<p>
<li><a name="one95">Some studies</a> have demonstrated that Inuit women are often unwilling to press charges due to a fear of reprisals against themselves or of the difficulties for the family in not having their spouse around. See H.W. Finkler, <cite>Inuit and the Administration of Criminal Justice in the Northwest Territories: The Case of Frobisher Bay</cite> (Ottawa: Department of Indian and Northern Affairs, 1976). Another study identified the Inuit characteristics of repressing emotions and evasiveness as silencing Inuit women. R.G. Condon, <cite>Inuit Behaviour and Seasonal Change in the Canadian Arctic</cite> (Ann Arbour: UMI Research Press, 1981). Repression of emotions can be exponentially more dangerous when alcohol is consumed because emotions are unlocked leading to erratic and unanticipated behaviour.
<p>
<li><a name="one96"><cite>Green</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 186 at 5. See also Ross, <i>supra</i> note 192.
<p>
<li><a name="one97">Canadian Broadcasting Corporation,</a> <cite>CBC Mackenzie Morning</cite> (Radio
broadcast in Yellowknife: 3 November 1993).
<p>
<li><a name="one98">The Labrador Inuit Association,</a> the Committee of Original Peoples' Entitlement (Inuvialuit), the Dene, and the Council of Yukon Indians have put this issue on the negotiating table. The Inuit have proposed this as well, but it has been only a secondary priority while negotiating the <cite>Agreement</cite>, not a mandatory requirement. It is to be an issue for further study which is proposed to be addressed in the Nunavut Constitution. See Nunavut Constitutional Forum, <cite>Building Nunavut</cite> (Yellowknife: Nunavut Constitutional Forum, 1983).
<p>
<li><a name="one99">One example</a> is South Island Tribal Council on Vancouver Island, where an elders council is called upon for diversion, bail supervision, pre-sentence reporting, speaking to sentence, custodial and probationary supervision and counselling while incarcerated. Circle sentencing is common practice in some
jurisdictions including some reserves in Northern Ontario as well as the Yukon Territory. See Ross, <i>supra</i> note 192; James, <i>supra</i> note 193.
<p>
<li><a name="twohundred">Northwest Territories,</a> Department of Justice, <cite>Aboriginal Justice in the Northwest Territories: A Discussion Paper</cite> (Yellowknife: Department of Justice, July 1991) at 4.
<p>
<li><a name="two01">Rasing, <i>supra</i> note 180.</a> In Greenland, local magistrates of Greenlandic descent receive legal training from higher court justices to preside over more substantial cases. See Jensen, <i>supra</i> note 125. A similar, but less comprehensive, program is in effect under the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 20.0.5, 20.0.14; however these are still only itinerant courts with limited jurisdiction.
<p>
<li><a name="two02">See S. Jolly,</a> &quot;Increasing Aboriginal Involvement in the Delivery of Justice Services&quot; in C.T. Griffiths, ed., <cite>Circuit and Rural Court Justice in the North</cite> (Burnaby: The Northern Justice Society Resource Centre, 1984).
<p>
<li><a name="two03">The powers of local justices</a> of the peace are stipulated in the <cite>Justices of the Peace Act</cite>, R.S.N.W.T. 1988, c. J--3. s. 4(1), they include jurisdiction over all territorial laws and territorial jurisdiction granted under the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> R.S.C. 1985, c. C--46, s. 785. [hereinafter <cite>Criminal Code</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="two04">In the <cite>JBNQA</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 20.0.20,</a> it was stipulated that the
<cite>Criminal Code</cite>, <i>ibid.</i>, <cite>Canada Evidence Act</cite>, R.S.C. 1985, c. C--19, and the <cite>Quebec Code of Civil Procedure</cite> would be modified to accommodate the needs of the Inuit and make the justice system more accessible. However, this may be a hollow guarantee, especially in light of the implementation problems and lack of cooperation by the Quebec government, since this would be honoured only if it is &quot;deemed necessary.&quot;  Discussions are still ongoing.
<p>
<li><a name="two05">ITC, <i>supra</i> note 6 at 74.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="two06">The author would like</a> to express his extreme gratitude to Judge Brown, who provided the author with information on the exciting prospects of legal education in the north.
<p>
<li><a name="two07">Northwest Territories, Legislative Assembly,</a> <cite>Debates and Proceedings</cite>, No. 1 (29 November 1993).
<p>
<li><a name="two08">Purich, <i>supra</i> note 3 at 76.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="two09"><i>Ibid.</i> at 116.</a>
</ol><p><br>
